<HEADLINE>
CHANGES BRING FUSION TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ His first practice as Miami Fusion head
coach was Friday, the day that Ivo Wortmann replaced Carlos Cordoba
for the expansion team, in last place in Major League Soccer's
Eastern Conference with an 8-11 record and just 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   During Friday and Saturday's practices, Wortmann, who is the
director of coaching at the Adidas Soccer Academy at the
Bollettieri Sports Camp in Bradenton, Fla., stressed where to start
marking the opponent, the balance between playing zone and
man-to-man, and how vital it is to play as a team.
</P>
<P>
   There were lineup changes, too. Some players who hadn't been
getting much time were made starters. Like Matt Kmosko, Henry
Gutierrez, and Pablo Mastroeni, all midfielders. There also was a
change of defensive alignment, the Fusion moving from a 3-6-1 setup
to a 4-4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the switch of goalkeepers. Fusion keeper Jeff
Cassar has a strained right quadriceps, and his backup, Scott
Budnick, has fractured ribs. So David Winner, who was with the
Revolution for three days in early July, got the start over
20-year-old Matt Napoleon. Finally, Carlos Valderrama, the Fusion's
best setup man (four assists in nine games), didn't make the trip.
He preferred to sit under a tree in the shade rather than
participate in Wortmann's first practice, and Saturday he didn't
even show up. He was unhappy that Fusion officials hadn't spoken to
him before letting Cordoba go.
</P>
<P>
   With all that, the Fusion still beat the Revolution, 2-1, the
team's first road win in regulation. Afterward, the Miami players
gave Wortmann a standing ovation upon his entrance to the locker
room, and he was presented with the game ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody was just happy to win, that's why we gave
him a standing ovation,'' said Fusion forward Dan Stebbins. ``He
brings enthusiasm, intelligence. He expects a lot of us. Any time
you change a situation things look great in the beginning, but the
key to this team is the long term and (Sunday) was the first
step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He organized the players to do a completely different role,''
Fusion midfielder Diego Serna said, ``as well as to give a totally
different style of play, that and working together.''
</P>
<P>
   Wortmann had seen many MLS games, the Fusion among them. ``I'm a
professional coach and I follow international soccer,'' said
Wortmann, 48, a former member of the Brazilian national team and
the head coach of the Saudi Arabian national team. He has coached
for 18 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   His first goal is to get the Fusion into the playoffs. The
Fusion are now in fifth place, having moved past the Revolution
with the 3 points. Miami is 1 point behind fourth-place Tampa Bay,
which has 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players made me happy because they followed the game plan
and they played with high energy,'' Wortmann said. ``I believe we
have good players in Miami. By working hard, and with this effort,
we can get into the playoffs. My job is to help the players make a
practical decision on the field. If the players don't want to help
me, nothing happens.''
</P>
<P>
   What's awaiting Wortmann now is a sitdown session with
Valderrama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
