<HEADER>
A3890 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-WAGNER-ASTROS-HNS     07-27 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WAGNER-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' Wagner tries to pitch in, but he's eager to do more
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEARLAND _ Sunday was a good news/bad news sort of day at the
home of Billy and Sarah Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   First, the bad news:
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were handed a tough loss by the San Diego Padres, and
there wasn't a darn thing Billy could do about it except give
encouragement and offer words of advice to his large-screen
Mitsubishi television set.
</P>
<P>
   The winning run scored while his good friend Mike Magnante was
on the mound in the 10th inning. Wagner, who is on the 15-day
disabled list, made every pitch with Magnante even though the two
relievers were more than a 1,000 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the good news:
</P>
<P>
   If the Padres had to win, Wagner was glad friend and neighbor
Donne Wall was the pitcher of record. This only qualified as
partially good news because Wall has bragging rights; at least for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner took comfort in the fact the Astros still managed to take
the season series from San Diego, which could be a confidence
booster should the teams meet in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The best news was that Sunday was the last day Wagner would have
to ride out Astros games from his recliner. Although he's not
eligible to come off the DL until Aug. 1, Wagner will be in uniform
tonight at the Astrodome when the Florida Marlins drop in for a
four-game series. After that, he hopes to pitch in a couple of
minor-league games before joining the Astros on their upcoming road
trip in Pittsburgh or Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of seeing the games from a distance and not being
able to participate, and I'm sick of not being dressed and ready to
play,'' said Wagner, who hasn't been on the mound since being
struck in the head by a line drive July 15 at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad this is the last day I've got to sit and watch
our team play on TV. This is the worst feeling in the world because
I know I shouldn't be here just sitting at home on a vacation while
my teammates are out there doing their jobs when I'm not doing
anything. There's just nothing I can do, and I'm tired of it. I've
enjoyed my time with my wife, but I'm not supposed to be here. I
like being out there fighting the battles with my teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's battle was all too familiar to Wagner, who spent
another day trying to sit still while his teammate went to war
without him. He calls pitches and tries _ successfully on most
counts _ to predict how each scenario will develop, seemingly to
feel like he's a part of the action.
</P>
<P>
   Watching a game with Wagner is like sitting in a broadcast booth
with a homer for an announcer. The commentary is endless, and the
Astros can do no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never make it as a broadcaster,'' he said. ``I'd never be
able to say anything negative about our guys.''
</P>
<P>
   But analyzing has been the extent of Wagner's involvement since
his injury, and Sarah has been his primary audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched the first couple of games together, but then I
think I started to get on her nerves,'' he said. ``I kind of get
into the games, so sometimes I'd end up watching upstairs and she'd
watch downstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, that was the case Sunday. Sarah, who is
expected to give birth to the couple's first child any day, was
napping when the game began, and she watched the ending downstairs
with Magnante's wife, Jill, and their infant son, Mark, who helped
take Wagner's mind off the game for a couple of innings.
</P>
<P>
   As Wagner rolled around on the floor with Mark, it was obvious
he can't wait to experience fatherhood. Some day, Wagner will sit
in his study with his own child and reminisce about the awards and
memorabilia that adorn the walls and shelves. One of the newest
additions is a autographed ball from Wagner's idol, Nolan Ryan, who
sent it as somewhat of a get-well card after Wagner was struck in
the head.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting late in the game, and the Astros are trailing by a
run. Wagner, now snacking on pizza, yells downstairs to warn Jill
that her husband is warming up in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gets so nervous when Mags pitches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's getting pretty nervous, too. The Astros need a
ninth-inning rally against Trevor Hoffman, who is going for a
major-league record 42nd consecutive save. Wagner predicts this is
the day Hoffman will blow it, and he's right. As Moises Alou steps
into the batter's box, Wagner puts on his announcer's cap again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll probably throw changeups and sliders,'' Wagner said of
Hoffman. ``Mo is a great fastball hitter. If he throws a fastball,
we might tie this game up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's first pitch was a fastball right down the middle of
the plate, and Alou crushed it into the left-field seats. As a
fellow closer, Wagner could feel Hoffman's pain, but he didn't
exactly feel sorry for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see people fail, but it's kind of refreshing to know
that you're not the only one it happens to,'' Wagner said. ``There
have been nights when I've given up a home run or blown a save and
come home and search ESPN to see if anyone else did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was a new game. Wagner inched toward the edge of
his seat, and it became quite obvious he is a better performer than
he is a spectator. The longer the game dragged on, the more fidgety
he became. Wagner was a conversational host over the first eight
innings, but the closer in him came out over the final two frames.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to get focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so frustrating not to at least be there and give your
team some support,'' he said. ``This is hard. It's a no-win
situation with Mags and Donne out there. I absolutely hate that
situation. Whoever wins, you're happy for them, but whoever loses,
you're going to be sad for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his longtime friendship with Wall, Wagner's allegiances
were clearly with Magnante and the Astros. In fact, he even hoped
out loud that Wall would lose on an error or some misfortune that
didn't result from Wall pitching badly.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work out that way. Astros manager Larry Dierker
instructed Magnante to intentionally walk Carlos Hernandez, and
Andy Sheets beat Magnante with a single to left, scoring Ruben
Rivera, who had reached on a flukish double that dropped between
second baseman Craig Biggio and right fielder Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I hate not being out there,'' he said. ``In all
likelihood, I should have been pitching that last inning. That's my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Wagner loves his job, the injury has helped him view
his profession in a different light. Although he repeatedly has
said he has no fear of returning to the mound, he realizes how
lucky he is to be able to entertain the thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have killed me,'' Wagner said of the line drive off
Kelly Stinnett's bat. ``It could have taken me away from my wife
and my kid. But you have to go out there and pitch with the faith
that God will protect you. When I think about the things I'm
missing with the team and then think about things I could have
missed with my wife and kid, it puts it all into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has changed the way I look at baseball. It's not do or
die, you just do the best you can and hope it's good enough.
Baseball is just a game. You should appreciate it, enjoy it and be
thankful that you have a chance to play it, but it's still just a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's a game Wagner is tired of watching on TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
