<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM, UAW REPORT PROGRESS IN TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to correct slugline to indicate following is 1stld) 
(Subs 3rd-5th grafs for updating, rewriting; subs 8th graf to
reinsert identification of Norwood Jewell.) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Negotiators from General Motors and the United
Automobile Workers union worked around the clock Sunday to settle
strikes at two GM auto parts factories here, struggling over a few
final details of GM's future investments in the factories.
</P>
<P>
   Bargainers took a break only to watch the arrival of 18 flat-bed
trucks at one of the factories. As more than 100 striking workers
cheered and waved green strike placards, the trucks brought back
parts-making equipment that GM had removed from an auto body parts
factory here over Memorial Day weekend, triggering the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Several people involved in the talks said late on Sunday night
that a deal was fairly likely on Monday. Charlotte Grimes, a GM
spokeswoman, said just before midnight that marathon talks were
under way at both the struck factories here and at three other
factories where the UAW has threatened strikes, but that no
settlement had yet been reached.
</P>
<P>
   The other three factories are an assembly plant here and parts
factories in Indianapolis and Dayton, Ohio. Workers have also
threatened strikes in recent days at a sports utility vehicle
factory in Spring Hill, Tenn., but GM has viewed walkouts at those
factories as less likely and has not tried to settle them on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the issues in the strike have already been settled, UAW
officials said, including health and safety disputes and the
minimum number of auto parts that some workers have to produce each
day. The UAW wants GM to promise that it will install the latest
equipment here, and that it will not sell or close either factory.
</P>
<P>
   All but two of 29 GM assembly plants in North America have
closed for lack of parts from the struck factories here, and more
than 100 GM parts factories have also shut down partly or entirely
because the assembly plants are closed. GM has temporarily laid off
192,000 workers, braking growth in the entire American economy this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   GM abruptly agreed Saturday evening to return dies used in
making parts, and the UAW agreed to have up to 160 workers cross
picket lines to clean the dies, make any needed repairs and install
them in huge mechanical presses.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood Jewell, chairman at the UAW unit at one of the struck
factories here, said Sunday that the workers would actually run the
presses and produce a few parts to make sure that the dies were
functioning properly, but would return then to the picket lines if
a settlement still had not been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have been under pressure to settle the strikes. GM
dealerships are running short of popular pickup trucks and sport
utility vehicles, raising the risk that customers might start
shopping elsewhere and never return.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Standard and Poor's warned last week that it might start a
formal review of GM's credit rating, and any reduction in that
credit rating would raise the company's borrowing costs and make it
more expensive for GM to offer auto loans. The duration of the
strikes here has also put in danger GM's schedule for the
introduction of 1999 models, including a new line of highly
profitable, full-sized pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW has been alarmed by a federal lawsuit that GM filed and
by arbitration hearings that ended here on Saturday evening. In the
lawsuit and in arbitration, GM has contended that the strikes here
violate its national agreement with the UAW, and has sought rulings
that would limit the UAW's ability to stage crippling,
factory-level strikes in the future. GM would likely withdraw its
lawsuit and arbitration grievance if a settlement is reached here.
</P>
<P>
   The national agreement allows strikes over assembly line speed
increases, subcontracting and health and safety grievances. The UAW
has raised all of these issues in the strike but its main demand
has been that GM invest in more modern equipment for the factories
here, even though the factories have high costs and low
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   A UAW official who insisted on anonymity acknowledged in an
interview Sunday that some of these same investment issues were now
among the final sticking points, but refused to provide details,
saying, ``I can't say that because we can't strike over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts have been calling for GM to use the strikes
as an excuse to close inefficient factories and stop production of
money-losing car models like the Buick Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   But while GM has threatened publicly to do both, Richard
Shoemaker, the UAW's vice president for GM issues, said at a news
conference on Saturday evening that GM had not mentioned to him any
plans to close factories. The UAW has expressed no objection to the
elimination of some models provided that the factories are
converted to other production instead of being closed.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the flat-bed trucks arriving here carried one to three
stamping dies. The dies resemble gigantic metal molds, a dozen feet
long and weighing almost 10 tons. The dies are used to stamp auto
body parts from galvanized steel sheets.
</P>
<P>
   The first die to return was for pickup truck hoods and had the
nickname ``Bob'' scrawled on the side with yellow chalk. After the
trucks had passed through the factory gates, the workers loudly
sang ``Solidarity Forever,'' the UAW's anthem.
</P>
<P>
   GM removed the dies over Memorial Day weekend for fear of a
strike by workers here angry about the company's decision last
spring to cancel plans to install the latest equipment here. But
the removal of the dies ended up triggering a walkout by the 3,400
workers here on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Another 5,800 workers at a speedometer and spark plug factory
several miles away then went on strike on June 11, partly to show
support for the auto body parts workers and partly because of
worries that GM would continue to winnow their work force through
attrition while buying more parts from non-union outside suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   GM moved the dies over Memorial Day weekend to a stamping
factory in Mansfield, Ohio, but never used them there. Canadian
auto workers, who will be building the first of the new pickups,
declared that they would refuse to accept any parts from the moved
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   UAW officials have also said that the dies were damaged
accidentally during the trip to Mansfield, but GM officials have
refused to confirm or deny this.
</P>
<P>
   For all their size and weight, stamping dies are remarkably
fragile, and will produce defective parts unless mounted with great
precision in huge mechanical presses. Striking workers here were
dismayed to see that some of the dies arriving here were stacked on
each other, which can cause damage.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Miller, a 49-year-old pipe fitter who has been working
with dies here for 31 years, said that it could take anywhere from
two days to two weeks to put the dies back in service, depending on
how much damage they have suffered. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
