<HEADLINE>
GLORIOUS DAY FOR SUTTON 
</HEADLINE>
 OF FAME-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ Very early in life, Don Sutton had to learn
about patience, and rejection. His ability to deal with both kept
the pitcher going in the major leagues for 23 years. Now he has
entered baseball's Hall of Fame, and the Hall is richer for it.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's moment of glory came Sunday as he became the 233d
person to be given baseball's highest honor. His rise from being
the son of a tenant farmer to the 57th pitcher inducted into the
Hall touched a lot of people. Sutton won 324 games, 12th highest on
the all-time list. But with only one 20-victory season on his
ledger, there always were doubters as to whether he belonged.
</P>
<P>
   His induction was not only an appreciation of excellence, but
also a tribute to his longevity, something you don't see much of in
baseball these days. To reach the 300-victory plateau, Sutton had
to pitch for five teams, including two stints with the Dodgers, for
whom he pitched from 1966-80 and again in 1988. Along the way he
made it to four World Series and four All-Star Games. He went 19-9
twice and averaged 14 wins a season.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest break came in 1966, when as a rookie in spring
training he was told he was being groomed as one of the starters to
replace Sandy Koufax and Don Drysdale, who were contract holdouts.
Both eventually came back and reclaimed their spots in the
rotation. But Sutton became a fixture for 14 years. He also pitched
for the Astros, Brewers, Athletics, and Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his obvious talent, Sutton had trouble rising from the
shadows. Fortunately, he learned how to deal with rejection and
failure early in his life. It helped him to survive even after he
retired in '88. Sutton made the Hall of Fame on his fifth attempt.
It is doubtful any of the modern pitchers will follow his path to
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's important to players anymore to play as
long as some of us did,'' said Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be willing to sacrifice and chase long-term
goals,'' said Sutton. ``I think you have to be deeply motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton said his first lesson about the struggle to Cooperstown
happened in 1964, the year before he turned pro. Two major league
teams recruited him him out of Tate High School outside Pensacola,
Fla. Both gave him tryouts and decided against offering him a
contract, although for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The first pink slip came from the Single A Fresno Giants, who
released the skinny 6-foot-1-inch righthander. Next came a tryout
with the Kansas City Athletics, then managed by Haywood Sullivan
(later to become Red Sox general manager). Chief scout Whitey
Herzog liked what he saw and offered Sutton a contract worth
$17,500. He sealed the deal with a handshake and called owner
Charles O. Finley.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not for that phone call,'' said Sutton, ``I would have been
with the Kansas City A's and maybe none of this would have
happened. Herzog offered me the $17,500, a white Buick Riviera
convertible with red trim, and my college education. Mr. Finley
gets onto the phone, and without as much as a hello says, `What's
your nickname?' I told him I didn't have one.
</P>
<P>
   ``His reply was that he had either signed or was about to sign
some guys named Blue Moon, Jumbo Jim, or Catfish, and if I didn't
have a nickname, I couldn't be signed. And then he hung up on me.
He left my face blank and Whitey wondering what he said. I handed
him the phone and (the deal) was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   But all's well that ends well. Sutton signed with the Dodgers
and made the 1966 club, thanks to the walkout by Drysdale and
Koufax. Walter Alston gambled on the 19-year-old with just one
year's experience. The rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton shared his day with four selections by the veterans
committee _ Larry Doby, George Davis, Joe Rogan, and executive Lee
MacPhail. Media choices were Sam Lacy of the Baltimore
Afro-American and Dodgers announcer Jaime Jarrin, a Latin voice in
baseball for 40 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
