<HEADLINE>
DON'T SHED ANY TEARS FOR MINGOLLA 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-MINGOLLA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUTTON, Mass. _ It was a bittersweet weekend for Pleasant
Valley's Ted Mingolla. The tournament chairman watched his 34-year
relationship with the PGA Tour come to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Mingolla saw veterans like Jody Sindelar leave the club in
tears, realizing that they would never play PV again. Mingolla gave
many aspiring Tour players exemptions over the years. Several, like
Sindelar, Paul Azinger, Blaine McCallister, and Billy Andrade,
returned this weekend to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Mingolla, who never has been one to hide his emotions,
is sad to see the PGA Tour leave, ``but I'm not going to get
weepy-eyed about it.''
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. There will be professional golf here next
summer when the LPGA returns to Pleasant Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The dates and title sponsor will be announced before the end of
the summer. Boston-based Entertainment Sports Equities holds the
rights to the LPGA tournament in the Boston area and last week,
ending months of speculation, it was announced Mingolla and his PV
staff would be hosting the tourney.
</P>
<P>
   Mingolla had an inkling that the LPGA would be coming to
Pleasant Valley next year. ``Knowing that there will be a
tournament here makes this final PGA event bearable,'' he said. ``I
don't want to think what it would be like if we didn't have the
LPGA coming here.'' If Pleasant Valley wasn't hosting an LPGA event
next year, ``I think I would have spent this weekend in my office
with Mully (his pet dog) watching the tournament on television.''
</P>
<P>
   There is women's golf history at Pleasant Valley. The LPGA
Championship was held here in the early 1960s, when Mingolla's late
father, Cuzzy, ran the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Mingolla attended the LPGA Friendly's Classic at Agawam CC
earlier this summer. ``It was interesting,'' he said. ``I tried to
low-profile it, but a sportswriter from Springfield saw me there.''
</P>
<P>
   LPGA officials already have visited Pleasant Valley. ``(LPGA
vice president) Jim Webb made a preliminary inspection of the golf
course and they liked what they saw,'' said Mingolla. ``We'll
probably make a few changes, build a few new tees for the women.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's tees at PV measure 5,800 yards and the men play from
6,600 yards. ``The LPGA likes their courses around 6,300 yards, so
there will be some changes,'' Mingolla said. ``I just hope the LPGA
comes in soon and makes some recommendations so that we can get
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Mingolla said he is looking forward to working with the women
professionals. ``I understand that they do everything they can to
support a tournament,'' he said. ``They are more friendly with the
fans and the sponsors. I'm looking forward to the women golfers and
their enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women's golf is going through the ceiling,'' said ESE
president David Rogers, who was among the crowd of 60,000 Sunday
and hopes to match those figures next year. ``It's just getting
bigger and bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Se Ri Pak is their Tiger Woods. Laura Davies is their John
Daly. Annika Sorenstam and the rest of the Swedish contingent are
something else,'' said Mingolla. ``It's going to be very
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said 12 courses were evaluated last winter, but when he
heard Pleasant Valley was losing the PGA, ``It just made sense to
go there. They have a great staff and it is a great facility. I was
talking to some of the volunteers and they said they've been
working this tournament for 28 years and they can't wait for next
year when the women come here. They know how to run a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good move for us,'' said Mingolla. ``I think we'll
become one of the top LPGA events in a matter of a few years. No
matter how much we raised the purse for the men, we'd always be a
second-tier event.''
</P>
<P>
   The purse for the LPGA event has not been announced, but it is
expected to be in the $800,000 range, which means all the top money
winners would be expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   So next year Mingolla will not go to PGA Tour events and beg
golfers to show up for his tournament. He doesn't have to shake
down any sponsors, either. All he has to do is run a tournament. So
you can understand why he wasn't weepy Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
