<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGINEST HOPING FOR RUSH ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Willie McGinest doesn't live in a cave. He
knows that when he signed a five-year, $25 million deal with an $8
million signing bonus in the offseason, some questioned the wisdom
of Patriots owner Bob Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five million for 4 1/2 sacks, with 2 1/2 coming in the
postseason?
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me at all,'' said McGinest of the criticism.
``It comes with the territory. I was injured. There was nothing I
could do about it. If I was healthy and played the full season, I
would have had the same kind of year I had the years before that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in an intrasquad scrimmage before an overflow crowd of
more than 7,000, the defensive end put on a show, sacking Scott
Zolak and Jim Murphy twice each as McGinest's Blue team
(essentially the first team) beat the White squad, 21-3. McGinest
had no problem busting through the second-team offensive line, and
often raced past second-round pick Rod Rutledge, a tight end from
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest has started strong and so far has avoided injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, my role is to stay healthy,'' he said. ``I started
out last year's camp with two or three injuries _ my groin and then
my hamstring and then a couple of games later my knee. It took me a
while to get back into it and get everything better, but toward the
end it started to come together for me. I've been trying to do some
things to help avoid those injuries this year like stretching a
lot, working out, and trying to eat right.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest, the former No. 1 pick from Southern California,
probably would have been pursued by several teams in the free agent
market. Surely, the Patriots weren't overly eager to part with $25
million. But if they lost McGinest, they would have had to spend
that much or more for a suitable replacement. So the team stepped
to the plate, and now is hoping the injury bug doesn't strike
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard watching from the sidelines,'' McGinest said. ``I
get into the games. I care. I want us to win and I was happy that
we were able to win some games I didn't play in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got back it felt good, but our defense had to start
stepping it up. As a defensive player, you can't really worry about
what the offense is doing, but it felt like we were the only ones
out there sometimes and if we planned on going anywhere we knew we
had to step up. I thought we finished strong and now we want to
start out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest said Sunday's game was fun, ``but any time it's a
scrimmage you can't go full-speed because they know your plays and
we know theirs, and you're going up against your own guys anyway.
You especially can't hit the quarterback, but you can still battle
out there and run your moves. I did all right, but it's camp.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest said the defense has a big advantage over last year at
this time because of its familiarity with one another and the
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty comfortable,'' McGinest said. ``We don't have any
new schemes. We're 10 steps ahead of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do expect a lot of ourselves. We have a lot of talented
guys and we've been playing together for a long time. Everyone
depends on each other. We've got guys who are under contract for a
while and we know we're going to be together. Chris Slade signed
last year and Willie Clay is out there with the leadership thing.
We have a good, young player in Lawyer Milloy who can really hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting right cornerback position is a concern, and
McGinest said Chris Canty, who had a nice breakup of a long pass by
Zolak to Anthony Ladd, has had a good camp. But he believes rookie
Tebucky Jones needs to get on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old saying, `You can't make the club in the tub,'''
McGinest said. ``(Jones) has a lot of talent and confidence and
when he gets out there he'll be comfortable. It takes a long time
to get back when you're hurt as a rookie because you have a lot of
catching up to do. I know because I was hurt my rookie year.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest's bookend, Ferric Collons, had an outstanding scrimmage
at left end, and Henry Thomas, despite missing a few days because
of a swollen knee, was also a force against the run.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Ted Johnson was in on several plays in the first half
of the 100-play scrimmage, but didn't play much in the second half
because of a strained left hamstring. Standing out on the White
defense were second-year linebackers Bernard Russ and Vernon
Crawford. It wasn't a good day for the White secondary, as Terry
Glenn, Vincent Brisby, Troy Brown, and Tony Gaiter excelled. Glenn
caught a 41-yard pass at the start of the game while Gaiter went 66
yards on a TD strike from Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make a big difference on the field, and this is a year
where I'd like to forget all about the injuries last year and let
it loose,'' McGinest said. ``It's going to be fun. But it'll only
be fun if we play to our capabilities, and that includes me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
