<HEADLINE>
THIS MAJOR ATTRACTED MINOR INTEREST IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The 1999 U.S. Senior Open will be held in Des
Moines, Iowa, and _ no offense to the U.S. Senior Open or Des
Moines _ they're made for each other.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senior Open and Los Angeles, apparently, are not.
</P>
<P>
   This turned into a terrific tournament Sunday after three rounds
dominated by Raymond Floyd and a bunch of glorified crabgrass. Jack
Nicklaus, bless his hip, finished with the lowest round by anybody
all week, although his 67 was too much too late. The rules of golf,
laid out in the funniest sports book since ``Ball Four,'' came into
play in the unusual incident that ruined Brian Barnes. Old pros
Floyd and Hale Irwin battled each other and the heat on a rare
breezeless day at Riviera Country Club in Pacific Palisades.
</P>
<P>
   And ultimately Irwin, the best and mentally toughest of the
senior golfers, though not on top of his game early on, summoned
three perfect holes to close out a dramatic one-stroke victory over
Vicente Fernandez with a 12-foot birdie putt on 18.
</P>
<P>
   To which Los Angeles responded with a barely stifled yawn.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Golf Association said 25,500 fans came through the
gates Sunday, and even in the unlikely case that figure is
accurate, it's barely half of what the final round of the PGA
Tour's Nissan Open attracts each March.
</P>
<P>
   There were open spots along the fairway gallery ropes as Irwin
and Floyd trudged up the 18th, and plenty of elbow room on the
natural amphitheater behind the green.
</P>
<P>
   The four-round crowd count, 76,500, was precisely 76.5 percent
of the lofty attendance goal set by tournament director Bill
Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Putting on a brave face, Knight called the fans' response
``reasonable... We're happy with it. We're not jumping up and down
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But after only 7,000 fans showed up on Thursday, the tournament
organizers had to cut back on overhead. For one thing, they reduced
the number of parking-lot shuttle buses.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is significant not because we're concerned about
the shuttle-bus industry but because Riviera would love to host the
!ital!real!off! U.S. Open _ the last in Southern California was Ben
Hogan's victory at Riviera 50 years ago _ and this might have been
an audition.
</P>
<P>
   The next unassigned U.S. Open is the 2004 edition, though it's
unlikely the event would return to the state that soon, since it
was held at the Olympic Club in San Francisco this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this course would be a wonderful venue for a U.S. Open
championship,'' Irwin said (and why wouldn't he?) after winning
with a 1-over-par 284 at Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether anybody would show up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, explaining the relative apathy this week might be
impossible, short of interviewing everybody who !ital!wasn't!off!
there. But theories, we have theories.
</P>
<P>
   There's the worn-out excuse that Los Angeles offers too many
sports and entertainment options. Over the weekend, you could have
gone to see ``Armageddon,'' ``Disturbing Behavior'' and ``Fear and
Loathing,'' and that's only one Dodgers game.
</P>
<P>
   And with the advent of Viagra, senior golf's fan base has one
more thing to do with its free time.
</P>
<P>
   Better, there's the argument that PGA, LPGA and Senior PGA Tour
events are so commonplace in Southern California _ eight this year,
12 if you count the winter ``silly season'' _ that a ``major
tournament'' is one too many for the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting that theory is the fact that this week's tournament
officially outdrew the '95 PGA Championship at Riviera (though
enthusiasm for that event was dampened by the requirement that fans
purchase a week's strip of tickets).
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the USGA can't complain about the amount of publicity
it received. The two L.A. newspapers published special sections
before the tournament. Then again, the cover stories were all about
Nicklaus and Arnold Palmer being on their last legs. That made you
want to come out to see them but only to help them across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Then the competition started. The rough was so thick, you could
lose a baseball, let alone a golf ball, in it. Suddenly, what
should have been a stroll through golf history, a chance to watch
Jack roll in one more long birdie and Arnie make one more charge,
turned into an afternoon watching Grandpa take the Weed-Whacker to
the back lawn.
</P>
<P>
   The regular senior-tour events are highly entertaining, the
players taking the competition seriously but also recognizing
they're museum pieces in a nostalgia exhibition. They sign
autographs, joke with the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Put the word ``major'' in front of the event, and try to make
Irwin's first triumph in the U.S. Senior Open sound as important as
his three in the !ital!real!off! U.S. Open, and the thing actually
becomes harder to take seriously.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. fans didn't take it seriously this week, at least not
enough of them. It will be different in Des Moines, probably.
</P>
<P>
   Said Knight, the tournament director: ``It'll be like the Super
Bowl in Des Moines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
