<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS MUST GIVE BASEBALL MINDS CHANCE TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This will not be just another week in baseball. Not
for the Mariners. Not for Woody Woodward. Not for the team's
quasi-accountable owners, who still have time to reverse themselves
and let their baseball people make baseball decisions.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a good deal to be made for Randy Johnson, Woodward
must be allowed to make it, because it is too big a waste to get
nothing for the Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a deal for the beloved Edgar Martinez _ one that
Martinez likes and is good for him and the M's _ Woodward must have
the right to pull the trigger, even if no one in Seattle wants
Martinez to go.
</P>
<P>
   There is much at stake over the next seven days. The maintenance
of a competitive ballclub _ one that fits the owner-dictated
payroll constraints _ needs almost hourly monitoring right now. You
can't be knee-jerk in big trade decisions. But you can't be rooted
in cement, either.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, the Mariners' vice president of baseball operations,
must have the chance to do his job _ especially now.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the M's are home for two crash-and-burn series
against the best teams in the American League. Cleveland and New
York will come to town to push the Mariners, the owners and
Woodward to their limit.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the week that tells the tale of 1998 and beyond:
Are the M's in or out of the playoff hunt? Do they trade or stand
pat? Do they play for '98 or do they think about '99, the new
stadium and beyond?
</P>
<P>
   One thing's for sure, this is not a week for the weak of heart.
</P>
<P>
   If the hot M's climb to within five or six games of the AL West
lead, maybe Woodward has to consider making a deal to bolster the
M's stretch run _ a notion unthinkable before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   But if Cleveland beats the M's and the gap between Seattle and
the best of the AL West stays near double digits, then Woodward
might have to stop thinking about '98 and consider any deal that
will benefit the team in '99 and beyond. Guaranteed, the fans will
appreciate that kind of forward thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the scenario is by Friday, the guy in charge of trades
must have the chance to react to the fluidity of the market.
</P>
<P>
   If Cleveland general manager John Hart decides he wants Johnson
and Martinez on his team, then Woodward has to be in a position to
react to the slew of players Hart might offer.
</P>
<P>
   The word is, Cleveland outfielder David Justice, second baseman
Enrique Wilson, first baseman Richie Sexson and reliever Paul Shuey
might be on the table in exchange for Johnson and Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward has to have the green light to at least consider this
kind of franchise-altering deal.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about Woodward. He has traded away Mariner
heartthrobs and prospects as if the club's farm system had the
power to clone major leaguers. But he has never shied away from
trading deadlines deals. He has been fully accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it has taken Woodward too long to pull off certain deals.
Last season, for instance, the Phillies were willing to trade
closer Ricky Bottalico and the White Sox were offering a slew of
bullpen help.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Woodward could not get the owners to OK payroll increases
fast enough, which is why he was left to trade Jason Varitek and
Derrick Lowe to Boston for Heathcliff Slocumb and Jose Cruz to
Toronto for Mike Timlin and Paul Spoljaric.
</P>
<P>
   (And if you look at how Cruz has struggled and Timlin has
pitched the last month, the Toronto deal doesn't look too bad now.)
</P>
<P>
   But the point is, Woodward has never blinked in the face of a
tough decision. He has made the deals that sacrificed long-term
health for short-term glory _ a philosophy that can't be knocked
when you're trying to cash in on a team that has had a roster as
star-studded as the Mariners'.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's crunch time again. Friday is the trading deadline. It
is a date that means there are two months left in the season. The
contenders have a chance to bolster their rosters, while the losers
have to think about next season.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the Mariners. Are they in or out? Do they
stand pat or do they make a move?
</P>
<P>
   The problem here in Marinerville is that the power to do what
might need to be done has been taken from Woodward. The owners have
issued a hands-off Randy Johnson edict _ a hand-tying move that has
kept Woodward from fulfilling his job description, which is to
improve the team according to the incredibly tense and
fast-changing climate of the baseball market.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Pelekoudas, M's vice president of baseball administration,
said late last week that the team is in contention for the AL West
division title. That bold stance was bolstered when the M's won two
in Baltimore this weekend. This second-half surge has only made
this critical week more tense for the M's. It has put more pressure
on the line, on Woodward's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Now the M's come home. It is crunch time. By week's end, if a
deal presents itself that makes sense for the long-term health of
the Mariners, the owners must let the Mariner baseball people have
the freedom to do their job. No time left to fool around in a
season of too much fooling around.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
