<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOUNCES GO MARINERS' WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ If you can't make conversation about baseball this
week in Seattle, then you've never heard of the infield fly rule or
a four-seam fastball.
</P>
<P>
   The long-simmering issue of Randy Johnson will come to a head by
the interleague trade deadline Friday night, and the M's thickened
the plot Sunday by completing a two-of-three series victory here
against Baltimore, splicing speed between clutch hitting for a 10-4
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some ground to make up,'' right fielder Jay Buhner
conceded. ``But if the teams ahead of us keep losing, it's going to
be a nice little turnaround for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But a little less today. As the M's were having their way with
the Orioles, both Anaheim and Texas were being shellacked, so as
Seattle points to an eight-game homestand against American League
powers Cleveland, New York and Boston starting Tuesday night, the
M's are 8{ games behind Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   That's the best state of affairs for the Mariners since they
were 8{ back on June 2, after giving away a game to the Orioles
here in this same park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get back to .500,'' insisted Jamie Moyer (8-7),
who won his third straight decision. ``I keep saying it, but I
really mean it. I've never seen a team win a division or a wild
card without getting to .500.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get to .500, obviously we stand to pick up some
ground, and we'll have gained some momentum by doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had five two-out hits that produced seven runs in three
different innings. And a team not known for its wheels took
advantage of Scott Erickson's slow windup for a club record-tying
five steals, including a personal-high three by Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ran, I guess,'' Griffey shrugged. ``I always have the
green light. I just never run.''
</P>
<P>
   With victories in the final two games of the series, the M's
blunted Baltimore's thunderous momentum mounted on 14 wins in 15
games.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty much all you need to know about this one was revealed in
two batted balls, one by the Mariners, one by the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, with John Marzano at third base and two
outs, Alex Rodriguez hit a grounder to the left of shortstop Jeff
Reboulet. The ball scooted under Reboulet's glove for an error,
something about as rare in Baltimore as those who remember Robert
Irsay fondly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe things are starting to even up a little bit,'' Buhner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oriole fans, used to watching a club that had made a major
league-low 47 errors, perhaps weren't wise to the ways of what such
a miscue can do. The Mariners, who know only too well, quickly
showed them.
</P>
<P>
   After Griffey walked, he and Rodriguez worked separate steals.
Edgar Martinez then stung a two-run single off Erickson, the league
leader in complete games, David Segui stroked the first of his four
hits, and Buhner struck a two-run double for a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner was fortunate to be intact to tell about that other
aforementioned ball, lofted to right by Brady Anderson leading off
the fifth inning. On a sunny afternoon, Buhner fought the high sky
and a background of light shirts in the stands and completely lost
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   As he settled into a crouch, waiting for the worst, Buhner
almost got it. The ball hit him square in the belt buckle, and he
was able to cradle it with his glove hand for the out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I never have another one like that, it'll be OK,'' Buhner
said. ``You can't practice that. I didn't come to the ball, the
ball came to me.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, the M's had a 7-3 lead, stretched by two runs in the
top of the fifth when, with the bases loaded, Shane Monahan turned
on an 0-and-2, hanging breaking ball from Erickson for a double
into the right-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made about eight bad two-strike pitches and they got
hits,'' lamented Oriole manager Ray Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got two strikes on guys and couldn't put them away,''
Erickson said. ``I was a little bit wild. Once I got two strikes, I
really couldn't strike anybody out.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Baltimore could have survived without Reboulet's big
error is debatable. Erickson, who also leads the majors in hits
allowed, gave up eight in a laborious five innings. But the
mistake, leading to Baltimore's second three-error game of the
year, removed any doubt.
</P>
<P>
   If the M's had time to admire their handiwork, they would know
that in rebounding from the opening defeat to win the series
against a hot club, they accomplished something substantial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got beat Friday night,'' Mariner manager Lou Piniella
said. ``(Mike Mussina) made good pitches. We've bounced back from
that type of situation fairly well. It's when we get sloppy that's
the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloppy, the M's know only too well. They hope to get a lot more
familiar with bouncing back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
