<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONILLA'S ACTIVE DATE A DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman said
Sunday he wasn't sure that Bobby Bonilla would return to action
from left-wrist tendinitis on Thursday. But whether that has been
told to Bonilla might be a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla said he expects to come off the 15-day disabled list
when he is eligible Thursday to join the Dodgers against the host
Philadelphia Phillies. Bonilla, who had wrist surgery during the
offseason, was placed on the DL on July 17, retroactive to July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Since being traded from the Florida Marlins to the Dodgers in
the May 15 blockbuster seven-player deal, Bonilla has batted .202
with one home run in 124 at-bats. When he returns, he will likely
be sent to left field and Adrian Beltre will stay at third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I was staying longer on the DL,'' said Bonilla.
``Do you all (the media) know something I don't? It's really up to
them. When I come off is when I come off. They haven't told me
anything differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of patience. I don't think a lot of people around
me have the same patience. It is really out of my control. I
thought I was going to be in Florida doing rehab, and the next
thing I know I was on a plane to L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Important trip?: How big is the Dodgers' upcoming 10-game
road trip? Well, Bonilla described it by saying, ``It's huge ...
huge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers begin a three-game series at Philadelphia on Tuesday
before playing four against ex-Dodgers star Mike Piazza and the New
York Mets (Friday-Aug. 3) and finishing with three contests against
the Montreal Expos (Aug. 4-6). Bonilla said the Dodgers can't
underestimate Philadelphia and Montreal, and they have to be
prepared to play in the ``zoo'' setting of New York's Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to determine how the next two months go,'' Bonilla
said. ``Why? Well, we're five games out (of the wild card).
Stranger things have happened, but this will be a good indicator.
We are on the road for one of the longest trips of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, however, begged to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it's do or die,'' he said. ``Every game is
important, and this (trip) is important. We just have to try and
stay within striking distance. Than if we can get everyone back
healthy, we'll have another run at these teams in August and
September.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Labor issue: Dodgers catcher Charles Johnson, who was
expected to take the game off, was dismissed from being in uniform
after his wife, Rhonda, went into labor. With Johnson unavailable
and usual backup Tom Prince starting, outfielder Trenidad Hubbard
became the emergency backup.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard, 32, was actually an all-conference catcher at Southern
University. But Hubbard said he relinquished his catching duties
with Houston's Double-A Columbus in 1990 because of his knack for
stealing bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd block the ball and catch if they needed me to. I'd go out
there without a (protective) cup on, just as long as I play,'' said
a joking Hubbard, who last caught for the Colorado Rockies in 1996
during an exhibition game against their Triple-A team.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard didn't catch against Arizona. Prince threw out two base
runners.
</P>
<P>
   __ Upcoming matchups: Dodgers left-hander Brian Bohanon (3-6,
3.21) will face Phillies right-hander Tyler Green (6-7, 4.66) on
Tuesday. Dodgers right-hander Dave Mlicki (5-4, 3.89) will meet
Phillies right-hander Carlton Loewer (4-3, 7.20). Dodgers
right-hander Chan Ho Park (9-5, 4.07) will face Phillies
left-hander Matt Beech (3-6, 5.00).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
