<HEADER>
A3905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-U.S.500-LEDE-HNS &LR;      07-27 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-U.S.500-LEDE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. 500 marred by tragedy
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moore captures wild race featuring 62 lead changes
</P>
<P>
   By TERRY BLOUNT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ When Greg Moore crossed the finish line a few
feet in front of Jimmy Vasser and Alex Zanardi, the Omega timing
computer failed to list Moore as the winner of the U.S. 500.
</P>
<P>
   The computer was set up to accept a maximum of 60 lead changes,
more than double any other CART event had ever recorded. But
Moore's pass of Vasser on the final lap was the 62nd lead change of
Sunday's race, something no one involved in the racing series would
have imagined possible.
</P>
<P>
   The 70,000 fans at the Michigan Speedway saw one of the most
exciting races in years. But the event was marred by a freakish
accident that killed three spectators and injured six when a wheel
off Adrian Fernandez's car flew into the grandstand after he hit
the wall late in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great show,'' Moore said. ``But when something like
that happens, it puts a damper on the entire day. I feel so bad for
the families of those people.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the drivers knew what had happened until the race was
over, but they all knew they had participated in a rare passing
festival that left the outcome in doubt until the final seconds of
the 250-lap event over the two-mile, high-banked Michigan Speedway
oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what, I've never seen a race like that in my
life,'' said Chip Ganassi, owner of the Target team that has Vasser
and Zanardi. ``From my vantage point, it's pretty damn exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasser finished .008 seconds (about three feet) ahead of Zanardi
after the teammates had passed each other more than a dozen times
during the race.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for all the passing was the new Handford Device,
which is a change in the rear wing that was used for the first time
to try to slow the cars on the superspeedway. It worked, but the
main effect of the change was an air tow that enabled the cars to
pass each other, almost at will.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a NASCAR race without bumpers,'' said Michael
Andretti, who finished sixth behind fourth-place Scott Pruett and
fifth-place Richie Hearn, but only 1.5 seconds behind Moore. ``It
was hairy out there with a lot of wheel-to-wheel racing, but that's
what racing is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans witnessed more than 100 lead changes in the race, but a
lead change isn't official unless the driver leads that lap. Nine
drivers led at least one lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' said Moore, 23, a Canadian who won for the
second time this season. ``But it did make things difficult. Guys
could get in the draft and get by you pretty quickly. There was
nothing you could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a good thing for superspeedways. It was great
for the fans, and it was 100 times more exciting than St. Louis
(another oval-track race).''
</P>
<P>
   The previous record for lead changes in a CART race was 27 at
Michigan in 1982 and 1985. The drivers eclipsed that mark Sunday
only five laps past the halfway mark. The race included six lead
changes in the last 10 laps, and five in the final five laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those last five laps were pretty intense,'' said Moore, who
drives the Player's Reynard Mercedes. ``I think I passed Jimmy with
three laps to go, but then he got back ahead of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided to follow him for one lap, and then I got a
good run on him in turn 1 of the last lap. I was weaving back and
forth to try to break the draft, then I looked in my mirror and saw
they weren't going to catch me.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasser, who won the event in 1996, was hoping to win again at
Michigan in his 100th career start as a CART driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to come in second, but Greg did a fantastic job,''
Vasser said. ``I just led the wrong lap and they came flying right
back on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fantastic racing, but I didn't get the breaks at the
end. We all said before the race that you didn't want to lead at
the white flag (next-to-last lap), but it's hard not to take the
lead when you are out there driving. It was a lot of fun out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The one person who disagreed with that assessment was Zanardi,
who was hoping to set a CART record with a fifth consecutive
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that is racing,'' said Zanardi, whose engine
caught fire on the last lap. ``It was funny, but it wasn't real
racing. You couldn't pull away from anybody. Guys would pass you,
and there was nothing you could do. But it was the car, not the
driver. I would call this a show, but I wouldn't call it racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if the fans saw that every week they would lose
interest. Some of that passing was a waste of time. It didn't take
a lot of skill to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore showed enough skill to work his way to the front despite
stalling his engine on two occasions in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a problem with the pit-lane speed limiter that would
cause the engine to die when we stopped,'' Moore said. ``But my
crew worked it out and kept me in it. This is a long race and I'm
still learning at these tracks. This is the first 500-mile race
where I've finished on the lead lap.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore won $100,000 for the victory. He had failed to finish in
the top 10 in the three previous races, including 25th- and
27th-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My team wasn't down, but I could tell some of them didn't have
that same gleam in their eyes as they had earlier in year,'' Moore
said. ``I think they got it back today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
