<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAW PLAYS SAVIOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With yet another debacle on the horizon, the Los
Angeles Dodgers' version of Superman swooped in from the bullpen to
save the day once again.
</P>
<P>
   After entering the eighth inning with a five-run lead over the
Arizona Diamondbacks, the non-Jeff Shaw members of the Dodgers'
bullpen were rattled once again by allowing three runs and leaving
the bases loaded with just one out. The All-Star, however, got the
next two batters to ground out to end the inning before earning his
30th save during the Dodgers' 5-3 victory over the Diamondbacks in
front of 37,353 on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The good news from Shaw, however, could not overcome the bad
caused when Dodgers starter Ismael Valdes left the game in the
sixth inning with a muscle strain on the left side of his back.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes (9-9), who threw five scoreless innings, allowing four
hits, will be re-evaluated today. Valdes, who is 6-2 at home this
season and owns a three-game winning streak, has never had back
problems in his major-league career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it is sore and it's hard to say if I'll make my next
start,'' said Valdes, who has also been bothered by the flu
recently. ``I don't want to miss a start, but I have no control of
it. No one likes this situation and this is new to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried. It's painful. I can't pitch with pain and deliver
good.''
</P>
<P>
   After throwing his first pitch to leadoff pinch-hitter Jorge
Fabregas in the sixth, Valdes winced, said catcher Tom Prince. And
after Valdez felt worse on his second pitch, Dodgers manager Glenn
Hoffman and assistant trainer Stan Johnston checked out the
right-hander and watched him struggle through a couple practice
tosses before summoning Mark Guthrie from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is scary. Hopefully it is not severe,'' said Hoffman, who
noted Valdes was throwing in the 90-mph range before the injury.
``When you're pitching, you use all the muscles in your side, back
and legs. When one is (injured), it can alter their pitching. That
is what we have to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie followed by allowing no runs, struck out three and
allowed just one hit during his first two innings. But after
entering the eighth with a 5-0 advantage, Guthrie allowed the bases
to be loaded with no outs on a double, a hit batter and a single.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Fox followed with a two-run single that trimmed Arizona's
deficit to 5-2 and brought images back of the Dodgers' debacle on
Thursday. On that night, relievers Antonio Osuna and Scott Radinsky
played a huge part in blowing a five-run lead against the Houston
Astros in the eighth inning during an eventual loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Arizona) took advantage of our voodoo eighth innings,'' said
Guthrie, who snapped his scoreless streak at 102/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   After Osuna came in and caused a pop fly for one out, Radinsky
allowed an RBI single to cut the Dodgers' lead to 5-3 and hit the
next batter. Despite facing a bases-loaded situation with no outs,
Shaw forced ex-Dodger Karim Garcia to hit the ball to the mound for
a force out at the plate. Then he got Brent Brede to ground out to
end Arizona's threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into the eighth inning is not unusual for me,'' said
Shaw, who has retired 32 of the 37 batters he has faced over 11
innings in nine appearances with the Dodgers. ``I did it a lot as a
set-up guy in Cincinnati and I'm doing it here.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the Dodgers also received a solo home run from Matt
Luke in the first inning and four runs in the third _ two on a home
run by Eric Karros _ all off $6 million Arizona starter Andy Benes.
Luke's round-tripper was his fifth in nine games. Karros went 2 for
4 with a double, home run and two RBI to extend his hitting streak
to six games.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' victory was their ninth in 14 games and kept them
five games behind the Chicago Cubs in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is asking too much to recover from five runs,'' said Benes
(7-11), who allowed five runs on eight hits in five innings. ``Five
runs is a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   And so is the possibility of losing Valdes for the
wild-card-seeking Dodgers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
