<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY POLICE OFFICER IN CRITICAL CONDITION AFTER BEING SHOT
IN HEAD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page.)  (sw) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New York City police officer was fighting for his
life after being shot in the head on Sunday night on Staten Island,
apparently by a 17-year-old parolee who was wanted for questioning
on a new murder charge, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Gerard Carter, 28, was on a routine patrol of the
West Brighton Houses project when he was shot at 9:25 p.m. in front
of 810 Henderson Avenue, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said at a press
conference at St. Vincent's Hospital in Staten Island. He was
listed in critical condition, and was undergoing brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Shatiek Johnson, was paroled in April after serving
one and a half years for a 1996 manslaughter conviction, the police
said. He was arrested earlier this summer on a farebeating charge,
but somehow slipped through the parole system. He was most recently
wanted for questioning in the July 16 murder of Eric Trotman, 20,
in Staten Island, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's incident was the most serious shooting of a New
York City police officer since May, when a police officer was
fatally shot in Brooklyn while trying to arrest a parolee.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani used the occasion to rail _ again _ against a parole
system that he has long said needs to be reformed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another example of the parole system putting the lives
of police officers and other innocent citizens at risk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Police Department spokeswoman, Officer Valerie St. Rose, said
Carter was sitting in a marked police van, in uniform and on duty,
when at least one shot pierced the front windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors reported hearing two quick shots that they said
sounded like discharges from a handgun. Then they saw the wounded
officer, face down, slumped over the steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's partner, Eric Storch, 29, was not wounded in the
shooting but was traumatized, said police spokesman Officer Dennis
Laffin. He was treated at and released from Bayley Seton Hospital,
said a spokeswoman there.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred in a section of Staten Island that is
dominated by the sprawling West Brighton Houses housing projects.
There is a large courtyard in the middle of the projects, and that,
according to neighbors, was where the officer was shot on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The police are known to maintain a visible presence in the
projects, mainly to crack down on beer drinking and drug activity,
neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, Carter was driving on a pathway through the
housing development, with Storch at his side, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   They were seeking to question Johnson, who had missed a day of
community service _ his sentence after the farebeating arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The officer saw one and perhaps three people and slowed the van
to a stop, the police said. At the point, Johnson approached and
fired through windshield, hitting Carter in the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Storch returned the fire with one or two shots, both of which
missed their target.
</P>
<P>
   After the shots rang out, the police responded with breathtaking
speed and urgency, the neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came from every angel,'' said one woman who declined to
give her name. ``They came from all angles.''
</P>
<P>
   The police said that they believed that the suspect was still in
the housing projects, and were preparing to conduct an apartment by
apartment search.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
