<SLUG> BC-RADIUM-BASE-TESTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR-BASE LAB TEAM TESTED FOR RADIATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BHAVNA MISTRY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. _ Air Force officials are testing
base workers for radiation after a small amount of radium
discovered in a recycling truck contaminated a base lab.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials don't believe there is any serious health
risk from the material discovered about two weeks ago, they said
Sunday. Nevertheless, two buildings were closed and tests were run
on the four people who handled the material, about one-half inch
wide and an inch long. There also was testing of several others in
the area when the radium was being examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urine samples of people who handled the material or entered
either building have been taken to determine if any ingestion
actually occurred,'' said Dennis Shoffner, spokesman for the base
in northern Los Angeles County. Results of the tests have not yet
been returned, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the two buildings remain closed, although other
portions have been decontaminated and reopened. ``People have begun
to reoccupy those areas that have been determined safe,'' Shoffner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Radium, commonly used in cancer treatment, can be fatal to
humans in high concentrations and can lead to bone cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the radium found at the base is still unknown. It
was discovered when a load of scrap metal that recycler Paul Ogden
brought to a Los Angeles recycling center set off radiation
sensors. Ogden believes he acquired the material when he made a
pickup at the base.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the years I've handled material, I've never seen an
incident like this,'' said Ogden, a Mojave resident who has
recycling contracts with the Air Force base. ``It seems to be an
isolated thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogden, in the recycling business for five years, drove the load
back to the base July 14 after the recycling center would not let
it in. He took it to the base, he said, rather than tear apart the
load piece by piece to find what set the sensors off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to do the responsible thing for my safety and the
safety of others,'' Ogden said.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the base, Air Force officials determined that the
radioactive source was the piece of metal in a 6-inch stainless
steel tube. They placed the potentially deadly material into a
pipe, along with brass shavings to keep it from moving. They sealed
the pipe with caps.
</P>
<P>
   It was transported to the base's hazardous material facility and
then taken to the base's bio-environmental safety lab where it was
examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an analysis sample was taken from the source, some of the
brass-filing packing material spilled,'' Shoffner said. ``This
material is thought to have rubbed off surface material from the
source tube, thus carrying a small amount of material.''
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force investigation team specializing in radiation
assessment has been on the base since July 17.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been determined if the material in fact originated at
the base, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   `We have no indication that it was ours to begin with,''
Shoffner said. ``It's a complete mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Air Force has permits to possess and use several
small, sealed sources of radioactive material for X-rays and
calibration of laboratory instruments, officials said the material
from Ogden's load does not appear to be in the same form.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing that we use here,'' Shoffner said. ``We don't
have any record that we had it or that we used it.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Baldenweg of the Radiologic Health Branch at the California
Department of Health Services inspected Ogden's business and found
no evidence that radioactive material had leaked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had four people testing to see if there's any
contamination,'' Baldenweg said. ``There was no detection.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldenweg and several Air Force official also visited Ogden's
home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
