<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENT'S HOMER MAKES A WINNER OF MESA 
BY DAVID BUSH
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jeff Kent, himself a product of one of general
manager Brian Sabean's deals, made one of the latest Giants'
transactions look good Sunday, when he belted a home run leading
off the 10th inning to give the Giants a 2-1 victory over the
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Kent's 13th homer of the year, a drive to left that stayed under
the Candlestick Point jet stream, made a winner of Jose Mesa (1-0),
who until last Thursday belonged to the Cleveland Indians. Mesa was
one of four new Giants Sabean added in last week's one-day dealing
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   In his second appearance with the Giants, Mesa struck out all
three batters he faced in the 10th inning, following starter Orel
Hershiser (seven innings, one run) and Robb Nen (two shutout
innings).
</P>
<P>
   Knowing he had Mesa in reserve, manager Dusty Baker had been
able to use his closer, Nen, in the seventh inning of a 1-1 tie.
Look for more such maneuverings when the Giants, who still trail
the Cubs by three in pursuit of the wild card, open an eastern road
trip tomorrow night in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very nice,'' Baker said of the double-barreled late
relief corps, which brings back memories of late 1997 and Rod Beck
and Roberto Hernandez. ``Robb hadn't pitched in almost a week
(since last Monday), and now he's tuned up for Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, who held the Reds to four hits and the single run
that came in the first inning, also welcomes the addition of Mesa,
a former teammate in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jose gives us a 1-2 punch out there,'' said Hershiser, who
showed the crowd of 34,638 a performance reminiscent of his
six-game winning streak two months ago. Hershiser had been 1-2 with
a 5.21 ERA since the All-Star break, but he feels his touch never
went away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've felt really good the whole second half, I just haven't
gotten the results,'' Hershiser said. ``I threw pretty much the
same today. It's not like I was out there trying to reinvent the
wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Sanders tripled to lead off the game and scored on a
sacrifice fly, but after that, Hershiser permitted just three
harmless singles and a walk, with only one other runner advancing
as far as second base.
</P>
<P>
   But all that earned him was no decision, largely due to
Cincinnati second-year right-hander Brett Tomko. He went the first
nine innings and held the Giants to just a run on two hits. Rey
Sanchez tripled in the fourth, when two Cincinnati outfielders
clanged into one another while diving for the ball. Kent drove
Sanchez in with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   But when the teams got into the bullpens, the Giants were
sturdier. Nen got himself into some trouble with a throwing error
and walk in the eighth but was rescued when Darryl Hamilton made a
sliding catch of Eddie Taubensee's shallow fly ball to end the
inning. He dusted off the effects of Willie Greene's leadoff single
in the ninth, then turned things over to Mesa, who knocked off the
three Cincinnati hitters he saw in just 14 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't try for strikeouts,'' Mesa said. ``You throw too many
pitches that way. I guess they were just not seeing the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   But to take the rubber game of the three-game series, the Giants
still needed a run. Kent, who was an RBI machine over the weekend,
took care of that when he belted the second pitch from reliever
Stan Belinda (4-7) over the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Kent, who joined the Giants in the winter of '96-97 in
the Matt Williams trade, 11 RBIs and four homers in the series,
following an 0-for-21 skid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a home-run hitter,'' said Kent, who is wearing a
lighter knee brace than the bulky device he tried after coming off
the disabled list July 10. ``It just happened. ... I didn't hit it
very high, so the wind didn't knock it down. I have been playing in
Candlestick for a year and three-quarters. I know the winds.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
