<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS' OFFENSIVE LINE SHOWING PROMISE 
BY IRA MILLER
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _It's a sure sign summer is here: There's
serious concern about the state of the 49ers' offensive line. It's
an area the team neglected for years, getting by largely with late
draft choices and free agents, and putting the line together has
become an annual adventure in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But one week into training camp, the reviews are good. Derrick
Deese has adapted at right tackle, Harris Barton is well along
toward a successful comeback, the depth looks decent and coach
Steve Mariucci says his concerns are easing a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to be as good or better than last year, provided we
stay healthy,'' Mariucci said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bobb McKittrick, the offensive line coach, judged the first week
of practice as ``a good one,'' saying it went about the way he
hoped. Said McKittrick: ``I didn't want anyone to be just horrible,
lay an egg, and nobody did.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' line remains a work in progress. Right guard Kevin
Gogan hasn't practiced because of a hamstring problem, although
he's penciled in to begin work Tuesday. Left tackle Jamie Brown has
missed some time because of a groin problem.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, things look more promising than they did the past
two years, when the 49ers were forced to scramble and begin the
season with a starting offensive lineman who had been out of work
just a few days before the opening game. In 1996, they signed Steve
Wallace to play left tackle and in 1997 they brought back Jesse
Sapolu to play center.
</P>
<P>
   For 1998, however, it looks like all the linemen the team might
need already are here.
</P>
<P>
   There are four main reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Deese, a guard moved to left tackle in an in-season emergency
move last year, has had time to settle in at right tackle. This
year, he had the offseason to bulk up for tackle, adding about
seven pounds and also working on his skills at that position.
</P>
<P>
   McKittrick believes the feisty Deese will be the team's most
improved player _ and he didn't play badly last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows I'm not a 6-7, 320-pound tackle,'' said Deese,
who's actually 6-3 and 292. ``You know what, I'll go out and fight
for you and do what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Barton appears to be showing little effect from the four knee
operations he endured last year, and his return is a huge boost for
the depth of the line. Mariucci said he was amazed at the way
Barton has been scampering around athletically, just as he used to
do. A longtime starting tackle, Barton is now working on the
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Fiore, who has been in the NFL for two years without
getting into a game, has made it back from his own knee surgery a
year ago and shown the coaches enough that he is listed as the top
backup at tackle. And Tim Hanshaw, who was victimized last season
in an ill-fated attempt to make him a tackle, shows signs he might
be able to make it as a guard.
</P>
<P>
   Hanshaw has been filling in for Gogan in practice, although
Mariucci says Barton, who has been working mostly at center, would
be his first backup guard. McKittrick says Hanshaw looks better
than he did in his three previous seasons with the 49ers, which
isn't really saying much. More to the point, McKittrick said, ``He
looks like an NFL football player. He knows what he's doing, and he
does it with intensity. He's a much better pass protector inside
than outside.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers also are developing three rookie linemen they drafted.
Second-round pick Jeremy Newberry, a guard/center, who underwent
offseason knee surgery, could be healthy by mid-season. Third-round
pick Chris Ruhman, a tackle, clearly needs more work on pass
blocking, especially on the right side; little is expected of him
anytime soon. Mariucci said yesterday that fifth-rounder Phil
Ostrowski was ``coming around pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   If everything works right _ a big if _ this could actually wind
up being a pretty good area for the 49ers. But Brown, the
first-year starter at left tackle, has to prove he can hold down a
job, and Barton, Fiore and Hanshaw must continue to progress. Among
other things, the depth that would provide would enable the 49ers
to bring their rookie linemen along slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1991-92 have the 49ers started the same offensive line
two years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
