u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-PAZIENZA-BROWN-BO     07-27 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-PAZIENZA-BROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAZIENZA DOWNS BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET PEQUOT RESERVATION, Conn. _ The 10th and final
round, as dramatic and stunningly savage as it was, would have made
a perfect climax to the movie Vinny Pazienza hopes to star in about
his miraculous comeback to the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Idle for more than eight months after losing a 12-round decision
to World Boxing Council International champion Herol Graham Dec. 6
in London, Pazienza made a triumphant return after a four-year
exile from Foxwoods Resort and Casino, where the Providence native
has reigned as one of the more popular draws, by scoring a 10-round
majority decision over tough super middleweight Glenwood ``The Real
Beast'' Brown at Fox Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the hell is it with me, making these guys rise to the
occasion?'' said Pazienza (42-7), who recovered from a jarring left
hook in the third that bloodied his nose and dropped him to a knee.
``Geez, he was supposed to be washed up. But he's a nice kid and
I'm kinda glad for him. Sunday was his (31st) birthday and at the
weigh-in, I said, `I like you Glenwood, but if I hurt you, stay in
your stool. Don't make me do it.' Then, during the fight, when he
gave me a head butt and gave a little cut in the eighth round, he
said in the ring, `Sorry, Vinny. I didn't mean that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `This guy's all right.' So then in the 10th
round, we went at it. It was a great round. I can't wait to see the
replays.''
</P>
<P>
   Pazienza's trainer, Kevin Rooney, implored his fighter to box
Brown, but mindful of the fact that Brown had yet to be knocked
out, Pazienza emerged from his corner in the 10th with other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just box,'' Rooney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin, I'm going to knock him out,'' Pazienza replied.
</P>
<P>
   Winless in his last four fights, Brown, from Willingboro, N.J.,
made what was his last appearance as a super middleweight his best
by withstanding a savage barrage from Pazienza in the 10th that was
reminiscent of ``Raging Bull.'' Only this time, Brown faced a
Raging Pazmanian Devil, who unloaded 113 punches and landed 66. In
all, Pazienza landed 280 of 596 punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit Vinny with that left hook in the third, I thought
it was all over,'' said Brown. ``But he showed what a great
champion he was by coming back. I hit him with some great shots,
too. But he took them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of two tuneups Pazienza planned before an
anticipated December challenge against Charles Brewer for the
International Boxing Federation super middleweight title. Then,
it'll be off to Hollywood, where Pazienza hopes to star in a film
project based on his life and his comeback from neck and spinal
injuries suffered in a 1991 car accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a durable warrior,'' Pazienza said of Brown. ``I hit
hard, and I know I surprised him a couple of times, but man, he
just wouldn't go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
