<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3929 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COP-SHOT-1STLD-WRI     07-27 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COP-SHOT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. CITY POLICE OFFICER IS CRITICAL AFTER BEING SHOT IN HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New York City police officer was fighting for his
life after being shot in the head on Sunday night on Staten Island,
apparently by a 17-year-old parolee who was wanted for questioning
on a new murder charge, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Gerard Carter, 28, was on a routine patrol of the
West Brighton Houses project when he was shot at 9:25 p.m. in front
of 810 Henderson Avenue, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said at a news
conference at St. Vincent's Hospital on Staten Island. He was
listed in critical condition, and was undergoing brain surgery with
his mother, ex-wife and girlfriend in close quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Shatiek Johnson, was paroled in April after serving
one and a half years for a 1996 manslaughter conviction, the police
said. He was arrested earlier this summer on a farebeating charge,
but somehow slipped through the parole system. He was most recently
wanted for questioning in the July 16 shooting death of Eric
Trotman, 20, on Staten Island, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's incident was the most serious shooting of a New
York City police officer since May, when a police officer was
fatally shot in Brooklyn while trying to arrest a parolee.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that two officers had been shot, allegedly, by two
parolees in the last three months, Giuliani last night railed _
again _ against a parole system that he has long said needs to be
reformed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another example of the parole system putting the lives
of police officers and other innocent citizens at risk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was sitting in a marked police van, in uniform and on
duty, when at least one shot pierced the front windshield, Valerie
St. Rose, a police spokeswoman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors reported hearing two quick shots that they said
sounded like discharges from a handgun. Then they saw the wounded
officer, face down, slumped over the steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as close to a cold-blooded act as I've seen in many
years,'' said First Deputy Police Commissioner Patrick Kelleher,
who joined Giuliani at the hospital on Sunday night. ``That a
police officer in uniform in a marked vehicle be appraoched at
point-blank range and shot is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   The officer's partner, Eric Storch, 29, was not wounded in the
shooting but was traumatized, said police spokesman Officer Dennis
Laffin. He was treated at and released from Bayley Seton Hospital,
said a spokeswoman there.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred in a section of Staten Island that is
dominated by the sprawling West Brighton Houses housing projects.
There is a large courtyard in the middle of the projects, and that,
according to neighbors, was where the officer was shot on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The police are known to maintain a visible presence in the
projects, mainly to crack down on beer drinking and drug activity,
neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Carter was driving on a pathway through the housing
development, with Storch at his side, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   They were seeking to question Johnson, who had missed a day of
community service _ his sentence after the farebeating arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The officer saw one and perhaps three people and slowed the van
to a stop, the police said. At the point, Johnson approached and
fired through windshield, hitting Carter in the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Storch returned the fire with one or two shots, both of which
missed their target.
</P>
<P>
   After the shots rang out, neighborhood children who were riding
bicycles past the van reported hearing Storch saying: ``Jerry,
Jerry, wake up! Stop playing! Yo Jerry, get up, get up!''
</P>
<P>
   The police then responded with breathtaking speed and urgency,
the neighbors said. And within minutes, it seemed, they had
blanketed the entire area with every imaginable police unit wearing
every imaginable uniform wielding every imaginable piece of
equipment, neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came from every angel,'' said one woman who declined to
give her name. ``They came from all angles.''
</P>
<P>
   Late on Sunday night, the police were still frantically pursuing
Johnson, describing him as a black male between 5 feet 6 and 5 feet
8, with dreadlocks, wearing shorts and a multi-colored shirt. They
had even established checkpoints at all the Staten Island
crossings.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that they believed that Johnson was still in the
housing projects, and were preparing to conduct an apartment by
apartment search.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani praised Carter, who also has a six-year-old son, for
having a brief but impressive record on the force, saying that the
officer had made 76 arrests in five years, many of them felonies.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was the most serious shooting of a New York City
police officer since May, when an officer, Anthony Mosomillo, 36,
was fatally shot in Brooklyn while trying to arrest a parolee who
had missed a court date on a drug charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
