A3981 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVRACE-TVDEBATES-SFC     07-27 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVRACE-TVDEBATES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TV SERIES FOR FALL _ DAVIS/LUNGREN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLA MARINUCCI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; The California governor's race _ all but
ignored by TV news this spring in favor of trash and flash _ could
become the most visible in the nation under an experimental program
to broadcast weekly prime-time debates statewide this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The project of the Alliance for Better Campaigns, which is
co-chaired nationally by veteran newscaster Walter Cronkite and
former Washington Post reporter Paul Taylor, has won the backing of
four of the state's major network affiliates: San Francisco's KRON,
Sacramento's KCRA, Los Angeles' KCBS and KGTV in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The stations, in a plan agreed to in principle by the
candidates, will allow Democratic Lt. Gov. Gray Davis and
Republican state Attorney General Dan Lungren to face off in a
series of live, five-minute debates, broadcast weekly on evening
newscasts for eight weeks preceding the Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   The project would mark the first time in memory that regular
airtime has been offered to political candidates _ particularly
during prime-time news shows, Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The format, while still taking shape, is designed to present
unscripted exchanges, `` `Nightline' or `Crossfire' style,'' he
said. ``You want it to be informative; you also want it to be
engaging.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes as Lungren and Davis prepare to meet
Friday at 6 p.m. in San Diego for the first of what is expected to
be five hourlong gubernatorial debates.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the debates could make the 1998 gubernatorial
race the most televised statewide campaign debate series in
California history, political insiders said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything would compare in the modern era,'' said
Dave Puglia, campaign adviser to Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to improve campaign coverage follows widespread
criticism of broadcast journalism's role in reporting the June 2
primary. In Southern California, particularly, many stations
slotted only minimal coverage of political topics in favor of
flashier news and crime stories.
</P>
<P>
   The reporting vacuum resulted in what many analysts called a
``virtual campaign,'' composed almost entirely of television
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you really see is a campaign that promises voters a much
greater level of context and information about the candidates'
character, background, experience and vision,'' said Puglia.
``California's broadcasters are recognizing they do have a public
service responsibility as it relates to political campaigns.
There's a lot of reason to be very encouraged by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the benefits to political campaigns of boosting
televised exchanges between the gubernatorial candidates could be
huge in a state where the cost of getting messages to 14.6 million
registered voters is astronomical, said Dan Schnur, the
high-profile GOP consultant who is a co-director of the state
project, along with Democratic consultant Michael Reese.
</P>
<P>
   But broadcasters also see benefits. ``Any opportunity to put the
issues in front of the voters is one that we're happy to take,''
said KRON News Director Dan Rosenheim. ``And the idea of
substantive _ although short _ minidebates that complement a longer
debate is really exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Schnur said that now that KRON, the NBC affiliate, has joined
with other network affiliates in California's major markets to
broadcast the minidebates live, TV stations in secondary markets
are clamoring to broadcast them on a taped basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means that California voters can turn on their TV set on
a particular day, at a particular time, and know they will see
substantive discussion between two candidates,'' Schnur said. ``We
believe there is an audience out there. . . . This is an
opportunity to build (it).'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There are still some details _ and a few problems _ to be worked
out, campaign managers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a laudable idea . . . and we've obviously been supportive
of the idea to get increased television coverage,'' said Garry
South, campaign adviser to Davis. ``But, in all honesty, I'm not
willing to give a blank check to these stations.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants to see ``ground rules established and also
agreed upon by the two campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   South said the short time span is another concern. ``Five
minutes is more time than a station spends on politics in any one
newscast _ but it's not a long time if you're discussing a
complicated issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said they will do everything possible to make those
minutes count and give both campaigns an active role.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public deserves campaigns that unfold on television in
ways that take the conversation beyond attack ads and sound
bites,'' said Taylor, who co-chairs the Alliance for Better
Campaigns under the auspice of the Annenberg Center for
Communication at the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think of politics as a product, a show that comes
around every couple of years, it is not a very good show,'' said
Taylor. ``So, let's see if we can change the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all,'' he said, ``this is merely about (voters')
futures, their water, their health care and their kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
