 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2466- JULY 27, 1998   NEWS and FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2466 -- July 27, 1998 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. PROTECTING THE WORLD'S REFUGEES Millions flee persecution and
war within their borders. The international community should be
ready to act when states fail to protect their own. By Roberta
Cohen and Francis M. Deng. From Foreign Affairs Magazine. 1,500
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
MY BORIS To American eyes, Boris Yeltsin, Russia's volatile
president, seems increasingly unmoored from reality. Michael
Specter, a New York Times correspondent who spent four years in
Moscow, offers an explanation of the warring impulses behind
Yeltsin's bluster. From The New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words.
3. A PLEA NOT TO REAWAKEN THE NUCLEAR ARMS RACE Today it is just as
true that if nuclear war, on any scale, were ever to be unleashed,
it would threaten the very existence of life on earth. It is
particularly important to keep this in mind in the wake of the
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan. What is not being discussed by
the established nuclear powers today is that the process of nuclear
disarmament has been stalled for several years now; it is just
marking time. By Mikhail Gorbachev. 1,000 words. 4. WORLD CRIMINAL
COURT NEEDS BETTER PREPARATION The notion of the ``international
community'' is often invoked nowadays. In recent years, it has
gathered more substance than ever before, with new treaties and
commitments. But it is still a misty idea groping for the
foundations of a global rule of law. By Flora Lewis. 1,000 words.
5. BUILDING THE NEW BERLIN The centre of Berlin today is the
largest construction site in Europe, a high-tech endeavour that is
pharaonic in scale. Berlin's dream is to be the ``Gateway to the
East,'' an affluent, service-oriented capital of Europe's richest
country and a beacon of hope to its neighbours in the East, where
prosperity remains elusive. Yet the early results, where visible,
hint at spectacular failure. By Gary Wolf. Wired magazine. 2,000
words. 6. THE IDEA OF CHANGING 'OIL PIPELINES FOR PEACE' GATHERS
</P>
<P>
   MOMENTUM IN THE CAUCASUS In the heart of Georgia, in the verdant
mountainous province of Sachker, 176 km. west of the capital
Tbilisi, excavators, bulldozers and cranes operated by Indian,
Pakistani and Georgian labourers are busy at work on the Baku-Supsa
oil pipeline. Early next year, the pipeline will carry some of the
oil extracted from the Caspian Sea to the Black Sea terminal at
Supsa. Georgia, which possesses no natural resources and has been
devastated by a civil war, believes its salvation lies in its role
as a gateway through which the wealth of the Caspian Sea can be
channelled westwards. By Marie Jego. Le Monde. (English translation
available.) 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
A SURVEY OF ANCIENT MARS Scientists have seen lots of big smooth
rocks on the surface of Mars, remnants of catastrophic flooding in
the distant past. But where did all that water go? New images from
Mars Global Surveyor hint at some answers. By Jeffrey Winters. From
Discover magazine. 1,600 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE: A. Splashdown : Look at all those
swirling patterns in a Pollock painting. Richard Taylor asks
whether they're satisfying more than your aesthetic self. B. Washed
Up : A clean beach is a lifeless one, says Fred Pearce, who has
found that seaweed, sewage and woodlice are encouraging sights. C.
Mean Machines : This is a story about big boys and their hot,
explosive toys. In garages and sheds all over the world, they're
building jet engines ... By Scott LaFee. D. Final Summer : The
ultimate summer is on its way. The Earth will be baked by a searing
heat and the oceans will boil away. It's going to be hotter than
hell. Charles Seife is very grateful that he won't be there. 9. ARE
U.S. TROOPS NEEDED IN JAPAN? Americans see the presence of U.S.
troops in Japan as a gracious favour. It's time for the Americans
to go home, writes Morihiro Hosokawa. From Foreign Affairs
magazine. 1,500 words. 10. MATERIALS : SPECIAL DELIVERY One of the
most effective ways of administering a drug is to pack it up in a
form that can be transported around the body, and to release it
exactly when and where it is needed. A promising new approach seems
to overcome some of the problems encountered. By Helen Phillips.
Nature News Service. (N/A France and Spain.) 600 words. Embargo :
1800 GMT Wednesday July 29.
</P>
