<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-1950S-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE, PEOPLE! THERE'S MORE TO '50S THAN DRIVE-INS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American people continue to astonish and perplex me. In
fact, I'm this close to admitting I have no clue what, if anything,
makes them tick. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's the latest outrage: To decide what to put on upcoming
commemorative stamps, the U.S. Postal Service asked people to vote
on the most memorable events and people of the 1950s and 1960s.
There were 30 choices for each decade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the '50s winners list were drive-in movies, the
``I Love Lucy'' TV series and ``The Cat in the Hat'' by Dr. Seuss.
For the '60s, the top finishers were the first moon walk, the first
Super Bowl and the peace symbol. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying I don't remember all that stuff. I certainly do.
But you simply can't convince me that drive-in movies were the most
significant achievement of the '50s or that the start of the annual
Super Bowl deserves such prominence in the '60s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As my 8th grade English teacher, Ruth Wilson, used to say in the
1950s when she was moved to slack-jawed awe by the obtuseness of
her students, ``People, people, people!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heck, I'd have voted for Ruth Wilson her own prim self before
I'd have voted for ``The Cat in the Hat.'' At least Miss Wilson
knew how to diagram a sentence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You hardly have to break open the '50s before you find some
simply amazing happenings that I'd love to see on a stamp long
before drive-in movies. For instance, the day I turned five years
old, Jan. 18, 1950, the U.S. Senate repealed the federal tax on
oleomargarine despite pressure from dairy groups. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The county in which I lived at the time in northern Illinois
was, it was said, the largest dairy-producing county in the
country. We had cows everywhere. Some of my best friends were
cows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't imagine for a minute that lifting the tax on oleo didn't
create quite a stir. Why, even as I entered Mrs. Dobbs'
kindergarten class that fall my classmates and I were still
carrying on about it. Probably. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days later in 1950, Alger Hiss was found guilty of
perjury. And ever since then our lives have been filled with hot
debate over whether Hiss was really a traitor. I have had Hiss on
my mind for more than 48 years, and would love to see his trial
commemorated on a stamp. Maybe that would allow us now to give him
the nickname I've always thought he should have had _ Boo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of gross oversights, the Korean War came in 15th among
stamp voters for the 1950s, and because the top 15 vote getters
will be commemorated on stamps, it's a winner. But the Cold War
lost. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People, people, people: Without the Cold War my grade-school
friends and I would not have learned how to hide under our desks so
we could survive a nuclear strike. I don't know what those tough
little desks were made of, but I was certain that mine would
protect me from enemy A-bombs. I'd buy a whole roll of stamps
showing kids hiding under school desks in bomb drills. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the 1960s, I admit the moon walk was a big deal. But I've
always been a little miffed at its timing. It happened the same
week that Ted Kennedy drove his car off the Dike Bridge on
Chappaquiddick Island, meaning Mary Jo Kopechne's death and
Kennedy's labyrinthine denials of responsibility didn't get the
media coverage they deserved. Why can't NASA plan better than
that? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I myself, in the '60s, was celebrating graduation first from
high school and then college, after which I degenerated into
journalism. And after all these years I finally know why: So that
now and then I can hold American citizens up to the ridicule they
deserve. People, people, people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
