<SLUG> BC-R-NIGERIA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
25.)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, July BURYING ABIOLA: ONE FALSE STEP BETRAYS NIGERIA's DESPERATION  
 (The Week in Review)  
 (duplication warning: also sent with `i' code)  
 (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ The day, sultry beneath low clouds, had long
been pregnant with violence. Gathered within the high walls of the
mansion, the crowd heaved this way and that, screaming abuse at the
soldiers outside, waiting for the body. In their eyes lay anger and
anguish and a frenzied desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Watching from a terrace in the house, I imagined the spark: a
soldier's shot, a knife drawn, a woman crushed against a wall and
this gathering would give way to killing. Bloodshed was coming as
surely as the day's heat was mounting. But no. Through some
unfathomable chemistry, a path was carved through the throng for
the corpse of Moshood K.O. Abiola, the Nigerian opposition leader
who died this month in detention.
</P>
<P>
   An unspoken language existed then, one inaudible to me. Nigeria,
cobbled together on a whim by a British colonizer in 1914, an
impossible amalgam of Islam, Christianity and other religions, land
of more than 200 ethnic groups and at least three unrelated
languages, was bound to disintegrate one day under the weight of
its contradictions. Or was it, I wondered, if this sense of
inevitable danger could so subside into order?
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly, the body that had carried the long-frustrated
democratic hopes of Africa's most populous nation appeared. Denied
his electoral victory in 1993 by the army, imprisoned in 1994, held
in solitary confinement, the man died in the company of U.S.
officials on the eve of a promised release that America had done
little to hasten.
</P>
<P>
   The body was wrapped in white cloth from head to foot, as Muslim
tradition requires. Abiola's many wives sobbed and wailed; his son,
Kola, and other male members of the family carried the body.
``Stop! Stop!'' somebody screamed, ``They are not ready.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They will never be ready,'' his son shouted. ``We're going
out.''
</P>
<P>
   As the corpse was carried into the yard, the path was swallowed
up by the crowd. I was lifted off my feet by the surge. I glimpsed
smashed chairs, a shattered lamp with blood on it and the face of a
terrified woman. The body disappeared toward its grave under a palm
tree. African chants and Muslim prayer rose in a strange unison.
</P>
<P>
   A young man, dressed all in black, the outfit that day of
Abiola's most devoted followers, took my arm. He said he would push
me to the graveside. It seemed an impossible task. But with the
help of others like him, he guided me there. I saw the feverishly
shoveled red earth falling into the grave. And, at that moment,
with the faces fixed in a rictus of grief, I felt the hand in my
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   I looked around. It was the young man who had helped me who was
now trying to pick my pocket as Abiola was at last buried. He
withdrew his hand. We exchanged glances. Not a word was spoken. In
his face, pain and shame mingled.
</P>
<P>
   I could not get his face out of my mind. Or the smell of that
crowd, a smell of sweat, of labor, of grinding effort in the heat,
of thankless toil. So far from the air-conditioned rooms where
Western diplomats had told me of Abiola's checkered past, his sweet
deals with the army, his odd calls for reparations for the slave
trade and the political problems posed by his insistence that the
``mandate'' of 1993 was still valid.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats are paid, above all, to promote their nations'
interests. We journalists are paid, above all, to record what we
see. A tension between these visions is inevitable. I could not
help feeling that Abiola had become a kind of abstraction to
America and its companies, an irritant when set beside the
importance of Nigerian stability and the outstanding, almost
sulphur-free quality of Nigeria's abundant ``Bonny Light'' crude
oil.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola's road had been a circuitous one. Rising from abject
poverty to become an executive of ITT, he had worked closely with
military governments on several communications projects and been a
member of the conservative National Party of Nigeria in the 1980s.
Insistent, but unconfirmed, reports here suggest he also worked for
the CIA. In the 1990s he veered toward the progressive Social
Democratic Party and put the eradication of poverty at the center
of his populist message.
</P>
<P>
   But what else in calamitous, vibrant, desperate, corrupt and
captivating Nigeria could one be but a populist? In the end, Abiola
brought hope for the millions living in shanties without work, hope
to the youth who tried to pick my pocket.
</P>
<P>
   That, in substantial part, is why his message reached across the
country, over tribal and ethnic barriers, earning this man from the
Yoruba south enormous support in the mainly Hausa and Fulani north.
Nigerians, tired of being robbed by their military leaders,
believed that this rich man would give back to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most basic belief of Abiola was that others should not
have to go through the suffering he endured to get an education,''
his friend, a former finance minister, Onaolapo Soleye, told me.
``We were at Baptist school together and he always sang the hymn:
`And if I be lifted up from the earth, I will draw all men unto
me.'''
</P>
<P>
   I T will never be known what Abiola might have achieved for the
``giant of Africa,'' where perhaps 60 million people now live in
poverty. What is certain is that the man who usurped his place, the
late Gen. Sani Abacha, plundered Nigeria's material and human
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian journalist Osita Nwajah last week called Abacha ``the
most recognizably evil Nigerian ever.'' But America held back from
oil sanctions, because, as one official explained, ``Oil is the
most fungible of commodities and it would have served no purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But the rapaciousness of Abacha and the other generals
before him staggers the mind. And where lies the cause of this
readiness to steal by those who, in the words of a young man named
Olu Aki, ``control people but are controlled by nobody?''
</P>
<P>
   I have heard many answers. In this coup-ravaged country, time in
office may be brief, so Nigeria's ``big men'' make their fortunes
quickly. People will think them stupid if they fail to become
``big'' from power.
</P>
<P>
   The one answer I have not heard is that Africa's white rulers
long stole _ gold, minerals, oil, people. Perhaps their example
stuck.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the funeral, I wandered into the Lagos slum of
Makoko, where perhaps 500,000 people live on a black lagoon that is
also an open sewer. I followed a youth to a home that was always
around the next corner.
</P>
<P>
   As we walked deeper into the slum, the raised wooden planks over
the stinking water became ever narrower and more unstable. The
water loomed, indescribable in its filth, and nausea and vertigo
swept over me. All Makoko seemed to sway in its Conradian horror. I
owed it to this kid to continue; I steadied myself. And I thought
that I understood more then of the desperation of the crowd at the
burial.
</P>
<P>
   I do not know if Abiola would have swept Makoko away and
provided decent housing. I do know that I wish I had not felt the
slithering hand in my pocket of the youth who helped me and needed
my help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
