<SLUG> BC-R-DUMB-ACCIDENTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
25.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, July (ATTN: Alaska)  
 I'VE FALLEN AND I'M A REAL JERK  
 (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANDREA KANNAPELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The noble idea of rescue comes alive in news stories about brave
men and women risking life and limb to snatch desperate adventurers
from the jaws of death on treacherous summits or in raging waters.
The drama is compelling: Will they make it in time?
</P>
<P>
   But the day-to-day reality of an emergency worker's life often
involves victims who, more than anything, need a Saint Bernard with
a little cask of common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felony stupidity,'' Ken Goodwin, the assistant director of the
National Sheriff's Association, calls it.
</P>
<P>
   Take a recent day in Alaska, one of the more rescue-oriented
states. Because Alaska has vast airspace for military training, it
is home to the para-rescue team of the 210th Squadron of the Air
National Guard. There are only three such teams in the nation.
These troops can jump out of airplanes with scuba gear, mountain
climbing equipment or other paraphernalia to help floundering
victims unreachable by any other means. At a moment's notice, the
210th's team will head off for Mount McKinley or other exotic
locations to fulfill their heroic motto: ``That others may live.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, the team rushed into action in a small jet after the
pilot of a plane flying about 70 miles northwest of Anchorage
reported an SOS stamped out in the snow. The team found the SOS,
spotted its author and dropped him a two-way radio, said Capt. Mike
Haller, a spokesman for the rescuers. ``He said, `Uh, yeah, I need
to be rescued, but I don't want any help from the feds.''' Just
then, the team was diverted to another call and left the man to
ponder his options.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 miles away, a state trooper was watching three 20-ish
tourists traipsing across the mud flats of Turnagain Arm, named for
a navigational necessity discovered by Capt. James Cook, the 18th
century explorer. The tide there retreats, then returns with a
powerful rush. The hapless pedestrians apparently did not know that
the incoming tide turns the mud into a kind of quicksand that can
trap anyone in its path. ``It's a horrible way to die,'' Haller
said. Just a week earlier, a man had drowned there while canoeing
in a rough tide.
</P>
<P>
   So the rescue jet, flying at extremely low altitude to dodge the
heavy planes of the air corridor directly above Turnagain Arm,
dropped a message telling the tourists to stay put. A short time
later, a helicopter swooped in and scooped them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really had put a lot of people out, and put a lot of
people at risk,'' Captain Haller said. And they were apparently
delighted, he added. ``I had a local reporter call me later and say
they just didn't get it,'' he said. ``They thought it was really
cool having this air show drop in on them.''
</P>
<P>
   But back to Mr. Anti-Fed. The unit changed crews and returned to
the SOS site with a couple of state troopers aboard. ``Him, they
took to the Alaska Psychiatric Institute,'' Haller said.
``Apparently, he called the troopers back later and said, `I don't
want to be here.' To which, I guess, the answer was, `Tough.'''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for those with poor judgment everywhere, rescuers like
the team at the 210th say they retain their good will. The Mountain
Rescue Association, an all-volunteer network of dozens of such
teams across the nation, resists pressure to charge people _ even
the most thoughtless _ for rescue services.
</P>
<P>
   ``What precedes an accident isn't our concern,'' said Commander
Mike Lapinski, a Coast Guard spokesman, though he acknowledged that
there might be a few people ``that we'd like to bring back here and
take out to the woodshed.''
</P>
<P>
   The commitment remains, even in the aftermath of tragedy. At
Denali National Park, which includes Mount McKinley, a rescuer died
this year, along with the climber he was trying to save. National
Park Service rangers try to keep from adding themselves to the toll
of the dead. ``There's only going to be one victim,'' said Daryl
Miller, the ranger who oversees rescues at Denali.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard lost three crew members last year in one of its
only recorded instances of rescue fatalities. Waves twice rolled
the rescue boat as it headed toward a sailboat whose mast had
broken in a storm. The Coast Guard spends $350 million a year to
answer 50,000 emergency calls, rescuing an average of more than a
dozen people a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on your valuing of human life,'' he said, ``there's
a great return on your investment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
