A4114 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MEDICAL-PRIVACY-REV     07-27 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MEDICAL-PRIVACY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
25.)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, July MEDICAL IDs AND PRIVACY (OR WHAT'S LEFT OF IT)  
 (The Week in Review)  
(also see SOCIAL-SECURITY-REVIEW) 
(bl) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The coupons arrived by the handful when Janlori
Goldman was pregnant with her daughter, and she couldn't figure out
how the companies knew she was expecting. There were coupons for
parenting magazines, baby announcements, diapers and children's
book clubs. ``I started to wonder,'' she said. ``Where are they
getting this information? Is the hospital selling it? Is my doctor
making it available?''
</P>
<P>
   She never got an answer, but to Ms. Goldman, the questions were
of more than passing interest. As the founder of the Health Privacy
Project at Georgetown University, her goal is to raise the public's
awareness about the erosion of medical privacy. It has been an
uphill battle. ``Privacy,'' Ms. Goldman said, ``has not always been
a top-line issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the news last week that the Clinton administration,
following a 1996 congressional mandate, is considering assigning
every American a health-care identification number that could be
used to create a giant electronic data base capable of tracking
everyone's medical records from cradle to grave.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the concept of medical privacy was thrust into the
public spotlight, with some members of Congress suggesting that the
1996 provision be repealed. Privacy experts like Ms. Goldman argue
that the ``unique health identifier'' would make an already bad
problem worse, marking the final step in what has been a long march
from privacy to a virtual information free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to think that medical information was a bunch of
intimacies that you gave to your doctor and your doctor went into a
back room and locked it up,'' said Lawrence Gostin, a Georgetown
University law professor who is chairman of a health privacy task
force convened by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
``That is a world that doesn't exist anymore. Now you have huge,
large-scale data bases in government, managed care organizations,
pharmacies.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how that information is used, and who has access to it, is
anybody's guess. Although about 35 states have enacted laws
intended to protect the privacy of patients, there are no federal
protections.
</P>
<P>
   While insurance companies and hospitals must develop privacy
policies to become accredited, there are no uniform standards, in
part because there is no societal consensus on what should, and
should not, be released without patient consent. In the wake of the
debate on the health care identifier, Republicans included privacy
provisions in health-care legislation passed by the House on Friday
that would actually nullify stronger state protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a legislative mandate or a social policy of what
is fair use,'' said Paul Clayton, director of clinical information
services at New York Presbyterian Hospital. ``So there is nothing
to regulate your pharmacy benefits manager from selling the fact
that you got pregnancy vitamins to the diaper service company.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, for instance, CVS Corp., the national chain
of drugstores, acknowledged it had joined with pharmaceutical
manufacturers to help them market new medicines. The manufacturers
paid the chain to comb its prescription drug data banks for
patients with particular ailments; CVS then provided lists to a
direct marketing company that sent out letters promoting the
companies' drugs.
</P>
<P>
   CVS says it never sold information or released confidential
data. But when The Washington Post published an article about the
arrangement in February, the backlash was so swift that, within a
week, the program was abandoned. CVS spokeswoman Joan Kronin said,
``What we learned is that this is a very sensitive area.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive indeed. While patients don't mind sharing their
information for some health-care purposes, surveys find they don't
want it sold _ or used for research without their approval. A 1993
poll by Louis Harris &AMP; Associates, for instance, found that just 18
percent of respondents thought it acceptable for health records to
be used for research without patient consent; 60 percent found it
unacceptable for pharmacists to provide patient data to marketers.
And 96 percent wanted penalties for unauthorized disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the national penchant for privacy is competing with a huge
commercial appetite for patient data. On the Internet, Medical
Marketing Service Inc., an Illinois company, advertises its
``Patient Direct'' data base with more than 20 million American
households whose statistics can be sliced by age, gender, income,
educational status and health condition, from allergies (4,343,400
households) to yeast infections (1,364,800). The company says the
information is culled from voluntary consumer surveys.
</P>
<P>
   But Gostin, the Georgetown law professor, sees a ``gross privacy
violation'' nonetheless. ``It is true that people voluntarily fill
out the questionnaire,'' he said, ``but they couldn't dream of how
it is going to be used.''
</P>
<P>
   As the debate over how to protect privacy unfurls in Congress
and elsewhere, one of Ms. Goldman's aims is to figure out precisely
who is trading on medical information, and how. ``There is a lot we
don't know,'' she said. ``Our health care environment is changing
so rapidly, with the linking of doctors and health plans and drug
companies, the patient is completely left out of the loop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
