<HEADER>
A4159 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN29-CO     07-27 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Wet heat vs. dry heat: We all lose
 &HT;    (For release July 29, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Someone once asked me what was necessary to qualify to
write about food for a newspaper. The first prerequisite, I said,
was that he or she should have eaten food for at least 18 years.
Everything else could be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   I also feel this way about weather. What qualifies me to write
about it? First prerequisite: I've lived in it a long time. You
don't have to be a climatologist to recognize how you're feeling in
weather.
</P>
<P>
   (Don't you love the TV weather people who tell you _ with
expressive authority _ that if you thought it was hot today you
were right, it was hot today?)
</P>
<P>
   What exasperates me, however, is the constant reference by
people in the American West and Southwest, particularly when they
are speaking with someone from Florida, that at least their heat is
dry.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, I have blindly accepted this regional gloat,
despite the fact that I spent two years of my younger life in El
Paso, Texas _ one of America's great saunas in the summer months _
and should know better and should have spoken out then.
</P>
<P>
   I confess that Florida, particularly South Florida, is woefully
sticky and hot in the summer months, but I still don't know what is
so good about dry heat. In fact, I have, upon recent personal
experience, come to the conclusion that there is not 10 cents worth
of difference between dry heat and wet heat.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, I have been in sections of central and
northern California where the egg would fry BEFORE it hit the
sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but it was dry heat, the natives would boast.
</P>
<P>
   And likely it was. But what did that have to do with the fact
that at 106 degrees Fahrenheit, the perspiration has soaked through
your trousers, your watchband, down your forehead into your eyes
and the local weatherman is warning anyone who is young or old,
sick or healthy to stay indoors OR YOU MAY DIE!
</P>
<P>
   There was one day, while driving through a town en route to the
Gold Rush foothills northeast of Sacramento, that I stopped at a
service station for a cool drink. My rental car had one of those
unavoidable L.E.D. temperature reports on the dashboard, and it
read 118 degrees!
</P>
<P>
   I failed to detect the value of dry heat, as opposed to humid
heat, inasmuch as I hardly could draw a breath of any kind of air.
</P>
<P>
   All I could do is what I also do in wet-heat South Florida: get
the auto air conditioner going as cold as it can following a brief
period of being scalded on the hot seats of the car once I returned
with the drink.
</P>
<P>
   On the day I drove through Stockton, Calif., the San Francisco
49ers were beginning their first day of football practice _ at 108
degrees. All the time, I was wondering how the folks were back in
Florida, having to endure 93 wet degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The TV weathermen back there tell you its 93 degrees but with
the heat index (humidity) added in, it feels like 103 degrees.
Well, that still ain't 108 degrees!
</P>
<P>
   By the time I reached San Francisco (12 below zero at any time
of day), I was openly challenging anyone who claimed that
California's was a dry heat while Florida's was an intolerable wet
heat.
</P>
<P>
   No more of that dry heat stuff for me! I knew it was a ruse when
I lived in El Paso, felt more of it when I covered a national
political convention in Dallas _ which bathes in 100-degree-plus
temperatures with regularity _ and, now, have the experience of
open blistering in the San Joaquin and Sacramento valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Miami may be muggy but it's not much different than arid
Sacramento when it comes to uncomfortable weather: hot is hot, no
matter how wet or dry it is.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
