<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4318 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX28-COX     07-27 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marilyn Geewax's Business Commentary: Futurists banking on
 &HT;    `coming matriarchy'
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Last week in Chicago, about a thousand participants
at a World Future Society conference mulled over forecasts for the
21st century, trying to discern what changes would be coming around
the 2000 bend.
</P>
<P>
   While opinions varied on many issues, the futurists seemed to
have little doubt about this: Women will become the dominant
players in the economy and the home. The futurists referred to
``the coming matriarchy'' as an almost certain outcome of the
``post-divorce'' society.
</P>
<P>
   The forecasters were not saying whether these changes would be
good or bad for society, but simply that they would be inevitable
given the changes in education, technology and birth control.
</P>
<P>
   In this century, the traditional family consisted of a husband,
wife and children, with the husband bringing home the primary
paycheck. That financial arrangement made sense in the Industrial
Age when employers paid a premium for strong workers who could fill
jobs in mining and manufacturing. Women, who had little control
over the timing of their pregnancies, were not well-suited to the
dirty, dangerous workplaces of the early and mid-20th century.
</P>
<P>
   But the structure of the traditional family is changing as
women's wages rise. In the Information Age, women and men are able
to perform equally well in most jobs, so pay is equalizing. For
example, being an auto mechanic used to require considerable
strength for lifting heavy parts and using manual tools. But with
each passing year, the role of the mechanic has been changing.
Today, muscles are less important than having the training to
analyze data from computer-controlled diagnostic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   With employers paying a premium for education, women are finding
more reasons to stay in school. The U.S. Census Bureau recently
reported the proportion of women completing college has topped that
of men, and the lead is widening. Among women ages 25 to 29, just
over 29 percent had completed four years or more of college as of
1997. That compared with only 26.3 percent of men. In 1997, young
women also led men in completing high school, 88.9 percent to 85.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the 21st century, these well-educated women will become more
financially secure and less interested in marrying, the futurists
predict. That means the ``typical'' family soon will consist of a
mother and her children, with men taking their place at the
periphery of home life, according to one of the convention's
speakers, David S. Mercer, author of ``Future Revolutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The futurists who called the next hundred years the ``century of
women'' made no predictions about what such changes might mean for
daily life, but it would seem the impact on our notion of home
could be huge.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if the typical family of the future really is the
Murphy Brown model, with a working mom and her child, then maybe
our idea of the perfect home will change, too. Today, the
stereotypical metro Atlanta family gravitates toward a
2,200-square-foot house with a big yard in a leafy suburb. But for
single women, such dream homes can become nightmares of endless
tasks.
</P>
<P>
   If women are going to be picking out houses for themselves,
perhaps they will choose smaller quarters set in a communal
grouping where families can share a common dining room and child
care center.
</P>
<P>
   But what will become of the men who are not firmly tied to
family life? Men who don't marry have higher rates of unemployment
and incarceration. Will crime and social disorder increase if more
men find themselves out of work and living alone?
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest challenges of the next century may be keeping
young men in school long enough to mold them into useful
participants in the economy and family life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-24-98 2313E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
