A4322 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES2     07-27 0316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ShortTakes: Polling the masters
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, the movie industry polled itself, declaring
``Citizen Kane'' the best movie of the century. Well, fair enough.
The posthumous honor would have amused Orson Welles, Kane's
presiding genius, who was treated despicably for his trouble by
Hollywood's cash barons.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a new poll. This one of great English-language books. The
Modern Library, which worries for the nation about great books,
asked its board to select the best 100 of the century. The top
book: ``Ulysses,'' by James Joyce. Joyce would have agreed, while
bemused by our impulse to name the top everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ulysses'' is entitled. Joyce and a few others, Virginia Wolff,
Laurence Sterne (of a different century) and Marcel Proust, changed
literature and human thought in much the same way Beethoven changed
music and human thought by composing his Third Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ulysses'' remains one of the least-read of books, recording,
obscurely, the thoughts of a few people on June 16, 1904, in
Dublin. The book was declared obscene, bitterly condemned, and
barely got published. Which proves once again how one generation's
obscenity can be another's masterpiece. Politicians, fearing the
marketplace, love legislating art.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern Library has invited readers to nominate their great
books via its web site. The last time I looked their leader was
``Dune'' by Frank Herbert, closely followed by ``Atlas Shrugged''
by Ayn Rand. I was delighted to see John Kennedy Toole's ``A
Confederacy of Dunces'' hanging in at 99 with 16 votes. A bit of
dignified ballot box stuffing is needed here.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
