<HEADER>
A4329 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOING-SOUTH28-COX     07-27 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOING-SOUTH28-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Take a lesson in summer survival from the folks at the border
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Beach
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Nuevo Leon _ We came to partake of the unbearable
hotness of being. In this summer of killing, creeping, sapping
heat, we came for border hot.
</P>
<P>
   We came to see how this heat is different from the heat we've
been wilting from in Austin. We came not to escape the heat but to
complain about it in a different place _ and had we known it was
110 degrees, we would have produced an opera of complaint. Such was
our good fortune that we were here when it was, yes, that hot.
</P>
<P>
   You can say our mission was stupid; we chose to think of it as
profound. You can hurl your non-dairy whipped topping pies of
mockery and derision; we will wear them as creamy badges of honor.
</P>
<P>
   At first, before 8 a.m., it was not yet hot on the border. In
the square outside La Posada Hotel , near the bridge in Laredo,
people were waiting for buses. They were comfortable because _ and
here I'm about to introduce a fairly arcane scientific term with
which you're probably not familiar, but bear with me _ heat along
this part of the border is a ``dry heat.'' This means the relative
humidity is much lower than in Austin, where the outside air is so
saturated with water that you can't breathe without scuba gear.
This ``dry heat'' means when you step out from air conditioning
into the world of Nuevo Laredo, your glasses don't fog over like
the airstrip in ``Casablanca.'' Being outside in Austin, by
contrast, is like being a pancake slathered in butter and hot Aunt
Jemima maple syrup.
</P>
<P>
   But because of this ``dry heat,'' people were in a state of
not-hotness. To make matters worse, there was a good breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is a city of innumerable squares, named for
revolutionaries and politicians and heroic postal officials, where
people would surely congregate to be hot. And so we paid our 35
cents to formally leave the United States and we walked across the
bridge. The south-to-north morning rush was chugging along with
pedestrians and cars full of people not breaking a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   The first square we came to contained no people being hot, just
a bunch of those large wooden shoeshine stands painted the same
unwavering institutional hospital green. We walked past the
duty-frees, the bars and restaurants, none of which contained
people being hot. We walked all the way to His Majesty the Taco,
the restaurant with the grandest name in all the world, but it was
not yet open and it was not yet hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's hot enough yet, Pat,'' Larry Kolvoord, the
photographer who came with me to chronicle the hot, said.
</P>
<P>
   We walked until we got very uncomfortable and we complained, but
no one was interesting in singing along. Hot is what it is here.
The awnings on the shop fronts roll down to about shoulder height,
so the sun isn't in your face. A few people carry umbrellas. One
woman on the street held a small battery-powered fan to the face of
her sleeping child. Hot's not news the way it is news in Dallas or
Austin or Wichita Falls. People move around and hug shade and get
through life and do not complain, as we Austinites do.
</P>
<P>
   Only the tourists complain, and there aren't that many of them
these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody comes over,'' said Eloy Garcia, who runs a drink stand
in the market area. ``The Saturdays look like Sundays and the
Sundays look like Mondays.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said his business was down 75 percent to 80 percent
because of the hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's complaining,'' he said. ``I hear the crying.
``I've been here 14 years and this is the worst year ever.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Tuesdays look like ... well, they looked like plenty of
tables and no waiting, even at the venerable El Dorado Bar. The El
Dorado is better than any Mexican restaurant in Austin because the
waiters all wear natty white jackets and none of them have tongue
studs. The waiters hereare gentlemen who wait with their whole
being, who comport themselves with grace and dignity. The waiters
at the El Dorado Bar are the best waiters in civilization, and they
are reason enough to go there, although it doesn't hurt that the
place has gin fizzes and Cuban cigars.
</P>
<P>
   So we asked our waiter, ``Any people complaining about the
heat?''
</P>
<P>
   And he shook his head and smiled, as if to say, ``If I had heard
any complaints, sir, it would be indiscreet of me to pass them
along.''
</P>
<P>
   For locals, talking about the hot is like Sociology 101:
Introduction to The Obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere people kept saying things like, ``You think this is
hot? I live in Louisiana or Saudi Arabia or Alaska and that's
hot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no breeze in Louisiana blowin' _ unless it's a hot
breeze,'' said Tamara Baxter of Marthaville, La. ``Our barn burned
down. That's how hot it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Next: ``As far as I'm concerned, it's hot as hell from here to
Canada,'' said Russell ``Stubby'' Turnbull, an actual Canadian who
was hot. ``It's bad at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Stubby hauls dairy cattle from Paris, Ontario, to Mexico, and
has for decades, so Stubby knows something about I-35 and hot. He
brought his wife, Joan, and one of his 22 grandchildren along on
this run, and they were all having quite a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the heat,'' said Mrs. Stubby, a k a Joan Turnbull, as
she lit a Benson &AMP; Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   Next: ``Vietnam was much worse,'' said Chuck Krumholtz of San
Marcos. ``The humidity is a lot worse there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's always worse somewhere else, and it wasn't too hot to keep
people from toiling. Vendors were still on the streets, preparing
to relieve tourists of their dollars in exchange for baskets,
Tweety Bird pin(tilde)atas, blankets, chewing gum, cartons of
cigarettes, belts, silver and marionettes. Nor was it too hot to
keep the hustlers from working: ``What you want? Women? Vitamins?''
</P>
<P>
   Relief, actually. Barring that, acceptance. And that's what we
can learn from Nuevo Laredoans: Getting cranky never chilled
anybody out. Larry and I even picked up on the vibe a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   It was 110 degrees, and we couldn't even tell. The opera closed
before it could open.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Beach is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
