NYT-07-27-98 1110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4332 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUNO28-COX     07-27 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNO28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Juno tries new tack to entice Net users
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most coveted Internet users are the ones who don't really
know how to use the Web.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring, Earthlink, WorldNet and other Internet service
providers know the best way to garner new subscribers is to lure
light users away from services like America Online or other
``starter'' services such as the free e-mail services, including
HotMail or Juno, and ``graduate'' them to a full-fledged ISP.
</P>
<P>
   Juno (http://www.juno.com), the popular, advertiser-supported
free e-mail service, realized the day is coming when its 5.5
million users will want to do more on the Net than just send
e-mail. They are, in the words of Juno President Charles Ardai, ``a
group that has taken its first step onto the Internet.'' Rather
than watch them drift off to other ISPs, Juno has decided to try to
become an ISP itself.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, the company unveiled two additional levels of
service: Juno Gold and Juno Web. Juno Gold goes beyond the free
e-mail service, adding the ability to send and receive graphic
attachments such as spreadsheets, pictures and other non-text
attachments.
</P>
<P>
   Juno Web will give users Web browsing capabilities using either
Netscape or Internet Explorer browsers. Search engine Lycos
(http://www.lycos.com) will provide the gateway, or portal, for the
Juno Web users. Juno Gold will be priced at $2.95 per month, while
Juno Web will cost $19.95 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Chernins, Juno's executive vice president, said the new Juno
services make the company into a ``full-fledged online service that
will offer choices to our users.'' With more than 5 million Juno
users, the company's ISP venture has the potential to become one of
the nation's largest ISPs, although the company won't say how much
of its user base it expects to convert to the paid services.
</P>
<P>
   Juno has critics
</P>
<P>
   But offering e-mail and Web browsing does not an online service
make, according to Forrester Research analyst Chris Charron. ``To
call Juno the second-largest ISP after America Online is stretching
the definition a little,'' he says. ``Lycos' content may help Juno
provide better value that may result in more paying customers. But
sandwiching e-mail together with portal content doesn't guarantee
success as an online service.''
</P>
<P>
   Charron says there are a lot of ``pieces of the puzzle'' Juno
needs to add to its mix before it can call itself a full-fledged
online service.
</P>
<P>
   However, Charron still says Juno's partnership with Lycos is a
good deal for both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lycos) may help improve the prospects for people signing up,
but it doesn't automatically make them a portal site,'' Charron
says. ``But if they want to build their e-mail service into
something more, this is a good first start.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Lycos, Charron says, ``Lycos needs traffic, and the deal
with Juno brings them added distribution. It's the opportunity to
put Lycos in front of another 5 million people.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Juno's big ISP plans, Chernins says Juno will never
abandon its free e-mail model. ``Some people will still only want
to send e-mail at no cost,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But hopefully, significant numbers of users will graduate to
the other services. We think newbies and users will want choices.
It's not a one-size-fits-all proposition. We think a significant
portion of our user base will subscribe to one or more as our
business evolves.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernins says Juno also plans to offer other products to
subscribers after Juno Gold and Juno Web are well established.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've cultivated 5 million pairs of eyeballs, and if we can
convert a portion of that, we'll have a significant business,''
Chernins says. ``We believe they will be terrific retention tools
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   PSunday, July 26, 1998 The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
