<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money Talk: More women preparing for retirement
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Women, nudged by necessity and the ever-hungry
financial services industry, are getting more active and more savvy
about saving for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   One-fourth of all women now put something into savings before
they pay their bills. That's lower than the 36 percent recorded by
men, but survey sponsor Merrill Lynch says the gap is narrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of women own stocks and bonds, according to
another survey. That's up from 53 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an encouraging statistic, provided by the National Center
for Women and Retirement Research: 94 percent of women believe they
are as capable as men when it comes to understanding money and
investing. On the other hand, women need to pay attention to their
retirement plans. Much more than men do, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Women live longer than men -- six years longer, according to the
National Center for Health Statistics. That means they have more
retirement years to finance.
</P>
<P>
   Women earn less money than men. That makes it no surprise they
save less: 1.5 percent of their income, vs. 3.1 percent for men,
says the Mutual Fund Education Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Women work fewer years and change jobs more frequently. Thus,
they can expect smaller paybacks from Social Security and pension
programs. Indeed, two out of three women have no pension plans at
all, according to the Employee Benefit Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   That all adds up to the need for many women to sharpen their
financial skills. Here are some ways to go about it:
</P>
<P>
   -- Put yourself first. ``It's not selfish to save for
yourself,'' said Ellen O. Keller, a certified financial planner in
Roswell. ``It's a gift to your family and loved ones, because they
won't have to take care of you when you're older. Everyone I know
wants their parents to have a nice life, and they don't want to
have to worry about them.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't succumb to fear. You may well need professional
advisers to formulate or just to polish your plans. But most people
can learn how to manage money and to plan for retirement. The
resource list on this page will give you some starting points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to give yourself time,'' said Keller. ``You can
say to yourself, `This is like someone is paying me money to learn
this. Maybe on Sunday afternoon I'm going to spend an hour or two
just reading.' Part of your budgeting is budgeting time to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Be persistent. Mary Ellen Garrett, a financial consultant
with Merrill Lynch in Atlanta, recommends you find experts --
perhaps at commercially sponsored seminars -- and grill them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid to ask questions,'' she said. ``This is your
business. You need to ask questions until you're comfortable with
the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Take it one step at a time. Keller suggests breaking these
sometimes complicated processes into manageable steps. Getting
debts under control is one step. Saving up an emergency fund is
another. Finding money to invest is yet another.
</P>
<P>
   -- Start saving now. If your employer offers a 401(k), join it.
``You need to contribute as much as you can possibly afford, and
especially you need to contribute enough to take advantage of the
company match,'' said Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   An individual retirement account, especially a Roth IRA, is
another inviting possibility for retirement saving. ``Saving is
really more a function of attitude than income,'' said Garrett.
``Everybody can find someplace to save a few dollars. If you start
saving now, it will be easier.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't be too conservative. ``Women often don't understand how
conservative investments are risky, because of inflation,'' Keller
observed.
</P>
<P>
   Like most other advisers, she recommends putting some portion of
retirement savings into the stock market, even in your senior
years. ``I see women who are 70, and they might live till they're
90,'' she said. ``They have conservative investments, and they're
getting poorer every year.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Know your retirement rights. It's important not just to
understand how your own pension works but how a spouse's plan is
set up. For a good introduction to the topic, check out the
consumer information at the Pension and Welfare Benefits
Administration Web site, http://www.dol.gov/dol
</P>
<P>
   /pwba/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
