<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SOFTWARE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Instructional software can help budding virtuosos hone their
musical skills
 &HT;    By John Ghirardini
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Music, Plato said, gives flight to the imagination and soul to
the universe. It also can be a balm for the spirit in the midst of
high-speed American life.
</P>
<P>
   But Plato lived in a simpler era, when demands on time were
fewer, and budding lyre virtuosos could spend all day learning the
intricacies and techniques of playing the instrument.
</P>
<P>
   If you think you or your child is ready to give piano or guitar
lessons a whirl, but you're worried there aren't enough hours in
the day, don't panic. Help is on the way, courtesy of the
Information Age.
</P>
<P>
   Music instruction has vaulted into the future with software that
teaches basic music theory and technique in a form with which both
children and adult beginners are comfortable. Hundreds of sites on
the World Wide Web also offer help, whether you're interested in
learning about autoharps or zithers.
</P>
<P>
   No software or computerized guidance can replace the subtlety,
experience and ear of a flesh-and-blood teacher, but for many
parents or novices such programs can be a good first step in
finding out whether aptitude or interest justify investing in
formal lessons, which average $15 a half-hour, or instruments,
which can cost several hundred dollars, even for models made for
beginners.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the instructional software costs between $45 and $99,
but requires a MIDI-capable, 16-bit or better sound card and a MIDI
keyboard. Many titles will run on Windows 3.1, and most have
Macintosh versions. MIDI _ musical instrument digital interface _
is what lets a sound device ``talk'' to a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Piano is still the instrument most parents want their children
to learn, says Kenon Renfrow, a music professor at the University
of Miami at Coral Gables. Renfrow, a keyboard specialist, also
serves as a software consultant for the Cincinnati-based Music
Teachers National Association. It's guitar titles, though, that
grab the lion's share of shelf space at many music and computer
stores. The same is true on the Web, where a mind-boggling number
of sites are devoted to the ``ax.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest advantages of using technology in music is
that students can get instant feedback'' on how they're doing,
Renfrow said, and perform at their own pace. Several instructors
said beginner-level software is an excellent reinforcement for
theoretical concepts, and that young students seem to retain them
better.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the teachers find this computer assist to be a useful
tool, though all emphasize the need for individualized instruction
to take students to their highest potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a box or computer program you can plug into a
wall and replace a teacher,'' Renfrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Some software packages that retail for less than $200 come with
a 49-key keyboard and all the necessary MIDI cables or connectors.
Two of the most popular are Piano Discovery System from Jump! Music
and the Family Music Center Play Piano from Midisoft.
</P>
<P>
   Piano Discovery System ($169) uses multimedia and games to
present music theory and basic note-reading. Once you've learned a
song, the software takes you to a ``performance hall,'' where you
play the piece with synthesized orchestral accompaniment. The
software then generates a review of your playing.
</P>
<P>
   The Midisoft title ($199) relies less on multimedia and offers
less step-by-step guidance, according to reviewers. After you
finish a section, the software scores you and highlights where you
hit the wrong notes.
</P>
<P>
   Another choice for teaching children the fundamentals is
Harmonic Vision's Music Ace ($49.95), which has garnered an
``outstanding'' rating from Children's Software Revue. There are
Windows and Mac versions available, and you can download a free
demo from the company's Web site (http://www.harmonicvision
</P>
<P>
   .com/). A MIDI keyboard is optional, not required, which makes
the software a good value.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are intent on being the next Andres Segovia or Jimi
Hendrix have a slew of choices, but reviewers have been most
impressed by Seattle-based eMedia's Guitar Method 1, for Windows 95
or Windows 3.1, which offers 60 lessons on the basics. You can use
either acoustic or electric guitar.
</P>
<P>
   The company has a second level available as students progress
that covers barre chords, music notation and scales, and licks like
hammer-ons, pull-offs and bends. Both titles include visual tuners
and digital metronomes, and retail for $59.95 _ about the price of
three lessons with an instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Guitropolis ($49.95) from Alfred Publishing takes the form of an
adventure game, but includes method-only versions of Alfred's
well-regarded Basic Guitar Method and Teach Yourself To Play
Guitar. Both provide solid instruction, reviewers say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another readily available option is G-Vox Guitar ($99.99,
for Windows 95) by G-Vox Entertainment. It includes all the
necessary hardware, as well as a music notation component. The
title comes with a pickup to attach either an electric or acoustic
guitar. A caution here, though: The instrument must have steel
strings, which can be devastating to uncallused fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   The technology may have changed, but there is at least one
element of learning music that hasn't changed since Plato's day: If
you want to get to the top, it's practice, practice, practice.
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly a string thing
</P>
<P>
   Here are some sites on the World Wide Web that offer music
instruction or guidance on how to obtain information on learning to
play a range of instruments.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL LINKS
</P>
<P>
   http://www.harmony-central.com/Links/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.lgu.ac.uk/mit/welcome.html
</P>
<P>
   PIANO
</P>
<P>
   http://jumpmusic.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.midisoft.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.unm.edu/(tilde)loritaf/pnolinks.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.voyetra.com/vywelcome.htm
</P>
<P>
   GUITAR
</P>
<P>
   http://www.museweb.com/ag/technique.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.sdgsoft.com/guitaron.htm
</P>
<P>
   http://www.emedia.org/guitar.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ubisoft.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.playmusic.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.alfredpub.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.lyrrus.com/
</P>
<P>
   MISCELLANEOUS
</P>
<P>
   http://www.mills.edu/LIFE/CCM
</P>
<P>
   /DIDJERIDU/instruction/instruction.html
</P>
<P>
   http://shareware.miningco.com/msubmusc
</P>
<P>
   .htm
</P>
<P>
   http://www.musicsearch.com/Instruments
</P>
<P>
   /Bag_Pipes.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
