<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Rundown of what's on the newsstand this week.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SEASON _ What kind of TV season is just around the corner? One
thing's for sure: of the 37 new shows there's not one ``ER'', not
one ``Friends,'' not one ``Ally McBeal'' _ nothing so far to
indicate there's a single freshman series that'll take viewers by
storm. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SEASON-QUOTES _ Quips and quotes from the just-ended TV critics
tour previewing the new fall season. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-AA _ Alcoholic Anonymous is credited with saving millions
who have drinking problems, but 70 percent of AA members will
relapse within five years. In a new book, ``How Alcoholics
Anonymous Failed Me,'' Marianne Gilliam of Conyers, Ga., asserts
that true recovery from addiction is possible only when the addict
takes control and no longer considers himself or herself a victim.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-SINGLE _ Single women have been portrayed as wallflowers,
predatory divorcees, man-hating career women, and welfare moms. But
for the most part, they have never been viewed as a collective
force. Marcelle Clements goes a long way toward remedying that
oversight in her new book, ``The Improvised Woman: Single Women
Reinventing Single Life'' (Norton). (Warmbold, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RYAN _ An immense debt of gratitude is owed historian Stephen E.
Ambrose, whose work inspired ``Saving Private Ryan.'' He is
credited as the film's consultant although he was consulted only
after the film was shot. But the biggest debt we owe is to the men
and women who fought, bled and died in that global conflict. It is
impossible to overstate the debt that free people of the world owe
them. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   LUTHERAN-KIDS _ ATLANTA _ They've come to play, pray and make a
difference in the lives of people who need help. Thirty thousands
teens, one of the largest national gatherings of young Christians
ever, are in Atlanta this week, part of the National Lutheran Youth
Conference. Henry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ The Associated Press started all this when it
began ranking the Top 10 college football teams. Now they're up to
25. In time it's liable to become the Top 100, just like the Modern
Library's list of the best English-language novels of the century.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GOING-SOUTH _ NUEVO LAREDO, Nuevo Leon _ We came to partake of
the unbearable hotness of being. In this summer of killing,
creeping, sapping heat, we came for border hot. We came to see how
this heat is different from the heat we've been wilting from in
Austin. We came not to escape the heat but to complain about it in
a different place _ and had we known it was 110 degrees, we would
have produced an opera of complaint. Such was our good fortune that
we were here when it was, yes, that hot. (Beach, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-PUBLISHING _ Over the past decade, African American
bookstores have flourished and faltered. They've provided a
valuable service to their communities by providing an outlet for
African American writings that were hard to find at mainstream
bookstores, by aiding the fight against illiteracy, by buying books
from small presses and distributors and by giving once-emerging
black authors, such as Naylor and Terry McMillan, a chance by
personally promoting their early books. (Martin, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-LOGGING _ TIGER BAY STATE FOREST _ These days the woods
echo not with the song of birds or rustle of wildlife, but the
racket of giant saws, bulldozers and lumberjacks measuring their
harvest. All around central and northern Florida, a massive logging
operation is under way in the wake of summer wildfires.
(Staletovich, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-WATCH _ ATLANTA -- Maybe, just maybe, customers who pay
to use bank ATM machines are beginning to fight back. Or maybe
they're just getting smarter. Many are shifting to their own banks'
machines to avoid being charged twice for their transactions -- one
fee by the bank that owns the ATM, if it is a bank other than their
own, and another fee by their own bank. At the same time, the
surcharges continue to rise, new studies show. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ ATLANTA -- Last week in Chicago, about a
thousand participants at a World Future Society conference mulled
over forecasts for the 21st century, trying to discern what changes
would be coming around the 2000 bend. While opinions varied on many
issues, the futurists seemed to have little doubt about this: Women
will become the dominant players in the economy and the home. The
futurists referred to ``the coming matriarchy'' as an almost
certain outcome of the ``post-divorce'' society. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-TALK _ ATLANTA _ Women, nudged by necessity and the
ever-hungry financial services industry, are getting more active
and more savvy about saving for retirement. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   PALMTOP-WINDOWS _ Windows CE is Microsoft's Windows 95
look-alike operating system for hand-held and palmtop PCs. Rolled
out with much ceremony at a big computer trade show in 1996,
Windows CE is a sign Microsoft is determined to compete in every
market where a rival operating system might gain some traction, as
has occurred with the proprietary systems built into such hand-held
devices as 3Com's highly popular PalmPilot. (Reid/Hume, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JUNO _ The most coveted Internet users are the ones who don't
really know how to use the Web. Juno (http://www.juno.com), the
popular, advertiser-supported free e-mail service, realized the day
is coming when its 5.5 million users will want to do more on the
Net than just send e-mail. They are, in the words of Juno President
Charles Ardai, ``a group that has taken its first step onto the
Internet.'' Rather than watch them drift off to other ISPs, Juno
has decided to try to become an ISP itself. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ OneClick is software that lives up to the Mac
ideal. It not only makes computing easy, it's fun, too. That's not
bad, considering OneClick is not a game but something called a
utility. It expands what your Mac can do. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING _ It's always nice to watch David beat Goliath.
Watching the soaring stock prices of Atlanta-based Internet service
provider MindSpring elicits a similar feeling. MindSpring founder
and Chairman Charles Brewer cut his vacation short to appear on
CNBC. When asked what was the secret to the Internet service
provider's success, Brewer replied with what is becoming the
MindSpring mantra: Keeping costs down and customers happy is the
key to profitability. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SOFTWARE _ Music instruction has vaulted into the future
with software that teaches basic music theory and technique in a
form with which both children and adult beginners are comfortable.
Hundreds of sites on the World Wide Web also offer help, whether
you're interested in learning about autoharps or zithers.
(Ghirardini, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
