<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOGGING28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After the fires, the logging begins
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIGER BAY STATE FOREST _ These days the woods echo not with the
song of birds or rustle of wildlife, but the racket of giant saws,
bulldozers and lumberjacks measuring their harvest.
</P>
<P>
   All around central and northern Florida, a massive logging
operation is under way in the wake of summer wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 500,000 acres that burned in the fires that started
Memorial Day weekend and led to the evacuation of about 112,000
residents, half was forest _ some plantations, some state lands and
some private property leased for timber. Now the clock is ticking
to get burned wood cut and to mills before it rots or is ruined by
pesky beetles, further harming the state's $9 billion a year timber
industry.
</P>
<P>
   But beating the clock isn't the only problem.
</P>
<P>
   A glut created by early harvesting during an exceptionally dry
winter and the falling Asian economy means a lot of wood will never
make it to a mill. Some say as many as 2 million cords of wood _ or
well over 5.5 million tons _ will go to waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``This couldn't have happened at a worse time,'' said Leon
Irvin, a silviculturist for the Florida Division of Forestry.
``Nobody really knows (how much will be lost). We've not had an
accurate assessment of the damage,''
</P>
<P>
   For Derrick Miller, a state ranger at Tiger Bay who tends his
forest like it is his own garden, the past months have been
heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the forest as my child,'' he said one day this week as
he watched a bulldozer that gathers logs, called a skidder,
lurching through his woods, a wide swath flattened in its wake. Up
to 65 percent of the 43,500-acre forests in Tiger Bay and Lake
George park was burned, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an emergency situation and if it will save the rest of
the forest, we have to do it. But it bothers me greatly.'' EARLY
HARVEST ERODES PRICE
</P>
<P>
   Florida is filled with woods. You might not see it from the
highway, but the checkerboard of palmetto prairies that inhabit
rare patches of undeveloped land in the southern half of the state
gives way to vast stretches of thick pine forests north of Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Logging first arrived in the 1800s, when valuable yellow pine
was shipped worldwide. But eventually heavy cutting left stands
barren, said Charles Maynard, chief of the forest management bureau
for the Florida Division of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a cut and get out type situation. Logging
companies would come in and remove the existing timber and get out
without much regard for the forests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the 1920s, realizing it was driving itself toward
extinction, the timber industry banded together to find ways to
nurture forests and establish ground rules for harvests, Maynard
said. In 1927 the state founded its Division of Forestry and hired
foresters to help the industry manage lands, replant woods and
control fires, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, nearly 15 million acres is harvested for timber, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific, which manages 5.8 million acres in North
America to produce $2.5 billion worth of wood, owns 586,000 acres
just in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the fire, a lot of wood is being harvested
prematurely, meaning an excess of pulp wood and a drastic drop in
price.
</P>
<P>
   Miller says his pulp wood, which brought $20 a ton last year, is
being auctioned at just $7 a ton. Lumber is also down by half,
going for only $20 a ton, he said. In addition, mills swamped with
wood are getting pickier about the wood they take and refusing a
lot of pulp wood, said state forester David Creamer.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that wood is slash pine, planted in place of native long
leaf pine on many plantations because it grows quickly. (Trees for
lumber are cut usually at age 30; pulp wood after 20 years.) While
plantations continue to grow slash, state and national foresters
are replanting with fire resistant long leaf. CUTTING WITH CARE
</P>
<P>
   In Ocala National Forest, about 250 acres of burned wood will be
auctioned for harvesting.
</P>
<P>
   This week rangers who normally cut trees only to thin woods so
forests can grow heartier, walked through charred stands marking
plots for logging. In an hour's time, Charlie Caughlin, a district
manager with the U.S. Forest Service, and his crew of three had
marked a stand that took 30 years to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yellow pine, seven, 35! Yellow pine, 14, 55!'' ranger Mike
Williams yelled, ticking off measurements of condemned trees, their
diameter and height.
</P>
<P>
   Forest floors usually made impassable by palmetto and oak are a
blanket of soot. Stripped naked, forests reveal what normally is
hidden: gopher tortoise holes, chicken wire wrapped around what was
once a marijuana plant, and piles and piles of trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swinus Americanus,'' Caughlin says as he points to another
mound of beer cans.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, foresters can still feel heat coming from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   After the foresters measure and mark the trees with nontoxic
paint, they will feed the numbers into a computer program that
determines the volume of wood in a stand and then auction it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real dilemma for us,'' Caughlin said as he described
how he would cut some trees in a stand but leave others for seeding
or to provide natural habitat for woodpeckers and other wildlife.
``One thing we don't want to do is any more harm to an area.''
HEALING BEGINS
</P>
<P>
   Miles away off State Road 40 in a forest owned by the Hunter's
Ridge subdivision in Ormond Beach, lumberjacks will take less care.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the state and national lands, these stretches are crops
for Georgia Pacific, pure and simple.
</P>
<P>
   In a day, Jack Wilkinson, who works for Mills Wood in Palatka,
says he can load more than 2,200 trees on trucks bound for
Georgia-Pacific's Palatka mill. His cousin Terry, a
fourth-generation lumberjack, will cut 100 trees in a half hour.
</P>
<P>
   When Terry Wilkinson started logging 25 years ago at 14, he used
a chainsaw. His father, who also started logging at 14, used a
hand-held saw and carried a bottle of kerosene to dissolve gooey
turpentine. Hydraulics replaced all that, Wilkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Today he drives a buncher, a bulldozer outfitted with a giant
saw that makes 1,150 revolutions per second and can cut through a
22-inch thick tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I got air-conditioning and stereo. That's a long way from
toting a saw,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the weather, rangers and lumberjacks will have
about a month or so to harvest wood for lumber, longer for pulp
wood. Mills are rushing to install irrigation to keep logs wet, and
making it last longer. Gov. Lawton Chiles also lifted weight limits
on some roads so more wood can be carried to mills.
</P>
<P>
   While the woods may be noisy these days, rangers say once the
harvest is over, replanting can begin and nature will quickly heal.
Already signs of life abound. A raccoon scurried through Tiger Bay
one afternoon this week. Just two days earlier, Miller said he and
a logging crew encountered two deer. The trees, fed on a healthy
diet of nutrients left behind by the burned forests, will grow
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always told my daddy they're gonna run out,'' of forests,
Terry Wilkinson said. ``He said they never would. Seems to me it
just keeps growing and growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
