r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN28-COX     07-27 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History and 'reel' history
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia, Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' opened last week following a public
relations campaign obviously planned as meticulously as the
invasion of Europe in 1944. The extensive public relations barrage
included an assertion that Steven Spielberg, the movie's director,
can be credited with reviving interest in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   If the movie has the effect of sparking interest in that
monumental effort, we should all be appropriately grateful. As an
aside, however, I wish that the hype surrounding the movie didn't
rewrite history. The Normandy invasion was the ``last great
invasion of the last great war,'' according to the advertisement
hoopla. That bit of public relations hyperbole overlooks the Iwo
Jima and Okinawa invasions in the Pacific Theater. But then, the
war in the Pacific usually gets short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   An immense debt of gratitude is owed historian Stephen E.
Ambrose, whose work inspired the movie. He is credited as the
film's consultant although he was consulted only after the film was
shot.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest debt we owe is to the men and women who fought,
bled and died in that global conflict. It is impossible to
overstate the debt that free people of the world owe them.
</P>
<P>
   Revisionists claim lamely that the war was a clash of competing
economies for market share. While wars usually have economic
overtones, I doubt those revisionists would relish the thought of
living in a country occupied by Nazi Germany or Imperial Japan.
</P>
<P>
   At D-Day Plus 54 years, the glow of victory and the distance
from it make it easy to forget that the outcome of the war was far
from certain even as late as 1943. The success of Operation
Overlord, the Normandy invasion, was so iffy that Dwight
Eisenhower, supreme commander of the Allied Expeditionary Force,
drafted a statement to be issued in the event that the invasion
troops were repelled.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end the fate of the free world rested with some very
young, very scared troops who maneuvered through the water, past
the obstacles and who overcame intense enemy fire and their own
survival instincts to carry the longest day.
</P>
<P>
   The troops who accomplished that mission were not professional
soldiers, but citizen soldiers. These were people who answered the
call, accomplished the mission and went home.
</P>
<P>
   I have often asked my father, a veteran of the war in the
Pacific, if he had any idea at the time how his service fit into
the grand sweep of history. He replies with shrugged shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   He has never said so, but the question may strike him as rather
silly. After all, a soldier's lot is to follow orders and try to
survive, not reflect on how the experience is going to fit in a
history book.
</P>
<P>
   It has been two and half generations since a WWII-scale
mobilization has been undertaken, and I can't help but wonder how
citizens of the United States in the waning years of this century
would respond to that kind of call. Vietnam made draft-dodging
socially acceptable. The all-volunteer military makes service and
sacrifice somebody else's thing for most middle-class young people.
</P>
<P>
   But as Jimmy Buffet wrote, they can go to movies and see it all
there. But you don't have to go to movies to see it all. Talking to
those who lived through the war and survived it while they are
still here to tell it firsthand is best.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it takes to remind us of what it took to make the lives
we now enjoy is most welcome, whether it's a Spielberg movie or an
Ambrose book.
</P>
<P>
   But the best source are those people in their 70s who lived
through it. Talk to them, they'll tell you.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget to thank them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
