</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ Now, a new poll. This one of great
English-language books. The Modern Library, which worries for the
nation about great books, asked its board to select the best 100 of
the century. The top book: ``Ulysses,'' by James Joyce. Joyce would
have agreed, while bemused by our impulse to name the top
everything. Brief insights from the editor-in-chief of Cox
Newspapers. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Fortune magazine, in its current
edition, has an ambitious new idea, a unique entry in the endless
lists of ``best companies.'' This list contains its version of the
50 best companies in the nation for African-American, Hispanic and
Asian employees and executives. (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ We have five acres of wine grapes planted on our
north Georgia farm, and some of our vines are beginning to wilt in
the drought. In fact, we're into our fourth week of no rain in
Tiger, though there have been thunderstorms in other parts of the
county _ lightning and thunder we could see and hear just two or
three maddening miles away. (Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-C0LUMN _ KEY WEST, Fla. It's the right time: a torpid
mid-afternoon in July. It's the right place: an unassuming white
frame house on a quiet corner in Key West. It's the right weather:
sweltering. Even the man on the barstool next to me is the right
man. But where is the fat man? (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
