<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fighting drought in North Georgia vineyard a labor of love
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA- Hurry and get on up here _ we need help with the bucket
brigade,'' pleaded my husband from our Tiger, Ga. farm .
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's our crackerjack fire department?'' I asked, referring
to Tiger's first and only shiny new red fire engine, the
christening of which was occasion for a town barbecue and blessings
by the itinerant Baptist preacher not long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my grapes that are buring up,'' he said, with a tone of
disbelief that I didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   We have five acres of wine grapes planted on our north Georgia
farm, and our some of ourvines are beginning to wilt in the
drought. In fact, we're into our fourth week of no rain in Tiger,
though there have been thunderstorms in other parts the county_
lightning and thunder we could see and hear just two or three
maddening miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Last season we fought off a harsh late freeze that turned the
first delicate green buds to brown in early May. (Fortunately, wine
grapes produce a second bud, but frost limits the quantity of the
harvest). This year, though, the grapes are voluptuous , their
tentacles twining in and out of perfectly formed clusters of
grapes_ a match for any Napa Valley scene.
</P>
<P>
   My husband John , who was born in the shadow of Tiger Mountain,
looked up last week-end and swore the leaves on the poplar trees
high up were turning up on the edges, a sure sign of rain , he
declared.
</P>
<P>
   But seven or eight more dry days and nights have passed. It's as
if some devious trickster had spread a giant invisible umbrella
right over Tiger. For it has rained just three miles away in
Clayton, and the hills of Western North Carolina, a little further
north, are fairly drenched . Meanwhile our poor vineyard rain
gauges are nothing more than worthless gadgets. Our woes,though,
aren't nearly as crucial as those of our farmer neighbors whose
corn and beans are shriveling in a manner similar to the farm crops
in South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The European grapes we've cultivated, the Cabernet Francs and
others, are planted deeper and aren't suffering like the Nortons,
our singular American variety. In fact, the French say a dry season
that makes the vines struggle also makes them produce a finer
tasting grape and a superior wine. But the American grapes remind
of moody and undisciplined children , harder to train on the wires
because of their tendency to wind off in directions, as if trying
to choke each other in some schoolyard scuffle. Now, because of
their shallower root system they're beginning to droop, while their
European cousins send roots far down into the earth to grab
whatever moisture they can.
</P>
<P>
   Dry as the poor Norton grapes are, I balked at the idea of
hauling buckets of water up and down the rolling hills of our
vineyard. It seems so primitive, I complained, remembering how we'd
boasted of our state- of- the- art ``Geneva curtain'' trellises
that keep the grapes divided and don't allow them to grow together
in old-style canopy form. The new trellis system lets the grapes
get more sun, and allows the air to move in and out of the vines,
warding off various types of fungus endemic to humid climates. We
have ``open lyre'' trellises for our European grapes which grow
upward instead of flopping down over the wires like the American
grapes want to do.
</P>
<P>
   I 've always said the open trellises look like giant metal arms
lifted skyward in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they are praying for rain, I muttered to John.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wanna lift or pour,'' was his only reply.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
