A4344 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN28-COX     07-27 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Where is the fat man?
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. It's the right time: a torpid mid-afternoon in
July. It's the right place: an unassuming white frame house on a
quiet corner
</P>
<P>
   in Key West. It's the right weather: sweltering.
</P>
<P>
   Even the man on the barstool next to me is the right man.
</P>
<P>
   But where is the fat man?
</P>
<P>
   I drop my straw bag on the bar and order a G&AMP;T, lime but no ice.
Overhead, a paddle fan clicks through its monotonous rotation. I
kick
</P>
<P>
   off a shoe and let my toes search listlessly for the cool metal
of a footrest. The metal is there but it isn't cool. About the same
</P>
<P>
   temperature as the ocean just down the street I'm thinking -
tepid.
</P>
<P>
   I nod thanks to the bartender, reach for the already dripping
glass, and take a look around. Five people. Two stools to my left,
a gray beard
</P>
<P>
   with sandals, reading the morning paper and sipping something
short and mean looking. Down at the end, a tired, middle-aged
couple. She's
</P>
<P>
   wearing a flowered dress and a flushed face. He looks overspent.
Tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The man seated next to me watches as I watch. He's curious but
silent. Finally, I ask him: ``Have you seen the fat man?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not today,'' he grins, picking up on my derailed train of
thought. ``Too hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed, I swear. ``Damn! He should have been here.'' I'm
thinking to myself, if ever there was a place where the fat man in
the white suit
</P>
<P>
   and Panama hat should have shown up, it is right here on this
stinkin' hot little spit of land where the Gulf of Mexico and the
Atlantic run
</P>
<P>
   together, and where Castro is 80 miles closer than Cocoanut
Grove. As an afterthought I add, ``...even if he didn't bring the
parrot.''
</P>
<P>
   The next barstool smiles. His teeth are straight. No curled lip.
No lisp. I practice my one-eyebrow raise. ``You're not Bogart?''
</P>
<P>
   Regretfully, he shakes his head and counters: ``You're not
Bacall?'' He's quick. I like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I glumly confess, ``but you can call me Betty if you
want to.'' He does.
</P>
<P>
   Another sweep of the bar - still no fat man. He'd stand out in
this crowd. Reaching for my purse, I turn to the man who isn't
Bogart, lower
</P>
<P>
   my voice half-an-octave and, shooting for sultry, purr: ``I'm
leaving, but remember, if you want anything, all you have to do is
whistle.'' He's
</P>
<P>
   still smiling. I carry on. ``You know how to whistle, don't you
Steve? You just put your lips together and blow.''
</P>
<P>
   The man who isn't Steve goes for it but a benign chuckle catches
him off guard and he can't pucker. ``'To Have and Have Not'.
Right?'' I ask
</P>
<P>
   him how he knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's this place'' he says making a half-turn to take it all
in. ``It could be Martinique - 1940, and we could've been waiting
here for days
</P>
<P>
   for the fat man to return our passports so we can get out of the
country before it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   I like the way this story is going and can't resist suggesting:
``If we're stuck here too long, I'll take a job singing at the bar.
It'll pay
</P>
<P>
   the rent and keep us in cracked conch.''
</P>
<P>
   The man who can't whistle, can't lie either and the smallest
hint of a grimace mixes with his smile. He's heard me sing so he
changes the
</P>
<P>
   subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ready for lunch?'' he asks. ``Doesn't look like the fat man is
going to show.'' We wander inside for seafood and gazpacho.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia comes in oddly wrapped packages; today, it's an old
house in Key West, on the corner of Caroline and Whitehead. The
brick steps
</P>
<P>
   leading up to Kelly's Caribbean Bar and Grill seduced two old
friends right back into a piece of Florida and a spot in time that
we had known
</P>
<P>
   as kids - a time when magic was still happening.
</P>
<P>
   The man who is not Bogart and the woman who is not Bacall are
old friends - about 48 years worth.
</P>
<P>
   As we move past the bar on our way out, I leave word with the
bartender: ``If you see the fat man, tell him we're looking for
him. We'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   I never look back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
