<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ernest Holsendolph's Business Commentary: Fortune lists top
firms that promote, pay minorities
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Fortune magazine, in its current edition, has an
ambitious new idea, a unique entry in the endless lists of ``best
companies.'' This list contains its version of the 50 best
companies in the nation for African-American, Hispanic and Asian
employees and executives.
</P>
<P>
   That may have a familiar ring. But this list, compiled with the
assistance of the New York-based Council on Economic Priorities,
grades survey participants on such wide-ranging criteria as
percentage of minorities in top-paying jobs and on boards of
directors, and presence of executives in profit-making operations
-- instead of staff jobs like public relations and community
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the survey tries to separate window dressing
from real corporate diversity.
</P>
<P>
   There were some familiar faces on the list. Detroit's Big Three
car companies made it. Bank America, Chase Manhattan and
BellAtlantic made it. Even Shoney's and Denny's made it. Some did
not. Texaco was a no-show. Even Time Warner, owner of Fortune
magazine, did not make it.
</P>
<P>
   And not a single Georgia-based company cracked the top 50. It
was a tough list. Lucent Technologies, based in Murray Hill, N.J.,
but with a huge installation here, finished 16th on the list.
Lucent won special praise for having seven minorities among its 25
highest salaried employees and for its financial support of
organizations that represent minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never realized until you told me that no Atlanta company was
on the list,'' said Roy S. Johnson, author of the Fortune articles
accompanying the listing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fact of the matter is that this is new,'' he said, ``and some
companies declined to participate because they did not understand
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others wondered if divulging some of the information may be an
invasion of privacy,'' said Johnson, formerly a sports columnist
for the Journal-Constitution during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Companies had to figure out the top 25 people on the payroll in
terms of annual salary and provide numbers on blacks, Hispanics and
Asians in the number. They had to tell where they concentrated
their corporate giving, winning gold stars if they helped minority
communities and financed such items as scholarships for minority
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola did participate in the survey but failed to make the
cut, finishing at 53rd on the list. Kim Price, a spokesman, said
the company was proud of its record in supporting minority
education through its foundation. And it considered its
comprehensive plan to do business with minority vendors to be a
pace-setter in industry.
</P>
<P>
   Coke placed above average in six of nine categories, Price said,
but obviously lagged elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   No other prominent Atlanta area company took part in the survey,
according to the magazine. We did not take part in the survey, said
a spokesman for Cox Enterprises, the company that owns the
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more fascinating features of the poll was the
presence of Advantica of Spartanburg, S.C., which owns the Denny's
chain of restaurants, as well as Shoney's of Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies were involved in splashy publicity over alleged
discrimination earlier in the decade, only to rally to change their
images.
</P>
<P>
   Shoney's, according to Fortune, paid $132.8 million to settle a
class-action discrimination suit in 1992, a suit brought by 20,000
employees and rejected job applicants. Two years later, Denny's
paid $54.4 million to settle two class-action suits brought by
black customers who said they were refused service at certain
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Shoney's (13th on the list) boasts 30 percent of its
store managers are minorities, and Denny's (2nd) was praised for
diversity among suppliers and the franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jim Abramson, chief executive of Denny's parent company
since 1995: ``White men tend to hire white men. ... I am a complete
supporter of affirmative action because I don't believe the playing
field is level. ... To undergo the kind of metamorphosis we have,
you have to take the initiative. It won't happen naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is this: For companies that are baffled about
ways to achieve diversity in their work forces and in their
executive suites, we now have 50 companies from every walk of life
that seem ready, willing and able to tutor them.
</P>
<P>
   CHART: The top 10 companies most comfortable for
African-Americans, Hispanics and Asians:
</P>
<P>
   1. Pacific Enterprises, a Los Angeles utility.
</P>
<P>
   2. Advantica, Spartanburg, S.C., owner
</P>
<P>
   of Denny's.
</P>
<P>
   3. BankAmerica, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   4. Fannie Mae, Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   5. Marriott International, Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   6. Applied Materials, Santa Clara, Calif., maker of
semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   7. Edison International, Rosemead, Calif., utility.
</P>
<P>
   8. Computer Associates, Islandia, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   9. Ryder System, Miami.
</P>
<P>
   10. Pitney Bowes, Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
