<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OneClick a fine shortcut for many repetitive tasks
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OneClick is software that lives up to the Mac ideal. It not only
makes computing easy, it's fun, too.
</P>
<P>
   That's not bad, considering OneClick is not a game but something
called a utility. It expands what your Mac can do.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind OneClick is simple. It reduces nearly any
repetitive task on your computer to a button click.
</P>
<P>
   That includes changing fonts, copying text and more complicated
chores such as inserting boilerplate text into e-mail. OneClick can
do all this and more.
</P>
<P>
   OneClick works through a motif of buttons and palettes. Every
palette displays a collection of buttons, and each button performs
a task.
</P>
<P>
   OneClick comes with lots of pre-configured palettes and buttons
that are ready to use. You'll find global palettes that include
buttons automating things such as closing windows and emptying the
trash.
</P>
<P>
   And there are application palettes for programs such as
PhotoShop and ClarisWorks. These palettes only appear when you're
using an application.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just the beginning. You can make your own palettes
from scratch, selecting everything from the shape of the button to
the background color of the palette.
</P>
<P>
   Creating buttons from scratch is easy, too. OneClick will record
a series of actions, such as copying text, and save them on a
button.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can write your own scripts with OneClick's own
programming language called EasyScript. Matt Neuburg, a reviewer
with Mac newsletter TidBits, said EasyScript ``is spectacularly
well thought out and easy to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to learn EasyScript or OneClick's record
functions to add new buttons and palettes. Others are creating new
ones all the time and posting them on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   OneClick has collected and organized them on its Web site at
http://www.westcodesoft
</P>
<P>
   .com. Check the list often, because it's always being updated.
Downloading and adding other palettes to your computer is easy.
</P>
<P>
   While it generally works great, OneClick is not without bugs. I
found it does slow the general speed of your system. In addition,
it messed around with the performance of some programs such as
Nisus Writer.
</P>
<P>
   OneClick can also make your screen a cluttered mess, with all
its different palettes. But the company has licked that problem by
letting you easily hide any or all of them.
</P>
<P>
   You can control OneClick through a pull-down button the program
puts in the upper right hand corner of your menu bar.
</P>
<P>
   OneClick is a powerful program with many, many features. I've
just scratched the surface here. To learn more about the program
and what others have to say about it, check out reviews in MacWorld
and MacAddict magazines. You'll also find user comments at the
company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Published by Westcode Software, OneClick sells for about $70.
The best place to buy it is from the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
