<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4358 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN29-COX     07-27 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Repairing racial injustice of wartimes
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifty years ago this week, President Harry Truman signed an
executive order barring racial inequality in the military.
Integration wouldn't start until two years later, forced by the
need to rush troops to the Korean War, and the last all-black unit
wouldn't be disbanded until 1954. Still, Truman's bold move marked
the beginning of the end for one of the more tormented tales in the
twisted history of American racial injustice.
</P>
<P>
   African Americans had fought to win, save and expand American
freedom in every of the nation's wars, only to be rewarded after
each, if rewarded at all, with meager rations from that freedom _
and with quick white forgetfulness. Every debt of honor was settled
on the cheap.
</P>
<P>
   We were still rescuing those memories last week, and settling
those debts.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200,000 black soldiers and sailors fought to save the Union
in the Civil War, but the forgetting began immediately. None
marched in the victory parade down Pennsylvania _ and never mind
their 16 Medals of Honor. A memorial to the black veterans was
unveiled in Washington last week.
</P>
<P>
   And survivors of the 2,220 black soldiers who volunteered to
leave their support units and fight beside whites in World War II's
Battle of the Bulge finally received the medals last week that the
Pentagon forgot to issue them after the war. Adding injury to
insult, black non-coms had been reduced to privates for the battle
_ no risk, then, they would give orders to whites _ and never had
their ranks restored.
</P>
<P>
   So it has gone. Crispus Attucks was one of the five to die in
the Boston Massacre, first blood in the Revolutionary War. Among
the blacks who served in the war was the all-black 1st Rhode Island
Regiment.
</P>
<P>
   Some 350 blacks fought with Andrew Jackson at the Battle of New
Orleans in the War of 1812, and a fourth of the sailors who won the
war's key Battle of Lake Erie were African American. Black units
were crucial to the Spanish-American War victories at San Juan and
Kettle Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The (now) famous Buffalo Soldiers protected American expansion
across the West, and some 400,000 blacks served in World War I,
most memorably the 369th Infantry, the Harlem Hellfighters. (Its
soldiers knocked the Germans out; its band knocked the French out.)
</P>
<P>
   African Americans, relentlessly steered to fetch-and-carry
roles, had to fight to fight in World War II, from infantry and
tank units to the distinguished Tuskegee Airmen. And they came home
to find furloughed German war prisoners welcome where they were
forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   Through all this, the armed forces everywhere were as segregated
as the Jim Crow South, yet African Americans soldiered on _ an
astonishing act of faith, based on precious little encouraging
experience, that their nation would one day vindicate in the
perfection of its justice the sacrifice they were making.
</P>
<P>
   America's black newspapers called World War II the fight for two
V's _ victory in combat abroad and victory for racial justice at
home. The first victory was complete, but although Truman's order
started dramatic changes for the better, those two recent
ceremonies in Washington remind us there is still some mopping up
to do on the second.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
