<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, July 27, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-GUNS (San Francisco) _ With children killing children and
last Friday's slayings at the U.S. Capitol, Paula Hollowell-Dhar
and her fellow congregants at a church in Berkeley, Calif., are
gathering names for a petition asking the Berkeley City Council to
withdraw its investments from companies _ and any businesses linked
to them _ that manufacture firearms or ammunition. By VENISE
WAGNER.
</P>
<P>
   ASTRONOMY-EXCITEMENT (San Francisco) _ The sky will never look
the same again. A flood of astronomical discoveries is making front
page headlines this year _ planets spinning around distant stars,
mega-violent explosions that rip apart galaxies, iceberg-covered
oceans of possibly inhabited alien moons, a universe that is
inexplicably expanding faster with time. Future historians might
recall the mid-to late-1990s as a renaissance of astrophysics. By
KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PRISON-HEAT (Huntsville, Texas) _ If you think you're hot,
trying spending a few summers in one of Texas' older prisons. It
was 126 degrees on the third floor of the Wynne Unit in Huntsville
the other day. None of the state's prisons is air-conditioned, and
fans must be provided by the inmates themselves. By KATHY WALT.
(Photo available on NYT photo service.)
</P>
<P>
   TERM-LIMITS (San Francisco) _ These days, the biggest headache
in the state legislature is dealing with the fallout from eight
years of term limits. Although many believe the legislature has
become vastly more democratic, state politics has been flipped on
its face, lawmakers and lobbyists say, with weaker leaders,
perpetually inexperienced legislators and a governor and his vast
bureaucracy seizing more power than ever. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ A reader wants to know about digging
and dividing crinumns, which seem to grow rapidly and seem a bit
crowded. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN (Houston) _ Whatever you do, resist the temptation to
buy Internet stocks because many of them look poised to flame out
because they're so overpriced. ``I like them, but they're
gasoline,'' said Brian Grove, a money manager here. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-AVENGERS-PROFILE (Las Vegas) _ Actor Ralph Fiennes may have
taken his role as secret agent John Steed, but Patrick Macnee is
still involved in the classic 1960s TV series ``The Avengers'' via
a new book and set of videos, which will be released Tuesday. He
also has a cameo in the movie version coming Aug. 14. By BRUCE
WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-CHILDRENS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at children's books
that the whole family can enjoy. From ``Yucka Drucka Droni''
(Scholastic, $15.95), a tongue twister of a story that must be read
aloud to be appreciated, to ``The Old Woman and the Wave`` (DK Ink,
$15.95), a whimsical story with a serious message. By JANE P.
MARSHALL.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-STADIUM (San Francisco) _ Eddie DeBartolo, the 49ers part
owner who personally financed a bond measure campaign for a new
stadium complex, is now the major obstacle to the deal going
forward, two sources close to the team's parent company said. By
CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   YOGI-BERRA (Lutherville, Md.) _ Asked what he would do if he
found a million dollars, Lawrence Peter Berra answered: ``If the
guy was poor, I would give it back.'' Yogi Berra was a
distinguished New York Yankees catcher, a most valuable player in
1951, 1954 and 1955, and he managed the team to the pennant in
1964. But he is best known for inspiring the name of the cartoon
character Yogi Bear _ and for wonderful word foulups. By MARTIN D.
TULLAI.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-DAVIS-MEMORIAL (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _The speech was short and
bittersweet. The words that National League president Leonard
Coleman spoke into the microphone were suffocatingly sad as he
talked about shortstop George Davis became, the first player
inducted Sunday afternoon into the baseball Hall of Fame Class of
1998. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BROWN-GIANTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Shedding 30 pounds, Gary
Brown, who had a stint with the Houston Oilers, came out of exile
to play for the San Diego Chargers last season. The Chargers chose
not to re-sign him this season, so Brown joined the Giants. Now,
starting over with his third team, Brown is trying to show he is
still a productive runner at age 29. By MARK SINGELAIS.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A chilled fog buried the coast
again this past week, and it hid a fire that hasn't burned so hot
in 15 years. Out on the beaches, from San Francisco on down 10
miles to south Pacifica, fishermen are again casting out to the
sea, their dawn images nothing more than silhouettes against the
ocean backdrop. On the beach the striped bass have roared in, and
the prospects for thrill, one-on-one, have rarely been better. By
TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ Some B&AMP;B owners seem to forget what
part of the title signifies _ as in breakfast. Fortunately for
Texas travelers, many innkeepers make certain the taste buds are
well satisfied. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COSTA-RICA (FORTUNA, Costa Rica) _ Arenal, one of the world's
most active volcanoes, makes a picturesque and exciting backdrop in
central Costa Rica, where visitors can hike, raft, ride horseback
or just kick back. By SYD KEARNEY. (Photos available on NYT photo
service.)
</P>
<P>
   COSTA-RICA-SIDER (Undated) _ Box on where to go and where to
stay when in Costa Rica to see El Arenal, an active volcano less
than a mile from the Tabacon Resort, a complex featuring a series
of lushly landscaped hot pools, two bars and a restaurant.
</P>
