   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Predicting a $3.7 billion state
budget surplus a few months before an election is kind of like
taking a bunch of kids to a candy store. You better get out of the
way. Political candidates have been scrambling all over one another
in their eagerness to cash in on Texas' continued prosperity. By
CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Truman Crabbe recalls vividly when
he was mugged. He was 69 and earning a quarter of a million dollars
a year managing the Albany office of IDS Financial Services. And it
was a year after American Express bought the company. That was when
he was replaced by a man in his 30s who would earn less than half
of what he was making. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   HEAT-EMPATHY (Albany, N.Y.) _ This past week, too much
conversation was focused on how hot it was. Yet we were just living
through a spell of weather that was perhaps four degrees above the
average. Nothing to get into a sweat about. Maybe our perceived
general discomfort was based on empathy; we thought we endured what
was happening in Texas. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   TSUNAMI (San Francisco) _ When the killer tsunami of July 13
obliterated thousands of lives in Papua New Guinea, an immediate
question along California's coastline was: Could it happen here? It
already has. More than once. And that's why a warning system is so
important.
</P>
