</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pattern you see (with incumbent lawmakers),'' said Paul
Hendrie, spokesman for the Center for Responsive Politics, a
nonpartisan group in Washington that monitors federal elections.
``But it's also safe to say Congressman Shuster is one of the best
at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's office referred questions on his fundraising to his
top campaign aide, Ann Eppard, who did not return calls for comment
on the story. Shuster has said in the past that he has never broken
the law, and that any attacks on his campaign practices, including
a U.S. Attorney's investigation into Eppard, are politically
motivated.
</P>
<P>
   This past spring marked the high point of influence in Shuster's
26 years in the House, as his Transportation Committee concluded
almost 18 months of haggling over the six-year highway bill. Its
impact will be felt in every state, every congressional district
and on every road project across the country in need of federal
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Due to his towering presence in central Pennsylvania and in
Washington, Shuster has only faced nominal opposition in his
reelection bids, if at all. When Democrat Monte Kemmler ran against
him in 1996, he was the first opponent Shuster had seen in a
primary or general election since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the Shuster fundraising machine takes a
break.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Shuster raised $776,175, according to the Almanac of
American Politics. In 1996, Shuster raised $1.2 million in winning
74 percent of the vote over Kemmler, who spent $113,000, a sizeable
amount for an unknown challenger.
</P>
<P>
   With token opposition in the May primary and no challenger in
the 1998 general election, Shuster has already raised more money
than he did in the 1996 campaign: $1.29 million in 1997 and the
first six months of this year for the virtually non-existent
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In just April, May and June, Shuster took $32,750 worth of
contributions from executives and political action committees of
construction companies, contractors and road builders. Another
$36,691.71 came from trucking, rail, auto and air industry
executives or PACs.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those industries had business before Shuster's
committee, either in the highway bill or in other areas such as
rail mergers. The alcohol and beverage industries, who lobbied
Shuster to kill a provision that would have forced states to adopt
.08 as the minimum blood-alcohol level for drunk drivers, kicked in
$3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that this mix of large contributions and
legislative activity creates the appearance of conflicts of
interest, at minimum, and is certainly not necessary since Shuster
faces no real political challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a culture of influence peddling in Washington, and Bud
Shuster knows how to take advantage of it,'' said Gary Ruskin, head
of the Congressional Accountability Project, a one-man shop begun
by Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no need to raise money,'' Hendrie, of the Center for
Responsive Politics, said. ``(The fundraising) is not driven by the
demand. It's driven by the supply -- the money is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more troubling to his critics is how Shuster spends his
campaign funds, since very little is needed to actually run his
election bids. Ruskin has filed an ethics complaint with the House
charging Shuster with using his campaign account to fund a lavish
lifestyle, something that would violate laws prohibiting candidates
from personally benefiting from their fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   For this election cycle, Shuster has already spent $1.18
million, FEC reports show.
</P>
<P>
   Those expenses include a $3,000-a-month salary for Eppard, his
former chief of staff who is now a transportation lobbyist but
mai+++bPOY
</P>
