<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STARR INVESTIGATION'S CAN OF WORMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prosecutor Kenneth Starr's long, costly investigation of
President Clinton seems not to have hurt Clinton politically. But
there is growing concern in scholarly circles that it has damaged
the office of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed on CNN last week, presidential historian Allan
Lichtman warned that Starr's far-ranging inquiries, along with
court orders sanctioning the scope of his almost limitless charter,
have already wrought a ``huge institutional change in the nature of
the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in history, Lichtman points out, a precedent
has been set allowing a sitting president to be sued for something
alleged to have happened before he took office. A private citizen
may sue him, and he is obliged to respond. Think of the
opportunities for mischief opened to anyone intent on distracting,
preoccupying or simply discrediting a chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   A second precedent is the concept that the president may be
investigated, at public expense, over things that do not relate,
even remotely, to his duties as president. The Whitewater episode,
genesis of this whole four-year investigative orgy, involved a
failed private investment in which the Clintons lost money years
before his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Still another disturbing innovation is the apparently accepted
verdict that an independent counsel, once installed, is virtually
unlimited in his prosecutorial authority and in widening the scope
of his inquiry. He can broaden the subject into almost any phase of
the president's life, and the president has practically no claim to
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Now arises the concern that future presidents' physical
protection may be compromised by Starr's insistence on subpoenaing
the Secret Service detail assigned to guard Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, nobody knows if that's a valid worry. Whether future
presidents may tend to distance themselves from their assigned
protectors when discussing private matters could depend on so many
variables, including individual personalities, that I can't even
hazard a guess. Commanding testimony from agents is not illegal,
but is it wise?
</P>
<P>
   It does seem clear that, in these four ways at least, the
presidency has been diminished. That should concern us all,
whatever our personal opinions of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Future presidents will have to live with the legal impediments
and inhibitions imposed upon previously presumed rights, powers and
immunities of that office.
</P>
<P>
   The prolonged, highly publicized investigative assault on
Clinton has left other less-obvious and less-measurable scars. One
is an undeniable loss of momentum for all the president's programs
stemming from the obsessive daily news focus on every petty, sordid
detail of the allegations. Other news has been squeezed out, to the
detriment of this chief executive's effort to stimulate public
support sufficient to move Congress to act on his initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Whether we agree or disagree with Clinton's policies, we must
ask if such systematic diversions of the public mind are healthy.
Think how easily future presidents may be similarly distracted from
achieving their leadership goals in the most fateful job on earth
if it's fair game now fK &QC; 1%Q% 1
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
