<SLUG> BC-BLIND-PHOTOGRAPHER-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLIND PHOTOGRAPHER PROVES EYESIGHT ISN'T ALL YOU NEED 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes photo 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By BEN WIDDICOMBE 
 c.1998 
 World rights except Britain and Australia 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Dugdale lives on one of New York City's prettiest streets,
</P>
<P>
   an avenue lined with lazy trees and hundred-year-old townhouses.
</P>
<P>
   The Chelsea skyline is visible through the conservatory of his
</P>
<P>
   top-floor apartment, where turn-of-the-century Americana sits
next
</P>
<P>
   to his collection of antique glass and porcelain. It's so
</P>
<P>
   beautiful, it's a pity he can't see it.
</P>
<P>
   Dugdale is almost blind.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him how much sight he has and he makes an eye shape
</P>
<P>
   with his thumb and forefinger, poking through the bottom with
the
</P>
<P>
   tip of his pinky. ``Oh, about that much in one eye,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between 1993 and 1994 I lost more than three quarters of my
</P>
<P>
   sight; I have a little bit out of the bottom of my left eye, but
</P>
<P>
   it's very blurry,'' Dugdale adds.
</P>
<P>
   Dugdale recently returned from two weeks in Britain, where he
</P>
<P>
   completed almost 100 landscape and interior compositions. The
</P>
<P>
   results will be a show called Nature and Spirit, opening in
</P>
<P>
   London this fall before moving to New York's Wessel and O'Connor
</P>
<P>
   Gallery in November.
</P>
<P>
   After also exhibiting this year in Rome and Sydney, Dugdale
</P>
<P>
   reflects that losing his sight propelled him from being
</P>
<P>
   just another commercial photographer for magazines like Vogue
and
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart Living to an internationally recognized artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tested HIV positive in 1985, but I was always very
</P>
<P>
   healthy,'' says Dugdale. ``I thought it was the end of my
</P>
<P>
   commercial career, but as a way to make my family feel better, I
</P>
<P>
   said: 'Don't worry, I'll be a great, blind, art photographer.'
</P>
<P>
   They were surprised that I said it and so was I, because it was
</P>
<P>
   the first time I verbalized it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As his sight dwindled, Dugdale came to rely on the help of
</P>
<P>
   assistants to focus his camera and set up shots. For composition
</P>
<P>
   he uses intuition and memory of other artwork, often putting
</P>
<P>
   himself in the pictures so he gets the right pose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely have a full, clear visual picture of everything
</P>
<P>
   that I photograph,'' he says. ``That really starts inside my
head,
</P>
<P>
   because eyesight and vision are completely different. I felt
very
</P>
<P>
   happy and safe when I realized my vision was totally intact.
It's
</P>
<P>
   just that my mechanical sight isn't working as well as it used
</P>
<P>
   to,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Able to make out dim outlines of buildings or natural features
</P>
<P>
   in strong daylight, Dugdale relies on touch to establish details
</P>
<P>
   like texture. Once he has felt an object or studied part of it
</P>
<P>
   with a magnifying glass, he explains, he sees it in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell from the light and the objects shape and from the
</P>
<P>
   100 questions that I ask people who are with me what is in front
</P>
<P>
   of me, and then I compose the shot in a very geometric way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Describing things to people, when they're doing the framing
</P>
<P>
   for me, I have to break it down to the utterly simplest kind of
</P>
<P>
   composition, because that's what people understand,'' Dugdale
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really communicate a photographic style or an eye to
</P>
<P>
   people, but what happened was the simplicity of the photographs
</P>
<P>
   turned into their style.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't stopped traveling, but the limitations of blindness
</P>
<P>
   mean much of his work concentrates on immediately available
</P>
<P>
   subjects, such as family, his upstate New York home and
</P>
<P>
   antiques.
</P>
<P>
   It was the classic, almost timeless feel of his art which two
</P>
<P>
   years ago attracted the attention of New York's Metropolitan
</P>
<P>
   Museum of Art. Associate Curator of Photography Malcolm Daniel
was
</P>
<P>
   involved with the decision to acquire a photograph of Dugdale's
</P>
<P>
   house, shot outdoors and inverted through the lens of a
</P>
<P>
   19th Century glass vase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The photograph expresses something about photography itself,
</P>
<P>
   and the way that the world that we've created is reflected
through
</P>
<P>
   art,'' says Daniel. ``What particularly appealed to us about
this
</P>
<P>
   was the element of self-referentiality it seemed to be about
</P>
<P>
   photography, and about light and images, and the way the vase
</P>
<P>
   itself acts as a lens to show the wider world that you don't
</P>
<P>
   actually see in the camera itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel denies that Dugdale, as a blind photographer, is a
</P>
<P>
   novelty act. ``It's not like the person who paints with their
toes,
</P>
<P>
   where you say, 'Isn't it remarkable for somebody who doesn't
have
</P>
<P>
   hands to be able to do that just with their feet?''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His deteriorating eyesight makes Dugdale more conscious of
</P>
<P>
   trying to capture certain effects of light and shadow which are
</P>
<P>
   essential to his work.
</P>
<P>
   And he's clear on the meaning of that work. ``My pictures are
</P>
<P>
   so accessible. They're about sadness, joy, beauty, death, life.
</P>
<P>
   All perfectly straightforward, unfettered emotions,'' he says,
</P>
<P>
   admitting to having run the gamut of those emotions himself.
</P>
<P>
   As AIDS began eroding his life, he admits, fear gave way to
</P>
<P>
   depression. ``I've had the experience of being lost in my own
front
</P>
<P>
   yard at my house in upstate New York. Most people have some
</P>
<P>
   ambient vision,'' Dugdale says, ``they can pick up shapes in the
</P>
<P>
   dark but as I lost my sight I would be plunged into total
</P>
<P>
   blackness when the sun went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only found the house by throwing pebbles and listening to
</P>
<P>
   where the sound came back from,'' he notes.
</P>
<P>
   His first book, ``Lengthening Shadows Before Nightfall,'' was
</P>
<P>
   published in 1994 and dealt with his feelings as doctors gave
him
</P>
<P>
   less than a year to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a specific message in the book but there was a
</P>
<P>
   sense of calm and tranquillity, because after struggling with
the
</P>
<P>
   disease, I had to prepare to pass away,'' Dugdale says. ``Every
time
</P>
<P>
   my friends and family came I had to say goodbye to them. At
first
</P>
<P>
   I was hysterical, but then towards the end of it I realized
there
</P>
<P>
   wasn't anything I could do by being insane, so I relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dugdale's health improved with new therapies and the book was
</P>
<P>
   a success, drawing attention for his use of techniques and
</P>
<P>
   equipment more at home in a history book than the studio of a
</P>
<P>
   contemporary artist.
</P>
<P>
   The distinctive blue of his work is the result of making
</P>
<P>
   cyanotypes, a ferrous-metal developing process pioneered in
1842.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to close out this century with the biggest body of
</P>
<P>
   cyanotypes that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Bedsides that process, Dugdale uses a 1912 camera in the
</P>
<P>
   field and shoots studio work with a 250-pound, 63-year-old
</P>
<P>
   behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   Dugdale's method has been such a success that his work commands
</P>
<P>
   up to $6,000 a print. As well as being in the permanent
collection
</P>
<P>
   of the Metropolitan, his patrons include Elton John, who
</P>
<P>
   hosted him on his recent visit to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Dugdale used John's estate as a base during his visit. From
</P>
<P>
   there he photographed English landmarks including Stonehenge.
</P>
<P>
   Printing a self-portrait taken on Britain's south coast, near a
cliff called Beachy Head, Dugdale was struck by his unconscious
choice of
</P>
<P>
   composition, a new theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beachy Head picture is so much about the precipice, and
</P>
<P>
   interestingly I didn't place myself on the edge of it,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm standing away, looking inland. Without getting too
</P>
<P>
   psycho-interpretive, that's a telling thing. I'm feeling present
</P>
<P>
   here and not on the edge anymore.''
 &UR; -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEN WIDDICOMBE is a free-lance writer based in Sydney,
Australia.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
