<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--CAFFEINE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAFFEINE: DEBATE STILL BREWS OVER ITS PROS AND CONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By KEN McALPINE 
 c.1998 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it's only fitting that one of history's earliest
references to caffeine involves loathing and self-recrimination.
</P>
<P>
   According to Chinese legend, Daruma, a Zen Buddhist leader,
dozed off during a nine-year meditation. Upon awakening, he was
filled with disgust. To prevent another nap he cut off his eyelids,
then threw them on the ground. A shrub sprouted, with the beverage
brewed from its leaves warding off sleep.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the tea plant, and its caffeine derivative has
firm roots: about 80 percent of Americans drink a little over two
cups of coffee, or caffeine equivalent, every day.
</P>
<P>
   Equally entrenched is the fear and guilt surrounding caffeine, a
drug. It's not pleasant to know there are people who would knee
their grandmother in the abdomen to get the last cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   And there's endless discouraging research, too. Studies have
linked caffeine to increased risk of heart disease and heart
attack, and as a possible contributor to bladder cancer and birth
defects. The whole thing is scary and depressing, enough to make
anyone give up caffeine - tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Your conscience will have to resolve things about your
grandmother. But as for the rest of it, it seems caffeine consumers
are engaging in unnecessary worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since caffeine is a drug, it would be nice if we could scare
people by saying your head's going to fall off if you ingest the
stuff,'' says Terry Graham, a professor at the University of Guelph
in Ontario, Canada. ``But really there is very, very limited
evidence that caffeine ingestion, unless it's very high, is going
to do much of anything other than create a mild dependency.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, a respected scientist whose work with colleague Lawrence
Spriet is regarded as the standard in caffeine research, is also
frank.
</P>
<P>
   Does consumption increase the risk of coronary artery disease?
No, says Graham. Bladder cancer? No. Birth defects? No. Addiction?
Yes, but mild and fairly easily overcome after a short withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Not to say caffeine is glitch free. There is good evidence, says
Graham, that women who drink a lot have a harder time getting
pregnant. And because caffeine increases the amount of calcium lost
in urine, it contributes slightly to osteoporosis. But one study
noted that women who drank four cups of coffee a day could offset
that with a glass of milk.
</P>
<P>
   The only link of real concern actually has nothing to do with
caffeine. In certain instances coffee can increase blood
cholesterol levels, which could lead to a heart attack. ``If coffee
isn't filtered through paper there are lipids from the coffee that
get into your blood,'' says Graham.
</P>
<P>
   But he's also the voice of reason. Drinking an espresso a few
times a week won't kill you. But if you regularly drink unfiltered
thick coffee, you might reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most experts agree. With caffeine, as with most
everything else, try moderation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cancer, birth defects, heart disease, they're all scare
tactics,'' says Ellen Coleman, a Riverside, Calif., sports
nutritionist who has examined effects of caffeine on health and
athletic performance. ``A moderate intake of caffeine is fine. And,
depending on the person, that could be the equivalent of up to five
cups of coffee a day.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem. Caffeine's effects, good and bad, can vary
tremendously by person, making it difficult to make specific
guidelines. Generally, Coleman advises keeping it to two to three,
8-10 ounce cups of coffee a day.
</P>
<P>
   She recommends this mostly to avoid negative short-term effects
_ nausea, headaches, insomnia, tremors, heart palpitations and the
certainty that, in short order, you will jump out of your skin.
</P>
<P>
   It's these consequences, not long-term health effects, that are
the problem, says Coleman. If you experience these, you're getting
too much caffeine. A lifelong coffee drinker, Coleman recognizes
her limit scientifically: if she drinks more than ten ounces a day,
``I feel horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   If you ignore these signals and continually drink too much
caffeine, Coleman suggests looking elsewhere for solutions. ``If
you're drinking more than three cups of coffee a day, or nine or
ten sodas, maybe you need to look at getting more sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   What about caffeine as a sports performance enhancer? Can it
make you run faster and bike longer?.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind that caffeine works, and
sometimes works very powerfully,'' says Graham. ``Many athletes can
improve their performance with caffeine.''
</P>
<P>
   This is news to some, but not others. Fifteen years ago, certain
athletes at the Hawaii Ironman Triathlon were drinking a concoction
of de-fizzed Coke, No Doz and aspirin named ``the Bomb.'' The
International Olympic Committee was sure enough about caffeine's
effects to place it on its banned substances list. And if an
athlete is found with urinary caffeine levels above 12 micrograms
per milliliter, they are punished.
</P>
<P>
   Several critical points. Most of us are not vying for an Olympic
medal. Second, without the aid of a pill, getting busted by the IOC
could be hard - you'd have to consume roughly 24 ounces of coffee,
16 cans of cola, or 8 pounds of chocolate beforehand. And, finally,
most research has been on highly conditioned athletes using fairly
high doses in pill form, more than you'd get in a cup or two of
coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, experts agree a moderate amount of caffeine might help
the ordinary athlete's performance. A long distance cyclist and
triathlete, Coleman finds a cup an hour before exercise has made
some long runs and bikes easier. A marathon runner, Graham has
experimented on himself in the lab, with positive results.
</P>
<P>
   But before you drink up, consider researchers still aren't sure
exactly how caffeine enhances performance. And in a
soon-to-be-published study, Graham and Spriet say they found coffee
somehow appears to inhibit caffeine's performance-boosting effects.
</P>
<P>
   That the precise effects of caffeine are still unresolved is an
enticing dilemma for researcher Graham. But athlete Graham resolved
it long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't touch the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ---------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ken McAlpine is a free-lance writers based in Ventura,
Calif.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
