<HEADLINE>
CROWS COLLECT BRIGHT MOMENTS INTO TWO-CD LIVE SET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time Counting Crows left their native Berkeley,
Calif., to go on tour it was the fall of 1993, before the release
of their debut CD, ``August and Everything After.'' They were
driving their own cars, and as they crossed the bridge to San
Francisco they blasted Bruce Springsteen's ``Thunder Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years and 6 million copies of ``August'' later, they
headed out again behind CD No. 2, ``Recovering the Satellites,'' in
a big ol' tour bus, 18 months of headlining shows around the world
in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big jump to make, and just how' big has everything to
do with the music on the band's new two-CD live set, ``Across a
Wire _ Live in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Recorded in August and November 1997 at Chelsea Studios (for
VH1's ``Storytellers'' series) and Hammerstein Ballroom (for MTV's
``Live From the 10 Spot'' series), ``Wire'' is one part
budget-priced gift to the fans, one part a stop-gap measure to
appease those waiting for a new Crows CD and one part a document of
how much the band had changed on the road _ from scuffling
opening-act club gigs to headlining sheds.
</P>
<P>
   Lead singer Adam Duritz is a big fan of bootlegs, and he wanted
to have one of his own band. This is as close as he'll ever come.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's like 250 bootlegs of us available,'' he says. ``We've
always kept in touch with fans on the Internet, so I know the kids
at the shows want a live album. Our fans won't stop bootlegging us
because they have this _ it's just a fun thing. And the shows were
really well-recorded. So we just decided to put it out.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, ``Across a Wire'' is a very good live CD _ in no small
part because it was done on a tour that found the band going beyond
the rather narrow sound of the first CD to embrace both harder rock
and a greater willingness to experiment.
</P>
<P>
   On the ``Satellites'' tour, big hits like ``Mr. Jones'' were
recast as acoustic folk and Duritz became a more expressive live
vocalist and more physical performer. And the band rose to the
occasion of having to simply make a bigger noise to fill the bigger
places they found themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   ``My songs are about yesterday _ how I feel about what happened
to me or what I thought _ and ``Satellites'' was about going on the
road for the first time,'' says Duritz. ``It was a huge change in
my life and traumatic and weird. It's pretty cool in some ways, but
you do give up your life for a big chunk of time _ people you know
go on with their lives and get married and have kids and you're
suspended in this bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 6, I stood in front of a mirror and pretended to be
the Beatles. Now I'm 33, and I stand in front of 20,000 people and
pretend to be the Beatles _ and I pull it off. It's a weird thing _
going out in front of that many people and going back to a hotel
room alone. But the last tour wasn't as big a deal _ I wasn't as
overwhelmed with the freakishness of it.''
</P>
<P>
   That, finally, is why ``Wire'' is, at times, fascinating _ or
should be to any Crows fan. In a very real sense, we're hearing a
band growing up onstage, finding out about themselves and what they
want to become.
</P>
<P>
   And all this change is drastically affecting the current
recording sessions for the band's third studio CD. The increased
confidence that came with the ``Satellites'' tour led to the band
going into the studio with nothing written, no scraps of ideas or
guitar riffs on tape or anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to have very few preconceptions,'' he says.
``It's very experimental _ you have to follow the muse. It's very
much a work in progress _ we're trying to explore the songs and
what they're about and different songs rather than getting a
groove. This is a dramatically different way of making a record for
us, and I have no idea when it'll be done.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
