<HEADLINE>
WATCH OUT FOR THE BUDGET-SURPLUS STAMPEDE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Predicting a $3.7 billion state budget surplus a
few months before an election is kind of like taking a bunch of
kids to a candy store.
</P>
<P>
   You better get out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Political candidates have been scrambling all over each other in
their eagerness to cash in on Texas' continued prosperity,
promising to spend _ prudently, of course _ the anticipated largess
on numerous worthwhile and/or politically popular needs and
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush wants to boost reading skills, renovate old
courthouses and give franchise tax exemptions to small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat John Sharp and Republican Rick Perry, the rivals for
lieutenant governor, like the tax break idea too. And Bush's
Democratic challenger Garry Mauro wants to give schoolteachers a
$5,000-a-year pay raise and repeal the sales tax on motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The list of promises goes on and on, aided and abetted by
another windfall, the $1.2 billion that Texas is expected to
receive in first-year payments under its record lawsuit settlement
with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Morales, who negotiated the tobacco deal,
is urging lawmakers to spend the cigarette money on health care and
anti-smoking programs. But Morales will leave office before the
Legislature convenes in January, and other politicians already are
suggesting other uses for the tobacco funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been poor, and I have been rich. Rich is better,''
singer Sophie Tucker once observed. And any number of state
officials, particularly those who remember the severe budget
crunches Texas endured during the recession of the 1980s, wouldn't
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, when state government was plagued with potential
deficits rather than blessed with surpluses, it usually was more
fun being a challenger than an incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Would-be legislators or would-be governors would simply promise
to cut spending or ``scrub'' the budget and vow to oppose higher
taxes because that's what most voters wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were elected, however, often ended up eating their
anti-tax promises.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the only kind of tax talk we hear from the campaign trail
is how some candidates want to cut taxes or _ in the case of Bush _
have already succeeded in trimming them.
</P>
<P>
   Remember last year's boost in the homestead exemption from
school taxes, the highlight for Bush during the 1997 legislative
session? It saved the average homeowner only about $140 a year, but
Bush's spin on it is a bit grander. Speaking collectively for all
the homeowners, he calls it the largest tax cut _ about $1 billion
_ in Texas history.
</P>
<P>
   The budgetary outlook for next year's session is so rosy that
Sharp, who now is the state comptroller and official revenue
estimator, certainly didn't mind projecting the record, $3.7
billion surplus several months early.
</P>
<P>
   A key legislator requested the preliminary estimate, but being
the bearer of good news didn't hurt Sharp's race for lieutenant
governor.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest beneficiaries of the state's good economic
times has been Bush, a fact that may sometimes be overlooked when
the governor's popularity and success in office are recounted.
</P>
<P>
   Without slighting Bush's own abilities, he had a much easier
time winning legislative approval of civil justice reforms, changes
in public education and other priorities because he didn't have the
enormous distractions that budgetary problems produced for other
recent governors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has avoided the public blame that incumbent leaders
receive, usually unfairly, when the economy turns sour. Instead, he
has benefited from the optimism that a good economy produces.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mark White was forced to call the Legislature into special
session to cut the budget and raise taxes only a few months before
Election Day, after the bottom had fallen out of oil prices in
1986. White didn't win a second term.
</P>
<P>
   The poor economy, among other things, also plagued Gov. Bill
Clements, who unseated White with an anti-tax campaign. Only a few
months later, Clements signed a record, $5.6 billion tax bill, and
his negative ratings with the public remained high the remainder of
his term.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Ann Richards, Clements' successor, also had to contend with
a revenue shortfall and sign a tax bill during her first year in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Bush courted a potential disaster last year when he urged the
Legislature to overhaul state taxes in order to provide deep cuts
in local school property taxes. The Legislature refused, mainly
because there was no financial crisis that required lawmakers to
make difficult political decisions on taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The budgetary stability helped Bush land on his feet. The
Legislature raised the homestead exemption and had enough money to
give school districts $1 billion to replace the revenue they lost
to the higher tax break, and Bush proclaimed victory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
