<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE TEMPTED BY INTERNET STOCKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reader called recently and asked whether I thought Internet
stocks were too hot to buy right now.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is a resounding yes.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I'm a big fan of computers and the Internet.
Both are key tools for me in my job and entertain me in my leisure
time.
</P>
<P>
   But resist the temptation to buy them because many of them look
poised to flame out because they're so overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like them, but they're gasoline,'' said Brian Grove, a
principal at money managers Vaughan, Nelson, Scarborough &AMP;
McCullough in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   People want to get in because they want to grab a winner. But
remember you are buying a piece of a business and ultimately, the
value of a business is based on profits.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, profits are nowhere to be found with most
Internet companies. Still, they're worth far more than many
profitable established companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm evaluating these companies, I wouldn't even know where
to start,'' said Brendan Connaughton, a portfolio manager in the
investment management group at Wells Fargo Bank in Houston.
``You're talking about companies that in some cases have never even
made a profit. How do you evaluate a company on pure potential?''
</P>
<P>
   That gaping hole doesn't seem to bother many investors. Any
stock remotely associated with the Internet has soared to
stratospheric levels.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   The market capitalization of Amazon.com., the pioneer Internet
bookseller, has soared to $6.4 billion, nearly the combined value
of competitors Barnes &AMP; Noble and Borders, both of which earn
profits, which Amazon.com has never done.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet company lost $21.2 million in the second quarter,
although sales more than quadrupled.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of search-engine companies, which help consumers find
Web sites, have risen so far so fast that investors are in a
fantasy world.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are buying these stocks without any thought as to what
they're doing,'' said Richard J. Fruth, head of Richard J. Fruth &AMP;
Associates in Houston, a money management firm.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Broadcast.com, which provides audio and video
programming over the Internet, became the best-performing initial
public offering in history when it rocketed from an IPO price of 18
to as high as 74 in its debut on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet stocks are selling at a whopping 30 to more than
100 times sales. That compares to a price that is 1.87 times sales
for Compaq Computer Corp., according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stocks are trading on so many assumptions about what's
going to happen in the future that the first time there's a hiccup
about any of these projections, the upside and the downside can be
dramatic, and they are certainly not for the faint of heart,'' said
R. Scott Bowers, senior vice president of investments at
PaineWebber in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that the Internet is here to stay, but the problem
with trying to buy the next CBS is there is no way to tell which
companies have staying power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has lots of opportunity, but we won't know who
the survivors will be until five or six years from now, and you can
be sure some of the favorites won't be around,'' said Anthony
O'Bryan, market analyst at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis, a
brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   A Houston company, which has joined the Internet frenzy, says
it's got what it takes to succeed in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata Corp., whose profits come from harvesting and processing
fish, is bent on becoming one of the world's largest Internet
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a solid financial base and that essentially separates
us from the rest of the Internet companies,'' said Avram Glazer,
president and chief executive officer. ``The majority of purchases
that Zapata has made are profitable Web sites.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think you're getting in on the ground floor of a great
thing, think again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's late,'' Fruth said. ``If they were going to buy these
stocks, they needed to buy these stocks two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   If you still intend to invest in Internet stocks, analysts
recommend that you put in no more than 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most prudent way to invest in these things is you buy a
diversified fund or a mutual fund,'' Grove said.
</P>
<P>
   But remember that what you're running up against is emotion and
greed on Wall Street _ a deadly combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people want get out of these things, they want out at any
price and when people want in, they want in at any price,'' Grove
said. ``That's fear and greed at work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
