<SLUG> BC-FILM-AVENGERS-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIGINAL AVENGER DECRIES VIOLENCE IN CONTEMPORARY FILMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The video screens at PlanetHollywood flare and blare
with madness and mayhem. Bruce Willis wastes a bad guy. Sly
Stallone slaughters another. That's entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Then the theme restaurant pauses for a ceremony: Guest of honor
Patrick Macnee receives a black leather jacket and an umbrella, the
latter signifying his role as dapper spy John Steed on television's
``The Avengers.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran British actor makes a statement _ and he wishes more
filmmakers would do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence is a terrible thing,'' Macnee says. ``I took pride in
`The Avengers' in not carrying a gun. Of course, my umbrella
concealed a blade, but violence wasn't the point.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it the point of the big-screen ``The Avengers,'' due in
theaters Aug. 14 _ at least as far as Macnee can tell. Macnee has a
cameo in the movie, and he spent a week on the set with Ralph
Fiennes, who plays his old role.
</P>
<P>
   That cameo is supposed to be a surprise, so Macnee didn't want
to talk about it. But he was eager to discuss the original ``The
Avengers,'' both as a pop-cultural artifact and as a new element on
video's vista.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, A&AMP;E Home Video will release 12 digitally remastered
episodes of ``The Avengers'' in two boxed sets costing $29.95 each.
(Individual tapes cost $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Each set will have three tapes, with two episodes per tape.
They'll be in sequence from the start of the fifth season in 1967,
when ``The Avengers'' crossed the pond to debut on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Macnee was working alongside Diana Rigg, the most
popular of his four female co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   Her character of Emma Peel continues in the film, played by Uma
Thurman. And it's Rigg, not Macnee, who's most prominent on the new
videos' box art.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing smashing mod clothes and crashing into villains with a
martial-arts kick, Rigg starred in 51 episodes during two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Besides those 12 episodes coming to video, a one-hour
retrospective is set for cable's A&AMP;E. Hosted by Macnee, ``The
Avengers: The Journey Back'' will air Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Macnee and Dave Rogers have co-written ``The Avengers and
Me,'' just released by HarperCollins ($22). It's Macnee's memoir of
the show's long history.
</P>
<P>
   In short, what A&AMP;E wrongly bills as a ``cult'' show is a widely
loved and ongoing phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of all these elements is ``really more of a
coincidence'' than evidence of a master plan, Macnee said. ``Two
years ago, I had no idea a movie was even being made.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was aware that illegal copies of ``The Avengers'' videos
were being peddled in the United States, and he helped fight a
battle to stop such sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``These video pirates had the nerve to say our show was in the
public domain,'' Macnee said. ``So we had to go to court to assert
the original copyright.''
</P>
<P>
   He's eager ``for people who weren't even born when it aired to
see our show the way we did it, with enhanced quality and no
minutes cut out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Avengers'' hasn't been shown in this country since A&AMP;E ran
the one-hour programs in 1990. But it was a TV staple here in the
'60s and '70s. ``The Avengers'' debuted in Britain in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were before the James Bond craze,'' said Macnee, 76. ``A
lot of people think we were post-Bond. Well, we were pre-Bond.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he appeared in the 1985 Bond film ``A View to a Kill''
_ and co-stars Rigg and Honor Blackman also starred in Bond movies
_ Macnee said he loathes 007.
</P>
<P>
   ``That phrase `license to kill' puts me off completely,'' he
said. ``Those three words are repulsive. I played it the opposite.
I also thought, `If you have women about, why not let them do the
fighting?'''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting females were a big part of ``The Avengers,'' which
championed the '60s women's-liberation movement.
</P>
<P>
   After Blackman and Rigg, Linda Thorson became Macnee's co-star.
The show ended, then returned in 1978 as ``The New Avengers'' for
one season in the United States, with Joanna Lumley (later of
``Absolutely Fabulous'').
</P>
<P>
   Each woman had a different style, but Macnee's Steed stayed the
same: an aristocratic, unflappable fellow with a bowler hat and an
ever-present umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   Rigg's shows are hitting video first, but only from her second
season, which was shot in color. Her first season was in
black-and-white, which isn't as commercially viable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'd love to see them colorized,'' Macnee said.
``Some people would look on that with horror. But we didn't do them
in black-and-white for esoteric reasons. We just couldn't afford
color at the time. As soon as we could, we moved to color.''
</P>
<P>
   The earlier Blackman shows are even more problematical. They
were shot not on film but live on tape, ``and they don't look very
good today,'' Macnee said.
</P>
<P>
   Rigg best matched his own lightheartedness, Macnee said. ``Honor
was much more serious, but Diana had a wonderful devil-may-care
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Avengers'' was ahead of its time in many ways, Macnee
said, but especially in its presentation of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who else had a woman in such an equal and vigorous role?'' he
asked. ``Do you remember the women in `Bonanza?' I bet you don't.
</P>
<P>
   ```The Avengers' was original. When you had a woman come out in
tight leather clothing, sparking teen-age boys to lust and knocking
men over her shoulder, that was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Rigg wore miniskirts even before they reached British
boutiques and ``The Avengers'' pioneered plots involving computers,
Macnee knows the show's posture isn't new by today's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he believes the new film will continue it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ralph quite liked having me on the set because I'm a
fairly benign person, and we became great friends,'' he said. ``To
my astonishment, he's playing Steed exactly the way I did it _ but
a lot better, because he's a hell of a better actor.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the London-born Macnee lives with his wife, Baba,
and their two dogs in Palm Springs, Calif. (He has two children
from a previous marriage.)
</P>
<P>
   He's far from retired.
</P>
<P>
   Macnee hosts ``Mysteries, Magic and Miracles'' for the Sci-Fi
Channel, and he often performs on recordings of books, notably the
thrillers of Jack Higgins. ``A lot of us aging actors do that,
since we don't have to put our fat bodies on the screen,'' he said
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier years, Macnee played on such TV series as
``Battlestar Galactica'' and in such films as ``Young Doctors in
Love,'' ``The Howling'' and ``This Is Spinal Tap.''
</P>
<P>
   He recently made a music video for the British rock band Oasis,
whom he found to be ``obnoxious and derivative of the Beatles.
Their talents are reasonable but don't justify their arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   But he reserves his true wrath for bigger and more sinister
forces, embodied in current films that mindlessly offer violence as
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been through World War II and seeing people blown to
bits, I think what (Steven) Spielberg is doing now (in his gritty
World War II film ''Saving Private Ryan``) is sensationally
right,'' Macnee said. ``I wish we'd had CNN with us at Normandy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now a major movie, `The Avengers,' is coming out with a hero
who doesn't carry a gun. Hopefully it will make some sort of
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his old show gaining new admirers on video, ``there's no
guarantee,'' Macnee said. ``People may feel they've seen it all
before. But it's a damn good show, and it still works.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
