<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKFASTS MAKE B&AMP;BS MEMORABLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By Harry Shattuck 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Upon arriving at a Texas Hill Country
bed-and-breakfast not long ago, I discovered a collection of breads
wrapped in cellophane and placed on a plate next to a handwritten
note.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of your breakfast is in the refrigerator ready for
you to warm in the microwave tomorrow morning,'' the missive read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can top that,'' a friend said when I related this story.
``At a B&AMP;B where I spent the night, the proprietor left two coupons
valid for breakfast at a cafe down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Am I confused?
</P>
<P>
   I thought the basic concept behind a B&AMP;B's existence involved
two priorities: (1) a bed and (2) breakfast. And we can find a
comfortable bed at Motel 6.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's the breakfast _ served by a gracious host, of
course _ that gives a good B&AMP;B its distinction. A B&AMP;B without fresh
fruit and juices, crisp bacon and eggs and toast or muffins is akin
to the ``Killer B'' Houston Astros without baseball All-Stars Jeff
Bagwell and Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   I recall fondly Betsy and George Delforge's strawberry French
toast at the Delforge Place in Fredericksburg; Cathy and Mike
Dillon's bananas Foster crepes at the Crystal River Inn in San
Marcos; and Ellenor and Arthur Link's huevos rancheros at the
Columns on Alamo in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   And I know folks who return time after time to savor venison and
pork sausage and grilled English muffins at Janie and John Orr's
Inn Above Onion Creek near Kyle; Dutch baby pancakes and raspberry
smoothies at Frances and Bill Harris' Heart of My Heart Ranch in
Round Top; and brie-and-bacon quiche at Pam and Tommy Traylor's Ant
Street Inn in Brenham.
</P>
<P>
   These hosts and others scattered about Texas have a passion for
creating a gourmet breakfast every day; it's the highlight of any
stay. I dare say they'd cringe at the thought of asking a guest to
nuke day-old food in a microwave.
</P>
<P>
   So would Jonnie Stansbury, owner-operator of Blair House in
Wimberley.
</P>
<P>
   Stansbury opened her seven-room B&AMP;B _ a lovely establishment
that doubles as an art gallery _ in 1991 after spending 20 years as
an investment banker in San Francisco. There, as a serious hobby,
she had honed her cooking skills under the tutelage of Ken Wolfe,
the French-and Viennese-trained executive chef at Ernie's, as well
as Julia Child and Kim Hom.
</P>
<P>
   Stansbury's breakfasts are legend among B&AMP;B devotees.
</P>
<P>
   The repast starts with fresh-ground French-roast coffee, carafes
of ice-cold juices and fresh fruit _ a mlange of cherries,
cantaloupe and blueberries at our table.
</P>
<P>
   The morning bread selection may feature a braided almond loaf,
spice muffins with dried cherries, cinnamon rolls, piping-hot
scones or biscuits accompanied by homemade jams.
</P>
<P>
   All that serves as a mere prelude to whatever Stansbury's
imagination dictates as a main course. Delicate omelettes are a
specialty; ours included goat cheese topped with tomatilla or
roasted chipotle salsa. On other days, guests may savor a
vegetable-medley omelette, Virginia ham or perhaps polenta topped
with poached eggs and asparagus, accented by Hollandaise sauce,
with grilled tomatoes on the side.
</P>
<P>
   And at Blair House, breakfast is only part of the culinary
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving guests are greeted each afternoon with spiced tea,
sodas or sangria. At 7 o'clock, dessert is served _ maybe
chocolate-cherry-coconut poundcake; a caramel or
dried-apricot-and-almond tart; or Chocolate Decadence, a pecan
brownie with coffee ice cream and a warm Belgian chocolate sauce.
</P>
<P>
   And don't think you can escape by wandering into downtown
Wimberley a mile and a half away: Dessert will be placed on the bed
to await your return.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday nights bring a real treat. Although Stansbury says she
has no desire to operate a restaurant full time, Blair House
maintains the required license. And each Saturday _ for a $50
charge _ she presents a five-course gourmet extravaganza for guests
and others (24 diners maximum).
</P>
<P>
   Also popular are Stansbury's cooking schools combined with a
stay at Blair House: She will focus on seafood and vegetables Sept.
27-29 and on French and Italian country cooking Nov. 8-10.
</P>
<P>
   Many other Texas B&AMP;Bs provide both delicious meals and
comfortable accommodations. We'll focus on some of the best from
time to time in the Chronicle's new Preview section, published on
Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   For reservations at Blair House or information on Stansbury's
other food-related endeavors, call 512-847-1111 or access
http://www.blairhouseinn.com on the Internet. Room rates are
$135-$165, including breakfast. A two-night minimum stay on
weekends is required; plan these visits well in advance, too,
because Stansbury says Blair House hasn't had a weekend vacancy in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Call these numbers to reach other B&AMP;Bs mentioned here:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Delforge Place: 800-997-0462 or 830-997-6212.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Crystal River Inn: 888-396-3739 or 512-396-3739.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; The Columns on Alamo: 800-233-3364 or 210-271-3245.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Inn Above Onion Creek: 800-579-7686 or 512-268-1617.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Heart of My Heart Ranch: 800-327-1242 or 409-249-3171.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Ant Street Inn: 800-805-2600 or 409-836-7393.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured that none of these places has forgotten the meaning
of B&AMP;B.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
