<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING AND DIVIDING FAST-GROWING CRINUMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Have you an easy way of digging and dividing crinums? I have
a variety of them and love them because they are so carefree. They
seem to get crowded; when is the best time to divide?
</P>
<P>
   How should I treat my mock orange to get blossoms? They spread
freely from the roots and send up long branches but no blooms. Did
I cut it back at the wrong time?
</P>
<P>
   A: Crinums do grow quickly, so when you dig and divide, give the
transplants plenty of room or you'll find them cozy again before
you know it. You can divide in the fall before it gets cold or in
early spring. Plant with the neck above the soil level. Water until
the newly planted bulbs are established.
</P>
<P>
   Mock orange flower buds form on lateral growth produced the
previous year, so keep this in mind when pruning. These flowering
shrubs are pruned after they bloom. After flowering, prune old
wood, either to the ground or back to a promising new shoot. You
can remove about a fifth of the big branches each year. If a branch
refuses to flower, take it out.
</P>
<P>
   Mock orange (Philadelphus spp.) will grow in sun to bright shade
in a fertile, moist but well-draining soil.
</P>
<P>
   Q: One of my angel's trumpets is losing a lot of leaves. The
other one is blooming but is getting a lot of yellow leaves as
well. The new leaves on my geraniums are almost white. What is
going on with them? Our fan palms are losing bottom fronds. Do they
like a lot of water? Some fronds are turning yellow before they
brown.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's difficult to maintain even soil moisture in the horrid
conditions we've had this summer in Texas. While it's normal for
the older angel's trumpets leaves to fall, the leaves on my plant
are yellowing and dropping more than usual. I blame the heat and
lack of an even supply of water. While I try to water daily, it is
so hot and dry the soil moisture does fluctuate. Too little water
causes leaves to yellow and wilt. The edges may brown and dry. But
too much water also causes foliage to yellow and wilt, and the tips
may brown.
</P>
<P>
   Geraniums do not like this weather. They are best off in bright
shade during the summer, or where they receive just a little
morning sun. While you want to water them, don't overwater so that
the soil is mushy. Frequent watering leaches nutrients from the
potting soil, leaving foliage pale. You'll want to replace those
nutrients with a time-release, balanced fertilizer or occasionally
apply a liquid formula. Don't try to encourage tremendous growth
and blooms this time of year. The plants usually revive when fall
arrives. Use of hard water also can cause pale foliage.
</P>
<P>
   It's natural for the lower fronds of your fan palm to yellow,
brown and die. This is an aging process. Simply remove these. Water
your palms twice a week during this critical time. Don't overdo,
it, however. About five minutes with the hose should be adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would appreciate your advice on how to go about preparing
my poinsettia for blooming for Christmas. It is healthy with lots
of green leaves.
</P>
<P>
   A: Let me begin with the guidelines on what to do with a
poinsettia after the holidays:
</P>
<P>
   Maintain your plant as you would most potted plants: Water and
apply a balanced fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   When the plant has dropped its leaves in spring, repot and prune
the plant back to 6 to 8 inches to achieve a full, rounded canopy.
New growth will appear. Pinch as necessary to maintain a bushy
appearance. Keep the plant outdoors in a sunny or partially sunny
spot during the summer. Water it well while it grows, and fertilize
regularly with a balanced formula.
</P>
<P>
   To trigger the coloring process, begin a light-dark rotation in
October. Bring the plant indoors each afternoon and keep it in a
completely dark spot for 14 to 15 hours. Take it back outside each
morning.
</P>
<P>
   A night temperature of 65 degrees is optimum; much below that
will delay the coloring process. Day temperature is not as
critical, but try to avoid temperatures higher than 85 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a problem with St. Augustine in my front yard. There
is a large Arizona ash in the yard, and every winter and early
spring the grass is thick under and around the tree. As the weather
warms, the grass begins to thin. No matter how much I water or
fertilize, it stays this way until the weather cools. I have
noticed other yards with large trees do not have this problem. What
can I do to keep the grass thick during the heat?
</P>
<P>
   A: The grass needs more sunlight to remain thick. The grass
begins to grow while the tree is shedding its leaves or is
leafless, then gradually thins when the foliage is full in spring
and summer. St. Augustine will grow fairly well under large trees
when there is filtered light through a thinned canopy or there is
unobstructed, strong light from the sides. Your tree is benefiting
from all that fertilizer, too.
</P>
<P>
   There's probably not much you can do about light from the sides,
as buildings and other large trees often block such light. But you
could have an arborist carefully thin the canopy to allow more
sunlight to filter through to the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The bulk of mail prevents
individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
