<HEADER>
A4483 &Cx1f; tth-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI &LR;      07-27 0247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Tuesday, July 28, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   WEDDING-COSTS (Undated) A cheap wedding? You must be kidding.
Well, no, it's really possible. Many people are discovering they
can have great weddings at far less than the so-called ``average''
cost in this country of $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   with WEDDING-COSTS-TIPS (Undated) Tips tips on how to have a
great low-cost wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Stories by Susan Phinney. (stories will move in the ``l''
category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-TCA (Pasadena, Calif.) Final column from Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OKANAGAN (Kelowna, B.C.) _ To most Americans, Canada is
known for dog-mushing Mounties and puck-slapping ice warriors, not
sun and heat. Got news for you. There's a huge valley in British
Columbia called the Okanagan, where heat rises off pine-covered
hills in summer and an 82-mile crystalline lake provides a
refreshing venue for all manner of recreation.
</P>
<P>
   By Greg Johnston. (Story will move in the ``t'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CURRENCY-EU (Brussels, Belgium) On Jan. 1, the euro _ one common
currency for 11 members of the EU _ will become a reality. In time,
the euro may rival the dollar as the dominant world currency.
</P>
<P>
   By David Horsey. (story will move in the ``k'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
