<HEADLINE>
COUPLE CAN STILL TIE THE KNOT IN STYLE WITHOUT BREAKING THE BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (WITH WEDDING-TIPS)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The high cost of weddings is causing couples to examine their
priorities, do their homework, comparison shop and compromise.
</P>
<P>
   They have to if they're hoping to marry for less than the
average cost in this country, which one source puts at a whopping
$17,634 _ and probably more!
</P>
<P>
   That, according to Modern Bride Research, was the cost of the
average U.S. wedding with 175 guests _ and that was in 1995, the
latest year for which statistics are available.
</P>
<P>
   The figure includes:
</P>
<P>
   _$4,068 for engagement and wedding rings.
</P>
<P>
   _6,503 for a reception.
</P>
<P>
   _And a $776 wedding gown.
</P>
<P>
   Plus basics such as flowers, photography and fees for clergy,
church or synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   The famed champagne maker Moet &AMP; Chandon tracks the cost of
weddings annually using 12 elements, including catering, gown,
flowers, cake, invitations and champagne (of course).
</P>
<P>
   Their survey found it will cost 2.6 percent more to get married
this year than it did in 1997, when the prices jumped a whopping
7.9 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Deduct the rings _ most people don't include them in their
budgets _ allow for inflation, and it puts today's average wedding
in the $15,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   That's a figure that makes some Seattle-area newlyweds and
soon-to-be-wed couples incredulous. They're having great weddings
at a fraction of the price.
</P>
<P>
   Take Lindsay Burch and Samuel Rathert, for example. Their August
wedding for about 125 guests promises to be fun, picturesque and
long on charm. And it will cost about half the so-called national
average.
</P>
<P>
   Burch says fun and comfort were all-important to them when
making wedding plans. ``We want people to come to a party and have
a good time. Miss Manners and Martha Stewart weren't important to
us at all.''
</P>
<P>
   They're being married at her home next to the Eastside
equestrian center, where she trains and teaches. Burch and Rathert
are spending the summer landscaping the grounds. They'll have
dancing, but it will be on the grass instead of a rented or
custom-built dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   Their wedding flowers are growing as you read. Burch bought 40
metal buckets she distributed to friends, asking them to plant them
with flowers and bring them to the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   She found a cotton wedding gown on sale for 50 percent off, and
arranged a trade-out with a photographer friend: Burch boards her
horse in return for wedding photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The couple opted for printed party invitations that were perfect
for the country-casual wedding and picnic. ``Engraved wedding
invitations wouldn't have set the tone,'' Burch says.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Spitzer and Cindy Smith knew they wanted to be married in
a beautiful place, so they spent $1,200 to rent the Daybreak Star
Center at Discovery Park for their June wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer says they seriously shopped around before hiring a
caterer for a pasta and Copper River salmon dinner for 90 guests,
costing $2,700. Then they used their network of friends to put
together the rest of the celebration _ totaling about half the
national average.
</P>
<P>
   A friend's sister baked the cake. The wedding couple brought the
wine and designed their own invitations. A friend arranged the
printing for a fraction of the cost of traditional invitations.
Another friend donated the flower arrangements, balloons and
seating cards as her wedding gift.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer says they chose a photographer who charged a flat rate
for covering the event, gave them contact prints and a small album,
then turned over all the negatives so they could make prints
whenever they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   A week after her July 11 wedding, newlywed Claudia Montalvo
D'Ambrosia can't even remember how many guests attended when she
married Damon D'Ambrosia at St. Brendan Catholic Church in Bothell.
</P>
<P>
   The bride wore a gown borrowed from her best friend. The garden
reception for about 40 was held at a relative's home. ``We wanted
something simple and beautiful,'' Claudia says.
</P>
<P>
   They got it with two rented canopies, a luncheon buffet of deli
foods, and a cake from Costco. Total cost was in the low four
figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the religious part of the wedding was more important
than the party,'' Claudia says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
