<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-COST-TIPS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO KEEP THAT WEDDING COST DOWN  
 (WITH WEDDING-COST) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's tough to keep a wedding in the low four figures or less,
even a very modest one that includes just the basics of a few close
friends, some flowers, a couple of attendants, apparel (rented or
purchased), marriage license, clergy/-judge fees, and photographs.
</P>
<P>
   And the cost will quickly soar as you increase the number of
guests and attendants, use two sites (a church or synagogue, and a
clubhouse reception, for example), serve a meal and hire a wedding
consultant, photographer and a videographer.
</P>
<P>
   Bridal consultant Karen Cook says food, especially a served,
sit-down meal, can kick a wedding budget over the top in a flash.
``That can double food costs,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Weather is another foe. ``Around here we often need tents. A
tent for 50 people is about $400. One for 300 to 500 people is
about $2,000. Tent a whole back yard and it can cost $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Photography can be another minefield.``People fall in love with
photographers _ it can be an $800 one or a $3,000 one, and when
they fall in love, that's usually it,'' says Cook. ``But you can
get just as good quality with someone who charges less.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooks, caterers, recent brides and grooms and those planning to
wed this summer offer a wealth of tips for keeping costs down.
Here's what they say:
</P>
<P>
   Establish a budget: Then figure out where you want to spend it.
Lavish food may mean less money for music, or clothes. Refer to the
budget frequently. Be up-front with service providers about what
you want to spend and find those who will work within your budget.
</P>
<P>
   Plan ahead: The more time you have to research, shop and
do-it-yourself, the more you can save. It also means fewer
compromises _ such as having to take whatever's available at the
last minute. Someone planning a summer '99 wedding, for example,
could find a sample gown from this season on sale right now.
</P>
<P>
   The Puget Sound region is notorious for its lack of wedding
sites. Clubs, restaurants with large party rooms, hotels, halls and
other sites (especially those with views) tend to be booked a year
in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Think small: Even an expensive venue _ a private club or hotel,
for example _ can be affordable for a small group. A wedding tea at
the Four Seasons Olympic Hotel is possible for $20 per person (plus
tax and gratuity).
</P>
<P>
   A private ceremony followed by a restaurant dinner for friends
can be another small, but elegant celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Use one site: Having the ceremony and reception in a single
location saves money and energy. The best possible solution is the
home or garden of a friend or relative. (Offer to pay for cleaning,
yard work etc.)
</P>
<P>
   If big homes and gardens don't run in the family, newlywed
Deyette DeJager raves about the Daughters of the American
Revolution house on Capitol Hill in Seattle. The $1,200 rental fee
gives you the whole beautifully furnished facility _ dining room to
ballroom. DeJager says this site includes china, silver,
candlesticks and other necessities for no additional fee.
</P>
<P>
   Always ask what the rental fee includes. Don't assume that the
social hall comes with the church, for example. Some sites don't
include tables or chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Some places require renters to use a specific caterer. Sometimes
this is cost-effective, sometimes not. But find out.
</P>
<P>
   Shop around: Find a gown, a caterer, a photographer that fits
your budget. Comparison shop. Bride-to-be Tina Summers found the
same wedding gown with two prices _ one $300 less than the other.
Guess which one she bought.
</P>
<P>
   Make what you can: Many couples design their own invitations or
have them printed inexpensively.
</P>
<P>
   One bride bought white chocolate hearts as favors and wrapped
each one by hand. She saved about $1 per favor, or $150.
</P>
<P>
   Beware of rentals: One bride found nice looking plastic plates
for one-third the cost of rented china. Rented tents, tables,
chairs, punchbowls and glassware can be very expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Some grooms buy formal wear when rental firms sell off their
stock. It's often cheaper than renting.
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything: A morning wedding followed by a wedding
breakfast/luncheon, or an early afternoon ceremony with a formal
tea are probably going to cost less than evening nuptuals and
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Summers got a disc jockey for her Sunday wedding for a fraction
of his Saturday night fee.
</P>
<P>
   Have your heart set on tulips? Marry in the spring. Importing
tulips in December can break a budget.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of flowers: According to one Capitol Hill florist, it's
easy to spend $5,000-$6,000 on wedding flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The alternatives?
</P>
<P>
   Find a home-based florist who does only weddings and special
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Or grow or arrange your own.
</P>
<P>
   Summers is buying potted plants and hanging baskets from a
nursery _ plants that go home and keep growing following the
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Some large supermarkets (Safeway, for example offer wedding
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   DeJager bought her flowers wholesale, then paid $50 to have them
arranged.
</P>
<P>
   Another bride bought all her flowers from a neighborhood grocer
and invited five friends over the morning of her wedding to wrap
and wire the stems, then make the bouquets and corsages.
</P>
<P>
   Bride-to-be Angela Bostic discovered she could make all the
table centerpieces she needed for $15. The florist wanted $60 each.
</P>
<P>
   Public sites: Seattle-area parks and community centers are so
popular that the parks department has a special wedding
reservations line, 206-233-7068. Fees start at $250, plus a $100
refundable damage deposit. Most parks accommodate about 200 people,
a few can take 400 and and three are suitable for 50 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Caterer Susan Magan recommends senior centers. ``They're often
very nice,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Community centers from Alki to Laurelhurst, Magnolia to Yesler
are also practical options. Alki rents out a room that holds 150
for $27 per hour. If the facility is used after regular hours, a
staff person must also be paid $14 per hour, plus another one-time
$14 charge.
</P>
<P>
   Contact the desired center for information and reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Who pays? Traditionally, the bride's parents gave the wedding
reception, the groom's family the rehearsal dinner. But those lines
are being blurred. Today's weddings are likely to be a group
effort, paid for by the bride and groom and their families.
According to etiquette books, it doesn't matter who pays as long as
all concerned are comfortable with the decision. And all
contributors must be willing to compromise when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simplify Your Wedding'' by Allana Baroni (Reader's Digest, 144
pages, $17.95) is loaded with good ideas. Chapters have a colorful
little boxs outlining simple, simpler and simplest solutions to
everything from controlling the guest list to sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
