<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-WHALING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INUIT HARPOONS SNAG ENVIRONMENTALISTS' IRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANGNIRTUNG, Northwest Territories _ Word of the feat swept
through the widely scattered Inuit communities of Canada's eastern
Arctic with uncanny speed, bringing whoops of jubilation, tears of
joy. Hunters from this Baffin Island settlement, once a reknowned
whaling station, had harpooned a bowhead, completing their first
succesful whale hunt in more than half-a-century.
</P>
<P>
   Simeonie Keenainak, 48, and other Inuits, or Eskimos, in the
boat-borne expedition earlier last week closed on their quarry amid
the frigid swells of Cumberland Sound and plunged their harpoons
into the great marine mammal's glistening flanks with the deadly
precision of their forebears.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very, very happy, and so proud,'' said Annie
Keenainak, daughter of the hunt leader. ``This is not simply a hunt
but a celebration of our Inuit ways. We are whaling people, and the
whale hunt was central to our society until it was taken from
us.'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But by giving its official blessing to the revived native hunt,
Canada has joined the ranks of renegade nations _ most notably
Norway and Japan _ defying a world ban on whale hunting.
</P>
<P>
   The International Whaling Commission, the world body responsible
for regulating commercial whaling, earlier this year condemned the
Pangnirtung hunt in a formal resolution and implored Canada to ban
it. The condemnation was echoed by antiwhaling activists and
environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outlaw whaling,'' said Paul Watson, head of the Sea
Shepherd Society. ``Unfortunately, in native communities, reviving
culture means having to kill something.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowhead whales in the eastern Arctic were hunted nearly to
extinction by commercial hunters, both aboriginal and white, during
the 19th and early 20th centuries. Although there is a healthy
population of some 7,500 bowheads off Alaska, the species has not
rebounded in the waters surrounding Baffin Island, where fewer than
700 survive, according to marine scientists. More than 10,000
bowheads swam in the same region a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is compelling scientific evidence that this is not a
population that can withstand any level of hunting,'' said Rick
Smith, Canadian director for the International Fund for Animal
Welfare, which has its headquarters in Yarmouthport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The bowhead is internationally classified as an endangered
species. Canada quit the whaling commission in 1982, insisting it
is no longer a whaling nation, and has ignored the body since.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian wildlife officials defend the hunt as ``sustainable,''
noting that under an agreement with the Inuit, a designated Inuit
community may kill only a single whale every other year. They argue
that the survival of a native culture that once centered around the
whale hunt justifies the limited taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have a cultural right to hunt this animal under
closely regulated conditions,'' said Stu Innes, a marine mammal
specialist with Canada's Department of Fisheries and Oceans.
</P>
<P>
   The Inuit say that the whales belong to them, not the world, and
that neither environmentalists nor the International Whaling
Commission have any business criticizing the hunt. ``It is our
right, part of our culture, to harvest any animal within Nunavut,
regardless of any regulations,'' said Eric Joamie, a leader of the
Pangnirtung Hunters Association.
</P>
<P>
   Nunavut, which means ``Our Land,'' is the name chosen for the
733,000-square-mile region _ inhabited by 25,000 people, mostly
Inuit _ that next April 1 will break from the Northwest Territories
and become a semi-autonomous Inuit homeland.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement leading to the creation of the new
territory, the Inuit won the right to resume hunting for bowheads.
The first such hunt, which occurred in 1996 near the mouth of
Hudson Bay, was a bloody debacle that humiliated the Inuit, who
take pride in their close relationship with creatures of the north,
even those they hunt for food, clothing, and implements.
</P>
<P>
   A team of hunters from Repulse Bay, near the mouth of Hudson
Bay, chased down a bowhead using high-tech sonar gear, then riddled
it with hundreds of shots from high-powered rifles. They finally
succeeded in killing the beast, but the carcass sank, washing
ashore several days later to rot on the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very ugly,'' Keenainak told the Toronto-based Globe &AMP;
Mail newspaper earlier this month. ``But we learned a lot from that
hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, the hunters were armed with an exploding harpoon
fired from a shoulder-mounted gun as well as with heavy-bladed
spears. Accounts reaching Pangnirtung from the hunters' base camp
on Cumberland Sound, where the whale was butchered, asserted that
the kill was clean and swift. It was the first for the once-famous
whaling settlement since the 1940s, when whaling died out because
of a lack of demand for whale products; it was later banned after
the whales were found to be virtually extinct in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Bowhead whales can weigh up to 100 tons and reach lengths of 60
feet. The animal harpooned by the Pangnirtung hunters measured 43
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Inhabitants of this community feasted on the flesh, and portions
of the whale's meat and chewy ``maktak'' _ the blubbery outer
coating, an Arctic delicacy _ were transported by bush plane to
Inuit settlements across the territory. Remnants of the whale will
be used to feed sled dogs or cured into jerky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ancestors carried out this harvest, and the whale hunt is
a way of making our culture once again whole,'' said hunter Joamie.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, took a dimmer view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not opposed to subsistence hunting by native groups,''
said Smith of the International Fund for Animal Welfare. ``But this
particular hunt is very ill-advised. At a time when Canada and the
world should be celebrating the coming of Nunavut, it's very sad to
see the Inuit doing themselves such a disservice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
