<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4492 &Cx1f; tth-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-OKANAGAN-SPI &LR;      07-27 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OKANAGAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B.C.'S OKANAGAN VALLEY TURNS UP HEAT ON RECREATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREG JOHNSTON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KELOWNA, B.C. _ To most Americans, Canada is known for
dog-mushing Mounties and puck-slapping ice warriors, not sun and
heat.
</P>
<P>
   It is the ``frozen north,'' after all, and everyone knows that
to find sun you head south.
</P>
<P>
   Got news for you.
</P>
<P>
   There's a huge valley in British Columbia called the Okanagan _
just north of Washington's Okanogan _ where heat rises off
pine-covered hills in summer and an 82-mile crystalline lake
provides a refreshing venue for all manner of recreation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are not used to traveling north to get warmth,''
says Rod Lampard, lifelong resident of the valley and director of
sales at Lake Okanagan Resort. ``Quite often, they stop off here on
the way to the (Canadian) Rockies and they find this valley and go
`Whoa!'''
</P>
<P>
   The Okanagan is British Columbia's summer playground. It's
centered on glacier-carved Lake Okanagan and is anchored in the
middle by Kelowna _ a happening city of 120,000 _ in the north by
Vernon and in the south by Penticton.
</P>
<P>
   You will need sunscreen; during a three-day visit earlier this
month, temperatures soared past 30 degrees _ Celsius, that is _
equivalent to the upper 80s and 90s on the Fahrenheit scale.
</P>
<P>
   Eight hundred feet at its deepest, Lake Okanagan is the alleged
home to an oversize and elusive serpent known as Ogopogo. The joke
in Kelowna is that it is most frequently seen by patrons leaving
the bars at 2 a.m. The lake is also a superior setting for water
skiing, wakeboarding and pleasure boating, from jet-craft rippin'
to houseboat loungin'.
</P>
<P>
   The Okanagan Valley is on the northern end of the vast, semiarid
region of the Northwest that stretches along the east slope of the
Cascade Range from Central Oregon through Washington, and includes
such hot spots as Bend and Chelan.
</P>
<P>
   The thing that sets the Okanagan apart _ other than uniquely
Canadian coins such as the ``loony'' and ``twoony'' and accents
that range from Irishlike lilts and brogues to snowboarder hip _ is
the dizzying variety of activities available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for a place that had swimming, golfing,
horseback riding and fishing,'' said Lauren Hartke of Auburn, who
vacationed with family members in the Kelowna area in early July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Chelan two years ago, but we couldn't get into the
condo there this year, and they didn't have horseback riding. This
is beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades the area has been known as one of North America's
top fishing regions. Lake Okanagan produces trout that can reach 20
pounds, and dozens of the famed ``Kamloops Lakes'' just to the west
offer superior fishing for a particularly renowned strain of
rainbow.
</P>
<P>
   In the hills and mountains on either side of the lake, hiking
and mountain bicycling are huge. Centers for these activities
include the historic Myra Canyon section of the old Kettle Valley
Railway, now a recreational path with 18 trestles and two tunnels
intact, and Okanagan Mountain and Cathedral provincial parks _ two
of 39 provincial parks in the Okanagan District.
</P>
<P>
   This is cattle country, and more than two dozen ranches offer
horseback riding in the surrounding hills and mountains. Kayakers
and canoeists have dozens of lakes to choose from, including
deep-blue Kalamalka Lake north of Kelowna. There also is excellent
rockhounding and bird-watching.
</P>
<P>
   The valley has long been known as Canada's ``fruit basket,'' and
in recent years the number of wineries has grown to 24, supporting
a blossoming ``agri-tourism'' industry. The valley also boasts
about 20 golf courses, three of championship caliber: Gallagher's
Canyon, Predator Ridge and The Harvest.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, two major ski areas operate in the mountains just to
the east: Big White and Silver Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``The valley is a four-season playground,'' says Jacob Astin, a
pilot for Air-Hart Aviation in Kelowna and a skier/snowboarder
who's partial to Silver Star. ``You can ski, golf and water ski on
the same day.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the main draw of the Okanagan is the giant lake and the
water sports it provides, hikers will find plenty of intriguing
opportunities. Backpackers head to 80,000-acre Cathedral Provincial
Park in the South Okanagan _ a rugged, forested wilderness of
alpine lakes, cliffs and canyons such as ``The Big Cleft'' _ or
26,000-acre Mount Okanagan Provincial Park just south of Kelowna.
</P>
<P>
   Okanagan Mountain is an arid expanse of spruce- and fir-covered
hills with about 20 miles of undeveloped shoreline on Lake
Okanagan. The area has two prime destinations: Wild Horse Canyon, a
lush and narrow rock defile popular among mountain bikers and
hikers, and a lovely cove called Commando Bay, where backpackers
set up camp above sandy beaches, with ancient pictographs on rock
walls nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a fabulous place,'' says Linda Jones-Evans, an avid
hiker and owner of Outdoor Adventure Gear in Kelowna. ``It is a
very hot environment, and people make the beach a destination. It
is very unique because it represents the typical Okanagan
wilderness'' before the arrival of Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   With six primitive campgrounds, the bays and coves along the
park's shoreline are also prime anchorages for houseboaters.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most popular path in the valley, however, is the
Kettle Valley Railway. Abandoned as a rail route in 1959, it winds
through the mountains above the valley at the 4,000-foot level for
hundreds of miles. The most dramatic stretch of ``the KVR,'' as
locals call it, is the stupendous 5.27-mile Myra Canyon, about a
half-hour drive from Kelowna.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that the 18 trestles and two tunnels are a
big draw,'' says Cam Baker, the goateed owner of Okanagan Mountain
Bike Tours, which leads trips there. ``When people get out on the
ridge, they are pretty blown away by the scenery.''
</P>
<P>
   The trestles, most of them wooden and one 780 feet long and
hundreds of feet high, remain a marvel of engineering, with views
from some reaching out over Kelowna and the lake valley below.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mellow ride, with decking and railing on the trestles
protecting cyclists and walkers from precipitous plunges, and the
railway bed is flat. However, at the western end of the canyon,
there is a rugged 3-mile ``single track'' called the Crawford Trail
that descends through forest and provides challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be dangerous and try to kill yourself there,'' says
Baker, ``or just take a slow, easy, scenic ride on the railway.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard-core bikers have plenty of other spots in which to ride.
Ask any bike shop in Vernon, Kelowna or Penticton about places like
Crawford Estates, McDougall Rim, Campbell Mountain or Silver Star,
and they'll point your wheels toward some bumpy runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Okanagan is kind of a quiet mountain-biking mecca,'' says
pilot Astin, also an avid rider. ``The Okanagan has some really
amazing riding.''
</P>
<P>
   Okanagan notes
</P>
<P>
   _Okanagan/Similkameen Tourism Association Web site:
www.osta.bc.ca
</P>
<P>
   _Thompson/Okanagan Tourism Association in Kelowna: 250-860-5999
</P>
<P>
   _B.C. Parks main office: 250-494-6500
</P>
<P>
   Branch office in Summerland: 250-494-6500
</P>
<P>
   Web site: www.elp.gov.bc.ca/bcparks
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
