<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4495 &Cx1f; tth-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CURRENCY-EU-SPI &LR;      07-27 2461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CURRENCY-EU-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRENGTHENING THE TIES THAT BIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID HORSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Imagine Claude Monet standing before his
easel in a garden.
</P>
<P>
   Paintbrush in one hand, palette in the other, Monet dabs paint
onto canvas in the serene sunlight, re-creating in quick
brushstrokes the flowers of the garden, two women under a parasol
and a table laden with the midday meal.
</P>
<P>
   Now picture Meriwether Lewis poised at the Continental Divide,
the first of his countrymen to look beyond the Rocky Mountains into
an uncharted wilderness. With little more than his wits and the
rifle slung on his shoulder, he descends into a new world to find
either death or glory.
</P>
<P>
   Monet and Lewis are archetypes of their respective lands.
Despite a shared modern world of cellular telephones and stock
reports, Hollywood movies and traffic jams, Europeans and Americans
continue to approach life with distinctly different priorities.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, stability, tradition and egalitarianism are prime
values. In America, innovation, risk-taking and unfettered
individuality are most highly prized.
</P>
<P>
   The American admonition to ``just do it'' is an alien idea in
consensus-crazed Europe, and the Jeffersonian maxim that ``the
government which governs best governs least'' does not apply on a
continent that looks to gigantic bureaucracies to provide a secure
society for all.
</P>
<P>
   Just one stark distinction between one side of the Atlantic and
the other: While American firms such as The Boeing Co. and
Microsoft Corp. stay competitive by getting many more than 40 hours
a week of work from most hard-charging employees, government
inspectors in France are conducting raids and fining companies
where middle managers exceed the weekly 39-hour work limit (soon to
be lowered to 35).
</P>
<P>
   Yet, a further look at the artist and adventurer will reveal
deeper themes that, in these concluding months of the 20th century,
are drawing Europe and the United States together in a common
interest that transcends differences, a shared destiny that could
allow the trans-Atlantic partners to dominate the globe for a
century to come.
</P>
<P>
   First, look more closely at Monet, the European. The moment in
which we have glimpsed him is a real day in 1870, and the artist is
not in a French garden but a London park. He has fled to England
while a Prussian army lays siege to Paris. Soon, the city will be
seized by revolutionaries on a doomed and bloody march toward a
more just society.
</P>
<P>
   The war and revolt from which Monet escaped were just two deadly
events in a long succession of intra-European bloodlettings that
would reach horrific proportions in the first and second world
wars. The civilized core of Europe that Monet represents would
finally assert itself only after that last war with a dreamy plan
for unity and permanent peace, a plan that today is taking
corporeal form, step by plodding step, in the evolving European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as five years ago, many doubted the plan would work.
A big scheme was in the works to create one currency for the
members of what was then called the European Community, and there
were three big reasons why it could never happen.
</P>
<P>
   First, the economic gaps between rich countries and poor were
too great. The Germans would never give up their strong deutsche
marks for a weak European currency dragged down by the likes of
Ireland, Greece and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Europeans, coddled by an extensive and expensive welfare
state, would never allow politicians to cut benefits in order to
lower national debts and budget deficits, even though a viable
common currency would depend on tight fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Europeans were just too nationalistic. They would never
give over such a significant piece of sovereignty to a committee of
international bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, on Jan. 1, 1999, the euro _ one common currency for 11
members of the EU _ will become a reality. Within a few years, even
in reluctant countries such as Britain and Denmark, the euro is
almost certainly going to take the place of pounds and kroners.
</P>
<P>
   The ommon currency will be a huge step toward a more united
Europe. It will create an economic bloc equal in size to the U.S.
economy, and a trading bloc bigger than America. In time, the euro
may well rival the dollar as the dominant world currency.
</P>
<P>
   How did this impossibility become possible? Mostly, it was a
matter of luck, stubborn will and a recognition of economic
realities.
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide economic boom of the past few years helped turn
backward nations, such as Ireland, into thriving centers of
economic activity. At the same time, the enormous cost of
unification with East Germany slowed the German economy, the result
being that most EU members now find themselves on a roughly similar
economic level.
</P>
<P>
   The dismal failure of the Marxist states of Eastern Europe and
the booming success of tight fiscal policies in the United States
pretty well resolved the economic debates between left and right.
Socialist leaders all over Europe became acolytes of Alan Greenspan
and market economics.
</P>
<P>
   This conversion created a unanimous view that national
governments had to slash budgets and reduce debts, a task suddenly
made easier by the robust world economy. With more money to work
with, the cuts and trimming turned out to be less painful.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent it was painful, national politicians placed blame
for the strict budgetary policies on those nasty EU bureaucrats in
Brussels, and escaped retribution themselves. This blame-shifting
has heightened resentment against Brussels among a majority of
Europeans, and there is currently a bit of a political backlash
against the EU in Germany, France and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But in the long run, it doesn't much matter. The key reality is
that the criteria for becoming part of the common currency regime
have been met by most EU members. The increased economic activity
the euro will create should make everyone feel more sanguine about
the EU, while the deepened ties of commerce will strengthen the web
of unity throughout the continent.
</P>
<P>
   As for national sovereignty, everyone came to realize that
economic independence was already seriously limited. As one EU
economist observes, ``The French central bank has 15 minutes of
freedom: from the time the German Bundesbank makes a proposal to
the time the French realize they must go along with it.''
</P>
<P>
   At least with a pan-European central bank, every country will be
able to put in its two cents (or two pence or two centimes) worth
before the Germans decide.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the persistent political will to make it all
happen. This will is born of a deep fear that, if the union of
European nations fails to thrive and expand until all of Europe,
from Portugal to the Ukraine is tied together by bonds of commerce
and law and democratic institutions, the horrific conflicts of the
past could too easily return.
</P>
<P>
   In the history of the world, there's never been a political
creature quite like the European Union. Observing the organization
at close quarters here in Brussels, one can easily agree with an
American official who describes the EU as ``a massive, throbbing
bureaucracy that runs on meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   The EU has no real head _ its presidency revolves from one
member state to another every six months _ and its parliament thus
far lacks much real power. Its consensual decision-making
procedures were designed for the original group of six nations, not
for 15. Unless major changes are made, the whole structure will
simply creak to a halt once another dozen countries join up.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlikely as it looks now, those changes will somehow be
willed to happen, and in 100 years the EU will have a very
different design. No one can say quite what it will be like, but as
Europeans like to point out, it took two centuries and a civil war
to make the United States what it is today.
</P>
<P>
   So now let's consider again the American archetype, Meriwether
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was not merely a solitary explorer, but the commanding
officer of a government-funded expedition sent not only to secure
the claim of the United States over a vast new territory purchased
from France, but to enter disputed lands beyond the Rockies and
find a trade route to the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewis and Clark expedition was a giant step toward the
eventual extension of American economic and military power around
the globe. Lewis broke a path that led to superpower.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans should be forever grateful that Thomas Jefferson
designed and promoted this mission to claim a continent. Without
the patronage of a superpower, without the economic engine of
American enterprise that rebuilt Europe after World War II and the
protection of American military muscle throughout the Cold War,
Europe may never have escaped the ashes of its conflicts and
revolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that with Europe prosperous, largely peaceful and
increasingly more unified, the United States no longer has a
purpose in Europe, and that Europeans and Americans will inevitably
go their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the opposite may be true. The lands of Monet and Lewis
have convergent interests that should bind them more closely than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The genocidal disintegration of Yugoslavia is convincing proof
that the old evils of European nationalism are not deeply buried,
and there is widespread agreement that the faster all of Europe can
be bound together, the better the chance for lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
   The EU, of course, provides one track for European integration.
But there is another complimentary track in which Americans have a
pivotal role: NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Many countries in Eastern Europe are so economically backward
that it will be years before they can meet the requirements for
membership in the EU. In the meantime, ways must be found to keep
them heading toward fuller democracy and freer markets, and away
from ethnic conflict and dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Whether as full NATO members or participants in the more
amorphous Partnership for Peace, it is current U.S. policy to bring
into NATO's orbit all the former vassal states of the Soviet Union.
This is a very controversial policy, as evidenced by the recent
Senate debate over admission of Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic into NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of this policy raise fears of offending Russia _ though
Russia has already been given a place at the table at NATO
headquarters in Brussels. They insist American arms manufacturers
will be the prime beneficiaries of NATO enlargement, and ask if
Americans are really ready to send their sons and daughters to die
defending, say, Slovenians or Bulgarians.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the policy insist NATO expansion is necessary to
fulfill past promises made to captive nations and to keep the lid
on European squabbles so there will be no more vast cemeteries on
European soil filled with the bodies of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides make serious points, but both ultimately are
projecting NATO's past role into the future. NATO's future,
however, will be very different from what most Americans realize.
</P>
<P>
   In the years ahead, NATO will be much less a tool for defending
territory in Europe than a vehicle for defending European and
American interests around the globe. Controlling arms
proliferation, protecting energy resources, projecting power
against anti-democratic forces in Africa and Asia _ these will be
NATO missions in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, NATO has been and continues to be a good deal for
Europeans. They get to keep their defense budgets low while they
enjoy the protection of the U.S. military shield.
</P>
<P>
   For Americans, though, it is crucial to understand what the
United States gets in return. NATO binds Europe to the United
States and provides a European forum where American influence can
be used to its maximum. Other than the French (who would like to
lead themselves), Europeans are generally quite happy to have
Americans lead NATO (they certainly don't want the French bossing
them around).
</P>
<P>
   Besides, what's the alternative? Would Americans be better off
with a more and more economically powerful Europe divorced from the
United States? Should the United States withdraw and leave a vacuum
in world power to be filled by an authoritarian China? Would it be
better to go it alone when confronting reactionary religious
zealots in the Middle East? Is it wise to leave an unpredictable
Russian state without a link to NATO and no incentive to move
closer to a democratic social model?
</P>
<P>
   No, there is no good alternative to a deeper alliance between
Europe and America.
</P>
<P>
   Already, trade and investment between the United States and
Europe add up to $1.5 trillion a year, and unlike trade with Asia,
it is trade that is in balance. One of every 12 American industrial
jobs is based on European trade. All of this will only grow as the
euro breaks down internal barriers in European markets.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are risks. Working with the ponderous and rigid
EU bureaucracy will often be infuriating. Of even greater concern,
the rise of the euro will mean the United States will no longer be
able to act alone when it comes to monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all the more reason to deepen cooperation with the
EU. The dollar will still be king, but it will have to share the
throne with a euro queen.
</P>
<P>
   For the Europeans, the risks may be greater. After years of
whining about American pop culture undermining European arts,
cuisine and languages, they now have more serious worries that, in
the freer market the euro will bring, Europeans will lag far behind
Americans in electronic commerce, agriculture, biotech products and
service industries.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the risks of engagement, the risks of drifting apart
are far, far greater. There will be many perils in the century to
come _ international crime, environmental emergencies, religious
fanaticism, ethnic conflict, nuclear terrorism. For democratic,
humane civilization to prevail, there must be a strong force to
meet those challenges.
</P>
<P>
   An American analyst at the U.S. mission to the EU states the
case clearly: ``When the EU and the U.S. work together, there
aren't many forces in the world that can block us. We are providing
a force for the improvement of mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Which other powers can do it? Which others are willing to lead?
None but the lands of Monet and Lewis, with all their differences,
united in common cause to defend the shared values of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Editorial cartoonist and columnist David Horsey is a member of
the P-I Editorial Board. This commentary is based on a series of
background interviews conducted with European and American
officials and analysts in Brussels and London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
