<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THEIR BOND BUY A BOMB? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Enclosed is a broker's statement involving municipal bonds we
purchased in May at the advice of our tax adviser, who stated we
should have some of our money in bonds that are not subject to
federal income tax. We have never purchased bonds before, so we
have no experience. We were shocked and surprised when we received
the statement and learned the value of our bonds was less than the
purchase price. The broker ``explained,'' but we were not
satisfied. Have we already lost $421.78 on our investment?
</P>
<P>
   J.Y., Lancaster, Wis. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, whatever else happened, your broker and/or tax adviser
did a poor job at explaining your investment to you. To my
thinking, making sure that a customer understands the securities
that he or she is buying is a critical part of the job, and it
wasn't dome here. But as long as you plan on holding these bonds
until their maturity in the year 2021, you have nothing to worry
about. Not only are the bonds insured, which means that the insurer
will make good on the indebtedness even if the issuer, a children's
hospital, can't.
</P>
<P>
   Have you 'lost' $421? No _ but you would have lost that amount _
plus the amount of your broker's commission _ had you sold the
bonds on the statement date. What that $421 is an unrealized loss.
How can bonds decline in value by about 2.8 percent in only two
months? Although the municipal bond markets are generally
considered a fairly sleepy corner of the financial arena, the fact
is that short-term swings in the bond market can be quite
significant. Bonds not only lose value when interest rates rise,
but even when people just worry that interest rates might be headed
north. Conversely, when interest rates fall, or when it seems
likely that they will, bond portfolios show principal gains.
Moreover, the longer the duration of the bonds _ and with more than
20 years until maturity, these are long-term bonds _ the greater
this volatility will be.
</P>
<P>
   Should all of this, including the unrealized loss of $421,
concern you? Well, I presume your tax adviser suggested this
purchase as a long-term holding, something that will provide you a
consistent, tax-exempt, return of 5.125 percent until maturity. As
I said before, if you hold the bonds until maturity (or until
they're called) your principal will be repaid in full.
</P>
<P>
   But as you've seen, bonds can make horrible short-term holdings,
and they're a poor investment for a person who might need to cash
out of the position to meet some financial emergency. If this
happens, and if you have the bad luck to have to sell at a time
when interest rates are significantly higher than when the bonds
were issued, you would face a substantial loss.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, I think that as you gain more experience as a
bond holder you'll begin to understand that the thing to do is
ignore current market value, prizing instead the tax- exempt
interest checks that will come in twice a year. Usually with bonds,
market activity represents a lot of choppy weather, but ultimately
they seem to go nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 48 years old and have been self-employed for the past 20
years. Instead of depositing money in a retirement fund, I used any
extra money to pay off a valuable piece of property that I used in
my business. In the near future I will sell this property, and my
CPA tells me I will net $500,000 after taxes. It would take $20,000
to pay off the mortgage on our home, which is the only thing we
own, and we intend to add on to the house at a cost of $30,000.
Should we pay off the house and pay cash for the remodeling, or
refinance and use invest all the money for retirement? I would like
to retire as soon as possible, and based on our current living
standard $30,000 a year would be enough for us to live comfortably
if the house were paid off. I am currently employed and can
continue to work as long as it necessary to assure an adequate
future income stream. How should I invest the money? For this
calculation, let's assume $450,000 will be available to invest.
</P>
<P>
   C.V., Vidor, Texas &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. From your last sentence, I assume you're pretty much decided
to retire the mortgage and pay cash for the remodeling, and I
agree. A paid-up home brings a very solid element of financial
security, and I wish more people looked forward to mortgage-burning
parties, rather than anxiously scanning the real estate market,
hoping to become eligible for an even larger homeowner's equity
line of credit.
</P>
<P>
   I think I'm following your thinking about retirement. You
calculate, I'll bet, that you would need only a 6.66 percent return
on the remaining $400,000 to generate that $30,000 income stream.
That is correct, but especially when you're thinking of retiring
before age 50, you have to think beyond a retirement income stream
and a paid-off home. You have to consider very seriously that
dreaded word 'inflation,' and the earlier you retire, the more
intensely you should think about it. If inflation runs at 3
percent, in a decade that $30,000 would have the buying power of
$22,322 of today's money; at 4 percent inflation, the buying power
would sink to $20,266.
</P>
<P>
   A rough rule of thumb I sometimes use is that a person retiring
early should have enough money saved so that only two thirds of it
will generate the desired income stream, with the final third,
invested more aggressively, is left to grow as a buffer against
future inflation. By this thinking, you would need to have $675,000
amassed to retire comfortably. You might achieve this by just
waiting, or speed up the process with additional savings. If you
were to simply invest the $450,000 and let the account grow until
it hits the target level _ in about 5.5 years if you achieved a
portfolio average 7.5 percent total returns (and paid the taxes
resulting from those gains from other funds.) If you were to add
$1,000 a month to the account and achieved the same growth rate,
you would reach the target in a little more than four years.
</P>
<P>
   As for investments, what I usually suggest as a portfolio to
generate an income stream is 50 percent in a good GNMA fund, and 25
percent each in a short-term bond fund and a high-yield bond fund.
At current rates, you could expect such a portfolio to deliver an
overall yield of about 6.5 percent. Excellent funds in these
categories are offered my most fund families _ I generally cite
Vanguard and Fidelity because both have good funds in these
categories with low expense ratios. So my suggestion is that you
put $300,000 of that $450,000 in such a portfolio. The final
$150,000 should eventually go into a solid and somewhat
conservative stock fund in the growth and income category _
something such as Fidelity fund or Vanguard Index Value fund. If
you are cautious about the markets in general, you might substitute
balanced funds, such as Fidelity Puritan and Vanguard Balanced
Index. This would lower your long-term returns, but would also give
you less volatility. However you go, I would use 36-month dollar
cost averaging to make the stock fund investments, which means
initially putting $4,500 into the target fund and the balance in a
money market fund. If you then had an additional $4,500 transferred
into the stock fund each month, you would be fully invested in the
36th month, presuming 5 percent returns from the money fund. This
technique would limit your returns if the bull market in stocks
continues to run apace, but offers you some protection if a market
correction hits.
</P>
<P>
   Finally , if you're going to be adding to the accounts, I would
allocate the additions to the overall portfolio so that the
proportions remain two thirds in the income portfolio and one third
in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. As a widow reaching 65 in November, I'm concerned that my
asset allocation is too heavy in stocks. I have $281,000 in stocks
and stock funds and $237,000 in fixed-income holdings, including
money markets. My financial planner advises more and more stocks.
</P>
<P>
   E.D., Arlington, Vt. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, I can't agree. I tally that you now have a little more
than 54 percent in stocks, which seems a lot to me, especially at
what I view as the petering-out phase of a bull market. Among the
holdings you detail is $50,000 of IRA money in a stock fund. This
is money which can be moved with no immediate tax consequence, so I
would simply transfer it to the fixed-income side, probably adding
to the position in Vanguard's GNMA or Total Bond Index. If there
are other stock investments you can liquidate without heavy tax
consequences, I think I'd go a bit further as well, seeking a
target portfolio with no more than $207,000, or roughly 40 percent,
in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
