<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOWLAM'S OPTIMISM ON PEACE IN NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- ``We are not going back,'' declares Tony Blair's
point person on Northern Ireland. And, as ever, Marjorie (call me
``Mo'') Mowlam maintains her trademark optimism _ not the cockeyed
kind but the clear-eyed variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fragile,'' she says, ``is too pessimistic'' a term to describe
the status of peaceful reform efforts in the wake of a historic,
multiparty agreement, an overwhelmingly approved referendum, a
tense Protestant marching season, and a horrific triple-murder of
three children.
</P>
<P>
   It helps to remember that from the beginning _ within days of
Blair's landslide election in Britain in the spring of last year _
Mowlam has been a consistently reliable indicator of the future,
usually in the face of widespread negativism and intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   She said jump-starting peace talks with a sense of urgency and
deadlines would produce multiparty negotiations, and it did. Down
the stretch this spring, she insisted agreement would come and that
it would win widespread voter approval, and she was right. She has
insisted that there is a formative new center committed to making
reconciliation work and to combatting political and terrorist
extremism. One should think than twice before betting against her.
</P>
<P>
   Over breakfast last week on a visit here to brief the Clinton
administration and congressional leaders and rally American
supporters after a rough patch of post-referendum road, Mowlam
identified the hyper-violent fringes of the Northern Irish scene as
the source of her greatest concern.
</P>
<P>
   This month's barbaric murder of three Catholic boys in a
firebomb attack on their home by apparently apprehended Protestant
killers, she said, was all the more barbaric because of its obvious
evil intent. This was no simple bombing; the attack was
specifically designed to trap the occupants inside. Similarly, she
noted what appears to have been the punishment killing of a young
Catholic man by terrorists last week. It was no execution, Mowlam
said; it was a torture murder. The victim was shot in both legs and
dumped in an elevator that was then disabled so he would bleed to
death.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the signatures of what are usually called the
paramilitaries of the Catholic and Protestant sides, but of
splinter groups desperate to torpedo the reconciliation process.
</P>
<P>
   So far, she said, there is not even a hint that larger,
established organizations on either side have even winked at the
murders for sectarian advantage. Indeed, all the evidence is to the
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   And the best evidence, in Mowlam's view as well as the public's,
is this: In the aftermath of the grisly murders of the three boys,
all but a handful of the Protestants taking part in the one ugly
confrontation with authorities during the marching season, when
Orange Order members insist on triumphalist parades through
Catholic neighborhoods, simply melted away into the night.
</P>
<P>
   A major piece of Mowlam's agenda here was to help keep support
from taking root among US supporters of the Irish Republican Army
for the splinter groups trying to torpedo the political settlement
via fraudulent appeals to nationalist sentiment. The US view is
that little of that is occurring, and that no serious money is
being raised to support terrorism, but official vigilance is high
and needs to be.
</P>
<P>
   So also is official US support for the peace process. While
Mowlam was on her way here, President Clinton's plans to visit in
September were announced, on the heels of a successful,
post-referendum mission by Commerce Secretary Bill Daley.
</P>
<P>
   And to maintain continuity in a difficult time of
institution-building, Clinton has asked one of the key architects
of the settlement, US Ambassador Jean Kennedy Smith, to stay on at
least through his own trip.
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable that violence always gets the most
attention, but Mowlam's plea for perspective (10 bomb plots foiled
just this month; thousands of marching season gatherings that
occurred without incident) is far from myopic.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains that a peaceful reconciliation process now has
political authority in Northern Ireland (70 percent of the seats in
the new assembly are occupied by Good Friday agreement supporters).
And splinter group terrorism is strengthening the determination of
the freshly empowered majority to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   When Mo Mowlam says, ``We are not going back,'' she is not
whistling past the graveyard. She is reporting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
