<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT CAUSES GOOSEBUMPS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why do we get goosebumps?
</P>
<P>
   M.R., Concord
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Long before Polartec and Thinsulate, our forebears were fur
bearers. That's how they stayed warm. When a sudden burst of cold
demanded extra insulation, tiny muscles in each hair follicle,
called piloerectors, would contract, making each hair stand up.
That fluffed up the fur, which trapped more air in the spaces
between the hairs, increasing the insulating effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Evolution has been working on humans like a slow-motion Nair
treatment and we no longer rely on fur for warmth. But so far,
evolution has left our piloreceptor muscles along. So when you feel
a chill and get goosebumps, you're experiencing the same body
response your predecessors did tens of thousands of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But what about `emotional' goosebumps, as in, ``Every time I
hear that song I get goosebumps''? That's left over from our
ancient kin too. Back in furrier times, pre-humans faced with a
threat responded with an instantaneous flood of hormones that raced
through the autonomic nervous system, which controls involuntary
actions like breathing and digestion, and triggered the ``Fight or
Flight'' response.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the ``Fight'' reaction was to look as threatening as
possible. The piloerector muscles puffed up the fur to make the
animal look bigger and more formidable. Lots of animals still do
this, including cats, dogs, and bears.
</P>
<P>
   Our emotional responses, whether sad or happy, excited or angry,
trigger the release of hormones that stimulate the autonomic
nervous system, sometimes bringing on ``emotional'' goosebumps,
depending on the hormones released.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; So if a friend cautions ``Don't get your hackles up'' (hackles
are the hairs on the back of an animal's neck), tell him you're
just experiencing an autonomic piloerector response, and there's
nothing you can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What makes helium change the tone of your voice?
</P>
<P>
   (Unidentified) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. ``The speed of sound is faster in that particular gas because
it's less dense,'' says Kenneth Stevens, an MIT electrical
engineering professor who studies speech formation.
</P>
<P>
   Helium is one-seventh as dense as air. As it passes your vocal
cords, they create vibrations, pretty much the way they do when
regular air goes past them. Not much changes at this point. But up
in the rest of the vocal tract, including your throat, mouth,
cheeks, tongue, teeth, and lips, the sound waves bounce around
faster through the thinner medium of the helium. Not only does the
sound move faster, but the waves themselves are smaller. We
perceive the shorter, faster-moving sound waves as higher
resonance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like those cute little _ what are they ... squirrels, in that
cartoon?'' says Stevens. Actually, Chip and Dale are chipmunks, but
we get the point.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, breathing in too much pure helium can change your
voice in a much more profound way. It can silence it altogether, as
you pass out from asphyxiation. Helium displaces oxygen. After more
than a few deep breaths of it in a row, the only sound you'll be
making is your oxygen-starved, unconscious body hitting the floor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The lighter-than-air helium will float up out of your lungs on
its own, and you'll probably recover. But Stevens warns that unless
you can be sure you're breathing a helium-oxygen mixture, you're
taking a big risk trying to sound like a couple of cartoon
chipmunks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
