<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOLPHINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRACKING THE DOLPHIN CODE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ The two dolphins wait attentively at the edge of
their 45-foot tank, their eyes riveted on the trainer standing
before them. He suddenly makes two wide sweeping motions with his
hands, and the dolphins immediately plunge below the surface and
swim away.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pause of a few seconds; are they pondering _ or even
discussing _ the task that has been set for them? Nobody knows. But
seconds later, they erupt from the water simultaneously, performing
a complex side-by-side leap in perfect synchronization.
</P>
<P>
   They have done what they were instructed to do: Perform some new
stunt _ not one that is part of their regular repertoire _ and do
it in tandem. Score one for the dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a half-dozen similar requests on a recent
afternoon, the dolphins came up with new things to do _ and did
them in perfectly-choreographed unison _ every time but once. That
one time they seemed to swim around in confusion; had they
forgotten the assignment, had they been unable to come up with an
idea _ or had they perhaps done something underwater that the human
observers could not discern?
</P>
<P>
   This coordinated creative activity is perhaps the most
startling, and enigmatic, result yet from 29 years of research that
psychologist Louis Herman of the University of Hawaii and his
associates have been carrying out at the Kewalo Basin Marine Mammal
Laboratory, next to a public beach in the bustling center of
Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   How do the dolphins synchronize their performance so perfectly
when they are doing a trick they've never done before? Are they
using some kind of language of their own to discuss and agree on
what to do, or is one simply following the lead of the other _
instantaneously and with remarkable precision? Human observers
don't see any sign that one dolphin is lagging behind the other, as
would be expected if it is a case of follow-the-leader.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Remarkable accomplishments are nothing new for the four
dolphins here and the researchers who work with them, along with
dozens of paying volunteers sent by Earthwatch, an organization
based in Watertown, Mass. Herman has already proved that the
dolphins are capable of understanding and mastering the key
concepts of language: That symbols can represent specific objects,
actions, or relationships; and that the order in which those
symbols are presented is crucial to the meaning of a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   His dolphins have no trouble responding correctly to commands
such as ``put the Frisbee on the left into the basket on the
right,'' even when there are Frisbees and baskets on both sides.
(``Usually she's much better than I am on left and right,'' Herman
says of Akeakamai, whose name means ``lover of wisdom'' in
Hawaiian.)
</P>
<P>
   They can even improvise responses to impossible commands: Told
to take a ball to a hoop when there was no hoop in the tank, one
dolphin took &UR;  &LR; the ball to a lever it had been trained to press to
signal ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the dolphins' abilities parallel those of
chimpanzees, gorillas, and parrots in experiments on animal
communication _ although &UR;  &LR; Herman has focused entirely on monitoring
dolphins' comprehension of artificial languages presented by
humans, not on getting them to produce language. This, he says,
makes it easier to ensure that rigorous standards of objectivity
are met, because monitoring objectively claims that an animal is
generating words and sentences can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Herman's experiments have also included careful precautions to
avoid inadvertently transmiting cues from the researchers to the
animals, or overinterpreting the animals' responses _ problems that
have caused acrimonious debates in many other experiments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when giving hand signals to the dolphins, the
trainer wears goggles, so the dolphins cannot pick up clues from an
inadvertent glance. And there is always a ``blind'' observer _ who
records what the dolphins do but can not see what commands they
were given.
</P>
<P>
   The dolphins have learned dozens of ``words'' _ either as
gestures or sounds _ just as apes and parrots have done, and have
learned rules of syntax that govern how the words are strung
together in sentences up to five words long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for some people to accept that animals could have
this unique quality of language comprehension,'' Herman said.
``It's a resistance based on species chauvinism.''
</P>
<P>
   But the experiments make it clear that the dolphins do grasp the
fundamental rules of the grammar Herman has created for them _ in
some cases, different rules for different dolphins. For example,
Phoenix has been taught a syntax in which the object is placed
first, then the subject, then the action (``hoop ball toss'' would
mean ``toss the ball through the hoop''). Akeakamai was taught an
opposite syntax for the same meaning _ subject, object, action
(``ball hoop toss'').
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate that the dolphins indeed understand the
grammatical rules, the experimenters sometimes throw in
incorrectly-structured sentences. The dolphin rejects those
sentences. ``She just sits there and stares at you. She doesn't
attempt to do the ungrammatical,'' Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   The dolphins ``are certainly the intellectual peers of chimps,''
he said. ``Most of the things chimps have done, dolphins can do,
and vice versa.'' But the dolphins have also mastered tasks that no
other animals have managed.
</P>
<P>
   For example, parrots and apes will react to a television image
with curiosity, but don't respond to commands or questions from a
TV image of their human trainer. But when Akeakamai, who had
learned a language based on gestures, was shown an image of a
signing trainer on a tiny black-and-white screen, she carried out
his commands correctly 12 out of 12 times.
</P>
<P>
   To test the limits of the dolphin's ability to respond to the
televised image, the human's body was blacked out, leaving just the
arms. She still responded correctly, and continued to do so when
the arms were obscured, leaving just hands.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers then went one step further, replacing the hands
with white discs _ disembodied shapes making gestures on the
screen. The accuracy level went down a little, but she still got it
right most of the time _ performing better than all but the most
experienced human trainers did on the same test.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins are also able to respond correctly when a human points
at something, a signal no other animal has been able to understand.
</P>
<P>
   When a chimp sees a human pointing, it focuses on the finger
itself, as do other animals. The concept of directing attention
away from the hand making the gesture appears to be too complex for
them to grasp _ even though chimps have hands that could point.
Dolphins, however, though they have no arms or hands, seem able to
figure out the symbolic gesture easily. Rather than focusing on at
the pointing hand, they look in the direction indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the lab's most exciting work is probably in the
``tandem'' behavior _ the tests in which two dolphins perform
first-time maneuvers together, perfectly synchronized. That hints
at an ability to communicate directly with one another in some
``language'' of their own _ whether through sounds, or motions, or
some other way _ but it does not prove it, and Herman insists on
getting rigorous scientific proof. ``There is no evidence that they
have anything approaching a language in the natural environment,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins do, however, live in a very rich auditory environment,
including streams of clicks they emit to track their surroundings
by echolocation, as well as unique ``signature'' whistles that each
dolphin emits, apparently as a way of keeping track of individuals
within the group.
</P>
<P>
   But figuring out how they carry out tandem stunts may be
difficult, because underwater sounds are complicated by multiple
echoes from the tank walls, and it is hard to know which animal
produced what sound. Further, the cloudiness of the water makes it
hard to videotape underwater behavior more than a few feet away.
Herman plans to intall more sophisticated underwater sound and
video recording systems in an attempt to determine what goes on
when the dolphins are preparing to make their tandem leaps, spins
or tail flips. ``We can probably answer it better in a year or
so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dolphins, it seems, are as eager as he to get on with it.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers have to contend with animals that often won't
cooperate at all; they either refuse to join in or they sometimes
give apparently deliberate wrong answers. People who work with
chimps have to concentrate on young animals, because adults are
often dangerous to work with. (``Most chimp researchers have parts
of fingers missing,'' Herman said.)
</P>
<P>
   Not so with his dolphins. They work two shifts a day, two to
three hours each. When a long session is about to end, he says,
``they sometimes resist having us take the apparatus out of the
water.''
</P>
<P>
   The dolphins are rewarded with a fish for correct responses. As
a signal that a session is nearly over, the trainer will hold up
the last three fish, and then the last two. When a dolphin is given
the last fish, ``usually they give it back, as a way of prolonging
the contact.'' Apparently, Herman said, ``they love to do the
work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Information about Herman's research is available on the
Internet at www.dolphin-institute.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
