<HEADER>
A4515 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-BERKSHIRES-BOS &LR;      07-27 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BERKSHIRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BERKSHIRES STATE OF MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Berkshire Mountain vistas are breathtaking, the air cool and
sweet, the restaurants excellent, the recreation seemingly
unlimited, and the cultural events unrivaled.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Boston goes on vacation _ or gets away for a weekend _
we don't take the easily passable Massachusetts Turnpike and head
west. Instead, we travel a frequently congested Route 3 to
backed-up bridges leading to Cape Cod, or motor up Interstate 93,
to the bottleneck just over the New Hampshire border.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkshires are in our state, but it is our neighbors the New
Yorkers who most enjoy them.
</P>
<P>
   Of the tourists who stay in the Berkshires for more than one
day, only 10 to 15 percent come from Greater Boston while more than
60 percent come from the New York area, says William R. Wilson Jr.,
executive director of the Berkshire Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   And when owners of second homes invade on weekends _ there are
more than 10,000 second-homes in Berkshire County _ once again, the
New Yorkers overwhelm the Bostonians.
</P>
<P>
   Take George Packer, a Cambridge writer who co-owns a place in
Monterey with a couple from ... New York. ``I assume everyone is
doing what I'm doing, but now that you ask, I honestly know nobody
from Boston who comes out on weekends. Nobody at all,'' Packer
says.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that last summer a total of 25,230 passenger cars and
motorcycles traveled the Mass. Pike from the Newton toll plaza to
Exit 2 in Lee, the first of two Berkshire exits. Another 27,584
cars traveled from the Route 128 entrance to Lee last summer.
</P>
<P>
   During the same three months, an average of 65,005 cars went
over the Sagamore Bridge each day, and 53,469 went over the Bourne
Bridge each day. While not all those cars were going to or from
Boston, if even 2 percent were, they still dwarf the Berkshire
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems so crazy _ I have nothing but good things to say
about going to the Berkshires,'' Packer says. ``I have gone out on
rush hour on Friday, and, after Framingham, it is fine. And I have
come back Sunday evening and it is never that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   So why do Bostonians shun the Berkshires? It may have something
to do with how the place reminds some of Manhattan in the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do see a lot of New Yorkers, which makes one a little
resentful, like `What are they doing here?''' says Packer. ``I once
saw a bumper sticker in Egremont on a car with New York plates that
said `Keep Egremont Small and Beautiful.' Well, the arrogant
outsiders are all from New York.''
</P>
<P>
   State Representative Christopher Hodgkins, a Democrat from Lee,
says the weekenders from New York ``can be very obnoxious. We don't
go downtown on a weekend, we leave it for tourists _ and we don't
say `tourists,' we say `New Yorkers,' because that is where they
are all from. They think we are hillbillies, but that's OK; we'll
take their money.''
</P>
<P>
   At Guido's Marketplace, an upscale grocery store in Pittsfield
and Great Barrington, some of the younger staff have a code name
for loud, demanding customers: two-one-twos. (The area code for
Manhattan is ... )
</P>
<P>
   But there are millions of pleasant, sedate New Yorkers, and some
of them summer in the Berkshires. So Boston's avoidance of the
Berkshires must involve more than our complicated feelings about
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire County is bounded by mountains on the east and west,
which means that the area was settled from the south. Around the
time of the Revolutionary War, Massachusetts claimed the area as
its own and auctioned off the land to raise revenue. ``They were
just making money off of it, and maybe Bostonians never felt
inclined to come back afterwards,'' says Bernie Drew, a local
writer and historian.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson and Housatonic rivers run north to south, and the
area's development, for the most part, mirrors that. While the
first railroad line and the first summer ``cottage'' owner came
from Boston, it was New York that quickly surpassed Boston in
sinking roots.
</P>
<P>
   Drew believes Bostonians seeking a cooler climate in the summer
logically headed north, or went to the seashore, rather than
heading out west.
</P>
<P>
   And if the mountains once stood as impediments, clearly they no
longer do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be some sort of psychological barrier because it
surely isn't physical,'' says Susan Eisley, executive director of
the Berkshire County Historical Society at Arrowhead Museum, once a
home of Herman Melville. ``I mean, Hannibal crossed the Alps with
elephants. It would seem like Bostonians could get to the
Berkshires if they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   So, maybe it's a matter of tradition. According to Drew, summer
tourism in the Berkshires dates to the 1860s, and if Bostonians
weren't going then, why should they go now? New England is
populated with traditionalists; if Grandpa and Grandma went to New
Hampshire for vacation, then that is where we will go.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Masiero, a co-owner of Guido's Marketplace, grew up on the
North Shore and says people who live in Greater Boston simply have
a poor sense of geography. ``The mentality of distance is warped.
It is only 150 miles out here, but it was like Worcester was the
breaking point, and anything beyond Springfield, well, you might as
well be in Ohio or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's tendency to dismiss the western part of the state as
unimportant is well-established. In matters of politics, the
Berkshires have long felt like a forgotten country cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one would think that the Berkshires' sheer loveliness and
many recreational opportunities would lure people _ especially in
contrast to the tourist-choked Cape. But Boston steadfastly refuses
to look westward, despite a strong push by the Berkshire Visitors
Bureau. The bureau, in conjunction with the Turnpike Authority, is
stepping up marketing in Boston, but the numbers _ while up a bit _
still disappoint Wilson, the bureau's director.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Stevens, who works in Boston but grew up in Williamstown,
says most people in Boston don't know where his hometown is, even
though it is also home to Williams College and the Berkshires' best
art museum. ``They ask you what it's like down in Virginia. I'm not
making this up. And you say `No. That is Williamsburg.' They were
printing T-shirts in Williamstown for a while that said `I'm not
from Virginia.'''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens says the Berkshires are greatly influenced by Albany,
N.Y., radio and television stations. That, coupled with the cold
shoulder from Boston, makes residents feel like the Bay State's
orphans. ``I was in the sixth grade before I realized Mario Cuomo
was not my governor and Dukakis was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bostonians who do make it to the Berkshires discover that
culture not only survives there, it thrives. The summer home of the
Boston Symphony Orchestra is at Tanglewood, but more New Yorkers
than Bostonians go there. Maybe Bostonians get their fill in the
winter, but Wilson says that's a mistake. ``I would contend that
there is a big difference between sitting in an auditorium and
sitting out on the lawn overlooking the Stockbridge Bowl while
listening to music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Bostonians know we exist, but they just don't know what
we have,'' says Wilson, sounding very much like the booster he is.
``There are more than 40 world-class cultural organizations
operating in the area. The Clark Art Institute in Williamstown has
over 30 Renoirs. The Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge has the largest
collection of original Rockwells in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, some 75,000 people visited the Hancock Shaker
Village, a 1,200-acre farm with 20 restored Shaker buildings,
including a round stone barn. About 5,000 of those visitors were
from Boston. About 16,000 were from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Olympia Brescia, of Ego Trips Unlimited, a Boston tour operator,
says that is not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``When foreign tourists hit Logan, they know more about our
culture than we do,'' Brescia says, adding that she took two Thomas
Cook travel agency executives to the Berkshires earlier this month.
As a result, they will promote the region heavily back home in
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bostonians just won't go there. If they want a lake and
mountains, they'll go to Winnipesaukee. Or they'll go to the Cape.
Really, the Berkshires are more of a cultural vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph L. Carini, president of Wheeler &AMP; Taylor Realty Co. in
Great Barrington, believes people want a vacation to be a little
exotic. Crossing a state line feeds that desire. Says Carini, ``It
works for the New Yorkers who come here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
