<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFANT-DEATHS-BOS &LR;      07-27 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFANT-DEATHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE UK, BABY DEATHS WITHOUT WORLDWIDE COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ On Tuesday, a nanny named Louise was charged with
killing a baby in her care in England.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the nanny's surname is Sullivan, not Woodward, and
she's Australian, not English. But the murder charge lodged against
Louise Sullivan, just one day after an English nanny was convicted
of murder for shaking a 5-month-old baby to death, has unsettled
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Some Britons thought Louise Woodward was framed for the murder
of Matthew Eappen, and many more were at least sympathetic to her,
seeing her as the victim of overzealous American prosecutors who
charged her with murder instead of manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   But the confluence of two similar cases on English soil &UR;  &LR; has led
to finger pointing and soul-searching about the dangers &UR;  &LR; of leaving
children with caregivers who effectively are strangers. In response
to the two most recent cases, the British government said it was
considering adopting a national register for child-care providers
and regulating the industry on a par with schools.
</P>
<P>
   The two cases here have given weight to warnings from Britain's
National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children that
shaken baby syndrome is on the rise. They have also shown that the
system for monitoring child-care providers is open to abuse.
</P>
<P>
   However, the cases have not led to the type of sensational news
coverage that marked much of the Woodward case, mainly because
British law prevents such coverage before or during a trial.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Helen Stacey, 41, was sentenced to life in prison
after a jury found she had shaken to death Joseph Mackin just four
days after she began baby-sitting him at her Norfolk home. Stacey
had registered with the local social services office that monitors
child-care providers.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Sullivan, 26, was charged with causing the head
injuries that killed 6-month-old Caroline Jongen at the baby's home
in north London in April.
</P>
<P>
   Sky News, Rupert Murdoch's satellite TV station, which
exhaustively covered the Woodward case, was more restrained in its
reports on the two recent cases. The tabloids that were jingoistic
in their assumption of Woodward's innocence appear much more openly
pro-prosecution in these two British cases.
</P>
<P>
   After Woodward was convicted, many in the British media
protested her innocence. After Stacey's conviction and life
sentence, however, all media outlets have made much of her alleged
past as a prostitute and unfit mother. Her past, however, was
unknown to the jury and played no role in deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Woodward's trial in Cambridge, Mass., which was
televised, cameras are barred from British courts. British law also
bars publicity beyond rudimentary facts about a case either before
or during a trial. Even if reporters obtain evidence that might
come out at trial, they can be charged with contempt for publishing
or broadcasting it.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Greenslade, media critic for The Guardian, a liberal daily,
was disturbed by what he saw as xenophobia in much of the British
coverage of the Woodward case. But even he says the marked
difference between the coverage of the Woodward case and that of
the two recent cases is rooted more in law than jingoism.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Greenslade said he is troubled by the disparate coverage
of and reaction to the convictions of Woodward and Stacey, as well
as by the sympathetic coverage of the recent release of two British
nurses who were convicted of killing a colleague in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are in danger in Britain of believing that no one
can get a fair trial anywhere but in Britain,'' said Greenslade.
``I would remind the British public that there have been many
miscarriages of justice here, with scores of Irish people serving
up to 15 years in prison for IRA activity they had nothing to do
with. And it's not just the Irish who have been on the receiving
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenslade said that while many British journalists were
convinced that Woodward's treatment in the Massachusetts court
system constituted a miscarriage of justice, no one in the news
media has suggested that Stacey may have just ``snapped'' in a
moment of frustration and have been guilty of manslaughter, as some
of Woodward's supporters have contended.
</P>
<P>
   The case British prosecutors presented against Stacey was
similar to that made by Middlesex County prosecutors against
Woodward. They said doctors determined that Joseph Mackin died from
violent shaking, and that only the nanny or the child's parents
could have inflicted the injuries. As did Woodward, Stacey
maintained she never harmed the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Portia Trust, a small, left-wing group that supports
female defendants, has voiced support for Stacey, saying the
evidence against her did not support a verdict ``beyond a
reasonable doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Fitzgerald, a London defense lawyer who is active in
civil liberties cases, said he detects a hint of jingoism in the
differences in the coverage and reaction to the two recent cases as
compared to Woodward's, though he believes laws barring
extrajudicial publicity explain most of the discrepancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be fair to the English system, it's more about possible
contempt than jingoism,'' said Fitzgerald. ``Once proceedings get
started here, the press can't say much. Abroad they don't have to
restrain themselves, as they didn't in the Woodward case. But
English girls abroad are a special phenomenon. It is a striking
feature about this country. The idea of a young oppressed English
girl abroad excites sympathy in the press. When a `nasty'
Australian comes into this country and does essentially the same
thing, she will not get the same sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald shares Greenslade's concern about the character
assassination of Stacey that followed her conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually the police leak after someone is convicted,'' said
Fitzgerald. ``That's why you get a burst of nasty stuff after a
trial. But it's almost always only from the prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenslade said that the stories that followed Stacey's
conviction, contending she was a former prostitute, had been
treated for depression, and had had her children taken away from
her for neglect, may be true, but that it is impossible to judge
because the information is not attributed to traceable sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a tradition of double-sourcing, or naming
sources,'' Greenslade said. ``These pieces that appear immediately
after trial are known as backgrounders, because they have been
written before and are heavily biased.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this information is often untrue, but after someone
is convicted no one goes back to check it. As much as we prevent
the press from publishing prejudicial material before and during a
trial, it all changes after a conviction. You're a person without a
reputation, not in a position to sue for libel, even if the
information is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   If many Britons saw the Woodward case as one of aberrant
behavior, the two other cases have led many, including the
government, to think again.
</P>
<P>
   The National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children
says a recent survey it commissioned found that about 200 British
babies are killed or seriously injured annually by being shaken,
and that the number is growing.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Stacey case, the British government said it
was considering a new national register for child-care providers.
The Times of London sneered at the government's ``knee jerking in
sympathy with a dreadfully bereaved couple,'' and accused Prime
Minister Tony Blair of cynically proposing ``a nationalisation of
nannydom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the Mackins' tragedy became headline news the
government was disinclined to proceed with plans for a national
register,'' The Times noted in an editorial.
</P>
<P>
   More sobering for Britons is the realization that the current
system for checking the backgrounds of baby sitters and nannies
depends largely on the honesty of those who register with local
councils. About 100,000 registered child care providers look after
some 350,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   The judge who sentenced Stacey to life imprisonment called for a
``searching inquiry'' into the current system.
</P>
<P>
   David Wright, the director of social services in Norfolk, said
the system failed Joseph Mackin because Stacey lied on an
application form. Had she answered truthfully about prior criminal
convictions and her own personal history, it would have raised
serious concerns. Wright added there was little authorities could
do to prevent someone from lying.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Corrine and Anthony Mackin said they want the
system improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want Joseph to have died in vain,'' they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
