<HEADER>
A4519 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-27 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOSE IMPROPRIETIES ARE WORSE THAN STARR'S? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When US District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson ordered a hearing
last week into whether Independent Counsel Kenneth W. Starr's
office leaked grand jury information to the media, she provided
hope for those who believe that Starr has simply gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   The order was a departure from Judge Johnson's previous rulings.
Until last week she had handed Starr significant victories _
including her ruling allowing him to question Secret Service
members who had guarded President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing on possible grand jury leaks will, in the end,
probably prove even more significant than the news reports Friday
suggesting that one Secret Service agent has testified that he and
a top aide to Clinton saw the president and former intern Monica
Lewinsky alone in a room off the Oval Office. (There was no
suggestion they were engaged in any improper behavior.)
</P>
<P>
   Unless a bombshell comes from the questioning of Secret Service
agents, the hearing on Starr's alleged leaks could be far more
damaging to the independent prosecutor than Secret Service
testimony might be to Clinton and Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and its supporters cheered Johnson's
order. Starr's supporters were stunned. Meanwhile, lawyers on both
sides of the issue noted how serious this could be for Starr if the
hearing determines that his office fed grand jury information to
the media.
</P>
<P>
   After all, violating the rule against disclosing grand jury
information ``is not just a bad idea; it's a crime,'' Howard Pearl,
a former federal prosecutor and now a Chicago lawyer, reminded
people.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, the fact that Johnson ordered the rare hearing
indicates that she already has knowledge suggesting improprieties
by Starr's office. If so, it does not bode well for him or his
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Johnson's order, as some former and current members of
the legal profession point out, comes from Starr's own remarks in
the new media magazine Brill's Content. In an interview, Starr said
he and a former deputy had talked to reporters about the case.
There is nothing improper about his office having contacts with the
media, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After his quotes circulated in Washington, Starr blasted the
magazine and its editor, saying the quotes and his ``abstract
discussion of the law'' were taken out of context. But his retort
could not erase the reaction to the article, including Johnson's
order.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson determines from the hearing that grand jury leaks did
indeed come from Starr's office, Starr will have to show Johnson
why his office should not be held in contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   If he fails to convince Johnson, the contempt ruling would stand
_ and that, in turn, could provide grounds for Attorney General
Janet Reno to fire Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Starr could also be disciplined for his conduct. At the very
least, a contempt ruling would undermine his assertion that he is
running a fair and objective investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, since this hearing involves the grand jury,
Johnson's ruling on Starr itself is secret. Even Johnson's order of
the hearing was supposed to be secret. But as Starr, Clinton, the
news media, and various participants in the investigation
acknowledge, leaks _ not secrecy _ have been the cornerstone thus
far in these proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing may also help Clinton in the court of public opinion
_ as well as give his lawyers a means to find out as much as they
can about the Starr investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, aware of how such a hearing could damage both him and his
investigation, has asked a federal appeals court to stop, or at
least limit, the amount of information that can be provided to
lawyers for Clinton and Lewinsky. But even with such limitations,
it's likely that Clinton's and Lewinsky's lawyers will still obtain
more information about the investigation than Starr would like.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's own legal troubles with Johnson do not stop him from
pursuing possible criminal charges against Clinton. Starr and his
aides are still determined to prove whether Clinton had sex with
Lewinsky and then asked her to lie about it to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that Starr is trying to get a US president on a lie
about his sex life has made the public more outraged over Starr's
prosecutorial conduct than over Clinton's alleged behavior. Polls
show that Starr has a low favorability rating with most Americans.
The nation's populace would not want to see a president impeached
on such a charge.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, a majority would like to see this investigation come to
an end. Before Johnson's order for a hearing, Starr and his team
were reportedly working to wrap up their investigation of Clinton
and present their case to Congress. But if Congress does not want
to deal with the case before the November elections, it may be
another few months more before Starr's findings are presented. And
when they are, Congress could be bogged down for a long time as its
members debate how, or how fast, to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   But if Johnson finds that Starr should be held in contempt of
court, that ruling could derail the investigation, giving relief to
a public tired of Starr and his partisan probe.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the hearing produces no contempt charge, Johnson's
ruling at least gave the nation hope. And where there is hope,
there is always the chance that justice will prevail, and Starr
ultimately will fail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
