<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4521 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-DEMOCRATS-BOS &LR;      07-27 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-DEMOCRATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A TOP-DOLLAR RACE FOR GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an agenda to make Lyndon Johnson smile.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a decade of me-too moderation from Democrats, the
party's top gubernatorial candidates are busy promising to pump
hundreds of millions of dollars into issues straight from the
progressive playbook.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Scott Harshbarger announces a plan to provide
health coverage to 200,000 uninsured Massachusetts residents. Then
rival Patricia McGovern, the former state Senate Ways and Means
chairwoman, tops him with a proposal to extend care to 385,000
people currently without coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger calls for devoting $100 million to repairing the
state's schools. A month later, McGovern proposes leveraging that
$100 million into a $1.2 billion fund for school repairs _ and
putting another $34 million into education. Harshbarger counters
with a scheme to spend an additional $163 million a year to hire
4,000 new teachers and meet other school needs.
</P>
<P>
   He unveils a proposal to put $25 million more into adult
education, only to have her offer a $152 million plan to establish
a comprehensive skills-training system.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern puts forward a $50 million plan for child care _ and
Harshbarger comes out for spending $120 million more for the same
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. Week by week, month by month, position paper by
press conference, Harshbarger, the Democratic front-runner in the
race to unseat Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, and McGovern, his
chief rival, have engaged in a war _ albeit an extremely civil one
_ of issues one-upmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Their competing proposals make one thing clear: On matters from
health care to education to worker training to child care, the
Democrats are ready and eager to spend. Indeed, not since the heady
days of the so-called Massachusetts miracle, when the only question
seemed to be how to divide the spoils, have Democrats proved so
ready to put state money where their passions are.
</P>
<P>
   The state's $900 million budget surplus only encouraged that
impulse. Espying that expanding pot of gold, Harshbarger recently
proposed a $200 million trust fund to supplement municipal budgets,
while McGovern called for devoting more dollars to early childhood
education and kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Former ambassador and US Representative Brian Donnelly, running
as a low-visibility moderate, even got into the act with the
highest offer in the surplus spending contest: a $500 million
Children's Trust Fund to pay for a wide variety of programs.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the candidates alone in their desire to boost budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are clearly open to new spending, too. After years of
fiscal discipline, legislative leaders agreed Monday to a $19.55
billion fiscal 1999 budget, up $1.3 billion, or 6.6 percent, over
last year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   According to spokesman Dwight Robson, Harshbarger's various
proposals would add about $300 million in new spending in his first
budget. Barbara Roop, issues director in the McGovern campaign,
says her plans would increase the budget base by about $200 million
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns stress that those sums are only small percentage
increases _ 1.5 percent for Harshbarger, one percent for McGovern _
of a $19.55 billion budget. Two caveats, however, are important.
That spending is just for new proposals, and doesn't included the
regular yearly adjustments in the budgetary base. And campaigns, of
course, are a time for low-balling costs, while high-balling
results; thus both those estimates should be viewed as spending
floors rather than ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Undergirding all the rival plans is a similar commitment to an
active, energetic, expansionist government eager to tackle new
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we should do more to reduce class size, attract
the best and brightest into teaching, help communities build new
schools, make classrooms safe, and expand access to affordable,
high-quality child care and health care,'' Harshbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats' willingness to spend certainly marks a distinct
change from the last two elections. If Campaign '98 is shaping up
as a time of wine and roses, back then the Democrats were offering
regimens of bread and water.
</P>
<P>
   John Silber, then the president of Boston University, became the
party's 1990 nominee by riding a backlash against the party's
overspending liberal establishment, offering the state a dose of
the fiscal and social castor oil that had purged BU's excesses and
brought the ailing institution back to health.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Democratic gubernatorial nominee Mark Roosevelt made a
quick transition from progressive to neo-liberal, coming out in
support of a family cap for welfare recipients, workfare, term
limits, and the death penalty _ and only a modest agenda for new
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Those campaigns, of course, took place in starkly different
contexts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the state's economy was mid-meltdown, its budget, after
two massive tax increases, still hemorrhaging red ink. In 1994, the
ledger was once again in balance, but there was no huge surplus to
make the closing of the books the fiscal equivalent of Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, today's overflowing fisc that makes it easy
for candidates to argue that new spending is affordable, the more
so since some of it would be a one-time bonus from this year's
surplus, while other proposals rely on nonrevenue sources. (Both
McGovern and Harshbarger, for example, hope to have the federal
Medicaid program pick up much of the expense for extending health
care for the uninsured.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Republican candidates are already raising warning
flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Left to their own devices, liberal Democrats will spend every
dollar that is on the table,'' warns state Treasurer Joseph D.
Malone, a Republican hopeful who has made his promise to hold
spending to the inflation rate the centerpiece of his campaign for
the nomination. ``That's why we need a fiscal conservative in the
governor's office,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So what does all this mean for the fall campaign? That it's
likely to shape up as a Montesquieuean battle of hope vs. fear, one
that pits the appeal of progressive ideas against the lingering
dread of a fiscal crisis like the one the state suffered through
from 1989 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the Cellucci campaign, strategists argue that the
Democrats' ambitious plans will scupper their own hopes. They see
the late 1980s, when a Democratic Legislature expanded the budget
at a pace that proved unsustainable when the economy turned sour,
as a stark cautionary tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be easy to make the point about why two-party
government is important because of all these new spending
proposals,'' argues campaign manager Rob Gray. ``If you have a
Democratic governor who is not fiscally conservative, then the
Legislature has carte blanche to spend whatever they want _ and the
taxpayers will foot the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger denies he would let his party slip back into a
reckless tax-and-spend mode. ``My plan is fiscally responsible ...
and will help move working families forward,'' he declares.
</P>
<P>
   Says McGovern, of her own ideas: ``This is a minimal budget
increase invested in programs that will, in the long run, generate
new revenues and reduce state spending for social services, public
safety, and health care.''
</P>
<P>
   With a big tax cut signed, sealed, and delivered, and boom times
overshadowing distant memories of the last fiscal crisis, others
are dubious the big-spending label will stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody cares about big spenders when there is enough money
around,'' contends political analyst Lou DiNatale, a senior fellow
at the University of Massachusetts' McCormack Institute. ``Paul
Cellucci isn't going to get anybody upset about the fear of
Democrats spending a budget surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Be that as it may, fiscal experts say that, given this year's
budget, voters and elected officials alike would do well to keep a
weather eye on the horizon. Although next year's 6.6 percent
spending increase remains well below the 10.6 percent average rate
of growth in the six fiscal years (1984 through 1989) leading up
and into the last budget crisis, it is almost 2 percent higher than
the 4.7 percent average increase between 1991 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Cam Huff, senior research associate at the Massachusetts
Taxpayers Foundation, a business-financed fiscal watchdog
organization, says revenues are more than adequate to pay for this
year's spending increase _ but not to sustain a similar spending
pace in future years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to understand that that kind of increase cannot be
sustained over the longer term,'' Huff said. ``We just don't see
the tax revenue that can keep up with that kind of increase.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Scot Lehigh covers the governor's race for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
