<HEADLINE>
TAKING A THOREAU LOOK AT THE CAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A map is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In October 1849, well after whatever passed for a tourist season
in those days, Henry David Thoreau set out from Boston to tramp the
outer beaches of Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Thoreau was propelled by the same thing that has brought
millions since his time to the Cape _ the wish, as he put it, ``to
get a better view than I had yet of the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Mulloney had seen plenty of the ocean as a vacationer
and a Hyannis-based television reporter, so it was simply cabin
fever and ``the need to get a life'' that prompted him to retrace
Thoreau's tramp through 1990s eyes, in a late-summer ramble that he
records in ``Traces of Thoreau,'' published last month by
Northeastern University Press.
</P>
<P>
   Mulloney was stuck in Boston ``between jobs,'' he said. One
night, he pulled an old, unread copy of Thoreau's Cape Cod journals
from his bookcase _ and sat down to thumb through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a downtime in my life,'' said Mulloney, 45, over lunch
across from the State House, where he now works as an aide to State
Senator Lois Pines. He had been laid off from his job as a reporter
for WCVX, a Cape Cod television station _ and had been
``pink-slipped'' from a Cape romance _ and to make matters worse,
was fretting over whether he would be admitted to the Kennedy
School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Mulloney found himself ``intrigued by the strong,
original voice that spoke to me'' from the pages of Thoreau's
``Cape Cod.'' When Mulloney had finished reading it, the idea of
retracing Thoreau's footsteps seemed a matter of ``destiny'' rather
than merely a way of filling a between-jobs gap.
</P>
<P>
   If Thoreau did not see why he ``might not make a book on Cape
Cod,'' Mulloney thought, then ``I didn't see why I might not make a
book on Cape Cod, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The book was a half-dozen years in the making, as Mulloney did
get into the Kennedy School and then had to wait for a sabbatical
from the State House. Other books have more or less trod the same
territory _ notably, Henry Beston's ``The Outermost House'' and
John Hay's ``The Great Beach'' _ but Mulloney said nobody had done
the Cape quite Thoreau's way, setting off from Boston by public
transportation _ railroad in Thoreau's case, a Plymouth &AMP; Brockton
bus in Mulloney's.
</P>
<P>
   Mulloney thought at first that he would keep to Thoreau's pace
of 8 to 10 miles a day. But ``when you want to stop and explore it
takes a bit longer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Thoreau at the end of the day,'' he said, ``I'd be
looking for a good meal and a little conversation,'' which would
involve heading inland from the beach by late afternoon to find any
lodging &UR;  &LR; with a vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   But, Mulloney said, he did try to keep to ``the Thoreauvian
spirit'' and ``opt for spontaneity when it came to `inland'
encounters.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course the Cape in the 1990s is not the same place Thoreau
saw a century-and-a-half before: no Christmas Tree Shops, no
miniature golf courses, no fast-food clam shacks.
</P>
<P>
   But there were elements of contemporary culture that Mulloney
thought would not be completely alien to ``H.T.'' _ as Mulloney
began thinking of him familiarly. ``I would have directed H.T.'s
attention to the surfers offshore waiting patiently for something
to ride,'' he writes, remembering that Thoreau thought that `the
duck does not take to the water with surer instincts than the Cape
Cod boy (and now add the Cape Cod girl), and what are our young
surfers but the most resourceful and inventive ducks, taking to
water in the accustomed Cape Cod manner?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; And the Great Beach, the 30-odd Atlantic-facing miles of
unbroken sand from Orleans to Provincetown, was still as
awe-inspiring as Thoreau had found it _ although Mulloney notes
with interest that Thoreau would be surprised to find it now
protected by the federal government ``with whom he was often at
odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulloney is back and forth to the Cape this summer for
book-signings and readings. Of his weekends, he said, ``it's one
day for the book and one day for Lois's campaign'' for attorney
general. Beyond that, ``I think I've been bitten by the
travel-writing bug,'' Mulloney said. ``But maybe someplace further
afield than the cape.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
