<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !!! ``Brother''  An exhilaratingly edgy import that captures the
violence and brutality of the new Russia while seeming a blood
brother to the American gangster movies of the '30s. Sergei
Bodurov, who has yet to shed the last residues of baby fat and
pimples, bids to become the first international star of the new
Russian cinema as a demobilized soldier. Arriving in St. Petersburg
to buy rock CDs, meet women, and hook up with his hitman brother,
he finds he's a much more lethally efficient killer than the
latter. (Unrated)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! 1/2 &LR;   &UR; ``Disturbing Behavior''  &LR; Better-than-average
teen-screamer, with more intentional laughs than blood and gore.
Brainwashed ``Stepford'' teens listen to Wayne Newton, hang out at
the local yogurt shop, stay true to their school, and murder anyone
who gets in their way. (R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ! 1/2 ``Mafia''  &LR; A few of the sight gags and one-liners in this
effort from the ``Airplane!'' and ``Naked Gun'' gang work. But
mostly this overextended and ponderous ``Godfather'' parody is more
desperate than funny. The only consistently watchable thing in it
are Christina Applegate's goofy riffs on the Diane Keaton character
in Francis Ford Coppola's original. It can't be said that the late
Lloyd Bridges went out on top in his Brando parody here. How could
he have, given that Brando himself, among others, long ago
exhausted the potential for parody here? (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! ``Pi &LR; '' &UR;  &LR; Here's the kind of sci-fi movie you wish ``The
 &UR;  &LR; X-Files'' had been. Hot-wired to weirdness and an edgy downtown
style, Darren Aronofsky's shoestring debut pulls us into its
claustrophobic story about a numbers freak who has patched together
a few homemade computers in his slummy walk-up and believes he has
penetrated the numerical pattern underlying everything in the
universe, from God to the stock market. Which of course attracts
the spiritually and materially greedy. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!!! ``Saving Private Ryan'' &LR;  The war movie to end all war movies.
Slamming us down with a bunch of grunts on deadly Omaha Beach on
D-Day, Steven Spielberg's masterpiece plunges us into the
moment-to-moment horror and chaos and heroism of war with a
completeness and immediacy that no previous film has. A Ranger
detachment led by Tom Hanks improvises its way behind the lines to
yank Matt Damon's last survivor among four brothers from the
carnage and get him home. It does what no Hollywood movie has done
before, namely convince us that war is no movie. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! 1/2 ``The Thief''  &LR; Pavel Chukrai elegantly and eloquently
revisits postwar Stalinist Russia in this story of a swaggering con
man and thief who dresses as an army veteran and wears a tattoo of
Stalin. Stealing hearts as well as the contents of communal
apartments, he finds life more complicated than he planned when he
hooks up with a young war widow and her 6-year-old son as cover.
Not that the film yields to sentimentality any more than to
allegory. It's unflinching about the brutality in which it deals
and tells its story powerfully and in classic Russian style. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
