<HEADER>
A4535 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MD-LICENSING-BOS &LR;      07-27 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MD-LICENSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD STRUGGLES TO DEFINE MEDICAL PRACTITIONERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Massachusetts board that regulates doctors may
change the legal definition of what constitutes the practice of
medicine, as insurance companies and technology prompt more
patients to reach out to doctors and nurses across state lines.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, doctors are forced to call insurance workers in
another state for approval to treat patients. Insurers encourage
patients to phone ``tele-nurses'' when they have medical questions,
hiring firms like one in Colorado that employs 500 nurses. And on
the Internet, a growing number of companies offer medical diagnoses
and drug prescriptions to patients worldwide, with no in-person
checkup by a physician.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers say some of these practices save patients millions of
dollars. But regulators are trying to claim more powers of
supervision, saying health workers in one state may be practicing
medicine without a license when they make decisions involving
patients in any other state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a decision is made in Colorado about you in Massachusetts
and you die, we have no recourse to do anything,'' said Alexander
F. Fleming, executive director of the Massachusetts Board of
Registration in Medicine, which licenses doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Colorado medical board could do something ... but your
body, the medical records, are all in Massachusetts,'' Fleming
said. ``It's tough for the Colorado board to even care about it,
but also tough for them to investigate it properly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts boards that regulate doctors and nurses are
both grappling with new licensing rules to deal with evolving
insurance practices and technologies. The most dramatic change is
contemplated by the board governing physician licensing, because it
could set up a confrontation with the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   Under a preliminary proposal, the doctors' board would rule that
any insurance company decision to deny care, or to deny payment for
care, to a Massachusetts patient must be made by a physician
licensed in Massachusetts, Fleming said. In essence, turning down a
patient's request for treatment or reimbursement would become an
act of practicing medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The largest Massachusetts health insurers say they use
physicians to make coverage decisions, so they already comply with
the proposed rule. But it is nevertheless likely to draw opposition
from the insurance industry. Nationwide, insurance companies often
use nurses and laymen to decide whether a specific treatment is
covered by a person's health policy, and they are adamant that
those decisions do not amount to practicing medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This appears to be an attempt by physicians to eviscerate
managed care,'' said Richard Coorsh of the Health Industry
Association of America, a trade group. ``There are many cases where
you don't need a doctor making these decisions, and doing so has
cost implications that would be passed on to patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry unsuccessfully fought a similar law in
Mississippi this year, saying it would raise premiums by 5 percent
and push employers to drop coverage for 13,400 residents. The Texas
medical board adopted a similar rule in 1996, and laws are pending
before several state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said the Massachusetts Legislature has already empowered
the medical board to enact the rule after public hearings, though
it could be vetoed by the secretary of consumer affairs or the
secretary of administration and finance. The board's thinking is
still evolving, he said, and there is no timetable for public
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   In reviewing who may practice medicine, and where they must be
licensed, state regulators are reacting to a variety of
developments:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Managed health care increasingly forces doctors to seek
approval before offering treatment or referring a patient to a
specialist, often by calling insurance offices far from the
patient's home.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)A growing number of Internet sites allow people to buy
drugs and receive diagnoses by computer. For $9.95, Dr. Thomas E.
Brandeisky offers a ``virtual consultation'' based on a client's
e-mail account of his or her symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Another site, called Cyberdocs.com, offers ``virtual
housecalls'' for $50 by Salem Hospital physicians Kerry Archer and
Steven Kohler. To avoid licensing problems with other states,
patients must certify that they are in Massachusetts or outside of
the United States, according to information posted on the site.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)New technology has allowed more ``tele-medicine,'' in
which physicians in one state obtain information by phone lines
about patients elsewhere, often at the time the patient is being
examined.
</P>
<P>
   This has forced regulators to grapple with the spectrum of
services that can be offered to patients from a distance, and to
begin thinking about what licenses should be required to offer
which services.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)More health plans are using ``tele-nurses,'' or nurses who
work the phones to answer routine medical questions, to make sure
patients are following treatment plans or refer patients to
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Tele-nursing has become a big business. As many as 100 million
people could have access to tele-nursing service in the next few
years, up from 35 million today, said Theresa Bonanno, executive
director of the state Board of Registration in Nursing. And that
has raised licensing questions for nursing regulators.
</P>
<P>
   One Colorado company, Access Health Inc., employs 500 nurses who
will field 4.5 million calls this year from all 50 states. Many of
the calls come from people whose health plans have hired Access
Health to answer basic medical questions, such as how to treat a
rash or whether a baby's fever should prompt a trip to the
emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   By guiding the right services to patients at the right time,
Access Health says, insurers and patients can save money. But some
critics have asked whether a nurse in Colorado can properly treat a
person with emergency symptoms in Rhode Island, or whether that
nurse can tell that a patient's rash is likely to be caused by a
regional illness like Lyme disease.
</P>
<P>
   And others say that all ``tele-nurses'' should be licensed in
each state where patients are located.
</P>
<P>
   The Access Health nurses are licensed in the state from which
they answer the phones: Colorado, California, Illinois, and
Arizona. Julie Brooks, the company's general counsel, says Access
Health complies with all state licensing laws.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Council of State Boards of Nursing maintains
that under current laws ``tele-nurses'' must be licensed in the
state where the patient is located. ``If you are giving care to a
patient in Massachusetts, you are practicing in Massachusetts,''
said Susan Woodward, spokeswoman for the council.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that a significant amount of improper nursing is
likely taking place today. ``Is this is an urgent matter right now?
I can't answer that,'' said Bonanno of the Massachusetts nursing
board. ``But there is a level of concern that will grow as this
practice continues to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the boards that regulate doctors, state nursing boards
are trying to work out a uniform set of rules that would allow
nurses to practice nationwide. Under a proposed interstate compact,
a nursing license would become something like a driver's license,
honored by all states and recognized as invalid by all states if
revoked.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-member Massachusetts nursing board supports the
interstate license, but it wants to study the idea more before
asking the legislature to approve it, Bonanno said.
</P>
<P>
   In their extreme, new state licensing rules could prevent a
Boston resident from consulting with a doctor at the
Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center in New Hampshire, said Dr. Barry
Wolcott, chief medical officer and co-founder of Access Health.
``State licensing statutes were set up to protect citizens from
quackery,'' he said, ``not to prevent them from choosing access to
high-quality services from outside the state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
