<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4538 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TAYLOR-BOS &LR;      07-27 1888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TAYLOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES TAYLOR HAS TANGLEWOOD ON HIS MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSFIELD, Mass. _ James Taylor made an offer no one wanted to
refuse.
</P>
<P>
   The popular American balladeer has been part of the Boston
Symphony Orchestra's extended family since Caroline Smedvig, the
orchestra's director of public relations and marketing, became his
significant other. Taylor was visiting Tanglewood recently and
thought it might be interesting for everyone, including himself, to
have an informal fireside chat with the fellows of the Tanglewood
Music Center, the BSO's summer institute for advanced musical
training. Because he is fully aware of recent allegations that the
TMC has headed full steam ahead down the track of blatant
commercialism, Taylor made it clear that since he had invited
himself, he was also willing to uninvite himself if his presence
would cause problems or offend sensibilities. TMC director Ellen
Highstein asked a number of students if they would mind meeting
with Taylor, and they looked at her as if she were crazy.
</P>
<P>
   So the chat took place in a rehearsal room earlier this month at
Miss Hall's School in Pittsfield, where the TMC is lodged. Four or
five dozen TMC fellows showed up, and so did Seiji Ozawa and Andre
Previn. Joel Smirnoff, first violinist of the Juilliard Quartet,
served as interlocutor and MC, and he proved he was not a tourist
in Taylor's world. He did a better job than Barbara Walters would
have.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor levered his Lincoln-esque frame into an armchair and
spoke with great candor and self-deprecating humor about his
career, his musical training and interests, and his experience of
the creative process; in answering questions, he asked a few of his
own. There are many differences between Taylor's musical road and
the ones taken by Tanglewood fellows, but the number of
intersections was striking, and intersections don't have to lead to
collisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered that so many of you showed up,'' Taylor said.
``I'm not sure what I have to offer, except that I have spent my
life in music, the way you have, and I am dedicated to it, the way
you are.'' With that by way of introduction, Taylor said, ``The
sooner we can get to questions and answers, the better off we'll
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Smirnoff started off by asking Taylor how his musical life
began. ``Music was always there to listen to in our house,'' Taylor
said, ``and my parents encouraged all of us to pursue our interest
in it. I played the cello for three years, and although I never
lifted off on that instrument, I think I got something out of it. I
got a guitar for Christmas when I was 12 years old, and right away
I started to get returns from my investment in it. It called me
back to experiment on it the way the cello never did. I kept
pulling the instrument out of its case. My brother Livingston and I
learned music together, and it was one big knot of folk music,
testosterone, and angst. I played a little bit for my pals, and met
more pals through the instrument, and we all taught each other
different things just as soon as we figured them out ourselves. I
started playing professionally when I was 15, but I was in my mid
20s before I developed a sense that music could be a career rather
than a hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every musician has encountered parental opposition. ``My
parents may have felt concerns, and I'm sure that my father, who
was a doctor, was disappointed when I chose music over science, but
an occasional disapproving glance was as far as it went; he never
uttered a disparaging word, even when I dropped out of high school
and got into trouble. By the time I was 18 I had fallen in with a
bad element, and it's a miracle that I'm still here. My life took
me into some dangerous places, but my parents let me fly away
anyway. It makes my blood run cold when I think of my own kids
doing the same things.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about what kind of music he loved, what kind of musician
he wanted to be, Taylor said, ``After my lackluster years as a
cellist, I thought I wanted to be a folk musician, or a modern
version of a folk musician. It was the time of the Great Folk
Scare. My family had rec-ords of people like the Weavers, Pete
Seeger, and Jean Redpath, and I liked listening to Merle Travis,
Doc Watson, and Lightin' Hopkins. I would copy licks off their
records _ I wasn't aware that I was doing anything all that
difficult, although sometimes later I felt like I was on a
treadmill with the speed set too high. I read Sing Out magazine;
the folk movement was utopian, and felt like family _ more,
sometimes, than home or the campus. This was a wave that passed
through America; it repudiated the available culture and
consciously tried to make a political and social statement.''
</P>
<P>
   A singer wanted to know how Taylor has kept his voice fresh and
sounding pretty much the same throughout a career of three decades.
``That's because I have a vocal maintenance program,'' Taylor said.
``I have trained my voice, and I don't sing until I have warmed up.
I have found various warm-up exercises that work for me. The voice
is a muscle, and it has to be developed the way you develop any
other muscle.''
</P>
<P>
   One TMC fellow wanted to know how Taylor came to write his most
famous song, ``Fire and Rain.'' Taylor began by expressing a
profound reluctance to talk about songwriting. ``Songs are a better
form of communication than prose, or conversational dialogues; they
offer emotional shortcuts into other people's hearts, and I think
it diminishes the process to talk about it. Talking about music is
a very good way to shoot yourself in the foot.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Taylor spoke, he became more and more forthcoming. ``I
improvise on the guitar, and work on the things I am working on.
Then out of the vernacular stored in my brain and fingers,
something comes out; it presents itself _ it may be a series of
chord changes, or a groove I like. This in turn may suggest a
melody that can happen in that harmonic context. Things are also
suggested by the emotional context or the cadence of the words;
language can also be in conflict with the music. That's how it all
starts. But finishing a song is a very different process from
starting one. They start off of their own accord, but then you have
to nail them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning specifically to ``Fire and Rain,'' Taylor remembered how
in 1968 he was recording an album with the Beatles in London when
he learned of the suicide of a sweetheart. ``This was the start of
three months of a very difficult time for me. I wrote the first
verse when I heard the news, and the rest came when I checked into
the Austen-Riggs Center (a private psychiatric hospital) here in
Stockbridge; it was part of a period of reconstruction. My songs
are very personal, autobiographical statements, which may be why I
admire the composers of Tin Pan Alley so much _ I envy the
journeyman craftsmanship that makes it possible to write anything
they need to, although it must be tough sometimes. My songs are
intimate, interior stuff, sticky and juicy.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor went on to express his surprise and gratitude that he's
been allowed to make a career. ``Somehow I've been able to make a
living out of self-expression; it's a unique situation, not having
to pay more attention to the marketplace than I do. The marketplace
can be a very punishing place for artists, and I've written some
songs about that. (He sings a bit of `Hey, Mister, That's Me Up on
the Jukebox.') Artists have to be protected, and Tanglewood does
that, but they also have to find a place in the world. That's a
very thin line to walk. And it's always been there. Record
companies and contracts and tours and promoters are relatively new
inventions, but musicians have always had to please sources of
power _ and it's always been a drag. As performers, too, we have to
be attuned to what other people think of us, which is a dicey
thing. How evolved is it to be thinking all the time about what
other people think of you? On the other hand, thinking only about
yourself _ there's something very masturbatory about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Smirnoff wanted to know what Taylor's youthful goals were _ how
much was he interested in music and how much in success. Taylor
laughed, ``I just wanted to meet girls ... sex and death are the
only two motivations there are!''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing, Taylor apologized for the need he felt to get
cosmic. ``Music is soul food; that's the reason why we do it. A
lion has his tooth and his claw; we have consciousness, and because
we have that we're not alone. That's why we need God _ a dog
doesn't. The spiritual connection offered by my music helps us give
isolation the slip; it offers us relief. It is the truest language
there is. It follows the physical laws of the universe _ it speaks
to trees, and it speaks to your cat. That's why I hate to see
Michael Jackson selling Pepsi, or a John Lennon song selling
Lincoln-Mercury; it's a shame and a betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa and Previn chimed in on an extended discussion about
improvisation that arose from Taylor's questions and observations
about the differences between classical music and his own work.
``There is a narrowness at both ends of the scale, I think,''
Taylor said. ``I can't sit down and play a guitar piece by reading
it off the paper; I don't read music and I have a block or a phobia
about it. And while I don't know a lot about classical music, I
think all the stuff a classical musician has to learn can take you
away from personal expression. The job, I guess, is to incorporate
everything you learn into your personal expression, and that's the
same for both of us. A player like Edgar Meyer has the benefit of
both worlds _ rigorous training and the ability to improvise.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said that although improvisation is important in his
writing, it doesn't play that big a role in his performances. In
response to a question about how he keeps his repertory fresh,
Taylor said, ``What continues to be compelling is the act of
performing. I like to perform in front of an audience which becomes
a shared experience and therefore unique, even if it is a
repetitive thing. I don't vary from performance to performance, at
least not very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa spoke of making the ``Marsalis on Music'' videos at
Tanglewood a few years ago. ``I was amazed _ I learned there are
rules in jazz, and ways to rehearse.'' Previn thinks that
improvisation and classical performance belong in different worlds.
``I don't like to improvise cadenzas in Mozart concertos, for
example; it's as if you were saying, `Move over, Wolfgang, I'm on.'
I can't do that. In improvisation, you really shouldn't be
comparing yourself to anything but yourself. In classical music, 99
percent belongs to the composer; in jazz, 99 percent belongs to the
performer. Attempts to mix the two up wind up leaving everybody
unhappy; each approach is equally valid, but one at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for a final word of advice, Taylor said, ``Stay out of
small Italian sports cars, avoid a major drug habit, and keep your
overhead down. Don't marry and have children until you are ready
for that. Render unto Caesar what is Caesar's, but no more. And
always remember the path back to the well. This is not investment
banking; it's music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
