<SLUG> BC-HEAT-EMPATHY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S `HEAT WAVE' PALES IN COMPARISON TO THE OLD DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The past week, too much conversation was focused
on how hot it was. The heat was the icebreaker for strangers riding
an elevator, and likely the opener of even discussions among
acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was brutally hot in certain areas of the country,
but these were distant from us here. When the record books were
consulted, it turned out that no recent hot-day records were broken
or equalled. We were just living through a spell of weather that
was perhaps 4 degrees above the average. Nothing to get into a
sweat about.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe our perceived general discomfort was based on empathy; we
thought we endured what was happening in Texas. It also provided us
with the opportunity to make daily talk about the weather a
year-round activity. Usually, and with good reason, we tend to talk
a great deal about it during our all-too-long winters. Perhaps it
was a special benefit to keep that sort of chatter up in the weeks
of July.
</P>
<P>
   I can take this sort of heat in stride because even all these
years later, when the subject of summer heat comes up, I can still
feel _ as if I were there now _ what it was like in New York City
during the dog days. These were the years before air-conditioning
became a ubiquitous household appliance.
</P>
<P>
   In those times, if you were looking for respite, you had to take
yourself off to what was called an air-cooled environment, which
was to be found in selected movie houses. They used the phrase to
attract customers at a time when sitting in a crowded theater
otherwise might not be a top priority for many people.
</P>
<P>
   Few office buildings then were air-conditioned or air-cooled, or
in any other way equipped to handle what summer brought. As a
consequence, long sleeves were rolled up, ties pulled way down and
collars unbuttoned. Large amounts of soda were consumed in a
self-defeating effort to bring down the internal temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Paperwork on desks stuck to constantly damp forearms and many
daily tasks, usually easily accomplished, became a special chore.
By the time the work shift ended, you were outwardly rumpled beyond
the possibility of repair. Inwardly, you were exhausted, totally
drained of energy and desire. And that's before you descended into
the non-air-conditioned subway for the trip home. What a unique and
memorable experience it was, day after day, to be crammed together
with a multitude of by-now fragrant folks for what seemed the
longest ride home.
</P>
<P>
   Now that was hot, and uncomfortable and bearable only because
there was no other option available.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering the bad old days without the means to routinely keep
cool makes today's hot spells seem slight by comparison. Besides
which, considering our long winters, the feelings of heat should be
stored up the way a camel takes in water, for use later on when it
will really be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Summer gives us leave to enjoy other pleasures that we tend to
deny ourselves during cooler seasons of the year, when strictures
of propriety flourish. Dress becomes more casual during summer, and
is tolerated in the business offices as it would not be at other
times.
</P>
<P>
   Summertime permits adults to return to the days of their
childhood, and vacationing is nothing so much as legitimizing
grownups to disport themselves in the barest essential minimum of
clothing. Walking shorts and t-shirts are to be seen everywhere,
and many feet get to go sockless from the time of arising in the
morning to the moment of retiring at night.
</P>
<P>
   In the other seasons of the year, class distinctions become
immediately evident from the suits and dresses worn. But nothing
levels the layers of a society becoming ever more stratified as the
appearance of rich man or poor man in jean shorts, moccasins and
t-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, there is much good in summer, and we would do well not
to exaggerate minor inconveniences, but to revel in it while the
reveling is good. There is only one thing wrong with summer: it's
about a month or two too short.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
