<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4542 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-NEW-ACTS-BOS &LR;      07-27 1567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-NEW-ACTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK'S NEW RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The message is clear. Radio and MTV, the twin towers of music
promotion, can no longer be relied on to break new bands into the
mainstream. Many acts have tried, but most have failed to dent
radio's restrictive formats and MTV's increased focus on non-music
programming. A band has a better chance of waiting for Godot than
of hearing its single played on a major radio station or seeing its
video on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Check these eye-opening statistics: More than 28,000 records are
released each year, of which only 8 percent actually make money,
says Larry Solters, a spokesman for Capitol Records. With those
odds, it's no wonder that artists and labels are forging new
strategies to get music across to a public already satiated with
entertainment options.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _New media darling Natalie Imbruglia, who has sold 2 million
copies of her debut disc, ``Left of the Middle,'' burst on the
scene this year by performing on ``Saturday Night Live'' before she
had a record out. That was a first _ and by the time radio got on
board, she was already well on her way.
</P>
<P>
   _The Minneapolis band Semisonic has a bassist, John Munson, who
is an expert fly-fisher. His label, MCA, has used that to pitch
Men's Journal, Hooked on the Outdoors, and other nature magazines
to do stories on him and the band. It's not the cover of Rolling
Stone, but it's still helpful exposure.
</P>
<P>
   _Rapper Master P is a new star on Priority Records, which has
aided his career by running high-impact ads on the alterna-hip
cable TV show ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   _Boston band Guster, following a path forged by industry
iconoclasts R.E.M., regularly plays college gigs to build a fan
base. The band also has an incentive program, via the Internet, of
giving fans free tickets to its shows if they sell Guster
merchandise and CDs. There are 800 of these ``Guster reps'' around
the country; each gets five to 10 CDs to sell to friends. ``It's a
way of getting your music to kids who can't always find it in the
stores,'' says Guster manager Dalton Sim.
</P>
<P>
   _New R&AMP;B group Melky Sedeck, featuring the brother and sister of
Wyclef Jean from the Fugees, is being pitched to fashion magazines
Vanity Fair, Cosmo, and Elle before its record comes out. Neither
artist is a fashion model, but they're ``gorgeous and have a strong
fashion sense,'' a label rep says of this trend to plant stories in
such magazines.
</P>
<P>
   All of which fits today's accent on alternative marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't just put a record out and have it become successful.
You have to look for your audience,'' says Cathy Halgas,
spokeswoman for rockers Letters to Cleo and singer-songwriter David
Poe. The latter's modus operandi is booking many in-store
performances (at the Borders Books &AMP; Tapes chain, for one) in hopes
of compensating for meager airplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any angle we can use is definitely better than nothing,'' says
Lori Berk, an executive with MCA Records.
</P>
<P>
   Today's artists and record labels _ tired of getting nixed by
radio and MTV _ are wising up. They're reaching consumers by such
diverse tactics as handing out sampler albums at skateboard events,
building up on-line services (and giving review copies of albums to
Internet writers, not just mainstream press critics), and
soliciting slots on soundtrack albums (which have helped break acts
ranging from Lisa Loeb to the currently hot Black Eyed Peas).
</P>
<P>
   Other tactics include seeking time on network talk shows (Jay
Leno, David Letterman, Conan O'Brien, and Magic Johnson are pitched
constantly), soliciting appearances on non-MTV cable outlets (the
Disney Channel has helped break teen bluesman Jonny Lang, country
phenom LeAnn Rimes, and new teen sensations 'N Sync), and booking
``residency'' tours for acts that play weekly in various regional
clubs, giving fans and media more chances to see them. This last
method is how Jewel built her audience. She gained more marketing
clout by playing at high schools wherever she went.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't count on radio anymore,'' says Guster's Sim.
His group recently signed with Sire Records and has been touring
with Widespread Panic and G Love &AMP; Special Sauce _ two other acts
that have had scant airplay, but have won audiences through
word-of-mouth, grass-roots efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure glad that we're successful already,'' says Adam
Duritz, singer with the Counting Crows. ``I wouldn't want to be a
young band right now. It's really hard for new bands to break
through. Modern rock stations are like the new Top 40 stations.
There's a real repetition of the same songs there. It's harder for
new bands to get a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to break new acts, because we're so
song-driven,'' admits Steve Strick, music director of Boston rock
giant WBCN-FM (104.1). ``No matter what format you're talking
about, a band has to have a song that will break through. It's not
like years ago when (radio) would nurture a band.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio airplay is still the promised land, but many bands, not
content with waiting for their shot, are even adopting alternative
strategies to impress radio programmers. Matchbox 20, for instance,
which has sold 7 million copies of its debut album, ``Yourself and
Someone Else,'' used to show up in radio station lobbies (whether
or not it had been invited) to pass out pizzas and perform acoustic
sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted them to remember us. We did it for two months,''
says Matchbox 20 singer Rob Thomas. ``It gave them faces to go with
the band, so Matchbox 20 wasn't just a CD that came across their
desks. It was, `Hey, I remember those guys. They brought us
pizza.''' It may sound a bit tacky, but Thomas is convinced that it
worked.
</P>
<P>
   One thing for certain: Today's marketing plans start early. Look
at Flight 16, a British hard-rock band whose self-titled CD doesn't
come out until Aug. 25 but who played a series of free, set-up
shows last month in the States. The band's label, Sony 550, chose
what it felt were the four hardest-rocking American cities (Boston,
Chicago, Dallas, and Los Angeles) to showcase the band.
</P>
<P>
   For the Boston date, the company enlisted the aid of the
Planetary Group, an alternative-marketing agency run by Adam Lewis.
He and his staff asked Ticketmaster to print up 1,000 tickets (at a
cost of $50, or a nickel per ticket) to Flight 16's show at the
Aerosmith-owned Mama Kin club. The tickets were then distributed
free to ``impact areas where the hipsters and college kids hang
out,'' says Lewis, referring to Tower Records, Newbury Comics, the
Allston Beat, and Urban Outfitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that with a baby band, there wasn't going to be a
huge draw,'' Lewis says. ``But we also knew there's a definite
value of having a hard ticket in your hand, as opposed to just
saying that you're on the guest list. We gave away 1,000 of the
tickets and 10 percent of the people showed up, which is pretty
good, I think. The emphasis is on getting people in front of the
band, not on making money. If we develop the band now, hopefully
the payoff will be later.''
</P>
<P>
   Flight 16 delivered a scorching set, filled with sniping guitar
solos and a ``Beatles meets Zeppelin'' sound, as singer Dave Sears
put it. The set was also seen by numerous music critics and by
WBCN's Strick. ``That was a pretty effective band,'' says Strick.
``I haven't heard the record yet, but I'll definitely check it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's marketing scenario places a heavy emphasis on playing
ability _ a refreshing change from past years, when bands spent
small fortunes to make videos that MTV would often ignore anyway.
Many experts now advise bands to perform as often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get a local following and if you start to draw 500 people a
night, the A&AMP;R folks (artist &AMP; repertoire, meaning talent scouts)
will come swarming,'' says Greg Glover, an A&AMP;R rep for Slash/London
Records. That's what happened to the band Harvey Danger, which
Glover signed out of Seattle. The group was making local waves with
the amusing, tongue-in-cheek song ``Flagpole Sitta'' (sample verse:
``I'm not sick, but I'm not well''). First aired on Seattle station
KNPD, it eventually became a recent No. 2 hit on the modern rock
chart nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the key to breaking an act into the upper reaches of
stardom is to have a multidimensional approach. ``You have to have
the press at the same time that you have radio and MTV,'' says
Elaine Schock, a vice president at RCA Records, which has broken
Imbruglia and is enjoying fast-rising success with 'N Sync and Eve
6. ``You need to see the group on TV, you need to hear it, you need
to read about it, and then you'll buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's easier said than done in today's convoluted
music market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, people want to get out there and make a return on
their investment quickly, but it can take time,'' says Tom Carolan,
who does A&AMP;R for Sony 550 and previously signed the Stone Temple
Pilots to Atlantic Records. ``You don't want to get too tricky. You
want to try to let a band grow organically and naturally. You don't
want them to rush out and play a bigger stage than is natural for
them. I'd rather see a packed 500-seat club than a half-empty
1,000-seat club.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a certain amount of hype involved in this
business, but the key word is `patience.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
