<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIM OF DOWNSIZING FINDS A NEW BULLY: THE IRS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Truman Crabbe recalls vividly when he was mugged.
</P>
<P>
   He was 69 years old. He was earning a quarter of a million
dollars a year managing the Albany office of IDS Financial
Services. And it was a year after American Express bought the
company.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Truman Crabbe was replaced by a man in his 30s who
would earn less than half of what Truman Crabbe was making. And, at
about the same time, other IDS divisional managers around the
country got similar bad news.
</P>
<P>
   They were all older guys. They all made big bucks. And they all
were part of a wave of corporate bloodletting that made Wall Street
cheer and grown men weep all across the country.
</P>
<P>
   In a 15-year period, corporate America erased about 45 million
jobs in cutbacks designed to drive up stock prices. By the time
Truman Crabbe was let go, it was no longer blue-collar workers
being thrown overboard. By then, layoffs were hitting mostly
higher-paid, college-educated workers who'd figured _ mistakenly _
that their tenure, loyalty and performance had earned them some
measure of job security. Some of these people just retired. They
went quietly. Truman Crabbe and 31 other IDS division managers
across the country were not among them. They sued for age
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   They won, too. The company coughed up $35 million in a
settlement. After legal fees, Truman Crabbe ended up with about
$500,000 in wage replacement and tort damages. A tort is a legal
term for a wrongdoing that causes damage, a violation of somebody's
rights. Truman Crabbe fully expected to pay taxes on the money the
company gave him for wage replacement. He would have paid taxes on
that money if he'd stayed with the company. But he didn't expect to
have to pay taxes on money awarded him for his legal fees or
because he'd been done wrong.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he wouldn't have had to pay taxes on legal fees or
damages if some drunk had run him down on with a car.
</P>
<P>
   He was left with only a bit more than a year's salary. The
government took the rest. It just didn't seem right to him. So he
left his home in the Albany suburb of Clifton Park and went to see
his congressman, Gerald B.H. Solomon, a man famously sympathetic to
corporate interests over his 10 terms in the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   And Jerry Solomon agreed with him that this just wasn't right.
</P>
<P>
   The result was House Bill 2792. Except for wage replacement
dollars, it would exempt such damage awards from taxation. It also
would permit the damaged employee to spread the amount of the award
over the period of time between the date of the damage and the date
of the award.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, since Solomon is chairman of the powerful House Rules
Committee, a bill like this would have an excellent chance of
passage. But Solomon recently announced that this will be his last
term in Congress. He's now a lame duck. And his bill remains
bottled up in the Ways and Means Committee, chaired by Rep. Bill
Archer, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Archer doesn't like this bill, and Solomon can't shake it free.
</P>
<P>
   So, HR 2792 dies when Congress recesses next month. And, unless
some other powerful member of Congress picks it up next session,
Truman Crabbe is out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, about two million Americans are affected by violent
crime. About 3 million people, a full 50 percent more, are fired _
many because they're too old and make too much money. They're
mugged by their employers as surely as any crime victim.
</P>
<P>
   And, because Bill Archer won't let this bill out of committee,
the ones who fight back are mugged again by the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
