<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-FINLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC KIASMA ENTERS FINLAND IN NEW-MUSEUM DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI _ A proper opera house used to be the prerequisite for
any European city laying claim to cultural consciousness. Now it's
a proper museum for modern and/or contemporary art. Bilbao and
Barcelona, the two leading cities of northern Spain, are duking it
out with major new museums that are also major tourist attractions,
Bilbao's by the American architect Frank Gehry, Barcelona's by
American Richard Meier. Stockholm's crowning achievement as this
year's Cultural Capital of Europe was the opening of its Moderna
Museet, designed by a Spaniard, Rafael Moneo. London's celebration
of the millennium will be capped by the inauguration of the vast
Tate Gallery of Modern Art, housed in the former Bankside Power
Station, which is being redesigned by Swiss architect Jacques
Herzog. And you could barely squeeze another new museum into
Switzerland or Germany, so crowded is the field.
</P>
<P>
   Now Finland enters the fray with Kiasma, a contemporary art
museum as captivating as its name, from the Greek word for
``crossover.'' The struggle for freedom of this nation so long
dominated by its aggressive neighbors, Sweden and Russia, has
helped define Kiasma. Many contemporary museums find the end of
World War II a logical starting point for their collections. Kiasma
starts with 1960 because, chief curator Maaretta Jaukkuri explains,
Finland was so crippled by the war, its spirit and treasury so
depleted, that the country ``turned inward, to heal the wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   It's now turned eagerly outward. Like the new museums in Bilbao,
Barcelona, Stockholm, and London, Helsinki's has been designed by a
foreigner _ the New York-based architect Stephen Holl, chosen from
an astonishing 516 applicants. Since Finland's greatest
contribution to world culture, along with the music of Sibelius, is
arguably its 20th-century architecture by the likes of Alvar Aalto
and Eliel Saarinen, its selection of a foreigner to design the new
$40 million museum is even more significant than similar choices in
Bilbao and Stockholm. The museum's site, at one of Helsinki's
busiest intersections, couldn't have stressed that significance
more. A couple of minutes' walk from Kiasma are two canonical
buildings: Aalto's majestic, marble-clad Finlandia Hall, now under
scaffolding as it undergoes major repairs; and Saarinen's mighty
railroad station.
</P>
<P>
   In this distinguished company, Kiasma holds its own with a
murmur rather than a scream. Holl's delicately balanced play of
curves and grids greets its surroundings graciously. The back of
Kiasma bulges toward Toolo Bay like a sail filled with wind. (Or
like the soaring roof of another great waterside culture temple,
the Sydney Opera House.) The side of the building facing Finlandia
Hall looks like a giant cornucopia sheared off at the end, its
glass walls allowing a view of all five floors of the interior.
</P>
<P>
   One other thing about the site. Between Kiasma and the street is
the equestrian statue of Marshal Mannerheim, Finnish war hero and
later Finnish president. Holl suggested it be moved to accommodate
the museum. ``He didn't know Finnish history,'' Jaukkuri says. ``It
was unfortunate that he said that.'' You don't mess with
Mannerheim, not in Finland, Holl found. So ultimately he didn't. In
its final form, his building becomes a fine backdrop for the
statue, which is reflected in the sleek glass walls, the rectangle
of the sculpture's base echoed in the rectangles of the building's
grid. And one window originally slated to have milk glass is clear
instead, to give museumgoers inside the building a good view of the
hero on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   Holl learned something of Finnish history the hard way, and
Finns seem appreciative if not quite ready to free him completely
of the arrogant-architect stereotype. My guide says that when Holl
came for the May opening of the museum, ``he tried to be modest.''
</P>
<P>
   On my first visit to Helsinki, in 1993, a Finnish acquaintance
pointed to a downtown restaurant and proudly announced that this
was the only place in the world where Salman Rushdie could eat in
public. The moral of the story is that Helsinki is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Kiasma is hardly safe architecture _ but it's seductive rather
than shocking. Its designer was until recently one of those
visionaries whose drawings ended up on gallery walls but whose
buildings didn't get built. That's been changing, with commissions
from Japan to Amsterdam. The only Holl building I'd seen previously
is his Chapel of St. Ignatius at Seattle University, a series of
fluid, intersecting volumes and meandering paths that suggest the
road to God is neither straight nor easy, but might be beautiful.
Walls curve. Chandeliers are made of liquid-looking glass.
Handrails unfurl like ribbons. The walls of one chapel are coated
with beeswax, with prayers on snippets of gold leaf embedded in the
wax; in the center of the space a madrona tree lifts its branches
heavenward.
</P>
<P>
   Kiasma, too, has ribbony door handles and wall sconces composed
of two arcs that cradle a bulb. It, too, has a chapel-like quality,
and traffic patterns that meander. The ramps and stairs do not
follow a linear path; nor, of course, does contemporary art. From
the ground floor, devoted to amenities including bookshop and cafe,
a curving ramp beckons upward into white spaces with diffuse white
light pouring in from above, a celestial effect interrupted by an
interior window with a view of Italian artist Maurizio Nannucci's
blue neon words, ``more than meets the eye.'' (The Nannucci is in
English. Labels at Kiasma are in English as well as Finnish and
Swedish, the country's two official tongues: Hence the joke ``Finns
are silent in two languages.'')
</P>
<P>
   While Holl's Seattle chapel is architecture and sculpture in
one, his brief in Helsinki was to make spaces that could
accommodate other people's art. ``I wanted a neutral, very Zen
simplicity to allow the art pieces to be in the foreground,'' he
says. That art goes far beyond painting and sculpture. ``We
emphasize new media,'' says Jaukkuri. ``We collect many works that
exist only on the Internet or CD-ROM.'' ``Media stations''
sprinkled through the museum allow visitors to explore and
experience contemporary art. Several spaces are devoted to video,
their curving walls and jutting dormers adding shape to video's
flatness. Kiasma is possibly the most forward-thinking,
technologically-minded of the new crop of contemporary museums. Its
very name signifies the intersection of art and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Kiasma was officially born in 1990, an offshoot of the Finnish
National Gallery, housed in temporary quarters until Holl's
building opened. Its collection of 4,000 works includes the usual
international suspects _ Serra, Salle, Lichtenstein _ but its
mandate is to collect in what Jaukkuri calls ``concentric circles _
Finnish artists first, then those from the Baltic States and
Russia, then the other Scandinavian countries, then further
afield.'' This policy results in delightful ``finds'' like
``Babylon,'' an installation by two Danish artists, Christian Skeel
and Morten Skriver, who have filled ceramic jars with strong scents
_ camphor, cedarwood, ambergris, and dozens more, making a quiz to
see what your nose knows.
</P>
<P>
   As for the native art, it makes up a major show called ``This
Side of the Ocean,'' which is, Jaukkuri says, ``about Finnishness _
the cliches and the myths. Finnish art is traditionally very well
made _ a characteristic that can be a weakness. It can be too neat,
too nice.'' Fanni Niemi-Junkola, one of the 11 artists in the show,
goes against that grain in her short film, ``Giants,'' a battle
between two women who kick and push in an effort to throw each
other into the sea. They're not nice at all. Pekka Nevalainen's
installation ``Nature Document (Six Spruces)'' includes a half
dozen bedraggled, shedding conifers that look like a Christmas tree
sale on Dec. 26. Marianna Uutinen's ``MacKesa'' includes a swath of
Marimekko fabric, in one of the firm's signature squiggle designs.
Esko Mannikko's panoramic photographs show a Finnish countryside
ridden with litter. Sirpa Alalaakkola's portraits depict immigrants
whose faces are Asian, African, Hispanic _ anything but the
blue-eyed blond that says ``Finnish'' to most outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   While Kiasma hasn't had the blitz of publicity that other new
museums have enjoyed _ Meier's Getty Museum and Gehry's Bilbao
topping the list _ it has had a highly positive reception. In her
book ``Towards A New Museum,'' an opinionated and often highly
critical analysis of the subject, architectural historian Victoria
Newhouse lavishes praise on Holl's aims and achievements. ``From
the moment one enters the museum's white concrete-walled reception
atrium,'' she writes, ``the mystery of its receding curve and
diffused skylight arouses a sense of excitement and anticipation.''
There's box-office evidence that Finns and other folks agree. In
its first month, Helsinki's new museum drew 100,000 visitors.
Kiasma has charisma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1354EDT &QL; 
