r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BROWN-GIANTS-HNS &LR;      07-27 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWN-GIANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARY BROWN OVERCOMES WEIGHT, GAME WOES TO PLAY WITH THE GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK SINGELAIS  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Feeling sorry for himself, Gary Brown wasted the
autumn of 1996, secluded inside a town house he rented in his
hometown of Williamsport, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployed running back wiled away the time by watching
television and eating _ especially his mother's specialty, macaroni
and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kind of sat around and didn't do anything,'' said
Brown, now playing for the New York Giants. ``It wasn't a good
situation then.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few months of this sedentary lifestyle, Brown ballooned
to 260 pounds, 42 pounds heavier than when he first entered the
National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like the end of Brown's career, which had included a
1,000-yard season with the Houston Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown's mother, Dorreen, repeatedly implored him to return
to football, and Brown had an epiphany while sitting in front of
the television in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I was watching the AFC playoffs, and I realized that I
wanted to play again,'' Brown said. ``I decided to dedicate myself
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Shedding 30 pounds, Brown came out of exile to play for the San
Diego Chargers last season. The Chargers chose not to re-sign him
this season, so Brown joined the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, starting over with his third team, is trying to show the
Giants he is still a productive runner at age 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I just have to go out and prove it again,'' he said. ``I'm
not really happy (just) to be in the league. That's no big deal.
The big deal is going out and proving again that I'm a quality
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is carrying a much more manageable 230 pounds on his
5-foot-11 frame. Despite his history, Giants coach Jim Fassel said
he doesn't monitor Brown's weight any more closely than any other
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's overweight, he gets fined,'' Fassel said. ``Right now,
he's fine. And he will be. He's worked at it, and I don't see
weight being a problem with him right now. And he'll probably trim
out a little bit as we continue to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said he likes Brown's extra effort, the ability to turn a
likely three-yard gain into four or five yards.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Brown run isn't pretty, but he keeps his shoulder pads
low and his legs are constantly churning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have a style,'' he said. ``I just go out and
run as hard as I possibly can. Because my pad level is so low and
because of my build, I always tend to go forward and I use that to
my advantage. In the fourth quarter, guys are getting tired and
starting to tackle high, so I run through a lot of arm tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the NFL's biggest surprises in 1993, when he ran
for 1,002 yards for the Oilers despite starting only eight games.
His 5.1 average per carry led his conference.
</P>
<P>
   He never reached that level again. His 1994 season was cut short
by a thigh injury and he was benched for six games in 1995. He was
cut in Houston's training camp in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was injuries and maybe a little bit of my
immaturity, being able to handle the type of pressure and success
that comes with a 1,000-yard season,'' Brown said. ``I didn't know
that after that (1,000 yards), they'd expect me do to it every
season.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Brown ate himself out of football in 1996, his mother tried
to give him a verbal kick in the pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him I knew that he loved football, and I knew he
wasn't ready to give it up,'' Dorreen Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Brown committed himself to physical fitness. He
worked out at the local YMCA and ran at a football field in his old
neighborhood in Williamsport.
</P>
<P>
   It was no small feat to burn off 30 pounds after five months of
inactivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to die,'' he said. ``But I figured that
I put myself in that position, so now I was going to get myself out
of it. That was my whole motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   He signed a one-year contract with San Diego, and nearly gained
1,000 yards, but a groin injury in the season finale against Denver
left him stuck at 945 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his comeback, Brown was unemployed again this off-season
when the Chargers decided to bring back running back Natrone Means.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were happy to sign Brown to a one-year contract, a
move that sealed the departure of franchise rushing leader Rodney
Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said his primary motivation isn't the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just going out and playing is my thing,'' he said. ``It's not
the glitz and the shoe endorsements and all that stuff. Everybody
wants that, but I'm in it for the respect of my peers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
