<HEADLINE>
NEW AND RECOMMENDED RECENTLY REVIEWED BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Hand'' &LR;  by Frank R. Wilson (Pantheon, $30). A
neurologist's provocative argument that the human hand, as much as
the human mind, has been the key to our evolution and our
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Explaining Hitler'' &LR;  by Ron Rosenbaum (Random House, $30).
Not a new account of the dictator but a sifting of what we can and
do know for sure about his life and what he stands for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Not Guilty!'' &LR;  by Betty Holcomb (Scribner, $25). An unabashed
partisan and a careful reporter, Holcomb acquits working mothers of
the charges of harming their children, their families, and their
society.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``A Beautiful Mind'' &LR;  by Sylvia Nasar (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25).
A biography of an extraordinary mathematician who went to madness
and back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``Angela the Upside-Down Girl: And Other Domestic Travels'' &LR;  by
Emily Hiestand (Beacon, $23). From Oak Ridge, Tenn., to Winthrop
and Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Where the Sea Used to Be'' &LR;  by Rick Bass (Houghton Mifflin,
$25). A fiercely beautiful first novel about oil, men, and western
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Meditations from a Movable Chair''  &LR; by Andre Dubus (Knopf,
$23). Muscular but sensitive essays, enlivened by Dubus's
storytelling prowess.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Freedomland'' &LR;  by Richard Price (Broadway Books, $25).
Cinematic story of a white mother's fabricated tale about a black
carjacker, and the horrific consequences for a divided city.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Final Vinyl Days'' &LR;  by Jill McCorkle (Algonquin, $18.95).
Stories of small-town Southern folk, trying to hold their lives
together.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Inn at Lake Devine''  &LR; by Elinor Lipman (Random House,
$23.95). A poignant novel of memory, prejudice, and understanding.
</P>
