<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASS ARE BACK ON THE BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A chilled fog buried the coast again this past
week, and it hid a fire that hasn't burned so hot in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the beaches, fishermen are again casting out to the sea,
their dawn images nothing more than silhouettes against the ocean
backdrop. Many are in groups, others are alone. It looks something
like men against the sea, classic and beautiful, but the reality on
the beach is that the striped bass have roared in, and the
prospects for thrill, one-on-one, have rarely been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe, there are bass everywhere,'' said Keith
Fraser, who founded the United Anglers of California based on a
proposed resurrection of the fishery.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're at the old spots, like 30 years ago, in the (San
Francisco) Bay, everywhere ...,'' Fraser said. ``And there lots of
them, not just a few, but just bass everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Klinger of Pacifica, something of a sea wolf, said the fish
are biting often even when there are no ``bird conventions,'' that
is, circling, diving birds indicating that a school of fish has
trapped baitfish against the back of the surf wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when there's no birds, you see guys out on the beach, and
they're getting them,'' Klinger said. ``Some guys even just use
bait, cast it out, and then spend the day, enjoying themselves.
Others are working at it, casting all day, and fish are being
caught.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Jonah Li of Hi's Tackle who first noticed last Christmas
that something might have suddenly turned for the better for the
bass. Over the Christmas and New Year's holidays, Li discovered
that striped bass were holding along Baker Beach and Crissy Field
near the entrance of San Francisco Bay, the first time that as
been documented in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was just a start, striped bass started being caught
in larger numbers in March and April at Ocean Beach on the San
Francisco coast, and then in early June, a huge throng roared out
of nowhere and into the Bay and coast, from Marin on through San
Francisco to Pacifica, some 20 miles of fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Nino cost my business a fortune, especially with all the
bad weather and no trips,'' said Craig Stone at Emeryville
Sportfishing. ``But now for the first time in years, we're seeing
all these stripers, really, it's unbelievable, the real thing, just
fish everywhere, especially hard to believe how many, and it's
turning this summer into something special, something a lot of
people will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   After the drought of 1991, the striped bass population crashed
to all-time lows, with year-after-year of the lowest spawning
success in the Delta this century. Stone, like many, believes that
the migration habits of the fish have changed due to so much water
being diverted into the Delta, where 80,000 gallons of water is
taken per second and sent to points south.
</P>
<P>
   But this spring, the Delta pumps were shut down for more than
two months, both for repairs for the California Aqueduct and also
because farmers in the San Joaquin Valley needed no extra water
after El Nino did its thing. For the first time in 15 years, water
flowed from mountains to Delta to Bay unimpeded, just as nature had
done.
</P>
<P>
   Just as suddenly, the striped bass are acting like they did in
the 1960s, before the Delta pumps started cranking, as well as back
in the early 1980s, when the pumps were also shut to repair the
400-mile Aqueduct.
</P>
<P>
   With the bass back on the beach, it provides a chance for a
special experience, to see if you can catch a big bass. It is the
kind of experience that has rare appeal because everything is up to
you, there is complete freedom, it's cheap yet a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Like religion, there are many paths but one truth. As Klinger
mentioned, some will just use bait, blood worms, pile worms,
anchovies, even cut fillets of sardine, cast it out at a favorite
hole, and even bring a lawn chair, waiting for a bite. Others take
different approach, reading their tide books, fishing the two hours
after the top of the tide, making long-distance casts with metal
jigs and spoons such as the 3 1/2-ounce Krocadile, chrome with the
lime-green stripe, or Hopkins, Kastmasters or Miki jigs.
</P>
<P>
   Others go the extra mile. Some daredevils will venture out on
the rocky points, then cast huge floating wood plugs called Pencil
Poppers, where strikes from 20-pound bass can come right on the
surface, sometimes within 10 feet. This can be dangerous, where a
rogue wave can sweep an unsuspecting angler right into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Party boats from San Francisco, Berkeley and Emeryville, all
with live anchovies for bait, are also making daily trips to the
beach, and the scores have been mind-boggling, with 2-fish limits
of striped bass often caught so fast that the boats have time to
also fish for halibut, rockfish and sometimes even salmon.
</P>
<P>
   The Huck Finn out of Emeryville, for instance, reported 84
striped bass (limits) to 21 pounds, plus a bonus of 20 halibut to
22 pounds for 42 people.
</P>
<P>
   The scene of excited anglers scrambling along the beach could
make for a mural with poetic qualities. But the results are as
concrete as the roads you drive on _ the bass are back on the
beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
