<HEADLINE>
YOGI BERRASPEAK AND OTHER BASEBALL MALAPROPISMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARTIN D. TULLAI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUTHERVILLE, Md. _ Asked what he would do if he found a million
dollars, Lawrence Peter Berra answered: ``If the guy was poor, I
would give it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Yogi Berra was a distinguished catcher for the New York Yankees
(1946-1963), most valuable player in the American League in 1951,
1954 and 1955, and he managed the team to the pennant in 1964. But
he is best known today as the inspiration for the name of cartoon
character Yogi Bear _ and for word foulups that were sometimes real
and (perhaps) sometimes contrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is 90 percent mental,'' he said. ``The other half is
physical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you a fatalist?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I never collected postage stamps.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Mantle's switch-hitting? ``Mantle was naturally
amphibious.''
</P>
<P>
   Berra wasn't alone as a baseball personality with a talent for
hilarious misstatements.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Ozark, who managed the Phillies from 1973 to 1979,
exclaimed during a losing streak: ``I know we're having troubles,
but that's nothing new. Even Napoleon had his Watergate.''
</P>
<P>
   Team morale? ``Morality is not a problem here.''
</P>
<P>
   About an infielder: ``His limitations are limitless.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Coleman, the former Yankee infielder who became a
broadcaster, described a long drive: ``There's a fly ball deep to
center field ... Winfield is going back, back _ he hits his head
against the wall. It's rolling toward second base.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Colemanisms: ``He salides into second with a stand-up
double.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Young Frank Pastore may have just pitched the biggest victory
of 1979, maybe the biggest victory of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gaylord Perry and McCovey should know each other like a book.
They've been ex-teammates for years now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Pete Rose brings the Reds in, they ought to bronze him and
put him in cement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Royster has gone six-for-seven against Shirley this year ...
and there's a single that makes him five-for-eight.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to Yogi Berra: Had he seen ``Doctor Zhivago''?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I feel fine.''
</P>
<P>
   To a waitress who asked if he wanted French fries: ``OK but no
potatoes, I'm on a diet.''
</P>
<P>
   To another who queried whether he wanted his pizza cut into four
pieces or eight: ``Better make it four _ I don't think I can eat
eight.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin D. Tullai is retired chairman of the history department
at St. Paul's School in Brooklandville, Md.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
