<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4556 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DAVIS-MEMORIAL-HN     07-27 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DAVIS-MEMORIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL FAMILY HONORS A GREAT SHORTSTOP, BELATEDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ The speech was short. Short and bittersweet.
Short and bittersweet, with so many things left unsaid,
unexplained, undone.
</P>
<P>
   The later in the day it got, the more suffocatingly sad the
words that National League President Leonard Coleman spoke into the
microphone became. Coleman could offer no personal touches, and
certainly no personal remembrances, about the first player inducted
Sunday afternoon into the baseball Hall of Fame Class of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody had to stand up on behalf of George Stacey Davis, who,
before a flying Dutchman named Honus Wagner came along, was the
standard-bearer for shortstops. By default, that somebody was
Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``As evidenced by the fact that I'm accepting this award for
him, no family member could be located,'' Coleman said. ``So in a
way, baseball was _ and is _ George Davis' family. And as George
sits resting with the Father, he will hopefully feel a great sense
of pride that his family has granted him the highest distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeous George Davis last played in a major league game 89
seasons ago. Davis escaped the textile mills of Cohoes, N.Y., made
it to the big leagues, made it to the World Series, made it through
20 seasons, made it big.
</P>
<P>
   And for what?
</P>
<P>
   Davis had been in a psychiatric hospital for two years _
sentenced to a slow, surreal syphilis death when baseball opened a
shrine to its best and brightest. Ty Cobb was in the inaugural Hall
of Fame Class of 1936. Babe Ruth. Walter Johnson. Wagner. Christy
Mathewson, who didn't live long enough to see the day he'd be
remembered for as long as bases are 90 feet apart.
</P>
<P>
   When Mathewson failed to revolutionize pitching the moment he
arrived in the majors, the owner of the New York Giants wanted him
to try the outfield. The Giants' manager, who happened to be the
star shortstop, would have no part of such a scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Mathewson became beloved as ``The Big Six.'' Life gave Davis the
Deep Six, not even giving him the courtesy of a decent burial.
Davis has been in a pine box _ and without a headstone _ since
1940. He left behind no children, no one who loved him enough to
pass on his memory to descendants of future generations.
</P>
<P>
   There was no mistaking the pride in the voice of Wilber Rogan as
he accepted a Hall of Fame plaque on behalf of his father.
``Bullet'' Joe Rogan won 113 games and batted .343 in the Negro
Leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally,'' Wilber Rogan said, ``people ask me two questions
when they ask about my dad: where did he get the name ``Bullet''
from, and who was faster, him or Satchel Paige? My answer is, `I
don't know.' But I do know that when Satchel was on the mound, he
needed a designated hitter. When my dad was on the mound, he batted
in the cleanup spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The late Larry MacPhail made the Hall of Fame after an
innovative career as an executive with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New
York Yankees _ he brought night games to the major leagues. On
Sunday, Lee MacPhail Jr. culminated a 45-year baseball career by
joining his father in the Hall of Fame. Larry and Lee are the first
father-and-son team enshrined in Cooperstown. Lee's son Andy is
president of the Chicago Cubs. Lee's grandson, Lee, is scouting
director for the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was brilliant,'' said Lee MacPhail, who was the
American League president from 1974 to 1983. ``He was colorful. He
was creative. He was dynamic. He was innovative. I could go on for
some time. I was none of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   What Lee MacPhail is now is one of 59 living Hall of Famers.
Considering how membership in the Hall of Fame is up to 237, that
makes him one of the truly lucky few. Larry Doby knows. Doby is 63.
He was the first African American to play in the American League,
in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Doby helped the Cleveland Indians win a World
Series. Those were the days when a picture of Doby and a white
pitcher, Steve Gromek, locked in a triumphant embrace was
considered a significant sociological development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've got, everything my family has got, we got it
from baseball,'' Doby said. If somebody had told me 51, 52 years
ago that I would be standing here being honored by the Hall of
Fame, I wouldn't have believed it. But thank God I've lived long
enough. I sure do appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Sutton got into the Hall of Fame the fifth year he was
eligible. It took voters that long to appreciate a body of work
that included 324 victories and nary a missed start in 23 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted this for over 40 years,'' Sutton said. ``So why am
I standing here shaking like a leaf? I think part of it is because
I'm standing in front of some of the people who were the greatest
artists in a wonderful business that I've ever seen before.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you don't feel an aura that's almost spiritual when you
walk through the Hall of Fame and when you stand with these people,
then check tomorrow's obituary: You're in it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Sutton eloquently thanked an array of people who made a
difference in his life, his 20-month-old daughter obliviously
fingered a small box of Cheerios. Jacqueline Sutton was born 16
weeks early. Doctors gave her a one in 100 chance of surviving. She
spent 12 weeks in intensive care. She has had two eye operations
and a double-hernia surgery. She taught her father that there is
more to life than baseball and its wonders.
</P>
<P>
   ``With apologies to Lou Gehrig,'' Sutton said, ``I'm the
luckiest man on the face of the Earth. I have everything in life
that I've ever wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   George Davis ended up with nothing but a plaque and belated
recognition. He left so many things unsaid, unexplained, undone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
