<SLUG> BC-SF-STADIUM-HNS </SLUG>
  
 DeBARTOLO IS KEY TO NEW STADIUM COMPLEX FOR 49ERS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Eddie DeBartolo, the part owner of the San
Francisco 49ers who personally financed a campaign for a new
stadium, is now the major obstacle to the deal going forward, two
sources close to the team's parent company said.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal of roles for DeBartolo _ from stadium-project
patron to deal breaker _ comes because he holds a written agreement
giving him 10 percent ownership of the proposed $525 million
stadium and shopping mall project, the two sources said.
</P>
<P>
   And DeBartolo is holding the mall developer involved in the
project, the Mills Corp., to the written agreement signed last year
giving him a separate share of the development, the two sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   With DeBartolo taking 10 percent of the earnings, the sources
said, the stadium and mall wouldn't be worth the investment for the
49ers' parent company, the Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. or the Mills
Corp. of Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the stadium deal crashes, it will be because he refused to
release Mills,'' said one of the sources. Both sources spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo and his sister, Denise DeBartolo York, own DeBartolo
Corp., which based in Youngstown, Ohio. If DeBartolo agrees to
dissolve his 1997 agreement with Mills, he would still stand to
gain financially from the project, because it would be a joint
development of the DeBartolo Corp. and Mills.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, however, DeBartolo has refused to give up the
ownership stake after putting up most of the $2.4 million spent on
last year's successful campaign to convince voters to approve using
municipal bonds for the construction of the new complex.
</P>
<P>
   Financial disclosures from the June 1997 election show $2
million in loans to the stadium campaign from trust accounts held
in the name of DeBartolo's three daughters _ Lisa, Tiffanie and
Nicole.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo didn't return a telephone message seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   A message left for Laurence Siegel, Mills' chief executive
officer, also was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts have dogged the project planned for Candlestick Point
since June 3, 1997, when city voters narrowly approved $100 million
in city bonds for the $325 million stadium and land-use changes for
a $200 million mall, called Candlestick Mills, to be built next
door.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, DeBartolo stepped down as chairman of the
49ers and as a director of the DeBartolo Corp. when he became a
target of a federal investigation into alleged influence-peddling
in a Louisiana riverboat casino venture. DeBartolo has not been
indicted in connection with the case.
</P>
<P>
   In January, DeBartolo's sister, who is chairwoman of the
DeBartolo Corp., issued a two-page statement that appeared to
further darken the stadium and mall project's viability.
</P>
<P>
   The statement cited new estimates for the project suggesting
costs had ballooned by $200 million, and the company directors had
voted to slow down ``and could not proceed ... until those issues
were resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, financial information the Mills Corp. reported to
the Securities and Exchange Commission showed sales tax revenue
collected by the city from Candlestick Mills would fall far short
of what would be needed to cover the annual debt service on city
bonds for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials say the project is alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ... remain committed to trying to make this thing work so
that in 2003 we are not only hosting the Super Bowl (at the new
stadium), but playing in it,'' said Larry Thrailkill, who became
interim president of the 49ers last week after Carmen Policy
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   National Football League Commissioner Paul Tagliabue promised
San Francisco it would host the league's championship game in 2003,
and be in a regular rotation for future games, as an inducement to
voters to approve the new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As a first step toward obtaining approval for the project, the
DeBartolo Corp. has said it would have an environmental impact
report on the stadium and mall completed by September. Meeting that
deadline is imperative if the stadium is to be built in time for
the 2003 Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But to put the financing package together, DeBartolo must give
up his separate 10 percent ownership stake, one of the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't, the source said, Mills could balk at going
forward for reasons other than having to share earnings with
DeBartolo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets back to the issue of a public corporation,'' said the
source, citing the investigation in Louisiana and the possibility
Mills shareholders might blanch at a joint venture with him. As a
publicly held company, the source said, ``you have to go into
things that are squeaky clean.''
</P>
</TEXT>
