AP's PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
<TEXT>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 26, 1998 -- NY-ALZHEIMERS-CAREGIVERS,
7-26 -- Program manager, Carol Briggs-Lewis dancing with Bess
Bromberg, a client at the Hebrew Home for the Aged in Riverdale,
Bronx. People with Alzheimer's disease often stay up all hours of
the night, leaving their families exhausted. A new overnight
program at the Hebrew Home for the Aged now offers them help. The
program, Elderserve at Night, takes place overnight, from 7 p.m. to
7 a.m., Wednesdays through Sundays. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON, Md. -- July 26, 1998 -- CAPITOL-POLICE-2,
7-26 -- A badge of a Capitol police officer banded in mourning for
the two Capitol police officers who died in the line of duty on
Friday. Congress prepared Sunday to pay tribute to Capitol police
officers Jacob Chestnut and Detective John Gibson, with an honor
usually reserved for former presidents and heroes of grand military
campaigns. The flag-draped caskets will be displayed in the Capitol
Rotunda on Tuesday, and the public will be allowed to pay its
respects. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON, Md. -- July 26, 1998 -- CAPITOL-POLICE-1,
7-26 -- Wenling Chestnut, right, the widow of slain Capitol Police
Officer Jacob Chestnut, received condolences from James and Gerri
King on Sunday at her home in Fort Washington, Md. Congress
prepared Sunday to pay tribute to Chestnut and fellow slain police
officer Detective John Gibson, with an honor usually reserved for
former presidents and heroes of grand military campaigns. The
flag-draped caskets will be displayed in the Capitol Rotunda on
Tuesday, and the public will be allowed to pay its respects.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LONDON -- July 26, 1998 -- THEROUX-NAIPAUL-2, 7-26 --
V.S. Naipaul, the author of numerous books exploring to remarkable
effect themes like colonialism, exile and religion. Paul Theroux,
the author of almost three dozen novels and travel books, including
``The Great Railway Bazaar,'' has written a book, ``Sir Vidia's
Shadow: A Friendship Across Five Continents,'' to be published in a
few months, which describes his intense and complex relationship
with Naipaul. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) EAST SANDWICH, Mass. -- July 26, 1998 --
THEROUX-NAIPAUL-1, 7-26 -- Paul Theroux, the author of almost three
dozen novels and travel books, including ``The Great Railway
Bazaar,'' on the beach near his home in East Sandwich, Mass.
Theroux has written a book, ``Sir Vidia's Shadow: A Friendship
Across Five Continents,'' to be published in a few months, which
describes his intense and complex relationship with the man he says
taught him how to be a writer. ``He was always the one who said you
have to tell the truth,'' says Theroux. (Ed Quinn/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DRENICA, Yugoslavia -- July 26, 1998 -- YUGO-KOSOVO, 7-26
-- Three members of the Kosovo Liberation Army, which is mainly
comprised of ethnic Albanians fighting to secede from Serbia,
walking along the hills in Drenica, northwest of Pristina. Serbia,
the larger of the two republics that make up Yugoslavia, has
rescinded the autonomy once enjoyed by the province, 90 percent of
whose residents are ethnic Albanians. (Wade Goddard/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ISTANBUL, Turkey -- July 26, 1998 -- TURKEY-PALACE, 7-26
-- Alpay Pasinli, director of Istanbul's Archeological Museum, with
a Byzantine fresco unearthed near the newly discovered ruins just
outside the Topkapi palace walls . ``What we have found is most
probably the Great Palace,'' says Pasinli, who is overseeing the
excavation. ``We would like to have taken more time before
reporting this, but it was impossible to keep the secret.'' (Staton
R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PARAMUS, N.J. -- July 26, 1998 -- TOYS-ONLINE, 7-26 --
Joel Anderson, vice president of Toys ``R'' Us Direct, holding a
bow and arrow set from the Disney movie ``Mulan.'' Shoppers can now
buy just about any toy online, from the very hot Teletubbies doll
to products based on the animated film ``Mulan.'' ``People are more
strapped for time, and they are looking for new ways of shopping,''
says Anderson. (Frank C. Dougherty/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LOS ANGELES -- July 26, 1998 -- TV-COMEBACK-MEDIA, 7-26
-- Peter Roth, Fox's president of entertainment, plans to move the
network toward a 52-week development program, with three pilot
seasons. Currently, all the producing, writing and acting talent in
Hollywood is called to arms at once in a headlong dash toward the
May schedule announcements made to the advertising industry in New
York. ``It's a very dysfunctional system'' says Roth. (Kim
Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
