<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, July 28:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SHOOTING (Washington) _ Ledeall: Eulogies by members of
Congress, debate over new security in the Capitol, other
developments in the aftermath of the shooting. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of the president. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR-ASSESS (Washington) _ Linda Greenhouse, N.Y. Times
Supreme Court reporter, examines the legal issues involved in
issuing a subpoena for the president to testify before a grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUDGET (Washington) _ Sen. Livingston writes to
President Clinton asking him to get more involved in the budget
fight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SOCSEC (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ President Clinton conducts
another roundtable on Social Security, focused on private accounts
invested in the stock market. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   NADER-MUSEUM (Winsted, Conn.) _ Ralph Nader wants to open a
Museum of Tort Law in his hometown, complete with exibits on
Corvairs and Pintos. By Jonathan Rabinovitz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MILITARY (Beijing) _ A look at China's military and the
changes it is undergoing. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGNT-DISSIDENTS (Manila) _ Secretary of State Albright, in
the Philippines, criticizes Chinese and Burmese governments over
their dealings with dissidents. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-ELECT (Phnom Penh) _ Developments in the Cambodian
elections. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Dateline to kum) _ Developments in the Kosovo
conflict between Serbian forces and ethnic Albanian rebels.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-TRIBUNAL-RAPE (The Hague) _ A rape case before the Balkan
tribunal has drawn much attention from lawyers and women's and
human rights groups. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-COP-SHOT (New York) _ A parolee is arrested in the shooting
of a New York City policeman; questions are raised about why he was
free; the officer is in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   NY-COLLAPSE (New York) _ Things start returning to normal in
most of the Times Square area, where hundreds of people were kicked
out of their homes by the collapse of a consturction site
scaffolding last week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GTE-BELL-ATLANTIC (Undated) _ Bell Atlantic and GTE are
discussing a merger that would have a value of as much as $55
billion. A combination of the two would be the latest in a series
of huge mergers that are reshaping the telecommunications
landscape. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Flint, Mich.) _ Developments as both GM and the UAW
say they are nearing a settlement of the long strike. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CENDANT-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Developments as the troubled
company issues its earnings report.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-RE-LIFE (UNdated) _ Swiss Re buys Life Re for $1.8 billion
in cash. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ECON (Mexico City) _ As if low oil prices were not doing
enough economic damage, Mexico also has to contend with the impact
of the Asian crisis. In the latest example of Asian fallout,
Mexico's largest steel producer, Altos Hornos de Mexico, is cutting
3,000 of its 20,000 jobs. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-SANYO (Tokyo) _ Sanyo, which is trying to emerge from the
shadows cast by bigger competitors like Sony and Matsushita,
acquires access to advanced semiconductor technology from IBM and
will use it in consumer electronics. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: The Dow Jones
Industrial Average was up 11 points at 2:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs''; details to come.
</P>
