<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERKELEY CHURCH WANTS CITY TO UNLOAD ITS STOCKS IN GUNMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VENISE WAGNER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Members of a Roman Catholic Church
congregation here are urging the city of Berkeley to divest its
holdings in companies that manufacture firearms or ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day we see the headlines,'' said Paula Hollowell-Dhar, a
member of the Newman Hall Holy Spirit parish. ``We've seen too much
violence, and our leaders, Congress, haven't done an effective job
of limiting the flow of weapons in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign organized by the church's Social Justice
Committee, Hollowell-Dhar is gathering names for a petition asking
the Berkeley City Council to research its investments and divest
from companies dealing in guns or ammo.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 church members signed the petition Sunday during a
meeting immediately following Mass. Hollowell-Dhar and Frank
Lucido, a board member of the Physicians for Social Responsibility,
gave a presentation at the meeting on gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to do something more effective to halt the flow of
weapons in our society,'' Hollowell-Dhar said. ``Gun manufacturers
have resisted measures to have more quality control. In our
society, prescription drugs, even children's pajamas, are
regulated. Weapons are not in any way regulated. We feel that
Congress is too beholden to the National Rifle Association.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Michael McGarry, pastor at Newman Parish, said it was
only coincidental that the petition drive followed the incident at
the U.S. Capitol Friday in which two guards tried to stop a gunman
from entering the building. The U.S. Capitol police officers were
shot dead and the gunman and a tourist were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign began more as an educational effort, McGarry said,
to raise awareness of social issues.
</P>
<P>
   The church's Social Justice Committee focuses on clear weapons,
gun violence and welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are quite surprised how eagerly and positively people have
responded,'' McGarry said, adding that the church may now take the
campaign to another level and encourage other churches and
religious centers to join in.
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley Mayor Shirley Dean said she would support the church's
proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
