<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-CHANGE-HOMOSEX     07-27 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-CHANGE-HOMOSEXUALS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 SHOULD CHURCHES `CHANGE' HOMOSEXUALS, OR MAKE THEM WHOLE?
 (Commentary)   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In recent weeks, newspaper ads across the country have featured
gay men and lesbian women proclaiming, ``You can change. I'm living
proof.''
 &HT;    The advertisements, sponsored by a variety of conservative
Christian organizations, appeared in the wake of remarks made by
football star Reggie White and Sen. Trent Lott (R-Miss.). Both men
-- themselves conservative Christians -- called homosexuality a sin
in terms offensive to many Americans.
 &HT;    The ads liken homosexuality to a sickness -- if not a sin -- and
highlight the religious right's leading issue in the upcoming
elections: moral ``degeneracy'' as evidenced by gay rights.
 &HT;    Can homosexuals change? The political debate -- fuelled by moral
and religious convictions -- regarding homosexuality centers on the
question whether the disposition issues from nature or nurture.
 &HT;    If gay men and lesbian women can change, then homosexuality must
be an environmental condition (usually one involving moral choice)
and can be cured. If they can not, then homosexuality might very
well be biologically inherited -- like skin color or gender -- and
demands legal protection against discrimination.
 &HT;    The religious right insists homosexuality is a product of
environment; the pro-gay and lesbian lobby insists it is
biological. One says it is inherently sinful; the other says it is
no more sinful than being African American or female.
 &HT;    Attempting to control the political damage caused by Lott's
remarks, Republican Party chairperson Jim Nicholson commented, ``I
don't know that we fully understand very much about the sources of
homosexuality or if there is a way to alter that. I've talked to
people in both the scientific and theological communities, and they
don't seem to be very clear about it.''
 &HT;    Not just politicians and theologians, Jim. Most Americans seem
confused whether homosexuality is a sexual preference or sexual
orientation.
 &HT;    Over the years, I've known a few people who changed. Often, they
engaged in homosexual behavior out of curiosity or as a result of a
particular situation such as abuse by a member of the opposite sex.
Through therapy or religious conversion, they became straight and
went on to live successfully as heterosexual mates and parents. For
these people, Christian healing ministries -- such as Exodus
International -- work.
 &HT;    But I've known many more people who could not change although
they struggled for years to do so. One friend spent countless hours
trying to be ``talked out'' of his desires by his Christian
classmates and a Baptist pastor; another repeatedly committed
himself to celibacy; another wrestled with his call to ministry;
yet another shot himself during his freshman year at college.
 &HT;    They would have changed if they could have. Anxious and afraid,
none ``wanted'' to be gay and each availed himself to treatment
options offered through churches. However, the treatments sickened
their spirits by increasing guilt, self-doubt, or self-hatred. Only
through accepting themselves as homosexuals did these men finally
find healing. It was not a matter of choice, it was a matter of
being.
 &HT;    I do not know the latest scientific research on sexuality.
Common sense and personal observation, however, point to the
logical conclusion that there is no single source for sexual
orientation. Sexuality is an intimately complex matter and sources
of sexual identity and expressions are multiple -- emerging from
both experience and biology. Sexuality is not simply a moral choice
or genetic predisposition. This is about human love and longing. It
is not the purview of politicians; this is the realm of poets.
 &HT;    So, where should our churches and synagogues stand in relation
to human sexuality? Religion should not be in the business of
making people straight; religion should make people whole.
 &HT;    Faith communities should mend sexual brokenness in whatever form
it takes. The heterosexual community is riddled with abuse,
pornography, addiction and promiscuity. From the White House to
Madison Avenue, our culture is mired in sexual sickness promoted --
in large part -- by greedy, ratings-hungry heterosexuals.
 &HT;    My homosexual neighbors living a faithful family life do not
worry me. The contempt displayed for the beauty and intimacy of
sexuality in the movies, television, and advertising does.
Homosexuals do not need to change. America does.
 &HT;    In the midst of this sickness, churches must promote sexual
wholeness. Wholeness means that homosexuals must be who God made
them to be; heterosexuals must be who God made them to be.
Wholeness means expressing our sexual selves with maturity,
integrity, compassion, mutuality, and commitment. Gay, straight, or
in-between, we all can and should strive for God's wholeness in our
lives and relationships.
 &HT;    Curing our sex-sick culture is not a political crusade -- nor a
call for Victorian prudery. Rather, it is the work of people
seeking wholeness in the context of faith and modelling a better
way to be human for the sake of our children.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
