A4678 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-CHILDRENS-REVIEW     07-27 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CHILDRENS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS, AND PARENTS, CAN READ THESE WACKY TALES FOR FUN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JANE P. MARSHALL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too hot for a lemonade stand. Too late to get swimsuit skinny.
Too impatient to read ``Ulysses,'' last week named the best
English-language book of the century.
</P>
<P>
   How about a good story?
</P>
<P>
   Even better, a silly story for the whole family. Read it aloud.
Laugh together. Talk about the pictures. But don't think too much.
It's too hot.
</P>
<P>
   These good-time picture books are some of the most fun stories
of summer:
</P>
<P>
   Put two talents like Audrey Wood and Mark Teague together and
the results are better than anything Disney ever dreamed of ``Sweet
Dream Pie'' (Blue Sky, $15.95) is crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Ma and Pa Brindle have a secret. It's Ma's pie. Eat some and
dream. It's the pie that is sweet, not the dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Pa wants pie. Ma says, ``Last time I made that pie you ate too
much.'' She agrees to get the special pan and bowl out of the attic
and make pie. ``But if things get out of hand, don't blame me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, things get out of hand. The huge pie affects the
whole neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Wood's stories always twist and turn in fanciful ways. Teague's
art is as bold and sweet as Ma's pie. Together they can fill a
summer evening with giggles.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Yucka Drucka Droni'' (Scholastic, $15.95) is a tongue
twister of a story that must be read aloud to be appreciated. If no
one is around, read it aloud to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Even the book-jacket note on the creators of the book is silly:
``In search of exotic places, Vladimir Radunsky, the great-grandson
of Humpty-Dumpty, and his wife and constant traveling companion,
Eugenia (the famous ventriloquist), found themselves in Brooklyn,
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The story _ if it can be called a story _ is about brothers
Yucka, Yucka-Drucka and Yucka-Drucka-Droni. They meet three sisters
and get married. That is the entire plot.
</P>
<P>
   The art is a creative marvel and establishes the outrageous
context for the brothers and their tale. It's all more fun than a
swimming hole near the hayfield.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rod Clement wrote and drew ``Grandpa's Teeth'' (HarperCollins,
$14.95), a mystery that doesn't threaten Joan Lowery Nixon or P.D.
James but does offer a rollicking good time and no red herrings.
</P>
<P>
   Grandpa discovers his teeth have been stolen. A detective
investigates, a TV show called ``Unsolved Crimes'' calls, and all
the townsfolk grin (so their own teeth will show and prove their
innocence).
</P>
<P>
   No robber is found, but the townspeople get so tired of smiling
that they pitch in to buy new teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Clement's drawings are as wacky as his story.
</P>
<P>
   Is the culprit ever found? Well, kinda. And that's all I'm
saying.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Old Woman and the Wave`` (DK Ink, $15.95), written and
illustrated by Shelley Jackson, is a whimsical story with a very
serious message. An old woman has lived in her cottage her whole
life. Hovering over the house is a wave.
</P>
<P>
   The wave loves her, but the old woman fears the wave. The wave
offers fish; the old woman throws them back. The wave offers her
beautiful colors; the old woman scoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The story is an existential metaphor. At last, the old woman
ventures to the top of the wave. The experience opens her eyes and
liberates her from her fears. The wave is not an end but a
beginning. It is not a danger but an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lesson, the story entertains and enthralls. Jackson
also tells the story through her art _ collages created from paint
and bits of maps, words and musical notes, all calculated to give
clues to the story and move it along.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Zelda and Ivy'' (Candlewick, $15.99), fox sisters, are a
worthy match for George and Martha, hippo friends. The book is
three short stories involving Zelda, the bossy older sister, and
Ivy, the more vulnerable little sister. They take turns being the
wise sister.
</P>
<P>
   Siblings will recognize their bond, both mischievous and loving.
Author and illustrator Laura McGee Kvasnosky knows about sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tina loved chocolate more than anything in the world.'' What a
beginning for a picture book. Maybe the kids can relate to the
topic. Probably the adult reading the story to the kids can.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Chocolatina'' (BridgeWater, $15.95), by Erik Kraft, is
Tina's nickname. The bad guy in this story is Mrs. Ferdman, the
health teacher, who insists on teaching the kids about good food by
using the phrase ``you are what you eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Chocolatina thinks this isn't a bad idea. One morning she
awakens to find she is chocolate. The antics are fun, the story
silly and the moral _ yes, there is a bit of one _ not
heavy-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Brunkus' illustrations are lively and full of character.
Pass the fudge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
