<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-DRUGS-BOS &LR;      07-27 1593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-DRUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE, LUCK COMBINE FOR WHAT MAY BE AN AIDS DRUG
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANDREW CAFFREY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a typically hot, muggy day in September 1987 when Arnold
Arboretum botanist John Burley slogged through the swampy forest of
the Malaysian state of Sarawak in northern Borneo, seeking nature's
medicines for killer diseases.
</P>
<P>
   On assignment for the National Cancer Institute, Burley's team
was randomly cutting specimens, and at first he almost passed by an
ordinary-looking tree, recognizing it was from a family of plants
that had been extensively collected. ``I almost didn't collect
it,'' Burley recalled recently. ``I thought it was unlikely to be
of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the fates that guide the hands of science.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But for Burley's chance cutting, researchers might never have
stumbled upon a substance that could become an important weapon
against AIDS. The 2 pounds of twigs, leaves, bark, and branches
that Burley collected from Calophyllum lanigerum contain the
substance calanolide A, which in the test tube has proved 100
percent effective in killing the mutant HIV viruses that develop a
resistance to the current pharmaceutical wonders known as triple
drug cocktails. Whether calanolide A's AIDS-fighting properties can
work in humans, of course, remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of laboratory trials _ in which the drug's
toxicity to humans is determined _ has just been successfully
completed. Sometime in the next few weeks, the pharmaceutical firm
MediChem Research Inc., in a joint venture with the Sarawak
government, will begin trials of calanolide A with HIV-infected
patients. If, as company officials believe, the initial results are
positive, then MediChem will test calanolide A in the popular drug
cocktails that have extended the lives of HIV-infected patients.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the discovery of calanolide A and Calophyllum
lanigerum, and of another, closely related tree that seems to be
producing an equally successful drug, is one of scientific
sleuthing and serendipity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole system is almost a game of chance,'' says Dr. Gordon
Cragg, who oversees the tropical plant initiative for the National
Cancer Institute's Natural Products branch. ``And you win some, and
you lose some.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although it might seem natural now, the idea to systematically
mine Mother Nature for new drugs was hardly a widely accepted
practice in the 1980s. In fact, the National Cancer Institute had
all but given up a once-ambitious initiative to scour the globe
looking for natural sources of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But under the leadership of Drs. Michael Boyd and Cragg, the
institute revived the pursuit, and since 1986 has spent about $7
million trooping through tropical forests and collecting more than
50,000 samples. Separate initiatives by the institute are combing
through other environments, such as the marine world, looking for
natural pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   With so little known about the chemical promise of so many
plants and animals, researchers purposefully try to make their
collections as random as possible so as not to exclude plants that
seem unexceptional at first blush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wandering around in a huge haystack equivalent, looking
for a needle,'' Burley explains, ``but not even knowing if there is
a needle to be found.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Harvesting cuttings from tropical rain forests requires a
meticulous two-step process: first, botanists collect about 2
pounds of bark, branches, leaves, stems, petals; then they take a
separate, larger cutting, a ``voucher specimen,'' preferably when
it has fruit or flowers, for mounting on a 12- by 17-inch sheet.
Both samples are then labeled in great detail, and cross-referenced
to each other.
</P>
<P>
   During this expedition, Burley estimates, he collected more than
500 samples of some 300 plant species. The bulk samples were
shipped back to the institute's lab for testing; the voucher
specimens, to the Harvard University Herbaria.
</P>
<P>
   By the standards of the rain forest, the version of Calophyllum
lanigerum that Burley almost didn't cut was a runt: a mere 25 feet,
and skinny to boot.
</P>
<P>
   But luck really was with Burley that day: The tree normally
grows in dry, rocky, elevated terrain, but Burley chanced upon one
in a swamp _ a fact that complicated matters later, when scientists
were in desperate search for more of the trees.
</P>
<P>
   After Burley bagged and labeled the requisite cuttings,
lanigerum was shipped off with dozens of other species to
Frederick, Md., where institute researchers stored the whole lot in
walk-in freezers until they could be tested.
</P>
<P>
   When researchers tested the lanigerum for its anti-cancer
properties, the results were discouraging. There were none. Then,
three years after the lanigerum was collected, researchers screened
the lanigerum extract for its AIDS-fighting potential.
</P>
<P>
   The results were positive and encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   With some determination, they telephoned the principal
investigator of the Southeast Asia expedition, Djaja Dole Soejarta,
a biologist at the University of Illinois at Chicago, and suggested
his team obtain more samples of this ``interesting'' compound.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Burley was busy with a new project in Indonesia, so Soejarta
engaged another botanist, who teamed up with the same Dyak
tribesmen who assisted Burley three years earlier, and they led him
to the location of the lanigerum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The tree was gone. Instead, the team found themselves looking
at a stump where the tree once stood _ suggesting that a local
villager had cut it down for firewood. But no bother. Soejarta's
botanist saw other trees nearby that resembled lanigerum, made the
logical assumption they would have the same chemical compounds and
pharmaceutical potential as their cousin, and shipped off the
cuttings to the institute for what he thought would be easy
confirmation. The result was negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly put my back against the wall,'' Soejarta
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Eeager to be in on the Next Big Thing in AIDS research, but also
driven by a sense of responsibility because he was in charge of the
expedition, Soejarta contacted Harvard biologist and Arnold
Arboretum curator Peter Stevens. Stevens is not only the world's
foremost expert on the Calophyllum tree, he is the world's only
expert. Soejarta asked Stevens to take a look at the original
cutting taken by Burley to see if they had correctly identified it.
Stevens scrutinized the distinct leaf of the lanigerum.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mistaking the tiny, finely-grained clusters of veins
that shoot off from the stem ``like grooving on an old record,''
Stevens said. Not only did he know which tree it was, but he even
knew where to find another: in downtown Singapore, in the city's
botanical gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I treated it rather prosaically,'' Stevens says of the
identification that had researchers on edge from Maryland to
Malaysia. ``If I hadn't spent 10 years on the group, it would have
been hell on everyone. There wouldn't be anyone else who would
know. So it's lucky I exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Soejarta himself traveled to Sarawak in March 1992,
saw the by-now rotting stump, and searched the forests in vain for
another lanigerum. Along the way, he too kept spotting other
Calophyllum species, and, refusing to go home empty-handed, began
to systematically sample those trees, too, again on the assumption
that they probably contained the same compound that so successfully
fought the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This time, Soejarta's hunch was right. Of the samples of six
different Calophyllum trees he sent back to the National Cancer
Institute, one, a variety called teysmannii, also scored the same
success in the AIDS screen as its cousin. Researchers labeled the
extract from the second tree calanolide B. MediChem, the drug
company, is just beginning trials in healthy humans to test its
toxicity.
</P>
<P>
   There are important differences between calanolide A and B that
help form one of the morals of this story, at least for the
botanists involved in the project.
</P>
<P>
   Though calanolide A appears to be the more powerful of the two
compounds, its potency when culled from lanigerum tree to lanigerum
tree is also much more erratic, making it difficult to harvest
large quantities of it from its natural source. MediChem has
perfected a synthetic reproduction of calanolide A, which means the
company doesn't need the trees anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Teysmannii, on the other hand, consistently produces calanolide
B from tree to tree, and in large quantities, making the trees a
valuable resource.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the potential medical breakthroughs, the
botanists see another benefit of their discovery: the possibility
that the trees' potential will convince governments such as
Malaysia's to stop logging their fast-disappearing rain forests.
The state of Sarawak, for example, will receive royalties and
income from the sales of calanolide A and the farming of teysmannii
trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today it happens to be AIDS and Calophyllum, but tomorrow it
could be something else, and we have to learn how to manage a
tropical rain forest sustainably,'' says the Arboretum's John
Burley. ``Use it, rather than lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the initial cutting of Calophyllum _ which is Latin
for beautiful leaf _ is on exhibit at the Hunnewell Building of the
Arboretum, as its scientists await word on the success of one of of
their more unusual endeavors into nature's drugstore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew Caffrey is a freelance journalist, and a political
analyst for WBUR-FM.)
</P>
</TEXT>
