<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4796 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSTA-RICA-ART-HNS &LR;      07-27 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTA-RICA-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVE VOLCANO LURES ADVENTURESOME TO COAST RICA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT photo service) 
(Eds.: An accent mark is needed over o in Tabacon; a tilde is
needed over n in Cano.) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORTUNA, Costa Rica _ Ignorance is bliss.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly when you're being kneaded by a strong-fingered
woman in the middle of paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Just a month earlier, the masseuses _ and 400 of their neighbors
and clients _ were evacuated when the volcano El Arenal began
spewing burning ash, rocks and gases during a major eruption.
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rica's most active volcano belched lethally for nearly
seven hours in early May, setting off 23 avalanches and sending
tourists and residents scurrying from one of the country's most
popular tourist areas.
</P>
<P>
   The slides stopped less than a mile from the massage tables at
Tabacon Resort, a complex featuring a series of lushly landscaped
hot pools, two bars and a restaurant. It was the most intense
volcanic episodes for the area in the past five years, and the
area's residents remained on alert for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Dormant since about A.D. 1500, Arenal Volcano rumbled back to
life on July 29, 1968. Seventy-eight people died, more than 40,000
cattle were killed and two villages were lost in several huge
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Arenal has become one of Central America's greatest
tourist draws. Its almost daily eruptions lure tourists to tiny
hotels and towns scattered around the 5,373-foot mountain's base.
Many daytrippers make the drive from San Jose, which is about 80
steep-and-looping miles southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Fortuna and the nearby Arenal Volcano National Park,
which opened in 1995, are rewarded with an exotic experience. The
relentless rumbling of the volcano, the calls of strange birds and
the guttural language of howler monkeys offer a fascinating
symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking around the skirt of the volcano is a favorite activity.
Rangers at the national park can offer suggestions for day hikes
and often lead evening tours that include dramatic views of the
lava flow. While there are boastful tales of reaching the volcano's
rim, it would be foolhardy to attempt this, as Arenal's eruptions
are lethal, frequent and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Several guide companies in the area offer horseback tours into
the forested park, which gets nearly 200 inches of rain each year.
Another popular activity is whitewater rafting.
</P>
<P>
   But with its frequent eruptions, Arenal is king of the hill for
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Most days, thick white clouds surround the tip of Arenal's
perfect cone. You'll hear a grumble and then see puffs of black
smoke push through the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   At night, you may be rewarded with clear skies, and then Arenal
becomes a feast for the eyes. Looking like liquid lightening bolts,
rivers of glowing lava inch their way down the mountain.
Mesmerized, you watch until the clouds dramatically draw the
curtain on Arenal again.
</P>
<P>
   For just a couple of bucks, you can bathe in volcano-warmed
pools located throughout the area.
</P>
<P>
   For a few dollars more, you can go deluxe at the Tabacon Resort
and its sister property, the recently opened 42-room Tabacon Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   The lodge's rooms have patios and balconies that put the volcano
centerstage. Days here are relaxing and peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   At the resort, you can splash around a large hot pool with
swim-up bar, sit under a misty waterfall, or share a romantic
moment in a secluded pond. Masseuses will rub your cares away and
then paint your face with thick coats of warm mud. Complete the
pampering with a manicure or pedicure. (But don't expect high tech,
and don't look too closely at the manicurist's tools.)
</P>
<P>
   The hot pools, fed by the volcano-heated Tabacon River, can vary
from 80 degrees to about 102 degrees. Chilly pools of water are
available, too. Best of all, the resort is open late into the
evening, providing the opportunity for a romantic, moonlit dip.
</P>
<P>
   The lodge's large rooms are cheerfully decorated and are
equipped with color televisions broadcasting CNN and other
English-language channels. The baths feature oversized showers and
generous vanities.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel doesn't officially open until later this year, but
word is out and the lodge was very full in early July. The hot
springs resort was built 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe the resort and lodge are too close to Arenal.
Volcano expert Jorge Barquero told the Tico Times, a local
English-language paper, last month that the resort should never
have been built.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volcano has repeatedly shown us that it is the one that
rules in that area, and it seems foolish to ignore it.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper also reported that if Arenal were to have eruptions
similar to ones it had in 1968 and 1975, hot lava could reach the
resort in just three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If that's too close for comfort, there are many lodges and
hotels that provide more distant but no less dramatic views of the
volcano. One inviting place to consider is Hotel La Garza, near the
small village of Platanar.
</P>
<P>
   This working dairy and cattle ranch also encompasses a primary
rain forest. Cooled by ceiling fans and large screened windows and
featuring distressingly thin walls, the bungalows look across the
Platanar River to Arenal.
</P>
<P>
   Guests can watch the cows be milked, explore the ranch on
walking trails or simply lounge in the hotel's pretty pool. The
hotel also can arrange balloon rides, cave tours and birding boat
rides that take in the Cano Negro National Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
<P>
   One of the favorite outings at La Garza is a horseback ride
through the rain forest. To reach the forest, riders must cross
through the ranch's many agricultural fields where crops such as
sugar cane grow taller than the horses.
</P>
<P>
   You end your days at La Garza on a hammock on the balcony of
your bungalow, watching Arenal's flows glow safely and peacefully
in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
