<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CHARLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES SEEKS TO MAKE PARKER BOWLES ACCEPTABLE TO BRITISH PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Prince Charles has embarked on an active campaign to
bring his longtime friend, Camilla Parker Bowles, into the British
royal circle as the first step toward marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year after Princess Diana's death in a car crash, it
has been disclosed that Parker Bowles will host a gala party in
honor of Charles's 50th birthday Nov. 14 and that his and Diana's
sons, Princes William and Harry, will come as ``honored guests.''
This will be the first royal occasion at which the once-detested
``other woman'' will have played a role.
</P>
<P>
   Charles, the controversial heir to Britain's throne, received
favorable publicity last month after arranging a meeting for the
first time between Parker Bowles and 16-year-old William. The two
were said to have spent a ``cordial'' hour together with Charles
present, and the meeting was disclosed only after it was deemed
satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   Enmity toward her by Diana's sons would obviously be an enormous
personal and political obstacle to marriage. Charles's strategy is
to demonstrate to his future subjects that the boys don't oppose
Parker Bowles and don't blame her for their parents' divorce,
according to some royal watchers.
</P>
<P>
   They say Charles and his advisers are confident that she is
gradually becoming more acceptable to the British public as his
future spouse, although probably never as queen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is testing the waters for an eventual morganatic marriage
such as has occurred in many royal families but never before in the
British royal family,'' according to Tony Ridley, author of several
books on European royalty.
</P>
<P>
   In a morganatic marriage, the wife of a crowned head is not
recognized as having royal rank and any offspring of the couple are
not regarded as eligible to succeed to the throne. In any case, it
is unlikely that Camilla, who is 52, would have children by
Charles.
</P>
<P>
   The prince has been working hard since Diana's death last Aug.
31 to repair his battered image by showing himself more in public
and by working earnestly at charity and environmental projects. The
highly publicized storm surrounding his marriage turned Diana into
a national heroine, despite admitted adultery on both sides, and
even seemed for a while to imperil the monarchy's survival.
</P>
<P>
   Popular demands that he step aside in favor of William when
Queen Elizabeth II dies have now subsided. But Ridley said that
Charles ``feels strongly that regularizing his relationship with
Camilla is important for the ongoing stability of the throne.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridley added: ``He believes that in a few years' time, as
memories of Diana grow less vivid, he and Camilla will be able to
marry without causing serious offense to popular sensibilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
