<HEADLINE>
MAKING HOMEWORK FUN WITH THE RIGHT SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;    (To publish this ``separate buy'' article it must be purchased
-- the rate is not prohibitive -- from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax, 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (--Mexico, Central America, South America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los
Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax, 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    (----- Please call or fax for a price quote.)
 By ANN ORR  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Transform your child's study sessions _ with the help of a
computer, CD-ROMs and the Internet.
 &HT;    The latest techno-tools can captivate reluctant students, bring
ordinary text to three-dimensional life and condense a bookshelf's
worth of reference guides into a single disk.
 &HT;    Is your son struggling with square roots? There's new and
exciting software _ see Algebra Smart _ that takes the drudgery out
of drill and practice and can be programmed to focus on square
roots, fractions or whatever else makes up this week's lesson plan.
 &HT;    Your daughter's studying Africa? With the click of a mouse _ see
Microsoft Encarta Virtual Globe _ she can hear the music of Rwanda,
see a sweeping 360-degree panoramic map, even access a Website that
details the war between the Tutsi and Hutu peoples.
 &HT;    Below are recommendations on the best and most interesting study
aids and reference tools _ each of which has been approved by a
panel of parent and child testers. You'll need a CD-ROM drive for
all of the programs mentioned, and an Internet connection to visit
the Websites.
 READING AND LANGUAGE ARTS  
 &HT;    Reading Blaster: Ages 6-9. For reading-skills practice, you
can't go wrong with this space-age game show that teaches
comprehension, vocabulary, spelling and phonics through seven
different reading games and three printable storybooks. In Word
Zapper, youngsters dodge falling meteors as they scramble to build
words based on phonics sounds and spelling rules. In Get-a-Clue,
children read for meaning as they use their deductive reasoning to
solve mysteries. More than 2,000 words are presented, and the
program features nine levels of difficulty.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. Knowledge Adventure, $30, ages 6 to 9.
 &HT;    Major League Reading. Sports fans can improve their reading
comprehension, spelling and vocabulary skills when they play this
simulated baseball game. Kids control the plays by reading
curriculum-based articles and answering questions that test their
comprehension.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. Sanctuary Woods, $29.95, ages 8 to 12.
 &HT;    Claris Works for Kids. While older kids can handle the adult
version of Claris Works, elementary-age children will enjoy hearing
their stories read aloud, learning about fractions by making their
own pie charts and creating multimedia book reports and
presentations with sounds and movie clips.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. Claris Corp., $49, ages 5-11.
 MATH  
 &HT;    Algebra Smart. This entertaining game makes studying algebra fun
_ no kidding! More than a hundred video lessons and 500 practice
problems make up the core of the program, but the zip comes from
the software's zany humor. In The Algebra Games, kids compete
against a team of math nerds, complete with thick specs and pocket
protectors.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. The Princeton Review, $30, ages 14 and up.
 &HT;    Treasure MathStorm! In an arcadelike format, children sharpen
their math and problem-solving skills. Their task is to climb a
snowy mountain _ capturing elves, answering math problems and
testing their knowledge of time and money along the way. The
software automatically adjusts in difficulty, or grown-ups can set
specific levels. Our testers couldn't get enough of this one!
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. Learning Company, $29.95, ages 5 to 9.
 &HT;    Geometry Blaster. Kids outsmart the evil Geometrons by
completing activities dealing with perimeter, area and volume,
proofs and theorems, ratios and proportion _ a full year's worth of
curriculum. Tutorials, extensive record-keeping and three levels of
difficulty make this an excellent choice. A ninth-grade math
teacher who tested this program liked it so much he promptly
ordered one himself.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. Knowledge Adventure, $35, ages 12 and up.
 &HT;    Mighty Math Calculating Crew. Third-to-sixth-grade math is the
focus of this excellent program. Superheroes such as Wanda Wavelet
use on-screen objects to teach addition, subtraction,
multiplication, estimation and geometry. There's a Superhero
Superstore where kids practice money skills and a 3D lab where they
classify two- and three-dimensional figures. The program tracks
each child's progress and automatically adjusts in difficulty.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. Edmark, $39, ages 8 to 12.
 SCIENCE  
 &HT;    The Universe According to Virgil Reality. Virgil Reality, an
offbeat professor, uses videos, songs, activities and projects to
teach dozens of science concepts, including the principles of
flight, animal behavior, magnetism and chemistry. Kids can witness
the Hindenburg's demise, view actual NASA footage and assemble a
working model of a compound microscope. Also includes directions
for hundreds of offscreen activities, including home experiments,
games, dioramas and paper airplanes.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows. 7th Level, Inc., $39.99, ages 8-14.
 &HT;    Eyewitness Encyclopedia of Science 2.0. This resource delves
deep into physics, chemistry, math and life sciences. Kids can
explore rotating models, see the inner workings of cells, meet
scientists from the past and present and test their knowledge with
the Quiz Master game.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. DK Multimedia, $39.95, ages 10 and up.
 GEOGRAPHY  
 &HT;    Rescue Geo I. Learning about U.S. geography has never been more
fun. Children are challenged with the task of repairing a computer
infected with pesky bugs and viruses. Kids turn to maps and other
visual aids to answer geography questions and save the day. The
software features more than 600 questions and more than 1,400 maps,
charts and photos.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. Houghton Mifflin, $59.94, 8 to 12.
 &HT;    Microsoft Encarta Virtual Globe 1998 Edition. A must-have for
any home software library, this version features 19 map styles, 1.2
million place names and 500 new geography articles. Kids can ride
along on spectacular 3-D fly-throughs over the Andes or the Grand
Canyon and zoom in on street-level maps of 50 world cities. Three
thousand color images and 4,000 sound and music clips add to the
memorable experience. This excellent reference tool is so slick and
entertaining parents and kids will return to it often.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows 95. Microsoft, $54.95, ages 10 and up.
 MULTI-SUBJECT  
 &HT;    Grolier's CornerStone Home. Here's an impressive set of
programs, perfect for concentrating on just those math and
language-arts skills that give a youngster the most trouble. This
12-volume series is grouped by subject and grade level. For
instance, there's one CD that focuses on third and fourth-grade
spelling and capitalization. Another CD helps seventh- and
eighth-graders practice their fractions and percents. Each program
presents lessons, quizzes, instant feedback and progress reports.
Success is rewarded with game time in a multimedia arcade. This is
serious skills practice in a fun package.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. SkillsBank Corporation (The Learning
Company), $49.95 per grade level and subject area _ English or
math, ages 7 to 13.
 REFERENCE SHELF  
 &HT;    Microsoft Encarta 98 Encyclopedia Deluxe. This graphics-rich,
two-CD set offers more than 30,000 in-depth articles, 14,000 photos
and illustrations, 150 videos and 2,300 sound clips. Special
features include a fully integrated dictionary, 100 guided tours,
Internet links and free monthly online updates.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. Microsoft, $54.95, ages 8 and up.
 &HT;    The World Book 1998 Multimedia Encyclopedia Deluxe Edition. This
two-CD set is a full-featured, well-designed encyclopedia with
17,000 World Book articles, a 225,000-word dictionary, hundreds of
videos and thousands of pictures. This software is easy to use, has
great content depth and includes handy tools such as on-screen
sticky notes and thousands of quick-links to the Internet.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows. IBM, $69.95, ages 9 and up.
 &HT;    Grolier Multimedia Encyclopedia 1998. Another excellent
reference, this features 35,000 articles, plus numerous videos and
animations. There's also an interactive atlas, timelines, 15 guided
tours and links to thousands of carefully chosen related Websites.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows/Mac. Grolier Interactive, $59.99, ages 9 and up.
 &HT;    Microsoft Bookshelf 98 Edition. No student should be without
this impressive set of 10 comprehensive reference guides on just
one disk. The software features the American Heritage Dictionary
(3rd edition), Roget's Thesaurus, The World Almanac and Book of
Facts 1997, the Columbia Dictionary of Quotations and a zip code
and post office directory. Also included: The Microsoft Bookshelf
Internet Directory, Encarta 98 Desk Encyclopedia and Encarta 98
Desk World Atlas.
 &HT;    Runs on: Windows/Mac. Microsoft, $54.95, ages 8 and up.
 &HT;    Ultimate Children's Encyclopedia. Designed especially for
7-to-12-year-olds, this encyclopedia takes a more playful approach
than those listed above. Content includes 28,000-plus easy-to-read,
concise articles, plus numerous videos, slide shows, animations and
maps.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows. Learning Company, $29.95, ages 7 to 12.
 &HT;    Compton's Interactive Encyclopedia 1998. An amazing 38,000
articles are presented in this encyclopedia, along with 15,000
photos. Other outstanding features include extensive search
capabilities, hours of sound and music, links to hundreds of
Websites and easy-to-use copy, paste and print functions.
 &HT;    Runs on Windows. Compton's New Media, $44.95, ages 10 and up.
 c.1997 Working Mother  
