<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PRISON-HEAT-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE BEHIND BARS PROVES TO BE HELLISH IN SIZZLING TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT photo service) 
 
By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ On a typical day inside Wynne prison, the
cacophony of inmates shouting, hooting and clanging on the cell
bars drowns out most attempts at conversation.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, around 3:30 p.m., the noise-making fades.
</P>
<P>
   It's the hottest part of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just too hot to be communicating,'' said Orlando
Rodriguez, grinning and running a hand across his shaved head, a
concession to the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, a convicted arsonist from Bay City in southeast
Texas, has pulled the mattress off his bunk and rolled it into a
cushion on the concrete floor. There, he sits in his underwear,
using his bare bunk as a table for chess playing. A clock radio and
fan dangle on shoelaces from the unoccupied upper bunk, which also
serves as a shelf.
</P>
<P>
   He's doing time in one of the hottest spots _ the third floor of
administrative segregation, where he's locked in his solitary cell
22 hours a day. A nearly two-story wall of windows on the west side
magnifies the heat of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some officer was talking the other day that it got up to 130
degrees, but I don't believe it,'' said the surprisingly upbeat
Rodriguez. His guess is it was 120, tops.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of the prison _ a major portion of which was
built in the 1950s _ a steady but warm breeze is blowing from
wall-mounted fans. Warden Michael Wilson has installed 20 new fans
in some cell blocks in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to add 30 more.
</P>
<P>
   As Texas bakes under near-record temperatures, prison life is
even more hellish than normal. Most state prisons have no air
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   The heat is suspected in the deaths of two inmates so far, one
in May, the other in June, said Dr. Lannette C. Linthicum, the
prison system's health services director.
</P>
<P>
   And late last week, said Linthicum, one inmate was hospitalized
in Tyler for heat stroke, and two others were hospitalized _ in
Abilene and Crosbyton _ with heat-related illnesses. Other
prisoners across the state have been treated, but not hospitalized,
for heat-related illnesses as well.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the cell blocks, the weather is a factor not just for
the 143,000 felons behind bars, but also for the 26,622 state
prison guards who work in the same sweltering areas.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no employees have suffered serious health problems from
the heat, although some prisons have reported isolated incidents of
guards who have become dizzy or even fainted.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Koenig, risk manager for the Texas Department of Criminal
Justice, said the agency has averaged 30 heat-related problems a
month among employees and felons, with most complaining of cramps,
headaches and nausea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with the system 13 years,'' Koenig said, ``and this
has been the most extreme heat we've experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Prisons across Texas have reported indoor temperatures ranging
from 100 to 125 degrees, Koenig said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Wynne Farm Unit, one of the oldest prisons in the
state, the 2,500 felons are sweating out their time behind bars
staying cool the only way they know how _ stripped to their boxer
shorts and barefoot, wet towels draped across their heads, with a
small plastic fan blowing. The fans are available to those who
shell out the $7.95 in the prison commissary.
</P>
<P>
   Warden Wilson, who is awaiting 30 more fans for the cell blocks
of Wynne, said the solitary confinement areas are top priority for
fan placement, because those inmates are in their cells for all but
two or three hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates in the general population, who are assigned to jobs or
who attend school, have more opportunities to escape the heat
buildup in the 5-by-9-foot cells, Wilson said. Classrooms are
air-conditioned.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the prison cell blocks, correctional officer Sam Riggs
is perched in a guard tower with no air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:30 p.m., the thermometer registers 100 degrees in the
shade. But then, the reading doesn't go any higher than 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just rather be outside,'' Riggs said, explaining why he
doesn't mind his eight-hour shifts at a job assignment that few
officers cherish. ``Between the two heats, I'd rather have this
(outdoor) heat. The inside heat is hotter.''
</P>
<P>
   Down below, on a concrete pad, other guards and inmates are
subjected not just to the sun, but also the blast of heat from the
pavement and the diesel engines of the tractor-trailers that come
and go all day. The trucks bring in supplies for prison industries
and carry out factory goods made there. Each truck &UR;  &LR; must be
inspected, including the engine area and undercarriage, for
contraband or inmates trying to escape.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of the 2,500 Wynne inmates &UR;  &LR; work, at a variety
of jobs, including license-plate manufacturing, a mattress plant,
box factory, diesel mechanic shop and a license sticker and plastic
sign factories.
</P>
<P>
   The lucky ones are in the sticker or sign plants. They are
air-conditioned _ for the benefit of computers not inmates, Wilson
explained.
</P>
<P>
   In the mattress factory, plant manager Jimmy Stone has rolled
out huge box fans to help keep his workers in relative comfort as
they make mattresses for the entire prison system and other
agencies, like state hospitals and county jails.
</P>
<P>
   There's no such relief, though, for those attending vocational
education classes in welding. If summer temperatures weren't
enough, it's exacerbated by the fire from welding equipment and the
long-sleeved leather protective gear and gloves the prisoners must
wear as the work in a three-walled shed.
</P>
<P>
   TDCJ officials say they have taken a number of preventive steps,
from altering work schedules of inmates and rotating employee work
assignments to authorizing wardens to buy Gatorade and sports
drinks for inmates. Those drinks will help replenish electrolytes
and, because they are flavored, will encourage prisoners to drink
more fluids, Koenig said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some help from nature, but we're doing all we can,''
said Linthicum, the health services director.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, TDCJ placed an emergency order for 100 fans to be
distributed &UR;  &LR; in prisons across the state to help cool things down
on the buses used to move inmates. Other units, like Wynne, are
buying their own fans to install in cell blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Koenig said several units have ordered water misters, which have
been shown to drop the temperature in a cell block 10 to 15
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Forced-air ventilation systems in some of the new prisons are
designed to suck air in from the outside and recirculate it
indoors. But this summer, where temperatures outdoors have reached
108 degrees in West Texas, even that doesn't work very well.
</P>
<P>
   At the Colorado City prison, warden Rodney Cooper said the fans
bringing in the outside air are shut down about 10 a.m. when the
air starts heating up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like standing in front of a heater,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
