<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHEAP PC MAY FIT YOU PERFECTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the attention paid to sizzling microprocessors speeds,
dazzling multimedia technologies and snazzy styling, the z's that
are most common in personal computers today are the ones that occur
while the computer is waiting for something to do.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true if the computer is used primarily for
word processing, electronic mail, keeping a calendar and to-do
list, and browsing the Internet _ applications that generally do
not demand the latest and most powerful processors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to save money when buying a computer is to
be realistic about how it is going to be used.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of computer applications demand high performance,
including three-dimensional games, software development, graphic
arts and publishing, multimedia explorations and complex financial
analysis. For people who do such things, or who anticipate getting
involved with such applications soon, no computer is fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   And some people are willing to pour money into powerful new
computers just to have the fastest machine on the block, or in the
belief that the more they spend up front, the longer they can
retard the computer's inevitable decline into the technological
junk heap. There is some validity in this thinking, but only if one
puts it in the context of what the computer's main tasks will be.
</P>
<P>
   If one accepts the fact that advances in PC technology are
accelerating even as prices are falling, an argument can be made
for buying a cheap PC today and simply replacing it with a cheaper
and more powerful computer when it can no longer keep up with the
demands made on it. We're not quite at the point of having
disposable PCs, but we're heading in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true for the growing number of people who use
the PC primarily as a communications device, more than as a
computational device.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is the largest driving influence in consumer PC
sales today,'' said Strategic News Service president Mark Anderson,
who was among the first technology analysts to forecast the growing
significance of inexpensive personal computers, or Cheap PCs, as he
calls them. ``Consumers are buying CPC's to get onto the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   For Net-based applications like e-mail, the PC itself may not be
the most critical component of a system. The slowest chip available
today is still idle more than 99 percent of the time while waiting
for someone to type the next character on the keyboard. This is
true even among the newest crop of CPC's selling for less than
$1,000. (When people talk about sub-$1,000 computers, they almost
always leave out the fact that one must spend a few hundred dollars
more on a monitor and a printer.)
</P>
<P>
   Are these cheap PCs a good deal? Or are they last year's
technologies, at the brink of obsolescence even as they come out of
the box?
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every low-cost PC on the market is capable of running
standard applications, except high-end games, for the next 18
months, said Stephen Baker, senior hardware analyst for PC Data of
Reston, Va. ``The big difference now, as opposed to a year ago,''
Baker said, ``is that PCs under $1,000 are designed to be
competitive. They're all based on current technology, so you don't
have to worry as much about obsolescence. It's the low end of the
current stuff, but it's still pretty current.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cheapest machines, those that are now flirting with a
$500 sticker price, are generally built around end-of-the-line
chips and bare minimum configurations. Some manufacturers try to
eke out a profit at these levels by cutting corners, so, if
possible, try the system before you buy it. Some of these come with
rickety keyboards, frail mice, scarce expansion slots, small or
fuzzy monitors, cheap speakers and just enough system and graphics
memory to do basic chores.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the $1,000 models today are surprisingly robust,
certainly for the common applications of word processing and
Internet cruising.
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule, draw the bottom line at 32 megabytes of RAM
(random access memory), a 4-gigabyte hard drive, a 24-speed CD-ROM,
at least 2 megabytes of video memory, a 15-inch monitor, and a
so-called 56K V.90 modem, the current top standard for dial-up
connections to the Internet or an online service. Any of today's
processors in the 233-megahertz or higher range can handle most
basic tasks, but for added oomph make sure the processor comes with
at least 256 KB of something called Level 2 or L2 cache, which
stores frequently used data in high-speed memory.
</P>
<P>
   At these prices, it becomes more important than ever to buy from
reputable companies. Almost all the major PC makers now offer
models under $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   While the average price of a PC bought today (not including
monitor) is still about $1,125, according to market researchers, it
is likely to drift below $1,000 by the end of the year, pushed
downward by price cuts for microprocessors, memory chips and other
standard components.
</P>
<P>
   (According to the research of ZD Market Intelligence, the
popularity of Windows 98, which requires more processing power,
memory and hard disk space than earlier versions of Windows, has
kept the average price higher despite the introduction of cheaper
PCs by Compaq, IBM, Hewlett-Packard and others.)
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp. cut prices again last week on Pentium and Celeron
processors, and accelerated the introduction of new 300-megahertz
and 333-megahertz Celeron chips that offer higher performance than
the ones now on the market. (They integrate a performance booster
called an L2 cache, which earlier Celeron chips lacked.) Those
chips will be available to computer makers next month.
</P>
<P>
   This will translate into higher momentum for low-cost personal
computers in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And Intel's price cuts typically prompt its rivals to cut
prices, too.
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder, then, that low-cost PCs are popular. They may
be just the right tool for people who have basic computing needs.
Why buy a Ferrari if you just need to drive to the grocery store?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
