<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4861 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      07-27 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE Q &AMP; A: WEATHER FORECASTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By C.CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forecast: Cloudy
</P>
<P>
   Q. When weather forecasters say there is a 50 percent chance of
rain tomorrow, what does that mean? And how far ahead can a
reliable forecast be made?
</P>
<P>
   A. When the National Weather Service forecasters use the term
``probability of precipitation,'' they mean that in 10 instances of
weather patterns similar to the one they are looking at, it rained
five times, said Sam Perugini, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania
State University.
</P>
<P>
   The service keeps cumulative records, and the probability
forecast is a statistic based on what has happened, he said. For
example, if a cold front is expected in mid-July in late afternoon,
and it has rained 7 out of 10 times that such a situation occurred,
there is a 70 percent chance of rain. The forecast covers
precipitation at any time in a stated period, like today, tonight
and tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   As to how far ahead it is practical to forecast, Perugini said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We can be very accurate up to about three days or so, in my
opinion. You can say that tomorrow will be sunny, with a high of
92, but after that, for four to seven days ahead, the way that one
presents what information we know has to be different. You give
more of a range.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can give a sense of what the weather might be like up to
two weeks in advance as a trend, like wet or dry, warmer than
normal or below normal, based on a pattern that favors hot and dry
or a pattern that favors cool and dry. But the specifics we don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions about science to:
</P>
<P>
   Questions
</P>
<P>
   Science Times
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036.
</P>
