<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIANS-COKE-0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW PALESTINIAN COKE BOTTLER CALLS DEAL 'MAJOR EVENT' FOR
NATION-BUILDING
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The deal announced last week between the Coca-Cola
Co. and a Palestinian bottler might be strictly business for the
international soft-drink giant, but it's a symbol of growth here in
the cash-strapped West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at is as a major event for Palestine,'' said
Zahi Khouri, chairman of the National Beverage Company Ltd., a
bottler based in the West Bank city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider any investment part of the nation-building
process,'' Khouri said.
</P>
<P>
   Khouri, a Palestinian-American with homes in New York and
Jerusalem's ancient, walled, Old City, owns restaurants in central
Florida, including Bennigan's and TGI Fridays. He has also, since
the signing of the Oslo peace accords in 1993, been a co-founder of
several major Palestinian businesses in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Atlanta-based Coca-Cola announced that it was buying
15 percent of Khouri's beverage company -- which he said has a
capital value of about $20 million -- and granting it franchise
rights to sell its soft drinks in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, an Israeli company has the distributing rights. That
company, the Central Bottling Company, is at the center of a long
relationship which kept Coca-Cola Co. in Israel despite a now-ended
Arab boycott of companies dealing with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's agreement with the Palestinian bottler means the
Israeli bottler will lose its access to the nearly 3 million
residents of the West Bank and Gaza strip. Those areas were
captured by Israel in the 1967 and are now slowly being turned over
to Yasser Arafat's Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Shackleton, country manager in Israel for Coca-Cola, said
the move was ``purely a business'' decision and not related to the
current political situation -- the eventual turnover of the area to
the Palestinians and the possible formation of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   He said Coca-Cola tries to use local bottlers in all of the
approximately 200 countries and territories where it sells the
popular soft drink.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Pepsi-Cola said that early this year his company
granted limited distribution rights to a Palestinian bottler in
Gaza that may eventually be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Other foreign companies, such as restaurant chains, car
dealerships and a cellular phone company, have granted franchises
to Palestinian firms.
</P>
<P>
   The deals have come as U.S. and other foreign officials have
encouraged companies to deal directly with Palestinians, in part to
help an economy that many say has actually seen a per capita
downturn since the Oslo peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite clear to me that the political process
contributed,'' said Ephraim Kleinman, economics professor at Hebrew
University in Jerusalem. ``I can only expect there will be more and
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Khouri and group of investors bought an existing bottler a year
ago and upgraded while it was negotiating with Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
