<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4869 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-HEAT-1200(2Tak     07-27 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-HEAT-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNINGS NOT DETERRING MANY FROM TRYING TO SLIP INTO UNITED STATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARRIZO SPRINGS, Texas _ The body, blackened by the sun, lay
sprawled below a game fence 25 miles from the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   The young man in the red ball cap and brown jeans might have
gone undiscovered were it not for three fellow Mexicans. After
stumbling onto the body Friday, they decided to report it to
authorities even though they knew it would mean being caught and
sent back across the border,
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw it, we got scared that it could happen to us,''
explained Miguel Juarez Comener, 28, of Guanajuato, Mexico, who
said he once worked in the kitchen of a Ninfa's restaurant in
Lewisville, Texas. His last job in Mexico was in construction and
paid the equivalent of $40 a week, not enough to support a family.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old who perished became the latest undocumented
immigrant claimed by the searing Texas sun while trying to slip
into the United States. Since mid-May, 51 people desperate for work
have died of heat-related causes in Texas, according to the U.S.
Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican media have been reporting the cases _ of those who
died and those who have been rescued by Border Patrol agents, who
now routinely carry 5-gallon jugs of ice water. Many agents have
also been trained to treat dehydration, and the Border Patrol has
launched a ``Stay Out, Stay Alive'' campaign that includes public
service announcements and fliers aimed at Mexico and Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   But the cautionary tone of Mexican news reports has not made a
dent in the number of people attempting to find jobs in Texas,
Tennessee, Illinois and North Carolina, agents said. Apprehensions
of undocumented immigrants in the Border Patrol's Del Rio sector
now average 356 a day, up 20 percent from a year ago, said Paul
Berg, chief patrol agent for the sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what the aliens tell us, the stories of heat deaths have
had no impact at all,'' said Ben Poncedeleon, 35, a Border Patrol
intelligence officer assigned to the Carrizo Springs station.
</P>
<P>
   Last week near Quemado (Spanish for burnt), a town between Del
Rio and Eagle Pass, agents chased down three undocumented workers,
although two got away.
</P>
<P>
   One of those caught, his long-sleeved knit shirt stained white
with dried sweat, said he had heard the news reports but didn't
realize how bad the heat was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the sign of the cross, made a little prayer and said,
`Let's go,''' said Ismail Ruiz, 19, of Torreon, Mexico, who wore
two wooden crosses under his shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had known it was like this, I would never have come,'' he
said through an interpreter. ``I carried a milk jug and filled it
up at a cattle tank, but it wasn't enough water.''
</P>
<P>
   The body found Friday was the second dead heat victim removed
from the sprawling Farias Ranch this month, said its manager, Harry
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago, a group of 12 walked up to the house and said a
man was very sick,'' Kelly said. ``When I got there, I checked his
pulse, but he was dead already. The others all wanted to go back.
Five of them were in pretty bad shape and couldn't walk anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepped-up operations in sectors to the north and south have
made Carrizo Springs and the rest of the Del Rio sector an
ever-more popular crossing area, although it comprises only about a
quarter of Texas' border with Mexico, Berg said. Patrols taper off
north of Carrizo Springs, a small ranching community 44 miles
southeast of Eagle Pass and the county seat of Dimmit County. If
undocumented workers make it past Carrizo Springs, most can make it
to Crystal City, San Antonio or beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy traffic through the area, combined with the 100-plus
temperatures, has meant that 26 _ more than half _ of the
heat-related deaths among undocumented immigrants have occurred in
his sector, Berg said. Last year, the Del Rio sector recorded just
nine deaths from all causes, including drowning, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicably, there are more ``runners'' _ undocumented workers
who try to flee when spotted _ near Carrizo Springs than elsewhere,
Poncedeleon said.
</P>
<P>
   But the heat can be an ally of the green-uniformed agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as they see the helicopter, they drop their water and
make a 300-yard sprint and, because of the heat, they just can't
run any farther,'' said Mark Douglas, an agent who has recovered
two victims of fatal heatstroke.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Some undocumented workers travel in groups led by paid guides,
known as ``coyotes.'' Others, like Jose Reyes Alvarez, who had
crossed before, risk it on their own. But many didn't count on the
unusually harsh weather this year, Poncedeleon said.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, a thin 19-year-old with a wispy mustache and goatee,
emerged from the desert brush after three days and gave himself up
at a highway. Heat exhaustion and brackish water had made him too
ill to go on.
</P>
<P>
   Some undocumented workers say ranchers put deworming chemicals
in the man-made ponds where herds water, said Adolfo Tapia, 38, a
Border Patrol supervisor. To ``purify'' the water, they drop in
lemon and Salde Uvas Picot, a fizzy Mexican patent medicine that
competes with Alka-Seltzer, he said. But rancher Kelly said tank
water can be unfit for humans simply because it's stagnant.
</P>
<P>
   On being picked up, Alvarez immediately reported passing a woman
overcome by heat, prompting a dogged, morning-long search by Border
Patrol agents in a helicopter, trucks, off-road vehicles and on
foot.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Randy Reinhardt steered his Ford Expedition through the
rugged ranchland, bounced past a half-eaten can of beans and a half
jug of yellowish water abandoned by Alvarez. At points, Poncedeleon
and agent Trey Leigh walked miles in the blistering heat to find
any trace of the lost woman.
</P>
<P>
   Roadrunners, wild turkeys, jack rabbits and Santa Gertrudis
cattle crossed the agents' path.
</P>
<P>
   After hours of peering at markings in the dusty ranch roads that
the veteran agents have learned to read, Reinhardt found the
woman's footprints near a bridge. He also found tire tracks. ``She
was picked up,'' he said. ``Vehicle tracks are on top of hers.
That's good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez was trying to make his way back to North Carolina where
he had worked in a furniture plant that employed 200 workers. He
planned to marry in January, and his fiance had urged him not to
risk the heat by heading north. To him, it was the difference
between a barely subsistence wage of $35 a week as a carpenter in
Mexico or $450 a week in Candor, N.C., he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard about those who had died crossing,'' said the
youth, whose father grows corn and alfalfa on a 116-acre farm _ not
enough to support an extended family, which now includes four sons
living legally in the United States. ``But I needed money to get
married.''
</P>
<P>
   On his first trip, Alvarez paid a guide $600 to smuggle him
across. ``Last time, it was only an hour walk and the coyote had
arranged transport. The coyote doesn't work anymore, and since I'd
done it before, I thought I could do it myself. I have family in
Houston. Once across, I could phone relatives and they could pick
me up,'' he said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio Grande was chest-high where Alvarez crossed, stripped to
his underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one hand I held up my suitcase and swam with the other,''
he said. In his suitcase was a jug, which he filled with river
water. Later, he filled it at an irrigation canal. He was sick for
two days, sleeping in the open, killing a rattlesnake with a rock
at one point, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That water made me throw up. But I kept drinking it. I had
nothing else. I felt so bad I went to the road and gave myself
up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the back of Reinhardt's Expedition, Alvarez said his aborted
quest hasn't left him despondent. ``I don't feel too bad because I
was sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Nursing a water bottle, the youth asserted that he wouldn't risk
another crossing but would return to his girlfriend in central
Mexico. But if he did, Alvarez said, he'd carry more water and less
clothes. ``I'd be more careful where I'd cross and I'd carry at
least four (gallon) jugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to drink a lot of water in this heat.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
