<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4919 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      07-27 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ICE MASS GOETH?  
 AN UNKIND CUT IN MONGOLIA  
 WHAT STARS EAT FOR DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., Calif., Netherlands)   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reason water does not slosh through the streets of New York
City or Miami is that it is safely locked up as ice in the West
Antarctic ice sheet. Whether the ice sheet will forever stay that
way no longer seems such a bed-rock certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Pine Island Glacier, a major ice stream that flows into the
Amundsen Sea, has been in retreat for the last four years,
according to a report in this week's Science by Dr. E.J. Rignot of
the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The glacier has a hinge line, the point at which its projecting
tongue leaves the sea bed and starts to float. The floating tongue
is lifted slightly by the ocean tides, and these small heaves and
swells can be detected by radar satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Rignot calculates that the hinge line retreated by three-fourths
of a mile a year from 1992 to 1996, the period for which data are
available.
</P>
<P>
   Because glaciers behave erratically, a four-year record is
insufficient to predict a trend. But Rignot's observations may send
a shiver through climatologists: Pine Island Glacier has been
identified as an Achilles heel of the West Antarctic ice sheet and
a possible trigger for its disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   The melting of the ice sheet might cause an estimated 15-foot
rise in sea level. But that could seem a mere inconvenience
compared with climatic shifts of the past, such as the Grand
Coupure (the Big Cut) that hit Europe 34 million years ago. The
inhabitants of Europe were then mostly perissodactyls, the order of
mammals that includes the rhino and the extinct brontothere or
thunderbeast.
</P>
<P>
   During the Grand Coupure, the entire fauna of Europe changed as
the thunderbeasts and their kind succumbed to a sharp cold phase in
the world's climate.
</P>
<P>
   An Unkind Cut in Mongolia
</P>
<P>
   A counterpart to the Big Cut has now been documented in
Mongolia. With the transition from warm humid conditions to a cold,
arid climate, the Mongolian brontotheres also disappeared and were
succeeded by rodents and hares, according to a fossil survey
reported in this week's Nature by Jin Meng of the University of
Massachusetts and Malcolm C. McKenna of the American Museum of
Natural History. Meng and McKenna propose that this dramatic
makeover of Asian fauna be called the Mongolian Remodeling.
</P>
<P>
   The forces that drove the Grand Coupure and the Mongolian
Remodeling would also have shaped critical events in the evolution
of primates, but details remain to be uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   What Stars Eat for Dinner
</P>
<P>
   The triumphs and tragedies unearthed by paleontologists are
trivial affairs compared with the titanic events that are
astronomers' daily bread. A satellite that scans the skies for
X-rays has turned up a hellish star in the constellation
Sagittarius. Four hundred times a second, the star emits a burst of
X-rays powerful enough to be detected from Earth, 12,000
light-years away.
</P>
<P>
   A slight tremor in these bursts betrays the presence of an
invisible captive, a companion star so close that it orbits the
X-ray pulsar every two hours. A stream of gas is ripped off the
captive star, generating the X-ray bursts as it hits a hot spot on
the pulsar's speeding surface.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers calculate the cannibalization has been in process
for more than 100 million years. As the pulsar acquires extra mass,
its spin increases, accounting for the extraordinary speed of
rotation now observed. Presumably the captive star will be
completely consumed eventually, leaving its voracious host spinning
in solitude.
</P>
<P>
   Theorists have long surmised that fast-spinning pulsars must
have been spun up by some vanished companion. This is the first
time that one has been caught in the act.
</P>
<P>
   The Sagittarius pulsar is reported in this week's Nature by
Dutch and American astronomers. The Dutch team discovered the
pulsar, but the Americans first detected its captive companion. The
Americans might have found the pulsar first, brags a statement put
out by the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, had not their
leader, Edward H. Morgan, been kept out of his office by a flat
tire on the morning the initial data from the satellite came
through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
