<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4928 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2T     07-27 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE SAFETY FOR SHIPS AT SEA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike the Titanic or the Andrea Doria, the Carnival cruise ship
Ecstasy lost not a single passenger or crew member. But in its
smaller way, the Ecstasy fire, which produced thick smoke that was
on hundreds of television newscasts, will probably contribute to
the evolution of marine safety.
</P>
<P>
   The time line of progress on marine safety reads as a perfect
counterpoint to tragedies afloat. After more than 1,000 people,
mostly children, died on an excursion aboard the General Slocum,
which caught fire in New York in 1904, requirements for lifesaving
gear and fire equipment were tightened.
</P>
<P>
   When more than 1,500 died on the Titanic in 1912, lifeboat
personnel were required to be certified, and an international
conference was called to approve a Convention on the Safety of Life
at Sea. The Andrea Doria-Stockholm crash in 1956, in which 52 died,
brought requirements that hulls be divided by steel bulkheads.
</P>
<P>
   With the Ecstasy, which was built with sprinklers, smoke
inhalation in corridors caused the only injuries, and they were
mild. (The investigators, at this writing, do not know if the
sprinklers were going to be effective in the fire, or if the
fireboats were essential. There were also complaints of confusion
and delay in informing passengers of the fire and the procedures to
follow.)
</P>
<P>
   There were no sprinklers aboard Commodore Cruise Line's Universe
Explorer, where five crew members died of smoke inhalation in a
1996 fire. That accident put the menace of smoke high on the list
at the National Transportation Safety Board, which investigates
these events, and the Coast Guard, which controls ship safety for
American vessels and provides the United States delegates to the
negotiations on international maritime rules.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other ships without sprinklers, or even smoke
alarms that go off on the spot. Sometimes they are installed then
taken out _ in a laundry, for example _ because they go off too
often.
</P>
<P>
   Experts at the two government agencies are pressing urgently for
changes that insure better safety for cruise passengers, 80 percent
of them Americans. Most passengers presume that United States
standards are in force on ships that dock in Florida, Louisiana,
California, Washington State or even New York. But the giant cruise
ships, while they may be American owned, are all registered and
taxed in foreign countries, and covered by those countries'
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard does inspect ships that dock in the United
States, but only to verify that the vessel meets the standards of
the Convention on Safety of Life at Sea, or Solas. There should be
twice as many lifeboat seats as potential passengers, and life
jackets for 125 percent of capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard also inspects cruise ships' food facilities and
their hot tubs, under the direction of the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   In severe cases, either for overall safety or for bad kitchen
conditions, the Coast Guard can keep a vessel from leaving an
American port. But it is rare, and the stringent safety rules that
govern inland ferries and riverboats do not apply.
</P>
<P>
   The Ecstasy, built in 1991, is registered in Liberia. Her owner,
Carnival, an American company, discussed in its 1997 annual report
why it believes she is virtually exempt from United States taxes.
Panama and the Bahamas also provide flags of convenience to
shipowners who find it more economical to register outside the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, a government report found that 74 percent of ships
visiting United States ports were registered in the Bahamas,
Liberia, Panama and Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Only one United States ocean-going cruise ship remains, American
Hawaii Cruises' Independence, and she is not subject to
international rules because she sails in the Hawaiian islands.
</P>
<P>
   Some ships that visit the United States are registered in
countries with venerable seagoing traditions, Britain, Italy and
Norway among them. But of Liberia, Barry Sweedler, head of the
office of safety recommendations and accomplishments at the
National Transportation Safety Board, said: ``What kind of
standards can it apply? Isn't it in the grip of civil war?''
</P>
<P>
   But just as mailing letters requires some international concords
about doing business, moving in international waters implies some
harmony on standards: signals, rights of way, communications and
rescue obligations.
</P>
<P>
   These basics are adopted by the International Maritime
Organization, a specialized agency of the United Nations set up in
1958, with headquarters in London. Its primary vehicle is Solas;
the most recent version, adopted in 1974, has been amended several
times.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, first designed to protect sailors, cover most aspects
of life at sea, such as load limits for ships and how tonnages are
measured. A passenger ship must be capable of being abandoned 30
minutes after a warning, for example, and lifeboats must be partly
covered to protect the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Each country is responsible for certifying that ships bearing
its flags meet the requirements of Solas. Each nation delegates the
inspection task to a group called a classification society, which
is paid by the nation's shipowners to do the work.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Solas cruise ship safety rules are now a patchwork because
the organization's delegates, representing national interests, are
reluctant to tell ship owners to modify existing ships; they would
rather lay down rules for new construction.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1994, for example, all new ships had to come out of
the yard with sprinklers and smoke alarm systems. But long phase-in
times were left for older ships.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent date for retrofitting requirements was October
1997. Solas fire protection rules at that point were nominally
applied to all ships built before October 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Sweedler said that his agency and the Coast Guard had gotten the
impression that there would be ``zero tolerance for noncompliance''
with rules requiring sprinklers, fire detection systems and smoke
alarms in all accommodations, including atriums, stairway
enclosures and corridors, plus self-closing doors. (In the Ecstasy
case, the 1997 rule was redundant, because Carnival had been
building in sprinkler systems on all of its ships since 1982.)
</P>
<P>
   But then, Sweedler said, American safety people began to
discover that the 1997 rule was not watertight. They learned that
15 vessels, including the Universe Explorer, whose laundry room
caught fire near Juneau on July 27, 1996, and the Vistafjord, which
lost a crew member in a linen room fire April 7, 1997, had sought
or received from their countries of registry what amounts to an
exemption from the requirement for sprinklers on board.
</P>
<P>
   The retrofitting rules permit older ships to postpone
installation of sprinklers until 2005 or 2009 provided they were
built of noncombustible materials and met other criteria. Owners
get this exemption by asking their flag nations _ the Bahamas,
Panama, Liberia _ to certify that the ship meets these criteria,
called Method I.
</P>
<P>
   If the exemption is granted, all the Coast Guard can then do to
protect passengers' safety is to verify that the Method I standards
have been met.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board conducted a gruelingly
detailed study of the Universe Explorer's failure to meet 30 of the
Method I criteria under which it was claiming an exemption. In
addition to the lack of sprinklers, for example, a bulkhead was
found to be missing between the laundry room and other areas, and
other repairs and replacements had been carried out with materials
that did not meet Method I rules.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Mayer, chief executive officer of Commodore Cruise Line in
Miami, said that the line was not required by the rules to install
sprinklers, but had a ``moral duty'' to do so. He said that this
work would be done in January 1999, if the design and parts were on
hand in time, or in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   He said that his company relied on the certification of the
Universe Explorer by its classification society, because it could
not count each door and wall; the previous owner removed the
laundry room bulkhead, he said. It has been replaced now, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Sweedler said that detailed inquiries, like the one on the
Universe Explorer, showed the impossibility of declaring all
pre-1994 vessels fire-safe, either by virtue of sprinklers or by
virtue of construction methods and materials. He recommends a tough
road: that all potential passengers ask their travel agents if
their intended vessel has sprinklers, everywhere, including the
laundry room.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is too inconsistent to assess otherwise, as
Carnival's forward-looking decision in 1982 to build in sprinklers
demonstrates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it is worth checking the brochure to learn the
country of registry of the ship and the date it went to sea. Ships
built before 1994 may have received exemption from the 1997
sprinkler requirement by claiming they conform to Method I
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board points out that
continual modifications may have undone the validity of the claim,
for instance, through use of flammable putty or insulation
materials during a repair.
</P>
</TEXT>
