<HEADLINE>
PUTTING UP THE DOG  
 BIKING IN BRITANY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL FREIREICH 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q.(italics)What hotels around Central Park can arrange for
guests who want to bring their dogs. I have two Chesapeake Bay
retrievers: one 70 pounds, one 80 pounds. _ Jack A. Grebb, Upper
Black Eddy, Pa.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Dog owners who want to be right on the park have a choice of
at least five hotels. While only three of them will not take dogs
as large as yours, there are also places a few blocks from the park
that will. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some hotels ask the owner to sign a waiver agreeing to pay for
damage done by the dog or charge a cleaning fee if a dog is a
guest. If there is a single criterion hotels agree on, it is that a
dog be well-behaved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While most of the hotels queried said that a dog did not have to
be in a carrier when the guest was out, some pointed out that if a
dog was free the housekeeping staff should not be expected to enter
a room.
</P>
<P>
   Rates here are for rooms, not suites, and apply to mid-August.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carlyle, 35 East 76th Street, New York, N.Y. 10021; (212)
744-1600 or (800) 227-5737, fax (212) 717-4682. Rate: $350 to $595.
</P>
<P>
   Essex House-Hotel Nikko, 160 Central Park South, New York N.Y.
10019. (212) 484-5100 or (800) 645-5687, fax (212) 484-4602. Guests
are asked to sign a waiver of responsibility. Rate: $229 to $275. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mayflower, 15 Central Park West (at 61st Street), New York, N.Y.
10023; (212) 265-0060 or (800) 223-4164, fax (212) 265-0227. Denise
Creel, reservation manager, said Rottweilers, pit bulls and
Doberman pinschers were not accepted because guests are afraid of
them. A waiver and a $100 deposit, refundable if no damage is done,
is required. Rate: $180 to $220.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Delmonico, 502 Park Avenue (between 59th and 60th
Streets), New York, N.Y. 10022; (212) 486-0508, fax (212) 755-3779.
Refundable deposit of $250. Rate: $210. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Plaza Athenee, 37 East 64th Street, New York, N.Y. 10021;
(212) 734-9100 or (800) 447-8800, fax (212) 772-0958. Rate: $275 to
$470. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These hotels set a limit on size:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four Seasons, 57 East 57th Street, New York, N.Y. 10022; (212)
758-5700, fax (212) 758-5711. Maximum weight: 10 pounds. A $100
cleaning fee. Rate: $415 to $750. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parker Meridien, 118 West 57th Street, New York, N.Y. 10019
(212) 245-5000 or (800) 543-4300, fax (212) 708-7477. Maximum: 15
pounds. Rate: $199 to $225. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pierre, 2 East 61st Street, New York, N.Y. 10021; (212) 838-8000
or (800) 332-3442, fax (212) 758-1615. Maximum: 40 pounds. Waiver
required. Rate: $475 to $645. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plaza, Fifth Avenue and Central Park South, New York, N.Y.
10019; (212) 759-3000 or (800) 759-3000, fax (212) 546-5324.
Maximum: 20 pounds. Waiver required.
</P>
<P>
   Stanhope, 995 Fifth Avenue (at 81st Street), New York, N.Y.
10028; (212) 288-5800 or (800) 828-1123, fax (212) 249-3720. Will
accept only dogs that can be picked up and carried. A $100 cleaning
fee. Rate: $245. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're planning to take your pet elsewhere in the city or
elsewhere in the United States, here are some helpful resources,
which include not only listings but also tips (playing a tape at
home of music that the dog finds relaxing and taking that tape to
play at your hotel, for example). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The AAA 1998 North American Pet Book, $12. Available at AAA
offices.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Road With Your Pet,'' Fodor's, $12. Sold at
bookstores. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Road Again With Man's Best Friend,'' by Robert and Don
Habgood, Dawbert Press; (800) 933-2923. The mid-Atlantic guide is
$15.95; the national guide is $24.95. Shipping and handling:
$3.95. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A useful Web site is www.petswelcome.com, which grew out of the
experience of Fred Grayson, one of its partners, in trying to find
lodging for his dog, a Gordon setter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)We are planning a bike trip to Brittany in France and
I am having a problem finding trains that take panniers. Can you
help? _ Patricia S. Ferrin, East Hampton, N.Y.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Taking a bike aboard a train in France is hardly encouraged.
The high-speed trains known as TGVs do permit them if you don't
mind taking off the wheels and pedals, folding the handlebars in,
putting it all in a bag and finding an out-of-the-way spot to place
the bike. Some local trains have baggage cars with bike racks, but
a pannier packed with gear may not fit.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Marr, co-owner of Randonee Tours, says that because bikes
sent by train have sometimes arrived more than a day after the
biker, it's best to send a bike ahead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two alternatives to transporting a bike are taking a tour that
provides one and renting.
</P>
<P>
   There are far fewer tours of Brittany than, say, of Provence,
the Dordogne and Burgundy. Here are two companies with
Brittany-only tours. Prices are per person, based on double
occupancy. The hybrid bikes that both use combine the gearing
abilities of a mountain bike with the larger-diameter wheels of a
road bike. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield &AMP; Robinson, 70 Bond Street, Toronto, Ontario M5B
1X3; (800) 678-1147 or (416) 864-1354, fax (416) 864-0541; Web site
www.butterfield.com. Seven-day tours, with six days of cycling,
starting and ending in Nantes, with an average of 30 to 35 miles a
day on flat or gently rolling terrain. Cost: $3,475, which includes
four-star hotels, 14 meals, services of guides and support van,
entrance fees and tips. Equipment: Cannondale 24-speed hybrid or
racing style.
</P>
<P>
   Space is available for Sept. 6. Prices for 1999 have not been
set, but departure dates have been: May 30, June 27, Aug. 29 and
Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Upon request, panniers can made available free. A front
handlebar bag and a rack on the back of the bike are standard
equipment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Randonee Tours, 249 Bell Avenue, Winnipeg, Manitoba R3L 0J2;
(800) 465-6488 or (204) 475-6939, fax (204) 474-1888; Web site
www.randoneetours.com. Eight-day self-guided tours, with six days
of cycling, starting and ending in Guingamp, with 22 to 26 miles a
day on some hills of moderate difficulty daily. Cost: $1,060, which
includes two- and three-star hotels, seven meals and help a phone
call away.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment: A 21-speed hybrid bike, usually a Raleigh, Gitane or
Lapierre, with rear pannier, pump and puncture repair kit.
Departures any Thursday, Friday or Saturday until Sept. 26.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to rent a bike to do your own tour, Ms. Marr
suggests Bourgogne Randonee, in Beaune; (33-3) 80.22.06.03, fax
(33-3) 80.22.15.58. Arrangements can be made by Randonee Tours.
Charge: $10 (at 6 francs to the dollar) for one week plus shipping,
which depends on destination.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a pickup in Chartres and dropoff in Angers, in the
Loire Valley, would cost $127 plus a flat booking fee of $20.
</P>
</TEXT>
