<HEADLINE>
STATE DEPT. WARNS AGAINST BOLIVIAN PLANES  
 CRATER LAKE BECOMES LESS VISIBLE FOR A WHILE  
 HISTORY OF GLASS ON DISPLAY IN ENGLAND  
 MORE TIME TO SEE THE SITES IN GREECE  
 MUSEUM FOR A TRIBE THAT STRUCK IT RICH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The State Department is warning Americans about flying on the
flag carrier of Bolivia, Lloyd Aereo Boliviano. The department said
that a number of recent incidents raised concerns about the
airline's safety practices, particularly with Boeing 727s used on
domestic routes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Embassy has instructed its own personnel to minimize
use of these flights whenever possible,'' the State Department
said. ``It also recommends that all American travelers exercise
caution in the use of domestic air services within Bolivia.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An aviation attorney in Washington, Robert D. Papkin, who is
representing the airline, said that the State Department's warning
was unjustified. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``LAB believes it has always followed faithfully all required
standards, and recently had a complete review of the aircraft
conducted by an independent U.S. expert thoroughly familiar with
these aircraft, all of which are flying again with full government
approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Bryant &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rangers at Crater Lake National Park in Oregon have closed the
hiking trail to the shore of the nation's deepest lake for most of
the summer so that a fuel line can be replaced, a project that has
also suspended tour-boat service until July 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will be limited to viewing Crater Lake from the rim of
the caldera, 800 feet above the shoreline. The deep-blue lake, in
the Cascade Range of southern Oregon, reaches a depth of 1,932
feet, and is famous for its clear water. The shore is accessible by
a single dirt path, the milelong Cleetwood Trail, which leads to
Cleetwood Cove and the tour-boat dock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Construction is expected to last until September, said John
Miele, a park spokesman. Keeping the hiking trail open during that
period would have been hazardous, he said. For information: (541)
594-2211 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new National Glass Center in Sunderland, 275 miles north of
London, is, appropriately, made mostly of glass, including a gently
sloping glass roof on which visitors can walk (still _ despite some
embarrassing cracks that have appeared in the roof, possibly design
flaws, possibly the work of vandals). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All 80,000 square feet of the $27 million center, designed by
the London firm of Gollifer Associates and opened in June, is
devoted to glass and the many uses it has filled in the 1,300 years
since man first mixed sand, lime and fire. The city of Sunderland
is where, in 674, the first stained glass was manufactured for a
monastery. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exhibition areas include the Kaleidescope Gallery, a permanent
display dealing with the history and manufacture of glass. The many
uses of glass are examined through exhibitions and interactive
displays. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A gallery devoted to temporary exhibitions is now showing
``Glass UK,'' a survey of the studio glass movement, founded in the
1960s when artists broke away from mass production. More than 130
works are are on view. Other highlights include demonstrations by
master artisans, as well as glassmaking classes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The center is open daily. Admission is $6, $3.40 for seniors,
students and children. The National Glass Center, Liberty Way,
Sunderland, SR6 0GL; (44-191) 515-5555. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New summer schedules featuring longer hours are in effect at
many archelogical sites and museums in Greece, as a result of a
joint decision by the ministries of tourism and culture. Major
sites are open daily from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. until Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   In September and October the sites and museums will close an
hour earlier. The winter schedule has not been announced.
Previously, many museums closed for prolonged lunch breaks, and
afternoon hours varied. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The places affected are the National Archeological Museum and
the Acropolis in Athens, the Temple of Poseidon in Sounion,
Mycenae, Epidauros, Olympia, Delphi, Dion, the Archeological and
Byzantine Museums of Thessaloniki, Pella, the Palace of Knossos and
Irakleion Museum in Crete, Lindos and the Palace on Rhodes,
Mystras, the Venetian Fortress of Corfu and the Royal Tombs of
Vergina. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Archeological sites that also have museums, such as Olympia,
Delphi, Corinth and the Acropolis in Athens, may now charge only
one admission fee for both the museum and the archelogical site. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information is available from the Greek National Tourist Office,
645 Fifth Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10022; (212) 421-5777. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ice will creak, the wind will whistle and the air will be
cold when a simulated glacial crevasse and the rest of the
Mashantucket Pequot Museum in southeastern Connecticut opens on
Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will see permanent exhibitions that move in time from
the ice age to the present, recounting the history of the Pequots,
the tribe that all but disintegrated before regrouping in the 1970s
and striking it rich with the Foxwoods Resort Casino in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   With $135 million from their casino profits and other sources,
the Pequots have built a 308,000-square-foot museum and research
center, a mile and a half from the casino, to tell their story and
that of the Eastern woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will go through the glacier simulation to a
multisensory diorama depicting an 11,000-year-old caribou kill.
They'll walk though a 16th-century Pequot village with life-size
figures, village sounds and the aromas of forest and campfire; view
a 3-D computer model of the 17th-century Pequot fort that was
discovered in 1992 just outside the museum, and proceed outdoors to
a re-creation of an 18th-century farmstead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mashantucket Pequot Museum will also show 13 original films
about the Pequots and other Indian tribes, including ``The
Witness,'' which tells how the Pequots were devastated in the
Pequot War of 1636 to 1638. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museum's temporary exhibition galleries will feature
contemporary Indian art, archeological artifacts and traveling
exhibitions. A 400-seat auditorium will present live performances
for the public and scholarly conferences on Native American issues.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant will feature Indian dishes, and the museum shop
will specialize in contemporary Native American arts and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   The Pequots are expecting 350,000 visitors a year, and a shuttle
service between the casino and the museum is planned.
</P>
<P>
   The Mashantucket Pequot Museum and Research Center is at 110
Pequot Trail, Mashantucket, Conn.; (800) 411-9671. Open 10 a.m. to
7 p.m., seven days a week (last admission at 6 p.m.); closed
Christmas, Thanksgiving and New Year's Day. Admission: $10, $6 ages
6 to 15, $8 over 55. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
