<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACH-ORGAN-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACH AS MOUNTAIN RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The idea was so preposterous that it hadn't even
occurred: What do you do for an encore after playing virtually all
the organ works of Bach? If you are Christopher Herrick (and not
many other people would try such a thing), you play two pieces
again, and two of the grandest.
</P>
<P>
   Herrick, a superb English organist whom it has been a pleasure
to get to know, finished his hourlong recital at Alice Tully Hall
on Sunday evening, his 14th in 14 days as part of the Lincoln
Center Festival, then added reprises from earlier evenings: the
great Fugues in G minor (BWV 542) and E flat (the ``St. Anne,'' BWV
552). Through almost the entire evening, Herrick was at the peak of
his considerable form, combining precision with panache,
interpretive freedom with a sheer joy in virtuosity.
</P>
<P>
   The playing was, in a word, triumphal, and appropriately so.
Here was shining confirmation, if such had still been needed, that
Herrick's splendid Hyperion recordings are not artificial products
of the studio; they represent a level of command that he can
achieve in concert and sustain throughout an evening.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, it had not always seemed thus. Herrick achieved
a similar level at times on earlier evenings, as in a powerful
account of the imposing Passacaglia and Fugue in C minor, and on
the whole his playing through at least the 12 recitals I was able
to attend was excellent. But there were letdowns, sometimes for a
moment, sometimes for a work or much of an evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had quite a lot on my mind,'' Herrick said from the stage
on July 20, having just given a mildly distracted account of the
``Little'' G minor Fugue (BWV 578) to begin the second week of his
marathon. ``But this Monday I have only half as much on my mind as
last Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   The task was indeed Herculean, and Herrick had edged it into a
busy schedule only six months before, replacing the ailing New York
organist Donald Joyce, who died in March. Herrick had not only to
coax all the music back into his fingers and toes but also to
familiarize himself with the fine Kuhn organ in Tully Hall and work
out registrations to give each piece a distinctive sound and
character.
</P>
<P>
   When asked at a symposium last Wednesday evening about his daily
regimen during the festival, Herrick said that when hall
availability allowed, he would practice for three hours a day
before the recital and three hours after. ``I'm relieved to say
that I have just finished registering the last program,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, therefore, Herrick was occasionally shown at less
than his best, the more so because of the hall's dry and
unforgiving acoustics. So was all of this a good idea?
</P>
<P>
   You bet. A number of other people seemed to think so, too. (The
14 who claimed to have attended all 14 recitals were photographed
afterward onstage with Herrick.)
</P>
<P>
   For a listener _ unlike Herrick, who had to trudge every step _
it was like flying over a great mountain range: the Rockies, say.
The simile is overworked, to be sure, applied to everything from
the Beethoven piano sonatas to the Mahler symphonies, but it is apt
here. For unlike those bodies of work, which progress more or less
along a single axis, the impression here was of a motley profusion
sprawling in all directions: majestic conical peaks alternating
irregularly with smaller outcroppings of every imaginable shape,
even the odd scruffy hillock.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bach organ works, which come down mostly in copies by
other hands and present myriad problems of dating and authenticity,
no single line of development can be established. Nor is it
possible to view the entire range, to play the advertised
``complete'' canon, in any but the loosest sense. Yet Herrick
provided a convincing sense of an immense whole, suitably varied.
</P>
<P>
   His notions of what to include tended to follow recent
convention in, for example, omitting the ``harpsichord'' toccatas,
now thought by some to be organ works, and performing works of
disputed authenticity, like the Toccata and Fugue in D minor, which
ended the series Sunday. For that inclusion and others, Herrick
received strong and spirited support from the Bach authority
Christoph Wolff, who, at that symposium, decried ``the naivete with
which people declare, `This is Bach, and this is not.'''
</P>
<P>
   Herrick, in any event, made an eloquent case for everything he
played. At the first recital, he noted that in Hollywood movies,
the English are typically cast as bad guys or butlers, and stated
his willingness to serve as Bach's butler. In the end, he was more:
good guy, even hero.
</P>
</TEXT>
