<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 CULTURE NOTES: ROCK AT SALZBURG FESTIVAL; SHAKESPEARE AT BUS
TERMINAL; `GYPSY' IN NEW JERSEY AND `CATS' ON TV; MILAN'S MUSIC IN
LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tradition is getting a bit of a boot at the Salzburg Festival
this year. Rock music will jolt the Austrian city where Mozart was
born.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to performances of Verdi and Wagner and concerts by
the Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra at the five-week event, which
starts on Friday, Gerard Mortier, the artistic director, who has
shaken up the festival since succeeding Herbert von Karajan in
1991, will stage the world premiere of ``Soon,'' a rock musical
about a religious sect by the film director Hal Hartley.
</P>
<P>
   But the city remains a bastion against the full onslaught of the
20th century. ``It is not yet time to invite the Spice Girls to
Salzburg,'' Mortier said.
</P>
<P>
   New Role
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you were free-associating about what sort of
spectacle you might come upon while passing through the Port
Authority Bus Terminal on Wednesday evening, what would come to
mind?
</P>
<P>
   Those who answered, Shakespeare's ``Midsummer Night's Dream,''
are correct. In what is said to be the first performance of a play
in the terminal, at Eighth Avenue and 42nd Street in Manhattan, the
Waterloo Bridge Theater Company, an off-off-Broadway troupe, will
present a fully costumed, full-length, free performance of the
comedy at 6:30.
</P>
<P>
   J. Brandon Hill, the company's artistic director, said
Shakespeare often staged plays at coaching inns, ``and it occurred
to me that the Port Authority Bus Terminal is a modern-day coaching
inn.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who miss the performance can catch the troupe in ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' for four successive weekends beginning on
Thursday at its 74-seat theater at 203 West 38th St., near Seventh
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Curtain Calls
</P>
<P>
   Betty Buckley, who won acclaim for her portrayal of Norma
Desmond in ``Sunset Boulevard,'' begins rehearsals next month to
play Mama Rose in a revival of the Jule Styne-Stephen
Sondheim-Arthur Laurents musical ``Gypsy'' at the Paper Mill
Playhouse in Millburn, N.J. Performances begin on Sept. 9 in a run
through Oct. 25. Deborah Gibson is to play the title role.
</P>
<P>
   Already seen by more than 50 million people in at least 27
countries, the long-running musical ``Cats'' still has another
premiere in it. ``Cats'' will have its world television premiere on
Nov. 2 in the PBS ``Great Performances'' series in a production
supervised by Andrew Lloyd Webber. It will star Elaine Paige, John
Mills and Ken Page.
</P>
<P>
   Changed Setting
</P>
<P>
   Milan's music went to Lebanon on Sunday night, drawing more than
6,000 people to the Beirut Forum in what was billed as La Scala
Philharmonic Orchestra's first concert in the Middle East. With
Riccardo Muti conducting 200 musicians, the 80-member La Scala
choir and the soprano Barbara Frittoli, the program included works
by Bellini, Puccini, Rossini and Verdi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
