<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE, DO YOU LIKE LIKES OR LIKE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 2.)  
 (Eds., items in boldface should be set in italics.)  
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was the handsome face of the basketball superstar and
footgear endorser Michael Jordan on the cover of Time magazine.
Walter Isaacson, Time's editor, gambled that the iconic Jordan
would astound the sports world in the coming week _ and sure
enough, the cover subject came through with a stellar performance
that won the championship for his Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The copy on the cover identified the face merely as ``Michael,''
on the assumption that if you didn't know the megastar's last name,
you probably lived in a cave beyond reach of mass communication.
Below that, a reverent comment: ``We may never see his likes
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen letters came in to Time, and several to me,
questioning the use of  &UR; likes &LR; . ``Shouldn't that have read, `We may
never see his  &UR; like &LR;  again'?'' asked J.A. Sullivan III of Caldwell,
N.J. ``I always thought that using  &UR; likes &LR;  had a bad connotation,
as in `I'm finished with the  &UR; likes &LR;  of you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Time's copy editors say they looked it up beforehand in
Merriam-Webster's Third Unabridged Dictionary and Eric Partridge's
Dictionary of Slang and Unconventional English. James Kelly, Time's
Saturday editor, preferred the plural and made the call. The
magazine resolutely stands by its usage (look, this isn't nerve
gas) and is braced for any assault by nit-picking readers or gotcha
grammarians.
</P>
<P>
   Partridge was one of the last of the one-man dictionary writers;
that generous sultan of slang used to do his research in the great
reading room of the British Museum, where he was available to help
such aspiring lexicographers as the likes of me. He opined that
 &UR; the like of &LR; , as used by the English vituperator William Cobbett
in the late 18th century, was ``generally in the plural'' today.
</P>
<P>
   Time's other source, Merriam-Webster's Third Unabridged, accepts
 &UR; the likes of &LR;  but lists first  &UR; the like of &LR; , labeling both
colloquial. In M-W's Dictionary of English Usage,  &UR; the like of &LR;  is
described as ``a variant phrase'' well chosen when ``the reference
is to a single object and no disparagement is intended.''
</P>
<P>
   Time could take further solace from Robert Burchfield, editor of
the New Fowler's Modern English Usage, who notes, ``I was upbraided
by a Scotswoman for writing  &UR; Who has not seen the likes of the
following? &LR; '' but found examples of the plural use in the OED.
( &UR; Upbraid &LR; , ``to criticize or scold severely,'' is rooted in the
Old English  &UR; bregden &LR; , ``to snatch, move suddenly,'' which lives in
modern slang as ``put a move on.'' Where was I?)
</P>
<P>
   OK; a case can be made that the plural  &UR; the likes of &LR;  is
acceptable in spoken English. (Lexies don't use the word  &UR; correct &LR; 
anymore.) This despite the usagist Ted Bernstein's condemnation of
it as ``a casualism that has no place in serious writing'' at
bastions of good grammar like The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The question then becomes: Does  &UR; the likes of &LR;  carry a
pejorative connotation? It does; even loosey-goosey usagists say
that when it has a single object like  &UR; you &LR; , ``it typically carries
overtones of disparagement.'' Even when it is used with  &UR; me &LR; , it
most often implies a gently self-mocking derogation, as used above
with  &UR; such lexicographers as the likes of me &LR; . Sullivan of New
Jersey had it right.
</P>
<P>
   But disparagement of Michael Jordan cannot be what Time
intended. On the contrary, its comment ``We may never see his
 &UR; likes &LR;  again'' is probably bottomed on the rumination of
Shakespeare's Hamlet about his ghostly father: ``He was a man, take
him for all in all, I shall not look upon his  &UR; like &LR;  again.'' Or
``The Odes of Horace'': ``When shall we look upon his  &UR; like &LR; 
again?'' Or the King James Version of the Book of Job, in Jehovah's
whirlwind description of the twisty serpent Leviathan: ``Upon earth
there is not his  &UR; like &LR; , who is made without fear.''
</P>
<P>
   You could say, with a sneer in your voice, ``Thank goodness we
won't be seeing the  &UR; likes &LR;  of him,'' because that plural of  &UR; like &LR; 
is part of a colloquial put-down. But you cannot run somebody down
with ``the  &UR; like &LR;  of him,'' because that  &UR; like &LR;  is comparative, not
pejorative; it means ``We may not see anybody  &UR; like &LR;  him again.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are we breaking our heads over this seemingly insignificant
issue? Because the headline troubled copy editors; because a top
editor weighed their evidence and made a decision about its use on
the cover; because a score of readers then wrote in that it looked
funny to them, and because it also struck me as just a little bit
off.
</P>
<P>
   Moral: Native speakers have an instinct for the ``correct.''
Norma Loquendi, trust your ear.
</P>
<P>
   SQUAD SQUAD STRIKES
</P>
<P>
   In defending the mother tongue from redundancies, often at the
behest of readers organized into ``the Squad Squad,'' I recently
hooted at the use of  &UR; convicted felon &LR;  (a person is not a felon
until convicted of a felony) and  &UR; sworn affidavit &LR;  (which is a
``written declaration upon oath'' akin to  &UR; affiance &LR; , ``to pledge
one's troth'' to a cohabitant once known as a  &UR; fiancee &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   A  &UR; felon &LR;  is still a ``convict,'' but Joseph Restifo, a lawyer
in Philadelphia, sends me this selection from the Pennsylvania
Rules of Civil Procedure: `` &UR; affidavit &LR;  ... either (1) sworn to or
affirmed before an officer authorized by law to administer oaths
... or (2) is unsworn and ... subject to the penalties ... relating
to unsworn falsification to authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Therefore,  &UR; sworn affidavit &LR;  is no longer redundant. Remanded to
usagists down the line for reversal.
</P>
<P>
   Relatedly, I came across some fused words on the Internet that
qualify as oxymorons:  &UR; found missing &LR; ,  &UR; working vacation &LR;  and _
here's an unexpected one _  &UR; tight slacks &LR; . Best is the
throat-clearing oxymoron, used by lawyers for incipient felons to
introduce summations to the jury:  &UR; Now, then &LR; . ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
