<HEADER>
A4978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RODGERS-BOOK-REVIEW-A     07-27 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODGERS-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RICHARD RODGERS': WONDRIN' WHAT'S BEHIND THOSE GREAT MELODIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What constitutes a great melody as opposed to a catchy tune or a
hook? In his six-decade career, Richard Rodgers probably composed
more great melodies than any other American songwriter. The best
ones (``My Funny Valentine,'' ``Where or When,'' ``Bewitched,
Bothered and Bewildered'') have the paradoxical quality of seeming
at once inevitable (you wouldn't think of changing a note or an
accent) and wholly original.
</P>
<P>
   As anyone remotely familiar with Rodgers' history knows, he
worked with two major collaborators of opposite temperament, each
of whom profoundly influenced his style. From the late 1910s
through the early 1940s, he collaborated with Lorenz Hart, who was
alcoholic and homosexual and drank himself to death. The best
Rodgers and Hart songs (the music usually came first) were
sublimely airy flights whose urbane, playful lyrics were often shot
through with a piercing sadness. Even when Hart was on his last
legs, he could still toss off a lyric in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s, Rodgers teamed up with Oscar Hammerstein II to
refine (with the shows ``Oklahoma!,'' ``Carousel,'' ``South
Pacific'' and ``The King and I'') what became known as the
integrated book musical. His songs with Hammerstein, who almost
always wrote the lyrics first, had a more elevated tone. A family
man from an illustrious theatrical dynasty, Hammerstein was a
painstaking craftsman who often spent weeks putting the finishing
touches on a lyric.
</P>
<P>
   Stylistically, Rodgers' songs with Hammerstein were closer to
European operetta than those written with Hart. Quite a few Rodgers
and Hammerstein songs, including ``You'll Never Walk Alone'' (from
``Carousel'') and ``You've Got to Be Carefully Taught'' (from
``South Pacific'') expressed a philosophy of tolerance and moral
uplift that mirrored the optimistic can-do spirit of American
postwar liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   After Hammerstein died in 1960, a year after the team's hugely
successful ``Sound of Music'' opened on Broadway, Rodgers tried
writing his own lyrics for the hit 1962 show ``No Strings.'' Later
collaborations with Stephen Sondheim, Sheldon Harnick and Martin
Charnin only fleetingly recaptured the magic of his work with Hart
and Hammerstein. Rodgers died in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers has always been remembered as aloof and stern, with a
tendency toward depression, for which he was once hospitalized. And
William G. Hyland's workmanlike but stodgy account of his life and
times adds little or nothing to our skimpy knowledge of his
personal life. His long marriage to Dorothy Feiner is duly noted
without ever being explored. We are told several times that the
composer was a ``ladies man,'' but not what that might mean. The
author appears to take at face value Rodgers' insistence late in
his career that he was the last to know about Hart's personal
demons.
</P>
<P>
   About as critical of its subject as the book gets is in
suggesting that Rodgers' coolness toward others (the result, the
author speculates, of his mother's withholding of affection) caused
his hard-nosed attitude, bordering on ruthlessness, in business
negotiations once he and Hammerstein became the titans of Broadway
with their own organization.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the book comes to telling a juicy story is a
description of how Danny Kaye, returning to the cast of the 1970
musical ``Two by Two'' after fracturing his ankle, largely
abandoned the script and selfishly turned the show into a
vaudeville act.
</P>
<P>
   If Hyland's coverage of Rodgers' personal history is
perfunctory, the book at least serves as a useful clearinghouse of
career information. Its core is a carefully assembled show-by-show
chronology, larded with sensible, if elementary musical analysis
and overly abundant, mostly unrevealing quotations from newspaper
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the material has been gleaned from previously published
books, including Rodgers' own autobiography ``Musical Stages,'' and
from his letters. The chronology also covers his work as an
instrumental composer, including his music for the television
series ``Victory at Sea''; his frustrating period as a contract
songwriter in Hollywood in the early 1930s, and his and
Hammerstein's roles as producers of other people's work, including
the Irving Berlin show ``Annie Get Your Gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Each musical has its own plot summary and description of the
production and business history with the key songs noted. If you
want to know which famous Rodgers tunes were cut from shows and
re-used later, this book will tell you.
</P>
<P>
   But with its stuffy, plodding, overly reverential tone,
``Richard Rodgers'' is an extremely dull read. Hyland is unable to
convey the excitement of a Broadway opening night or evoke the
sparks of Rodgers' clashes with legendary men of the theater like
Florenz Ziegfeld and Joshua Logan.
</P>
<P>
   His analysis of Rodgers' songs is at once labored and
shortsighted. No mention is made of Rodgers' reaction to the rise
of rock-and-roll or his influence on the work of nontheatrical New
York songwriters like Carole King and Billy Joel.
</P>
<P>
   The author repeatedly describes Rodgers' tunes as being
``simple.'' True, most did conform to a standard 32-bar format, but
they were far from simple. Beyond repeating the most commonplace
observations about Rodgers' role in the history of musical theater,
the author fails to place him in the broader continuum of American
music and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Rodgers'' has the ponderous official-sounding tone of
a late Rodgers and Hammerstein ballad, say ``Climb Ev'ry
Mountain,'' a song the author seriously overestimates.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RICHARD RODGERS'
</P>
<P>
   By William G. Hyland
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 362 pages. Yale University Press. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1733EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
