<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5006 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOM-VERDICT-HNS &LR;      07-27 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOM-VERDICT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MOTHER RECEIVES LIFE SENTENCE IN KILLING OF DAUGHTER'S
EX-BOYFRIEND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The wife of a prominent South Texas surgeon who turned
to a border folk healer for help in murdering the teen who jilted
her daughter was sentenced Monday to life in a federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   Dora Cisneros, 60, of Brownsville, who was convicted in May of
using an interstate communication device _ a telephone _ in a
murder-for-hire scheme, stood solemn and wordless as visiting U.S.
District Judge Filemon Vela sentenced her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I could give you less than life,'' the judge said, ``I
don't think, given its gravity and seriousness, that the case
warrants anything less ... All of us who are acquainted with you
and all of us from my community have just one question _ `Why?'''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by her attorneys, Cisneros faced the judge and remained
silent.
</P>
<P>
   Vela then denied bond for Cisneros' pending appeal, telling
defense attorneys Tony Canales and David Botsford, ``I do not agree
with your position that she poses no threat to herself or to
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Vela also fined the woman $25,000, a sum her attorneys said she
is unable to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's sentencing in the Houston courtroom marked the end of
Cisneros' second trial for the 1993 hit on Joey Fischer, an
18-year-old Brownsville honor student who had broken off his
relationship with Cisneros' daughter, Cristina.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros' earlier conviction on a state capital murder charge
was overturned on appeal in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While Cisneros would have been eligible for consideration for
parole after serving 40 years in state prison, she will be required
to spend the remainder of her life behind bars if the federal
conviction withstands appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Mercedes Martinez, 77, the folk healer Cisneros consulted
to arrange Fischer's death, is serving a 20-year sentence for
conspiracy in state prison. Daniel Garza, a San Antonio house
painter who also assisted in arranging the killing, is serving life
in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who secretly taped her conversations with Cisneros,
was a star witness in the federal trial.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony showed Cisneros acted out of rage against Fischer, who
had briefly dated her daughter, now a San Antonio college student.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer, described as a ``late bloomer'' who had never had a
girlfriend, began dating Cristina Cisneros _ both were students at
an exclusive, co-ed Catholic high school _ in the spring of 1992.
The romance lasted only months, however, as Fischer apparently
dumped the Cisneros teen in favor of a girl from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony showed that Dora Cisneros met with Fischer's family in
an attempt to patch up the failed relationship. When that proved
unsuccessful, the indignant mother contacted the Rio Grande Valley
folk healer to work magic against the offending youth.
</P>
<P>
   When the elderly healer declined, Cisneros enlisted her help in
arranging a hit on the high school student for $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez then contacted the San Antonio house painter, a former
client, who was acquainted with contract killers in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer was fatally shot twice in March 1993 as he washed the
windshield of a car in his family's driveway. The shots were heard
by Fischer's mother, brother, sister and stepfather, but no one
witnessed the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme began to unravel, though, when authorities found a
Dallas bail bondsman's business card at the scene. The card
ultimately led to the house painter, then to Martinez and Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's sentencing, the dead youth's mother, Corrine
Nelson, tearfully embraced relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I feel relieved that justice was served,'' she said,
``but it will never be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sentiments were echoed by assistant U.S. Attorney Mervyn
Mosbacker. ``Justice has prevailed, that's what is significant for
the community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Fischer's father, A.J. Fischer, and stepfather, Vernon
Nelson, praised Harris County jurors in the federal court for
rectifying the ``miscarriage of justice'' at the hands of the state
appeals court that struck down the earlier conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot fathom that kind of mind _ so deviant,'' Fischer's
father responded when asked if he could empathize with a woman
facing life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's twisted,'' Nelson, the youth's stepfather added.
``Forgive her? God forgive me, no.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
