</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERM-LIMITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS SEE LIMITS ON LEGISLATIVE TERMS CAUSING TURMOIL IN
CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ In the plush and private Assembly Members'
Lounge, there are three kinds of headache reliever and one brand of
antacid available at no charge from hospital-sized dispensers
sitting above the numerous coffee urns.
</P>
<P>
   These days, they may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest headache in the California state Capitol is dealing
with the fallout from eight years of term limits. Under Proposition
140, the initiative voters approved in 1990, Assembly members are
limited to three two-year terms in office. Senators can serve up to
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Although some people believe the Capitol has become vastly more
democratic, state politics has been flipped on its face, lawmakers
and lobbyists say, with weaker leaders, perpetually inexperienced
legislators and a governor and his vast bureaucracy seizing more
power than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now seeing the full harvest of term limits,'' said
Assemblyman Don Perata, D-Alameda, who is running for the state
Senate before his Assembly terms are up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who put term limits on the ballot had this in mind.
These are people who did not believe in government and felt the
best way to minimize it was to create an ongoing change of elected
officials ... and everybody is in a state of chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, one first-term Assembly member co-sponsored a bill,
then inexplicably rallied opposition to it. Other lawmakers openly
discuss trading votes or eagerly ask lobbyists for campaign
contributions in Capitol hallways.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democrats are submitting to Republican Gov. Pete
Wilson's plan for a huge tax cut, something they wouldn't have
considered just weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am satisfied that we have fractured the concentration of
power,'' said Lewis Uhler, president of the National Tax Limitation
Committee and co-author of the 1990 term limits initiative.
``That's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly leadership is still trying to figure out the new
political dynamic. Tactical procedural errors, which occur
frequently, quickly turn into crises or another example of failed
leadership. It takes hours just to get everybody in line for a
single vote.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny disagreements over policy turn into personality clashes.
The Assembly has yet to pass an effective assault weapons ban
because two Democrats, who earlier had voted for the measure, were
in personal spats with the Assembly leadership and the author of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   After only three terms, many are distracted by new campaigns for
other offices. A few are leaving even before their terms are up,
because they don't want to miss a chance to run for an open Senate
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for some real advice on how to cope, Democrats
continuously consult with former Assembly Speaker Willie Brown, a
Democrat who is now mayor of San Francisco. This is the supreme
irony of term limits: The one lawmaker the limited-government
advocates wanted thrown out still helps run the place by providing
advice to lawmakers without his experience in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening over there is a function of term limits, pure
and simple,'' said Senate President pro tem John Burton, D-San
Francisco, who left the Assembly because of term limits and must
leave the Senate in 2004. ``There's nothing you can do about it,
unless you repeal term limits.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the entire Legislature will turn over when 11
senators are forced out of office at the end of their terms,
including Democrat Ralph Dills of El Segundo, who joined the
Legislature during the Depression, and Quentin Kopp of San
Francisco, the craggy intellectual and last remaining independent.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyist have become more powerful because they, like the
governor, have the time and experience to manipulate information.
Yet even lobbyists complain that lawmakers want to rush things
through without thinking, just to get a law under their belts.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyist Kathy Dresslar said she has spoken with new lawmakers
about their bills when they suddenly start talking about upcoming
political fund-raisers, a clear violation of the law prohibiting a
promise of money for support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe it's due to unfamiliarity with the law,''
Dresslar said. ``It's not a deliberate shakedown. They are just
naive. They just find themselves busier than they have even been in
their life, and it all comes out in the same breath.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
