<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, July 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the 22nd consecutive day of high temperatures of 100
degrees or greater in Dallas, Texas. Sprawling high pressure at
20,000 feet will remain over the southern Plains Tuesday, providing
bright sunshine and squelching the development of thunderstorms.
Highs will top 100 across much of Texas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   The stationary front marking the boundary between the torrid air
hovering over the southern Plains and a more seasonable air mass to
the north will be the focus for thunder from Colorado to the Deep
South. One cluster of thunderstorms will drench Alabama and Georgia
while another cluster will develop over Colorado. Tropical
downpours will form along the central Gulf Coast as cooling sea
breezes lift moist air into towering cumulus clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, burgeoning warmth and humidity will affect the
Northeast as breezes from the south increase. Ample sun will allow
temperatures to approach 90 degrees in much of the Piedmont, though
the increased humidity will support a few showers over the
Appalachians. A cold front that promises to bring an end to the
humidity in New England by Thursday will ignite a broken line of
storms over the upper Midwest. Behind the cold front, bright
sunshine and comfortable humidity will grace the northern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms will percolate in the afternoon over
the Rockies from Montana to New Mexico while unusual heat plagues
the interior Pacific Northwest. California will be seasonal with
some clouds along the coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tropical Depression
</P>
<P>
   The first tropical depression of the Atlantic hurricane season
was christened Monday west of Africa. The system grew from a
cluster of thunderstorms that earlier rumbled west off the coast of
Africa. Vast amounts of heat were released in thunderstorms as
water vapor condensed in cloud droplets. In turn, heating caused
barometric pressure to lower. Like a hot potato, the area of lowest
pressure hopped from place to place, but as thunderstorms
organized, heating was focused at the center and a circulation of
winds began. With sustained winds of 30 mph, the depression was
born.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
