<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-ELECT-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE TALLY UNDER WAY IN CAMBODIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ International observers voiced cautious
optimism Monday over the conduct of Cambodia's parliamentary
election as villagers and townspeople in 11,699 polling places
painstakingly tallied Sunday's ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Rising before dawn to get an early start, as many voters did the
day before, local election officials followed elaborate procedures
to reopen the sealed ballot boxes and check and cross-check the
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   With the first official results not expected until Saturday, the
country was alive Monday with claims and counterclaims of victory,
best-guess analyses and fears of manipulation by the governing
party headed by the country's strongman, Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from polling stations indicated that Hun Sen's party was
in a close race with that of his rival and former coalition
partner, Prince Norodom Ranariddh. A third party headed by a critic
of the government, Sam Rainsy, also appeared to have considerable
support. Few votes were going to the remaining 36 parties.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome _ and however fair or unfair the vote tally
_ no party was expected to win the two-thirds vote needed to form a
government in the 122-seat National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Election analysts said that once the votes were counted, they
expected hard bargaining over the shape of a new government and
that the crucial question was whether the loser would accept the
result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the outcome of this election _ if it's very close or
if it's very clear, whatever happens _ the important thing is they
must honor and respect the people's wishes,'' said Glenys Kinnock,
the special representative of the European Union, which is largely
financing the election.
</P>
<P>
   In the Philippines, where she is attending a regional
conference, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright struck a
similar note, saying, ``The real test of Cambodia's democracy will
come after the ballots are counted.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Kinnock, visiting a downtown counting station Monday,
offered a positive preliminary assessment of the voting itself. She
said the election on Sunday, in which officials said more than 90
percent of the country's 5.4 million registered voters took part,
was ``almost entirely free of serious irregularities.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the laborious vote count Monday, in provincial offices
crowded with election officials and observers from independent
monitoring groups, Ms. Kinnock said: ``I think the process of
verification of the votes seems to be very satisfactory, and that's
the message we're getting from other areas of Cambodia as well.
From what I have seen, every possible effort has been made to make
sure that the votes are counted fairly and very carefully.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thun Saray, director of the local poll-watch group Comfrel,
said, ``Although there were some irregularities and incidents of a
serious nature, these did not take place on a wide scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign observers from the European Union and the United
Nations, interviewed Monday at several rural polling stations, also
said they were impressed by the seriousness and apparent
transparency of the count. But some election observers voiced
concern over possible manipulation in the next stages of the tally,
in which local totals are consolidated, after a delay Monday night
in an announcement of preliminary partial returns.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the delay, a spokesman for the National Election
Committee said the faxes his office had received from polling
stations were illegible and lacked official stamps. In addition, he
said, the available results were so few that they could not offer a
useful sample of the nationwide vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not significant,'' said the spokesman, Samraing
Kimsan. ``We want to have more news.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Rainsy, who has been a leading critic of the election even
as he took part in it, told reporters that he was worried by the
delay. ``We are moving into a very dangerous game,'' he said.
``They want to buy time. They want to arrange the results of the
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign and Cambodian observers of the election have been
concerned from the start about manipulation, given the strong-arm
practices of Hun Sen's party and its near-total control of
government and military power throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen has also demonstrated his determination to hold power,
demanding and getting a share of leadership after losing the last
election in 1993 and seizing full control a year ago in a coup in
which he ousted his co-prime minister, Prince Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
   Since the coup, human rights groups and U.N. monitors say, at
least 100 of Hun Sen's opponents have been killed. The 30-day
election campaign was preceded and accompanied by a variety of
abuses carried out by Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``These abuses consisted of widespread and subtle intimidation
of potential opposition voters in the countryside, de facto
vote-buying by Hun Sen's ruling Cambodian People's Party,
inequitable media coverage and violence, including killings of
opposition activists,'' said the International Crisis Group, an
independent international human rights monitoring agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Crisis Group also pointed out what is in effect a
self-inflicted no-win situation for Hun Sen's party, which has lost
the trust of much of the outside world. ``If the opposition wins in
a decisive way, the international community can easily conclude
that the elections were sufficiently free and fair,'' the group
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, if the ruling party wins convincingly, doubts will
always persist over the conduct of the polls,'' it said. ``It will
never be possible to determine whether the CPP election victory was
a result of intimidation, vote buying and violence or else it
broadly represented the will of the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
