<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5061 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLSTREET28-COX     07-27 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLSTREET28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wall Street: Companies are supplying proof to back up
Greenspan's caution about earnings
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan thinks the
stock market is a bigger threat to the economy than the Asian
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated his argument last week in his semiannual
Humphrey-Hawkins testimony before Congress, after which the stock
market tanked.
</P>
<P>
   The household wealth created by an eight-year bull market has
helped to create ``as impressive (an economy) as any I have
witnessed in my near half-century of daily observation of the
American economy,'' said Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primarily because of the rise in stock prices, about $12.5
trillion has been added to the value of household assets since the
end of 1994,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While only a fraction of that enormous sum has been spent, it
was enough to play an instrumental role in ``propelling the economy
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The upside of this spending has been steady job growth,
increased job security and more revenue to local, state and federal
governments.
</P>
<P>
   But the downside is the prospect of renewed inflation,
especially the kind of wage inflation generated when job growth
exceeds labor force expansion.
</P>
<P>
   If inflation occurs, the Fed would be forced to act, probably by
raising interest rates to restrain the economy, Greenspan
explained.
</P>
<P>
   It would be better, Greenspan suggested, if household spending
slowed.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock market were less rewarding, it would generate less
household wealth, spending would slow and the economy would expand
at a less inflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you make stocks less attractive?
</P>
<P>
   According to Greenspan, you tell investors the truth -- that the
``three-to-five-year (profit) projections of analysts are
unrealistic'' and that ``the real world'' will make that clear ``in
no uncertain terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how Greenspan expressed it: ``Reduced prospects for the
return to capital would not only affect investment directly but
could also affect consumption if stock prices adjust to a less
optimistic view of earnings prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Translated: If earnings prospects were less optimistic,
investment returns could be lower, not only reducing direct
investment but household spending as well.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, Greenspan may get a chance to find out what effect
shrinking profit growth will have on stocks, since profit growth is
in fact shrinking and the news is getting around.
</P>
<P>
   According to First Call, a Boston research group that tracks
earnings forecasts, only 3.7 percent of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
companies that have reported second-quarter earnings -- and just
over half of them have -- have posted year-over-year profit growth.
A year ago it was 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1998, most of the people who have put money in stocks had
only experienced strong earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P 500 companies posted double-digit earnings growth in all but
four of the 28 quarters between 1992 and the end of 1997 -- some of
them recording gains of 25 percent or 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   First Call research director Charles L. Hill calls that an
``unprecedented record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is unusual about the current (seven-year economic)
expansion, and probably is a record, is the number of quarters with
double-digit profit growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of profit growth that propelled the S&AMP;P 500 to
annual gains of better than 20 percent from 1995 through 1997, and,
so far this year, 17.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill, Greenspan and others say this level of quarterly
profit growth will not continue in an economy that Greenspan, at
least, will do what he can to restrain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
