A5083 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NICOLAS-CAGE-IN-SNAKE     07-27 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICOLAS-CAGE-IN-SNAKE-EYES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICOLAS CAGE KEEPS THE ACTION COMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Nicolas Cage in a scene from ``Snake
Eyes.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He doesn't mind being called a movie star.
 &HT;    A lot of big names insist on being considered actors, not stars.
And with a Best Actor Oscar for ``Leaving Las Vegas'' (1995),
Nicolas Cage is more entitled than most to make that distinction.
But he insists that he doesn't have any problem with Hollywood
stardom.
 &HT;    ``I've been acting professionally since I was 17, and I've sort
of slowly grown up in the industry,'' says Cage, now 34 and the
most unlikely member of the elite A-list, $20-million-per-film
contingent. ``Nothing has been overnight, so I'm comfortable with
everything that's happened.
 &HT;    ``I'd better be comfortable, because I can't go back,'' he adds.
``I've got projects that excite me and am working with directors
who are wonderful, so I'm where I want to be.''
 &HT;    Cage is in the midst of a remarkable hot streak that encompasses
``Leaving Las Vegas,'' ``The Rock'' (1996), ``Con Air'' (1997),
``Face/Off'' (1997) and, most recently, ``City of Angels'' (1998).
He's proven not only his range but also his popularity with
audiences who have followed him from drama to action to
otherworldly romance.
 &HT;    On August 7, Cage returns to action with Brian De Palma's
thriller, ``Snake Eyes.'' The film casts Cage as Rick Santoro, an
on-the-take Atlantic City cop who joins his pal, Navy Cmdr. Kevin
Dunne (Gary Sinise), to unravel _ on the spot _ the assassination
of the Secretary of Defense during a major boxing match.
 &HT;    ``I'd just played the angel in `City of Angels,' and that was
more of a reserved, introverted performance,'' Cage says as he
settles into a chair at the Four Seasons Hotel in Beverly Hills.
 &HT;    ``I felt liberated when I knew I'd be playing Rick Santoro,''
the actor recalls. ``I got into the character's rust-colored suit
and the Hawaiian jacket, and I thought, `This guy feels good, he's
the king of the city. I can have some fun with him.'
 &HT;    ``My friends who've seen the film said, `It's the old Nic
again,''' he says. ``Maybe I'm back to my `Wild at Heart' (1990)
days.''
 &HT;    Deserved or not _ and it's an eminently debatable point _ De
Palma has a reputation as a director who provides style over
substance. Cage acknowledges that reputation, but considers it
unwarranted.
 &HT;    ``Brian loves actors, and you feel this sense of trust from
him,'' he says. ``I felt safe that I could go for it, that he'd
print the right take and I wouldn't be embarrassed.
 &HT;    ``I've never understood the feeling that his technical expertise
overshadows his actors,'' Cage adds. ``My opinion of his previous
films and my experience with him was that he's equally devoted to
the camera and the actors.
 &HT;    ``At one point we shot a scene and then went to lunch, and I
wasn't thrilled with what I did but didn't say anything,'' the
actor recalls. ``I came back from lunch ready to shoot the next
scene, and Brian said, `Let's do that last scene again.'
 &HT;    ``And I nailed it,'' Cage says appreciatively. ``During lunch
Brian noticed that the scene didn't quite work, and we redid it.
That to me is not a director concerned with the technical aspects
at the expense of the performances.''
 &HT;    Though Cage played standard-issue heroes in ``The Rock'' and
``Con Air,'' lately he's been returning to some of the sort of
risky performance choices that made him so intriguing a screen
presence early in his career. He chewed every last bit of scenery
in ``Face/Off,'' went New Age in ``City of Angels'' and is all
jittery energy in ``Snake Eyes.''
 &HT;    Of course, it's one thing to take risks in low-budget,
early-career ventures such as ``Valley Girl'' (1982), ``Raising
Arizona'' (1987), ``Moonstruck'' (1987) and ``Vampire's Kiss''
(1989). It's another thing entirely to do it with the whole world
watching, at $20 million a pop.
 &HT;    ``That's a reality or, at least, a state of mind that's
impossible to deny,'' Cage says, a sly grin crossing his face.
``The worries are there, but I've thought a lot about it and I'm
not so sure my work in `Face/Off' or even `Snake Eyes' is that
mainstream.
 &HT;    ``There were some things I did in `Face/Off' that were direct
steals from `Vampire's Kiss,''' he insists. ``So I think that my
independent background was a laboratory to cut my teeth and learn
what I could do and how I could express myself.
 &HT;    ``I can still tap into that edge and use it, even if the stakes
are higher now.''
 &HT;    Cage used to tell interviewers that his performances were
offbeat because he himself was offbeat.
 &HT;    ``Like many of us, I've sometimes had a feeling of being a
little different,'' he says. ``When I was in school I was always
considered imaginative or offbeat.
 &HT;    ``Today when I meet people, they actually say that I seem quite
normal,'' he says. ``I've changed. I think everybody changes. It's
impossible not to live and grow and change.''
 &HT;    Cage smiles.
 &HT;    ``I'm not the same kid I was when I was 17,'' he says after a
moment. ``I'm 34 now, and in growing up you go through all kinds of
maturation processes.
 &HT;    ``The thing about being famous is that whatever you say in the
press when you're 17 stays there,'' he adds, ``but that 17-year-old
is not the same person as the 34-year-old.''
 &HT;    Cage will next be seen in ``8mm'' _ pronounced ``eight
millimeter'' _ a dark drama about the world of snuff films. With
the much-discussed ``Superman'' feature grounded indefinitely due
to budget concerns, Cage will spend this fall shooting ``Bringing
Out the Dead,'' in which he'll play a burned-out paramedic.
 &HT;    The latter film reunites the ``Taxi Driver'' team of director
Martin Scorsese and screenwriter Paul Schrader. After it, Cage's
plans are murkier. He may play Howard Hughes in De Palma's
biography of the eccentric billionaire or star in and produce a
big-screen version of the beloved television sitcom, ``The
Courtship of Eddie's Father.''
 &HT;    So busy is Cage at the moment that he admits that his family is
getting the short end of the stick, especially his wife, actress
Patricia Arquette.
 &HT;    ``You know what? I am fitting life into career now,'' he says,
``but that will change. All of us in the business, if we're really
lucky, get a certain pocket where you're hot and get the roles you
want.
 &HT;    ``I'm going to be 40 in six years,'' the actor adds, ``so now is
the time to make my mark, to really strike. After that I will
probably have more time to myself, to do outside things, to slow
down.''
 &HT;    In the meantime, he's grateful to have a wife who understands
the business firsthand.
 &HT;    ``You kind of have to hope that the people around you, close to
you, understand the position you're in,'' he says. ``At some point
I'd like to blend the two and do a film with Patricia. We're trying
to find a way to do that.
 &HT;    ``In general, though, I feel that I made the right choice in
working as much as I have been.''
 &HT;    Cage shakes his head, lost in thought.
 &HT;    ``I feel older than 34, much older,'' he says. ``That's a good
thing and a bad thing: Because I've been working so hard since I
was 17, I haven't had a lot of play time.
 &HT;    ``But acting has given me a responsibility and a maturity,
perhaps even a wisdom, that I'm very thankful for,'' Cage says.
``So I'm happy.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
