<HEADER>
A5084 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMIE-LEE-CURTIS-IN-H     07-27 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMIE-LEE-CURTIS-IN-HALLOWEEN-H20-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCREAM GIRL: THE RETURN OF JAMIE LEE CURTIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jamie Lee Curtis in a scene from
``Halloween: H20.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It takes a lot to frighten Jamie Lee Curtis.
 &HT;    Don't try to spook the original teen scream queen with dark
shadows, strange sounds or even slashing knives.
 &HT;    ``I can watch gore all day long,'' she says. ``I can watch Linda
Blair's head spin around in `The Exorcist' until it falls off.''
 &HT;    No wonder, though. As the star of the seminal ``Halloween''
(1978) and ``Halloween II'' (1981), not to mention lesser chillers
such as ``Prom Night,'' ``Terror Train'' and ``The Fog'' (all
1980), she's been there, done that.
 &HT;    And now she's back there, back doing that. ``Halloween: H20,''
opening on Aug. 7, picks up her character, Laurie Strode, 20 years
after the events of the first two films in the series. She's the
mother of a teen-age son and, understandably, still has some
psychological issues to work out from her past.
 &HT;    Looking lovely in navy pants and a cashmere tank top, her hair
short and spiky, Curtis explains over coffee on an early Sunday
morning at Los Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel that the movie was, in a
way, a return to her roots. It was ``Halloween,'' after all, that
made the daughter of Tony Curtis and Janet Leigh a star in her own
right.
 &HT;    ``It was strange,'' she says, ``but about three years ago, a
friend of mine mentioned, `Did you know that ``Halloween'' is about
to hit its 20th anniversary?'''
 &HT;    Intrigued, Curtis met with Miramax chief Bob Weinstein, who at
the time was finishing postproduction work on a little-touted movie
called ``Scream'' (1996).
 &HT;    ``I said to Bob, `A lot of bad stuff happens to the young women
in horror films and then everybody just goes home. And nobody ever
thinks of the fact that Laurie Strode survived. She has been alive
for 20 years.'
 &HT;    ``To me we had an opportunity to show what happens to a
victim,'' Curtis says. ``There are real people out there who are
very damaged and who go through these experiences. They try to live
a normal life _ they get married, they have children. But you can't
have a normal life when your soul is taken away from you.''
 &HT;    Curtis smiles.
 &HT;    ``I know I should probably be lighter about all of this, because
it's a `Halloween' movie,'' she admits, ``but I take this very
seriously. To me this sequel is not just about a nutjob who is
running around with an ax. It's really about what happens when
everything that is good is taken away from a young person. Laurie
lost her trust, her courage and her ability to love.''
 &HT;    To prepare, Curtis did something she had avoided for almost 20
years: She watched all the old ``Halloween'' films. She also
practiced her scream, which is as blood-curdling as ever.
 &HT;    Curtis laughs.
 &HT;    ``I actually did a Planet Hollywood appearance recently, and for
the first time in my public life, I screamed outside the work,''
she says. ``It felt very weird. I actually went home and said, `Why
did I do that?' Somehow it sounded fake to me.''
 &HT;    Curtis wasn't the only slasher-movie veteran on set. Janet
Leigh, best known for ``Psycho'' (1960), has a hilarious cameo as
her daughter's secretary.
 &HT;    ``You know, my mom is the best,'' Curtis says. ``My mom is from
a very meager background. She made sure I grew up in a very normal
way. I know it sounds a little Pollyanna-ish, but both of us are
really appreciative that we had careers.
 &HT;    ``For her and I to share a genre that is the pinnacle of both of
our careers is a joy,'' Curtis adds.
 &HT;    The actress grew up outside of Los Angeles as the daughter of
Hollywood royalty. Inside her own office these days are old Screen
Stories magazines featuring pictures of Leigh, a baby Jamie and
sister Kelly. The headline on one: ``Janet Leigh says: We Are One
of the Three Happiest Families In Hollywood.''
 &HT;    That wasn't exactly the case. Curtis was only 4 when her parents
divorced. Eventually Leigh married businessman Robert Brandt, and
the family stabilized. Still, there are scars from her parents'
breakup.
 &HT;    ``When I sit down to write children's books, my mind immediately
goes to the age of 4,'' says Curtis, whose new book ``Today I Feel
Silly'' is due out this fall. ``Age 4 is when my family split up
for good. I think you never get over that feeling of loss.''
 &HT;    The 40-year-old Curtis has sworn to spare her children such
loss. She and her husband, director Christopher Guest, have two
children, 11-year-old Annie and 2-year-old Tom, and Curtis says
they're her top concern.
 &HT;    ``It's really all about my children,'' she says. ``Chris and I
don't do the social side of Hollywood at all. We live a quiet life.
We don't seek attention.''
 &HT;    Oh, and don't worry, the kids won't be seeing ``Halloween:
H20.''
 &HT;    ``I want my daughter to feel safe in the world,'' Curtis says.
``I have a real problem introducing images into her world that are
disturbing and fearful. As soon as she hits 14 or 15, she can start
to understand right and wrong, fiction and nonfiction. But she is
11.
 &HT;    ``I'm not sure if the opening scene of `Scream' or `H20' are
images I want in her world,'' Curtis adds. ``What good could
possibly come from her seeing that stuff?''
 &HT;    It's only fair: Curtis didn't see ``Psycho'' until she was in
her late teens.
 &HT;    ``I remember my mother never wanting me to see it,'' Curtis
says. ``But I caught the movie on the late-late show, and I was
horrified. Even worse was that my mother had one of those
shot-by-shot books from `Psycho.' I remember looking in that book
as a little kid and freaking out.
 &HT;    ``I've never seen `Psycho' on the big screen and never will,''
Curtis says. ``I mean, that's my mom up there.''
 &HT;    One other thing: Even if her character survives the latest
``Halloween,'' don't expect to see Curtis in a new string of
sequels.
 &HT;    ``This is the end for me,'' she insists. ``Let Neve Campbell be
the new scream queen.''
 &HT;    Actually, Curtis says, she doesn't like sequels in general. The
only one that might interest her would be ``True Lies II.''
 &HT;    ``I would love to re-examine that character, because I took a
lot of hits,'' she says. ``People said because I did a strip scene
that it was demeaning to women. I thought this was one of the
strongest women I've ever played.''
 &HT;    To date, anyway. In the upcoming ``Virus,'' Curtis gets to do
some big-time action scenes. In fact, through that film she's
realized a longtime goal: having her own action figure.
 &HT;    ``Do you know that scene in `Jerry Maguire' where Tom Cruise
says to the girl, `You complete me?'''
 &HT;    She smiles.
 &HT;    ``Well, that's how I felt about my doll,'' she says. ``I looked
at her and said, `You complete me.'''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
