<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADRIAN-LYNE-DIRECTS-LOLITA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADRIAN LYNE BRAVES A HURRICANE CALLED `LOLITA' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Adrian Lyne directing a scene from
``Lolita.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Adrian Lyne slumps gratefully into a chair in a Pasadena hotel
suite.
 &HT;    ``Thank God, it's cool in here,'' he says with a sigh.
 &HT;    The heat has been on Lyne for several years now, all on account
of ``Lolita.'' It's taken two years and recourse to the small
screen to bring his adaptation of the Vladimir Nabokov novel to
American audiences, after Hollywood waffled at the thought of
distributing a movie about a grown man's lust for a 12-year-old
girl.
 &HT;    The controversial, $58 million film will premiere Aug. 2 on
Showtime, which is billing it as the most expensive first-run film
ever on cable. It will also receive limited theatrical release to
qualify for Academy Awards consideration.
 &HT;    It's not as if the 57-year-old director is a stranger to
controversy. After all, he's the man who shook audiences with Kim
Basinger and Mickey Rourke's explicit pawings in ``Nine 1/2 Weeks''
(1986), shocked them with equally steamy sex between Michael
Douglas and Glenn Close in ``Fatal Attraction'' (1987) and then
paired Demi Moore and Robert Redford for ``Indecent Proposal''
(1993), which suggested that the price of a good woman's virtue
might be $1 million.
 &HT;    But no previous ruckus compared to the flap raised by
``Lolita,'' which stars Jeremy Irons as Humbert Humbert and
newcomer Dominique Swain as the provocative Lolita.
 &HT;    ``In my films, I've explored vulnerability and weakness in
relationships,'' the director says, ``and it becomes a bit puzzling
when people just isolate the sexuality.
 &HT;    ``People are forever talking about the sex scene between Michael
and Glenn in `Fatal Attraction,''' he adds. ``They all fixate on
it, but it only consumes about two minutes of screen time.
 &HT;    ``I live in France a good deal of the time, and the French don't
seem to have the same obsession with sex that Americans do,'' Lyne
continues. ``I don't mean everyone isn't interested in sex, and
there's no reason why they shouldn't be. But here, and I guess in
England too, it somehow becomes associated with guilt. So I get
accused of making smutty movies.''
 &HT;    That's not new for ``Lolita,'' which was the subject of
censorship battles as a 1950s novel and as a 1962 film. Director
Stanley Kubrick's version had no sex scenes whatever. In fact,
under pressure from the Hays Office, Kubrick wasn't even permitted
to show an onscreen kiss between James Mason and Sue Lyon.
 &HT;    ``Naturally, there have been a lot of comparisons between my
version and Kubrick's,'' Lyne says. ``That's difficult for me to
talk about because, although I admire Stanley tremendously, his
`Lolita' is not one of my favorite films.
 &HT;    ``I fought to keep the sex scenes between Jeremy and Dominique
because I thought they were essential,'' he says. ``People seem
uncomfortable that they seem erotic. I realized they had to be,
because we're seeing this through Humbert Humbert's eyes. Lolita is
his erotic obsession. That has to be shown.''
 &HT;    Lyne chuckles.
 &HT;    ``The irony is that Jeremy and I felt a lot more uncomfortable
than Dominique did,'' he says, smiling. ``She never seemed to have
an anxious moment. Her mother and her teacher were always right
there with her.
 &HT;    ``There was never any contact between her and Jeremy,'' he adds,
``because we had this thing called `the pad' that separated their
bodies. When it came to the glimpses of Lolita nude, we used a body
double.''
 &HT;    He pauses for a moment.
 &HT;    ``But I remember the scene when Dominique first really kissed
Jeremy, with her tongue in his mouth and everything,'' he says.
``We had talked about how she had already given a boyfriend a
French kiss, so she knew what it was all about. But when we rolled
the camera, Dominique kissed Jeremy with such gusto that the crew
was sort of stunned, as was I. You could hear an audible gasp on
the set.''
 &HT;    Defining the limits of what he could actually show in a theater
was a challenge, Lyne admits.
 &HT;    ``It's an R-rated movie, not an NC-17,'' he says. ``I spent five
or six weeks in the editing room with an attorney, going over every
frame of the sex scenes. I took out a bit here and a piece there.
The result has already been shown in Europe, and you'll see exactly
the same version on Showtime.''
 &HT;    Lyne remains hopeful that viewers will see beyond the sex to
discover a story that encompasses much more.
 &HT;    ``In his novel, Nabokov makes you horrified by what Humbert does
to Lolita,'' he says reflectively. ``You recoil from it. Yet you
also occasionally find yourself laughing and, ultimately, you begin
to feel a sort of sympathy for this man.
 &HT;    ``You begin to understand that he really did love Lolita in his
screwed-up way,'' the director says. ``I think that, if she had
stayed with him, he would have been faithful to her to his dying
day.
 &HT;    ``There's a kind of redemption for Humbert at the end,'' he
concludes. ``I think you feel that in my film, and I think that's
something that Kubrick never achieved in his.
 &HT;    ``Perhaps what's disturbing about what I've put up on the screen
is that there are so many shades of gray,'' Lyne adds. ``The
audience finds itself reluctantly sympathizing with a man they feel
awkward about sympathizing with. That's why the novel makes you
uncomfortable, and that's why the film makes you uncomfortable.''
 &HT;    Part of the problem with finding an American distributor for the
film was bad timing. ``Lolita'' was completed at almost the same
time that the nation was horrified by the killing of tiny JonBenet
Ramsey in Boulder, Colo., and shocked by the revelation of the
murders of children held captive by a child-pornography ring in
Belgium.
 &HT;    ``There's a sensitivity toward child abuse in the '90s that I'm
not sure we ever had before to this degree,'' the director admits.
``I saw a TV show not long ago on which kids were being instructed
about how to react when touched by an adult in certain ways. It's
easy for that to blossom into over-reaction.''
 &HT;    Lyne recalls a recent situation in which he felt exactly that
kind of response.
 &HT;    ``I was in a restaurant in France,'' he says. ``I saw a girl of
about 13 in her father's lap, kind of flinging her arms around him
and giving him a kiss. I suddenly found myself a bit put off,
wondering what was going on. Five years ago, I wouldn't have given
it a second thought.
 &HT;    ``Kids should be protected,'' he concludes, ``but I think
there's a case for overprotection.''
 &HT;    The little-seen, very expensive ``Lolita'' has proven something
of a millstone to Lyne, consuming years of his career. He admits to
ambivalence about the whole experience.
 &HT;    ``It's been a tough ride,'' he says. ``If I had known in the
beginning all that it was going to require, I might not have taken
the ride.
 &HT;    ``But I'm incredibly happy to have brought Nabokov's novel to a
wider audience,'' the director adds. ``It's so extraordinary and I
know it will endure, even if the film doesn't.''
 &HT;    He sighs.
 &HT;    ``This is a tough act to follow,'' he admits. ``I'm not sure
what I'll tackle next, because it's been so hard to let go of
`Lolita.' In the end, if just a few scenes in the movie hold a
candle to what Nabokov put on paper, then it's all been
worthwhile.''
 c.1998 Pentacom Productions  
