<SLUG> BC-FISHING-WITH-JOHN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ZEN OF `FISHING WITH JOHN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of host John Lurie and singer Tom Waits in a
scene from ``Fishing With John.'' 
 By CHARLES STRUM  
 c.1998 The New York Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To grasp ``Fishing With John,'' a six-part series of loopy water
safaris on the Independent Film Channel, it helps to understand the
Lurie principle, named for the creator, co-star and director of the
show, John Lurie.
</P>
<P>
   It is this: Life is like fishing. If you just sit there,
something is bound to occur to you.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe this is not the Lurie principle. A chat with the
45-year-old Lurie, an actor and saxophonist _ his avant-garde jazz
band, the Lounge Lizards, recently released a new CD called ``Queen
of All Ears'' _ will not clarify much about the creative process,
his or anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   But then, who cares? ``Fishing With John,'' whose initial six
episodes are airing on IFC throughout August, is not about clarity
as much as it is about spending corporate money to film improbable
fishing vacations with your pals.
</P>
<P>
   In the first four installments, each running 30 minutes, Lurie
invited filmmaker Jim Jarmusch to Montauk, Long Island, to fish for
blue shark. Singer Tom Waits came to Jamaica for red snapper. Actor
Matt Dillon went to Costa Rica for snook and tarpon, while fellow
actor Willem Dafoe headed for Maine for ice fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Dafoe episode is perhaps the most startling
moment in the series. After 11 days of failure outside their
do-it-yourself hobo's shed on a frozen lake, the two men die of
starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the final, two-part episode, a special trip to
Thailand with actor Dennis Hopper, opens with the purposely
intrusive narrator _ the unctuous, generic, true-life-adventure
voice of Robb Webb _ saying, ``I made a mistake. John is still
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus relieved, viewers are off on the last great quest of the
series, ``in search of the elusive giant squid.'' Please note:
Hopper and Lurie have chosen to stalk their prey, a 60-foot
behemoth that lives miles below the surface, with spinning reels
and fiberglass rods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's partly a travelogue _ a surreal travelogue _ partly a
play, like a kids' play,'' Lurie says in a telephone interview from
New York. ``You know, like you build a fort in your living room
with your best friend when you're 10?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're attacking macho,'' he says of the shows. ``They're
also an interview show. Each one has a myth to it, almost like a
folklore thing to it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for scripts, Lurie says, ``I never told anybody to say
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   This is probably true. Here's an example from one of many quiet
interludes, as Hopper and Lurie, whose vacation wardrobe looks as
if it were designed by Kramer of ``Seinfeld,'' enjoy an impromptu
chat.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie: ``Why do you think that when people go on vacation they
wear the most ridiculous clothes? Things they would never wear.
It's like, you know, `Well, I'm a bank clerk, so I'm going wild
when I go on my vacation, shock people with my colorful shorts.'
You think that's what it is?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not really interested in this conversation?''
</P>
<P>
   Hopper: ``Not really.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it is. You figured it out, and I'm agreeing with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thailand jaunt provides ample illustration of Lurie's need
to be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know we were going after giant squid,'' he says.
``We could have been trying out for the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the filming, he and Hopper came across some
monks, but their conversation was inadvertently not recorded.
Later, during editing, Lurie decided to have the narrator explain
that the two fishermen had come upon an ``order of squid monks''
and had asked them for the secret to finding the giant squid, but
``the monks only showed them photographs of their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Lurie reports that the series has been shown at theaters in
Japan, where it's a big hit. In fact, he says, the productions were
underwritten by a Japanese company, Telecom Japan, ``that makes
weird travel shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no clue,'' he adds cheerfully. ``I don't know why
they did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Will there be more shows? Lurie hopes so, and adds that he
already knows whom he'd like to invite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noam Chomsky and Gorbachev,'' he says. ``I want to use the
wine spot on his head as a map.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Charles Strum reports on entertainment for The New York
Times.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
