A5096 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NADER-MUSEUM-2TAKES-N     07-27 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-MUSEUM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NADER ENVISIONS TORT LAW MUSEUM AS TOURIST LURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   (bl)  
 By JONATHAN RABINOWITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTED, Conn. _ At first glance, only a first-year law student
whose sole ambition is to make law review would appear to be a
likely visitor to a museum here in rural Connecticut dedicated to
the seemingly arcane topic of tort law.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it would be hard to blame the people of this old mill
town if they seem a bit skeptical that a proposed museum to honor
some of the most reviled professionals in the country _ trial
lawyers _ was a surefire way to transform their downtown into a
mecca for weekend visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But listen to Ralph Nader, Winsted's town's most famous native
son, as he details his dream of a Museum of American Tort Law and
brings his passion, which launched the consumer movement, to the
unlikely cause of making personal injury law into a tourist
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be the Pinto with the exploding gas tank, flammable
pajamas, asbestos and breast implants, the whole history of medical
malpractice, and of course the more recent toxic pollution, like
Love Canal,'' Nader said in a telephone interview, sounding like a
carnival barker reeling off a litany of horrors that could rival
the more macabre exhibits at Madame Tussaud's.
</P>
<P>
   The project manager, Dr. Fred Hyde, remarked that there even
would be a gift shop that would sell ``the tschatchkes of tort
law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, like models of defective toys, products that were
taken off the market,'' added Hyde, a consultant with degrees in
both medicine and law. ``We don't want to trivialize it, but we
want to have a way to memorialize the visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader's vision for a family trip, of course, has a distinctly
political edge. He has begun a $10 million fund-raising effort for
the museum at a time when the rights of citizens to sue large
corporations for faulty products is very much under attack.
Business groups, whom Nader has dubbed ``tort deformers,'' have
been pushing Congress to pass legislation that could restrict the
amount of damages a plaintiff could win in such suits.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, scheduled to open in late 1999 or early 2000,
clearly is intended to cast a more positive light on the practices
that have resulted in large jury awards to consumers who bought
questionable products, not to mention the lucrative fees for the
lawyers who championed them.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, proponents of tort reform dismiss the whole idea as
little more than propaganda for trial lawyers. ``Mr. Nader should
make sure to have ample parking space for trial lawyers' his and
her Lear jets,'' mocked Lester Brickman, a professor at Benjamin N.
Cardozo School of Law at Yeshiva University, who has argued that
lawyers contingency fees are too high.
</P>
<P>
   And other critics have wondered aloud about the potential perils
of opening such a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Would it be able to serve hot coffee in a museum cafe for fear
of scalding customers' mouths? How can display cases be built
without sharp corners that could accidentally cut scrambling
children? And will lawyers whose work is portrayed not to their
liking sue for defamation?
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of this small city in the foothills of the
Berkshire Mountains, residents were a bit puzzled by the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually no one here is happy that the old factory building
that would house the museum has been all but vacant for years.
Built in the late 19th century to manufacture gold and silver
fixtures for coffins, it is on a prominent downtown corner, across
from a pool hall and an auto parts store, right on the banks of the
Mad River.
</P>
<P>
   In more than a dozen interviews, local citizens generally
remarked that a tort museum was better than nothing. Still, people
were confused about what exactly they were getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a tort?'' said Monique Goulet, 20, a clerk at Ivery &AMP;
Dudley Pharmacy on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't they the blue laws?'' asked Bill Wood, owner of the
nearby Deluxe Package Store.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, tort does not refer to laws regulating moral behavior,
nor to a cake made with many eggs and often grated nuts or dry
bread crumbs and usually covered with a rich frosting. It is a
legal term for a wrongful act that can be the basis of a civil
lawsuit, though its exact place in jurisprudence is very much up
for debate.
</P>
<P>
   For some, tort means justice and restitution. One pharmacy
clerk, who thought that people could learn a lot from such a
museum, described torts as ``the laws that protect the little
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader, who rose to prominence in 1965 with his book ``Unsafe at
Any Speed,'' revealing the design flaws of the Chevrolet Corvair
and other automobiles, called the American tort system the ``best
system in the world,'' a pillar of United States democracy that is
not adequately appreciated by the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tort law, the law of personal injury, was a major step on the
march to justice,'' Nader, a 64-year-old graduate of Harvard Law
School, explained. ``There's been a lot of attention to civil
liberties but not to physical integrity - how our law protects the
physical integrity of human beings from harmful behavior, unsafe
products, toxic chemical or auto crashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Others believe tort means little more than big money for
lawyers. They charge that big settlements lead to frivolous suits
and that the system creates huge costs for business, which
discourage companies from innovating.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lagassey, a 32-year-old machinist who was born and
raised here, said he appreciated Nader's efforts, though he would
prefer to see the building reopen as a factory. ``There's too much
suing,'' he said. ``What we need is jobs.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is unlikely that many manufacturing jobs will return
to Winsted, once an independent small city but now a section of the
town of Winchester, population 11,000, about 24 miles northwest of
Hartford. While Winsted had years ago been a place that made
clocks, knives and woolen clothes, it today is a poor pocket in
tony Litchfield County, a haven for New Yorkers with country homes.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's father, a Lebanese immigrant who died in 1991, ran a
restaurant here. His mother, Rose, and sister, Claire, still live
here. Another sister, Laura, an anthropology professor at the
University of California, Berkeley, spends summers here. And the
family is well-known in this town, though not always well-loved,
for its involvement in local politics.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's late brother Shafeek is credited with bringing a
community college to the town in the 1960s, over much local
opposition. A decade ago, the Naders fought unsuccessfully to stop
the town from tearing down an old school, and more recently they
have spearheaded _ with mixed success _ an effort to maintain a
local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A Nader family foundation, Northeast Highlands Resources
Preservation Trust, purchased the empty factory building in the
early 1980s with the goal of using it to encourage the development
of small businesses. That effort has yielded little results, and
the only people in the building are three public interest lawyers,
who work on community and agricultural projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``That building has sat empty too long,'' said Noreen
Lampognana, a 61-year-old Winsted native, who was curious to learn
more about the tort museum. ``The Naders have done some nice things
for this town,'' she added, though cautioning that their ideas
sometimes raise people's ire. ``They're very intelligent, maybe too
intelligent to the degree that a lot of common people think they're
eccentric.''
</P>
<P>
   While some local people wondered who would come to this museum,
its boosters maintain that educational tourism is a booming
industry and that the number of specialty museums has grown rapidly
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Spamtown U.S.A., a museum honoring Hormel Food Corp.'s most
famous product, attracted more than 60,000 visitors last year, and
is being expanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has a lantern museum, a garlic museum, 63 medical
museums and 31 lumber and timber museums, not to mention a museum
on every conceivable sport,'' said Nader. ``But no law museum.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that comes close, Nader added, was the exhibition
area in the basement of the American Bar Association in Chicago,
which he described as a ``cubby hole.'' Tort law ``has a a great
history, and there's nothing covering it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nader last month started to send letters to potential
supporters, describing the museum. He also has solicited design
proposals from several prominent museum design firms.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to raise $5 million by the end of the year that will
be used to renovate the factory building, as well as to establish
an endowment to fund outreach programs, establish a web site and
cover administration costs. In the future, Nader said he hopes to
raise another $5 million so that the museum can lease exhibition
space in Washington and hold conferences in Winsted.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is supposed to provide an interactive experience,
said Hyde, the project manager, who has both medical and law
degrees, with re-enactment of famous trials. Visitors could
actually sit in a real jury panel, Nader exclaimed, and hear the
same testimony that actual jurors once heard.
</P>
<P>
   (``Donahue suggested that,'' Nader added, referring to the
former television talk show host, Phil Donahue, who has made a
pledge to the museum.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, there will be artifacts, Hyde promised, noting that he
wanted to find a vintage Corvair or an old Pinto fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
   Already lawyers are calling to donate trial exhibits to the
museum's collection. ``I just had a call from a fellow who wanted
to send a defective refrigerator,'' said Hyde. ``Everyone has a
case somewhere. These are real things that happened to real people,
these things can all be memorialized.''
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers have to capture a jury's interest, and there are
warehouses full of elaborate trial displays across the country,
Hyde said. '
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, they're like Hollywood,'' he added. ``Like seeing
Spielberg in a courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader insisted it would be riveting. ``This has all the drama
that television has _ industrial violence, the battle between
corporations and lonely litigants and exceptional lawyers,'' he
said. ``This is David versus Goliath. These are stories of great
human triumph.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
