<HEADLINE>
HOUSES PASSES BENEFITS FOR WIDOWS OF SLAIN OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House approved Monday a special benefit of a
year's pay, tax free, to the widows of the two Capitol Police
officers who were slain last week.
</P>
<P>
   The widow of Detective John M. Gibson will receive $51,866, and
the widow of Private First Class Jacob J. Chestnut, $47,280.
</P>
<P>
   The House resolution also formally establishes a memorial fund
for the officers' widows and children. Gibson and Chestnut were the
first Capitol Police officers to die in the line of duty since the
creation of the police force more than 100 years ago. Donations can
be sent to the US Capitol Police Memorial Fund, Washington, D.C.
20515.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gibson and Chestnut were 18-year veterans of the Capitol
Police. Gibson, 42, leaves his wife, Evelyn, and three children, a
17-year-old daughter and two sons, ages 12 and 14. Evelyn Gibson is
the niece of Representative J. Joseph Moakley, a South Boston
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, 58, who was within months of retirement, is survived
by his wife, Wen, their two children, and three children from a
previous marriage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
