<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Tuesday, July 28. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
IMMIGRANT-BOMBS - In deadly summer heat, illegal immigrants
crossing the southern Arizona desert are increasingly at risk of
being blown up by bombs. Rising numbers of trespassers are
traveling through the Chocolate Mountain Aerial Gunnery Range
northwest of Yuma, a site controlled by the U.S. Marine Corps but
used by all military branches, even NATO, to train bombing pilots.
The danger is advertised on warning signs in Spanish in English,
but that hasn't deterred crossers. In just two weeks between June
19 and July, the Border Patrol picked up nearly 350 people on or
near the range. By GRACIELA SEVILLA. Story will move in the ``A''
category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
ABORTION-POLITICS (Undated) - In a political climate of mounting
restrictions against abortion and escalating violence at clinics,
some abortion-rights supporters foresee a day when abortion is
legal but offered only by an underground network of doctors. In
fact, that is the new strategy that has been adopted by abortion
opponents, the same critics say, and it's working. In Arizona,
abortion is readily available only in Phoenix, Tucson, and
Flagstaff. The result, critics say, is that women have fewer
choices and are increasingly likely to turn to clinics like the one
in Phoenix in which a patient of Dr. John Biskind's bled to death.
With ABORTION-MEDICINE. By CHRIS MOESER. Story will move in the
``A`` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ABORTION-MEDICINE (Undated) - Access to safe abortions is
threatened by the lack of qualified doctors who perform the
procedure, and that could lead to increased incidents like the one
in Phoenix in which a woman bled to death from a punctured uterus,
supporters of women's reproductive rights say. Dr. Beth Weber,
medical services director for Planned Parenthood of Central and
Northern Arizona, said part of the problem is historical ignorance
by young doctors entering practice. ``Most of the younger
physicians are unaware of the pre-Roe (vs. Wade) days when women
did seek illegal abortions,`' she said. ``They don't understand the
repercussions when abortion is not provided and not provided
safely.`` By Vanessa DeRuyter. Story will move inthe ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BRADY (Undated) - Potential buyers of shotguns and rifles, take
heed: if you make your purchase Nov. 30 or later, your background
will be checked by law enforcement agencies. If you didn't know
this was coming, you're far from alone. By CHARLES KELLY. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ALARMS (Phoenix) - If you believe the numbers, Phoenix-area
homeowners have more to fear from Christmas decorations, billowing
drapes, and feisty ferrets than from robbers. That's because 65
percent of the alarms called into Phoenix police are false, wasting
millions of dollars and thousands of hours annually. False reports
are now fined, and the worst offenders go to False Alarm School. By
HANNAH MILLER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ADS-OVERLOAD (Undated) - A new pizza delivery offer is
rubber-banded to your doorknob _ every day. Classified circulars
are so numbing they are slowly turning to mulch on your front lawn.
``Banner'' advertisements on the Internet are disguised to look
like computer upgrades. You have to wear a certain T-shirt to get
free popcorn at the movies. Rump roast is on sale at Albertson's.
The phone rings and a resonant recorded male voice says, ``Hello. .
.'' Americans are besieged by advertising, an estimated 600 to
1,200 commercial messages every day. By MARTIN VAN DER WERF. Story
will move in the ``F'' and ``K'' categories. &QL;
