A5103 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUTHERAN-KIDS-COX     07-27 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUTHERAN-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping the faith while keeping the faith
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA-- Kathryn Padberg bounced once and then laughed as her
feet slipped off a pogo stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hard!'' she exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Back up she went, and slipped again.
</P>
<P>
   And again. And again. And again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stilts were easier,'' she concluded, handing the pogo
stick to its next victim.
</P>
<P>
   Padberg, 18, came to Atlanta from Merrillville, Ind. to be part
of the 30,000-strong National Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod Youth
Gathering meeting through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a great time!'' she said. ``I have met so many
different people from so many different states! The high you get
from being here is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Every convention that comes to Atlanta should be so much fun:
</P>
<P>
   A carousel.
</P>
<P>
   Tricycle races.
</P>
<P>
   Music and dancing every night.
</P>
<P>
   All in the Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   But there's also Bible study in the Georgia Dome, food-sorting
at the Atlanta Food Bank and workshops on everything from
Adolescent Spirituality to the theology of ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat did not wither nor rain dampen the enthusiasm of the youth.
</P>
<P>
   They traveled in groups, some with matching T-shirts _ bright
yellow from Nebraska, Orange from Kansas, smoky blue from Southern
Illinois _ but all with the ubiquitous red back packs stuffed by
local volunteers. By noon Monday the Lost and Found department (not
to be confused with a band called Lost and Found that performed
Sunday night) had collected 18 of the backpacks, along with boxes
full of sunglasses, shirts, wallets, hotel keys and other assorted
droppings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where're y'all from?'' a boy in a red backpack asked, in a
cowboy accent, as he stood shoulder-to-armpit on a subway with
dozens of other backpack equipped teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minneso-o-ta, don'cha'know,'' replied a tall blonde girl,
speaking intentionally as if she just stepped onto the set of
``Fargo.'' ``Where'r'you from?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Waco, Texas,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was repeated on escalators and in food court lines,
standing on corners waiting for stoplights and sitting, with
numbers in hand, waiting to donate blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strengthens your faith to be around this many other people
who share the same faith','' said Luke Walta of Eau Claire, Wisc.,
a 20-year-old college student in a ``Satan Is Ugly as Sin'' T-shirt
who had just given a pint to the Red Cross. Walta, along as an
advisor, attended the last triennial youth gathering three years
ago in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the magnitude of it,'' said John Paluch, 16, from just
outside Houston. Paluch sat at a table gluing pieces of felt
together to make a ``story quilt'' in the Southern Culture area. He
pointed to a cross to represent Christ, a circle of braided red and
black strips to symbolize the struggle between good and evil, and a
flame that he said lights his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact that we can all get together and have a great
time and not really worry about drugs, sex or violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While organizers hope Paluch is right and there's no sex in the
hotel rooms, they made sure it was on the program. A group of girls
sat in an empty room 45 minutes early to make sure they got seats
to ``Chastity, Because You're Worth It,'' and inside a double
ballroom there was standing room only, with kids outside waiting
for the next session of ``Sex and Dating.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Bob Lenz read a Bible verse from 1 Corninthians about
sinning against the body, ``the temple of God.'' He laughed about
the awkwardness of first kisses and prayed about the destruction
caused by sexual abuse. He recounted his mother's talk to him about
sex when he was a teenager: ``Keep your pants up and your zipper
up. That's what my mom really said.'' And he told hundreds of
teen-agers that he has never had sexual intercourse with anyone
except his wife of 15 years. They cheered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing. It's indescribable,'' said Alexis Johnson, 15,
of DeKalb County who helped cover the gathering for a daily
newspaper, The Atlanta Call, being published by a teen-age staff
for the teen-age city inside the congress center. ``You have that
feeling inside that all these youth are here in the name of the
Lord. They are not ashamed to say they believe in God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're well behaved. They ain't wild,'' said congress center
cleaning worker Michelle Haynes as she stood, broom and dustpan in
hand, sweeping up bits of trash in an exhibit hall full of
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're cool,'' said her co-worker, Sharon Sims.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sure are happy,'' said Haynes. ``They're happy,'' agreed
Sims, and they swept on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5104 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN28-COX     07-27 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Modern Library's list is just another list
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are a listing nation. Not in the maritime sense of a ship
taking on water, but in our mania for ranking things. Usually by
10s. We rank the 10 Best Steakhouses, 10 Best Beaches No One Knows
About (after which, everyone does), 10 Best Mutual Funds ...
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press started all this when it began ranking the
Top 10 college football teams. Sportswriters who had never seen
most of the teams play, even on television, would decree week by
week who was best, who was second best, who was third, fourth,
fifth ... all the way down, now, to No. 25. In time it's liable to
become the Top 100, just like the Modern Library's list of the best
English-language novels of the century.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, football or literature, it's hard to come off
magisterial when you're pinning a tail on a donkey. You're safe
with Nebraska and Florida State, but beyond that is anybody's
guess.
</P>
<P>
   That being so, you'd expect a certain randomness and anarchy.
Instead, as most know but will not admit, a good bit of looking
over the shoulder goes on. (``Where've you got Washington State?''
``I've got A&AMP;M at No. 6. Think that's too high?'')
</P>
<P>
   So it goes, as Kurt Vonnegut would say, with literary lists.
James Joyce at No. 1, with ``Ulysses.'' Also at No. 3, with ``A
Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man.'' F. Scott Fitzgerald, whose
stock over the years has risen and plummeted and risen again, at a
surprising No. 2, with ``The Great Gatsby.'' But the real surprise
_ well, there were many, but this one took the chair out from under
me _ was Vladimir Nabokov at No. 4, with ``Lolita.'' The august
jury is telling us the century has seen but three novels in English
better than the story of a middle-aged man's obsession with a
13-year-old girl. Just three.
</P>
<P>
   For one reason or another, no one is happy with the nts. Even
so, one little thing gnaws at me, and I might as well say it: The
people who composed the jury simply have not read all those books.
</P>
<P>
   Assertions that cannot be proved are, obviously, hobbled from
the start. But it's an assertion in response to an implicit claim.
I don't take many things on faith. If it's incumbent on me, or
anyone else, to prove the jury hasn't read the material, it's
equally incumbent on the jury to give reason to believe its members
have read all 100 of those books.
</P>
<P>
   And not just those 100, but _ just as important _ several
hundred more. A ranking of 100 has no meaning outside a larger
context. In this case, that means a few hundred that did not make
it. How many unranked books? I don't think 400 is asking too much.
It's probably asking too little.
</P>
<P>
   So it would interest me to know which 400 other books
Christopher Cerf, Gore Vidal, Vartan Gregorian, William Styron,
A.S. Byatt and the rest of that jury have read cover to cover. Not
that these people aren't well read, mind you, but I just don't
believe any one of them, even the omnivorous Vidal, has read that
many. (It would be unkind to ask the same of the college kids who
got up their own list, something called the Radcliffe Publishing
Course list.)
</P>
<P>
   Do I cavil? I think not. It would have been fine with me had the
jury said, ``Look, folks, some of us have read more of these books
than others, we've talked to friends who've read books we missed,
and we've dredged up some old reviews in the Times. We've put our
heads together, and this is how it shakes out. See what you
think.''
</P>
<P>
   But the jury didn't do that, and, with few exceptions, neither
did it suggest why those books transcend the century. Is it because
of ideas given life in the story? Is it because of their artistic
merit as novels? Their influence on literature in English? On how
we view the world? ( I don't think, in many instances, it's because
they keep you up nights.)
</P>
<P>
   These aren't trivial questions. It's fairly clear why jurors
ranked Joyce's ``Ulysses'' No. 1. ``The watershed of the 20th
century from which all modernism flows,'' Styron pronounced. And
flows, he might have said, 'round and 'round, inasmuch as
circularity and return to origins are two of its motifs.
</P>
<P>
   But significance, after a point, becomes its own justification,
and that's never good. Once it does, words and meaning part
company. In some accounts of the Top 100, they split rather quickly
and that great all-purpose imponderable was pressed into service.
Thus, in its second paragraph, The New York Times called Joyce's
``Ulysses'' ``a metaphor for the human condition.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not tell us what the human condition was. It is not
exactly self-evident, any more than the significance of ``Lolita.''
Maybe someone should empanel a jury to rank the Top 100 nonsense
expressions in English. I vote ``the human condition'' No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
