<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rolling Stone: Gays not accepted as much in rural Georgia
counties
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The times they are a-changing _ at least everywhere but in
pockets of the South. When Sam Baldwin decided to come out of the
closet, the high school sophomore realized he could not go through
adolescence as a gay teenager in Cherokee County(Ga.). So he moved
in with his father in Cobb County(Ga.). Before he left, Baldwin
tells Rolling Stone ($3) contributing editor David Lipski, ``One
gay student got his mailbox crushed and his car tires slashed. I
didn't want to be the only one anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin has plenty of company, according to Lipski, who
interviewed more than 100 gay teens nationwide. In Atlanta, where
Lipski interviewed several teens who do their cruising around the
Tara shopping center, there is more acceptance. Not so in the
boondocks. ``Nobody ever used the word gay in Cairo,'' says Tom
White, who grew up in the small Georgia town. And in Heard
County(Ga.), Lipski was chased off the high school grounds by two
police officers when he tried to interview a gay student.
</P>
<P>
   -- In-depth coverage: National Geographic ($5) is famous for its
prize-winning photography, but this month's cover is truly
eye-popping. The landmark issue features 3-D images of the surface
of Mars and the wreck of the Titanic. Yes, you have to wear those
silly red-and-green cardboard glasses to view them, but the effect
is remarkable. Photographer Emory Kristof shot the Titanic using
paired video cameras on a 50-hour expedition at the bottom of the
Atlantic Ocean. In the Mars photographs, transmitted from the tiny
rover Sojourner, you can see everything but little green men.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lone gunman: In the aftermath of the Capitol shootout Friday,
Newsweek ($2.95) chose to feature a blurry photograph of accused
gunman Russell Eugene Weston Jr. on the cover. Time ($2.95) opted
to go with E. coli, and devoted five pages inside to as washing
your hands after handling raw meat and cooking hamburgers
thoroughly, Kluger stresses there's not much even the most
germ-wary person can do.
</P>
<P>
   -- By George: John F. Kennedy Jr. knows that sex sells.
Otherwise he wouldn't keep putting glamorous babes on the cover of
George ($2.95). But behind the glitter is a magazine that's solid
and sophisticated. The August issue features several compelling
articles, including a portrait of imprisoned Mary Kay Letourneau,
36, the teacher who fell in love with a 13-year-old student and is
pregnant with their second child. Also of note is ``A Mobster's
Last Resort,'' a fascinating portrait of turn-of-the-century Hot
Springs, Ark., when gangster Owen Madden used the town as a
playground.
</P>
<P>
   -- Quick reads: If you haven't read enough about Tom Hanks
lately, pick up the latest People ($2.79). The two-time Oscar
winner talks about love, work and, of course, ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' Entertainment Weekly ($2.79) reports that ``There's
Something About Mary'' is just another in a long line of gross-out
movies. Remember the flatulence scene in ``Blazing Saddles'' or the
barfing scenes in and ``The Exorcist''? Of all the special effects,
says director John Waters, throwing up is the cheapest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
