<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father claims voice led to drowning son
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSWELL, GA. -- You don't have to convince John Robinson, 52,
that ESP is real.
</P>
<P>
   When his 15-year-old son was 4, they were swimming at a friend's
house, and something ``very weird'' happened, Robinson says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was way down at the other end of the pool from him,
talking,'' says the retired Air Force colonel. ``All of a sudden, I
heard a voice, and it was very emphatic, clear as a bell, as if
someone was talking to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swam to the other end, and my son, who couldn't swim, had
slipped off an inner tube and fell to the bottom. If I hadn't come,
he'd have drowned.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Robinson, one of the people who responded to The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's Southern Focus Poll: ``There's a lot we
don't understand. But there's no doubt in my mind that what saved
David was supernatural. It was something in the mind that we don't
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Other poll respondents also offered stories of uncanny
intuition.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Kimsey, 50, of Loganville had a premonition just before
Christmas 1987 that someone at their family gathering wouldn't be
around another year.
</P>
<P>
   She'd never sensed anything so morbid or so vivid, and she
immediately went hunting for a video camera to record the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a strong impression it was my daddy,'' she said. ``And
sure enough, he died in February. It wasn't a fluke, because I'd
thought it might be my grandmother, who was in ill health. Things
have happened all my life I couldn't explain.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the premonition didn't come in a dream, but in
broad daylight. She was simply overwhelmed by ``this urge, a real
need, to find this video camera. It was like somebody was standing
behind me saying, `You need to do this.' It wasn't a verbal voice;
I could sense it more than hear it. I think it was the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson maintains that ``we're all so bombarded with stuff on
TV, you never know what to believe. I am religious, but I think
there's things about the mind we don't even come close to
understanding in this unfathomable universe.''
</P>
<P>
   He himself was saved during his tour in Vietnam by a voice that
told him to take a later plane from one base to another, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The one he'd been scheduled to take crashed, killing everyone on
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you think,'' he says. ``And I think about these
things every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
