<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Country stars to release meaningful albums
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emmylou Harris and Vince Gill, two of country's ultra-respected
singers and songwriters, have career-marking albums coming Aug. 11.
Harris' ``Spyboy,'' also the name of her band, is significant
because it's a live career retrospective. Gill's ``The Key'' comes
about a month after his divorce from Janis Arnold Gill and about a
year after the death of his father, Stanley Gill. Gill's title cut,
``The Key to Life'' is about his father and features Gill, a gifted
picker whose life has always figured into his songs, playing his
father's banjo.
</P>
<P>
   After noting that the ``Spyboy'' liner notes don't say where the
live tracks were recorded, Harris fans may recall that she helped
the late Gram Parsons with a faked ``live'' medley on his 1974
album ``Grievous Angel.'' Reminded of that, Harris laughs, then
says she simply wanted to be ``nonspecific'' about where the tracks
were recorded. The long-ago faux medley, Harris says, was done
``very tongue-in-cheek with a tip of the hat to the things we'd
done and places we'd played.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Jermaine Dupri, ``Life in 1472 (The Original Soundtrack)''
(So So Def). Grade: A-.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gloria Estefan, ``Gloria!'' (Epic/Sony). Review in Thursday
Living. Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nanci Griffith, ``Other Voices, Too (A Trip Back to
Bountiful)'' (Elektra). Grade: B+.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Small Soldiers'' soundtrack (Dreamworks). Review in
Thursday Living. Grade: C+.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Sound of Music'' 1998 Broadway cast album (RCA Victor).
Grade: C-.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
