<SLUG> BC-TV-SEASON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: The winner for ``Best New Show for the `98-`99 TV
season'' is. . .
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coolest new TV series coming this fall? That would probably
be ``Buddy Faro'' (9 p.m. ET, Fridays on CBS), a swingin',
retro-hip detective comedy that's rat-packed with goofy dazzle.
</P>
<P>
   The most unlikely new star? No quetion, it's Sammo Hung, a
tubby, blank-faced Hong Kong martial arts whiz of astounding grace
whose English is as thick as his midsection. He'll star in
``Martial Arts'' (9 p.m. ET, Saturdays on CBS).
</P>
<P>
   The sweetest new couple? Moira Kelly (``Chaplin'') and Jason
Beghe (``G.I. Jane'') who play a newly married public defender and
cop in ``To Have and to Hold'' (9 p.m. ET, Wednesdays on CBS).
They're sexy, funny and have chemistry to burn.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of any of these new shows breaking out and becoming
a hit? Think snowballs on Satan's sidewalk. And not just because
they all happen to be on CBS, although that probably doesn't help.
CBS is taking chances, but its audience doesn't usually want
chances; it wants ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman'' back on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Television is no more fair than the rest of the universe, and
arguably less sometimes. Starting late next month, six networks
will start bringing forth 37 new shows, most of which will fail,
and most of which deserve to fail. What's sad is when TV gets it
right, and the audience gets it wrong. Witness last season, when
the smart, edgy ``Nothing Sacred'' died, while ``Veronica's
Closet,'' a comedy that flopped around like a marlin on a boat
deck, was a Top 10 hit just because it followed ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm just back from two weeks in California spent watching most
of the upcoming fall series and talking to the people who make
them. There's no single trend; the zeitgeist is as hazy as the
skies, and Los Angeles was under its highest-level smog alert some
of the time I was there.
</P>
<P>
   When they're not idiotically promising that all of their new
shows will be strong, brave and true, most network executives are
fretting that the system of making pilot episodes in the spring to
launch as series in the fall has broken down irretrievably. There's
too many shows, and too little talent to make them, particularly
talented writers. ``As an actor, you're a victim of the writer,''
says actor William Devane, breaking through the fog of numbed
optimism with which most stars try to promote their new series.
Actually, the viewers are victims, too.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, it's amazing when a show itself breaks through. Like
the WB's ``Felicity,'' (9 p.m. ET, Tuesdays) about a confused but
endearing young woman (played by Keri Russell) in her freshman year
of college, midway between Claire Danes' Angela of ``My So-Called
Life'' and Calista Flockhart's ``Ally McBeal'' _ two shows it has
the potential to emulate. Or ``Cupid,'' a slight but very romantic
drama (10 p.m. ET, Saturdays on ABC) that will appeal to those
people staying home Saturday night and drowning their sorrows with
Haagen Dazs.
</P>
<P>
   The bad, of course, also abounds, which comes as no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's sitcom ``Costello'' (8:30 ET, Tuesdays on Fox) stars Sue
Costello, a tart, painfully honest stand-up comic from South
Boston. Her show, though is just painful: a bunch of dim louts in a
bar. It's what ``Cheers'' would have been if all the customers had
been Carla's in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vengeance Unlimited'' is a nasty little piece of work starring
Michael Madsen (``Reservoir Dogs'') as a vigilante. ABC is airing
it at 8 p.m. ET, Thursdays, which is too early in the evening; 3
a.m. would have been a better choice.
</P>
<P>
   WB's ``The Army Show'' is so stunningly stupid it makes you long
for the sophisticated wit of ``McHale's Navy,'' while NBC's surfin'
soap opera ``Wind on Water'' (8 p.m. ET, Saturdays) is mainly a
desperation career move for Bo Derek, which pretty much tells you
what you need to know.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the new fall series are not really hateful, they're
just there, or will be soon (and gone even sooner).
</P>
<P>
   So what will be the big hit be? Based on the Duh! theory of
prognostication favored by highly paid media buyers on Madison
Avenue, it's ``Jesse,'' which will air at 8:30 p.m. ET, Thursdays
on NBC, between ``Friends'' and ``Frasier.'' Christina Applegate,
having shed every trace of her Kelly Bundy image, plays a single
mom working in her father's bar in Madison, Wisc., and playing
emotional caretaker for the men in her life: young son, bellicose
dad, wierdo brother. It's likable enough, and somehow managed to
escape being run through the NBC sitcom homogenization machine
(``Suddenly Fired Up Naked in the City''), but if I never see
episode two, I'll live.
</P>
<P>
   There's also some strange dualism theme running through the fall
schedule; there's two of practically everything, including Olsen
twins. Their new show, ``Two of a Kind'' (8 p.m. ET, Fridays on
ABC) kind of sums up this doppelganger effect.
</P>
<P>
   There's two shows that go behind the scenes at TV shows (``The
Brian Benben Show,'' 9:30 p.m. ET, Mondays on CBS) and ``Sports
Night'' (9:30 p.m. ET, Tuesdays on ABC). There's two sitcoms about
black families moving into white suburbia (``The Hughleys,'' 8:30
p.m. ET, Tuesdays on ABC) and ``Living in Captivity'' (8 p.m. ET,
Fridays on Fox). There's two shows about big, boisterous Irish
families in Boston (the aforementioned ``Costello'' and ``To Have
and to Hold''). Guess how many shows there are about single dads
with wacky brothers raising little kids? Count 'em: ``Brother's
Keeper'' (9:30 p.m. ET, Fridays on ABC) and ``Holding the Baby''
(7:30 p.m. ET, Sunday on Fox).
</P>
<P>
   But if popular culture can survive two big feature films about
giant rocks heading toward earth in one summer, it can survive the
Olsen-twinning of television.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
