</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The real truth about television
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pasadena, Calif. _ Every summer, the networks trot out their new
fall shows for the Television Critics Association meeting here,
which concluded Sunday. And every summer, every show is great, to
hear the people involved tell it.
</P>
<P>
   No sitcom actor took a gig in a second-rate show that will soon
be cancelled because he or she needed to pay the mortgage; no, the
script or the character really spoke to him. Every producer got his
first choice for a cast. Every cast has bonded and become like a
family.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. But sometimes, some interesting truths, or just
plain unscripted comments, slip out. A few examples from this
summer's tour of fall shows:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``We're selling tennis shoes and potato chips. That's what
shows are on television for.'' _ D. L. Hughley, star of the
upcoming ABC sitcom ``The Hughleys.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I would like the idea of combining stunt casting with
actual stunts. Get Sharon Stone and fire her out of a cannon.'' _
Michael J. Fox of ``Spin City.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``There's just so many (programs) that tend to be about
dating, and more dating, and specifically very beautiful
20-year-olds dating.'' _ Producer Diane English, creator of
``Murphy Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I really didn't know who she was. My dad and my grandpa
sure did.'' _ Twentysomething actor Brian Gross on co-starring in a
new series with Bo Derek.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``To me, 'edgy' has become a bit tiresome.'' _ Ken Olin, star
of CBS's upcoming ``L.A. Doctors,'' on one of TV's favorite
buzzwords.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I think I'd like to see more shows about single, white,
thirtysomething, pretty women working in the media.'' _ Producer
Tom Werner (``3rd Rock From the Sun''), sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``In a way we're like athletes, except we're older, fatter
and we run like girls.'' _ ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?'' star Colin
Mochrie, on training to do improvisational comedy.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I came out of a (network) meeting a couple of weeks ago,
and they said the first rule was: nothing rural, nothing Southern,
nothing dealing with country and western, nothing dealing with
anyone over 40 _ literally.'' _ Producer Matt Williams (``Home
Improvement'').
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The pants can only come half-way off.'' _ Actor Brian
Benben on the biggest difference between his HBO show ``Dream On''
and his new CBS comedy ``The Brian Benben Show.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``You're in there rootin' for someone to go down.'' _ William
Devane, on being in a midseason replacement series (CBS's
``Turks'').
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I was living in a one-room apartment in Hollywood. I would
have written a show about homosexual parakeets.'' _ Writer-producer
Joanne Waters, producer of the new series ``To Have and to Hold,''
on breaking into the business.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
