A5113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WISDOMTEETH-COX     07-27 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WISDOMTEETH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer wisdom: It's time for teens to get molars out
 &HT;    By Bette Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many teenagers, summer means hanging out with friends,
lazing by the pool, perhaps working and, ugh, having their wisdom
teeth pulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the teenage rite of summer,'' groans Reanna Justus, 18,
of Cobb County(Ga.), who along with her twin, Amanda, will undergo
the surgery in August. ``Most of my friends already have had it
done. We need to do it before we get our senior pictures taken so
we won't look like chipmunks.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, most teens dread the procedure. Having their
wisdom teeth pulled is often their first experience with surgery.
The best part of the whole ordeal comes afterward, when their moms
fuss over them, changing ice packs and offering them special soft
treats like applesauce and Italian ices.
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom teeth, or third molars, are the last teeth to develop.
Although some adults have mouths large enough to accommodate them,
most don't. If there isn't room, infection, pain and crowding of
existing teeth may occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can usually tell by the time they're in their midteens
whether or not their wisdom teeth are going to have adequate room
to erupt properly,'' says Marietta oral surgeon Dr. John Freihaut.
``The teenage years are an ideal time to have wisdom teeth removed
because young people heal quickly and with few complications.''
</P>
<P>
   The procedure is so common _ Freihaut estimates that two out of
every three teens will need their wisdom teeth extracted _ that
almost every teen knows at least one other who's had it done this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Straight had hers taken out July 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it wasn't bad,'' says Straight, 18, of Suwanee, Ga..
``I think having your braces tightened is worse, you know, in the
pain department.''
</P>
<P>
   Teens trade wisdom teeth extraction stories like war veterans _
this one swelled out to ``here''; that one chug-a-lugged
painkillers; another couldn't eat anything except chocolate pudding
for two days.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Goldstein, 17, of Cobb County, didn't mind the
experience a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, they give you laughing gas and you float around the
room for a while,'' he says. ``Then they numb you. Then they wake
you up and it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   So how long did he exist on chocolate pudding?
</P>
<P>
   ``What pudding?'' he laughs. ``I always put food before pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
