u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELFARE-EMPLOYERS-HNS     07-27 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-EMPLOYERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS MOST EMPLOYERS SATISFIED IN HIRING WELFARE RECIPIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most employers who hire former welfare recipients
are satisfied with their work, but a majority of the workers get
low pay and few benefits, according to two reports released Monday
by the Urban Institute, a Washington-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of the employers who have hired people on
welfare said the new workers have a positive attitude and are
reliable, according to one of the reports. These traits are the two
most important attributes for entry-level positions such as
cashiers, busboys and hotel housekeepers, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In hiring people off welfare rolls, employers are sending a
message of ``get to work on time, be courteous, have a good
attitude and get along with people,'' said Jack Meyer, president of
the Economic and Social Research Institute (ESRI), which produced
the report on employers for the Urban Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Other job qualifications such as experience and training were
far less important to the 500 employers surveyed around the
country. Meyer said 12 percent of them rated experience high and 4
percent ranked training as important when they hired people for
entry-level jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 500, more than 60 percent, said they had hired welfare
recipients, and 94 percent of those 309 employers said they would
be willing to hire more such workers again, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The Urban Institute also released a report on income differences
between people on welfare and those who have taken entry-level jobs
in 12 states _ Alabama, California, Colorado, Florida,
Massachusetts, Michigan, Minnesota, Mississippi, New Jersey, New
York, Texas and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   About two thirds of the entry-level jobs available to welfare
recipients pay less than $6 an hour, the report said. The annual
income of a welfare family of three jumps an average of 51 percent
when one member of the family takes a part-time job working 20
hours a week and earning the minimum wage of $5.15 an hour. That
family's income goes from $8,808 to $12,888, the study reported.
</P>
<P>
   If the employee gets a full-time job working 35 hours a week at
the minimum wage, the family income goes up another 20 percent, the
report said. About half the entry-level jobs available to people on
welfare are part-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people still living on the edge,'' Meyer said.
``They are quite vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of low wages and no or few health benefits is
still a problem for former welfare recipients, even though a large
number of employers are willing to hire them, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Urban Institute's report said only half of the firms that
offer entry-level jobs have health insurance and paid vacations for
those workers. A quarter of the firms offer no benefits, it added.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the year that President Clinton signed Congress'
welfare overhaul legislation into law, 12.4 million people were
receiving cash assistance, according to the Department of Health
and Human Services. Millions have left the welfare rolls since
then, but many others are deterred by the lack of health insurance
and day care, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to keep people in the labor force beyond a
year or two, they're going to need to know they have a sick day,
that they have health coverage,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Although government incentives encouraging employers to hire
entry-level workers are numerous, nearly three quarters of the
bosses surveyed did not know about such programs as subsidies and
federal or state tax credits, the ESRI report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
