<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS STILL WARY ON RUSSIA'S DEBT SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian stock prices plummeted again Monday, a clear
indication that investors still doubt whether the government can
make good on a pledge to climb out of its seemingly bottomless hole
of domestic and international debt.
</P>
<P>
   The government seemed to underscore its plight by announcing
over the weekend that it would raise money by selling part of its
controlling stake in the huge Gazprom natural-gas monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Trading System index of stock prices, which fell 17
per cent last week, dropped another 9.1 percent Monday, to 143.46,
roughly where it was before the International Monetary Fund agreed
to prop up the government's finances with billions in new loans.
</P>
<P>
   The first of those loans, totaling $4.8 billion, reached
Russia's central bank late last week and was used to increase
foreign-exchange and gold reserves, which had been dropping
rapidly. One condition on the loans was Russia's commitment to make
sweeping and basic changes in how it assesses and collects taxes
and in its spending policies, a promise that President Boris
Yeltsin's government has made but which the Russian Parliament so
far has rejected.
</P>
<P>
   An analyst in London for Salomon Smith Barney, Mohamed Erian,
said that the loan package and the promise of reforms alone are
good news, but not good enough to satisfy skittish investors who
have seen similar promises fail before.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a reform-minded team in place,'' said Erian, the
firm's European chief of emerging market research. ``The issue
comes down to implementation, implementation, implementation. And
the market is watching that very, very carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's reforms still face at least two major obstacles: more
opposition from the Parliament, which is expected to resume
considering the fiscal overhaul next month, and opposition from
consumers and big business, both of which face higher taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Given the fall in stock prices, it seemed a poor time for the
government to sell shares in Gazprom. American Depository Receipts
in Gazprom, which are traded on foreign stock markets, have fallen
by more than one third in the last 10 days, to a 52-week low.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin approved plans this weekend to sell 5.87 percentage
points of the government's 41 percent stake in Gazprom, the world's
largest natural-gas company and a linchpin of the Russian economy.
The shares being sold are worth about $1.4 billion on foreign
markets, and experts suggested Monday that the government would try
to interest two foreign partners in Gazprom ventures, the Royal
Dutch/Shell Group and ENI SpA, the Italian energy conglomerate, to
buy the shares. The stock would be worth considerably less _ about
$520 million _ were it sold to Russians on the Russian stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov said the sale would ``enable
the government to attract additional funds to the budget and keep
the state's position'' as the largest shareholder in Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
   Though the government's financial position has improved in the
last week, it still must find $7 billion by the end of September to
pay off bonds that were sold at very high interest rates earlier
this year when the treasury was in a severe cash crunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0261 </DOCNO>
