<HEADER>
A5143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWELFTH-NIGHT-SETS-AR     07-27 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWELFTH-NIGHT-SETS-ART-625(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATING ONSTAGE MAGIC WITH WATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The setting for ``Twelfth Night'' is an Oriental
fantasy of the mind. As far as the eye can see, there is a road
winding through water. At the front of the Vivian Beaumont stage,
actors are lolling sybaritically, surrounded by burning candles and
incense. Nearby is a pool for swimming and dunking. Later in the
play there will be a rainstorm. In Bob Crowley's enchanting scenic
design for Nicholas Hytner's production, water is the central motif
_ more than 10,000 gallons at every performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is literally and metaphorically a waterlogged play,''
Crowley said. ``It begins with a shipwreck, and the water imagery
is in virtually every other scene. There is also the narcissism of
the characters, constantly looking at their own reflections. The
idea of water being the first mirror, the twinning of things _ all
that has resonance.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, ``there is a liquidity about the theatrical floor
plan.'' The set is ``all curved,'' he said, trilling his ``r'' so
that the word itself sounded curved.
</P>
<P>
   It is a set unlike any other previously at the Beaumont and a
most unusual design for ``Twelfth Night,'' which is generally
presented in a variation of house and garden: alternating between
the Duke's palace and Olivia's luxurious home, with Viola disguised
as the Duke's male messenger plying a path between the two. Seldom
is the play presented completely alfresco as in this Lincoln Center
Theater production.
</P>
<P>
   There is ample performance dexterity onstage, beginning with Max
Wright, Brian Murray and Philip Bosco as the comic characters,
although some reviewers had reservations about several of the other
actors. There was unanimous enthusiasm for the scenery. The set is
the first striking element that greets theatergoers. Applaud the
scenery? ``I have no objection,'' Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   After more than 20 years of working in the theater, the
45-year-old designer is accustomed to ovations, this year with
``Twelfth Night,'' several seasons ago with Hytner's production of
``Carousel,'' also at the Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley, who was born in Ireland, studied painting and sculpture
before going to drama school and deciding to be a scenic designer.
In England he has worked both at the Royal Shakespeare Company (the
original production of ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses'') and the Royal
National Theater.
</P>
<P>
   He has designed in the widest diversity of surroundings, from
the small Cottesloe Theater at the National (an intimate,
corridor-style production of ``King Lear,'' starring Ian Holm) to
Royal Albert Hall (``La Traviata''). At the National, he also did
David Hare's trilogy about major English institutions, filling the
great expanse of the Olivier stage with photographic collages as
well as swiftly sliding columns.
</P>
<P>
   In the second act of Hare's ``Amy's View'' (starring Judi
Dench), the star's dressing room opens up and is replaced by a
deep, transforming look at the theater stage and what is behind it.
As Crowley says, ``The space determines the way a production should
look.''
</P>
<P>
   Hytner, who has frequently worked with Crowley in theater and
opera over the last 10 years, said about his collaborator: ``He
always responds poetically to a play. His sets are often painterly.
My taste, which is influenced by Bob, is not toward architectural
literalism or social realism. The kind of worlds we like to create
are worlds of the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowley specializes in creating magical environments. To the
director as to the designer, Shakespeare's Illyria in ``Twelfth
Night'' meant, in Hytner's words, ``not here, not now, somewhere
different, a world where romantic impossibilities are made possible
_ a midsummer madness that can be resolved through the power of the
stage.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
