<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5144 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     07-27 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCESSIVE BREAKS CONSIDERED COMPANY THEFT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Question: At a recent staff meeting, I stated that
taking too long a break was the same as stealing, and that making a
personal call should count as one of your breaks. Now, everyone is
giving me the cold shoulder. Was I off base, and should I offer an
apology? C.K.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: When fellow employees give you the cold shoulder because
of some arguably defensible job-related comments you made, they are
far more off base than you. If they disagree with your comments,
the appropriate response is discussion, not ostracism.
</P>
<P>
   There are many experts who regard overly lengthy breaks as a
form of theft, and they could just as easily argue that personal
calls should count as breaks. Presumably your associates would
ostracize these experts too.
</P>
<P>
   However, the reality is that people are going to take breaks,
occasionally long breaks, and they are going to make personal
calls, and none of this needs to be viewed automatically as theft
or grounds for reduced break time. In this age of increased
flexibility, long hours and family commitments, such actions are
commonplace and acceptable, as long as they are not excessive.
</P>
<P>
   There is a standard of reasonableness that needs to be applied
here. When personal calls or breaks enter the unreasonable zone for
your company, these behaviors can be described in many ways, such
as insubordination, disloyalty or even theft.
</P>
<P>
   The issue that you raised calls for more discussion with your
colleagues. And, by any standard of reasonableness, they owe you an
apology.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I happened to overhear a couple of people I work with refer
to me as a spy for management. I was stunned and said nothing at
the time. I have never spied on anybody, and I am personally
offended. Is there anything I should say to them? S.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: If you rush to tell these delightful associates that you
overheard what they said, they will probably respond with, ``Aha!
You were spying on us!''
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting to note that when employees feel that a
co-worker is spying on them, such employees are often doing
something they would prefer to keep away from management. In such
circumstances, there can even be some paranoia, with these
employees looking around for spies and even inventing them. In your
situation, it sounds like they invented you.
</P>
<P>
   Since this accusation is so distressing for you, along with the
fact that this type of claim can be rather contagious, there is a
way to communicate your concern to these individuals, without
generating a counterattack. During a lunch or informal
conversation, indicate that all of you used to work well together,
and you wonder why that seems to be slipping. Soon enough, the spy
comment will be released, and you can express your feelings and
facts on this matter.
</P>
<P>
   Another approach is to consider discussing your concern with the
informal leader of the work group. If this person aligns himself or
herself with you, the inventive detractors are likely to fall into
line.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently found out about two jobs in different departments
at a local company and had an ``informal chat'' with people from
both. The meetings were two weeks apart. It has been four weeks
since the first meeting, and although I normally would call the
first person, I liked the second position better and hate to push
the first person to make any decision before the second position is
available, which will be at least three weeks from my meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But, if I don't call, someone else may get that job, and, if it
is offered to me, do I turn it down and risk losing the second
position and then having nothing? M.D
</P>
<P>
   A: Since the second position is the one you want, it is the one
you really should pursue. If you go with the first position, the
second position is going to be lingering in the back of your mind,
and that preoccupation can interfere with your job satisfaction and
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the game plan should be to maintain regular contact with
the decison makers for the second position. You need to be in a
sales mode here, and persistence definitely counts.
</P>
<P>
   If you are pursued for the first position, you should call your
contacts for the second position and let them know you are not
trying to apply leverage, but an offer is forthcoming. Let your
first choice know you prefer to work for them. Ask where they are
in their decision making and where you are in their decision
making. If you go with your second choice, you are in for a lot of
second guessing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWELFTH-NIGHT-SETS-AR     07-27 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWELFTH-NIGHT-SETS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the stage.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As usual, Crowley began his research in a museum. In creating
the New England background for ``Carousel,'' he was inspired by the
paintings of Andrew Wyeth and Winslow Homer. With ``Twelfth
Night,'' he drew upon two exhibitions at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art: one of Oriental carpets, the other of illustrated pages from
an Indian manuscript. The designer and Hytner saw them early this
year when Crowley was working on the elaborate, highly graphic sets
for Paul Simon's ``Capeman.'' Crowley made clear that he had not
tried to reproduce anything in the exhibitions for ``Twelfth
Night,'' but approached them for their atmospheric emanations.
</P>
<P>
   The environment is generically Eastern, stressing the play's
fabulistic side. ``We talked about the hallucinogenic nature of the
piece and the obsessive nature of the people who occupy the
place,'' Crowley said. The aim was to give `'people's desire and
dreams _ and the language _ room to breathe.'' The approach, as
with all his Shakespeare productions, is to keep it ``fairly free
and abstract'' and not to ``straitjacket it into a certain time,
place or period.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest the production comes to a period is in dealing with
the comic characters who are like ``English freeloaders abroad,''
while the others are exotics, with the Duke ``the ruler of a
strange land living in an extraordinary kind of Buddhist temple''
and Olivia the equivalent of Rapunzel locked in a tower.
</P>
<P>
   Studying pictures of the Alhambra gardens, Crowley was struck by
the way that light filtered through the space so that things were
half seen. Avoiding solid scenery, he wanted the setting to have a
translucent quality, so that people could be glimpsed on the wing.
Intentionally, the feeling is cinematic, with crosscuts between
scenes. As one scene finishes downstage, another begins upstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the characters met,'' he said, ``they would recognize each
other and the play would finish. Instead, they take the opposite
road like we all do in life, and life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Working closely with costume designer Catherine Zuber, he was
conscious, he said, of ``the idea of disguise, that it's only a
layer of clothing, a thin piece of fabric protecting somebody from
being discovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowley likes to deal with natural elements, with fire for the
witches in a production of ``Macbeth,'' and with water here and in
``The Night of the Iguana'' at the National Theater, in which there
was a thunderous tropical rainstorm onstage. For ``Twelfth Night,''
the walkways had to be made safe for the actors rushing across the
paths. Extra care was taken to avoid flooding, so that there would
not be ``a very wet `Brain' downstairs,'' he said, referring to ``A
New Brain,'' the William Finn musical at the Mitzi Newhouse Theater
(where, several seasons ago, Crowley did an imaginatively high-tech
set for ``Hapgood'').
</P>
<P>
   For ``Twelfth Night,'' the Beaumont stage was opened to its
widest dimension. Because the audience looks down on the open
stage, as it might in a Greek amphitheater, everything _ the cast
as well as the minimal scenery _ is low-lying. ``The most important
part of the Beaumont is the floor,'' Crowley said, explaining why
the actors often recline.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Beaumont was considered a difficult if not an
unworkable stage. Crowley was undeterred by the reputation of the
theater, finding it an exhilarating place to work: ``I'm quite
happy to work in big spaces, the bigger the better.'' One director
who previously solved the Beaumont problem was Peter Brook. He
presented his version of ``Carmen'' in a sandpit in the middle of
the arena. That production and Brook himself were models for
Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke about Brook's influence, he clarified his own
concept of design. Heretically, he does not like scenery, at least
not an abundance of it, whenever possible choosing the simplest
setting. In this production, there are a bench and at one point a
wall, both of which pop out of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate moving furniture onstage,'' he said, ``and it is even
harder to move it offstage.'' Only cushions are carried on and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather look at a beautifully lit backstage with a
great actor in the middle of it than a great production with 55
tons of naturalistic living rooms flying in and out,'' Crowley
said. In his eyes, an empty stage can be a design choice, and it
can be exquisite, if properly lighted. ``I'm putting myself out of
work, aren't I?'' he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to Brook's production of ``The Cherry Orchard,'' in
which there were carpets and an absolute minimum of furniture, he
said there was no such thing as something's not being designed:
``As Brook says in `The Empty Space,' the minute an actor walks
across the stage and somebody looks at him, that is the beginning
of a piece of theater.''
</P>
<P>
   But where does the designer come in? Crowley responded with
questions: ``Is the floor wooden or is it a piece of canvas? Is it
covered in dirt? Does it need sweeping? What's illuminating the
actor? Those are all design decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, he first makes sketches, followed by a scale model of
the set, which in this case he sent to the production manager with
a note attached: ``Here's the model as requested. Just add water.''
</P>
<P>
   After the model was unveiled for the cast and crew at the
Beaumont, the director and the designer walked outside the theater
into the plaza, where they faced the large pool with a Henry Moore
sculpture in the middle. Although he has often sat by that pool,
Crowley said he ``had completely forgotten that what is outside the
building reflects what the audience sees inside.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he said, he thought about floating a miniature
version of the Moore sculpture in the set, but decided to leave
such parallels to the imagination of theatergoers, who arrive in
this Illyria as to another world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
