<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5146 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALTERNATIVE-COUNTRY-1     07-27 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-COUNTRY-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY AREN'T MAINSTREAMERS BUYING ALTERNATIVE COUNTRY?
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanied by BC-ALTERNATIVE-COUNTRY-PRIMER) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998, alternative-country is everywhere:
</P>
<P>
   _Junior Brown, whose music can sound like Ernest Tubb jamming
with Jimi Hendrix, does very funny commercials for Lipton ice tea.
</P>
<P>
   _Whiskeytown, having received incredible critical notice for its
latest CD, ``Strangers Almanac,'' is opening for John Fogerty.
</P>
<P>
   _Former cult favorite Robert Earl Keen has become a major Texas
singer/songwriter who can fill small halls.
</P>
<P>
   _The Old 97's are THE most popular band in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   _Critics are hailing Lucinda Williams' just-released ``Car
Wheels on a Gravel Road'' as one of the year's best CDs.
</P>
<P>
   _And alt-country acts such as Steve Earle, the Mavericks,
BR5-49, Wilco, Joe Ely, Son Volt, the Bottle Rockets, Don Walser
and Gillian Welch fill clubs nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But good luck trying to find any of the above on mainstream
country stations. Don't hold your breath while looking for their
CDs on the national CD or singles charts.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone loves alt-country _ except mainstream country.
</P>
<P>
   Call it alt-country or insurgent country or y'allternative or No
Depression, but this music hasn't caught on with most of the people
who love Garth, Shania, LeAnn, George and Reba. Despite laudatory
reviews, the top alt-country acts (BR5-49, Brown, Wilco and Earle)
sell, at most, 150,000 CDs _ a pittance in an era when most top
country acts can sell at least 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the Mavericks, who have learned the hard way what it
means to buck the system: When their music was more easily
identified as country, they were Nashville's darlings: Their third
CD, 1994's ``What a Crying Shame,'' sold 1.2 million copies. But
this year's excellent ``Trampoline,'' which adds more Latin
touches, has sold just more than 100,000 copies and fell out of the
national Top 40 after less than four months.
</P>
<P>
   But industry observers, musicians, label executives and such
alt-country stars as Robert Earl Keen say the pendulum is swinging
back; that mainstream country has become so homogeneous, so slick
and so faceless that country fans will eventually reach for the
music's raw, blue-collar core.
</P>
<P>
   ``The face of country music WILL change,'' says Keen, who is
recording his next CD in Austin, Texas. ``It's really bad right
now. But there will be a respite, because even diehard country fans
I know can't stand it, and it's going to turn in the next couple
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Marino, the Americana editor of Gavin Magazine, a radio
industry trade publication, says that ``country used to have a
specific, loyal audience _ now it's pop music. The two audiences
are sharing performers now, people like Shania and LeAnn and Garth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, alt-country is truer to country traditions than
mainstream country. Don Walser, Joe Ely, the Mavericks _ they're
all rooted in country traditions, and they're going to attract
people who want something more traditional.''
</P>
<P>
   Alternative-country can be described, generally, as anything
that's identifiably country but, well, somehow outside the narrow,
slick sound currently in vogue in Nashville. It can be the
Nashville-goes-Latin sound of the Mavericks or Steve Earle's
hard-edged tales of hard living or the throwback sounds of Robert
Earl Keen or Junior Brown, which hark back to, respectively, the
``outlaw'' movement of the '70s or the glory days of Lefty Frizzell
and Tubb.
</P>
<P>
   And as the name implies, there's often a nod toward rock 'n'
roll. Which is hardly new: From Elvis Presley to Bob Dylan, major
rock artists have always had more than a little country in their
sound.
</P>
<P>
   The ties became closer in the late '60s and early '70s with the
Byrds' groundbreaking '68 LP ``Sweetheart of the Rodeo'' and
records by the Flying Burrito Brothers, the Burritos' star-crossed
leader Gram Parsons, and the Grateful Dead's ``Workingman's Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s, the Eagles' ``Tequila Sunrise'' and ``Lyin' Eyes''
were played on mainstream rock stations. In 1981, Elvis Costello
released ``Almost Blue,'' a straight country record that included
Hank Williams and Gram Parsons covers. The '80s brought a wave of
acts combining country, punk and roots music, including Jason &AMP; the
Scorchers and Lone Justice. Lyle Lovett, k.d. lang and Earle were
all embraced, to one degree or another, by rock and/or folk fans.
</P>
<P>
   If alt-country is having an impact on mainstream country today,
however, it's through the songs these artists are writing for
mainstream artists.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lauderdale, John Prine and Buddy Miller make a good living
(or at least a lot of supplemental income) by writing hits for
others. Prine co-wrote Strait's recent No. 1 hit ``I Just Want to
Dance With You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that many alternative songwriters are writing hits
bodes well for the situation,'' says Mike Ireland, whose debut CD,
``Learning How to Live,'' has won critical praise for its blend of
honky-tonk and the string-laden ``countrypolitan'' sound favored in
the '70s. ``If alternative-country never breaks, we'll continue to
have Lucinda Williams and John Prine records _ they'll be able to
continue to make music. In country, it matters who the songwriter
is _ there's a level of respect there.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Still, some believe that the genre will continue to be on the
fringe, and that performers will only break through on a
case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   After all, notes Marino and others, the alt-country acts that
have had some success have all had, well, a gimmick, a certain
kitsch appeal: Brown has his guit-steel and funny lyrics, BR5-49
have their throwback hillbilly clothes and humor. The subtlety of a
Wilco, or the country-meets-Latin sound of the Mavericks will
likely remain at odds with the slick sounds coming out of
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Others speculate that alt-country will find a home in mainstream
or alternative rock, discovered by rock fans looking for something
that's not as slick as Hootie, that's more adult than matchbox 20
and that sounds nothing at all like techno.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Snider, a partner in the Gypsy Tea Room, a Deep Ellum venue
in Dallas that books a lot of alt-country acts, says the music
attracts a variety of fans. ``The people who come to the Tea Room
are just people who like good music _ you get some country fans,
some rockabilly fans, the swing crowd,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And Murry Hammond, bassist for the Old 97's, says that his band
has ``much more to do culturally'' with rock audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Country isn't a mystery to rock people,'' he says. ``They know
Hank Williams and the real stuff from the cheese-ball stuff. It's
like all the rock people who have warmed up to swing _ it's
basically uptempo boogie. And it's happening _ we get intense
airplay on some rock stations. Groups like Wilco and us have a real
good chance of being embraced by the rock people.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Miller, president and co-founder of Chicago's Bloodshot
Records, agrees. Bloodshot, he says, was founded in 1993 as a
reaction against how boring alternative rock was, not how boring
mainstream country was.
</P>
<P>
   He sees the audience for Bloodshot acts such as the Waco
Brothers, Robbie Fulks and Moonshine Willy as aging alt-rock fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get the same honesty from our acts as you did from the
Replacements _ it's three chords and in your face,'' he says.
``Most of our audience is disaffected rock fans, aging punks like
myself. I wouldn't have liked what we put out when I was 16 _ young
rock fans just hear `country,' and it's a big red flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the new BR5-49 CD, ``Big Backyard Beat Show,'' which was
released July 14, is getting a major push toward independent CD
stores in an attempt to generate a buzz in the alt-rock community,
according to Dan Herrington, sales and marketing manager of Arista
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're drilling for oil here _ you never know,'' says
Herrington, noting that the band has already made inroads in rock
by opening for both Bob Dylan and the Black Crowes. ``But if you
see a Whiskeytown show, or a BR show, a lot of the audience is the
same people who like the swing stuff. They're both danceable, and
they're both an alternative to Third Eye Blind and Tonic and
matchbox 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to be the wave of the future. For alt-country to be
big and go to the masses, it'll take that Nirvana syndrome _ one
song by one band and everyone follows the leader. Hopefully BR will
be that band.''
</P>
<P>
   But can anybody be that band? Redbeard, a longtime disc jockey
at KTXQ/102.1 FM, thinks rock fans probably always will resist
anything labeled ``country.''
</P>
<P>
   Redbeard says his station has played Denton's Slobberbone, as
well as the Jayhawks and Wilco, but in general ``it just doesn't
break through. Country stations say it's rock, and rock stations
say it's country. The problem that's always plagued country-rock
plagues it now: Nobody will claim it as their own.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe that's OK. There's a large enough audience for
alt-country CDs that the artists can continue to record and tour,
if not get rich. And if that Nirvana-ish hit doesn't ever kick the
door wide open for every other band _ that's OK, too. For guys like
Murry Hammond, filling clubs around the country and getting to play
the music they want to play is reward enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of country people don't care about us or look like us,''
he says. ``They'll never give us the time of day. People in
alt-country will never become more mainstream musically _ we're not
capable of it. And the fact that alt-country is an incredible
failure commercially is a pretty good indication it's doing
something right.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
