<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS28-COX     07-27 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veteran Martin ready to settle in
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tony Martin has pretty much adjusted to his change in
residence, after buying a condominium. Now, it's just a matter of
settling into his new job.
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons traded next year's second-round draft choice to
San Diego to acquire Martin, they did so with the intention of
replacing Bert Emanuel as the speed receiver.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin, who will be 33 on Sept. 5, is being reminded that
it's not always defensive backs he has to worry about. There are 11
receivers in camp, and sometimes there aren't enough balls to go
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, he hasn't had many opportunities yet to catch
balls (in live drills),'' receivers coach Rennie Simmons said.
``It's my experience that sometimes you'll go two or three
practices and only get one or two balls, and then get several at
once. But in drills, he's shown us everything we expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin doesn't seem to mind the logjam, at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, everything is going OK,'' said Martin, a 10- veteran.
``I'm still learning the offense. We have a young group of hungry
receivers who bust their butts to get to balls. That's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month's trade brought Martin to the same city as his
father, Hal, and that's good for business. Hal, who buys and sells
radio stations, also handles many of Tony's financial affairs.
Martin recently bought a music recording studio in Charlotte,
although he hasn't opened the doors yet.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Martin, a 6-foot-1, 181-pound former
quarterback from Mesa College in Colorado, is out to prove he's
still the player he was in 1996, when he went to the Pro Bowl after
catching 85 passes for 1,171 yards and 14 touchdowns _ tying the
NFL high that season.
</P>
<P>
   He again led the Chargers in receiving in 1997, but his 63
catches for 904 yards and six touchdowns gave some people the
impression he might be aging.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Martin says. For one thing, he was one of just 10
Chargers to start every game. And when quarterbacks Stan Humphries
and Jim Everett went down with season-ending injuries, the team's
passing attack became nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very frustrating,'' Martin said. ``You didn't know who
the quarterback was going to be the next week, and it's hard enough
getting used to one quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shortage of passes, Martin is having no problems
adjusting to Falcons' quarterback Chris Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man, I didn't think he could throw the ball like he can,''
Martin said. ``He puts the ball in spots you don't think he can.
And I thought Humphries threw a great deep ball, but Chris throws a
beautiful deep ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
