<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5153 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARINO-COX     07-27 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marino willing to give NFL another year _ at least
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ The real-life picture of Dan Marino loping onto
the Miami Dolphins practice field last week was enough to elicit
thousand-word essays on the relentless ticking of the NFL's
biological clock.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a quarter-century after Marino began firing footballs at
the stop sign outside his parents' home in the South Oakland
section of Pittsburgh, the trademark hop-step that preceded
millions of passes has all but disappeared. An incredible release,
once measured in nano-seconds, has slowed. And when Marino enters
the locker room now during his 16th training camp, an assistant
trainer usually is a stride behind with two bags of ice.
</P>
<P>
   Marino has nothing wrong with his ears, however, and he hears
the clock ticking on his crusade to add a Super Bowl ring to all
those gaudy passing records. His best football, he acknowledges, is
behind him. Even if this camp isn't Marino's final fling, he won't
have many more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at this stage of my career, I'd love to play a lot
longer, because I still enjoy the game,'' Marino said. ``But will
that happen? I'm really not sure. I feel like I can (keep playing).
I'm not sure I will.''
</P>
<P>
   It was painful to watch Marino struggle last year in a moribund
offense bereft of playmakers, and the results left Miami
management, the fans of South Florida and even some of his young
teammates skeptical about what to expect in 1998. Marino will turn
37 in seven weeks. His career passer rating is superior to all 18
quarterbacks in the Hall of Fame, but he threw only 16 touchdown
passes last year, his fewest in a full season, and had five
interceptions returned for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been anathema several years ago to suggest the
Dolphins might be better off without Marino, who holds 24 league
records and shares seven others. But callers to a local sports-talk
radio station are pushing for coach Jimmy Johnson to begin the
transition by turning over the offense to backup quarterback Craig
Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   And team officials correctly pointed out that the Miami defense
is more settled than the offense for one of the first times in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Marino's cool demeanor off the field often has been perceived as
indifference. And his fiery sideline tantrums, usually directed at
receivers running wayward routes or some inexplicable playcalling
by departed coordinator Gary Stevens, were viewed as selfish. But
nobody ever doubted his physical ability until last year's
late-season collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Marino knows that his skills have deteriorated. How much remains
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can still make all the throws when nothing around him
breaks down,'' said Keith Jackson, a former Miami tight end. ``But
everybody's coming after the ol' gunslinger now.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of questions surround the franchise in Johnson's third
season, but none seems bigger than this one: In the twilight of a
Hall of Fame career, can the Miami quarterback approximate the
Marino of old or is he simply an old Marino?
</P>
<P>
   Marino worked diligently each of the last two offseasons to cut
his weight, and the new regimen has paid dividends. His body-fat is
at an all-time low. The paunch that appeared about five years ago
is gone; his upper body is taut, and Marino has gone four-straight
years without offseason surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taken care of himself,'' Johnson said. ``But we have to
take care of him, too. If we do that, Danny won't have to feel like
he's under the gun to win every game himself.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Johnson fired Stevens, who abandoned the running game too
easily and overwhelmed players with ponderous game plans. He also
scrapped the Don Shula-designed offense Marino used for his first
15 years and a four-wide-receiver set that contributed to the
Dolphins' undoing in December.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two seasons, Johnson meant to establish the same
type of physical running game he had in Dallas. But he always
leaned on Marino's arm when things got tough. This year, he has
mandated the run. Shula and Stevens were offensive pack rats,
annually adding new wrinkles, never editing out the old, and the
result was an encyclopedic playbook that confused even veteran
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made mistakes sometimes because people didn't understand
what it was they were supposed to be doing,'' Johnson said. ``With
a young team and because of free-agency, you have to be simpler.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle James Brown said, ``There were times last year
when the (opposition) defense knew what we were doing better than
we did.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an economy of words in the Dolphins' new offense, fewer
audibles and, Johnson said, more of his imprint. If the overhaul
stripped Marino of a comfort zone, it also has done away with the
normal camp tedium. The quarterback can't react from years of rote
anymore, because he's learning the offense like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a kind of kick in the (butt), but really a good
one,'' Marino said. ``It won't be as monotonous a camp now.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes were obvious in two practices Saturday. In years
past, a seven-on-seven passing drill drew most of the attention,
and Marino might go days without missing a receiver against the
skeleton defense. On Saturday, the focus was a run-the-gauntlet
ball-carrying drill meant to test a player's toughness.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the offensive line terribly unsettled, Miami will run
the ball and Marino will, for the first time in his legendary
career, become a complementary player. He is comfortable with the
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played in many games where I've thrown it 60 times and we
got out butts kicked, and that's no fun,'' said Marino, who has
thrown fewer than 25 passes in just 18 games and more than 40
passes in 53. ``It's more fun, believe me, when you throw it 20 or
30 times and win.''
</P>
<P>
   If Marino and the Dolphins can make such a dramatic conversion,
then the best quarterback never to win a championship could have a
sweet 16th season. If they can't, a bittersweet year figures to be
Marino's last.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
