<SLUG> BC-NFL-MEETING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Revamped Browns still anyone's team
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS - The bid process for a resurrected Cleveland Browns
franchise won't conclude here today, but it could escalate to
another level.
</P>
<P>
   During a one-day session, NFL owners will fine-tune the process,
and there is a chance that league officials will narrow the field
of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Credit-card magnate Al Lerner, a one-time partner of former
Browns owner Art Modell, is perceived as the front-runner. His
status was enhanced last week when San Francisco 49ers team
president Carmen Policy resigned to join the Lerner bid, and the
partnership was endorsed by former Browns quarterback Bernie Kosar.
</P>
<P>
   But commissioner Paul Tagliabue insisted that the Lerner group
is not a certainty to get the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what we've been told, everything is still wide open,''
said Charles Dolan, whose group includes comedian Bill Cosby and
Hall of Fame coach Don Shula. ``There's still a long way to go in
this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, a lot of money will be spent in pursuit of the
Browns, who begin play in 1999. The first sealed-bid process in
league history probably won't fetch the $1 billion franchise fee
several owners had predicted two months ago. But the winning bid is
expected to come in between $500 million-$600 million, and the
ownership should be determined by September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given all the revenues that franchise is going to generate, I
think that we're certainly justified . . . in expecting something
in that range,'' Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although there will be plenty of debate over the plan to stock
the Browns with players, a formula similar to that used with
Carolina and Jacksonville could be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is a good chance owners will approve the sale
of the Minnesota Vikings to San Antonio businessman Red McCombs.
The powerful finance committee huddled here Monday evening to
review documents on that deal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
