<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SOUTHERN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big accomplishments expected from Ga. Southern
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The Georgia Southern Eagles are the choice of
both the media and coaches to soar highest in the nine-member
Southern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of no one attending the conference's annual
two-day ``Rouser'' that ended Monday afternoon, the team picked to
finish atop the league is stationed in Statesboro.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, first-year coach Paul Johnson guided Georgia
Southern to a 10-3 record and the school's second Southern
Conference title since it joined the league in '93. And now the
locals in Statesboro are talking loudly about a possible fifth 1-AA
national title. ``That just means we've got a target on our chest
and everybody is shooting at us,'' said Johnson, who has been
associated with 50 victories at Georgia Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, enough people thinkJohnson and his staff have
brought the Eagles back to the level that won four national titles.
</P>
<P>
   A four-year assistant at Georgia Southern during the coaching
days of Erk Russell, Johnson was part of two of those
championships, in 1985 and '86. His 1997 team, which lost three
games by a combined total of 22 points, returns 17 starters among
47 lettermen.
</P>
<P>
   And Georgia Southern's schedule could not be more favorable for
quarterback Greg Hill and mates to make a run for the championship.
The Eagles start the season with three games at Paulson Stadium
among a total of seven home games.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, at 5-11, 165 pounds, was a big numbers guy as a freshman
and sophomore. Last season, the Saratoga, Fla., native rushed for
1,171 yards and 18 touchdowns, and passed 770 yards more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, (Hill) is as good as any quarterback I've ever
coached,'' said Johnson, who worked with legendary Eagle Tracy Ham.
``I'm excited about him, and I think he's going to have a great
season.''
</P>
<P>
   In the conference media poll, the Eagles received 17 of the 18
first-place votes. The other went to Furman, which was picked
fourth in both polls, behind Appalachian State and East Tennessee
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, Georgia Southern is in the right position, and
probably East Tennessee,'' Western Carolina coach Bill Bleil said.
``But three through nine could go any way.''
</P>
<P>
   East Tennessee State, which replaced SMU-bound Mike Cavan last
year with 39-year-old Paul Hamilton, was the runnerup pick in the
coaches' poll but third behind Appalachian State in the media
voting.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being the overwhelming choice to win the conference
crown, Georgia Southern had only one player selected to the
pre-season all-conference first offensive unit, junior guard Mark
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Three Eagles were picked for the first defensive unit: linemen
Voncellies Allen, a junior, and Eric Davis, a senior, and sophomore
linebacker Daryl Morrell.
</P>
<P>
   The conference gathering ended Monday with a speech by former
NFL quarterback and coach Sam Wyche, who played at North Fulton
High School and Furman.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Conference media preseason poll
</P>
<P>
   1. Georgia Southern 161 points
</P>
<P>
   2. Appalachian State 130
</P>
<P>
   3. East Tennessee State 125
</P>
<P>
   4. Furman 115
</P>
<P>
   5. Chattanooga 92
</P>
<P>
   6. The Citadel 62
</P>
<P>
   7. Western Carolina 58
</P>
<P>
   8. Wofford 44
</P>
<P>
   9. Virginia Military 19
</P>
<P>
   Coaches' poll
</P>
<P>
   1. Georgia Southern 71.5 points
</P>
<P>
   2. East Tennessee State 65.5
</P>
<P>
   3. Appalachian State 65
</P>
<P>
   4. Furman 55
</P>
<P>
   5. Chattanooga 50
</P>
<P>
   6. The Citadel 36
</P>
<P>
   7. Western Carolina 29
</P>
<P>
   8. Wofford 19
</P>
<P>
   9. Virginia Military 14
</P>
