A5161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      07-27 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Runway Shows May Be Held Earlier
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The wheels are turning to shift the entire slate of
women's American runway shows from the end of the fashion cycle to
the beginning, pre-empting London, Milan and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an 80 percent chance the shows will be early,'' said
Fern Mallis, the executive director of Seventh on Sixth, the
organizing body for the unified American shows held twice a year in
Bryant Park and other locations around the city. Normally, they are
held in April and in late October. The change would mean shows in
February and September.
</P>
<P>
   Seventh on Sixth personnel are now busy with the men's shows
that are under way and when they are over, their attention will
shift to reorganizing the women's schedule. Dates under review for
the fall 1999 shows are Feb. 8 to 12 and Feb. 14 to 19. The
American menswear shows, which take place in early February or
midmonth, may be adjusted to give the industry more time between
menswear and women's wear.
</P>
<P>
   While the final decision rests with the designers for whom Ms.
Mallis works, conversations have already taken place with sponsors,
Bryant Park Restoration Corp., which runs Bryant Park, and FTL
Architects, which provides the tents. Several designers said they
would rather wait another season to make the switch but the
industry cannot afford to have a split fashion week, Ms. Mallis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all designers welcome the move to earlier dates. As Nicole
Miller pointed out, it will force designers to show their clothes
long before the consumer is ready to buy. She added that it would
ignite a forest fire of earlier shows, earlier deliveries to
retailers and earlier promotional sales in stores. But she said she
would go along with it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mallis said, ``Some people see that if the bulk of the
people are going to move, they'll do it, though grudgingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Erecting and heating tents in February would not be a problem,
Ms. Mallis said she has been told. But if there is a snowstorm,
fashion week will be fraught with complications. Bryant Park has
pledged to work with Seventh on Sixth on the new dates but has
already sounded the alarm. ``Early September is still very much
summer in New York City,'' Ms. Mallis said. ``People will not be
too happy that we're taking over the park at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan follows news of the decision by Helmut Lang, Calvin
Klein, Donna Karan and Searle Blatt, announced this month, to stage
their spring 1998 show in September rather than October or early
November.
</P>
<P>
   Sneakers Change Tune
</P>
<P>
   While the United States is choking on sneaker endorsements by
athletes, an Australian sneaker company, Royal Distributions, has
moved to music. It has hired Goldie, the irreverent English DJ and
producer, to design a special-edition athletic footwear, which it
called Royal Headz.
</P>
<P>
   The company made 2,000 pairs, all of which sold out, according
to a spokeswoman for Royal. The Headz name is a play on metal heads
music. She did not know if the Goldie sneaker would be made
available in the United States, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Barneys New York will introduce Royal Elastics for fall.
Made from synthetic material, the distinctive Royal slip-on
sneakers, or trainers, as the English call their athletic footwear,
have elastic side gussets and look somewhat like a designer version
of a traditional sneaker crossbred with an orderly's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Music is the engine that drives style. And there are as many
people these days making fashion statements in sneakers as there
are working out in them. However, athletic footwear companies have
not tapped into this entertainer-endorsement market.
</P>
<P>
   Nike, for example, still depends solely on athletes like Michael
Jordan, Tiger Woods, Sheryl Swoopes and Dawn Staley to design and
endorse its products. ``We position ourselves as a company that is
geared to athletes,'' Robert Mitchell, senior manager for corporate
communications for Nike, said. ``If someone wants to wear the
products for some other purpose, that's fine, but Nike products are
produced for athletes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
