<SLUG> BC-MA-DEADLY-PARTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMEOWNER GETS COMMUNITY SERVICE IN GIRL'S DRINKING DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A North Andover man was ordered Monday to perform 100
hours of community service in a case in which a teenage girl died
after getting drunk at a party at his house.
</P>
<P>
   John Zarella, 45, was allowed by a Lawrence District Court judge
to plead no contest to a charge of contributing to the delinquency
of a minor. Under the plea Zarella did not have to admit guilt
before accepting punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ellen Flatley accepted the plea despite a tearful plea
from the victim's mother to punish Zarella more severely for
allowing minors to drink alcoholic beverages in his house &UR;  &LR; and then
ignoring the victim as she lay on his basement floor, dying.
</P>
<P>
   Meaghan Duggan, 17, fell down a flight of basement stairs in
Zarella's Campion Road home on Sept. 27 and cracked her skull in
two places. Duggan's mother, Teresa, said Zarella admitted to
her &UR;  &LR; that he supplied alcohol to the teenagers who were celebrating
his daughter Nicole's 18th birthday in his home.
</P>
<P>
   Duggan, a senior at North Andover High School, tumbled down the
stairs after drinking about 15 beers, then lay at the base of the
steps for seven hours before an ambulance was called. It was
revealed in court Monday that Duggan was dragged unconcious on the
basement floor while others cleaned up around her and that Zarella
and a another person stepped over her.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could they do that?'' Duggan's mother, Teresa, demanded.
``You wouldn't do it to an animal. How could you do it to a
child?''
</P>
<P>
   Zarella, who owns a water and sewer pipe cleaning business, left
the court without comment and could not be reached by telephone
Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Flatley also ordered Zarella to attend a seminar on brain
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Duggan, who has terminal cancer and who lost her husband
to the same disease in 1991, sobbed as she delivered her victim
impact statement to the court. She recalled a daughter who lit up a
room when she walked in; a girl who kissed and hugged her mother
daily and whose smile and embrace will be missed forever. Meaghan's
older sister, Marcia, also told the court about the pain of losing
a sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is a slap to Meaghan's memory for John Zarella to
stand here and not admit what he did,'' said Teresa Duggan. ``I
will become a victim again if you just slap John Zarella on the
wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   An Essex County prosecutor recommended that Judge Flatley find
Zarella guilty and sentence him to one year in the county House of
Correction with 60 days to be served and the balance suspended for
two years probation.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney may appeal the judge's decision at the end
of Zarella's one-year community service sentence, according to
Charles Grimes, a spokesman for Essex District Attorney Kevin
Burke.
</P>
<P>
   Duggan's attorneys, meanwhile, will likely file a civil suit
against Zarella next week. Robert R. Berluti said the suit would be
the only way the Duggans can make Zarella accountable for his
actions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
