<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5168 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADS-OVERLOAD-AZR &LR;      07-27 1961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADS-OVERLOAD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCT PLUGS LOSE PUNCH AMID COMMERCIAL OVERLOAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN VAN DER WERF  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - A new pizza delivery offer is rubber-banded to your
doorknob _ every day. Classified circulars are so numbing they are
slowly turning to mulch on your front lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banner'' advertisements on the Internet are disguised to look
like computer upgrades. You have to wear a certain T-shirt to get
free popcorn at the movies. Rump roast is on sale at Albertson's.
The phone rings and a resonant recorded male voice says, ``Hello. .
.''
</P>
<P>
   You hang up. You know what's coming.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are besieged by advertising, an estimated 600 to 1,200
commercial messages every day. And that's probably an underestimate
on days they visit a mall or a supermarket. Or watch MTV.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't going to change. The advertising industry is growing at
a pace faster than almost any other; 1998 should be the first year
it becomes a $200 billion-a-year business domestically.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much advertising that I think the industry is kind
of inoculating the public against it,'' said Tim Riester, partner
in Riester/Robb advertising agency of Phoenix. ``As we do consumer
testing to try to figure out a way to get to consumers, we find
people have just become jaded.''
</P>
<P>
   There was probably a time when someone saw a sign atop a
taxicab, and said, ``Wow! What a great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there are five blimps floating over the Super Bowl in
addition to the once-extraordinary Goodyear blimp, and chihuahuas
lead us in reverential songs to taco chains, and we shrug our
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers are resorting to beaming advertisements onto clouds
with lasers. A middle school in Grapevine, Texas, has a Dr Pepper
billboard on the roof to catch the attention of passing airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of other advertising techniques just getting tested
are likely to reach consumers soon:
</P>
<P>
   _Direct-mail videos and CD-ROMs. This idea started with
political candidates in 1992 and is spreading quickly. Some Phoenix
area consumers have gotten videos in the mail from A.J.'s Fine
Foods; Whole Foods, a new supermarket in Tempe; and Coulter
Cadillac. Expect it to grow dramatically, with Jiffy Lube, LA
Fitness and Nationwide Insurance among the companies that have
signed up lately to send videos to potential customers, said Robert
Brucato, an account manager in the Phoenix office of Vaughan
Communications, a Minneapolis company that is one of the
originators of the approach.
</P>
<P>
   _Movie advertisements on ATMs. Quick sound and video clips play
while you wait for your money. This has been test-marketed in San
Diego since November and may spread nationally.
</P>
<P>
   _There are ads for the Arizona Lottery on the handles of the gas
nozzles at Circle K convenience stores. . Some Arco and SuperPumper
stations have taken the concept one step further, fitting gas-pump
islands with video screens that run a stream of advertisements to
capture the attention of bored tank-fillers.
</P>
<P>
   _Microsoft was paying $200 to university professors who used its
programming tools in a scholarly presentation, or merely mentioned
the software. That offer has been pulled off the company's Web
site, but company officials hint that it might return.
</P>
<P>
   _Sabre Group Holdings Inc., owner of the nation's largest
travel-agent reservation network, said earlier this month that it
is considering selling individual travel itineraries to hotels,
car-rental agencies and other business partners. Consumers' travel
plans are ``a potential gold mine,'' according to the company. This
plan, however, might run aground because of privacy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   What a refreshing change that would be. There is very little
that is considered off-limits for advertising. Consider the growing
number of bars and restaurants putting advertisements on the inside
of the door to restroom stalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always trying to figure out the sacred places where no
advertisers have gone before, and we all rush there,'' said Will
Rodgers, a partner in SHR Perceptual Management in Scottsdale.
``They end up being further ways to pollute our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The public has become so inured to it that the very notion of
what constitutes advertising is changing.
</P>
<P>
   ABC and ESPN are being congratulated for their
``commercial-free'' broadcasts of World Cup soccer games. Instead
of interrupting play, the announcers said, ``Thanks to Budweiser
(or Canon or the U.S. Army, et al) for sponsoring this portion of
the game commercial-free.'' Then that sponsor's logo was on the
screen for five minutes or so, until the next sponsor took over.
</P>
<P>
   By whose definition is that ``commercial-free''?
</P>
<P>
   Billboards are banned along urban freeways, but advertisers have
figured out a way around that. A year ago, the Arizona Department
of Transportation announced that it would allow commercial
enterprises to adopt sections of the highway and pay for their
cleanup. Now the signs, which used to have the names of an Elks
Club or a college fraternity, carry the logos of Fox 10, or KZZP
radio, or Popular Outdoor stores.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in sports, it's way out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   You may have thought sports had reached the depths of crass
commercialism seven years ago when a college football bowl game was
named after a Weed Eater.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, every timeout, every listing of stats has a sponsor.
Nearly every stadium also has a corporate name, and the sale of the
naming rights are automatically figured as a source of revenue when
the stadium is being financed. This seems to be an American
phenomenon. Note that the new soccer stadium outside Paris is the
Stade de France, not the Evian Stade de France.
</P>
<P>
   Watch a baseball game, and just so you won't concentrate too
much on the batter, a rolling sign behind him is advising you where
to get a home loan or what sports drink to buy.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there is Diamondbacks' Bank One Ballpark,
the stadium with the biggest advertising package of any sports
stadium in history, a $430 million agreement with 60 companies.
</P>
<P>
   One baseball fan was so outraged that he couldn't find an
American flag for all of the billboards at BOB that he wrote a
letter to ``The Arizona Republic'' to complain about it. You know,
the newspaper that has the most prominent sign of all at the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   People used to go to the movies for an escape from real life. No
more. It was maybe 10 years ago that advertisements started running
in movie theaters before the feature film, but long before that,
ads were running as part of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, the astronauts in the British sci-fi flick ``Fire
Maidens fromOuter Space'' called uncanny amounts of camera time to
their Camel cigarettes and Longines watches.
</P>
<P>
   This sales method really seemed to hit its stride with the
Superman movies of the late '70s and '80s. Villains were constantly
being hurtled into every sort of billboard. It was in ``Superman''
(1978), the original, that we learned that back in Smallville,
Clark Kent's breakfast of champions was . . . Cheerios.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, with each new James Bond movie, you can expect ad
campaigns with star Pierce Brosnan not only hawking the film but
all the products he uses in it.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger. Better. Ubiquitous.
</P>
<P>
   They have been the watchwords of the advertising world. But
there are many more examples of creeping advertising that are more
cunning.
</P>
<P>
   Now, not only do you get spam, or ``junk'' e-mail, you get spam
pages. Call the number back and you get a recorded message
describing how to earn $1,000 a week by selling from your home, or
some other such pitch. There are ads on golf courses that show
golfers the shape and length of the hole, then advise them where to
drink after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Just about every television station or network has its logo in
the lower right-hand corner of the screen at all times. Except, of
course, when there are real ads running. On a recent afternoon, the
Channel 3 (KTVK) logo was superimposed over the Superstation logo
on ``Inside Edition,'' which, showing that it is learning, has
moved its logo to the lower left-hand corner.
</P>
<P>
   Supermarkets know everything about you. Research shows that soup
sales drop 6 percent if the cans are arranged alphabetically on the
shelves. Toothbrush sales increase 8 percent if they are at eye
level. Background music with 60 beats per minute increases sales by
38.2 percent over music with 108 beats per minute. It's all a
science, and now some enterprising marketer has found that grocery
shoppers also look at the floor a lot. So now that's where ads are
appearing _ beneath our feet.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit advertising used to be no more complex than a sticker on a
bunch of bananas that told you where they were grown and who grew
them. Pick up an apple now and a sticker tells you that ``Liar,
Liar'' is available on video.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of us have become walking billboards. Not only do we seek
out and pay a premium for clothing designed by Tommy Hilfiger or
Guess?, we are willing to wear shirts that advertise the maker.
</P>
<P>
   It is a clever form of imagemaking.
</P>
<P>
   For clothing manufacturers, creating an attitude is as important
as designing a fashion. People are looking to create a personality
for themselves by the clothes they wear. Wearing clothing with the
name printed on it helps create that image, Riester said.
</P>
<P>
   According to several ad executives, this sort of imagemaking is
where the industry is headed.
</P>
<P>
   Forrest Richardson, partner in a small Phoenix advertising
agency, Richardson Or Richardson, said, ``I think the way to cut
through the clutter is to make ads that don't look like ads.
Consumers no longer buy products, they buy brands. You need to
create a culture for yours.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Nike isn't just a maker of athletic shoes. It is a
major player in youth sports and event promotion. The swoosh logo
gives the buyer an association with famous athletes, all of them
carefully selected. And it is now a retailing concept: Niketown,
the huge, multilevel stores with video walls and loud music that
are slowly spreading around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an environment, an association,'' Richardson said. ``That
is advertising in the year 2000. That is how you sell Nike shoes
today.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an approach that is similar to the way Dodge saved its
truck business, Rodgers said. Ford may run ads saying its vehicles
are ``built Ford tough,'' but Dodge, by attaching a grille that
looks as if it came from a Mack truck, ``redefined what tough looks
like.'' Now Dodge, a distant third before the redesign, sells
almost as many trucks as Ford, the industry leader.
</P>
<P>
   Simple visual images that are instantly associated with a
product will become more important, Rodgers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the world gets more complicated, we tend to want to
simplify,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Riester sees advertising heading in a completely different
direction. The competition just to get products into a store is so
intense, he said, that he sees more marketing being directed at
buyers, store owners and the other people making decisions on
product mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hot buttons that would motivate a store are much different
than those that will motivate the consumer,'' Riester said. ``I
think that's the direction the smart companies will go.''
</P>
<P>
   So does that mean we will never again be subjected to Louie, the
Budweiser iguana?
</P>
<P>
   Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else in advertising, this has been researched.
</P>
<P>
   Don Godfrey, a professor of journalism at Arizona State
University who has studied advertising extensively, said studies
have consistently found that ``the more annoying the ad, the more
we remember it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martin Van Der Werf can be reached at martin.vanderwerf(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5171 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADS-OVERLOAD-AZR &LR;      07-27 1962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADS-OVERLOAD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCT PLUGS LOSE PUNCH AMID COMMER CIAL OVERLOAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN VAN DER WERF  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
