<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL TV SCHEDULES CERTAINLY DO LOOK SAFE _ AND SORRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Reporters covering the annual fall season preview
in Pasadena returned to their hotel rooms to find an unwanted
intruder: a 4-foot inflatable punching bag of Hong Kong action star
Sammo Hung. CBS had planted the wiggly, wobbly air bag to promote
``Martial Law,'' its campy drama featuring the pleasingly plump
Hung, who established his reputation as a skilled physical
performer in Kung Fu comedies like ``Enter the Fat Dragon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Martial Law,'' about a Hong Kong cop who joins the Los Angeles
police force, is CBS' attempt to squelch its image as the network
for the gray-haired, a PBS with sitcoms. By offering a series in
which kicking and fighting is emphasized over plot and
characterization, (uh, isn't that ``Walker, Texas Ranger''?) CBS
expects to lure those disloyal young males who disappeared when its
NFL football telecasts did.
</P>
<P>
   With pigskin returning this season, CBS expects its male
audience to come back. For insurance, it has lined up a
testosterone-laden fall season. Seven of nine series screened here
featured male leads; the others are ``Maggie Winters,'' with
``Murphy Brown's'' Faith Ford as a woman forced to return to her
tiny hometown, and ``To Have &AMP; To Hold,'' a romantic drama zeroing
in on the union of a hard-nosed detective (Jason Beghe) and his
longtime love, a feminist lawyer (Moira Kelly).
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get younger,'' admitted Leslie Moonves, CBS'
president and chief executive officer, during the 19-day publicity
blitz called the ``press tour,'' which ended Sunday with UPN and
its almost laughable version of must-see TV. ``This effort is
partially based on economics and partly to provide a broad range of
programming for our viewers. We want to have something for everyone
on CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the new mantra for NBC, CBS and ABC _ to be ``broad,''
to be something to everyone, to, basically, color inside the lines
and drive the posted speed limit. In other words, to be safe. Never
before has television entered a season with such trepidation and
self-doubt, trying to create TV programs people want to watch while
keeping a strict account of the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   As channel choices multiply, as the audience continues to drift
from the traditional networks to cable, satellite and the Internet,
producers and network executives are less willing to take risks,
even as audience erosion continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't gamble when you're a really big network,'' says
Teller, half of the comedy-magician duo Penn and Teller, whose new
series of variety specials will air on cable's FX this fall.
``They've got this idea: You must go after 21-year-olds who drink
this brand of beer. And if you have three minutes that might not be
exactly what they're looking for, then everybody's going to run
away. And I just believe that human beings are more complex than
that. I believe you learn a lot from demographics and focus groups.
But I also believe that, you know, 20-year-old frat boys also want
to see stuff that's good once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good'' is relative in the new TV landscape. For every
``Becker,'' CBS' midseason hope, a well-conceived Ted Danson sitcom
about a cantankerous doctor, there are five series like ``Mercy
Point,'' a painful-to-watch UPN drama that's a cross between ``ER''
and ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now there's a tremendous drain on the creative community
_ it's as simple as that,'' says Amy Lippman, co-creator and
co-executive producer of ``Party of Five.'' ``It's a situation
where there are more shows than performers with national followings
or possessing a persona which translates well to TV or even
writers, who are being hired and promoted before they are ready.
They merely write in packs, feeding off other shows.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Thus, sameness. ``They all tend to be about dating and more
dating, and specifically very beautiful 20-year-olds dating,'' is
the way Diane English, ``Murphy Brown'' creator and producer whose
new series is ``Living in Captivity'' on Fox, puts it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's probably true that there are just a handful of people
who can execute these things well at any given time on the planet,
and so when you try to do 65 of these things a season, you're just
not going to get a level of quality that you would get 20 years ago
from a singular talent like Norman Lear.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, 36 new series are scheduled to begin this season,
beginning as early as the second week of August and as late as
mid-October. With 21 comedies, the yuks rule, though that number is
smaller than in years past. (Last season, NBC had 18 comedies; this
season, just 14).
</P>
<P>
   Comedy pilots screened here worth mentioning are NBC's ``Will &AMP;
Grace''; Fox's ``That '70s Show''; and ABC's ``Two of a Kind,''
``The Hughleys'' and particularly ``Sports Night,'' a high-grade
dramatization of ESPN's popular ``Sports Center.'' (Nathan Lane's
sitcom, ``Encore!Encore!,'' wasn't screened.)
</P>
<P>
   On the drama side, The WB's ``Hyperion Bay'' and ``Felicity''
are worth recommending. The romantic in me wanted to see more of
``To Have &AMP; To Hold'' before dismissing it to the cancellation
heap. NBC's family drama ``Trinity,'' from ``ER's'' John Wells,
received far more notice for its focus on Irish Americans (the
``ethnic'' trend for the season) than for its content.
</P>
<P>
   But there's not one ``Ally McBeal'' among the bunch, not one
series that clears your senses from the first sniff.
</P>
<P>
   After being battered for ``Nothing Sacred'' and ``Cracker,''
last season's most engaging one-two punch, ABC wanted to ``go
lighter, have more fun,'' and the result is ``Cupid,'' about a man
convinced he's the Love God; ``Vengeance Unlimited,'' about a
creepy vigilante; and ``Fantasy Island,'' which has taken on a
darker face lift with Malcolm McDowell as Mr. Roarke. He and the
other island workers aren't there for fun _ they appear to be
trapped, paying off some kind of nefarious dues.
</P>
<P>
   By moving ``King of the Hill'' to Tuesdays, Fox broke up the
great one-two punch it had on Sundays with ``The Simpsons.'' In
terms of gaining viewers on other nights, it's not a bad move.
``King'' will face two weary giants in ``Home Improvement'' on ABC
and ``Mad About You'' on NBC. Both are likely in their final
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting back watching the bigger boys duke it out is The WB,
which opened its session with a video montage of its young, hot
stars, many of whom are popping up in feature films. With the new
``Felicity,'' another series starring young pretty people, joining
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and ``Dawson's Creek,'' The WB is
creating a trend in which networks are about as narrow as cable
channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some degree (the networks) are starting to become
self-defined,'' said Garth Ancier, The WB's president of
entertainment. ``Fox is still a younger network than NBC or ABC.
You don't need a chart to know that it's your parents watching CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's exciting to us is that you can build a real business on
12- to 34-year-olds. That's the hot target. It says you don't do
your shows with Ted Danson. You do them with Joshua Jackson. Or
Sarah Michelle Gellar. That's the future of television as we see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
