<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SOCSEC-350&AMP;AD     07-27 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOCSEC-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.M.)  
 CLINTON MULLS MARKET-ORIENTED APPROACH TO SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ President Clinton said Monday that he was
seriously considering relying on the financial markets to help
solve Social Security's long-term problems, but said he had not
made up his mind about any of the details.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a forum and town hall meeting here on Social
Security, Clinton discussed the pros and cons of establishing
individual investment accounts within the retirement system or
having the government itself invest a chunk of Social Security's
reserves in stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't know what I would do today,'' Clinton said
when asked which option he would choose if forced to make a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   But he all but endorsed the general notion of seeking higher
investment returns on Wall Street to reduce the need for benefit
cuts, tax increases or other changes to ensure that Social Security
will be able to pay promised retirement benefits in coming decades
to the baby boom generation. Without any changes, Social Security
will run short of money starting in 2032.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any way we can get a higher rate of return in a
market economy, while minimizing the risk, whether it's in either
one of these approaches, we ought to go for it, because the other
alternatives were much less pleasant already,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president has not made any final decisions, his aides said,
and some of his advisers still argue that Social Security should
not invest at all in stocks and corporate bonds. Currently Social
Security's reserves are invested in safe but relatively
low-yielding government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials said investing in the markets will
more than likely be a component of whatever approach Clinton
ultimately supports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president was very much making clear that he is seriously
considering some form of equity investment as part of Social
Security reform,'' said White House economic policy adviser Gene
Sperling. ``But he is holding out the caveat that the public and
Congress and the administration are going to have to be willing to
deal with the potential downsides of the risk.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nearly all proposals for shoring up Social Security rely to some
degree on reaping the presumed gains available on Wall Street. But
there is a vast gulf between one camp _ led by Republicans but
including a number of prominent Democrats _ that wants to allow
individuals to invest a portion of their Social Security payroll
taxes, and another camp led by liberal Democrats in the House that
is pushing for the government to invest the retirement system's
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The differing approaches were vigorously debated Monday by
politicians of both parties and a panel of experts assembled here
for the third in a series of Social Security forums organized this
year by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Diamond, an economist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, said private investments in the market as part of
Social Security would be risky for individuals, and that a chunk of
any gains would be eaten up by the high costs of administering
millions of accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Boskin, an economist at Stanford University, said there
was a ``very strong moral case'' in favor of granting Americans the
chance to own stocks and build wealth in their own name, and that
many of the criticisms of private accounts amounted to ``scare
mongering.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won a measure of support Monday from Sen. Pete Domenici,
R-N.M., who was among those on the stage with the president. Like
Clinton, Domenici is battling plans by House Republicans to use
projected federal budget surpluses to finance a big tax cut as well
as to deal with Social Security's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called in January for any surpluses to be placed off
limits until the country settles on a plan for Social Security.
Domenici reiterated his support for that approach Monday, saying
Clinton had settled on a ``fantastic fiscal policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
