<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALARMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALSE ALARMS RING UP BIG BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HANNAH MILLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Thousands of Phoenix area homeowners and business
people have installed alarm systems to ward off burglars.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems they have more to fear from Christmas decorations,
billowing drapes and feisty pets.
</P>
<P>
   That's because 65 percent of alarm calls to police in Phoenix
alone are false, caused by an endless variety of human errors and
costing police $4.9 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, alarms are one of the top three calls police
receive, along with domestic violence and suspicious persons.
</P>
<P>
   It's the price of fear _ escalating in the past five years as
the number of alarm systems in homes has doubled, as prices drop
and developers install systems as standard features.
</P>
<P>
   And some people must pay the ultimate price: False Alarm School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Micky set my alarm off,'' admitted Bob Stott, sitting at a
school-style desk last week in a small room at the Mesa Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my ferret.''
</P>
<P>
   The schools, usually held twice a month in several Phoenix area
cities, are two-hour sessions where the electronically challenged
can learn the secrets of their security systems. Most students are
there voluntarily, though Tempe requires its top 10 violators every
month to attend.
</P>
<P>
   More than 700 students have gone through Mesa's class, and
Phoenix boasts a 90 percent success rate _ no more false alarms _
for its students. Now Glendale and Chandler are considering
starting schools of their own.
</P>
<P>
   New homeowner Donna Foster said she enrolled just to prevent
having to pay Mesa's fine, which is $50 per false alarm after the
first four free ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it, but I set my motion detector off the first
day I had it,'' Foster said. ``I think it was the paper drapes . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the cause, police are left to deal with the result
_ 282 false alarms a day last year in Phoenix alone. An estimated
70 percent are due to human error _ which is combatable, although
alarm operating instructions are often as well understood as those
for a VCR.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has become so bad that most cities have hired
administrators just to deal with the devices, which now monitor 1
in 6 American homes. Cities also have introduced increasingly
stiffer fines for false alarms to cover costs.
</P>
<P>
   Perimeter monitors, fixed-glass alarms, passive infrared, panic
buttons _ homeowners feel safer, and business owners swear by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who doesn't have one in this area,'' said Claire
Schere, a Scottsdale retiree who lives alone _ and well-guarded _
``is just crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the statistics from Phoenix don't conclusively show that
alarms deter break-ins. And experts say that the largest proportion
of burglary happens to those who can't afford alarms anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Valley police take alarms seriously, recommending them to
homeowners and giving calls the highest priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do prevent burglary,'' said Detective Mike McCullough of
the Phoenix Police Department, ``but in an intangible way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa police Sgt. Bryan Soller said, ``We always treat alarms as
the real thing. It's not aggravating, but it is a burden.
Especially if we're getting hammered in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every city is as lucky. In many, the false-alarm rate is as
high as 98 percent. Las Vegas doesn't even dispatch an officer
anymore, unless on-scene security guards or owners call it in
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix area homeowners can relax: Police will respond, no
matter what. One unlucky Mesa police officer drove out to a house
four times one night before he realized a balloon was setting off
the home's motion detector.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely worth having an alarm in your home,'' said
Susan Brenton of the Arizona Burglary and Fire Alarm Association.
``Just make sure that you are familiar with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Brenton herself knows, no one is safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My house was broken into two weeks ago,'' Brenton said.
``Because my alarm went off, all they got was an old VCR. And
that's when I was at the National Alarm Association conference.'' &QL; 
Hannah Miller can be reached at hannah.miller(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
