A5184 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-MILITARY-ECON-A     07-27 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MILITARY-ECON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN REPORT ON MILITARY, CHINA CALLS ITSELF `PEACE-LOVING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also CHINA-MILITARY) 
(ART ADV: A graphic showing China's military-industrial complex is
being sent to NYT graphics clients, for use with either
CHINA-MILITARY-ECON or CHINA-MILITARY. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China's locomotive-like economic growth and its
brittle public face have helped foment a perception overseas that
it poses a growing military threat to its neighbors. In the next
century, some experts have predicted, China could even clash
militarily with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by today's measurements, sketched out vaguely in a report
issued here Monday, China's military forces are still rudimentary
by international standards. China's military budget was officially
less than $10 billion in 1998, not 4 percent of the U.S. budget and
less than half of South Korea's.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no mention of the estimated 15,000 businesses
controlled by the army or how much they earn.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``China's National Defense,'' is a rare public
description of the scope of operations by the People's Liberation
Army. The study was apparently written for an international
audience, laden as it is with assurances that China is a
peace-loving nation.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report reveals no previously unknown vital
information about the military forces, Western military analysts
said it was a milestone for a military whose most basic operations
are ordinarily considered secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese don't give very much away here,'' said Tai Ming
Cheung, an expert on the Chinese military who works for the Hong
Kong office of Kroll Associates. ``The real issue is that it's a
symbolic breakthrough just to release this kind of report.''
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from other countries, especially the United
States, to be more open about its basic operations, Beijing has
used the report to outline the army's basic aims, duties and
operations. Yet much of the study is simply bland pronouncements
about the commitment to peace and regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Facts show that China is a responsible big country and a firm
force safeguarding world peace and stability,'' is a typical
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The report reiterates Beijing's long-held position on Taiwan,
that reunification is favored through peaceful means, but that
resorting to force is always an option.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most relevant section is on expenditures, even
though it relies only on official statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Dividing its military spending into three categories, the report
says that $3.5 billion was spent last year on personnel costs, $3.2
billion on ``maintenance of activities'' and $3.1 billion on
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Overall the report insists that the national military policy is
defensive in nature and is geared toward resisting aggression. It
extols the country's ``peace-loving tradition'' and says China has
resorted to military force only after an enemy had struck first _
though border disputes with India in 1962 and Vietnam in 1979 might
suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese people are willing, together with the people of
the other countries in the world,'' the study says, ``to make
unremitting efforts for the lofty cause of promoting world peace
and development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
