A5186 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-HNS &LR;      07-27 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS SHOW RENEWED INTEREST IN VISITORS CENTER IN WAKE OF
SHOOTINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prompted by the deadly shootings of two Capitol
guards, lawmakers have resurrected the idea of constructing an
underground visitors center where tourists could be screened before
entering the main building.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss, said Monday that he
was ready to move on the visitors center, which he estimated could
cost as much as $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should look at even doing it this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and others said the visitors center would not only enhance
security but provide more comfortable accommodations and
educational facilities for the millions of people who visit the
Capitol each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always troubles me when I come to work in the Capitol and I
see our constituents lined up in the heat, the rain, the snow and
with nowhere really to go to find out what they are fixing to see,
to get information on this great building,'' said Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he hoped private interests would fund most of the
project. About $23 million has been raised for the project through
the sale of a commemorative coin that was issued on the 200th
anniversary of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a visitors center was proposed in 1983 in response
to a bomb that exploded that year in the Senate area. The initial
plans were completed in 1991. At the time, a number of lawmakers,
including then House Minority Whip Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., objected
to the cost and scope of the center.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later Congress appropriated $2.5 million to translate
the concept into a formal design. In 1995 the architect of the
Capitol presented the refined plan to Congress, with a $95 million
price tag.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 draft plan submitted to Congress called for all tourists
to go through a central screening area in the visitors center,
which would be constructed underground on the east grounds of the
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   After they moved through the security area, the tourists would
be allowed to proceed by escalator, stairs or elevator into the
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Currently tourists enter through a number of doors at the
Capitol, where they go through metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that the security area would be placed ``at a
secure distance from the Capitol itself.'' It would include metal
detectors, facilities for interrogation and a temporary storage
area for impounded property.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed three-level visitors center would also include a
cafeteria, rest rooms, an exhibition hall and auditoriums where
tourists could watch a 15-minute informational video.
</P>
<P>
   While lawmakers are expressing renewed interest in the visitors
center, a spokesman for a conservative taxpayer's groups said the
project would be an expensive and ineffective solution to violence
in the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't any proof that an underground visitors center
would stop a deranged mad man with a gun,'' said Pete Sepp, a
spokesman for the National Taxpayers Union. ``Unfortunately
Congress can take a tragedy and head in the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sepp said that if lawmakers are worried about security, they
should consider beefing up police presence or building just an
underground checkpoint rather than an elaborate visitors center. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
