<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-COUNTRY-PRIMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S WHO, AND WHO'S HOT, IN ALT COUNTRY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-ALTERNATIVE0-COUNTRY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _BR5-49. Great clothes, great songs, a great twangy
neo-hillbilly sound and a dandy sense of humor all make this
Nashville band one of the genre's emerging superstar outfits.
</P>
<P>
   _Junior Brown. Beyond the oddly shaped guit-steel and the
hilarious slice-of-night-life lyrics (as in ``My Wife Thinks You're
Dead'') there is an amazing amount of real talent and passion, as
both an instrumentalist and a keeper of the Ray Price/Ernest Tubb
flame.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Earle. One part troubador, one part stone hard rocker,
Earle has long been one of Nashville's best songwriters. And in
recent years, having put drugs behind him, he's recorded two
excellent CDs, ``Train a Comin' '' and ``I Feel Alright.''
</P>
<P>
   _Joe Ely. With his ability to blend honky-tonk, roadhouse rock
and blues, Ely was alt-country a good 20 years before people began
throwing the term around. He still delivers dynamite shows and
terrific CDs, including the recent ``Twistin' in the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   _Robert Earl Keen. Another Texan, another great writer. Keen's
mix of danceable country and folk first made him hugely popular on
Texas college campuses, but recently he's gone beyond cult fave.
</P>
<P>
   _The Mavericks. America's best band? Quite possibly. With their
mix of trad country, Latin, rock and lounge, the Miami-based band
(led by the gorgeous, Roy Orbisonish vocals of Raul Malo) has cut a
series of wonderfully eclectic records, including this year's
marvelous ``Trampoline.''
</P>
<P>
   _Old 97's. The Dallas-based 97's' raw-boned country-rock sound
has a real chance of being embraced by a wide rock audience _ and
certainly deserves to be. Catch 'em whenever you can, and look for
a new CD in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   _Gillian Welch. She grew up in Los Angeles, but her music sounds
straight out of the hills of West Virginia, circa 1933. Welch's
debut, ``Revival,'' was one of the best CDs of 1996, and ``Hell
Among the Yearlings'' (which comes out in August) is just as good.
</P>
<P>
   _Whiskeytown. One part mournful country and one part Tom
Petty-meets-the-Replacements rock, the music Ryan Adams and his
posse makes is all frayed edges and regret, and often as memorable
as that of classic country artists. The band will open for John
Fogerty at Starplex in August.
</P>
<P>
   _Wilco. Like Son Volt, this band was formed out of the ashes of
the highly influential Uncle Tupelo. Wilco is the better band: Jeff
Tweedy and company make finely honed music that could almost be
called art-country _ and sometimes rocks plenty hard. ``Being
There,'' from 1996, is the place to go _ and the band recently
teamed up with English folkie Billy Bragg for ``Mermaid Avenue,'' a
collection of previously unrecorded Woody Guthrie songs.
</P>
<P>
   _Lucinda Williams. The recent ``Car Wheels on a Gravel Road'' is
getting a ton of attention, but the Louisiana-born
singer/songwriter has never put out a bad (or even mediocre) CD.
Rootsy, restless, bluesy, tough and dark, her sound and deft,
less-is-more lyrics are among the best in country _ alt or
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
