A5195 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-WELFARE-BOS &LR;      07-27 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WELFARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS WELFARE RECIPIENTS BENEFIT FROM PART-TIME JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Welfare recipients in Massachusetts are better off
financially if they work even part-time, minimum-wage jobs,
according to a study released Monday by a nonpartisan research
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the Urban Institute in Washington, D.C., said the
typical welfare family consisting of a single mother with two
children receives $825 a month in cash benefits and food stamps in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But with the state now making transitional child care subsidies
and health coverage available, by just working 20 hours a week at
$5.15 an hour, the mother can increase the family's monthly income
47 percent to $1,209.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite jobs that are generally low-wage, part-time, and with
few benefits, work does pay for welfare recipients making the
transition from public assistance into the working world,'' Greg
Acs, co-author of the study, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is among 12 states the nonpartisan research
organization has chosen to examine as part of its multi-year study
on the impact of the shifting of responsibility for social programs
from the federal government to states.
</P>
<P>
   As with the 11 other states, however, the study found that in
Massachusetts the economic benefits of working tend to be less
dramatic when a mother works more hours and at a higher salary,
largely because she can no longer take advantage of the federal
earned income tax credit, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a mother who moves into a fulltime, minimum wage
job from a part-time one would see her income jump another 20
percent to $1448 a month. But, if her hourly wage goes up to $9 an
hour, she will only see a five percent boost to $1522.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Harris, a lawyer who specializes in welfare issues for
the Massachusetts Law Reform Institute, an advocacy group, had not
seen the report, but observed: ``The state has done a lot to help
work pay. But the welfare time limits closes the door to families
trying to work their way off welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   State welfare officials, meanwhile, felt vindicated by the
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been saying that for years, that people are much better
off working,'' said Dick Powers, spokesman for the Department of
Transitional Assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
