A5196 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-27 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF IT'S THE RIGHT VERDICT, THE TIME DOESN'T MATTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The jury got it right. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors in New Braunfels, Texas, found ex-Air Force Academy Cadet
David Graham guilty of capital murder, the same verdict delivered
by Fort Worth jurors who were asked to decide the fate of Graham's
former fiance, Diane Zamora.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora's jury convicted her of capital murder in February, and
she is serving a sentence of life in prison. Judge Don Leonard
sentenced Graham to life shortly after the guilty verdict was
announced on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Capital murder carries an automatic life sentence when
prosecutors do not seek the death penalty, and they did not seek it
in the case of either Zamora or Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Zamora were found guilty of murdering 16-year-old
Adrianne Jones in December 1995. They killed Jones wantonly,
brutally and without anything resembling justification. It was a
sociopathic act committed by two teen-agers who harbored no respect
for human life or the fundamental dictates of existence in a
civilized society.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors, Zamora believed that Graham had a
sexual encounter with Jones and demanded that Graham prove his love
by killing Jones. Prosecutor Mike Parrish said during Graham's
trial that the affair never happened, which made the killing all
the more heinous and inexplicable.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfathomable: Graham and Zamora committed coldblooded
murder because Zamora ``imagined'' that Graham had cheated on her?
</P>
<P>
   Life in prison hardly seems sufficient punishment for
individuals who could be so blatantly indifferent to the life of an
innocent young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Jones and Scott Jones, Adrianne's brothers, were on
target when they addressed the court after Graham was sentenced and
described him as an animal.
</P>
<P>
   Justin said he couldn't hate an animal, but Scott glared at
Graham and said that he ``ruined so many lives, so many families.
Unlike my brother, I can hate an animal, and I hate David Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Braunfels jury deserves society's congratulations and
gratitude for fulfilling its collective responsibility to see that
justice was done. Defense attorney Dan Cogdell had reminded the
jurors at the end of his closing argument that they held justice in
their hands, and they took him at his word _ although a conviction
for capital murder was surely not what Cogdell had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing matters except the eventual verdict, of course, but some
trial watchers were wondering by midday Friday if the Graham jurors
were up to the task that had been assigned to them. This looked as
much like an open-and-shut situation as a capital murder case can
be; Cogdell didn't even put on a defense, resting his case without
calling a single witness to testify on Graham's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said he didn't need to call witnesses because
prosecutors hadn't proved their case. That statement seemed even
more preposterous than his claim that Graham had nothing to do with
the killing _ that he was nowhere near the murder scene when his
pistol was used to fire two bullets into Jones' head.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors offered up, among other evidence, the murder weapon;
a confession that Graham personally composed on a word processor;
and witnesses who testified that Zamora had told them that she and
Graham committed the crime together.
</P>
<P>
   How in the world could jurors deliberate for nearly 10 hours
before realizing that the evidence added up to a guilty verdict?
They should have convicted Graham in 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, why quibble about methods when the results are
impeccable? These jurors may have been slow, but they were
effective.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, jurors deliberated for nearly seven hours in the Zamora
trial, and they had darn near a suitcase full of confessions to go
on _ not to mention Zamora's testimony, which struck some courtroom
observers as far more laughable than plausible.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, it doesn't matter in the least how long it takes a
jury to arrive at its decision _ as long as the decision is the
right one.
</P>
<P>
   And the decision in the Graham case was definitely the right
one.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
