<HEADLINE>
CHANGES IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three major happenings, all of a different nature
and beyond White House control, are about to have a dramatic impact
on the final phase of the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   For public excitement this cannot match Powerball mania. Nor is
it Zorro.
</P>
<P>
   But the long-running tale of political thrust and counter-thrust
that is the story of President Clinton's survival in public office
is reaching a turning point. Very soon, nothing will be as we have
known it.
</P>
<P>
   The president's fortunes now turn on the closing actions of
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, the exit from the White House of
some of Clinton's best friends and a constitutional reality that
defines his office.
</P>
<P>
   The most sensational transformation will stem from Starr's rapid
move, for better or worse, into the last aspect of his Monica
Lewinksy probe. Finally he is confronting the principals, and a
report to Congress appears near.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Starr has the bad political judgment to indict the
25-year-old former White House intern for the shocking,
unforgivable crime of catching a president's eye is unclear.
Negotiations to give her and her mother immunity have suddenly been
revived. And nobody knows what Lewinsky may say on the stand.
</P>
<P>
   But by sending Clinton an unprecedented subpoena to testify
before a grand jury, Starr is forcing him into a constitutional
showdown with potentially grave consequences for the separation of
the three co-equal branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   This is a signal that Starr has no other potential witnesses and
is winding up or down, depending upon your point of view, his
unrelenting pursuit of alleged Clinton wrongdoing. After four
years, this will be a relief, no matter what evidence Starr
eventually claims to have accumulated. This distraction has
outlived its welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, both Clinton and Starr will emerge diminished. The
battle between them has become so nasty that neither can win.
Clinton's legacy has been forever tarnished. As for Starr, all he
can do is retreat to Pepperdine University in California.
</P>
<P>
   The second drama involves the loss of confidants rather than the
clash of enemies. The pending departure from the White House of
popular spokesman Mike McCurry, powerful chief of staff Erskine
Bowles and other key advisers may be more significant than it first
appears.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how able their replacements, the new aides are
essentially employment afterthoughts and can never reach a level of
political experience and presidential intimacy equal to that of
their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   It's lonely at the top and it's about to become lonelier.
</P>
<P>
   The president may come to rely on them, or may not. They may
give better or worse advice. But they are unlikely to develop the
personal relationship to successfully overcome Clinton's weaknesses
with their own wisdom as he enters his least promising presidential
period.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the third saber cutting into Clinton's power. After
this fall's congressional elections, his lame-duck status becomes
acute. And if Democrats do not increase their numbers in Congress,
his isolation could marginalize him.
</P>
<P>
   The knowledge that he can serve only two more years leaves him
without the normal presidential leverage. Voters and other
politicians will look elsewhere, toward Vice President Al Gore,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush or other figures with the future
potential of reward and retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the best that Clinton may be able to hope for is a
world in which he will be ignored and peacefully consigned in due
time to the peripheral role of other retired presidents. The
alternative scenario is Starr's vision of convincing the courts and
the Congress that Clinton deserves to be impeached now before he
can get away.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation meant to explain Starr's excesses has ranged from
his presumed frustration over an inability to prove anything
damning to a presumed fury over sweeping presidential obstruction
of justice, witness-tampering and various other felonious abuses of
power. We dummies not on the favored lists for leaking such gossip
don't know where the truth lies, if anywhere. The leakees may not
know either.
</P>
<P>
   But the tawdry saga now approaches a new era. The president is
likely to speak up at last, in response to Starr's legal end-game.
Then Starr will have to fish or cut bait in response to the
president's political end-game. Good.
</P>
</TEXT>
