<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-SHOOTINGS-MEMORIALS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    CLINTON AWARDS ARLINGTON CEMETERY BURIAL TO NON-VETERAN POLICE
OFFICER KILLED IN CAPITOL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In honor of an officer who fell defending a symbol
of democracy, President Clinton on Monday awarded a hero's burial
to Capitol Police special agent John Gibson, saying the non-veteran
will join other American heroes at Arlington Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision came as members of Congress and countless
visitors to the Capitol paid their respects Monday to Gibson and
fellow officer Jacob ``J.J.'' Chestnut, who were gunned down Friday
at their posts in the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, an Vietnam-era Air Force veteran, will also be laid to
rest in Arlington Cemetery. Both burials will be later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system worked, but at a terrible personal cost,'' House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., said Monday during a solemn and
sometimes teary tribute in the House. ``We are safe because of
their sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   The House set aside its legislative agenda Monday to honor the
work and lives of Gibson and Chestnut, casting votes only on
resolutions recognizing the two men and ensuring that they will be
remembered and that their families will be cared for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow we must live our lives knowing that this country was
a better place because of the dedication and the courage of these
two men,'' said House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, in whose
office the gunman was downed after fatally shooting Gibson, a
member of DeLay's personal security team.
</P>
<P>
   Near the door where the gunman entered the Capitol Friday, a
public memorial continued to grow Monday: a wreath DeLay; two tiny
teddy bears in red sweaters with white hearts; a child's drawing of
a U.S. flag, inscribed ``God Bless America _ Regina.''
</P>
<P>
   The flowers, some in bouquets, some a single stem, continued to
arrive as well, from anonymous well-wishers and from well-known
mourners, among them Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., and Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol that was wracked by terror and violence Friday
becomes a shrine Tuesday to the two officers as they lie in state
in the Capitol's Rotunda before and after a memorial service to be
attended by the officers' families, members of Congress and both
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, an Air Force veteran of Vietnam veteran, and Gibson
will be buried later this week at Arlington Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
