<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lopez not such an easy target anymore
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Teams are attempting fewer stolen bases against the
Braves this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know one thing,'' said catcher Javy Lopez. ''It's not
because they're afraid they're going to be thrown out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez is being hard on himself. In one season, he has gone from
one of the easiest catchers to steal on to above the National
League norm. He caught just 28 of 98 attempted steals (28.6
percent) in 1997. Through the first 105 games this season, that
rate has improved to 36.7 percent (22 of 60). The average NL
catcher this season throws out 33.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last few days have been terrible,'' said Lopez, after
teams stole three bases in his last five games. ''But I think I've
been doing a lot better than the year before last. Compared to last
year, I don't see that many people try to steal this year.
Sometimes, we go like five or six games without anybody trying to
steal a base. Most of the time when they do try to steal, the
hitters swings the bat, like a hit and run.''
</P>
<P>
   Stolen base attempts are down slightly in the NL this season,
from one attempt every 8.2 innings in 1997 to one every 10.6
innings this year. This may be partly explained by home run mania
and the state of pitching in an expansion year, prompting managers
to wait on the long ball rather attempting to create runs.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the explanation, Lopez has had a marked improvement,
coming in the same season when he's having his best season at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward to throwing more people out at second base,''
he said, ''but I've had it in my mind to improve all my numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez is carrying a rainbow-colors bruised on his left
buttock, courtesy of bullpen coach Ned Yost, who hit the reserve
catcher during batting practice Sunday. The bruise has caused such
appreciation around the clubhouse that Yost actually autographed
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's my first righty,'' said Yost, who in his eight seasons
with the club recalls previously hitting only Dwight Smith and Tony
Tarasco.
</P>
<P>
   Added starter
</P>
<P>
   The Reds firmed up their pitching plans for the series, moving
up Steve Parris to pitch Wednesday's game and giving left-hander
Rick Krivda his first start as a Red on Thursday afternoon. Parris
had been set for Thursday but was moved when after the club demoted
projected starter Scott Winchester on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Krivda was acquired from Cleveland June 16 in exchange for Eddie
Priest and had been used in relief nine times. Thursday will be his
first NL start. He started a total of 34 games for Baltimore the
previous three seasons but was waived by the Orioles during spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   Relief
</P>
<P>
   The Braves bullpen came into Monday's game with a 4.07 ERA, the
seventh highest in the league. They have also worked the fewest
innings (232-1/3) and yielded the fourth lowest batting average
(.239). Atlanta starters, who have the lowest group ERA in the
league (3.02), give up a .245 average.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro news
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves are waiting for a sign that Pedro Borbon is close
to being able assume a left-handed set-up role in Atlanta, those
hopes were not helped by the latest report from Class AAA Richmond.
Borbon, on injury rehab assignment the last several weeks, gave up
three runs in the seventh as Richmond lost to Indianapolis 4-1
Sunday. In six Richmond appearances, Borbon had given up eight hits
and six runs while striking out three in 5-2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
