<HEADLINE>
LONG-GUN BUYERS FACE BACKGROUND CHECKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Potential buyers of shotguns and rifles, take heed: if
you make your purchase Nov. 30 or later, your background will be
checked by law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't know this was coming, you're far from alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very low awareness, almost non-existent awareness, at
this time,'' said Dave LaRue, owner of Legendary Guns in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Background checks for handgun sales _ primarily to ensure that
the buyer doesn't have a criminal record _ have been conducted
under the Brady Law since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Brady Law provided for similar checks for long guns starting
five years after the original legislation passed in 1993. But that
fact hasn't been highly publicized.
</P>
<P>
   The new system will use ``instant checks,'' as opposed to the
potential five-day wait now involved in buying a handgun. But
Arizona already uses instant checks, so shooting-industry people
predict the transition will be smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come in here and with a 10- or 15-minute background
check, they're on their way, no hassle,'' said Marty Mandall, owner
of Mandall Shooting Supplies in Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McComb, a Legendary Guns customer, said that he's not
thrilled about the extended checks, but that they don't really
bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can start getting paranoid about Big Brother and he's
checking on everything,'' said McComb, a television photographer.
``But realistically, I don't think it's a big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Nov. 30 will mark a switch from a potential
five-day wait for a background check for handgun sales to a
potential three-day wait for all gun sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the possible three-day delay would kick in only if an
instant check turns up some suspicious issue that needs to be
cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   And, in fact, Arizona will see little practical change.
</P>
<P>
   The Handgun Clearance Center at the Arizona Department of Public
Safety already checks people out in minutes, said Teresa Fuentes,
head of the center. The hurry-up checks will continue when long
guns are added to the mix, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The changeover will bring some differences, however.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, her department will be called the Firearms
Clearance Center. For another, its workload will increase by 50 to
75 percent. And, for a third, it will be checking more types of
records than before.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the DPS clears buyers if they don't have a felony
conviction, aren't the target of a warrant, and haven't been
convicted of a misdemeanor involving domestic violence, Fuentes
said.
</P>
<P>
   But starting Nov. 30, the department will check for other
disqualifiers. Right now, it's adding computer files that will
allow it to check military, immigration and, where possible,
mental-health records. Some states, including Arizona, won't allow
checks of mental-health records.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to criminals, the Brady Law bars sales to people who
are under indictment or who have a dishonorable discharge from the
military, those who have renounced U.S. citizenship or are illegal
immigrants, and those with mental problems.
</P>
<P>
   It also disqualifies drug addicts, but documenting drug
addiction is difficult, Fuentes said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Arizona buyers have been subject only to
criminal-record checks because the other records weren't readily
available, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 2.5 percent of potential buyers have been
disqualified since the Brady Law checks began in Arizona in 1994,
Fuentes said.
</P>
<P>
   Before passage of Brady, the National Rifle Association _ the
major lobbying group for gun owners _ asked for the instant checks,
believing them to be less burdensome than waiting periods for gun
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the long-gun checks are in the offing, the NRA says the
new checks will be fine as long as they are carried out reasonably.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think gun owners are both optimistic and cautious,'' NRA
spokesman Jim Manown said.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA is concerned because the FBI wants to levy a $16 tax on
gun buyers for each check and to hold onto the sales records for 18
months following the sale, Manown said.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA opposes both proposals, and is backing legislation that
would ban the tax and force the FBI to destroy its records of a gun
sale immediately after the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates also have mixed feelings about the new
check on long guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support the background check on long guns,'' said Nancy
Hua, a spokeswoman for Handgun Control Inc., based in Washington,
D.C. ``However, we're not happy with the fact that the waiting
period goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Hua said Handgun Control thinks there should be a mandatory
three- to five-day waiting period for handgun sales, to guard
against angry people looking for revenge and depressed people
looking for a way out.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, though, regard the new long-gun checks with pained
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is John Weir, manager of Don's Sport Shop, 7803 E.
McDowell Road in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see it,'' Weir said. ``It's just one more thing that
government interferes in.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
