<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CANOES-ART-670(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A NEW MUSEUM, CANOES GLIDE INTO MYTHOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETERBOROUGH, Ontario _ Like other men who have dipped paddles
into dark, clear waters and felt the soulful satisfaction of
gliding through perfect silence, John Jennings has been captivated
by canoes. He has been that way since he was a boy, and he can
think of few things better than to enter the northern wilderness
with four weeks of supplies in a 16-foot canoe and simply
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 15 years, Jennings has pursued an obsessive, some
might think odd, dream that has made his treasured wilderness
outings rare. A bookish, soft-spoken college professor whose
enthusiasm for Canadian history is matched only by his passion for
the fine elegance of canoes, Jennings has devoted himself to
founding a museum dedicated to the Canadian canoe.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he feels he is also doing his bit to keep his
country together.
</P>
<P>
   Taking shape now in some old industrial buildings in this
canoe-making town in the hill country northeast of Toronto is the
Canadian Canoe Museum, a national collection of about 600 canoes
that, taken together, trace the history of Canada and paint a
picture of the rugged spirit and boundless energy needed to
establish this enormous country.
</P>
<P>
   For Jennings, the canoe and the pioneering voyageurs who
traveled in them across the North American wilds are to Canada what
the dark stallion and the solitary cowboy are to the United States.
Or at least they could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The canoe is really the closest thing Canada has to a national
symbol,'' Jennings said during a stroll through the building where
some of the canoes have been on display since last July.
</P>
<P>
   No admission fee is collected yet because the exhibits are still
too limited, he said. But the museum's staff is in the middle of a
$7 million fund-raising campaign, and opening the museum's
collection has been a way to bring people on board.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest canoe in the collection was discovered in a swamp in
Ontario and is thought to date back more than 500 years _ long
before the first Europeans arrived. The odd west coast Kootenay
canoe _ with a sturgeon-shaped nose _ is unlike those found
anywhere except in the Amur Valley of Siberia, proof that people
from Asia brought their culture with them when they crossed the
Bering Strait to North America.
</P>
<P>
   The canoe used by a Canadian man to travel from Winnipeg,
Manitoba, to the mouth of the Amazon River in South America is part
of the museum's collection. So is the ceremonial canoe that Grand
Chief Matthew Coon Come of the Cree Indians carried through the
streets of New York City to stop the construction of the James Bay
II hydroelectric project in northern Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, a professor of history at Trent University in
Peterborough, is on a crusade not just to build a museum but also
to have the canoe recognized as a romantic symbol of Canada's
founding, one that crosses the lines between French, English and
native people that so often tend to divide the country.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that, as a symbol of unity, the canoe might at first
have problems because it was French fur trappers and explorers who
adopted the native Indians' big birch bark canoes _ canot in
Quebecois French _ to reach deep into the continent while English
colonists were still huddled east of the Appalachian and Allegheny
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   But English explorers eventually followed the same watery trail
in similar canoes and what's important is that Canada needs a
symbol, Jennings said. Researching a book about the significance of
the American cowboy, he found that it was only in the late 19th
century, when worries about the crime and depredation of U.S.
cities were rampant, that the myth of the heroic, ruggedly
individualistic cowboy was written, in large part by urban writers
from the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing could easily happen with the image of the
voyageur,'' Jennings said. ``The more urban people are, the most
susceptible they are to the image of the wilderness.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   He may be on to something. The McMichael Canadian Art
Collection, which is widely known for its works by the Group of
Seven _ some of Canada's most famous artists _ is featuring a
special exhibition of 69 works connected to canoes. In some, like
Frances Anne Hopkins' ``Canoe Manned by Voyageurs Passing a
Waterfall,'' a canoe is being paddled or carried. In others, the
canoe's presence is merely implied by the artist's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had an exceptional response,'' said Linda Morita,
project leader for the exhibition, called ``In the Wild.'' She said
the show, in Kleinburg, has drawn serious art lovers as well as
people who are not necessarily interested in art but came to see
the canoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many it was a kind of emotional response,'' Ms. Morita
said. ``The canoe has a certain history and emotional attachment to
the Canadian experience.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that attachment that the makers of Upper Canada beer are
trying to tap. The advertising campaign for their new maple brown
ale uses a print of a voyageur canoe to appeal to Canadians' thirst
for a positive reflection of their own history.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are Canadian icons, an easily and highly recognizable
part of our heritage,'' said Dan Fox, marketing director of Sleeman
Breweries Ltd., which manufactures the maple beer. He said
marketing research has found that Canadians seem to have ``a
greater interest and affinity to the spirit and values of the
Canadians who helped build this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The immensity of Canada _ its vast expanses of ice and water,
its rugged peaks and huge plains _ has always pulled against the
concept of nationhood. ``Canadians don't have the mythology that
helps them understand who they are,'' former Prime Minister Kim
Campbell said at a seminar this year.
</P>
<P>
   There is the maple leaf on Canada's flag, but Jennings points
out that he saw few maple leaves in Alberta, where he grew up.
There is hockey, but with expansion most National Hockey League
teams are not in Canada and players are no longer mostly Canadians.
Not everyone loves the Royal Canadian Mounted Police, and the
beaver _ well, an orange-toothed rodent has its limitations as a
national symbol.
</P>
<P>
   But not the canoe. ``The canoe reaches deep into our history and
extends into our future as the symbol of our stewardship of the
land,'' Jennings wrote in an essay on the Canadian canoe. ``The
symbol of the canoe can do much to bring Canadians together and
remind them of their quiet passion for this land.''
</P>
<P>
   With 2.1 million Canadian paddlers and 1.3 million canoes and
kayaks lying on their sides at Canadian cottages and river camps,
this is a country that already is at home with, and entranced by,
canoes. And Jennings is not alone in using a 16-foot cedar plank
canoe to measure the Canadian character.
</P>
<P>
   A widely visited Canadian news site on the Internet is called
Canoe. The popular Canadian historian Pierre Berton once defined a
Canadian as ``somebody who knows how to make love in a canoe.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the 1940s, long before he became prime minister, a young
Pierre Elliott Trudeau wrote evocatively of a voyage into Canada's
outback.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sets a canoeing expedition apart is that it purifies you
more rapidly and inescapably than any other,'' Trudeau wrote.
``Travel a thousand miles by train and you are a brute; pedal five
hundred on a bicycle and you remain basically a bourgeois; paddle a
hundred in a canoe and you are already a child of nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Or a Canadian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
