<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-ASSESS-     07-27 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: QUESTION WITHOUT AN ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By issuing a subpoena to President Clinton to
testify before a grand jury that is investigating him for possible
federal crimes, Kenneth Starr has made urgent and concrete the
theoretical question that has hovered at the margins of the
independent counsel's 4-year-old investigation: Can a sitting
president be subject to criminal prosecution?
</P>
<P>
   Despite fervent and opposing assertions by partisans on both
sides, the answer is no more clear now than when the investigation
began, or when lawyers for President Nixon brought the question to
the Supreme Court nearly 25 years ago. That is to say: No one
knows.
</P>
<P>
   The justices never answered Nixon's question, although as a
corollary to the Watergate tapes, the court accepted briefs and
heard argument on whether impeachment was the sole means of
pursuing criminal charges against a sitting president. The court
did rule that Nixon had to turn over the incriminating White House
tapes, rejecting his claim of executive privilege. Nixon had been
named an unindicted co-conspirator by the Watergate grand jury,
whose jurisdiction he was challenging in the months before he
resigned after losing his Supreme Court battle.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Jaworski, the last Watergate special prosecutor, was candid
with the Supreme Court in acknowledging the constitutional
ambiguity of his position. ``It is an open and substantial question
whether an incumbent president is subject to indictment,'' he wrote
in his Supreme Court brief, adding: ``Resort to constitutional
interpretation, history and policy does not provide a definitive
answer to the question of whether a sitting president enjoys
absolute immunity from the ordinary processes of the criminal
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers in Jaworski's office, after researching the question,
had told him he could seek an indictment of Nixon. But the
prosecutor, who died in 1982, wrote in his memoirs that while he
believed the Supreme Court might support indicting a sitting
president for a crime such as murder, it would not uphold an
indictment for obstruction of justice, especially given that the
House of Representatives had already begun impeachment proceedings.
For that reason, he had sought only to have the president named an
unindicted co-conspirator. Nixon's lawyer, James St. Clair, argued
that even that action was a constitutional ``nullity,'' beyond the
grand jury's authority.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution itself is both elaborately explicit and
frustratingly inscrutable on the question of whether impeachment
stands alone. Article I gives the House of Representatives ``the
sole power of impeachment'' and the Senate ``the sole power to try
all impeachments,'' language that does not necessarily displace
ordinary criminal proceedings. However, Article I goes on to state
that an impeached official, after conviction by the Senate, ``shall
nevertheless be liable and subject to indictment, trial, judgment
and punishment, according to law.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Clair argued in his Supreme Court brief on Nixon's behalf
that this language demonstrated the Framers' intent that any
prosecution would follow impeachment and removal from office and
that, consequently, a president could not be prosecuted while in
office. In his rejoinder, Jaworski said the sentence only meant
that an impeached official could not raise a double jeopardy
objection to a subsequent prosecution, since the Constitution
obviously contemplated the availability of both.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Supreme Court did not decide the question, the
briefs remain as pithy, fully developed expressions of the
competing positions on impeachment versus prosecution. In addition
to the textual debate over how to interpret Article I, the lawyers
also disputed the issue on the deeper, structural ground of the
constitutional separation of powers.
</P>
<P>
   Since prosecution is an executive branch function, and since
Article II of the Constitution declares that ``the executive power
shall be vested in a President of the United States of America,''
St. Clair argued that ``it is hardly reasonable or sensible to
consider the president subject to such prosecutions.'' Jaworski
argued in turn that the country ``has evolved since 1789,'' with
expansion of the executive branch far beyond the office of the
president itself into numerous departments and agencies, so that
the classic theory of the ``unitary executive'' was not a realistic
way to frame the issue.
</P>
<P>
   And there the issue has sat, unexamined by any court, since
1974. In the current search for any possibly relevant history, some
lawyers and historians have resurrected an opinion by Chief Justice
John Marshall from 1807, sitting not in his Supreme Court function
but as a trial judge presiding over the grand jury in Richmond,
Va., that indicted Aaron Burr for treason. After Burr sought
documents from President Jefferson that he said were necessary for
his defense, the chief justice issued a subpoena to the president
on the ground that Burr, on trial for his life in a capital case,
had a constitutional right to evidence in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   The president complied by offering an edited version of the
material, which Burr accepted. Burr was acquitted of the charges
and the case never reached the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   There is ample precedent, in fact, for presidents to appear as
witnesses in criminal investigations of others. President Ford gave
testimony on videotape against a woman who tried to assassinate
him, and President Reagan objected but ultimately gave videotaped
testimony in the Iran-contra prosecution of one of his aides, Adm.
John Poindexter. Much earlier, Presidents Monroe and Grant also
provided testimony in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   But in none of these cases was the president himself the
criminal target. After more than 200 years of silence, the Supreme
Court may finally answer the question, unless somebody backs down
first _ either Starr, from a constitutional battle he might not
win, or Clinton, who could win the legal battle while losing what
may weigh heaviest in the fevered calculations now taking place,
the political war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
