<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5231 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CLINTON-LEWINSKY     07-27 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-LEWINSKY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON FACES SETBACKS IN BATTLE WITH STARR
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's face-off with independent
counsel Kenneth Starr intensified on three fronts Monday, with a
ruling requiring deputy White House counsel Bruce Lindsey to
testify before a grand jury, a surprise meeting between Starr's
office and Monica Lewinsky and deadline negotiations over whether
Clinton might be interrogated as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   In a potentially damaging setback for Clinton, a U.S. appeals
court ruled that his conversations with Lindsey, perhaps Clinton's
closest confidant, are not shielded by traditional attorney-client
privilege and are fair game for Starr's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ''A government attorney may not invoke the attorney-client
privilege in response to grand jury questions seeking information
relating to the possible commission of a federal crime,'' stated
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   As an attorney working for the White House, Lindsey's job ``is
not to defend clients against criminal charges and it is not to
protect wrongdoers from public exposure,'' the judges stated in a
two-to-one ruling that upheld a lower court's earlier decision.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey has appeared several times before the grand jury, but
reportedly has declined to respond to key questions from Starr,
asserting attorney-client privilege designed to protect the
confidentiality of discussions held between individuals and their
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   White House Counsel Charles Ruff issued a statement Monday
assailing the court ruling and saying he is considering whether to
appeal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed that the Court of Appeals has decided
that, unlike every other attorney and client in this country,
government attorneys and their clients do not enjoy the right to
have confidential communications,'' Ruff's statement read.
</P>
<P>
   ''The practical result of the court's decision is that the
president, and all other government officials, will be less likely
to receive full and frank advice about their official obligations
and duties from government attorneys,'' Ruff wrote. ''Without the
privilege, frank and candid exchange of information and advice will
be chilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision was made by U.S. Court of Appeals Judge Judith
Rogers, a Clinton appointee, and Bush appointee Judge A. Raymond
Randolph, according to the Associated Press. Judge David Tatel,
another Clinton nominee, dissented from the main part of the
decision, warning of the potential for the sort of ``chilling
effect'' alluded to by Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   On a second front, Lewinsky met for several hours on Monday with
members of Starr's office, according to the Associated Press, in
the first such meeting known to have taken place since January.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky is seeking immunity from federal prosecutors in
exchange for her testimony in Starr's investigation into
allegations that Clinton had an Oval Office affair with the former
White House intern and later coached her to lie about it under
oath.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has denied both charges.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the investigation told the Associated Press
that Starr's office reached no immunity deal with Lewinsky on
Monday and that another meeting was anticipated, somewhere outside
of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Starr last January refused to grant Lewinsky immunity in
exchange for her testimony that an affair took place. On tapes of
recorded conversations, Lewinsky reportedly talked about the
alleged affair and said Clinton urged her to deny it.
</P>
<P>
   Against the frenzied backdrop of court activity and immunity
talks, Clinton's personal lawyer, David Kendall, held negotiations
with Starr's office over whether, and under what terms, the
president might testify before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall's office issued a brief statement confirming that the
talks were underway, but offered nothing of substance beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working with the Office of Independent Counsel, as we
have in the past, to devise a way for the president to provide
information for the OIC's investigation, consistent with his
constitutional role and responsibilities'' the statement said. ``It
would not be appropriate to comment further at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of failed talks with the White House about the
prospect of Clinton coming forward and testifying voluntarily,
Starr has subpoenaed Clinton to appear before the grand jury this
week. The White House has yet to publicly respond.
</P>
<P>
   A refusal to testify could spark a constitutional crisis
centered on the question of whether the federal courts may compel a
sitting president to testify in criminal proceedings against
himself.
</P>
<P>
   A refusal could also place Clinton in a politically precarious
position. He said, when the Lewinsky allegations first surfaced in
mid-January, that questions about his relationship with her were
legitimate and that he hoped to answer those questions sooner
rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   A refusal to come forward now and do so could make his denials
ring hollow to some people, and even Clinton's fellow Democrats on
Capitol Hill have hinted in recent days that stiffing a Starr
subpoena would be a move few public figures would support.
</P>
<P>
   Another matter reportedly under discussion between Kendall and
Starr is the question of where Clinton might testify _ in the
regular grand jury room, as Starr insists, or in the White House or
Kendall's office, as Clinton would prefer.
</P>
<P>
   One possible compromise reportedly under discussion would have
Clinton testify live from the White House, transmitting his
testimony over a closed-circuit television system to the grand
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue is whether Clinton would appear before the grand
jury alone, as is customary, or with his attorney, as he would
prefer.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
