<HEADER>
A5232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-ECON-OBUCHI-675&AMP;     07-27 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-ECON-OBUCHI-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST ASIAN NATIONS NOT INSPIRED BY NEW JAPANESE LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Japanese voters are not the only people who reacted
tepidly to the election of Keizo Obuchi as the leader of Japan's
governing party. The choice of Obuchi has deflated many in the rest
of Asia, who were hoping that a forceful new leader would step up
to recharge Japan's weak economy and repair its faltering financial
system.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their extensive trade, foreign investment and credit
links with Japan, most Asian countries are effectively hostage to
Japanese economic fortunes. As Japan has slid into a recession, it
has dragged down resilient Asian economies like those of Taiwan,
Hong Kong and Singapore, and deepened the pain for weaker economies
like South Korea's, Thailand's and Indonesia's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of Asia is looking for, and demanding that Japan be the
locomotive to pull it out of this slump,'' William Overholt, head
of research at BankBoston in Singapore, said in assessing the
selection Friday of Obuchi, who will likely become the next prime
minister of Japan. ``The region was really hanging on this
election, and people were hoping for a dynamic prime minister.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks across Asia declined sharply Monday, as investors
expressed pessimism that a government led by Obuchi, who has been
foreign minister, would perform the radical surgery that economists
say is needed to revive the Japanese economy. In Tokyo, the
benchmark Nikkei index of 225 issues dropped 2.5 percent, while the
Hong Kong market slipped 3.3 percent. The dollar strengthened to
141.95 yen in Asia and rose further to 142.41 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The gloomy reaction came despite Obuchi's assurances in a
meeting over the weekend with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
that he would move quickly to revive Japan's economy. ``I can and
will act promptly,'' U.S. officials quoted Obuchi as telling
Albright, who was in Manila to attend a meeting of foreign
ministers from Asian and Pacific nations.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi, 61, is expected to seek about $42 billion in tax cuts
and $70 billion in additional public spending to stimulate consumer
demand. But he has offered few proposals about how to reform the
Japanese banking system, which is staggering under $600 billion in
troubled debt. Until he does, analysts said, economies like
Thailand's and Hong Kong's, which depend heavily on Japan for
loans, will continue to suffer, as Japanese banks curtail their
lending.
</P>
<P>
   As leader of the governing Liberal Democratic Party, Obuchi is
all but certain to be elected prime minister this week. Analysts
said that one measure of his determination to confront Japan's
problems will be his choice of finance minister. Monday,
speculation centered on Kiichi Miyazawa, a 78-year-old party elder
and former prime minister, though Japanese newspapers said he was
also considering two other officials: Seiroku Kajiyama and Koiichi
Kato.
</P>
<P>
   Kajiyama, who challenged Obuchi in the race for the party
presidency, would offer some hope to the markets, according to a
few analysts, because he expressed a willingness to shut down
troubled banks. But other experts said that no finance minister, or
even prime minister, could rise above a system that prizes
consensus and prefers incremental change to upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is no radical change or speeding up of the reforms in
Japan, I'm afraid it will delay the recovery of the rest of the
region,'' said Chia Yew Boon, research director at Santander
Investment Securities in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Chia said Japan's economic problems were hurting other Asian
markets in three ways. First, the weak yen makes Japanese products
cheaper than those of neighboring countries, further depressing
their already poor exports. Second, the troubles in Japan's
financial system force banks to call in loans to other Asian
countries, damaging businesses in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Third, and potentially most destabilizing, the collapse of the
Japanese economic model is eroding confidence in other Asian
countries, like South Korea and Malaysia, which have imitated Japan
by creating a handful of large, national conglomerates with close
ties to banks and government agencies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Friday, Moody's Investors Service lowered its rating on
Malaysian government debt, citing ``the rapid deterioration in
Malaysia's economy this year and the expected effects on the
banking sector and government finance.'' The downgrading has forced
the Malaysian government to postpone a $2 billion bond issue
planned for later in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's troubles affect Asian countries in different ways.
Malaysia and Indonesia, for example, export huge quantities of raw
material like timber to Japan. In 1997, such exports accounted for
11.5 percent of Malaysia's gross domestic product and 6.8 percent
of Indonesia's, according to Santander. As Japan's housing market
has stalled and demand for timber has declined, so have Malaysian
and Indonesian exports.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks have been prodigious lenders to Asian countries _
both to companies and governments. Hong Kong-based companies owe
$40.7 billion to Japanese banks, an amount equivalent to 23 percent
of the territory's gross domestic product. The Indonesian
government owes $22.8 billion, or 10.6 percent of its annual
output. Now, the spigot has been turned off _ to the chagrin of
property developers in Hong Kong and Cabinet ministers in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   For Asians, the most alarming thing about Japan's travails is
the possibility that the cure could be worse than the disease. In
order for Tokyo to reform the banking system, analysts said it must
first acknowledge that some of the biggest Japanese banks are
insolvent, and then close them. The outgoing prime minister,
Ryutaro Hashimoto, took the first steps by authorizing the
development of a bridge-bank program to protect depositors in
smaller banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one baby step in cleaning up the financial
system,'' said Ronald Bevacqua, a Merrill Lynch economist in Tokyo,
``I have no question that Obuchi will take the first step. But will
he take the following steps?''
</P>
<P>
   Bevacqua said Obuchi had as good a chance of success as any
Japanese politician _ partly because he has many friends in his
party and few enemies outside it. That may enable him to steer a
painful financial package through the Parliament more effectively
than a more confrontational leader.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other Asian nations, they can really only be
bystanders. Japan's economy is too big for its neighbors to export
around and too powerful for them to control. They are in the
frustrating position of hoping that Obuchi can deliver on his
campaign promises _ and then go well beyond them.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Margolis, a regional strategist with Merrill Lynch in
Hong Kong, said, ``Even if the Japanese locomotive doesn't come out
of the siding and needs a radical repair job, it's probably better
to get on with that than deal with years of zero growth and
consumer demand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
