<HEADER>
A5234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN28-COX     07-27 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time for Barnes to set himself apart
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let me tell you something.
</P>
<P>
   You're going to hear that a lot in the next four months. He
enunciates the words more carefully these days _ in court or at the
Capitol the phrase used to roll off his lips as one word,
``lemmetellyasumpthin'' - but Roy Barnes still uses the phrase as
liberally as Newt Gingrich says ``frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   That phrase is also a conversational tip-off to the strengths
and weaknesses which the Democratic nominee-in-suspension _ a
working title for his status until the runoff makes the nomination
official _ brings to the governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Barnes can tell you something, about hardware
stores, suburban growth, Georgia law and the General Assembly. He
is the only lawyer-legislator of his generation to invite
comparison with former Rep. Denmark Groover, who was legendary for
his command of the state code. Barnes has been known to leave a
morning session of the legislature and win a multi-million-dollar
court judgment in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, sometimes he'll tell you something and wish
he hadn't, as was the case when he wisecracked to reporters in the
closing days of the primary campaign that his wife, Marie, was
pregnant. Lewis Massey's wife, Amy, who is pregnant, took offense
at the inference her condition was connected to her husband being
the race and demanded an apology.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles created by Barnes' quick tongue have been mostly
minor distractions, but even those can be deadly in a race as
tightly paced as this one is going to be.
</P>
<P>
   The last few days have been heady ones for the Barnes campaign,
with Massey's suspension of his campaign and Guy Millner's
unexpected problems with Mike Bowers. Those developments create the
illusion of a lead. In fact, Barnes has to hurry to make up the gap
between himself and Millner, whom the Democrat coyly declined over
the weekend to designate as his opponent pending the results of the
recount.
</P>
<P>
   For all the reputation he enjoys in government and legal
circles, Barnes is a little like a famed Broadway actor taking a
crack at an action movie. He has to appeal to a much wider
audience, within a fraction of the attention span to which he's
accustomed. Above all, he can't afford the mistake of thinking that
his audience knows him already.
</P>
<P>
   The millions Barnes laid out on early television in the primary
race could be crucial to his chances in the general election, if
that early exposure helped define Barnes to new voters before
Millner takes a shot at it.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Millner referred to him as ``lawyer Barnes'' in
his only primary debate than Barnes began referring to Millner as
``defendant Millner.'' He can give as good as he gets in verbal
volleys, but Barnes now faces an opponent who can spend what it
takes to paint him in a negative light from now until November.
Compared to what he faces in the general election, Massey's
negative ads were only a warm-up.
</P>
<P>
   With his folksy appeal, suburban background and big-city
finesse, Barnes has the potential to create a sort of Georgia
Party, one that might briefly unite disaffected Bowers voters,
Democratic core groups and independents looking for a candidate
with roots in the state and a proven track record.
</P>
<P>
   A former colleague of Barnes pinpointed the weakness in this
strategy: ``Barnes is very Georgia,'' he said, ``but Georgia
isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   To win this race, in other words, Barnes has to stretch himself
past the associations built up over a career, and rely on more than
a reputation that stretches back to law school at UGA. And he
doesn't have much time to do it.
</P>
<P>
   AJC political editor Tom Baxter provides opinion, analysis and
commentary in his column.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
