<SLUG> BC-YUGO-KOSOVO-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS ADVANCE IN KOSOVO, IMPERILING DIPLOMATIC EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE O'CONNOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Yugoslav government forces continued
their intensive attacks against separatist guerrillas across Kosovo
province on Monday, officials said. The soldiers have retaken
stretches of major roads that were held by the rebels, the
officials added, and are beginning to confine the rebels to two
areas of the province.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats here said the attacks might have dealt the
ethnic Albanian rebels their worst setback of the war, but they
acknowledged that information from the field was skimpy.
</P>
<P>
   The government attacks threaten Western efforts to stop the war
through negotiations, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of tens of thousands of civilians who live in the areas
under attack is unknown. Relief agencies say they cannot determine
how badly those people may need food and medical supplies because
aid workers are being kept away by the fighting and by government
checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   The handful of foreign diplomats who have been allowed to visit
the combat zones report that the government appears to be trying to
clear rebel forces from major roads. Whether the government forces
will continue the fighting in the countryside if they regain
control of the roads is impossible to predict, the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Government press officials, eager to demonstrate a successful
military action, allowed a convoy of journalists to drive from
Pristina, the provincial capital, to Pec late Monday, but the
convoy came under sniper fire in rebel territory.
</P>
<P>
   The government offensive comes as Western diplomats were turning
a bit less pessimistic about their chances of persuading ethnic
Albanian leaders and the Serbs to negotiate. Albanians are about 90
percent of the population of Kosovo, and some of their political
leaders and the rebels are demanding independence from Serbia,
which forms the major part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and European diplomats who have been trying to induce
ethnic Albanian leaders to join in forming a negotiating team said
the Serbian offensive might be angering the Albanians to the point
that they will not negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have yet to build a strong enough negotiating base that it
can withstand this kind of blast,'' a Western diplomat said.
``Violence never helps real negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   One diplomat said that if the guerrillas, who call themselves
the Kosovo Liberation Army, are badly hurt, they might refuse to
negotiate until they regained some losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a problem ending this war if one side or the other
feels too strong or too weak,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials said the second stage of the government
offensive began in earnest Monday as troops moved to force the
rebels into two areas in the center of the country.
</P>
<P>
   In a third area, near Junik on the Albanian border, about 1,500
rebels were surrounded, the officials said, adding that their
surrender will be demanded. But for the two other, much larger
groups of rebels, the strategy is to contain them, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have the roads and they will be concentrated in
pockets we can control,'' one government official said, adding that
the burden of caring for thousands of civilians would make it
difficult for the guerrillas to mount a significant counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   The officials are close to the Yugoslav military and spoke on
the condition that they not be identified by name.
</P>
<P>
   Relief workers estimate that as many as 90,000 people have fled
their homes and are now living in areas under rebel control. Some
of the areas are isolated and were poor even before the refugees
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The relief workers worry about sanitary conditions and the
availability of food, water and medicine for refugees. In one area,
very near where government troops are now attacking, 10,000 to
15,000 ethnic Albanians have arrived after fleeing fighting nine
days ago, the aid workers said, and diplomats expressed concern
that many of the refugees would join the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   U.S., European and Russian diplomats and military experts were
to be allowed to monitor the conflict, starting July 1. But most
monitors have not arrived, and three U.S. military cargo planes
carrying armored cars and radios for the monitors were first
allowed to land in Yugoslavia on Monday, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel forces have grown quickly and have established their
own authority in about one-third of the country, diplomats say. But
foreign military analysts and ethnic Albanian leaders say the
rebels are still poorly armed and badly organized. With disputes
and competing strategies among its leaders, the Kosovo Liberation
Army may take some time to regroup from the Serbian attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But as government troops move to retake roads and clear broad
areas of land on either side to protect them, they now have
hundreds of square miles to guard.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, diplomats say, the government was having trouble
paying the costs of military operations well before this offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gains from this offensive could ebb away because of
something as simple as not having enough money to buy fuel to keep
all the soldiers and tanks deployed,'' one Western diplomat said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
