<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5239 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-SLAIN-BOS &LR;      07-27 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SLAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID TEARS, PRAISE, ROTUNDA PREPARED FOR SLAIN POLICEMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid black bunting and heavy hearts, Congress
resumed the nation's business Monday, as thousands of men and women
who work in the US Capitol mourned two police officers who died
protecting the marble monument.
</P>
<P>
   Tears flowed from a dank loading dock to a crowded cafeteria
counter to the chandeliered corridors of power. ``We lost two
members of our family,'' said Kaye Willis, a Senate doorkeeper,
after drying her eyes. ``And all I can see is their smiling
faces.''
</P>
<P>
   As workers prepared for the slain officers to lie in state
Tuesday in the historic Rotunda, lawmakers set aside partisan
bickering to pay tribute to Capitol Police Detective John M.
Gibson, 42, and Private First Class Jacob J. ``J.J.'' Chestnut, 58.
</P>
<P>
   The officers died Friday in a bloody gun battle with Russell E.
Weston Jr., an unemployed drifter who invaded the Capitol, firing
until he was critically wounded in the office of Representative Tom
DeLay of Texas, the House majority whip.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate, in their first official sessions since the
tragedy, immediately passed resolutions praising the officers and
authorizing memorial trust funds for their wives and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They died saving lives,'' said DeLay, whose office door was
draped in black bunting and guarded by officers with badges banded
in black ribbon. ``They died doing their duty.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay called Gibson, a Waltham, Mass. native who served on his
personal security team, his ``guardian angel.''
</P>
<P>
   The first officers slain in defense of the Capitol, Gibson and
Chestnut were little known beyond their immediate circles of
friends, family and co-workers. But like the unknown soldiers of
war, they are expected to represent all law enforcement officers
who have been killed in the line of duty when they are honored
today in a memorial service led by President Clinton and
congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It will mark the first time that two coffins have lain in state
at the same time in the Rotunda. To date, only 24 national leaders
and heroes have received the honor in the Rotunda, including
Presidents Abraham Lincoln and John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fitting that these two brave men will lie in state in
the Capitol building where they gave their lives,'' said Senator
Edward M. Kennedy, the late president's brother.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Kennedy placed two dozen yellow roses on a floral
tribute to the officers that sprawls up the marble steps on the
east side of the Capitol building. With each bouquet, he left a
card that offered ``deepest condolences, as we mourn the loss of a
profile in courage.''
</P>
<P>
   The cards were signed: ``The Kennedy family.''
</P>
<P>
   The memory of both officers, who will be buried at Arlington
National Cemetery after funerals later this week, was alive
throughout the Capitol. Their ready smiles were familiar to many:
politicians and pages, tour guides and maintenance workers,
congressional aides and fellow officers.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, a 20-year Air Force veteran who had served 18 years as
a Capitol Police officer, was recalled for maintaining his genial
nature, even as he was demanding that House staffers run through
the metal detector every box of fried chicken they brought into the
Capitol to make sure they contained no contraband.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, who also served 18 years on the Capitol Police force,
was known for seizing the attention of those around him with a
simple glance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you remember John, remember that grin that could melt
your heart or tell you that you had done wrong with just one
look,'' said DeLay, quoting an aide, Mary Ellen Wright, who saw
Gibson shot to death as he exchanged gunfire with Weston at the
threshold of DeLay's office. ``When you remember John, remember
that twinkle in his eye...a twinkle of compassion and love.''
</P>
<P>
   Another DeLay aide described Gibson, a deeply religious man who
graduated from St. Mary of the Annunciation High School in
Cambridge, Mass. in 1974, as his ``vision of what a Catholic priest
would be like if he was allowed to marry and raise a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the joint House and Senate resolution, which passed both
chambers on unanimous votes, plaques commemorating each officer
will be placed near the spots where they died. Congress also will
pay for their funerals and give each of their families a sum equal
to one year's pay.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Senate spent much of the day debating a federal
credit union bill, the House postponed all other activities as the
days dwindle to the summer recess, which begins for the Senate on
Friday and the House on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   However, the tragedy prompted lawmakers from both chambers to
discuss reviving a plan to build a visitors center outside the
Capitol that would limit access to the building and improve
security.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, security appeared tighter in the tragedy's aftermath,
and many officers who rarely wore their optional bullet-resistant
vests before the shooting wore them Monday. And the crush of
tourists continued at its usual pace of 18,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   As they stood near the spot where the shootings occurred, Ann
Easter, of Clayton, N.Y., said she had worried about how her
8-year-old son, Chris, would react to visiting the scene of the
crime. But she said he was assured by Gibson's and Chestnut's
heroism. And he agreed. ``I feel safe and secure,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5240 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-POPU     07-27 1948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-POPULAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO ARE NETANYAHU'S STAUNCH SUPPORTERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For purchase information _ the rates are not prohibitive --
contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By EHUD SPRINZAK  
 c.1998 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Foreign observers have always had trouble understanding Israel's
complex politics and following the twists and turns of the Jewish
state's foreign policy. But nothing in Israeli political history
has raised eyebrows like the ascendancy of Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is still popular despite his razor-thin margin of
victory over Shimon Peres, in the '96 elections _ and, since then,
his repeated diplomatic blunders and derailment of a peace process
that is overwhelmingly supported by Israelis _ nearly 60 percent,
according to recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed Netanyahu's continued appeal is the great paradox of
Israeli politics today.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the Netanyahu enigma is a new configuration of
domestic forces that has allowed him to rule the country
comfortably and commit foreign-policy mistakes with electoral
impunity.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu relies today on a conservative alliance comprising
three major forces: Israel's nationalist right, its radical right
and its soft right.
</P>
<P>
   The first two groups have long been part of Israel's political
landscape. What is new is the soft right, an odd melange of
ultra-Orthodox Jews and secular immigrants from the former Soviet
Union, whose newfound influence lets Netanyahu defy political
gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1977, when the Labor Party lost an election for the first
time ever to the Likud Party, Israel's political map has been split
into two large and roughly equal ideological camps polarized over
the future of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   While Labor, under Yitzhak Rabin and Peres, advocated moderation
and territorial compromise, the Likud of Menachem Begin and Yitzhak
Shamir pursued a hard-line agenda, urging the settlement and
eventual annexation of the occupied territories. In the center has
been a smaller ultra-Orthodox camp that cares less about the
territories or the Palestinians than about government largesse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Rabin's appeal as a security-minded pragmatist led
Labor back to power. This made possible the Oslo accords with the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) and a formal peace treaty
with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's right was galvanized by the Six Day War of 1967, in
which Israel took the West Bank and East Jerusalem from Jordan, the
Gaza Strip and the Sinai from Egypt, and the Golan Heights from
Syria. Since then, the Israeli right has been composed of two major
segments: the secular nationalist right, embodied in the Likud of
Begin and Shamir, and the radical right, spearheaded by settlers of
the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
   The radical right is far more militant than the Likud and has a
penchant for extra-parliamentary politics and extralegal action,
including illegal settlement-building and violence.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the ultra-Orthodox, who do not serve in the
Israeli army, remain disinterested in the national issues of war,
peace, the territories and the Palestinians. Convinced that all
these ``minor'' problems will be resolved in the messianic era, the
ultra-Orthodox have focused exclusively on the welfare of their
constituents and the prosperity of their yeshivas, or religious
seminaries.
</P>
<P>
   By playing a shrewd game of hard-to-get with both Labor and
Likud, the ultra-Orthodox are experts at pushing through
legislation enshrining their monopoly over religious affairs and
obtaining large state subsidies for their communities and yeshivas.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli politics has, however, quietly undergone a great shift.
As highlighted by the 1996 elections, the ultra-Orthodox camp has
moved decisively rightward and now offers virtually automatic,
monolithic support for the Likud Party's prime ministerial
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The ultra-Orthodox shift to the right has been neither
ideological nor theological. The sages, as ever, see Jewish
settlements in the West Bank as meaningless. They address the
question of whether to hold on to the territories only in terms of
``pikuakh nefesh,'' the principle in Jewish law that saving lives
is one's paramount obligation, and thus, in fact, may be willing to
back a territorial compromise that would avert bloodshed. The
movement of the ultra-Orthodox toward the nationalist right and the
radical right has been primarily emotional, based on a mutual
animosity toward the Arabs and the godless Israeli left.
</P>
<P>
   As for the new soft right, their stock in trade is intense
mistrust of and hostility toward Arabs and _ thought to be just as
bad _ their secularized Jewish ``collaborators'' on the Israeli
left. The most aggressive element within the soft right is its
political activists, hundreds of young men, in their 20s and 30s,
who support Netanyahu with unbridled enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1977, the year the Likud first won power, the
ultra-Orthodox ranks have grown dramatically with students exempted
from service in the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) because they wish
to devote their lives to the study of Jewish law. But the higher
seminary enrollment produced many marginal students who were
ill-prepared for rigorous studies.
</P>
<P>
   These restless and energetic young men were astutely targeted by
the followers of the late Rabbi Meir Kahane, an extremist from
Brooklyn who fomented anti-Arab violence. Many of these marginal
students were attracted to the quasi-fascist Kahanist subculture of
violence ``in the name of God'' and aggressive radical-right
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Another segment of Israeli ultra-Orthodoxy _ Habad, the Hasidic
followers of the late Rabbi Menachem Mendel Schneerson of New York
_ have long been close to the Israeli right. Since Israel took the
West Bank in 1967, Habad's revered spiritual leader repeatedly
insisted on the holiness of the entire land of Israel, including
the newly won territories.
</P>
<P>
   For years, however, Habad stressed its nonpartisan educational
mission. But of late, the intensity of Israel's struggle over the
territories dragged the movement into politics, with a marked and
growing right-wing bias. In 1996, Habad money poured into
Netanyahu's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992-96 Labor government, with what appeared to be an
anti-religious political and legislative agenda, was enough to
unite the soft right. So was a forceful radical-right campaign
against the Oslo peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   Shrewdly focusing on the ``unholy alliance'' between Rabin,
Peres and Israeli Arabs _ the alleged ``secret partners'' of
``arch-terrorist'' Yasir Arafat and the PLO _ the Israeli radical
right further succeeded in mobilizing the soft right. Moreover, a
wave of suicide terrorism by the Islamists of Hamas had a
devastating effect on the Israeli psyche, cementing this emotional
alliance and paving the way for Netanyahu's victory.
</P>
<P>
   But without the overwhelming support of Jews from the former
Soviet Union who have immigrated to Israel since 1990, Netanyahu
would never have been elected. Making up more than 10 percent of
the Israeli electorate, Russian Jews have become a major factor in
the nation's politics, and 65 percent of them voted for Netanyahu
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that most Russian Israelis cannot tolerate the
rhetoric of the left because of their painful memories of the
Soviet Union. Having been exposed to intense anti-Semitism, many of
these insecure immigrants share the widespread ultra-Orthodox
distrust of Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   While the Russians, unlike the ultra-Orthodox, do not have an
echelon of young activists who dictate their political agenda, they
are nourished by several conservative daily newspapers printed in
their native language. This right-leaning Russian press is, in
fact, the unifying element of a highly diverse group.
</P>
<P>
   However, with their secularism, heterogeneity and large number
of countries of origin, the Jews from the former Soviet Union are
the softest part of the soft right. Russian electoral behavior can
be quite pragmatic. While their rhetoric remains conservative, the
Russians are in nobody's pocket. Netanyahu will have to work hard
to keep their loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Grateful to the soft right for its votes, Netanyahu has been
quick to recognize the price of its continued support. A superb
communicator, Netanyahu knows that this emotional constituency is
enamored of chauvinist rhetoric and attacks on Arab terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   When a crisis with the Palestinians, Hizballah, the Clinton
administration or alleged ``Arab sympathizers'' anywhere erupts, a
belligerent Netanyahu rushes for the cameras. The astounding
success of this media strategy was evident after the Mossad, the
Israeli security service, bungled an assassination attempt last
year on a Hamas leader in Amman, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Under fire from the Labor Party, the United States and a livid
King Hussein of Jordan, Netanyahu told the soft right exactly what
they most wished to hear: that, regardless of political risk, he
would continue to hunt terrorists wherever they might be and that
Israelis' security would remain his sole consideration.
</P>
<P>
   On another occasion, in a meeting with an elderly Sephardic
kabbalistic rabbi, Netanyahu pandered again to soft-right
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Not realizing that he could be heard by reporters, the prime
minister whispered that Israeli leftists had forgotten how to be
Jews and could not be entrusted with the nation's security because
they are prepared to accept Israeli Arabs as partners in
government.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the vocal departures of Binyamin Ze'ev Begin _ the
son of Menachem Begin, the Likud's founder _ and others from
Netanyahu's cabinet undermined his authority among members of his
own party.
</P>
<P>
   But with the backing of the soft right, who either disregard his
critics outright or see them merely as ``in-fighters,'' Netanyahu
is able to maintain solid public support and convince his
detractors that he is still the best game around. In an age of
television and virtual politics, the soft right is a great asset
for a leader of Netanyahu's style.
</P>
<P>
   And, to be sure, the ultra-Orthodox and the Russians dislike the
Arabs and distrust the secular left, but they are not prepared to
enter into a bloody confrontation with the Palestinians or Syrians.
Unlike the Israeli right's hard core, which is ready to fight for
the land of Israel and to accept the concomitant sacrifices, most
Israelis, including the Russian immigrants, are opposed to spilling
blood to keep the West Bank. Ultra-Orthodox and Russian families of
soldiers are especially likely to resent any government that leads
the nation into a costly military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, by making it known to Netanyahu that a continued
deterioration in the peace process could cause them to switch
allegiances, the soft right may have its finest hour.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ehud Sprinzak, a professor of political science at the Hebrew
University of Jerusalem, is the author of ``The Ascendance of
Israel's Radical Right.'' He is currently a senior fellow at the
U.S. Institute of Peace.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
