<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5243 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMINE-EXPERT-SLAIN-N     07-27 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMINE-EXPERT-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLL OF U.N.'S CIVILIAN WORKERS OVERTAKES MILITARY DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ An expert in famine relief with more than 25
years' experience in Africa was killed Thursday in Burundi, the
latest victim in series of violent deaths among U.N. officials.
</P>
<P>
   After the killing of three unarmed military observers and their
translator in Tajikistan this month, the United Nations said that
more civilians than soldiers had been killed this year in missions
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The killing in Bujumbura of the aid expert, Renato Ricciardi, an
Italian who was working for the World Food Program, raises the toll
in just that organization to six this year. Ricciardi was ambushed,
robbed and shot in his house.
</P>
<P>
   The team in Tajikistan _ Jourajon Mahramov of Tajikistan, Adolfo
Sharpegue of Uruguay, Ryszard Szewczyk of Poland and Akino Yukata
of Japan _ were on patrol in a marked U.N. vehicle when they were
``ambushed and ruthlessly executed,'' a U.N. statement said last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary General Kofi Annan called it ``an act of coldblooded
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   The deaths in Tajikistan followed the kidnappings and killings
this month of two Afghans who were working for U.N. agencies in
Jalalabad, Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jan. 1, 17 civilians have died in U.N. service, and 13
soldiers have died in military peacekeeping operations. Last year
the toll was 44 on-duty soldiers and 17 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Nine civilians killed this year died in airplane or helicopter
crashes, including the secretary general's envoy in Angola, Alioune
Blondin Beye, who died in a still unexplained plane crash in the
Ivory Coast this month. The other eight were killed or died in what
appeared to be deliberate attacks, the United Nations said.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials and independent aid agencies are increasingly
concerned about the perils of working in civil conflicts, where
outsiders are often deliberately made a focus. Officials say the
respect traditionally shown for international monitors or aid
workers has all but disappeared in many areas, where violent
criminals also attack or kidnap people in remote posts.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said Monday that Annan had requested a report on
dangers to aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about safety contribute to a reluctance to accept
assignments, even on short-term contracts, for U.N. work where law
and order have broken down.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Emergency Relief Coordinator Sergio Viera de Mello said in
an interview Monday that attacks on relief workers were ``becoming
almost routine.'' He said that was why the United Nations was
insisting that such violence be considered war crimes under the
proposed International Criminal Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a convention for peacekeeping personnel,'' de Mello
said. ``But nowhere are humanitarian staff given any sort of
international protection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5247 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-MILITARY-2NDTAK     07-27 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MILITARY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BEIJING: running production. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's a push to separate the military buyers from the
sellers,'' said a Western expert in China's military, based in Hong
Kong. ``The domestic military manufacturers are extremely poor at
delivering product on time. The idea is to make them more
efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Realigning the core businesses among China's 15,000 companies
owned or controlled by the military will also inevitably lead to
deep change involving some of the most lucrative and powerful
positions in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang has said repeatedly that he wants to wean the military off
its secondary income from these companies, and to rely solely on
money from the central government.
</P>
<P>
   Cheung, who works for Kroll, estimates that more than 95 percent
of all Chinese military enterprises are small and medium-sized
companies. It may not be difficult to sell or transfer the bulk of
these companies into civilian hands.
</P>
<P>
   A more critical question is what happens to the 500 to 1,000
large enterprises that generate about three-quarters of the untold
billions of dollars earned by military-owned or controlled
businesses, many of which are being consolidated into
conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   The largest among them, like China Poly Group, Xinxing Group and
Carrie Enterprises, are already international corporations with
offices around the world, including in the United States. Military
leaders will likely be more reluctant to let go of these jewels
unless they are given a fair price.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Pollack, an expert in China's military at Rand Corp.,
noted that official news accounts of Jiang's announcement last week
were riddled with ambiguities about the scope of the order to
separate military from business operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This warrants some skepticism on the parameters of what Jiang
is undertaking,'' said Pollack. ``Though I think even a few actions
here to curtail some of the friskier business units would resonate
with a cynical public.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the key factors in the transformation of the military and
defense-related industries is the reorganization of the Commission
for Science, Technology and Industry for National Defense, also
known as COSTIND.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, with Deng at the helm of China's military, the
commission was run like a personal fiefdom of the family of Marshal
Nie Rongzhen, a veteran of the Long March, the defining experience
for elder leaders of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Only in 1994, as Jiang began trying to oppose the widespread
nepotism in the defense industry, was Nie's daughter, Nie Li,
forced to retire from the board of the commission. Yet her husband,
Gen. Ding Henggao, remained in charge of the commission until
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ding was best known outside China for championing the
development of long-range ballistic missiles and the Long March
series of satellite launching systems. Ding was replaced by another
military leader, Lt. Gen. Cao Gangchuan, a deputy chief of staff in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this year, as the commission was reformed, a civilian was
placed in charge: Liu Jibin, a former vice minister of finance with
experience in aeronautics.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the commission technically answered both to the
State Council, China's Cabinet, and to the Communist Party's
Central Military Commission, probably the single most powerful
organization in China's vast political apparatus. The military
commission often overruled or meddled with decisions by the State
Council, causing innumerable delays.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new reforms, the Commission for Science, Technology
and Industry for National Defense is expected to exercise direct
control over key groups a civilian-run defense industry. That
includes China Aerospace Corp., Aviation Industries Corp., China
North Industries Corp., China National Nuclear Corp. and China
State Shipbuilding Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0317 </DOCNO>
