<HEADER>
A5255 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMY-FRATERNIZE-475&AMP;A     07-27 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-FRATERNIZE-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY EXPECTED TO ADOPT NEW RULES ON FRATERNIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Department of Defense plans to order the Army
to adopt strict new prohibitions on dating, sexual intimacy and
other close relationships between officers and enlisted personnel,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules would make the Army's fraternization policy
consistent with those already in effect in the Air Force, the Navy
and the Marine Corps. Those services bar virtually all personal
relationships between officers and enlisted personnel, from that of
gambling buddy to that of business associate. The Army currently
allows them, so long as they do not involve people within the same
company or chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes have emerged from one of two Pentagon
reviews of the military's regulation of personal behavior and
morality. And like the other review, of the prosecution of
adultery, the review of fraternization has had officials struggling
to balance the demands of military discipline with the mores of the
larger society.
</P>
<P>
   Fraternization is a military crime punishable by a maximum of
two years in prison, and a dishonorable discharge for enlisted
personnel and dismissal for officers. While the Army defines
fraternization differently from the other services, the maximum
penalty is the same in all. As a practical matter, though,
fraternization alone is rarely prosecuted; instead, most such cases
are handled with administrative punishment like a letter of
reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen said last Monday that he wanted
to establish a clearer, ``more balanced'' approach to both adultery
and fraternization. Cohen, who ordered the Pentagon reviews in June
1997 in the wake of a series of scandals involving sexual conduct,
said he hoped to make a decision on new rules for adultery and
fraternization soon.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed changes have encountered opposition within the
military, and the resistance could still scuttle the draft
recommendations made by officials who have been conducting the
reviews for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps has publicly objected to the proposed changes
on adultery, which would treat that offense less severely. And the
Army has repeatedly objected to having to change its rules on
fraternization, although its dissenting has been done behind the
scenes, once in a meeting late last month with Cohen and the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said the
new rules were unnecessary. The service has not had significant
problems with fraternization, they said, and should not be required
to change solely for the sake of having a tougher policy consistent
with the other services.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also said the proposed change could cause havoc
among the scores of officer-enlisted couples already involved in
relationships or even married.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have works,'' one Army officer said. ``And it's worked
for decades.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The military has long defined fraternization as any improper
relationship between superior and subordinate. While the word
itself connotes relationships between men, the growth in the number
of women in the military, who now account for nearly 14 percent of
the nation's 1.4 million troops, means that fraternization these
days most often involves liaisons between the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it is regarded as a grave disruption of morale and
discipline, and all the services warn officers to avoid even the
perception of it.
</P>
<P>
   Their rules vary, however, as to what constitutes a violation.
Only the Army allows officers to have personal relationships with
at least some enlisted personnel. Only the Navy prohibits all
relationships between senior enlisted and junior enlisted
personnel. But what is more, enforcement is uneven, with the Air
Force considered most likely to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   These differences have caused confusion, especially since many
bases in the United States and overseas have units from more than
one service. Even where confusion is absent, there is a perception
of inequitable handling.
</P>
<P>
   In one case reviewed by the Pentagon officials who have proposed
the changes, an Air Force lieutenant in San Antonio recently
received an official admonishment and a career-threatening
performance evaluation because she had dated an Army sergeant for
several months, even though they served at different bases, both in
Texas. Under the Army's rules, the sergeant had committed no
violation and so, the officials said, received no punishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
