<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5257 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-SHOOTINGS-HNS     07-27 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-SHOOTINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAB DRIVER DISPUTE LEAVES 1 DEAD, 2 HURT AT AIRPORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A cab driver went on a shooting spree Monday at
Dallas-Fort Worth Airport, killing a fellow driver and wounding two
others as they sat in a sweltering metal shed waiting to be
dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman was identified as 35-year-old Bile Abdi Farah. He
surrendered to airport police under an overpass near the scene of
the shootings. Airport spokesman Joe Dealey Jr. said Farah is a
legal immigrant from Somalia, and authorities believe the victims
also are Somalian.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Issa, 25, was taken by helicopter to nearby Harris
Methodist HEB Hospital, where he was pronounced dead. Abdalla Mead,
31, was shot in the arm and was listed in good condition at
Parkland Hospital in Dallas. Anthony Sugalo, 23, who was wounded in
the back, was in critical condition at &UR;  &LR; Fort Worth's Harris
Methodist Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Dealey said the shooting occurred shortly before noon, when
Farah parked his cab at the central taxi queue near the Hyatt
Regency DFW West and entered the metal shed, where drivers escape
from the sun while awaiting service calls.
</P>
<P>
   Although no motive for the shooting was known late Monday,
Dealey said he believes Farah had a confrontation with the three
victims before shooting them. Mead, wounded in the arm, ran from
the building toward a nearby utilities plant.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect allegedly followed and fired more shots at Mead in
the parking lot, but missed. He then returned to the shed and fired
more shots at the other two men he had wounded earlier, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed Amhed, who drove up minutes after the shooting began,
said he saw Farah pursue Mead into the parking lot and shoot at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grabbed the wounded guy and put him in my car to try to take
him to the hospital,'' he said, ``but just then a police car showed
up. I have blood in my cab.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Issa staggered from the building and tried to get
into his cab, but apparently died at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   There was no information available on the type of handgun used,
but airport public safety director Tom Shehan said, ``We think it
was an automatic.''
</P>
<P>
   The central taxi queue is removed from the terminals and no
passengers were endangered, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear if Farah had specifically targeted
the three victims. One driver for Big Tex Cab, Abdirizak Ali, was
in the building when Farah came in and began firing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two people were hit right beside me,'' he told The Associated
Press. ``He was shooting for everybody. And he was trying to shoot
at me, but I ran away.''
</P>
<P>
   Farah had worked for Taxi Dallas for about six months, a company
spokesman said, and had previously worked for several other cab
companies. The spokesman would not speculate on a possible motive.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings occurred in an area where hundreds of cabs line up
for the often long waits between fares. Some drivers said tempers
have been frayed by the lingering heat wave that has sent
temperature above 100 degrees at the airport for 35 straight days
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Dealey agreed that the heat may have have been a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hot as hell,'' he said. ``When you have 100-plus
temperatures and combine that with tempers and competing taxicab
companies and grudges, there's only so much the airport
(administration) can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempers continued to boil over at the scene long after the
victims were removed. Other drivers complained that more than 30
minutes elapsed before the first ambulance arrived, a fact Dealey
disputed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are in a situation like this,'' he said, ``even a
very short few minutes can seem like an eternity. That's probably
what happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   The first ambulance was dispatched at 11:41 a.m., just after the
call was received, he said. It left the airport with one victim,
bound for Parkland Hospital, at 11:50, he said. A second ambulance
arrived from Grapevine, a small town just north of the airport, at
noon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
