<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5258 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COATES-ASSAULT-BOS &LR;      07-27 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COATES-ASSAULT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS PLAYER PLEADS INNOCENT TO ASSAULTING EX-GIRLFRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL A. GRECH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WRENTHAM, Mass. _ Ben Coates, a star pro football player for the
New England Patriots, pleaded not guilty in District Court Monday
to allegedly attacking a jealous ex-girlfriend during a
confrontation Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Coates, 28, at his home in the Chestnut Ridge
Condominiums, Franklin, Mass., around 10:30 p.m. after the alleged
attack on Jennifer Marshall, 27, the mother of Coates' young
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   He was released Sunday night on cash bail of $500, but
prosecutors convinced a judge to raise Coates' bail to $1,000
during the arraignment. The judge also issued a no-abuse order to
Marshall. Coates' lawyer did not contest the move.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, who suffered a cut on her arm during the incident
outside Coates' condominium, did not seek a restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 inch, 245-pound Coates, an All-Pro tight end who is
married with three children, remained silent throughout the hearing
and refused to talk to reporters afterward. A pretrial conference
has been set for Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am certain that at the end of this legal process it will be
clear that Ben has done nothing wrong,'' defense lawyer Peter
Barlow said after the hearing. ``Ben only wants to get back into
the business of playing football. He is a quiet and private person
who likes to remain within the parameters of the playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Franklin police report, Marshall and a friend,
Corina Parkinson, 22, of Norwood, drove to Coates' house at around
10:30 p.m. on Sunday and knocked on the door.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall was apparently upset because she saw an unfamiliar car
in the driveway, the report states. During the confrontation, the
two shouted and shoved one another.
</P>
<P>
   In their accounts to police, Coates and Marshall blamed one
another for the assault.
</P>
<P>
   In her statement to police, Parkinson said she and her friend
believed the car belonged to Coates' new girlfriend. She said they
wanted to take pictures of the woman and the car.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall told police she became upset when she saw the car in
the driveway and knocked on Coates' front door.  &UR;  &LR; A heated argument
ensued, drawing curious neighbors from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall and Parkinson say Coates came from the house screaming
at Marshall, then pushed her to the pavement. Marshall told police
that when she pushed him back, Coates slammed her head to the hood
of the car, and threatened to knock her out.
</P>
<P>
   But Coates told police that Marshall initiated the assault. He
told officers she knocked on the front door, then attacked him when
he opened it. Coates said he pushed her away in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor, who did not want to be identified, said he saw the
incident and backed Coates' account. In an interview Monday, the
neighbor said Marshall initiated the confrontation and pushed
Coates first.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor, who said he lives close enough to hear their
screaming matches, said Marshall had gone after Coates before. On
one occasion, the neighbor said, Marshall kicked in the screen on
Coates' front door.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  During the off season, Coates resides in Concord, N.C., with
his wife Yvette and three daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Coates, who this fall will enter his seventh season with the
Patriots, is the highest-paid tight end in the NFL. His 1997
contract is worth $7.5 million over three years and featured a $3
million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 Coates broke the NFL tight end record for receptions
with 96, and for the past four season has been in the Pro Bowl,
being selected All Pro in the last two.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots vice president Don Lowery said the team completely
supports Coates. He said the player looks after the daughter he had
with Marshall, and ``he pays child support.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll, the head coach, would not talk about the incident
in detail, but said Coates' arrest ``does remind us again'' that
players are constantly in the limelight, and they must ``just avoid
the situations (where) that can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this can be a distraction for us, but we'll deal
with it as it comes,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The incident was the second in less than a week in which star
players faced assault charges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  On Friday, a Boston clerk-magistrate threw out assault and
battery charges on Willie McGinest and Lawyer Milloy brought by a
23-year-old Boston woman who claimed the players attacked her in a
nightclub. The players claim they were helping the womman to her
feet after she stumbled and fell. The alleged victim did not appear
for a court hearing the next day.
</P>
<P>
   In January, quarterbacks Drew Bledsoe and Max Lane were named in
a lawsuit stemming from an incident during a rock concert at the
Paradise nightclub in Boston last November.
</P>
<P>
   The players were cleared of criminal charges, but a Maynard
woman who was injured claims the players landed on her after diving
from the stage into the crowd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICAN-ECON-500&AMP;ADD-     07-27 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICAN-ECON-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN ILLS RESPONSIBLE FOR STEEL-INDUSTRY LAYOFFS IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Despite considerable nervousness about the impact
of the Asian crisis on Mexico and other Latin American countries,
until last week the main effects had been confined to the financial
markets, with only limited repercussions for the broad economy.
</P>
<P>
   So considerable interest has been aroused by the announcement
last week from Altos Hornos de Mexico, the country's largest steel
producer, that falling international demand and the availability of
cheap steel from Asia were forcing the largest layoffs in Mexico
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The elimination of 3,000 jobs constitutes ``the first case in
which we can see a very direct effect of the Asian crisis, and that
makes it notable,'' said Abel Beltran del Rio, the top Mexico
analyst at Ciemex-WEFA, a consulting group. Still, he said,
``unless there are serious new devaluations of the Asian
currencies, which we think is unlikely, we expect the Mexican
economy to come through very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks here have dropped 14 percent since the beginning of the
year, and 22 percent in dollar terms, yet some of the worst Mexican
damage associated with the Asian crisis had been seen in plunging
oil prices due to slackening demand. About a third of government
revenue comes from Pemex, the state oil monopoly, and as petroleum
prices have fallen this year, the government has been forced to
make significant cuts in spending, carving $3.7 billion out of a
federal budget around $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those cutbacks, the Mexican economy as a whole has
continued robust growth, at an annual rate of 6.6 percent in the
first quarter, the government says. Noting that strong domestic
consumption is driving the current boom, Ciemex-WEFA has predicted
growth of 5.6 percent for all of 1998. Even if the Asian crisis
were to worsen significantly, Beltran projects that the economy
would grow 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the news that Altos Hornos de Mexico, which controls
about a quarter of the $4.3 billion-a-year steel industry, was
embarking on major cost cutting fed the jitters here over the Asian
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican steel producers, which have already seen average prices
fall by 10 percent in recent months, fear that more drastic price
drops are on the horizon later this year. The company, in a
statement this week outlining its cost-cutting plan, predicted that
average steel prices would fall a further 13 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst is not what's happened so far but what we expect to
happen soon,'' said Jose Antonio Gomez Urquiza, executive director
of the National Chamber of the Steel and Iron Industry. He said
that although prices averaged about $300 a ton last year, some
steel from South Korea, Russia and several other countries had
recently been sold in Mexico for as little as $200 a ton. ``And
we've seen some quotes that are even lower than that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Mexican textile and chemical producers have also complained
in recent weeks of the appearance in this country of very
low-priced Asian imports. But so far, those industries have not
announced layoffs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Mexican steel industry, which is dominated by five major
producers, has through much of this decade enjoyed considerable
prosperity, following the privatization of three state-owned
companies in 1990, including Altos Hornos de Mexico. The main
producers are operating on the basis of plans to invest $2 billion
in modernization in 1998 and 1999, and those plans so far have not
been scaled back, Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   The investments are expected to raise Mexican steel production
capacity to 19 million tons from 15 million by the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   But the Asian crisis has raised doubts for two reasons, said
Mauricio Reveco, a Latin American steel analyst with Solomon Smith
Barney. Worldwide demand for steel is dropping as Asian economies
retrench. And even as Mexico builds its own capacity, producers in
Asia, the former Soviet republics and the rest of Latin America are
reacting to the fall in their own countries' demand for steel by
attempting to increase exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, you have Asia becoming a steel exporter,
Latin America becoming an exporter, Eastern Europe becoming an
exporter,'' Reveco said. ``So where is all this steel going to
go?''
</P>
<P>
   The mounting surplus could affect Mexico more severely than the
other big Latin American producers, Brazil and Argentina, because
those countries are situated farther from the Asian producers,
making transportation costs higher and shielding them somewhat from
Asian imports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our industry has enjoyed a very good period since the
privatizations in 1990, with a lot of investments in modernization
and good prices,'' said Miguel Elenes Inchaurregui, associate
editor of Acero Steel, a Mexican magazine that reports on the
industry. ``But now we fear that the cycle is going to move
downward. We expect a lot more jobs to be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican steel industry currently employs a total of 60,000
workers. Altos Hornos de Mexico alone had 19,000 workers at the end
of 1997, a spokesman, Luis Arias Ibarrondo, said.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000 jobs the company said it would eliminate are the most
extensive employment cuts in the industry since the same company
cut 12,000 jobs in 1991. Although all Mexican steel producers will
be squeezed by the falling worldwide prices, Altos Hornos de Mexico
may be feeling the pain more acutely than other producers because
of its debt of around $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company's sales last year were $1.5 billion and are
projected to be $1.4 billion in 1998, Reveco said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the jobs will be lost at foundries at Monclova, a desert
city of 180,000 in the state of Coahuila, which borders Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
