<HEADER>
A5262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLOWER-DISTRIBUTION-A     07-27 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOWER-DISTRIBUTION-ART-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BUSINESS OF BLOOMS CONSOLIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Col., Fla., Wash.)  (ART ADV: A graphic depicting USA Floral stock price, earnings per
share and three largest acquisitions is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The scene at 5 a.m. in the Miami International Airport
cargo area hasn't changed much over the years. Refrigerated trucks
with logos of companies like Atlantic Bouquet, CFX (``The Cut
Flower Experts'') and Continental Farms still rumble through the
security gates, back up to the loading docks and fill their
trailers with boxes of roses, lilies, chrysanthemums, baby's
breath, bird of paradise and dozens of other kinds of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Then they make their way along Northwest 25th Street to the
swath of industrial parks five miles away that is the hub of
Miami's flower-distribution business. By 7 a.m., the flower
companies' sales reps are hitting the phones, scrambling to find
buyers for any inventory that hasn't already been sold.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath all the hubbub, though, one thing is very different than
it once was _ and as a result, U.S. shoppers can expect to find a
lot more flowers in a lot more outlets before too long. Those
Atlantic Bouquet, CFX and Continental Farms trucks, as well as rigs
with a half-dozen other names splashed across their sides, now all
belong to a single company, USA Floral Products Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation craze that has swept through industry after
industry during the last few years _ from insurance and banking to
publishing and railroads _ has percolated down to an unlikely
corner of the U.S. marketplace: flowers.
</P>
<P>
   And leading the pack is USA Floral, which aspires to be the
undisputed giant of the $14 billion flower trade. In the last year,
it has snapped up 14 mom-and-pop distributors, wholesalers and
bouquet makers for a total cost of $152 million. It owns companies
in 22 states and Canada and says it will soon expand into Europe
and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month, USA Floral announced plans to purchase eight
more floral businesses around the country for $17.4 million in cash
and stock. Those include Channel Islands Floral, a bouquet maker in
California; Floramark, a Denver-based bouquet maker; and Evergreen
Wholesale Florist in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Few people will notice USA Floral's growing market presence
because it is letting the companies that it acquires keep their
names, largely because of the brand loyalty of many of their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   But already, its revenues have shot up to a projected $561
million this year, from $184 million in 1997, the company says, and
it confidently predicts that sales will soar to $1 billion next
year.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how big USA Floral wants to be, Robert Poirier, its
chairman and chief executive, responds with a question of his own:
``How big is the floral industry?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a small part of floral consumption over all,'' he said.
``There is a tremendous amount of business that is left on the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody _ least of all a lot of investors _ shares
Poirier's enthusiasm, however. The company went public last October
at $13 a share, and its stock surged to a peak of $23.875 in
February. But it has sunk since then, dropping as low as $15.375 in
mid-June before recovering a bit. Analysts blame a lack of investor
enthusiasm for consolidation companies. (It closed Monday at
$15.75.)
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the risks of the so-called roll-up strategy have
become evident, with analysts saying that some companies have grown
too quickly, failed to integrate operations, relied too much on a
few large customers and used large acquisitions to mask serious
operating problems.
</P>
<P>
   None of that fazes Poirier, who says the current price still
represents a premium from the $13 offering.
</P>
<P>
   Poirier, a 23-year veteran of the flower industry, is overseeing
USA Floral's expansion with the help of a pioneer in the relatively
new field of consolidating small, fragmented industries, Jonathan
Ledecky.
</P>
<P>
   Ledecky, who is the nonexecutive chairman of the company and its
largest shareholder with a stake of more than 8 percent, founded
U.S. Office Products Co. in 1995 and built it into a $2.8 billion
giant by buying hundreds of independent stationery stores and
furniture and office-product suppliers that were struggling to
survive against Office Depot and Staples. And last year, he formed
Consolidated Capital Corp. to string together businesses in
similarly dispersed industries.
</P>
<P>
   Poirier said he was following Ledecky's strategy of buying
high-quality companies at a modest premium and letting them
continue as independent operators with their old names and
suppliers intact. ``This is a video replay of U.S. Office
Products,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   But the similarity may be what has jaded investors. And Poirier
is also quick to point out the ways in which his business model
differs from that of U.S. Office Products. His focus on buying only
floral companies and moving quickly to consolidate operations has
helped USA Floral escape some of the criticisms facing U.S. Office
Products these days. And one significant difference _ the use of
the purchase method of accounting versus pooling to record
acquisitions _ should keep federal regulators at bay. It may also
stave off steep stock price declines like those experienced by U.S.
Office Products, whose shares have plunged as much as 42 percent
since June 1.
</P>
<P>
   While some other flower companies are also growing, USA Floral
is a standout. Its most formidable competitor is probably Dole Food
Co., the $4.3 billion California conglomerate, whose flower sales
surged from nothing to $100 million this year when it bought the
largest wholesaler in Florida along with its production farms in
South America. (Such well-known companies as 1-800-Flowers or
Florists' Transworld Delivery Inc., known as FTD, are not direct
competitors because they are essentially marketing operations and
retail florist groups.)
</P>
<P>
   But the main reason for USA Floral's upbeat outlook is the
enormous room that it sees for the growth of the entire flower
market, which is split almost evenly between the $6 billion
fresh-flower business and the $8 billion industry in potted plants
and vases. Only about 25 percent of Americans buy flowers
regularly, compared with 60 percent of Europeans, and USA Floral is
confident it can get the numbers up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average American is in a grocery store two to three times
a week,'' Poirier said. ``I'd like people to start thinking that if
they haven't got flowers, then there's something missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers are a diverse business. Imagine the stems of the
industry spreading throughout the nation, creating a wild
arrangement of largely family-owned businesses, including roughly
9,700 domestic growers, 1,000 wholesalers, 27,000 retail florists
and 23,000 supermarket floral operations. The industry has its tap
roots in Latin America, and the pot, so to speak, is centered
around the Miami airport, where approximately 100 importers handle
roughly 70 percent of all flowers consumed in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   USA Floral isn't the only company with grand ambitions, of
course. Dole's purchases last month gave it a foothold in the
flower business, and it hopes that its presence in supermarket
produce departments will give it a marketing edge to increase the
revenues of its floral companies. (USA Floral does not own any
farms, but it has exclusive agreements with several farms it deals
with.)
</P>
<P>
   Several Miami companies are also forming alliances and
considering mergers in order to make sure they are big enough to
compete. And a smaller, Los Angeles-based public company, Sun Cut
Floral Network, was formed earlier this year after it was acquired
by a former medical technology company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not certain where all of it is going, but the trend is
probably unstoppable at this point,'' said Alvaro Varela ,
president of Agriflora , a Miami importer. Varela said his company
had spurned a takeover bid from USA Floral because ``the group is
so big already we don't know where we would fit.'' Instead, he
said, Agriflora plans to merge with some other local distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Moran, the executive vice president and chief executive
officer of the Society of American Florists, said the flower
industry had long resisted the big-is-better mentality so prevalent
in other sectors of the economy. Previous efforts to forge national
floral empires have failed ``because the business is really driven
by relationships and outside people misjudge those relationships,''
he said. But things have changed. ``There's definitely a mania
going on,'' he said. ``Everybody's concerned that if they're not
part of a strategic relationship'' they will not survive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, meshing operations in the flower trade _ where
maintaining the freshness of one of the world's most perishable
products is the key and where ``keep it moving'' is the mantra _
won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Within the space of 24 hours, flowers are harvested on farms in
Ecuador, Colombia and Costa Rica; shipped to Miami; X-rayed as they
pass through 33-degree refrigerated coolers and then examined by
U.S. Department of Agriculture inspectors, all under the watchful
eyes of security cameras; picked up by distributors; warehoused;
and finally put on trucks bound for florists', Stop &AMP; Shops,
Kroger's stores and Wal-Marts all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an industry that lends itself to cookie-cutter
production. At one Miami bouquet company owned by USA Floral, each
worker assembles a single bouquet. At another, women stand in front
of conveyor belts, dropping set numbers of particular flowers into
each passing bouquet. Neither company plans to change its
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Still, USA Floral believes it can save money by consolidating
back-office operations like accounting, finance, insurance and
employee benefits. For example, it says, it recently cut costs by
more than $700,000 by combining the hazard insurance policies of 16
of its companies. It also saved almost $500,000 by channeling its
telephone business to a single long-distance company. And it plans
to fold its 10 Miami companies into six locations by year's end.
Task forces of executives from several of the companies are
exploring such other economy moves as adoption of a single computer
system.
</P>
<P>
   The company believes its heft will also allow it to distribute
more flowers at lower cost and save on transportation, flower
handling and storage. Poirer wants to create a string of regional
distributors in cities like Atlanta and Dallas to put flowers in
customers' hands more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, USA Floral hopes to do joint marketing and
merchandising with retailers. Today, the industry spends less than
$100 million a year on flower promotions, according to Moran of the
Society of American Florists. ``For a $14 billion industry, that's
not going to move the needle much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate goal is to make flowers so ubiquitous that
Americans _ who now mostly buy them on impulse or as infrequent
gifts _ will get into the habit of picking up bouquets once or
twice a week. To achieve that, the industry will have to reach
people like Mary Radford, a marketing executive in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When she lived in New York in the early 1990s, Ms. Radford
bought flowers all the time at a local corner grocery store, she
says. And she was an even more avid consumer when she lived in
Europe in the late 1980s. ``In Paris, flowers are all over the
place,'' she said. ``There are a lot of little florists' shops all
over the city, and they were cheap enough to justify the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   But she hasn't bought a single bouquet since she moved to
Washington two years ago. ``I don't think about it,'' she said,
``because they're not in front of me all the time and I have the
perception that they are more expensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
