<HEADER>
A5265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT &LR;      07-27 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS FRAZIER SHOW IS NOT MUST-SEE TV  
 LITTLE-LEAGUE SHOCKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Walt Frazier thesaurizes so pestiferously on New York
Knicks radio games that Peter Roget must wail lachrymosely in
lexicography heaven. Evidently, no producer has forcefully
persuaded Frazier that his silly wordplay hurts his credibility and
overwhelms the insight that his partisans say he possesses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clyde will now analyze Knicks games on TV. Is this bumbling
and fumbling by the MSG Network? Moving and grooving without
pertinacity?
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the skepticism,'' said MSG executive producer
Mike McCarthy, who characterizes Frazier as entertaining and
candid.
</P>
<P>
   By shifting Frazier away from WFAN, MSG can reunite Marv Albert,
rehired to call 50 games on radio, with John Andariese, his former
TV sidekick. (Gus Johnson will call the other 32 games on the radio
with Andariese.) On TV, Frazier will be back with Mike Breen, his
former radio mate, with whom Andariese worked last season.
</P>
<P>
   There is logic to reteaming Albert and Andariese, and elevating
Albert's comfort level. And Andariese does not view a return to
radio as a demotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone else had worked with Marv, I'd be jealous,'' he
said, adding that he sensed it was Albert's preference to work with
him.
</P>
<P>
   But Art Kaminsky, Albert's agent, said, ``Marv told them he'd be
pleased to work with whomever they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if Albert and Andariese light up WFAN, losing
Andariese to radio diminishes the TV product. And who's to say
Frazier would not have improved beside Albert, whose ability to
mine the best from his partners is well known?
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, hoping to capitalize on Frazier's strong points, seems
to be setting up a Clyde boot camp. ``He has a lot of adjustments
to make,'' McCarthy said. ``But he knows if this doesn't work out,
we can switch him in a heartbeat. He knows we won't be patient. If
he can't do this quickly, he'll go back.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said past efforts to tame Frazier's shtick did not
compare to the new plan. ``This is going to be intense,'' he said.
Besides subduing his ``verbalizing,'' the biggest adjustment for
the former Knicks superstar will be in taking off ``the star
costume and become part of the reporting community,'' McCarthy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier would not have been made the Knicks' TV analyst if
another option MSG was believed to have pursued _ bringing in Doc
Rivers _ had worked out. But Rivers is committed to call games for
TNT and the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   So, on a tether as short as Mel Rojas' in the Mets' bullpen,
Frazier must prove that he's more than shtick, more than a lot of
``hooping and swooping.''
</P>
<P>
   Having made the switch, McCarthy said he is not planning a
flip-flop of the the newly reconstituted teams after the 1998-99
season, to put Albert and Andariese back on TV again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not in contemplation at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL PROBLEM: There is a chilling moment in ABC News' ``Peter
Jennings Reporting: The American Game'' (Thursday, 9:30-11 p.m.)
when a Little League father, outraged by his son's perceived
laziness, threatens him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremy, listen to me,'' Chris McAfee says. ``I'm going to kick
you, I don't care, you didn't even want to bend down, Jeremy,
Jeremy, I'm on camera with a microphone, but I'm going to get you
tonight because you're letting me down, brother. ... I'll get you,
buddy. Cry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jennings documentary is not an expose of out-of-control
youth league parents, but a fly-on-the-dugout-wall look at two
months in the life of the Little League of Hagerstown, Md., from
May to July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And what a terrific program, relating tales about the star
player; the only girl; the talented catcher with an awful attitude;
the successful coach who admits to being sexist; the mixed-race boy
who seeks an escape from racism by playing in the Little League,
and a look back at the 1959 integration of the town's Little
Leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But the scene with McAfee resonates. ``We were shocked,'' said
Marty Smith, the producer. McAfee then amplified his disciplinary
style in an interview with Jennings. ``I thought there'd be a
denial, and he'd waffle,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the scene's power almost offered a compelling rationale not
to show it.
</P>
<P>
   What about the impact on the youngster? ``It was an ongoing
concern,'' Smith said, ``but it's better for the community to know
what's going on. More likely than not, it has a restraining effect.
We told the league officials about what we heard. He was banned
this season, and his kid made the All-Star team.''
</P>
<P>
   AIRWAVES: The ABC crew at the U.S. 500 Sunday in Brooklyn,
Mich., did not know the extent of the injuries that resulted when a
wheel flew into the grandstand until the race ended, when Robin
Roberts, in New York, reported the three deaths and six injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Only one distant camera showed the carnage. ``If we had a more
graphic look, we probably wouldn't have shown it, out of decency,''
said Mark Mandel, an ABC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   HBO's ``Real Sports'' (Tuesday night at 10) excels in a piercing
report on state-sponsored use of anabolic steroids by East Germany
to boost athletes' performances in the 1970s and 1980s, and a
sensitive report on what some groups are doing to save thoroughbred
horses from slaughterhouses.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's decision last week to shift Isiah Thomas from game
analysis to the ``NBA Showtime'' studio was absolutely right.
Thomas' insights as a player, union activist and team executive
were always best suited for studio work.
</P>
</TEXT>
