<HEADLINE>
N.Y. STATE PROBES CORRUPTION IN BROADWAY TICKET SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The state attorney general's office is close to
wrapping up an investigation of what officials say are rampant
kickbacks and price-gouging practices involving the biggest
theaters on Broadway and the most powerful entertainment and sports
venues in the city, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One target is the Roundabout Theater, whose ``Cabaret,''
temporarily closed because of the construction accident in Times
Square, has become one of the most coveted tickets in years.
Roundabout general manager Ellen Richard said the theater has been
cooperating with the attorney general's office since it was asked
to turn over records.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout was named as a subject of the investigation
Monday in the Daily Variety.
</P>
<P>
   But David Corvette, a spokesman for the office of Attorney
General Dennis Vacco, said that similar requests for information
had been made to more than a dozen other theaters and entertainment
companies. He said the investigation goes far beyond the Roundabout
to what investigators believe is rampant corruption that is
inflating ticket prices for entertainment and sports events. The
investigation includes many of the most recognized names in the
theater and entertainment industry, Corvette said, but declined to
name them.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was greeted with skepticism by many people
involved in the theater and ticket industries, who said some degree
of price inflation for coveted tickets had always been a part of
the entertainment business. They added that campaigns against
ticket scalping or price gouging have long been popular ploys for
politicians in election years.
</P>
<P>
   The most common form of corruption is what is called ice, in
which box offices overcharge ticket brokers for tickets to choice
events, adding costs that are then passed along to consumers, many
of them out-of-towners intent on getting tickets to events that
sold out long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that ice is rampant in the industry, and that it's a
major reason people have to pay so much to go to Broadway or
concerts these days,'' Corvette said. The practices being
investigated would affect consumers who buy tickets through brokers
rather than those who buy them directly from a box office. But, he
said, the attorney general's office believed that the ingrained
price gouging over time had the effects of inflating ticket prices
across the board.
</P>
<P>
   Targets of the investigation, he said, include ``the most
prominent Broadway venues along with some of the most prominent
concert and entertainment venues.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said the attorney general's office is taking depositions in
connection with its investigation and is preparing to file lawsuits
or take other legal steps. The department's investigation should be
completed ``within the next couple of months,'' Corvette said.
</P>
<P>
   One official of a company that deals in theater tickets also
argued that ice, ticket scalping or other practices had long been
part of the entertainment business. He said the investigation had
more to do with politics than with lower prices. Vacco, a
Republican, is running for re-election in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt ice exists,'' said the official who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``It does exist, it always has existed and
it always will exist. But I think you have about as much chance of
stomping it out as you have of outlawing prostitution. We see these
kind of investigations all the time, particularly in election
years, but I don't think it's likely to change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Richard of the Roundabout said, ``I have no knowledge of
anything happening here, but if someone in our box office is
selling tickets, I would really like to find out about it and see
them prosecuted. We're a not-for-profit theater. Someone making
money off our tickets is offensive to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But an official with the attorney general's office said the
abuse being investigated at the Roundabout appeared to be more the
theater's common practice of selling tickets to brokers at prices
above those allowed by law _ meaning not more than $5 or 10 percent
above the ticket price _ rather than the actions of one rogue
individual.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office said it believed that the practice
is endemic in the entertainment industry, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office has taken action in other
investigations related to ticket pricing. Joseph Nekola, the former
manager of the Jones Beach Theater, pleaded guilty in June to
second-degree grand larceny and third-degree computer tampering in
the theft of more than 8,000 tickets for the theater's 1996 summer
concert series. In April, Janet Rosenblatt and Gerald Nahay, owners
of the Manhattan theater company Tickets on Request, were charged
with selling tickets to sports events and concerts at rates as high
as 830 percent above the face value on the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The office has also sought information from concertgoers about
where they got their tickets and how much they paid.
</P>
<P>
   No action has been taken against any of the big-name
entertainment companies and theaters said to be the subject of the
current inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Corvette denied that the two-year-old investigation had more to
do with publicity than law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because this sort of thing has gone on for years does not
make it right or justify the impact it has on the exorbitant prices
for tickets that consumers have to pay,'' he said. ``If we can put
a dent in that, we've accomplished something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
