<HEADLINE>
IN DIVING, AMERICANS ARE MAKING A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif.)  (lb) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST MEADOW, N.Y. _ Until the 1980s, the world's best divers
usually came from the United States and its college and club
systems. Then the Chinese discovered and developed the sport, the
Russians made a resurgence, the great American champion Greg
Louganis retired and American diving struggled.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Americans seem to be making a small comeback, although
when the Goodwill Games diving competition ended Monday night,
China and Russia had won the most medals. After eight of the 10
events, China had 10 medals (four gold), Russia six (three gold),
the United States three (one gold) and the rest of the world five.
</P>
<P>
   The best diver here was Dmitri Sautin, a Russian who won the
men's 3-meter springboard on Sunday and was favored off the
10-meter platform Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans made a strong impression Sunday night when
20-year-old Laura Wilkinson, a University of Texas junior from
Houston, won the women's platform title. Wilkinson had won seven
U.S. championships, but never a big international competition. And
this one was big. The field included the world champion (Olena
Zhupina of Ukraine) and runner-up (Cai Yuyan of China).
</P>
<P>
   Here, every contender except Wilkinson made at least one major
error _ an overrotation here, an underrotation there, a failure to
keep the knees straight or the legs together. Wilkinson made no big
mistakes. And when she needed a solid last dive to overtake Cai,
she made it, a back 1{ somersault with 2{ twists, that drew scores
of 8.0 from all seven judges.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the ninth and last round, Wilkinson trailed Cai. Then
Cai, only 16 but more experienced than Wilkinson, barely finished a
3{ somersault pike. The door was open for Wilkinson, who dived
next. She said her nervousness disappeared, and she nailed her
dive. But she said that for her and for the American team, this was
only one competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to keep working on everything,'' she said. ``And since
the other teams are so good, we've had to work twice as hard to be
able to compete with them. I think we're making progress. I don't
know if it was U.S. diving slipping so much as the Chinese and
Russians getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Li Hongping of Mission Viejo, Calif., a former Chinese champion
and one of the three coaches of this American team, was cheered by
Wilkinson's victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very significant,'' he said, ``because it shows our
divers are as competent as anyone else. This builds confidence in
her and in the whole diving program in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to compete with someone who is training
more, like the Chinese and the Russians. We have to be mentally
tougher than anyone and have a more positive attitude. I'm seeing
that. It happened with Laura, and that's why she won a gold medal,
so this is a very good step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
