<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-KIMBLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BO KNOWS GLORY DAYS ARE BEHIND HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bo Kimble isn't a star. He has lost a step and is past his
prime. The player known for his deadly jump shot does not average
35 points per night, as he did in college. Now, Kimble is just
happy to get on the court and play with the young bucks.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that.
</P>
<P>
   And that honesty with himself is what makes Kimble special at
age 31. Unlike aging hoopsters who cling to their highlighted
pasts, he accepts his present situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm not going to make it back to the NBA,'' he said.
``I've stopped holding my breath on that one. At this point, I'm
playing because that's what I love to do. It's not about money. I
want to play as long as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks, Kimble has been one of the oldest
players in the Fila Summer Pro League at The Pyramid. He led his
team in scoring, but had obvious differences from his teammates.
While most of the players in the league are embarking on
professional careers, Kimble has been out of the NBA for four
years, a longer time than he spent in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   His place in basketball now contrasts his place in 1990, when
the Clippers made him the eighth selection in the draft. In the
1989-90 college season, the senior shooting guard from Loyola
Marymount led the nation in scoring, averaging 35.3 points per
game.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA, he played in 96 games in two seasons with the
Clippers. After they released him in 1992, he had a stint with the
New York Knicks. Since then, he has played in France, Portugal,
Taiwan and on the Harlem Globetrotters, among other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he played for the Continental Basketball
Association's Yakima Sun Kings and made $1,200 per week. This
upcoming season, he expects to play overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of small towns in the CBA, so the fan support is
really good,'' Kimble said. ``You can have a really good image at
home to them.''
</P>
<P>
   His image used to be that good in Los Angeles, when he played at
LMU. Kimble and teammate Hank Gathers helped bring LMU's program
out of obscurity. In their junior and senior seasons, LMU took its
run-and-gun style to the NCAA Tournament, attracting a great deal
of attention.
</P>
<P>
   But in their senior season, in the WCAC championship, the
unthinkable happened, stunning Kimble and LMU.
</P>
<P>
   Gathers collapsed during the game and died.
</P>
<P>
   The death affected college basketball in general. Kimble was
forced to reevaluate his priorities. Today, the incident still is
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about him every day,'' Kimble said. ``There's just
always some reminder I see every day of him. When I think of Hank,
I only think of the great things. It's similar to being in denial
... Hank could be a little selfish, a little self-centered. He was
used to getting his way. When I think of him, I never think of that
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   While he does not forget Gathers, Kimble is now having fun
again. His teammates at the summer league acknowledged that and
respect his strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's aggressive that's the best thing about his game,'' said
Marlon Garnett, 23, who played last season in Turkey. ``To be a
great shooter, you have to be aggressive, to shoot it when you
should ... He's a little older and maybe lost a step. But he's
still a legend.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Prince, 24, who graduated from UC Santa Barbara in 1996,
pointed out something else. ``He may be getting on in age,'' Prince
said. ``But he's got it. You can see guys who are 30, 31 or 32 out
here who don't sprint, have no degree, no IRA, and are throwing up
air balls. He's not like those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimble said he plans to play ``until he can't move.'' Living in
Los Angeles, he is embarking on a new endeavor. He is opening
Jamaican restaurants in Philadelphia and Baltimore. And after
basketball, he has a plan, albeit vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go into broadcasting, acting, promoting clubs or
the restaurant business,'' he said. ``You know, I'd like to stick
with the fun stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
