<HEADLINE>
H,35P5,30,EB EVERYTHING EVERY WOMAN NEEDS TO KNOW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   After watching Lifetime _ a TV channel aimed at women _ for 72
hours,  &UR; Rebecca Barry  &LR; of Mademoiselle magazine learned five
invaluable Lessons of Life:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Women, like cockroaches, are virtually indestructible.''
Whatever physical trauma they endure, including rape and
strangulation, they ``still look pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The bonds of womanhood are so strong that any ill deed one
woman does another is forgiven by her loving sister.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Women are in constant danger of smelling bad,'' and most ads
tout products to ensure ``freshness'' in every area of the home and
body.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``There are three kinds of men: the good, the bad and the
European.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Overweight women should not be seen or heard from.'' One
program advised that dieters avoid friends who eat. ``You won't
have much of a life,'' said the host, ``but think of how thin
you'll be!''
</P>
<P>
   (The Women We Love issue of a Magazine Women Hate specifies that
men don't like women with bushy eyebrows or long pointy noses and
that the ideal woman is 30 years old, weighs 120 pounds and has a
rear end ``not too big, not too small.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (And  &UR; Elizabeth Jagger &LR; , 14-year-old daughter of  &UR; Jerry Hall &LR; 
and  &UR; Mick Jagger &LR; , has begun a modeling career at a  &UR; Thierry &LR; 
 &UR; Mugler &LR;  show in Paris. She has been signed to model for  &UR; Vivienne &LR; 
 &UR; Westwood &LR; 's Red Label line, for ``affluent 13- to 18-year-olds,''
says the London Telegraph.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In Brazil,  &UR; Anthony Quinn  &LR; spotted an 11-year-old girl
watching the filming of a movie on the beach, declared her the
reincarnation of someone close to him in a previous life and
invited her to come live in the United States. Meanwhile,  &UR; Celine &LR; 
 &UR; Dion &LR;  will lend her celebrity presence to the opening of a National
Car Rental center in Sunrise, Fla., on October 3.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anti-fur protests notwithstanding, British designer
 &UR; Alexander McQueen &LR; 's latest show included a dress decorated with a
``garland'' of stuffed parakeets, reports the Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; John Taylor &LR; , director of the  &UR; Richard Nixon &LR;  Library &AMP;
Birthplace, is complaining that his letter to  &UR; Tom Johnson &LR; ,
president of CNN, demanding an apology for the sarin nerve gas
story has been ignored. Taylor also told the Washington Times that
the network owes an apology to  &UR; Henry Kissinger &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Baird Jones &LR; , curator of a exhibition of  &UR; Red Skelton &LR; 
paintings at Webster Hall in New York, says the velvet ones, such
as the work owned by  &UR; Newt Gingrich &LR; , are the most valuable.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tom Jewell &LR;  says the proposed term Lewinsky _ for 1 trillion
bits of information _ should really be the Lipinski because the
former name of the quantity is the terabit. ``Perhaps the term
Lewinsky could be reserved for 1 trillion bits of misinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; John Palomino &LR;  of the Polish Antidefamation League has
written to express the group's official displeasure at PMS (Polish
Mood Shades) nail polish, which suggests that ``our members are
pystoffed or bloated. ... PADL's members' fingernails may change
color, but it is generally as a result of hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WAR MOVIE TO END WAR MOVIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say this war movie is too realistic,'' writes  &UR; Jim &LR; 
 &UR; Mullen  &LR; of Entertainment Weekly about ``Saving Private Ryan.''
``But so far everyone who's seen it has lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless,  &UR; J.M. &LR;  said it was the first time in memory that he
forgot to eat his popcorn. And a reader who calls himself  &UR; the &LR; 
 &UR; Cray  &LR; was ``impressed'' by the movie, but not so much that he
didn't notice an error: A photograph of the four Ryan boys in
uniform together, in Mrs. Ryan's house, is at odds with Private
Ryan's statement later in the movie that the last time they were
together was before one went off to boot camp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are degrees of extreme dieting, just as there are
degrees of madness, from eccentric to stark-raving. Eccentric is
using mustard, and only mustard, in lieu of salad dressing;
stark-raving is treating mustard as an entree.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From an Allure magazine story on fad diets.
</P>
</TEXT>
