<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS BUOYED BY AMEX EARNINGS DATA; DOW UP 90.88 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An earnings report that was stronger than expected
lifted stocks out of the doldrums Monday as most major market
indexes closed higher.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts were not impressed by the rally, which pushed
the Dow Jones industrial average up 1.02 percent. And the gains in
the stock market did little to mask a growing bearish sentiment on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   After gaining just 4.38 points Friday, the Dow Jones industrial
average roared back past 9,000 Monday, rising 90.88 points, to
9,028.24. The rebound, led by strong gains in American Express came
after the Dow fell more than 400 points last week.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks began gaining ground after American Express reported
second-quarter earnings that topped analysts' forecasts, helped by
heavy increases in the use of its charge cards and sales of mutual
fund shares.
</P>
<P>
   American Express closed at 112 13/16, up 5} points, or 5.4
percent, contributing nearly 24 points to the Dow's advance.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 6.47 points, to 1,147.27.
And the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index gained 2.27 points,
to 1,933.26. Microsoft, Ericsson and Intel were among the leading
gainers.
</P>
<P>
   Small company shares, however, continued to falter Monday. The
Russell index of 2,000 smaller company stocks fell 5.42 points, or
1.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expressed concerns about the limited breadth of the
rally, where gains were concentrated among a small group of large
companies. And some cautioned that things could get worse for
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Predictably, after the big drop we had investors went back
into the same big names,'' said Larry Rice, chief investment
officer at Josephthal &AMP; Co. ``The correction wasn't deep enough,
and the rally wasn't strong enough'' to be sustained, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barton Biggs, chief global strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, warned investors Monday that ``we may have entered a
cyclical bear market in the U.S. which could see the market go down
20 percent to 30 percent over a period of months or quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   And he cited Asia's financial crisis as a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian economies are much worse than most people recognize,
and they should continue to deteriorate,'' Biggs wrote. In
addition, ``Japan's election of Keizo Obuchi appears to be a
negative development for Japan, Asia, and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggs advised clients to reduce holdings of stocks because of
Asia's woes. He recommended investors put 12 percent of their
portfolio in large-capitalization U.S. stocks and 13 percent in
large-cap European stocks, down from 13 percent and 14 percent,
respectively. Investors should shift the money into cash or
short-term securities, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Asian stock markers were lower Monday, as investors in the
region expressed concern that Japan's incoming prime minister,
Obuchi, would not take quick action to spur growth in the Japanese
economy, which is still seen as a vital engine for the Pacific
Rim's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's benchmark Nikkei 225 index fell 2.55 percent to a
one-month low. Stock markets in Hong Kong, Malaysia and Thailand
fell 2 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, commodity prices were weaker, as investor expressed
similar concerns about Japan's fiscal health.
</P>
<P>
   Copper fell more than 1 percent, backing away from its highest
price in more than two months, amid expectations that Japan's new
government will not revive the economy of the world's
second-largest copper consumer. Rising supplies, at a time of weak
demand in Asia, also hurt copper prices Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the market's sold off in the past it has always been a
good time to buy stocks,'' said Richard Cripps, chief market
strategist at Legg Mason Inc. in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But ``earnings numbers are coming down,'' he said. ``There's no
major driver to move equity prices higher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
