</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRESSE STILL HURT BY DODGERS' DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the reeling Los Angeles Dodgers had scored an extra-inning
victory over the Anaheim Angels on June 25 at Dodger Stadium, Mark
Cresse came across Reggie Smith in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm gone,'' the Dodgers' batting coach told the
Dodgers' bullpen coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I remember thinking to myself, ``I just can't
believe they would fire someone the caliber of Reggie Smith,'''
relates Cresse.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, the Dodgers' new manager, Glenn Hoffman, told
Cresse, ``Before you shower, I need to talk to you in my office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart sank to my knees right then,'' says Cresse. ``I knew
right then it was going to be my turn to get the bad news. I walked
into Hoffman's office, and there were Charlie Blaney (Dodgers'
director of minor league operations), Ralph Avila (Dodger scout),
Tom Lasorda and Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat in a chair in the middle of the room. Hoffman said,
`Mark, we need to make some changes to get this team turned
around.' My head dropped, and I guess I looked pretty agonized. I
was in total shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I finally looked up, I saw Tom Lasorda smiling. `Beach
(Cresse's nickname), relax, we're not firing you,' he said. `We
want you to manage our San Bernadino team.' Tommy just kept
smiling, as though all my prayers had just been answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might have thought going to San Bernardino would be a great
move for me, but I didn't. I felt about as low as a human being can
feel. I had given 25 years of sweat, blood, tears, and hard work to
the Dodger organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never said no to anyone. When the community affairs people
needed someone to make an appearance, I always made myself
available. I was a problem-solver for every department's dilemma.
I've always felt that if you give 100 percent at your job, work as
hard as you can and keep your nose clean, you'll never be let go.
But I was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than a month now since Mark Cresse stopped
drawing a paycheck from an organization he had joined in 1974 and
had served for the past 22 seasons as its bullpen coach, the
longest tenure of any coach in Dodger history.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than a month now since Mark Cresse was told his
well-regarded services coordinating the Dodgers' pre-game drills
and bullpen activities no longer were needed by the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than a month now since Mark Cresse heard those
unwanted words from Glenn Hoffman that would dramatically change
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cresse insists he's not bitter, doesn't despise Glenn
Hoffman or Tom Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenn did what he felt was best for the team, and I can live
with that,'' Cresse says. ``Actually, I agree with Tom Lasorda's
decision to give Glenn the power to pick his own coaches. Such
authority might not have been good for Mark Cresse, but I think the
manager should be able to bring in the coaches he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mark Cresse admits he remains in a state of shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had been some rumors going around before the coaching
firings, and a lot of us were on edge,'' says Cresse. ``Joey
Amalfitano (Dodgers' third base coach) had gone through things like
this as a coach with the Chicago Cubs and Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when the Dodgers made the changes in their manager and
general manager, I thought to myself, `Wow, I guess I'm lucky. I'm
gonna be safe.' After all, I've always been Tommy's right-hand man.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw Tommy after he became the GM, he put his arm
around me and we hugged. He asked me a few things about the team,
and I told him. I thought everything was cool. But I guess it
wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Befitting a workaholic, Mark Cresse still has remained busy even
though he's no longer pitching batting practice, hitting fungoes,
or typing up scouting reports on a daily basis for the Dodgers
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   He now spends his days alternating among the four sites
Huntington Beach, Aliso Viejo, Irvine and Villa Park of the
baseball schools that bear his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I've gone from holding two full-time jobs to
holding just one,'' he says. ``But I'm still putting in 12 hour
days. The kids ask me all the time what happened to me with the
Dodgers. I don't sugarcoat anything to them. I just tell them the
truth. I just tell them I got fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Why was a man who was celebrated for his extraordinary work
ethic fired by the Dodgers?
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have no idea,'' says Cresse.
</P>
<P>
   Had he been on bad terms with Glenn Hoffman?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' says Cresse. ``We worked together in recent
years during the winter workouts at Dodger Stadium. He'd be in
charge of the minor leaguers, and I'd be in charge of the major
leaguers. We got along fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he sided with Fred Claire against Tom Lasorda?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never, ever got involved in office politics,'' says Cresse.
</P>
<P>
   What Mark Cresse finds even more bizarre about his ouster is
that no one has replaced him in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really floors me is that I got replaced by a guy (John
Shelby) who sits in the dugout and positions the outfielders
defensively,'' says Cresse. ``I still think what I did in the
bullpen was important. But I guess some people see it
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Cresse quickly declined the Dodgers' San Bernadino offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A minor league manager busts his hump for years to be a major
league coach,'' says Cresse. ``I've already been a major league
coach for 22 years. I think I've proved that I can do the job. And
I also felt that if an organization didn't think I was good enough
to work for it at one level, then why would I want to work for it
at another level?''
</P>
<P>
   Cresse and his wife Jean Ann, long-time residents of College
Park East in Seal Beach, are planning to relocate near Palm
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just put in a offer for a home in La Quinta,'' says Cresse,
whose son, Brad now touring Italy with a U.S. National team hit 29
home runs the past season at LSU. ``You can say the Cresses are now
down-sizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cresse already has been contacted by two big league teams,
and hopes to be back in the majors by next summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he stays busy with his baseball school, which
had a clinic at Dodger Stadium on July 14 before the Dodgers game
with the San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bussed about 300 kids up to the stadium, and they spent the
afternoon listening to people like Mickey Hatcher and Mike Scioscia
and Joey Amalfitano talk about baseball,'' says Cresse. ``Tom
Lasorda also spoke to them.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the first time Mark Cresse had returned to Dodger
Stadium since he had been shown the door, and he admits it felt
strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still watch all the Dodger games I can on television,'' says
Cresse. ``I still have a lot of friends on that team I root for.
But I'm still crushed and hurt by what happened to me. I think
people usually get fired for good reasons. I still wish I knew why
I was fired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
