<SLUG> BC-WOLF-AD-COLUMN-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: WOLF GROUP ACQUIRES SHOP AFTER SHOP TO MEET TWIN
GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Toronto, Ohio, N.C., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Who is Larry Wolf, to paraphrase the title of a
rather obscure Dustin Hoffman movie from 1971, and why is Madison
Avenue saying all those things about him?
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is the soft-spoken, low-key chairman and chief executive of
Wolf Group Integrated Communications Ltd., a privately held agency
company based in Toronto that has been growing rapidly through a
skein of ambitious acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The American-born Wolf _ described by The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail
as perhaps ``the most successful unknown advertising man in
Canada'' _ has been snapping up shops on both sides of the border
with the twin goals of becoming a top-20 agency company in billings
and going public.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'd like to leave behind is another great agency brand,''
Wolf, 58, said in an interview during a recent visit to the midtown
Manhattan office of Partners &AMP; Shevack, a midsized shop gobbled up
by Wolf Group last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so exciting about being in marketing communications
today is the incredible fluidity and volatility,'' he added.
``We're looking at a lot of opportunities in various stages,''
including a potential acquisition on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Partners &AMP; Shevack more than doubled Wolf
Group's billings to $400 million-plus from $177.3 million in 1997.
Wolf said he wanted to more than double billings again, reaching $1
billion ``in two or three years.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth of Wolf Group is emblematic of a subtheme in
the consolidation trend that is remaking the agency industry: the
rise of holding companies smaller than such giants as Omnicom
Group, WPP Group PLC and the Interpublic Group of Companies. The
second-tier tiny titans include, in addition to Wolf Group, Snyder
Communications, which acquired Arnold Communications and Barry Blau
&AMP; Partners, and CKS Group, which acquired McKinney &AMP; Silver and
Site Specific Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had not heard of Wolf Group, I'll be honest with you, and
I'm an advertising junkie,'' said Brett Shevack, chief executive at
Partners &AMP; Shevack. He joined Wolf and Bob Barocci, chief operating
officer at Wolf Group, for the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``But being acquired by Wolf,'' Shevack said, ``gives us the
opportunity to get in the ground floor of something very dynamic,
to become part of an engine for growth with great firepower.''
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Partners &AMP; Shevack gave Wolf Group its first
outpost in downstate New York after serving the upstate region
through offices in Buffalo and Rochester. Others offices are in
Cleveland and Toronto, with service offices in Columbus, Ohio, and
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolf Group client roster includes such familiar names as
Aamco Transmissions, Alberto-Culver Co., Canandaigua Wine Co.,
Continental General Tire, Eastman Kodak Co., the Fisher-Price unit
of Mattel Inc., Haagen-Dazs Co. unit of Diageo PLC, Pfizer Inc. and
Smith Corona Corp.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The best-known work from Wolf Group may be the series of
commercials created by the Cleveland office, formerly known as
Meldrum &AMP; Fewsmith Communications, that used special effects to
depict Fred Astaire dancing with the Dirt Devil line of vacuums
made by Royal Appliance Manufacturing Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to expand and develop our ability to serve our clients
in even more depth than now,'' Wolf said, adding that being based
in Canada was a benefit because ``we're so spread out
geographically with a small population that you have to learn how
to do a lot more with a lot less.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And while niche marketing makes a great deal of sense in the
States,'' he added, ``there you can niche yourself down to
negligibility. That demands a holistic, integrated marketing
approach in which advertising is just one way to win customers and
keep business, in tandem with public relations, loyalty programs,
direct marketing, package design and Web sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Barocci, who jokingly described himself as ``the silent
partner'' because of his judicious participation in the interview,
said that a strength of Wolf Group was its structure ``as a law
firm with managing partners, key people like Brett spending the day
looking at every possible way to build a client's brands, not on a
plane to Beijing to visit an office there.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Wolf said they were concentrating their buyout efforts
among entrepreneurial agency principals who want to remain active
in advertising rather than cash out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in retirement planning as the primary
objective or our new partners,'' Wolf said. ``We want people
excited about building something with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Wolf Group thrive in a shrinking ad world, or will the
acquirer someday become the acquired?
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is not whether Wolf Group is the size of Omnicom
or Interpublic,'' Barocci said, ``but whether our resources can
help clients grow their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said: ``The point of purchase is the moment of truth when
you make or lose the sale. What happens at that moment is critical.
And the consumer doesn't know how big your agency is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
