<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Campsites, old mines being checked in search for Rudolph
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS, N.C._ As the search for Birmingham bombing suspect Eric
Robert Rudolph dragged on in the soggy Western North Carolina
mountains, lab techinicians are analyzing old canned goods and
other evidence removed from caves and campsites, but have yet to
link them to the fugtive, a federal official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that looks llike a campsite or garbage we would
recover that and take it to the lab and process it,'' said Jack
Killorin, head of the Atlanta officie of the U.S. Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. ``We don't have any positive results
on any of that testing.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI on Monday appealed for the help of anyone with knowledge
of old caves and mines in the area and reiterated their commitment
to solving the two-year-old Centennial Olympic Park bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Enderson, inspector in charge of the Southeast Bomb Task
Force, urged Rudolph to turn himself in during a Monday press
briefing so ``he can tell his side of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Enderson said they are sending up additional helicopters and
airplanes to support the 200 federal, state and local agents
slogging through the rugged terrain three weeks after the fugitive
resurfaced at the home of an elderly health food store owner.
Rudolph later took a pickup truck and six-months worth of food and
other supplies from 71-year-old George Nordmann.
</P>
<P>
   Nordmann, who first talked with the 31-year-old carpenter on
July 7, waited until July 11 to report the encounter. His truck was
found July 13 and at the time federal agents figured they were
closing in on their suspect, with only 15 hours separting them.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph has continued to elude the reinvigorated manhunt, as
agents methodically search a 30-square-mile area by grids in the
Nantahala Forest in Macon County, N.C. Their search has taken them
into old silver mines in neighboring Swain County, just over a
mountain ridge from Rudolph's family's old homeplace.
</P>
<P>
   But experts on caves and mines in western North Carolina said
there are virtually no long-term, subterranean hiding places for
Rudolph near Nantahala. Steve Maynard, who has gone caving around
the Nantahala Gorge, said the caves in that part of the state end
after a few hundred feet. ``In the Nantahala Gorge, there are small
caves,'' Maynard said. ``But there are no networks. It's not like
you'd find in Tennessee or Kentucky. There are caves in Kentucky
where you can go for hundreds of miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Maynard said the caves he has explored are damp, and often
there's just room to crawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be a comfortable place to be for a long time,''
Maynard said. ``You come out cold and chilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the mining done in western North Carolina occurs at
the surface for crushed stone and granite, said Fred Allen,
executive director for the North Carolina Aggregates Association, a
mining lobbyist group. There once were underground mines as
prospectors searched for gold, silver, mica and other minerals, but
those are few and were dug a ``long, long, long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Marlon Manuel
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
