<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-LANDANO-TRIAL-875&AMP;     07-27 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-LANDANO-TRIAL-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDANO IS ACQUITTED IN 2ND TRIAL FOR 1976 MURDER OF POLICE
OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. _ Vincent Landano, who paid dearly for a crime
he steadfastly denied committing for 22 years, won the battle of
his life on Monday when a jury here acquitted him in his second
trial for the 1976 murder of a Newark, N.J., police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Landano had served 13 years of a life sentence for the killing,
was freed after a judge ruled the state had suppressed evidence at
the first trial, and lived for nine more years under constant
law-enforcement surveillance as prosecutors continued to pursue
him.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he taught himself law and attracted a loyal
following of people who believed that he was framed for the murder
of Officer John Snow. Among them were a lawyer who devoted
thousands of hours to Landano's case for free and a sprightly woman
who met him on a visit to prison and married him.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I ever asked was for 12 jurors to listen to the facts,''
said Landano after the verdict, as he stood on the courthouse steps
amid a crowd of jubilant supporters _ including one woman who had
served on the jury that initially convicted him and said she had
regretted it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion of Landano's long roller coaster ride through the
justice system passed swiftly in comparison with his fight for
vindication. The trial in Superior Court lasted three weeks. The
jury of 10 women and two men deliberated just under five hours.
When the forewoman softly pronounced the words ``not guilty,'' the
graying 58-year-old Landano thrust his fists in the air and
shouted, ``All right!''
</P>
<P>
   An instant later, the trial judge, Shirley Tolentino, told him
he was free to go.
</P>
<P>
   Landano did not tarry. With his arms wrapped around his wife,
Camille, he proclaimed his first worry-free plan. ``Right now,'' he
said, grinning, ``all I want to do is get as far from this building
as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Gardner, an assistant Hudson County prosecutor, said the
Snow murder will not be pursued further. ``This matter, for all
intents and purposes, is closed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he accomplished what he set out to do. ``We reached a
verdict which brings closure to this case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It did not bring closure to the family of the murdered Snow,
whose daughter broke down and wept in the courtroom as the verdict
was announced. She had said she remains convinced that Landano is
her father's killer.
</P>
<P>
   Landano was an unemployed construction worker with a heroin
habit and a three-year stint at Attica State Prison in New York for
grand larceny, when he was charged with shooting Snow in the neck
during a robbery of the Hi-Way Check Cashing Service in Kearny,
N.J., on Aug. 13, 1976.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his arrest, two other men were already in
custody, both members of a motorcycle gang called ``The Breed''
that specialized in armed robberies. They cooperated with the
state, naming Landano not only as their accomplice in the heist but
as the gunman. Snow, who was on duty at the time, was in Kearny
unofficially to deliver $46,000 in cash to the Hi-Way management.
</P>
<P>
   From the first, Landano protested his innocence. He said he had
been set up by a childhood friend, Victor Forni, who was described
by gang members as the brains of the outfit and the one who figured
out the plans for their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Forni, in fact, was charged and pleaded guilty to conspiracy in
the Hi-Way robbery. But that only happened later _ after he lost a
two-year battle against extradition from New York to New Jersey. In
the interim, his old friend Landano, who said he was not even in
New Jersey at the time of the robbery, was tried, convicted and
sent to jail.
</P>
<P>
   In prison, he told his story to Neil Mullin, a lawyer from
Montclair, N.J., who eventually became consumed with the Landano
case, devoting countless unpaid hours and nearly 20 years to
overturning the conviction. In 1989, he convinced Judge H. Lee
Sarokin of U.S. District Court in Newark that the state possessed
undisclosed evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented raid, federal marshals, acting on Sarokin's
orders, scoured the files of police departments and the
prosecutor's office for all information related to the Snow murder.
Based on what was found _ including evidence that some of the
witnesses were pressured by the police to identify Landano as the
gunman _ the judge said the state had ``systematically'' withheld
evidence, and he ordered Landano released from state prison.
</P>
<P>
   The state fought back. The case ricocheted for another seven
years through various courts. By then, however, Landano's fight to
clear his name had acquired another foot soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Lepore-Kaneko was a juror in the first murder trial in
1978. She said she went along reluctantly with the others in their
guilty verdict. ``I thought maybe they had understood things I
didn't,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But reading Sarokin's decision 11 years later, Mrs.
Lepore-Kaneko decided her courtroom misgivings might have some
basis after all. She contacted Landano and followed him from
hearing to hearing. She flew back from Osaka, Japan, where she now
lives with her husband, for the second trial.
</P>
<P>
   When the verdict was read, Mrs. Lepore-Kaneko began to weep and
tremble. ``So relieved! So relieved!'' she gasped. ``The
intensity!''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the second trial, the star witness was the one Breed gang
member who agreed to testify again on behalf of the state _ Allen
Roller, who had been convicted of actually robbing the Hi-Way Check
Cashing Service and served eight years in prison. Forni, whom the
defense claimed framed Landano, was subpoenaed by the state and
brought to Jersey City. He refused to testify and remains in the
Hudson County Jail on contempt charges.
</P>
<P>
   As he has before, Roller named Landano as the gunman. But on
many other issues, he contradicted his earlier statements. Paul
Casteleiro, Landano's trial lawyer, called him a ``misfit'' and a
``liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Casteleiro, who called no witnesses for the defense, also sought
to discredit the state's main piece of evidence, a blue denim hat
found on the seat of the getaway car splattered with Snow's blood.
The hat may well be Landano's, he said, but it was stolen and
planted in the car by the Breed gang as part of their carefully
planned crime.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, the prosecutor, portrayed the Hi-Way Check Cashing
robbers as a gang bumblers who forgot to bring a bag for the money
and then got lost in their getaway car as they careened away from
the scene. Framing Landano, he argued in his summation, was beyond
their talents.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, however, simply did not believe either the state's hat
story or Roller.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept pushing the hat, the hat, the hat,'' Frieda Smith,
one of the jurors, said in a telephone interview after the verdict.
``But that didn't make him the killer.'' There was also general
disagreement in the jury room, she said, that Roller lacked
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was thinking the same thing,'' Ms. Smith said.
``There were a lot of `ifs.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
