<SLUG> BC-SWISS-LIFE-RE-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS ACQUISITION FURTHER CONSOLIDATES THE REINSURANCE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   (EDS: Previously skedded as SWISS-RE-LIFE)  
(js) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Furthering a consolidation that has recently accelerated in the
reinsurance industry, Swiss Reinsurance Co. said Monday that it had
agreed to acquire the Life Re Corp. for $95 a share, or about $1.8
billion, in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase by Swiss Re, the world's second-largest reinsurance
company behind Munich Reinsurance, is the third deal in the
industry in little more than a month. Last week Gerling AG, the
German insurer, bought Constitution Reinsurance Corp. from Exor
Group SA, an investment company controlled by the Agnelli family of
Italy, for $700 million. And in June Berkshire Hathaway Corp., the
holding company run by Warren Buffett, bought General Re Corp., one
of the world's largest reinsurers, for just under $22 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the trend would almost certainly continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies just have too much capital,'' said Cathy
Seifert, who follows the reinsurance industry for Standard &AMP; Poor's
Corp. ``And the best way to redeploy that capital is through
acquisitions. Also, the financial services business is globalizing,
and within the insurance sector, reinsurance is perhaps the most
global business there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin Devine, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, said European
companies are likely to be interested in additional U.S.
properties. ``From a valuation perspective, European insurance
company stocks trade at about double the multiples of the stocks in
this country,'' he said. ``For many international companies, that
makes the American reinsurance sector very attractive right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Life Re, based in Stamford, Conn., sells traditional life and
administrative reinsurance throughout the United States. Last year,
Life Re had a net income of $49.6 million and revenue of $645.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Reinsurance companies buy policies from other insurers, helping
to spread risk. In effect, reinsurers promise to cover much of the
claims of their clients _ other insurance companies _ for a
relatively small portion of the premiums collected from
corporations and individuals. And they agree to pay if the
insurance companies suffer huge losses. But huge losses are rare
and often the reinsurers have little to pay out. As such, the
business can be extremely profitable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The $95-a-share price for Life Re represents a premium of 6.3
percent over the company's $89-a-share closing price Friday on the
New York Stock Exchange. Shares of Life Re jumped after the deal
was announced, and closed at $91.3125 Monday, up $2.3125.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Zurich, Swiss Re maintains more than 70 offices in 30
countries. Last year, the company had after-tax income of about
$1.5 billion on insurance revenue of $11.9 billion. At the end of
1997, the company had 7,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition deepens Swiss Re's presence in the U.S. life
reinsurance market.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The deal ``further develops our strategy to expand our life and
health operations,'' Walter Kielholz, Swiss Re's chief executive,
said in a statement. ``With Life Re Corporation as an integral part
of Swiss Re, we believe there is significant opportunity to
increase revenue, earnings and shareholder value growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Swiss Re said the transaction was subject to approval by state
insurance regulators, Life Re shareholders and ``certain other
conditions.'' Analysts said regulatory approval usually takes about
six months.
</P>
<P>
   Once the deal is approved, Swiss Re said Jacques E. Dubois, Life
Re's president and chief operating officer, would succeed Jeff Hart
as chief executive of Swiss Re Life and Health America.
</P>
<P>
   Devine of Salomon Smith Barney noted that the U.S. life
insurance market was ``very much'' a growth industry, a fact that
added to Life Re's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Seifer, the Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst, said there are 10 to
15 publicly traded reinsurance companies in the United States that
could well be scooped up by larger entities. She said that group
included Nacre Corp., Risk Capital Holdings , Capital Re Holdings
and IPC Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. served as Life Re's financial adviser on
the transaction. Swiss Re was represented by Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
