<SLUG> BC-HEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unbearable heat in Texas will stay put _ for now
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It's the kind of heat that makes the sky go white, that
makes people who are forced to be outside seek shelter in even a
postage-sized bit of shade. And there is no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   After 22 days of temperatures above 100 degrees, Monday's Dallas
Morning News had a grim forcast for the week: It pictured five
boxes with a blistering sun in each. No clouds. No rain. And,
again, temperatures above 100 every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a rain dance or something,'' said Shelia Hill, who sat
on a bench under a shade tree outside the Bank One building in
downtown Dallas Monday, taking a cigarette break. ``I had to go buy
another air conditioner, because my old one wasn't strong enough.
Now, I just close myself off in my bedroom, and I got rid of my
kids. They're at my sister's. She's got air conditioner forever. I
wish I could bottle it and bring it home.''
</P>
<P>
   All over town, folks are doing what they can to stave off
misery. Paul Lacey and his friends do yard work in the early
morning around south Dallas, and then come home and fill up the
cooler with cold drinks. ''We've definitely been struggling,'' he
said. ''Usually we just stay in the house, but my air conditioner
doesn't work real well. Right now, it's cooler out there than it is
in here. But at least we don't have a shortage of water.''
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Fort Worth, water main breaks have prompted the
city to order water restrictions, such as not watering lawns.
</P>
<P>
   More than 94 people have died in the Texas heat wave. State
officials are trying to help those without air-conditioning or
fans, and the local energy company has a phone number set up for
people to call to get an air conditioner donated.
</P>
<P>
   But then there's that touch of Texas defiance through it all.
Some people are wondering what all the fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm doing fine,'' said Azell Cooks, who was sitting in the
shade of his porch in south Dallas. Retired, he was doing a little
carpentry, building a wooden box. ''It's all a mind-over-matter
thing. Naturally it's hot, but if you dwell on it, it will seem
hotter.''
</P>
<P>
   ''People in Dallas are used to 100-degree heat,'' said Jan
Gifford, who works in marketing at the Dallas Public Library's main
branch. ''You just learn not to go out unless you have to.'' Hill
said her last electric bill was $333. She called TU Electric.
''They said `send what you can' and not to worry about it, just to
keep my unit running,'' she said. ''I tell you, it is so cool in
that Bank One building, if I could sleep there, I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
