<HEADER>
A5299 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCLC28-COX     07-27 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCLC28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King taps church roots, celebrity donors
 &HT;    By Kimberly H. Byrd
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By kicking off the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference's 41st annual convention in the church, Martin Luther
King III is setting the tone for an organization that is striving
to rebound as a spiritually grounded powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The church is) the only thing we can build from,'' King said
Monday afternoon after a youth awards banquet at the convention's
headquarters, the Omni Shoreham Hotel. ``That is our foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, his vision for empowerment, equality and unity is
unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   His team _ old-school civil rights workers and volunteer
advisers such as Jerome Edmondson, the first black franchise owner
of a Denny's restaurant _ have tapped Hollywood celebrities to
pitch in financially and mentor youths in the name of SCLC. They
have contacted Bill Gates' office and asked the Microsoft
co-founder to help meet the SCLC's computer needs. They are
rounding up professional athletes to serve as role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it important for us to support SCLC?'' asked actor
Thomas Ford (''New York Undercover'' and ``Martin'') during
Monday's banquet. ``As long as there is oppression, as long as
there is racism, it's important that we have an SCLC.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford told the young people that their forefathers had fought
many a battle so that life would be better for them. ``Young folks,
it is time for us to do some re-defining,'' he said. ``Today is our
day. We have a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Ford turned to the adults, describing them as mirrors for
tomorrow's leaders. And that's why, he said, ``We have to love one
another honestly. We must embrace one another honestly. We must
support one another honestly.'' SCLC has been in the nation's
capital since Saturday for a five-day convention that started with
the installation of King as the fourth president. The convention
ends Wednesday after a health forum.
</P>
<P>
   SCLC was organized in 1957 by King's father and other ministers
as a direct-action, protest arm of the civil rights struggle. In
recent years, it has had trouble raising money and defining its
role.
</P>
<P>
   As SCLC works to cement its mission of equality, empowerment and
unity, some have wondered about its validity and its necessity.
</P>
<P>
   In his inaugural address Sunday night, King, 40, cleared that
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn on CNN, ABC, CBS or NBC. Turn on `Nightline' or get
on-line,'' King said. ``Until there are no longer barbaric acts
like the murder (of a black man) in Jasper, Texas, or racial
burnings in Jackson, Miss., until there is no discrimination from
Wall Street to 125th Street in Harlem, until there is no
discrimination from Beverly Hills to Compton in L.A., until there
is no discrimination in the board room and until there is equality
in the classroom, there will always be a need for the SCLC
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   In a seminar Monday afternoon, Les Brown, an author and public
speaker, urged members to clearly define the organization's
mission, assess and determine an appropriate way to meet the needs
of the community, and join hands with other organizations that have
similar goals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
