<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5300 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEAMSTERS-CAREY-905&AMP;A     07-27 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-CAREY-905&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTERS PRESIDENT IS EXPELLED BY REVIEW BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A court-appointed review board expelled Ron Carey,
the Teamsters president, from the union Monday, apparently ending
the career of a labor leader who once seemed destined to clean up
one of the United States' largest but most troubled unions.
</P>
<P>
   The review board concluded that Carey breached his fiduciary
duty by failing to stop an illegal scheme that siphoned more than
$750,000 in union funds into his 1996 re-election campaign. The
board said that there was insufficient evidence to conclude that
Carey approved or knew about the scheme, but the board chastised
him for failing to ferret out or inquire further about fraudulent
activity that was going on right in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   The decision expels for life a figure who was one of the
nation's best-known, most charismatic union leaders, a man who won
widespread public support for his leadership in the Teamsters'
three-week strike against United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   Carey was first elected president of the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters in 1991 as a Mr. Clean, vowing to
eliminate corruption in a union long known as the nation's most
corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the campaign fraud _ in which three Carey campaign
aides have pleaded guilty _ the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters donated more than $750,000 to liberal groups, and in
return, traditional donors to those groups contributed $221,000 to
the Carey campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carey had a duty to inquire into the unusual proposed
transactions, and he failed to exercise it,'' the Independent
Review Board wrote. ``A fair inference to be drawn from all the
facts is that Carey closed his eyes because he knew or suspected
that those contributions were to generate a personal benefit for
him, i.e., benefits to his campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey's lawyer, Reid Weingarten, insisted that the decision was
wrong, and vowed to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a fit of regulatory overzealousness,'' Weingarten said,
``the Independent Review Board found that Ron Carey did not have
actual knowledge of an illegal fund-raising scheme and then imposed
severe sanctions upon him solely on the basis of his failure to
prevent misconduct that he knew nothing about. Under this
reasoning, every bank president who has been unable to stop a
teller from embezzling money can be tossed out of his job and
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The review board was set up as part of a 1989 consent decree
that involved the federal government dropping a civil racketeering
suit, in which it charged that the Teamsters had a ``devil's pact''
with the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Before the board's decision takes effect, it must be confirmed
by Judge David Edelstein of U.S. District Court in New York, who
has been highly critical of Carey in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, after uncovering the campaign fraud, a federal
election monitor overturned Carey's 52-percent-to-48-percent
victory over James P. Hoffa in December 1996. In November another
monitor, Kenneth Conboy, barred Carey from running for re-election,
and days later, Carey took a leave of absence. Conboy found that
Carey had apparently approved the embezzlement scheme _ a finding
that clashes with Monday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Carey is under investigation by a federal grand jury in New
York, but several lawyers said Monday that an indictment became
less likely when the review board failed to conclude that Carey
approved or knew about the fraudulent scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Judge Frederick Lacey, the chairman of the
three-member board, issued a separate concurring decision saying
that he, unlike the two other board members, believed that Carey
knew about the scheme. Lacey relied heavily on a statement that
Carey's campaign manager, Jere Nash, had said he once made to
Carey.
</P>
<P>
   Nash had testified that he once told Carey that if the Teamsters
president approved a large donation to Citizen Action, a
progressive grass-roots group, it would ``help Martin Davis in the
fund raising that he is doing for our campaign.'' Davis was the
campaign's chief fund-raiser and handled its direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   Carey told the board under oath that he had no memory of that
conversation with Nash.
</P>
<P>
   While not finding guilty knowledge, the two other board members,
William Webster, the former head of the FBI and CIA, and Grant
Crandall, a mine workers' attorney, said they often thought Carey
was not telling the truth. They wrote that Carey ``was less than
credible'' when he denied remembering anything about close to $1
million in political contributions that the Teamsters made and that
he approved, including a $475,000 donation to Citizen Action.
</P>
<P>
   All three board members took Carey to task for a management
style in which, when on the road campaigning, he asked his
secretary for minimum details about such large contributions and
refused to return calls to senior aides who opposed such
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling, Webster and Crandall wrote, ``While the
information provided to Carey was not sufficient to establish
Carey's knowledge of the nature of the scheme, it was sufficient to
impose on Carey a fiduciary duty to inquire further about any
relation or tie between Carey's own campaign fund raising and the
IBT's payment to an advocacy group like Citizen Action.''
</P>
<P>
   With Carey barred for life from the union, Hoffa is the
front-runner in the new race for the presidency of the
1.4-million-member union. Ballots are scheduled to be mailed out in
September and counted on Oct. 14.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a statement issued Monday, Hoffa said, ``Today's Independent
Review Board decision banning Ron Carey from the Teamsters for life
is a small step toward returning honest, competent and above all
democratically elected leadership to the Teamsters.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Ron Carey will trouble our union no more, but dozens
of his political cronies continue to hold office illegitimately at
the Teamster headquarters.''
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the review board also expelled Bill Hamilton,
who had already resigned as the union's director of government
affairs, a post in which he oversaw the Teamsters' lobbying and
political donations. Hamilton has been indicted on six counts for
participating in the siphoning scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The board found that Hamilton knew about the campaign fraud and
had worked closely with Nash in implementing it, by, for example,
writing numerous memos seeking to gain speedy approval of the
political contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's lawyer, Robert Gage, said, ``Bill has done nothing
wrong and we strongly disagree with the board's decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
