u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT &LR;      07-27 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY MEETS WITH PROSECUTORS IN POSSIBLE PRELUDE TO IMMUNITY
DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN BRODER and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prosecutors met for five hours at an undisclosed
location in New York on Monday with Monica Lewinsky, the woman at
the heart of the White House sex and perjury inquiry, in a possible
prelude to an immunity deal.
</P>
<P>
   In a development fraught with danger for the president, several
lawyers from the office of Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel,
interviewed Ms. Lewinsky in New York in an effort to gauge her
credibility as a witness and secure her grand jury testimony. Starr
has insisted that his attorneys meet face to face with Ms. Lewinsky
before offering her immunity from prosecution in exchange for her
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors neared a deal with Ms. Lewinsky, the pressure on
President Clinton intensified on two other fronts on Monday as
Starr's investigation moved inexorably toward a denouement.
</P>
<P>
   A divided federal appeals court rejected the president's
invocation of lawyer-client privilege to bar the grand jury
testimony of his closest aide, Bruce Lindsey, setting the stage for
a Supreme Court confrontation or Lindsey's imminent return to the
grand jury. The court said that a president cannot hide criminal
behavior behind the shield of lawyer-client confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton's private lawyers continued their negotiations with
Starr over terms of compliance with an unprecedented presidential
subpoena. Little progress was made on Monday, according to lawyers
involved in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers with knowledge of Ms. Lewinsky's meeting with
prosecutors indicated that the session had moved the two sides
considerably closer to an agreement that would lead to Ms.
Lewinsky's grand jury testimony. In proposed testimony submitted
earlier this year, Ms. Lewinsky acknowledged having had a sexual
relationship with the president but denied that he or anyone else
had tried to persuade her to lie about it under oath. Ms. Lewinsky
repeated those assertions on Monday, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is moving quickly to secure the testimony of Ms. Lewinsky
and Clinton _ the two central parties in the matter _ at virtually
the same time as the fact-gathering phase of his investigation
nears a conclusion. Clinton's lawyers have agreements with many of
the witnesses to share information about grand jury appearances. By
taking Clinton's and Ms. Lewinsky's testimony simultaneously, Starr
may be seeking to prevent their coordinating their accounts,
according to lawyers involved in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on the president was heightened by a Tuesday
deadline to respond to a subpoena delivered last week for his
testimony in the Lewinsky matter. His lawyers continued their
negotiations with Starr to find a means to respond to prosecutors'
questions without the spectacle of a president for the first time
appearing personally before a criminal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers involved in the inquiry said that Starr would not
attempt to enforce Tuesday's deadline as long as talks were
underway with the president's lawyers. David Kendall, one of
Clinton's private attorneys, said that he was working with the
independent counsel's office ``to devise a way for the president to
provide information for the OIC's investigation, consistently with
his constitutional role and responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to the president, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said that deadline is unimportant, because both sides are seeking a
compromise. Clinton is willing to testify if the questioning is
limited to the Lewinsky matter and does not become a broad fishing
expedition into unrelated topics, the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also adamant about not being forced to appear at the
federal court house, the adviser said. The president is willing to
provide written answers to prosecutors' questions or to submit to a
videotaped session.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's testimony _ at some time and in some manner
_ is now inevitable, the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is now put in the position that if he doesn't
testify he's got to have some really overwhelming reasons, and
there are damn few of them,'' the adviser said. ``He has said in so
many words that he is prepared to cooperate under certain
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here dealt the president a
further legal setback on Monday, ruling that his conversations with
Lindsey, deputy White House counsel and a longtime confidant of the
President's, were not protected by lawyer-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The far-reaching decision, issued by a divided three-judge
panel, said ``it could be contrary to tradition, common
understanding and our governmental system'' to shield Lindsey from
appearing before a federal grand jury investigating serious
criminal charges, including witness tampering, perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an executive branch attorney is called before a federal
grand jury to give evidence about alleged crimes within the
executive branch, reason and experience, duty and tradition dictate
that the attorney shall provide that evidence,'' the court wrote.
``Their duty is not to defend clients against criminal charges and
it is not to protect wrongdoers from public exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ruff, the White House counsel, said that the president
and his legal advisers will decide whether to appeal after they
have thoroughly studied the 60-page opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``We are disappointed that the Court of Appeals
has decided that, unlike every other attorney and client in this
country, government attorneys and their clients do not enjoy the
right to have confidential communications. The practical result of
the court's decision is that the president and all other government
officials will be less likely to receive full and frank advice
about their official obligations and duties from government
attorneys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
