<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-DRUGS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IAAF SUSPENDS 2 U.S. ATHLETES FOR POSSIBLE DRUG OFFENSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., W.Va.)   (bl)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The international drug scandal in sports widened from cycling's
Tour de France to track and field Monday when the sport's world
governing body announced that two top American athletes, sprinter
Dennis Mitchell and 1996 Olympic shot put champion Randy Barnes,
had been suspended for possible doping offenses.
</P>
<P>
   However, the U.S. Track and Field Federation said it would not
enforce the suspensions, calling the allegations unproven. The
national federation also accused the world governing body of
contravening the Amateur Sports Act of 1978, which was enacted by
Congress and which entitles American athletes to due process before
they are declared ineligible to compete.
</P>
<P>
   This apparently means that Mitchell and Barnes remain eligible
to compete in the United States but not internationally. Neither
athlete returned calls Monday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, the 1992 Olympic bronze medalist at 100 meters, tested
above the acceptable 6:1 ratio of testosterone, the male sex
hormone, to epitestosterone, a related chemical, according to
Giorgio Reineri, a spokesman for the International Amateur Athletic
Federation, track and field's world-governing body. Anything above
6:1 is considered suspicious of using testosterone as a
muscle-building steroid.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, the world-record holder in the shot put, tested positive
for a prohibited substance with steroid-like qualities, Reineri
said in a telephone interview from France. The Associated Press
identified the substance as androstenedione, a banned nutritional
supplement. Because he previously was suspended for drug use,
Barnes faces a potential lifetime ban from competition, while
Mitchell's career could be suspended for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mitchell and Barnes were given random, out-of-competition
drug tests in the United States on April 1, Reineri said. The
spokesman said he believed that only the first of two samples,
called the A and B sample that each urine specimen is divided into,
had been tested for each athlete. U.S. law, however, calls for both
samples to be tested and for athletes to be given a fair hearing
before they are suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are outraged that the IAAF knowingly breached our
confidentiality rules, which were put in place to protect those
ultimately determined to be innocent,'' Craig Masback, president of
the U.S. track federation, said in a statement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The suspensions were announced on the same day that the
International Olympic Committee called for a world conference next
January to reappraise its campaign against what is believed to be
the extensive use of banned performance-enhancing substances.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's actions followed controversial remarks reportedly made
Sunday by International Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio
Samaranch, who was quoted in the Spanish newspaper El Mundo as
calling for ``drastically'' reducing the number of banned
substances. He was also quoted as saying that he did not consider
it doping if an athlete used a performance-enhancing drug that was
not believed to be harmful to that athlete's health.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch's remarks elicited pointed responses of support and
criticism Monday from the worldwide Olympic community. Steve Ovett
of Britain, the 1980 Olympic champion at 800 meters, said it
appeared that Samaranch was ready to ``throw in the towel'' on drug
testing.
</P>
<P>
   Others, such as Jaques Rogge of Belgium, a surgeon who is vice
president of the IOC medical commission, said it was difficult, if
not impossible, to differentiate between substances that are
harmful to an athlete's health and those that are not.
</P>
<P>
   Who is to say, some Olympic officials wondered, that steroids
are harmful if taken in regulated doses under careful monitoring by
a doctor? And what about substances that aren't
performance-enhancing but are considered harmful? Should they be
banned?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Olympic Committee executive director Dick Schultz noted
Samaranch's strong anti-drug stance and wondered whether he had
been accurately quoted.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Schultz said, he agreed that a review of the
IOC's drug-testing policies was necessary. There are no uniform
standards or application of drug penalties among various
Olympic-related sports.
</P>
<P>
   And a sense of frustration has grown over the inability to
develop tests for such substances as EPO, a synthetic hormone that
increases aerobic capacity and is at the center of the Tour de
France scandal, and human growth hormone, which has steroid-like
qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a morass out there that needs to be reviewed to
determine what is performance-enhancing and what is not,'' Schultz
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I don't think there's any question that the drug
gurus who are trying to beat the system are ahead of the police.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC issued a statement seeking to clarify Samaranch's
remarks. It said that he sought a ``a clear definition of doping''
at the 1999 world conference and that he had been referring to
codeine, which has been removed from the banned list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight against doping must continue in a spirit of
heightened unity,'' the IOC statement said. ``The IOC president
noted that the IOC's determination was greater than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said the USOC was also looking to host a worldwide
meeting on the drug issue in late 1999 or early 2000. Primo
Nebiolo, the president of track's world governing body, backed
Samaranch's call for a world conference in January of 1999 at IOC
headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem of doping affects the whole of the sports movement
and needs to be resolved quickly and effectively after years of
indecision and ineffectual actions,'' Nebiolo told reporters in
Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
   Nebiolo said that the drug scandal at the Tour de France
``destroys the image of one of the great symbolic sporting
events,'' and added that doping is ``harmful for the athletes and
can kill a sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Festina, the world's top cycling team, has been suspended from
the Tour de France, and a Dutch team also faces possible expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   And now U.S. track and field, already reeling from public
indifference and suspected widespread drug use, has to deal with
the international suspension of two of its most prominent stars.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is particularly embarrassing for Mitchell, 32, of
Gainesville, Fla., who is chairman of the track federation's
athletes advisory committee, which has taken a vociferous anti-drug
stance. However, the science on t/e ratio testing is murky and the
USOC questioned the efficacy of such testing last year during the
Mary Decker Slaney case. Her suspension by the IAAF was overturned
by the U.S. track federation and is now headed toward arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, 32, of Charleston, W.Va., set the world outdoor shot put
record at 75 feet, 10 1/4 inches in 1990, but was suspended in 1991
and 1992 after testing positive for the banned substance
methyl-testosterone. He returned to win a gold medal at the 1996
Summer Games in Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIPHOP-CONCERT-REVIEW     07-27 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIPHOP-CONCERT-REVIEW-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP REVIEW: HIP-HOP WITH A MESSAGE INSTEAD OF JUST A BOAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLMDEL, N.J. _ The third annual Smokin' Grooves tour, which
came to the PNC Bank Arts Center here Sunday night, might as well
have been called the Hip-Hop Holdouts tour. It assembled groups
that insist, against the commercial tide, that hip-hop isn't
exclusively about ``playas'' who brag about their wealth, their
women, their brand-name possessions and their unsavory pasts while
borrowing the melodies of pop hits.
</P>
<P>
   For three of the groups on the bill _ Public Enemy, Gang Starr
and Wyclef Jean's Refugee Camp _ hip-hop is still a way to address
social issues, using the beat to carry messages. ``It might feel
good, it might sound a little somethin'/But damn the game if it
don't mean nothing,'' Chuck D. intones in ``He Got Game,'' the
title track from Public Enemy's current album. The other
headliners, Cypress Hill and Busta Rhymes with the Flipmode Squad,
also stand outside the ``playa'' realm. Cypress Hill sticks to its
narrow obsessions with marijuana and guns, and Busta Rhymes
single-mindedly incites a party.
</P>
<P>
   For all the groups, hip-hop isn't just a star trip; it's a
display of camaraderie, an employment program and an opportunity
for empire-building. While rock groups may talk about community,
they keep their stage shows clear of nonmusicians; hip-hop groups
perform amid friends, hangers-on and affiliated talent, bringing
the neighborhood to the stage in what can look like near-chaos. The
image of block-party fraternity _ nearly all the participants were
male _ is as important as what the rappers say.
</P>
<P>
   Public Enemy, the headliners, has reunited after drug
rehabilitation for Flavor Flav, Chuck D.'s partner and the group's
comic relief. The set also had a guest rap from Professor Griff,
who had been dismissed from Public Enemy in 1989 after declaring
that Jews were responsible for ``the majority of wickedness that
goes on across the globe.'' His thankless job here was to follow
the pro-marijuana raps of Cypress Hill with the admonition, ``We
can't stay high forever.''
</P>
<P>
   With Security of the First World, its dancing drill team, Public
Enemy has long been one of hip-hop's most capable live acts; Chuck
D. strides around the stage, Flavor Flav strikes jokey poses, and
the disk jockey Terminator X oversees booming rhythm tracks. The
set depended on past glories, from the late 1980s and early '90s,
when Public Enemy articulated rage and resistance in music that
bristled with sonic irritants and language so dense it begged to be
decoded. In more recent songs Chuck D. has grown didactic, as if he
no longer trusted his listeners to make an effort to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He Got Game'' gives in to the Puff Daddy style of pop hip-hop;
the song appropriates Buffalo Springfield's ``For What It's
Worth.'' But the older material _ ``Bring the Noise,'' ``911 Is a
Joke,'' ``Fight the Power,'' ``Can't Truss It'' _ was a reminder of
how many remarkable songs Public Enemy contributed to hip-hop.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cypress Hill reunited B-Real, its lead rapper, with D.J. Muggs
and Sen Dog, and it also relied on older songs. Unfortunately its
material has grown threadbare: tales of pot smoking, paranoia and
gunplay delivered in B-Real's nagging singsong voice. Back in 1991,
Cypress Hill managed to push titillating hot buttons with songs
like ``Hand on the Pump,'' but it soon reduced them to a formula,
with diminishing returns. Two songs from the band's fourth album,
due in October, were largely unintelligible; one taunted, one
leered. B-Real had to exhort the crowd to stand up, something Busta
Rhymes never had to mention.
</P>
<P>
   Rhymes was as much a cheerleader as a rapper: bounding across
the stage, constantly touting his five-member Flipmode Squad and
getting the crowd to shout along with the party chants of songs
like ``Woo-hah!'' Gang Starr had more serious intentions; its
rapper, Guru, paid tribute to Chuck D. and preached self-respect.
Where Gang Starr's albums use a light, slightly jazz-tinged
backups, onstage Gang Starr harked back to rap's old school, with
deep, basic beats from D.J. Premier. Gang Starr also had guests,
including Freddie Foxx and MOP.
</P>
<P>
   Jean's set had diverse intentions: showing off his skills as
singer, guitarist and rapper; mixing Caribbean and American music,
and plugging his associates Pras Michel (of the Fugees), John Forte
and Canibus. True to rap's demotic ideals, Jean made his entrance
like a street-level fan: he clambered up on stage and wrestled with
a security man like a stage crasher.
</P>
<P>
   For many concertgoers, myself included, the opening acts,
Black-Eyed Peas and Mya, were sacrificed to a 75-minute wait for
what turned out to be a nonexistent security check. The Arts Center
has presented previous Smokin' Grooves shows; by now, it ought to
be better organized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
