<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OPEN TO SOCIAL SECURITY `OPTIONS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Amid many questions and no answers about
saving Social Security, President Clinton said Monday he would be
open to ``options'' such as the private investment of some of the
fund's money.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the president signaled his willingness to
consider letting Americans invest their Social Security savings in
stocks and bonds as some Republicans and moderate Democrats have
advocated.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, members of Congress and experts fielded questions from
New Mexicans at the third of four national debates on Social
Security reform. The session focused on privatization and its risks
and whether the individual or the government should control the
investments.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Clinton proposed a series of forums around the
nation to be capped by a session at the White House in December.
The forums are sponsored by the American Association of Retired
Persons, the Concord Coalition and Americans Discuss Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, Clinton will appoint a bipartisan commission
that will submit recommendations to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton expressed the same uncertainty voiced by the
majority of Americans about what should be done to save Social
Security from its expected bankruptcy in 2030.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do, the president said, ``I don't know. I
don't know what I would do, but I am open to the idea that if we
can get a higher rate of return in some fashion than we have been
getting in the past while being fair to everyone ... we ought to be
open to those options.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, Clinton's economic adviser, said the president
was signaling his willingness to explore the investment issue.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the employer and employee pay 6.2 percent each into
the Social Security fund as a payroll tax. The money is invested in
government Treasury notes and returns are guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls released this weekend show Americans favor
private investment. A USA Today poll published Monday showed
two-thirds of those surveyed supported allowing individuals to
invest their Social Security funds but 59 percent opposed giving
the government the power to make the investment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper poll also showed an overwhelming majority opposed
the traditional methods of prolonging the life of the nation's
retirement fund. It found 85 percent opposed cuts in benefits, 70
percent opposed raising the retirement age and 62 percent opposed
hiking payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The USA Today poll and an AARP survey of New Mexicans found
citizens have stronger feelings about what should not be done than
what should be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here in New Mexico, according to a new AARP survey,
hold views similar to the rest of the country: They know Social
Security is important and they know it needs real changes. Yet,
there's no consensus, in New Mexico or elsewhere, on what those
changes should be,'' said Horace Deets, AARP executive director.
</P>
<P>
   More than 44 million Americans receive Social Security benefits.
One-third of the beneficiaries, however, are not retirees but
receive benefits from spousal life insurance or disability.
</P>
<P>
   The trust fund will be unable to meet all guaranteed benefits
beginning in 2030 as the 76 million baby boomers fully enter
retirement age. The number of elderly people will double while the
number of tax-paying workers will dwindle to two people paying
payroll tax for every one person drawing benefits.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of experts also disagreed on the issue of privatization.
Some argued the risk was too great to allow individual investments
while others argued the government may be too inept to make
collective investment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Clinton joked that ``you may leave here more
confused than when you came in.''
</P>
<P>
   Several proposals have been introduced in Congress. Two
bipartisan proposals call for reducing the current 12.4 percent
Social Security payroll tax and allowing citizens to set up
individual investment accounts with the savings. It would retain
the Social Security Trust Fund as a guaranteed benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservatives have called for the complete privatization of
the trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined at the forum by Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.,
chairman of the Senate Budget Committee; Sen. Jeff Bingaman,
D-N.M.; Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz.; and Rep. Xavier Becerra, D-Calif. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
