<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GTE-BELL-ATLANTIC-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC REPORTED SET TO ACQUIRE GTE FOR $52.8 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.Y., Conn.) (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp., which dominates the local telephone
business from Maine to Virginia, has agreed to acquire GTE Corp.,
the nation's largest independent local and long-distance company,
for $52.8 billion in stock, executives close to the negotiations
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The companies plan to announce the deal and lay out the
financial details Tuesday morning, the executives said. The board
of each company approved the acquisition Monday night, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, GTE's chief executive, Charles Lee, 58,
will become chairman and co-chief executive of the merged
companies, while Bell Atlantic's chief executive, Ivan Seidenberg,
51, will become co-chief executive and president. The executives
close to the negotiations said that Seidenberg, who was scheduled
to take over from Raymond Smith as chairman of Bell Atlantic on
Jan. 1, would become sole chief executive and chairman of the
merged companies after 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will be based in New York, according to people
close to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by federal regulators, a deal between Bell Atlantic,
based in New York, and GTE, based in Stamford, Conn., would be the
latest in a torrent of multibillion-dollar mergers in the
telecommunications industry. Companies of all description are
engaged in a scramble for scale as they try to offer bundles of
voice, video and data services to customers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic's acquisition of GTE would mean little in the
short run for most of the companies' residential customers. But the
companies are likely to assert that their combined financial muscle
will allow them to accelerate the deployment of expensive
high-speed Internet services and to compete in local phone markets
dominated by other Bells.
</P>
<P>
   By acquiring GTE, Bell Atlantic would secure its place as the
nation's largest local phone company, serving more than 62 million
customers. At Bell Atlantic's current size, the pending $62 billion
combination of SBC Communications, known to many of its customers
as Pacific Bell or Southwestern Bell, and Ameritech Corp., the
Midwest's dominant phone company, threatens to push Bell Atlantic
to the No. 2 position.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts and executives say they expect the global
telecommunications market, now more than $500 billion annually, to
be dominated in a few years by a handful of international giants.
Each of the big U.S. phone companies wants to be one of them, even
if that means joining forces with a rival.
</P>
<P>
   Just last year, Bell Atlantic acquired Nynex Corp., which
provided local phone service in New York and New England, for $26
billion. With more than 21 million local telephone customers in 28
states, mainly in the Sun Belt and Midwest, GTE would greatly
expand Bell Atlantic's presence outside the Northeast and would
give it a toe-hold in the long distance and data networking
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would have about 255,000 employees. Bell
Atlantic and GTE are not expected to announce layoffs as part of
their merger announcement, although it is unlikely that all current
employees could be assured of remaining in their present jobs. One
rationale for many mergers is the savings realized by eliminating
redundant workers or transferring employees to new posts.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies will no doubt describe their deal as a merger
of equals, but in some ways it represents a downsizing of ambition
for GTE.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, GTE tried to acquire MCI Communications Corp., the
nation's No. 2 long-distance carrier, for $28 billion. But Lee,
GTE's chairman, was outmaneuvered and outbid by Bernard Ebbers,
chairman of Worldcom Inc., who won MCI with a $37 billion offer.
</P>
<P>
   A merger between Bell Atlantic and GTE would pose thorny
questions for the federal regulators who would review such a deal.
As one of the Baby Bells that emerged from AT&AMP;T Corp. in 1984, Bell
Atlantic operates under a broad range of regulatory restrictions
while GTE, an ``independent'' phone company that was never part of
AT&AMP;T, enjoys much more freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act of 1996, which aimed to open
communications markets to competition, prohibits the Bells from
selling long-distance service until they can demonstrate that they
have opened their local networks to potential competitors.
</P>
<P>
   While no Bell has yet passed that test, GTE, which is bigger
than three of the five Bells, has already been allowed to offer
long-distance services in the local markets it serves. It has
already won more than 2.2 million long-distance customers.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators will probably approve the deal but force the merged
companies to operate under the two existing sets of rules: one for
Bell Atlantic's traditional region and another for the areas where
GTE had offered service.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean that most current GTE customers would be able to
continue getting both long-distance and local phone service from
the merged companies, while current Bell Atlantic customers would
still have to use a separate long-distance company.
</P>
<P>
   A precedent for such a structure emerged earlier this year after
SBC agreed to acquire Southern New England Telecommunications
Corp., Connecticut's main local phone company, for $4.4 billion in
stock. Like GTE, SNET is allowed to sell long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department approved that deal, allowing Connecticut
customers to use SBC for long-distance service even though SBC is
not allowed to sell long-distance calls in its home region.
</P>
<P>
   One potential complication is that GTE offers combined service
in parts of some states that are currently dominated by Bell
Atlantic, including Pennsylvania and Virginia. Some of the rules
that keep the Bells out of the $80 billion long-distance market in
the United States do so on a state-by-state basis.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, federal regulators could have as many as three options:
allow Bell Atlantic to keep selling long-distance service to former
GTE customers even in Bell Atlantic's traditional states; force
GTE's current long-distance customers in Bell Atlantic states to
give up the service; or have Bell Atlantic sell the GTE properties
in its traditional states.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With the regulatory process and financial transactions, the deal
will probably take more than a year to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Another potentially troublesome regulatory issue is that GTE
owns BBN Technologies, one of the nation's biggest carriers of
Internet traffic. The same rules that prevent Bell Atlantic from
supplying long-distance services within its region also apply to
long-distance data networks.
</P>
<P>
   BBN carries Internet data all over the country, including within
Bell Atlantic's Northeastern region. Bell Atlantic has asked the
Federal Communications Commission for a regulatory waiver that
would allow the company to build a long-distance data network, but
it appears unlikely that the commission will approve the
application, mostly because advanced technology would allow Bell
Atlantic to use the data system for voice calls.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the regulatory uncertainties, the drive to
consolidate is so strong in the telecommunications industry that
GTE was also approached about a possible merger by BellSouth Corp.,
according to people close to those talks.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it appears that Bell Atlantic did not have to come up
with billions of additional dollars to woo GTE.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, GTE's shareholders will get 1.22 Bell
Atlantic shares for each GTE share. Based on Bell Atlantic's
closing price of $45 Monday, that works out to $54.90 for each
share of GTE. GTE's shares closed Monday at $55.75, down 2 3/16.
Bell Atlantic shareholders are expected to hold 57 percent of the
merged company, said a person close to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   One reason GTE was interested in doing this merger, people close
to the talks said, was because of the recent string of high-level
defections, a result of the company moving its headquarters from
Stamford to Irving, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, J. Michael Kelly, GTE's chief financial officer,
left to become America Online's chief financial officer. In April,
GTE's chief planning and development officer, Dan Cohrs, left to
join Global Crossing, an undersea cable company. And last October,
Lewis Wilks, an executive who supervised new ventures designed to
take GTE beyond its core local-phone service business, joined Qwest
Communications International, the startup long distance company.
</P>
<P>
   That, combined with GTE's loss of its MCI deal to WorldCom, and
the impending acquisition of Ameritech by SBC, put GTE in a
situation where it needed to act fast.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the talks said that intensive discussions
between the two chief executives started in late June and that they
worked out the major points of the merger themselves, with bankers
being brought in two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, these people said, Bell Atlantic's Seidenberg
said repeatedly that he did not want bankers involved in the talks
because he feared leaks. Bell Atlantic was advised by Merrill Lynch
and the Bear Stearns Cos. GTE was advised by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
