<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS PAYS TRIBUTE TO SLAIN OFFICERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to clarify Gibson being buried at Arlington; minor
editing throughout) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress on Monday opened an emotional, two-day
tribute to the police officers slain while trying to protect
lawmakers, their staffs and the public from a deranged shooter who
unleashed his violence in the marbled hallways of the U.S. Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and the Senate passed resolutions honoring
Capitol Police Detective John Gibson and Officer Jacob J. Chestnut
as heroes of the bloody Friday afternoon shootout with Russell
Weston Jr., who was charged in federal court Monday with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, who was shot at point-blank range by Gibson, remains in
serious condition at a hospital. He has been charged with the
murder of one of the federal officers, but other federal charges
are pending against him and he could face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Congress gave its approval for an extraordinary memorial service
to be held at 3 p.m., EDT, Tuesday in the Capitol Rotunda, where
the two 18-year veterans will lie in state as President Clinton,
Vice President Al Gore and others pay homage.
</P>
<P>
   Such services are usually reserved for presidents or members of
Congress. But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said it
was only fitting that the two men who paid the ultimate price while
performing their duties be honored under the center dome of the
building where they worked every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow, amid those grand statues of heroes past, we will
honor two of our own to whom heroism was simple duty,'' Lott said
during a Senate tribute to the officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those two ... this open Capitol, with wide-eyed kids
learning their nation's history, with strangers from abroad awed by
its grandeur, with Americans of all creeds and races and regions
celebrating their common faith in God and in one another, this
Capitol itself will be their enduring monument.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott called the violence that unfolded Friday ``a tragedy for
the nation.'' But for the people who work on Capitol Hill, he
likened it to ``a death in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   As Congress prepared for its special tribute Tuesday, flags
continued to fly at half-staff over federal buildings, and tourists
brought more flowers to the east steps of the Capitol in honor not
only of Chestnut and Gibson but of law-enforcement personnel across
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who serve and protect, we owe you our gratitude,''
read one card.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., also honored all the
Capitol Police in his remarks during a House tribute. ``We
sometimes take them for granted,'' he said. ``They're the salt of
the Earth. They're the reason our democracy can live.''
</P>
<P>
   In Albuquerque, N.M., to attend a forum on Social Security,
Clinton paid his respects again by asking the crowd to join in a
moment of silent prayer for the two officers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   The president spoke with Chestnut's widow by phone Sunday. He
called Gibson's widow from New Mexico on Monday to offer
condolences.
</P>
<P>
   Although speeches and tributes to Chestnut and Gibson dominated
congressional proceedings Monday, the Senate did return to
legislative business for part of the afternoon session. On the
House side, however, the chamber remained in recess through much of
the afternoon until a formal tribute in the evening was convened.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to several resolutions honoring their memories and
service, the House and Senate also authorized the federal
government to pay the costs of the officers' funerals.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, 58, was a 20-year veteran of the Air Force. He will be
buried Friday at Arlington National Cemetery with full military
honors.
</P>
<P>
   After a request from lawmakers, the Army also cleared the way
for Gibson, 42, to be buried at Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was assigned to guard House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, and is credited with firing the shots that downed Weston
while taking fire himself. DeLay said Gibson's actions prevented
Weston from shooting anyone else after he ran into DeLay's suite of
offices. Weston had shot Chestnut after rushing through a ground
floor entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``John and I went everywhere together,'' DeLay said during a
House tribute. ``He knew that someday it was likely that he'd have
to throw his body in front of me or my staff,'' DeLay continued,
his voice cracking with emotion. ``You never think it's going to
happen. But it happened on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Weston was being treated Monday at a Washington hospital for
gunshot wounds to the chest, arm and leg. His condition has
improved enough that doctors said they believe he will be able to
stand trial. But federal authorities in the capital, and in Montana
and Illinois where Gibson has lived, acknowledged that he has a
history of mental illness, a fact that could be used to prevent a
death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Weston is being represented by Washington lawyer A.J. Kramer,
who was appointed by the court. Kramer told reporters that he spoke
with his client Monday morning. He said Weston was ``not in good
shape'' physically, but he refused to comment on his mental
condition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
