<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COP-SHOT-575(2TAKE     07-27 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COP-SHOT-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CONVICT YOUTH SEIZED IN POLICE SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL COOPER 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 17-year-old ex-convict accused of shooting a police
officer was captured during an armed standoff on Staten Island
Monday morning, and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani cited the suspect's
criminal record as yet another example of why the state's parole
system needs to be overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday night shooting of Police Officer Gerard Carter, who
was in critical condition Monday in a Staten Island hospital, came
three days before the state assembly is expected to break a
legislative logjam that has prevented the passage of a law that
would sharply curtail the use of parole in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   While the mayor said that the shooting highlighted the failure
of the parole system and described the suspect, Shatiek Johnson, as
a parolee, Johnson was not, in fact, technically on parole.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was freed in April after serving two-thirds of a
three-year sentence for a manslaughter conviction in 1996. During
his imprisonment, he had been denied parole, but the authorities
were forced to let him go in April because state guidelines require
doing so when a prisoner serves two-thirds of his sentence and does
not commit major infractions in prison.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson had been an adult, he would still be in prison under
the terms of the law the legislature is considering this week,
known as Jenna's law after a young woman who was killed by a
parolee. ``Jenna's law'' would not have applied to Johnson,
however, because he was tried and convicted as a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after his conditional release _ in which he was still
under parole supervision, while technically not on parole _ Johnson
was arrested for fare-beating in Times Square. On July 16, the
police said, they believe Johnson was involved in the shooting
death of a 20-year-old man at another Staten Island housing
project.
</P>
<P>
   It was against that backdrop at 9:30 p.m. Sunday that he
encountered Carter _ a 28-year-old father of one with five years on
the force. Carter was on patrol in the West Brighton Houses,
looking for Johnson to question him in the July 16 killing.
</P>
<P>
   When Carter and his partner, Officer Eric Storch, spotted
Johnson from their marked police van, they thought they recognized
him from a wanted poster, the police said. They drove around the
corner, looked at his picture and returned to the courtyard where
they had spotted him, the police said. Without a word being
exchanged, the young man walked up to the windshield, pulled out a
gun and fired, striking the officer in the head, police officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Storch returned fire, but did not hit the assailant, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who has long pushed for the abolition of parole, used
the case to assail the system and questioned why Johnson was not
taken back into custody in June when he was arrested for
fare-beating in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason,'' he said, ``even though he was on parole for
manslaughter and he indicated within two months of being released
on parole that he was still totally disrespectful of the laws, he
was not violated on parole.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Grant, a spokesman for the division of parole, said that a
fare-beating charge by itself was not considered sufficiently
serious to require sending Johnson back to prison. Nonetheless,
after the fare-beating arrest, the division issued a warrant for
Johnson's arrest after he stopped seeing his parole supervisor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Johnson was taken into custody Monday morning after a night in
which the police cast a massive dragnet throughout Staten Island.
Helicopters hovered overhead, dogs searched shrubbery, police vans
blocked off streets, officers stopped young men in the streets and
others combed the West Brighton Houses, where the shooting took
place.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of officers also went through the area acting on old
arrest warrants in the hopes of culling information about Johnson's
whereabouts. They even went to people not known to have any
connection with Johnson in the hopes that someone would know
something. This tactic led to his capture.
</P>
<P>
   A team of officers with the Emergency Services Unit, an elite
squad that performs rescues and executes search warrants, went to
apartment 2A at 820 Henderson Ave. at 3:30 a.m. to serve an
outstanding warrant on a man found guilty of driving with a
suspended license. When the officers arrived, the man was out and
two young women said they were there alone, but the officers saw
Johnson in a back room.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Christopher DeLevan, carrying a bulletproof shield,
walked into the back room with Officer Steve Blihar. At that point,
the police said, Johnson drew a .45-caliber handgun and pointed it
at the officers, but one of the women who lives in the apartment
was in the line of fire, so the officers did not shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Blihar spun his partner to the side, so that the shield
covered them, and they charged Johnson, forcing him into a closet.
</P>
<P>
   For hours, they tried to talk Johnson out of the closet. Sgt.
Jack Cambria acted as the negotiator, trying to coax the suspect
out with promises of cigarettes and water. At 5:30 a.m. they struck
a deal: they would open the door and Johnson would walk out
backward with his empty hands raised.
</P>
<P>
   When they opened the door, the police said, Johnson was facing
the officers with a gun in his hand and pulled the trigger, but the
weapon did not fire. The officers again held their fire, pushing
Johnson back into the closet with their bulletproof shields. They
later found that Johnson had apparently dropped his ammunition clip
before firing.
</P>
<P>
   First Deputy Commissioner Patrick E. Keller _ who is commanding
the Police Department in the absence of Commissioner Howard Safir,
who is on vacation _ praised the officers for their bravery and
their restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twice they had a gun pointed at them which was believed to be
fully loaded and they held their fire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the officers cut a hole in the bottom of the closet
door and convinced Johnson to pass his gun out. He complied, and
was arrested at 8:30 a.m. The occupants of the apartment _ Tara
Hall, 17, and Tasha Hall, 20 _ were arrested on charges of aiding a
fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was arrested on charges of attempted murder and assault
for the shooting of Gerard and on charges of first-degree murder in
the death of Eric Trotman, the man who shot at a nearby project on
July 16.
</P>
<P>
   Political pronouncements followed fast on the heels of the
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   It came as the Democratic-led state assembly prepared to return
to Albany Wednesday for a one-day special session in which they
plan to pass Jenna's law, the bill supported by Gov. George Pataki
that would eliminate parole for first-rime felony offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Senate passed the measure in May, and
Pataki has said he would sign the bill into law. Among other
things, the bill would require inmates to serve 85 percent of their
maximum sentence, up from the 66 percent they are currently
required to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that the shooting of Gerard showed that the state
should go further in ending parole. ``It never should have
happened,'' he said, ``because a long time ago we should have done
away with parole for all offenses, not the kind of watered-down
version the state Legislature is now talking about, and for
juveniles.''
</P>
<P>
   And Pataki issued a statement saying that the case illustrated
the need for the legislature to pass another bill he is pushing,
the Juvenile Justice Reform Act, which, he said, ``was designed to
prevent such outrageously lenient sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's earlier conviction for manslaughter stemmed from an
incident on March 25, 1996, when he was 15. Johnson and an
accomplice, Kinte Carter, who was then 17, were convicted of
beating a 38-year-old homeless man to death after a dispute over
$10, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The beating took place outside Papa Joe's Liquors, in the same
West Brighton neighborhood where Johnson lived and where Carter was
shot. Johnson and Carter got into a fight with the homeless man,
Richard Martin, and beat him severely.
</P>
<P>
   Martin died the next day, and his death was initially attributed
to natural causes. A week and a half later, when the results of an
autopsy showed that his spleen had been ruptured and his ribs
fractured, the police began an investigation. They arrested the two
youths and both were indicted on manslaughter charges.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson pleaded guilty to first-degree manslaughter _ the most
serious charge against him _ and was given a one- to three-year
sentence, which he served at the Harmen Valley Secure Center, a
youth facility. Carter, who was viewed as the aggressor, was
sentenced to two to six years.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson came up for parole on Feb. 19, 1997, the board
turned him down, writing: ``It is the opinion of the board that
your release is incompatible with the interest of society. The
severity of your offense, manslaughter one, in which you and your
codefendant beat your victim to death, militates against your
discretionary release.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 10, 1998, when he served two-thirds of his sentence, he
was freed, as is mandated by law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
