<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-NUKE-430&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-27 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-NUKE-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ MAY HAVE ABILITY TO MAKE NUCLEAR WEAPONS, AGENCY REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE and JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven years after Iraq pledged to dismantle its nuclear weapons
program, international inspectors still suspect that Iraq may be
hiding the documents, equipment, and material needed to make an
atomic weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The International Atomic Energy Agency, in a report Monday to
the United Nations Security Council, said that it has found no
evidence that Iraq has nuclear weapons. But the agency said that
Iraq's failure to account for key nuclear equipment and technical
blueprints leaves open the possibility that it has hidden the
necessary expertise and material for future use.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and foreign intelligence officials have also become
increasingly concerned about Baghdad's nuclear capabilities,
including the inability of inspectors to confirm that Iraq
destroyed a furnace that can melt uranium into the spheres forming
the core of a nuclear bomb. Iraq maintains that it has destroyed
the furnace, but a foreign intelligence official said the
international inspectors were pressing Iraq to document that
assertion during their latest mission, which ended July 3.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, the United Nations' nuclear monitoring arm, must
tell the Security Council that it is satisfied with Iraq's
disclosures about its nuclear program as a condition of lifting
sanctions imposed after Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official said that he did not believe Iraq has a ``bomb
in the closet.'' But he said he was disturbed by the inspectors'
inability to get answers about Iraq's nuclear expertise and offers
of assistance from countries with sophisticated nuclear energy
programs.
</P>
<P>
   In their report, the international inspectors criticized Iraq
for its lack of full transparency about the secret nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed it is prudent to assume that Iraq has retained
documentation of its clandestine nuclear program, specimens of
important components, and possibly amounts of non-enriched
uranium,'' the agency said in its report.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said that ``there remains in Iraq a considerable
intellectual resource in the form of the cadre of well-educated,
highly experienced personnel who were employed in Iraq's
clandestine nuclear program.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is likely to create problems for those members of the
Security Council who were expecting to begin lifting the sanctions
step by step. An embargo on Iraq oil sales will be lifted only when
inspectors certify that Baghdad has fully dismantled its nuclear,
biological and chemical weapons programs and long-range missile
systems. Iraq hoped its nuclear program would the first to pass
that test.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The report said they agency would continue to look into reports
that Iraq received an offer of assistance from a foreign nuclear
expert. This appears to be a reference to A.Q. Kahn, the father of
Pakistan's nuclear program, who has denied he offered any such
help.
</P>
<P>
   It also criticizes Iraq for not providing the agency with
drawings of a weapon design, experimental test data, and other
documents related to its nuclear program, and in particular, its
use of centrifuges to produce weapons grade uranium and what is
called a vacuum induction furnace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq did have a program to be able to make these furnaces
indigenously,'' said David Albright, president of the independent
Institute for Science and International Security. ``This is an
essential component in making a bomb,'' he added, ``but of equal
concern is Iraq's unwillingness to give the inspectors unfettered
access to the Iraqi nuclear experts.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Albright, a leading private expert on the Iraqi nuclear
program, said he was ``disappointed'' with the latest agency
report. Albright, who has been critical of the agency in the past,
said: ``Iraq still refuses to provide a lot of information about
how close it came to developing nuclear weapons. So the report
doesn't raise the alarm sufficiently about Iraq's nuclear
capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, agreed, but said he was pleased that the report did
not appear to endorse the desire of some members of the Security
Council to hear that Iraq has answered the major outstanding
questions about its program. Therefore, the official added, it will
be hard for the Security Council to give Iraq a clean bill of
health and close the nuclear file when it considers the report this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The agency action team responsible for inspecting Iraq visited
Iraq most recently between June 29th and July 3. It was led by Gary
Dillon, a British citizen and longtime agency official who is
expected to brief the Security Council on his trip Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If the Security Council decides during its next sanctions review
in October that Iraqi inspections can move to long-term monitoring
from hands-on disarmament and destruction of material, the report
said, a range of intrusive inspection techniques will have to be
used. These include unannounced inspections of any site, aerial
surveillance photography and an almost total environmental
monitoring of air, water, soil and vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   Spelling out these measures now may in part be intended to meet
concerns of independent arms control experts who charge that the
agency has not in the past been rigorous enough in Iraq and cannot
be counted on to be as intrusive in the future as the U.N. Special
Commission, which is inspecting and destroying biological and
chemical weapons systems and missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq, however, is already quibbling over the terms of long-term
monitoring, the report reveals.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis will not allow the agency planes to use the Rashid
air base near Baghdad, where the inspectors have their
headquarters. The inspectors will have to continue to use the
Habanniya base, an isolated wreck of a military installation more
than an hour's drive from the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Iraqis told agency representatives this month,
that if there will be a comprehensive environmental detection
program, the intrusive inspections should be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis also demanded access to raw data collected in
surveillance, ``in particular the data collected through aerial
radiation surveys,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's hopes that not only the nuclear file but also inspection
programs for biological, chemical and missile system might be
shifted to a new level this year seem to be dimming on all fronts.
Richard Butler, executive chairman of the Special Commission, will
go to Iraq this weekend to gauge Iraqi progress in non-nuclear
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The finding of the nerve gas VX by American weapons experts
examining missile shell fragments recently raises challenges to
Iraqi declarations that the gas had never been ``weaponized'' or
stored in a stable form.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq is also refusing to give Butler documents and other
material on an extensive biological program.
</P>
<P>
   In almost all these areas, including nuclear weapons. Iraq
denied the existence of anything more than research work until
President Saddam Hussein's son-in-law, Hussein Kamal, director of
the arms programs, defected to Jordan in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Iraq _ which claimed to find mountains of
incriminating documents in a chicken farm belonging to Kamal _ has
blamed him for concealing the programs.
</P>
<P>
   Kamal was killed when he went back to Iraq several months later,
apparently persuaded that he would be forgiven by the regime. Some
experts have suggested that his flight was staged. Others believe
that Kamal expected to start a new life abroad, apparently with a
great deal of Iraq's budget and his father-in-law's money, but was
disappointed when he sank into oblivion in Amman, and made a fatal
decision to chance a return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
