<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TESTIFY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY CASE CLOSES IN ON CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica S. Lewinsky, the former White House intern,
ended six months of silence Monday and met with prosecutors for
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, in a move that may foreshadow
a grand jury showdown between Lewinsky and President Clinton as the
investigation into their relationship seems near its end.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's meeting came on the same day that Clinton's defense
was dealt yet another severe setback. The U.S. Court of Appeals
ruled late Monday afternoon that Clinton's closest confidant, White
House deputy counsel Bruce Lindsey, is not protected by
attorney-client privilege and must honor a subpoena to testify
before a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton and his lawyers, the options grow scarcer by the
day. Lewinsky's meeting with prosecutors marked the first time
since January that Lewinsky, accompanied by her newly hired legal
team, talked personally and directly to the prosecutors who will
decide her legal fate. To that end, it also signaled a possible
breakthrough in Starr's efforts to either grant her immunity or
seek her criminal indictment. By Monday night, no decision was
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Lewinsky's meeting with prosecutors was
particularly notable, coming just days after it became publicly
known that Clinton has been subpoenaed by Starr to appear before
the grand jury. Under the terms of the subpoena, Clinton would be
expected to appear for testimony Tuesday, but aides said that will
not happen as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Lewinsky have denied under oath that they
engaged in a sexual relationship with each other. But Lewinsky was
captured on hours of secret tape recordings discussing sexual
encounters with the president. Starr is specifically investigating
whether Clinton committed perjury in his denial and whether he
pressured Lewinsky to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day Monday, Clinton's personal attorney, David
Kendall, negotiated with Starr's office over the guidelines and
venue for any presidential. Meanwhile, White House officials and
lawyers continued to indicate that Clinton would fight the subpoena
before the Supreme Court rather than appear in person before the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton insisted that any testimony
be videotaped at the White House, with his lawyer present, and
shown later to the grand jurors. Witnesses usually answer
prosecutors' questions in front of the grand jury with no lawyer
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working with the Office of Independent Counsel as we
have in the past to devise a way for the president to provide
information for the OIC's investigation consistent with his
constitutional role and responsibility,'' Kendall said in a
statement Monday. It was his first public acknowledgement that
negotiations were under way over whether and how the president may
comply with the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of a presidential subpoena is a controversial and
murky one. Never in the nation's history has a president been
subpoenaed to testify before a grand jury in a criminal case, and
constitutional scholars are split on the legality of such a step.
In 1974, President Nixon was ordered by the Supreme Court to turn
over his White House tapes, but his own testimony was never
compelled.
</P>
<P>
   On the Lindsey decision, three appellate judges _ two of them
Clinton appointees _ issued the highly anticipated ruling that
could bring Lindsey, Clinton's closest adviser on the thorniest of
legal, personal and political issues, before the grand jury in the
coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``A government attorney may not invoke the attorney-client
privilege in response to grand jury questions seeking information
relating to the possible commission of a federal crime,'' the
ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus, Lindsay's advice on political, strategic or policy
issues, valuable as it may have been, would not be shielded from
disclosure by the attorney-client privilege,'' the judges said.
</P>
<P>
   The judges also noted that it is the duty of government lawyers
``to defend clients against criminal charges and it is not to
protect wrongdoers from public exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Monday they were reviewing the ruling
and contemplating an appeal to either the full panel of appellate
judges or the Supreme Court. The last time the White House appealed
an appellate ruling, on the order that Secret Service agents were
compelled to testify, the administration immediately lost its bid
for relief before any higher court.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials also complained that Monday's Court of
Appeals ruling could have long-term implications, chilling the
relationships between public officials and their government legal
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed that the Court of Appeals has decided
that, unlike every other attorney and client in this country,
government attorneys and their clients do not enjoy the right to
have confidential communications,'' said Charles F.C. Ruff, the
White House legal counsel, in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government officials and lawyers need to have frank and candid
conversations,'' Ruff said. ``The attorney-client privilege serves
the public interest by fostering fully informed and more accurate
decision-making because officials are more likely to seek legal
advice and attorneys to provide that advice. Without the privilege,
frank and candid exchange of information and advice will be
chilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's meeting with prosecutors, held at an undisclosed
location outside of Washington, seemed indicative of a dramatic
shift in legal strategy by either Starr or Lewinsky or both of
them. When William Ginsburg of Los Angeles worked as Lewinsky's
lawyer, he refused to have his client talk directly to Starr's
prosecutors until she was given full immunity. The two sides
haggled over an immunity deal that was never reached and their
relationship deteriorated into an angry, silent stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, widespread press reports indicated that Lewinsky, in
a written proffer, had agreed to testify before the grand jury that
she and Clinton had a sexual relationship. But she declined to
testify to the potentially more serious allegation, that Clinton
had pressured her to lie about the affair under oath.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Lewinsky fired Ginsburg and hired two prominent
Washington criminal defense attorneys, Plato Cacheris and Jacob
Stein, each of whom have personal ties to Starr or to lawyers in
his office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr now founds himself with three options in his dealing with
Lewinksy: indict her for perjury in hopes that she will become more
cooperative in the face of criminal charges; grant her sweeping
immunity if she will detail her relationship with Clinton; or
subpoena her before the grand jury under a more restricted form of
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   With Washington engulfed in speculation about the legal
manueverings of the Starr investigation, Clinton went about his
presidential business. Monday he attended a forum on Social
Security in Albuquerque. He is planning to speak at the memorial
service Tueday afternoon for John Gibson and Jacob Chestnut, the
two Capitol Police officers slain in Friday's rampage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
