<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATORS IN GM STRIKE PRESS ON AS ARBITRATION NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER with NICHOLE CHRISTIAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Negotiators, seeking to resolve strikes at two
General Motors parts factories here, continued to put in long hours
Monday, as union officials, in particular, had an incentive to
settle before an arbitration ruling on the strikes' legality that
could come as soon as Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Talks continued at both struck factories, at a suburban Flint
hotel and at three other factories where the United Automobile
Workers union has also threatened strikes. People involved in the
bargaining said that an overall agreement was close, but cautioned
that it was impossible to predict when the last details would be
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes here have forced GM to close most of its North
American factories and lay off close to 200,000 workers. But
Monday, using replacement parts from outside suppliers GM reopened
two of its 29 assembly plants, a sport utility vehicle factory in
Silao, Mexico, and a Chevrolet Corvette factory in Bowling Green,
Ky.
</P>
<P>
   UAW officials criticized these moves and warned that workers in
Bowling Green might not cooperate. But Billy Jackson, the president
of the UAW local in Bowling Green, said that only one worker there
was involved in the installation of replacement parts _ gas pedals
that would normally come from a struck factory here and are now
being purchased from another company. The worker did not reject the
parts because GM could try to dismiss him in retaliation, Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The current round of negotiations here picked up speed rather
suddenly on Saturday evening, at the end of four days of legal
arguments before an arbitrator, Thomas Roberts. A person briefed on
the arbitration said the UAW had filed several procedural motions
on Saturday, mainly seeking more time to respond to the
documentation that GM's lawyers had presented. Roberts turned down
all the motions and indicated that he would rule as soon as
Wednesday, said the person, who insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The UAW has little to gain from a ruling and much to lose, and
has been eager for a settlement since Saturday evening. A
settlement before Wednesday would be likely to include GM's
withdrawal of the grievance in arbitration, which would forestall a
precedent-setting ruling on the strikes' legality.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW's national contract with GM, which runs through
September 1999, allows local strikes only over increases in
assembly line speed, subcontracting disputes and health and safety
issues. The UAW has cited all these issues here, and has also
demanded that GM invest more money here and guarantee that jobs be
preserved. Those are the same demands that the union has made in
more than a dozen other local strikes over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   A battalion of outside labor lawyers hired by GM argued before
the arbitrator last week that the UAW was really emphasizing only
the investment issues and was therefore in violation of the
national agreement. The UAW denied this. But if the union loses the
arbitration, it would face a pending federal lawsuit in which GM
has demanded that workers be forced to return to their jobs. GM,
having suffered heavy losses during the strike, has also sought to
have financial penalties imposed on the union, but labor lawyers
give it little chance of collecting damages.
</P>
<P>
   Wary of settling the strikes here only to face walkouts
elsewhere, GM is demanding that the UAW reach agreements at as many
factories as possible, and not just at the two struck here. The
other three factories where intensive bargaining is under way are
parts factories in Indianapolis and Dayton, Ohio, and a car
assembly plant here. The UAW had tried to keep threats of local
strikes alive to discourage GM from trying to sell or close the
factories.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Lobaccaro, an auto analyst at Merrill Lynch, estimated
that the strike had already cost GM at least $3.2 billion in
after-tax losses in the second and third quarters. But he added
that GM might be able to shave the final loss to $1.8 billion if it
settled now and ran a lot of overtime in its factories to refill
its dealerships quickly.
</P>
<P>
   GM executives have been hinting that they might stop production
of some money-losing models after the strikes, reduce the work
force more rapidly through attrition and perhaps close or sell a
few small factories. But such actions might have been inevitable
regardless of the strikes, and the potential gains of up to $500
million cannot fairly be offset against the cost of the strike,
Lobaccaro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea this restructuring has something to do with the
strike is just giving Wall Street something to chew on as it looks
at the bill'' for the strike, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While UAW leaders are eager for an end to the strike, and while
GM executives would like to stem the company's losses, many
strikers are less enthusiastic about returning to work soon after
nearly two months of showing up only once a week for two-hour
stints on the picket lines. With cool, crisp weather here, many of
the strikers have been taking summer vacations, after five years of
working six or seven days a week to keep up with an unusually
strong auto market. While the workers' strike benefits are only
$150 a week, most have ample savings from their years of extensive
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a couple more weeks as long as this weather holds
out,'' said Jeff Irish, a 43-year-old heavy equipment repairman,
who has spent much of the last two months camping and sailing but
was in Flint on Monday morning picketing an auto body parts
factory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
