<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5347 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GTE-BELL-ATLANTIC-ART     07-27 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GTE-BELL-ATLANTIC-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: traditional states. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the regulatory process and financial transactions, the deal
will probably take more than a year to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Another potentially troublesome regulatory issue is that GTE
owns BBN Technologies, one of the nation's biggest carriers of
Internet traffic. The same rules that prevent Bell Atlantic from
supplying long-distance services within its region also apply to
long-distance data networks.
</P>
<P>
   BBN carries Internet data all over the country, including within
Bell Atlantic's Northeastern region. Bell Atlantic has asked the
Federal Communications Commission for a regulatory waiver that
would allow the company to build a long-distance data network, but
it appears unlikely that the commission will approve the
application, mostly because advanced technology would allow Bell
Atlantic to use the data system for voice calls.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the regulatory uncertainties, the drive to
consolidate is so strong in the telecommunications industry that
GTE was also approached about a possible merger by BellSouth Corp.,
according to people close to those talks.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it appears that Bell Atlantic did not have to come up
with billions of additional dollars to woo GTE.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, GTE's shareholders will get 1.22 Bell
Atlantic shares for each GTE share. Based on Bell Atlantic's
closing price of $45 Monday, that works out to $54.90 for each
share of GTE. GTE's shares closed Monday at $55.75, down 2 3/16.
Bell Atlantic shareholders are expected to hold 57 percent of the
merged company, said a person close to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   One reason GTE was interested in doing this merger, people close
to the talks said, was because of the recent string of high-level
defections, a result of the company moving its headquarters from
Stamford to Irving, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, J. Michael Kelly, GTE's chief financial officer,
left to become America Online's chief financial officer. In April,
GTE's chief planning and development officer, Dan Cohrs, left to
join Global Crossing, an undersea cable company. And last October,
Lewis Wilks, an executive who supervised new ventures designed to
take GTE beyond its core local-phone service business, joined Qwest
Communications International, the startup long distance company.
</P>
<P>
   That, combined with GTE's loss of its MCI deal to WorldCom, and
the impending acquisition of Ameritech by SBC, put GTE in a
situation where it needed to act fast.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the talks said that intensive discussions
between the two chief executives started in late June and that they
worked out the major points of the merger themselves, with bankers
being brought in two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, these people said, Bell Atlantic's Seidenberg
said repeatedly that he did not want bankers involved in the talks
because he feared leaks. Bell Atlantic was advised by Merrill Lynch
and the Bear Stearns Cos. GTE was advised by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
