<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5348 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISON-COX     07-27 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio governor seeks to close private prison after six escape
 &HT;    By Tim Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Gov. George Voinovich wants to close the only
private prison in Ohio in the wake of a weekend escape that saw six
dangerous criminals slip through one fence, over another and make
their way into the city of Youngstown.
</P>
<P>
   In a strongly worded letter to state Attorney General Betty
Montgomery, Voinovich called the incident ``a very serious matter
impacting the health and safety of citizens in Youngstown and the
surrounding areas.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked Montgomery's office to research what can be done to
shut down the Northeast Ohio Correctional Center. The
medium-security prison is operated by the Nashville-based
Corrections Corp. of America to take prisoners from Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate officials did not return calls Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday afternoon, five of the six inmates were back in
custody. A massive search was continuing for the remaining escapee.
</P>
<P>
   The escape _ coming on the heels of two inmate murders, 13
stabbings and reports of violence against staff since the prison
opened in May 1997 _ intensified the already sharp political debate
in the capitol about the privatization of public services.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats seeking statewide office and those who make up the
minority in the General Assembly sharply criticized Republicans who
have pushed for privatization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privatization simply does not work and Ohio should put an end
to putting profits before public safety,'' said Lee Fisher, the
Democratic candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Buerck, press secretary for Republican gubernatorial
candidate Bob Taft, said Taft agrees with Voinovich's decision. He
added, ``We should not rule out private prisons, but should
determine if this is a problem with one company or with the
concept.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Rhine McLin, D-Dayton, chairwoman of the Correctional
Institution Inspection Committee, also applauded Voinovich's move
to try to close the prison, but said if that proves difficult due
to legalities, other steps must be taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``This prison operates under a contract between the city of
Youngstown and Washington, D.C., so there may be legal concerns
that may take some time to resolve,'' McLin said. ``But we can
immediately increase the rules and regulations, and we should do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The prison was built by CCA to handle the overflow from public
prisons in the nation's capitol. It houses about 1,500 inmates.
</P>
<P>
   McLin said she may convene her committee as soon as next
Tuesday. She and other members of the committee tried to tour the
prison in April after continued reports of violence, but were
stopped at the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps if CCA had been more cooperative in working with us
and other local and state officials, they could have avoided these
very serious problems,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items McLin wants to discuss is increased staff
training, tighter security and perhaps having the state take over
the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now you have a situation where the experience of the
inmates is much greater than the experience of the staff and that
poses a very serious problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly did approve a bill in March increasing some
of the regulations on the CCA prison and requiring that the company
pay the costs for any unusual incidents, such as the weekend
breakout.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the anger expressed by government officials centered on
CCA's apparent violation of past promises and difficulty in
reaching company officials following the escape.
</P>
<P>
   The operation is classified as a medium security prison and the
company is under a federal court order to remove prisoners
classified as more dangerous. Four of the six escapees were
convicted murderers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This prison has had a disturbing history of problems including
being dishonest wZh the mayor of Youngstown and other local
officials and apparently violating a federal court order,'' said
Mike Dawson, Voinovich's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Davey, communications director for Attorney General
Montgomery, said the office is considering ways to get ``legally
involved in this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are united (with the governor) in our displeasure with
what's gone on at the private prison, and the office will take a
hard look at the concept of private prisons,'' Davey said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Montgomery had not actively supported legislative
attempts to tighten regulations on the prison, he said Montgomery
has a ``great respect for the legislative process'' and wanted to
let it work its course. But, he added, ``when the experiment in
northeast Ohio clearly has gone awry and the public is at danger,
it becomes clearly appropriate for the attorney general to adopt a
more aggressive role.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fought, press secretary for Democrat Mary Boyle, who is
opposing Voinovich for a U.S. Senate seat in November, said the
administration is acting correctly, but too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sen. Rhine McLin was denied access to the prison, that
should have been a red flag that something was terribly amiss,''
Fought said. ``But nobody in the Voinovich administration was
listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Wray, communications director for the Ohio Civil Service
Employees Union, which represents most of the employees as Ohio's
public prisons, said the problems in Youngstown should force the
state to halt plans for its own private prisons in northern Ohio,
near Grafton and Conneaut. Those facilities will hold Ohio
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should shut the process down now,'' Wray said. ``Making
money first and security second is a very bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Miller writes for the Dayton Daily News from the Columbus,
Ohio bureau. Daily News staff writer Tom Beyerlein contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
