<HEADER>
A5349 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISON-SIDE-COX     07-27 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prison privitization started out as good idea, ended up being
nightmare
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It seemed like a great deal at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Youngstown would sell a decrepit old manufacturing site on 100
acres of land to Corrections Corp. of America for $1 and give the
Nashville-based company a 10-year, 75 percent property tax
abatement worth more than $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, CCA would build a privately run prison on the
former brownfield site and provide 350 good-paying jobs and an
annual payroll of $20 million to the economically distressed city.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal quickly went sour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost immediately, there were reports of assaults in the
facility and our guys _ the police _ couldn't get in there to
investigate,'' Youngstown Law Director Robert Bush Jr. said Monday.
There have been at least 13 stabbings, including two homicides,
since the Northeast Ohio Correctional Center opened in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since its inception, we've had nothing but problems, from the
assaults to the stabbings to the homicides,'' said Mayor George
McKelvey. ``Now the straw that definitely broke the camel's back is
the escape of six prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   The six inmates from Washington, D.C. _ four of them serving
time for homicide _ escaped Saturday. All but one had been rounded
up by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said they will ask a federal judge this week to
order a ban on new prisoners, the continued lockdown of existing
prisoners, reclassification of all inmates' security levels and
removal of any inmates classified above medium-security.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Youngstown school board on Wednesday plans to ask
the city council to invalidate the tax abatement on the grounds
that CCA defaulted on its contract with the city by housing more
than 1,500 inmates and by accepting maximum-security inmates at the
medium-security prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``My phrase is, 'Don't tax my little house, tax the Big
House,''' said attorney Martin Hughes III, who is representing the
school board.
</P>
<P>
   CCA officials didn't return phone calls. But in a Monday news
release on another matter, the company said it is the industry
leader in private prisons with 64,946 beds in 79 facilities in the
U.S. and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report, CCA said it operates in 19 states and the
District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, the United Kingdom and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, company officials said they expect strong growth
in prison privatization. The company's net income grew from $5.6
million in 1993 to $53.9 million in 1997, according to the annual
report.
</P>
<P>
   Most CCA facilities were built and are owned by government
entities and are operated by CCA under contract. But the Youngstown
prison, Ohio's only private prison, was built by CCA to house
inmates from Washington, D.C. According to the report, the capacity
is 2,016, although there was a 1,500-inmate limit in the tax
abatement agreement.
</P>
<P>
   McKelvey said CCA officials told him in January there were no
maximum-security inmates at the prison, but ``in June or July, they
'discovered' 166 of them and moved them out. I call that a
credibility gap as wide as the Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   Prison inmates have a lawsuit against CCA pending in federal
court, raising concerns about safety and health care. The city of
Youngstown joined the inmates in asking U.S. District Judge Sam
Bell of Akron to order reclassification of the inmates' security
levels. Bell ordered the reclassification, and city officials said
CCA removed more than 160 inmates to other states.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D.C., officials have acknowledged that the
Youngstown prison had received some of D.C.'s most incorrigible
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two days before the escape, (CCA officials) sent a letter to
Judge Bell saying they got the last maximum-security inmates out of
there,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose classification book classifies (the killers who escaped)
as medium security?'' McKelvey said. ``It's a travesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
