<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP-     07-27 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT'S FATHER APOLOGIZES FOR CAPITOL SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the nation preparing to pay extraordinary
tribute on Tuesday in the Capitol's Great Rotunda to the two police
officers killed on Friday in a House corridor shootout, the father
of the suspect expressed his sorrow for the violent rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize to the nation for the grief and the trauma that he
has caused,'' an agonized Russell Weston Sr., the father of the
suspect, Russell Weston Jr., said in a television interview. ``I'm
so sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Weston, 66, said he had ``always had to walk a tight
line'' with his son, in whom paranoid schizophrenia had been
diagnosed. The father said that he had wanted to try to control his
son but that he also had compassion for him because of his internal
torment.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old son, known as Rusty, lies sedated and
ankle-cuffed to his bed in D.C. General Hospital, where he is
recovering from gunshot wounds he received, officials say, after he
blasted his way into the Capitol, leaving the two police officers
dead in a shootout after they tried to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged in federal court Monday with murder (the federal
courts were not open over the weekend), but no hearing date was
set, because of uncertainty over his physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   There is also some question about Rusty Weston's current
lucidity. His lawyer, A.J. Kramer, the chief public defender in the
District of Columbia, who was appointed Monday by the court, said
he and an associate had met with Weston for 45 minutes. But the
lawyer declined to provide any details about their conversation
other than to acknowledge that it was a dialogue and that Weston
was shackled to the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials said that Weston understood he was a prisoner
and that he was being medicated to calm him. They said he remained
in danger of heart problems and blood clots, and they credited Sen.
Bill Frist of Tennessee, who is a heart surgeon, with saving his
life. Frist treated Weston at the scene on Friday and rode with him
to the hospital in an ambulance, pumping air into his lungs and
applying pressure to his thigh to stop the flow of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Frist said Monday that he was unaware at the time that Weston
was the suspect. ``I didn't think about it until we were
three-quarters over on the ambulance ride,'' he told reporters.
``Again, from a physician's standpoint, you are not a judge, you
are not a jury, you are a physician.''
</P>
<P>
   The aftershocks of Weston's shooting rampage were evident
everywhere on Capitol Hill Monday as members of Congress and their
staffs returned to the building for the first time since they were
evacuated on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Many wore black ribbons pinned to their lapels and laid bouquets
of flowers on the steps leading up to the Great Rotunda, where the
bodies of the two officers, Detective John Gibson, 42, and Officer
Jacob Chestnut, 58, of the Capitol Police, will lie in flag-draped
coffins on Tuesday for a special memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is calling the service a ``congressional tribute'' to
distinguish it from the 27 times in the nation's history that the
bodies of national leaders have lain in state in the Rotunda. The
tradition began in 1852 to honor Henry Clay, the former speaker of
the House, and was upheld most recently in 1989 to honor Rep.
Claude Pepper of Florida.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The makeshift shrine on the steps has accumulated flowers, flags
and notes, a copy of the Policeman's Prayer to St. Michael (``When
we lay down our night sticks, enroll us in your Heavenly Force''),
and a boom box that played Verdi's ``Requiem.'' Propped up in the
middle was the life-size figure of Jesus with two toy lambs placed
there daily by a regular visitor to the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Among the thousands of tourists at the Capitol on Monday was Ed
Kortefay, 43, of Lincoln, Neb., who said that he and his family had
long planned their vacation here for this week, and that the
shootings put the Capitol on ``the priority list of things to
see.'' Kortefay, who supervises a group home for troubled youths,
said he had little sympathy for the Weston family, despite their
apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel obligated to relieve themselves of the guilt,'' he
said. He described Rusty Weston as ``a classic loner nutcase.''
</P>
<P>
   A few questioned why the police officers were not wearing their
bulletproof vests, even while acknowledging that vests would not
have protected Chestnut, who was shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, said
Monday that his security guard, who had not worn his bulletproof
vest in the past, was wearing it Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also said that the shooting had given new urgency to plans
for a $125 million underground visitors center that would act as an
extra level of security.
</P>
<P>
   Congress had considered such a visitors center in 1991 but
rejected it as too costly. Back then, it would have cost $71
million. Rep. Newt Gingrich of Georgia, now the speaker but then
the minority whip, had called the visitors' center ``madness,''
saying, ``The American people should be able to come in the front
door of Congress, not the basement.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Holmes Norton, the delegate from the District of
Columbia and a Democrat, complained at the time that such a center
might increase traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Their tone changed in 1995, when some members of Congress
proposed that the project be paid for with private donations, which
have since mounted to about $25 million. Already $2.5 million has
been spent on maps and architectural renderings of a three-level
underground orientation center, with shops and a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need another study,'' Lott told reporters
Monday. ``I think we need to get this done.'' Asked if the project
might be scaled back so that it would cost less, Lott said, ``If
we're going to do it, let's do it right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
