<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SEE NO `DOUBLE-STANDARD' IN COATES CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ In the wake of tight end Ben Coates's arrest
Sunday night on assault charges and subsequent innocent plea in the
case, there will be no immediate ramifications regarding his status
with the Patriots, a team spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Coates' case is being compared with the case involving former
New England running back David Meggett, who was charged with sexual
assault in February. The charge was later dropped, but Meggett was
released at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Don Lowery, the Patriots' vice president of development
and community affairs, was incensed that many were accusing the
Patriots of a ``double-standard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no double-standard,'' said Lowery. ``The Dave Meggett
case has nothing to do with what's happening to Ben. Nothing
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery said Coates has the team's complete support.
</P>
<P>
   He said the tight end acknowledged he has four children, three
with his wife and one with the alleged victim, Jennifer Marshall,
27, of Norton, Mass., and said, ``he pays child support.''
</P>
<P>
   The team also believes Coates is innocent of any wrongdoing,
which was echoed Monday by Coates's agent, Mike George.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, they'll find that Ben is not guilty. We're hoping
the charges will just be dropped, because we don't believe there's
a case.'' said George.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Patriots have certainly made a statement
regarding their stand on abusive acts against women. They renounced
Christian Peter, a fifth-round pick in 1996, when they found out
about his long list of offenses against women. Meggett's release
seemed to follow the same pattern after the Toronto incident. But
now the team is saying that's not the reason they cut the kick
returner.
</P>
<P>
   ``David was released for a multitude of reasons,'' said Lowery.
``The incident in Toronto was of great concern, but it was not the
sole reason why he was released. David was released because of the
injury he sustained, for football concerns about his productivity,
and high salary cap number.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Bob Kraft's wife, Myra, is the president of the Rose
Foundation, which raises funds for battered women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben is the one who made the call to the police,'' said Lowery.
``He asked the woman to leave. She came back and he told her to get
off of his property.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates appeared unfazed by the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Ted Johnson said he didn't notice Coates was missing
from practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it didn't have that big of an effect on me,'' said
Johnson. ``I don't think it's that big of a deal because the
details haven't surfaced. Until we know what really went on, I'm
sure none of his teammates are going to pass judgment on him. I
don't think it'll be a distraction at all. I'm sure he'll deal with
it as best he can. Whatever problems we have off the field, I'm
sure we'll deal with it. We have a job to do on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be a big deal if the Patriots have to start the season
without Coates, a four-time Pro Bowler, and with rookie Rod
Rutledge, Lovett Purnell, and Scott Dragos. Coates is Drew
Bledsoe's favorite receiver and is a vital part of the Patriots'
offense, perhaps second only to Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Under league rules, the Patriots have notified the NFL office
about the alleged assault case, as they did with Meggett. In all
assault cases, the league requires that the player undergo
psychological evaluation. Lowery said that the league will likely
require the evaluation sometime next week. If Coates is convicted,
he would face a fine and possible suspension by the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates opportunities for young guys,'' said coach Pete
Carroll. ``We have to go about it in that manner. Rod Rutledge was
working with the first squad (Monday). It does open opportunities
for us to see other guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
