<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-DISSIDENTS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT REBUKES CHINESE ON ARREST OF DISSIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
protested to the Chinese foreign minister Monday over the arrest of
several political dissidents since President Clinton's visit to
China, a development that other administration officials said had
alarmed and embarrassed the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made quite clear that arresting people is not the way that
we see follow-through,'' Albright said at a news conference here
after meeting with Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan. ``So I can assure
you that the subject was raised.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright also called a special news conference to denounce
Burma's leaders for their treatment of the leading Burmese
dissident.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups say at least 15 democratic activists in
China have been detained since Clinton's meeting in Beijing last
month with president Jian Xemin. While some of the dissidents were
released within days, others remain jailed and appear likely to
face long prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
   One of the dissidents, Zhu Zhengming, 35, was released on Sunday
after 17 days of detention in the eastern city of Hangzhou, but he
said his freedom was still restricted by police. ``The police told
me I shouldn't meet certain people,'' Zhu said in an interview with
Reuters. ``I shouldn't say certain things and shouldn't do certain
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The detentions have dismayed senior Clinton administration
officials, who had portrayed the president's nine-day visit to
China as having advanced the issue of human rights there. Clinton
was allowed to make broadcasts on Chinese television and radio to
call for greater political freedom in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major successes of the president's trip was to
raise human rights issues publicly in China,'' said Albright, who
is in the Philippines to attend an annual meeting of foreign
ministers from the Association of Southeast Asian Nations and other
countries with an interest in the region. ``I did raise our
concerns about some of the recent arrests.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials traveling with the secretary of
state, speaking on condition of anonymity, said she had protested
forcefully to the Chinese delegation led here by Tang.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't miss the point,'' a senior official said, adding
that the arrests ``go in the opposite direction that we're looking
for _ that has an impact on the overall relationship.'' Another
U.S. official said Albright expressed concern to the Chinese
foreign minister ``about these recent steps backward in the human
rights situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Chinese dissidents are reported to have been arrested in
the last week alone. Human rights groups said that at least four
people were taken into custody Friday night in southern Hunan
Province.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday police arrested Zhang Shanguang, a prominent
dissident who had already spent seven years in jail, for trying to
organize a group of laid-off workers. Last Tuesday a Chinese court
sentenced a dissident, Fan Yiping, to three years in prison for
helping a fellow activist escape from China.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her criticism of the Chinese, Albright said she and Tang
``talked about the successes of the summit'' between the American
and Chinese leaders, ``which I think were great in terms of working
towards developing a strategic partnership with China.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And she noted the administration's pleasure in last week's
refusal by the House of Representatives to block Clinton's granting
of so-called normal trade relations status to China, formerly known
as most-favored-nations status.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the vote ``signals the increasing acceptance of
the fact that having a relationship with China in trade does not in
any way change our stress on the importance of the human rights
agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever her criticism of Beijing, it paled by comparison to her
attack Monday on the government of Burma, which is a member of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations and has found itself the
target of growing criticism by its neighbors over its human rights
record.
</P>
<P>
   Albright called a special news conference Monday to denounce the
Burmese junta for its treatment of the nation's most prominent
dissident, Daw Aung San Suu Kyi.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Aung San Suu Kyi, who won the Nobel Peace Prize for her
campaign to bring democracy to Burma, was reported Monday to be in
the fourth day of a standoff with the military, which stopped her
car outside the capital, Yangon (formerly Rangoon), as she tried to
drive to a meeting with opposition colleagues. News reports say she
has refused to budge from the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are gravely concerned about the health and safety of Aung
San Suu Kyi and will hold the Burmese authorities directly
responsible for insuring her health and welfare,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech earlier in the day to Asian foreign ministers,
Albright warned that Burma is in danger of social collapse. ``This
is a moment of truth and of urgency for Burma and for all of us
concerned about its fate,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
