<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5357 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BECHTEL-SFCHRON-BECHT     07-27 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BECHTEL-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL MAY GIVE BAY AREA 4 POWER PLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - BECHTEL   By Kenneth Howe  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In a move to would make it one of the state's largest power
companies, Calpine Corp. said yesterday that it and a unit of
Bechtel Group would spend $1 billion to build four new electric
generating plants in the Bay Area.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; San Jose-based Calpine and Bechtel Enterprises, an affiliate
of the privately held San Francisco construction giant, plan to
build, own and operate the plants in a 50-50 partnership. The two
would split financing costs and revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The four plants, with a total output of 2,000 megawatts, would
join eight other power plants that are in the development stage,
according to the California Energy Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Calpine and Bechtel said the first plant would be a 535- to
800-megawatt facility at the Dow Chemical facility in Pittsburg
(Contra Costa County), which Calpine announced that it was buying
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Calpine also hopes to build a plant to help power San Francisco,
said Ron Walter, the company's senior vice president of business
development.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, PG&AMP;E announced that it was shutting down its
aging Hunters Point facility, which had become the target of
environmentalists and community groups who complained of pollution.
</P>
<P>
   However, Walter stressed that a plant need not be built within
San Francisco in order to help power the city.
</P>
<P>
   The boom in power plant construction is being fueled by at least
two factors. Energy deregulation in California, which began March
31, opened up the electricity market in the state, creating new
opportunities for companies to build power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, the newly deregulated market comes at a time when many
of the existing power plants owned by the once-dominant utility
companies are aging and out of date.
</P>
<P>
   The latest major utility-owned power plant was built in 1972,
Walter said.
</P>
<P>
   New power plants often are controversial because they raise
concerns about pollution. However, Calpine and Bechtel stressed
that their plants were designed to be relatively clean and
fuel-efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Bechtel, which will construct the plants, said the modern
natural gas-fired plants emit 93 percent less harmful nitrogen
oxides compared with existing fossil fuel plants and 40 percent
less carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   A global engineering and construction giant, Bechtel has built
more than 450 power plants since the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is both an environmental and consumer dividend from
deregulation,'' said Ralph Cavanagh, energy program director for
the Natural Resources Defense Council, an environmental
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Cavanagh noted that the new power plants are cheaper to build
and more efficient. That means power will be produced at a lower
costs, generating savings for consumers. At the same time, the
plants are far cleaner than other fossil fuel plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new plants essentially will be replacing the oldest,
dirtiest plants,'' Cavanagh said.
</P>
<P>
   With the new plants, to be built during the next four years,
Calpine would have 5,100 megawatts of capacity in 10 states, making
it one of the larger power companies in the West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0376 </DOCNO>
