<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PESTICIDE-TESTS-NYT &LR;      07-27 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PESTICIDE-TESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP WANTS PESTICIDE COMPANIES TO END TESTING ON HUMANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pesticide companies have conducted tests of
pesticides on humans and told the government that they expect to do
more, saying the tests may provide more reliable data than animal
tests and might justify less stringent rules on pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   However, an environmental organization Monday called on the
Environmental Protection Agency to impose a moratorium on human
experiments for purposes of pesticide regulation and to set
explicit new guidelines for any such research.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Working Group, a nonprofit organization based
in Washington that advocates tighter controls on pesticides,
discovered last week that documents about the little-known tests
were being circulated by the industry and the EPA, and described
them in a report issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The human experiments have raised scientific and ethical
concerns at a time when stricter regulation of some pesticides is
being contested by the industry. But a senior official of the EPA
said Monday that the agency questioned human testing of pesticides
and would review the matter.
</P>
<P>
   A senior aide to the EPA administrator, Carol M. Browner, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said, ``We are very concerned
about the possibility of increased human testing as a way to
potentially avoid some of the protections that the Food Quality
Protection Act establishes.'' The 1996 law overhauled the system of
pesticide regulation.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, most pesticides were tested on laboratory animals
to determine how much exposure might trigger health problems in
people. The tests, conducted by the manufacturers, are used by the
EPA to set limits on the use of chemicals on crops, around the
home, or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Because regulators cannot be sure that the highly toxic
chemicals affect people in the same way they do animals, they first
use the animal tests to estimate safe doses and then use an extra
margin of safety, called an uncertainty factor, to make the legal
limits 10 times stricter.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the uncertainty factor, industry officials have told
the EPA, the companies are increasingly likely to use humans for
tests of some chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of three tests conducted in England last year, for
example, adult volunteers were given small doses of the pesticide
dichlorvos to see how much it reduced their blood levels of
cholinesterase, an enzyme that affects brain and nerve cells.
</P>
<P>
   Amvac Chemical Corp., the California manufacturer of the
chemical, has asked the EPA to consider the new data in its reviews
on the continued use of the pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Monday, Amvac said its experiments had
been conducted in a licensed laboratory in Cheshire, England, on
fully informed volunteers and had been reviewed by a medical ethics
committee. The company said there were no ethical reasons why
similar tests could not be conducted in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA is conducting a comprehensive review of the class of
chemicals known as organophosphates, which includes dichlorvos. The
agency is considering tightening the limits on the organophosphates
under provisions of the Food Quality Protection Act.
</P>
<P>
   In a report published in June that made recommendations to the
agency for implementing the new pesticide law, an industry
coalition said that human testing would probably be limited
``almost exclusively'' to short-term studies measuring whether
certain organophosphates inhibit cholinesterase in the blood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
