A5361 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     07-27 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR'S TEAM MEETS WITH LEWINSKY, PRESSES CLINTON TO TESTIFY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Escalating the pace of the investigation into an
alleged presidential affair and cover-up, prosecutors met Monday
for the first time in six months with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky and pressed President Clinton to appear before a
federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a federal appeals court handed independent counsel
Kenneth Starr a major victory by ordering presidential confidant
Bruce Lindsey to cooperate with the grand jury investigation into
the alleged Clinton-Lewinsky affair and cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling and Lewinsky's daylong meeting with Starr's deputies
were a setback for Clinton, and intensified pressure on his legal
team to reach agreement with Starr on how the president will
provide information to grand jurors without having to trek to the
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is using the grand jury to examine whether Clinton or any
of his associates lied, urged others to lie or otherwise tried to
cover up alleged White House sexual encounters between the
president and Lewinsky and one other woman, Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton, 52, and Lewinsky, 25, have denied under oath
engaging in sex. Clinton has said he never told anyone to lie. The
president, who acknowledged meeting privately with Willey, denied
any inappropriate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiations led earlier this year by her former attorney,
William Ginsburg, Lewinsky reportedly agreed to testify that she
and Clinton engaged in sex. That testimony would have been part of
a deal to avoid prosecution. At the same time, she declined to
offer anything regarding a cover-up attempt, which prompted Starr
to reject her offer of testimony-for-immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Lewinsky has hired a new legal team, and
negotiations resumed with Starr, which sources said led to Monday's
meeting in New York. It was Lewinsky's first face-to-face session
with prosecutors since they confronted her six months ago after the
FBI secretly tape recorded her talking to a friend, Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication late Monday that an immunity deal had
been worked out for Lewinsky. Starr spokesman Charles Bakaly did
not respond to requests for information about the meeting.
Lewinsky's lawyers, who were traveling, could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, the U.S. Court of Appeals for Washington upheld a
lower court ruling compelling Lindsey _ a longtime Clinton friend,
confidant and adviser on various scandals _ to answer all of
Starr's questions before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge appeals panel rejected the Clinton
administration argument that requiring Lindsey, who serves as
deputy White House counsel, to divulge his conversations with the
president would violate the long-recognized confidentiality of the
attorney-client relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``A government attorney may not invoke the attorney-client
privilege in response to grand jury questions seeking information
relating to the possible commission of a federal crime,'' said the
ruling by Appeals Judges Judith Rogers and David Tatel, who were
appointed by Clinton, and Raymond Randolph, an appointee of former
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The duty of government lawyers, such as Lindsey and other White
House attorneys, ``is not to defend clients against criminal
charges, and it is not to protect wrong-doers from public
exposure,'' the judges said. ``Lindsey's advice on political,
strategic or policy issues, valuable as it may have been, would not
be shielded from disclosure by the attorney-client privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff issued a statement saying
that the president's legal team would review the opinion before
deciding whether to appeal. If Ruff and Clinton choose to fight the
decision, they could seek a review by all 11 members of the Court
of Appeals or could appeal directly to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed that the Court of Appeals has decided that
unlike every other attorney and client in this country, government
attorneys and their clients do not enjoy the right to have
confidential communications,'' Ruff said, adding that frank and
candid conversations between public officials and government
lawyers ``will be chilled'' if the ruling is allowed to stand.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton's private attorney David Kendall confirmed
that he was negotiating with Starr ``to devise a way for the
president to provide information for the investigation, consistent
with his constitutional role and responsibilities.'' Kendall added
that it ``would not be appropriate to comment further.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury is to meet Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, and
Clinton's subpoena reportedly indicates he must show up this week
to testify. The date of his appearance could be pushed back while
Kendall and Starr resolve their differences over how Clinton
presents his information to the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The president reportedly is holding out for testifying on
videotape or closed-circuit television with his attorneys present
during questioning by Starr and his deputies. Starr is balking at
allowing anyone from Clinton's legal team to attend the interview,
sources said. Normally, witnesses' lawyers are barred from grand
jury rooms.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton refuses to testify, a constitutional crisis could be
triggered over the question of separation of powers or whether the
federal courts can compel a sitting president to testify in
criminal proceedings in which he could be a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   A decision to fight Starr's subpoena could be politically
harmful to Clinton in light of his promise early in the scandal to
answer questions about his relationship with Lewinsky. Since then,
the president has refused to discuss the relationship and, for the
most part, Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three days, Clinton has ignored reporters who
raised questions about his subpoena and whether he plans to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
