<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5363 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAMMING-SFCHRON-SLAM     07-27 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAMMING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEAZY PRACTICE OF SLAMMING MAKING GAINS IN CALIFORNIA  
 BY JONATHAN MARSHALL  

</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - SLAMMING   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
California's telephone industry regulators are discovering that the
price of consumer protection is eternal vigilance.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After nearly wiping out the problem of ``slamming'' _ the
improper switching of long distance service without a customer's
consent _ investigators at the California Public Utilities
Commission are alarmed by a sharp rise in new cases this year.
</P>
<P>
   In one ongoing investigation, they have learned that former
employees of a Georgia company, which allegedly slammed 90,000
California customers several years ago, are now running another
firm that has drawn complaints of slamming and ``cramming'' _ the
placing of unauthorized charges on phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   At the national level, the number of slamming complaints is
soaring. The Federal Communications Commission last year received
20,475 written complaints about slamming, up 134 percent over the
total in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But California bucked that trend until recently through vigorous
regulatory enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The number of customer complaints about long-distance slamming
recorded by Pacific Bell ran about 20,000 a month in 1996 but fell
to a low of 5,022 this January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cut slamming 80 percent through a novel approach: We
enforced existing laws,'' said Larry McNeely, deputy director of
the PUC's Consumer Services Division. ``We put every available
investigator on this and took the financial incentives and rewards
away from slammers. This was a frontal assault.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides yanking the operating authority of slammers in
California, the PUC slapped large fines on major violators and
worked closely with local district attorney's offices to arrange
further penalties for slammers and financial settlements for their
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make the slammers disgorge any profits,''
McNeely said. ``That's where the DA's have been so helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Since January, however, the lure of a fast buck has once again
invigorated slammers. The number of consumer slamming complaints
doubled to 10,166 in June, Pacific Bell said in its latest report
to the PUC.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that the commission has only three investigators
assigned to utilities cases, involving electric as well as phone
company issues. It recently got budget authority for four more
enforcement positions but has not yet filled them.
</P>
<P>
   PUC investigators are particularly concerned about Georgia-based
America's Tele-Network Corp., which operates in about 30 states and
at its peak had about 10,000 California customers.
</P>
<P>
   In late March, the PUC opened a formal investigation of ATN
based on consumer complaints and the discovery that the company's
president and controller used to work for Sonic Communications, one
of the biggest slammers in California history.
</P>
<P>
   In one seven-month period in 1994, Sonic, also based in Georgia,
switched nearly 97,000 Californians to its long-distance service
from other carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Sonic sent out tens of thousands of $10 checks, which contained
tiny, light-gray print authorizing the service switch when the
checks were endorsed. In some cases Sonic allegedly switched
customers without any semblance of authorization.
</P>
<P>
   When Sonic began doing business in late 1993, the PUC's only
investigators were in the transportation division. The commission
was unprepared to deal with allegations of widespread
telecommunications fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was totally out of control before anyone realized
it,'' McNeely recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC, working with state attorneys general in Georgia,
Illinois, New York and Texas, shut Sonic down in 1995 and arranged
a $1.2 million settlement for California customers. The company
subsequently declared bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the PUC took the belated step of revoking Sonic's
operating authority _ even though the company has been defunct for
some time.
</P>
<P>
   PUC investigators were thus shocked to discover early this year
that Sonic's former information systems manager is now head of ATN
and that Sonic's controller is now ATN's controller. The launch of
ATN was funded in part with a personal loan from Sonic's founder.
Neither had disclosed their ties to Sonic when applying for
operating authority to the PUC.
</P>
<P>
   PUC investigators also heard from numerous consumers that they
had signed up with ATN under false pretenses. Many customers were
people who responded to newspaper ads placed by ATN, promising to
pay up to $600 a week for helping to market its service.
</P>
<P>
   Marlys Chamberlain, a Stockton retiree, wanted something to do
in her spare time and answered an ad last September. The ATN
representative promised her free long-distance service and a free
800 number as part of the job, if she switched service. She
willingly agreed.
</P>
<P>
   After several weeks of hearing nothing more about the job, she
began to worry about being scammed. ``That was kind of dumb of me,
but I didn't spend any money,'' Chamberlain recalled thinking at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Then she got her next monthly phone bill. It included a $10
service charge from ATN, a $10 charge for 800 service, a $4 charge
for calling-card service and several other charges, including a
long-distance call she never made. ``My husband had a big old
fit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, a former employee at the Department of Consumer
Affairs in Sacramento, complained to Pacific Bell, the FCC, PUC and
anyone else she could think of. Eventually ATN returned her money,
but other consumers interviewed by the PUC weren't so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ATN's attorney, Charles Helein, said the company is negotiating
a settlement with the PUC, without admitting guilt, rather than
waging an expensive battle to fight the charges. ``The best defense
in the world won't get you much down the road with regulators,'' he
said. ``They don't want to hear the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Helein, who previously represented Sonic, said that Sonic was
innocent of slamming but was convicted in the press ``before they
could open their mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the ATN employment ads that brought some customers
to it were genuine, not come-ons.
</P>
<P>
   And he said it's not illegal to put unauthorized charges on a
customer's bill for services they never ordered. Eager
telemarketers frequently get carried away and misunderstand a
customer's grunt as approval, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a highly competitive market with commissions, you can
expect there will be a lot of Wild Bill Hickocks out there shooting
from all sides,'' he said. ``I'm not trying to justify that
practice, but ... there's no law against it.''
</P>
<P>
   PUC investigators said ATN's alleged slamming was hard to trace
because the company resells long-distance service from WorldCom, so
orders show up under WorldCom's name. AT&AMP;T recently curbed its
marketing efforts after its anonymous resellers generated a rash of
slamming complaints against the company.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the U.S. Senate unanimously passed the Consumer
Anti-Slamming Act, which imposes fines of $40,000 to $150,000
against offenders. A similar bill is now before the House
telecommunications subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
