r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IPO-SFCHRON-IPO &LR;      07-27 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPO-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE SEX SITE WANTS TO BE FIRST TO GO PUBLIC  
 BY JON SWARTZ 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - IPO   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
   The next big Internet IPO is generating a buzz in the investment
community _ but not because of a breakthrough technology or
marketing plan.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet Entertainment Group, the money-making online company
best known for marketing the sex video of actress Pamela Anderson
and rocker Tommy Lee, says it plans a stock offering in six months.
If successful, it would be the first U.S. adult-entertainment Web
site to go public, as well as one of the only public online
companies turning a profit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In addition to porn, IEG sells psychic services, vitamin
supplements and golf equipment via the Internet. It plans to use
its IPO proceeds to buy other porn sites and distribute its content
over televisions equipped with Internet set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the Viacom of new media,'' company CEO Seth
Warshavsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Warshavsky, 25, said his 100-person Seattle company _ one of the
biggest and best-known online pornographers _ is sifting through
audits and talking to prospective underwriters &UR;  &LR; in preparation for
an IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Smut sites are among the most financially lucrative _ and
technologically advanced _ on the World Wide Web. They are pioneers
in real-time video, electronic commerce transactions and graphic
design.
</P>
<P>
   But none in the United States has gone public because of the
stigma attached to their content. A continued strong Internet IPO
market, however, could improve the climate for IEG and others to be
publicly traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make a lot of money by selling sin, and that could be
enticing to investors,'' said Tom Taulli, market analyst for IPO
Monitor in Calabasas (Los Angeles County). ``IEG is creating
another Playboy. Sex sells, but even more on the Internet, where
you can order porn from your personal computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Web sites, which give away their content in hopes of
generating a big enough viewer base to sell advertising, IEG is
charging subscribers $24.95 monthly to gawk at thousands of
pornographic photos, video clips and live cybercasts. It also sells
ads for sex-related products and services.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The business model, aided by low overhead costs, has made IEG
one of the most profitable ventures online. The Seattle-based
company said it anticipates earnings of at least $15 million on
sales of $40 million this year. Warshavsky said he hopes to raise
at least $40 million to $50 million in an offering.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo Inc., by comparison, has reported earnings of $15 million
on sales of $96 million over the past three quarters. The Santa
Clara-based company, which provides an Internet search engine, chat
rooms, news and shopping services, has a market valuation of $8.9
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that other online porn services will follow
if IEG is successful,'' said Mark Tiarra, CEO of Tiarra Corp., an
adult Web site in Midland Park, N.J., that is entertaining ideas of
an initial public offering. ``They are the bellwether of our
industry, and the Net IPO market is hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Market momentum is expected to pick up steam later this year,
with the highly anticipated IPOs of GeoCities, which provides free
e-mail and Web design tools, and eBay, an online auctioneer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But industry observers say an IEG offering is not a certainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to gauge IEG's prospects,'' Taulli said. ``It's six
months away, and its services are narrow, unlike a Yahoo. Besides,
would they be able to attract a strong underwriter for such a
company?''
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely, say investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just look at the numbers, the answer is sure,'' said
Jim Feuille, head of investment banking at Volpe Brown Whelan &AMP; Co.
in San Francisco. ``However, underwriters do not base their
business decisions strictly on that criteria. Underwrit ing a
company (like IEG) would be a very controversial move in terms of
image. It will spark some interesting debates.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
