<HEADLINE>
DEL MONTE RETURNS TO THE TRADING FLOOR 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - DEL MONTE   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Del Monte Foods, one of nation's most venerable brands, is about to
re-emerge as a publicly traded company.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based king of canned fruits and vegetables is
expected to price its shares as early as this afternoon. And after
a 19-year intermission, Del Monte shares could resume trading on
the New York Stock Exchange tomorrow under the ticker symbol DLM.
</P>
<P>
   The company should raise close to $250million if it sells 14.7
million shares at the preliminary estimated price of $16 to $18 per
share. Current owners, namely Texas Pacific Group of Houston and
San Francisco, plan to sell an additional 4.4million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Del Monte has gone through several ownership changes in recent
years. Texas Pacific, which specializes in buying private companies
and tuning them up for sale to the public, acquired Del Monte 16
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, Del Monte was acquired by R.J. Reynolds, merged into
RJR Nabisco, sold to leveraged buyout specialists Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts, passed on to a group led by Merrill Lynch and then sold to
Texas Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Del Monte shed its fresh fruit and international
operations along with several product lines including puddings and
fruit punch. ``Del Monte has one of the most familiar brand names
in the world but it hasn't been able to do a lot with it,'' said
one stock broker.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Pacific has been out to change that as it did with
Beringer Wine Estates. It bought the Napa Valley vintner from
Nestle USA less than two years ago and took it public last October.
</P>
<P>
   With two Dole Food veterans at the helm _ CEO Richard Wolford
and Chief Operating Officer Wesley Smith _ Del Monte has refocused
its operations in several ways:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; New products and promotions &LR; . Del Monte nearly quadrupled its
consumer promotions budget to $46 million from $12million and added
higher profit margin products like Orchard Select premium bottled
fruits and Fruit Smoothie Blenders flavored drinks.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Broader markets &LR; . It expanded in high-growth distribution
channels like supercenter and club stores such as PriceCostco.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Strategic acquisitions &LR; . Last November, Del Monte bought
Contadina's line of canned products for $197 million, consolidating
its position as the leader in the processed foods business. It also
ranks No. 1 in canned fruits with 41 percent market share and
canned vegetables with a 20 percent market share.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Cost cutting &LR; . Del Monte said in January that it would cut
1,000 jobs and close two of its six California plants, including an
80-year-old San Jose cannery and a 70-year-old Stockton facility.
</P>
<P>
   Del Monte is growing nicely but it is not yet a big moneymaker.
It lost $56 million on $1.4 billion sales in 1997. The company has
a heavy $1.2 billion debt load. And the prospectus tells investors
not to expect dividends for ``the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   But since 1891, the company has built one of the best-known
brands in business. It also has a well-known group of underwriters
led by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Robertson Stephens, Bear
Stearns, BT Alex Brown and Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
