<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL UP TO THE PATRIOTS, NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is not Wil Cordero. This is not David Meggett. This is Ben
Coates, who pleaded innocent Monday to domestic abuse charges. This
is not just another player you can toss out the window, trying to
make yourself so politically correct.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Hall of Fame-bound football player. Without him in the
lineup, the Patriots' Super Bowl chances disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Coates is the best pass catcher the Patriots have ever had, and
he is the key to quarterback Drew Bledsoe's success. Without his
All-Pro tight end, Bledsoe is not Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   So the question today, and for the rest of the season, is: What
face will the Patriots put on?
</P>
<P>
   Will they follow the road paved by Christian Peter and Meggett,
or will they suddenly forget the standards they appeared to have
set for their team when they dispatched both Peter and Meggett on
short notice.
</P>
<P>
   Peter, to refresh the memory, was a fifth-round draft choice out
of Nebraska two years ago. Peter had a history of trouble at
Nebraska. Two days after he was picked, and Peter's off-field
activity was criticized in the media, the Patriots dumped him in a
hiccup. Of course, the hypocrisy came in the announcement with his
release, that they really didn't have all the details of his
background, and if they had, they wouldn't have drafted him. The
truth is, they knew everything he did, but didn't consider what the
fallout would be in the local media. When it hit, they ran away
from him like he was contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   Meggett was considered the best offensive player the Patriots
had at the end of last season. He was hurt going into their final
playoff game in Pittsburgh, and then suffered a broken foot on the
first play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, he was arrested and charged with sexual
assault and robbery in Toronto. The Patriots claimed they would
wait until he had his day in court before they decided his future.
Meggett has yet to get to court, but they still released him at the
end of May, putting out the word that it had more to do with his
off-field activity than it did with his playing. The assault charge
already has been dismissed, and robbery charge may also be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Coates is a lot like Meggett. Very productive on and off the
field, but he means more than ever to the Patriots this year,
because of the events of the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of last season, the Patriots have lost Curtis
Martin, Keith Byars, Sam Gash, and Meggett, the four major
backfield contributors the last two seasons. Those four, plus
Coates, carried the load the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Coates has caught 361 passes from Bledsoe in the regular season
the last five years, and holds the Patriots' all-time season record
with 96 catches in 1994. Everyone who has watched the Patriots play
the last five years knows that when Bledsoe is in trouble, or needs
a big play, he is going to look to Coates. The opposition knows it
as well. And even if they have two players surrounding Coates,
Bledsoe believes in him so much the ball is going to be thrown in
Big Ben's direction. The offense this year, with no running game,
would be nothing without Coates.
</P>
<P>
   So Bob Kraft has his biggest spin job to date. How does he keep
Coates on the field, and say he is any different than Meggett, when
they both have recently had similar alleged violent episodes off
the field?
</P>
<P>
   Where will the standard fall? Will it be the same treatment for
Coates as it was for Peter and Meggett, or will some hypocritical
excuse be made to keep Coates on the field?
</P>
<P>
   And then there is another problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Coates may become a test case _ so to speak _ for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months back, at the annual league meetings,
commissioner Paul Tagliabue announced a new Violent Crime Policy,
which gives him the right, by his own ruling, to take action
against any employee of the NFL involved in violence off the field.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy went into effect July 1. It puts what Coates
allegedly did Sunday night right in Tagliabue's lap. Threat of
physical violence and domestic violence are both covered. Under
this policy, Tagliabue has the right to fine or suspend a player.
Automatically, because he was arrested and charged, Coates has to
enter an NFL-sponsored counseling program. If he pleads guilty, or
is found guilty, he can face further punishment from Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, in a short period of time, has become one of the most
powerful owners in the NFL. He carries a lot of clout with
Tagliabue. The commissioner has placed Kraft on the all- important
television committee, and then gave him the most important
ownership assignment in the league, chairman of the finance
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft will make it a tough call for Tagliabue if he pleads for
leniency, in view of the commissioner's statements this past March
on getting tough with players involved in violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, if I owned the Patriots, he'd be playing, unless the
courts decide he has to be put away. I wrote the same thing about
Cordero and the Red Sox. I'd bring Meggett back in a heartbeat if
he was healthy. Just because they are athletes, and in the
spotlight, they should not be held to a different set of rules than
the average person in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
