<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S TO HE ROES, HERE AND THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The blood had yet to dry when I got there. Two boys
playing nearby pointed it out to me. By then, investigators had
left the scene and neighborhood children ran around the parking lot
pulling behind them tails of yellow plastic tape with the words
``Crime Scene: Do Not Cross'' printed on it.
</P>
<P>
   A few of them wrapped it around their waists. One made it into a
headband, the words bending around his forehead like an electronic
ticker tape.
</P>
<P>
   The boys showed me the spot where the officer came to rest. The
patch of blood on the asphalt was as large as a dinner plate, and
shiny, like jelly spread on chocolate cake.
</P>
<P>
   I'd heard about the shooting on the car radio on my way to work.
It had happened overnight. It was January 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police Officer Robert Fike pulled into a dark parking
lot behind a convenience store at 11th Street and Indian School
Road. The glaring cone of light from his patrol car's spotlight
caught 21-year-old Matthew Millburn shooting up cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Millburn financed his drug habit with the occasional armed
robbery. When the officer got out of his car and approached the
young man, Millburn pulled a pistol, pointed it at the policeman's
face, and fired.
</P>
<P>
   Fike was 43. &QL; 
1st cop's blood &QL; 
It was the first stain of cop's blood I saw on the streets of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   I stood there, staring at it, not knowing what to do, when an
elderly couple approached.
</P>
<P>
   The man carried a bucket half filled with topsoil, The woman
held a gardening shovel. When they got to the place where the blood
had not yet dried, the woman made the sign of the cross and prayed
silently. She dipped her spade into the bucket and sprinkled dirt
on the shiny patch of pavement until it was covered.
</P>
<P>
   Then they turned and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   When I see TV news coverage today showing the flag-draped
caskets of Detective John M. Gibson and Officer Jacob J. Chestnut
of the Capitol police, killed in a shootout Friday in Washington,
D.C., I'll be thinking of Officer Fike.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be thinking of Leonard Kolodziej, too, a Phoenix policeman
shot dead by a sniper in 1991. Officer Kolodziej had patrolled my
neighborhood. He once stopped by our house to make sure everything
was OK.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be thinking of Bob Martin, the 57-year-old state Department
of Public Safety officer killed in 1995 on Arizona 87. I'll be
thinking of Maricopa County sheriff's Deputy Vernon Marconnet, and
DPS officer Ed Rebel, and Phoenix Officer Kenneth Collings, and
corrections officer Brent Lumley.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   All of them died in the line of duty. None of them got what
Chestnut and Gibson are getting. &QL; 
High-level attention &QL; 
The president, vice president and the leaders of Congress didn't
attend their memorial services. They didn't make the national news
or rest for a time in the Capitol Rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Chestnut and Gibson don't deserve the attention;
it's that the others don't deserve anything less.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, that wouldn't be practical. If each fallen
law-enforcement officer were treated the same, the president and
vice president would have attended more than 90 funerals so far
this year. That's how many cops have died on the job in America
since January.
</P>
<P>
   We could fill the Rotunda with caskets.
</P>
<P>
   So, while the nation remembers Chestnut and Gibson, I'm
remembering Fike, Kolodziej, Marconnet, Rebel, Collings, Lumley and
the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Some of their friends in local law enforcement believe people in
my business don't give a damn about the ones who die. They figure
we're more interested in screw-ups than heroes.
</P>
<P>
   They say it's name-calling; we say it's calling 'em as we see
'em.
</P>
<P>
   It won't change.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the things we call them, though, the best name we have
for cops is peace officers. At least for today, forget the rest.
</P>
<P>
   And rest in peace, officers. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
