<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES SQUARE IS OPENED TO TRAFFIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Times Square was reopened to traffic at dawn on
Monday, but optimism at the pace of work on the damaged scaffolding
at the Conde Nast building gave way to renewed safety concerns in
the afternoon when gusty winds apparently sent a 15-foot-long
aluminum pipe falling more than 400 feet to the roof of a theater
next door.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured, and there appeared to be little, if any,
damage to the theater's parapet, officials said. The pipe was kept
from falling farther from the construction site _ and possibly
causing serious damage _ by the nylon protective netting that
workers are busily draping around the scaffolding tower, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nets, to the extent that they're in place, are doing what
they're supposed to do,'' said Richard Kieler, senior vice
president at Tishman Realty and Construction, the construction
manager at the project.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, both the city and the company that erected the
scaffolding said they had called in forensic engineers to determine
the cause of the fatal collapse at the Conde Nast building on 43rd
Street last Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the area around the city's most famous intersection
returned to normal beginning at 5:45 a.m., when the police reopened
Broadway, Seventh Avenue and the streets to the west, and taxis and
trucks again streamed through Times Square. With that, its short
life as a pedestrian's paradise came to a screeching halt.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 p.m., Bryant Park was reopened to lunching office workers,
as well as to cleanup crews, which found a week's worth of leaves
to rake up.
</P>
<P>
   There were other minor but noticeable improvements: Pedestrians
were allowed to walk along 42nd Street as far west as the Avenue of
the Americas, meaning about a dozen businesses could reopen, if to
less-than-brisk sales. And most of 43rd Street between Fifth and
the Avenue of the Americas was opened to delivery trucks,
customers, employees and residents but not to through traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But the Avenue of the Americas remained closed to vehicles from
34th to 46th Streets, said Deputy Chief Michael Fox of the Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Hauer, director of the mayor's Office of Emergency
Management, said that the Avenue of the Americas, 42nd and 44th
Streets would be reopened to all traffic as soon as the nylon
protective netting has been draped around the scaffolding as far
down as the ninth floor. That could happen sometime on Tuesday, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he warned that the timetable could be extended once again,
especially in light of the fall of the length of aluminum pipe.
</P>
<P>
   The safety netting, which consists of 12-foot-wide,
300-foot-long sheets, is being unrolled and fastened to the
scaffolding and additional supports by three-person crews working
around the clock from a metal bucket dangling from a crane.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, workers finished the first of two sections of
netting, from the top of the scaffolding to about the 21st floor.
On Monday, they were attaching the second section. But at about
2:20 p.m., while a crew was suspended over the scaffolding's north
side, a 15-foot pipe brace fell over its east side. The crew was
immediately raised aloft to the roof and work ceased for about two
hours. Kieler said that a gust of wind appeared to have dislodged
the 20-pound pipe from the scaffolding.
</P>
<P>
   It fell inside the netting, he said, before bouncing away from
the tower where the netting had not yet been installed. The pipe
landed with a bang on a parapet on the roof of the Henry Miller
Theater, which has been refashioned the Kit Kat Club for the
revival of ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters minutes later, Hauer said the incident
underscored the danger present in dismantling the scaffolding,
which he has likened to an outsized game of ``pick-up sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it seems at times that things are going very slowly,
but that is very calculated,'' he said. ``Had those workers been
anywhere near where that beam fell, we could've had loss of life.''
</P>
<P>
   To ensure against that, he said, 43rd Street itself between
Avenue of the Americas and Broadway may not be reopened for weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
