<SLUG> BC-DIGITALBAY-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO GUARANTEE THAT FOREIGN WORKERS BILL WILL BECOME LAW  
 TOM ABATE/DIGITAL BAY 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - DIGITAL BAY   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The White House hasn't signaled whether it will endorse last week's
House-Senate ``compromise'' on a controversial bill to increase the
number of foreigners who can work in the United States under
temporary H-1B visas.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the high-tech lobby cheered the deal, there's no
guarantee it will overcome an administration threat to veto the
H-1B bill unless it contained ``protections'' to ensure that
Americans weren't displaced by workers from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Lamar Smith, R-Texas, wrote such protections into
his original H-1B bill in the House, requiring that companies
``attest'' that no American was laid off to employ a foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   But when the high-tech lobby balked, Republican leaders
pressured Smith to water down the ``attestation'' provision. As a
result, in the compromise bill, only firms whose staffs were more
than 15 percent H-1B workers would have to swear they weren't
dumping any Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of higher H-1B limits _ notably organized labor and
some professional engineering associations _ say Smith caved,
because only a handful of employment agencies that specialize in
hiring out H-1B workers will have to attest to anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a compromise, it's a victory for high-tech,'' said
Norman Matloff, a University of California at Davis professor and
H-1B opponent.
</P>
<P>
   He contends the compromise bill is really the industry-backed
Senate version authored by Senator Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., with a
15 percent attestation tacked on.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether the 15 percent is enough of a fig
leaf to hide the fact that the compromise bill is essentially the
same legislation that President Clinton threatened to veto.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say White House economic advisor Gene Sperling, who'll
make the recommendation to Clinton, hasn't seen the actual
compromise language _ because Abraham's staff is still drafting it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, you can be sure tech leaders will be pressuring the
White House to approve the Smith-Abraham agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage it would be hard for the president to disappoint
high tech,'' one Republican Senate staffer said.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Hollowed ground? &LR;  After Lockheed Missiles &AMP; Space Co. said
last month it would cut some 2,000 heads from its 9,500-person Bay
Area workforce, a Lockheed veteran drew me aside to com plain that
the gray-haired were the first to be shown the door _ robbing the
firm of its institutional memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not ageism but economics,'' the source said, requesting
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are being retired based on their cost,'' he added.
``They happen to be the oldest and most experienced people. Many
projects are showing gaps in engineering knowledge as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Lockheed spokesman Dave Waller confirmed that employees 55
and older have received letters offering voluntary early
retirement. But no group _ neither older workers nor new hires _
have been singled out for layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Waller disputed any notion that the company was shedding its top
brains, saying Lockheed reserves the right to deny early retirement
to older workers with essential skills.
</P>
<P>
   But my source said Lockheed has been thinning its senior ranks
for years. The latest letters are just more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks the results of this ``brain drain'' are evident in
troubled programs like the Theater High Altitude Area Defense
(THAAD), which is supposed to protect troops in the field by
shooting down enemy missiles. But the system has been highly
criticized by the press.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; God on our side? &LR;  The trade publication Government Computer
News recently reported that a software screwup in May made the
Navy's ``smart ship'' go dead in the water.
</P>
<P>
   According to GCN, the missile cruiser USS Yorktown _ called
smart because it uses software to replace 10 percent of its crew _
lost propulsion for 45 minutes because of an error caused by its
Windows NT operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The glitch led one civilian engineer to grumble that using the
relatively-new NT instead of the battle-tested Unix to run a
warship ``is similar to hoping that luck will be in our favor''
when the shooting starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; So what's new? &LR;  Pacific Bell's voice mail was down _ again _
for much of Saturday and for about 45 minutes yesterday. Spokesman
John Britton said the cause of yesterday's outage was unknown.
Saturday's down time occurred while the company was installing a
software update.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate &LR; sfgate.com &LR; ).
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
