<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-SANYO-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANYO BUYS ACCESS TO TECHNOLOGY FROM IBM
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Sanyo Electric Co., struggling to emerge from the
shadows cast by bigger competitors like Sony and Matsushita, has
bought access to some of the most advanced semiconductor technology
to use in its consumer electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Under a deal announced Monday with the International Business
Machines Corp., Sanyo gets access to advanced semiconductor
manufacturing processes and is permitted to design chips that
incorporate IBM's copper circuit technology, a breakthrough in
semiconductor manufacturing that greatly reduces energy consumption
and improves performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us access to cutting-edge technology that's needed
for the next generation of consumer devices like digital cameras
and digital decoders for television, things that need more power
than conventional home appliances,'' said Daniel Cox, a spokesman
for Sanyo.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is also another step in Sanyo's efforts to build a
name for itself in the computer chips business, potentially a much
more lucrative area than consumer electronics.
</P>
<P>
   New consumer electronics, like cellular phones and digital
cameras, derive their capabilities from sophisticated computer
chips inside the devices. ``Many companies know they can't make
huge operating margin from assembled consumer electronics,'' said
Masashi Kubota, an electronics analyst at ING Barings in Tokyo.
``They're facing increased competition from Korean manufacturers
and price-cutting in Japan and know that the place to make money is
in electronic components and semiconductors.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal will give IBM greater presence as a chip supplier in
Japan. ``It's further acceptance of technology that we've developed
and evidence that it's valued by others,'' said Mac Jeffery, a
spokesman for IBM Asia Pacific in Tokyo. ``Plus, a fair amount of
our income is derived from licensing our technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Terms were not disclosed. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sanyo's alliance with IBM, like an earlier one between Sony and
Fujitsu, highlights the high cost of developing the new, more
sophisticated chips used in modern consumer electronics. These
chips are home to a combination of transistors and circuits that in
the past would have each resided on separate chips.
</P>
<P>
   The complexity of creating a neighborhood of tiny transistors
atop a postage-stamp-sized silicon wafer is immense, as is the
price. But as the world moves toward increasingly digitalized
consumer electronics, such ``systems on a chip'' become more
important as DVD storage disks replace CD-ROMs and cellular phones
replace desktop phones.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its deal with IBM, Sanyo will have access to IBM's
core library of chip design technology, including methods that
provide superior performance using less energy. It will also be
able to tap IBM's manufacturing technology to produce transistors
with a width of eighteen-hundredths micron and thinner, or less
than five one-hundredths of the width of a human hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us access to technology that we otherwise wouldn't
have,'' Cox said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
