SCI-GRANDPARENTS-STRESS-2, 7-27 -- Susan Silverstein, a social
worker in Great Neck, counsels grandparents and their
grandchildren. ``I am amazed at the need,'' says Ms. Silverstein.
``A huge percentage of the grandparents describe feelings of
depression and problems with eating and sleeping. Most attribute
those problems to stress, but whether they are purely due to stress
or to a combination of stress and physiological problems is
difficult to ascertain.'' (Lois Raimondo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 27, 1998 -- SCI-GRANDPARENTS-STRESS-1,
7-27 -- Dr. Ronald Adelman believes grandparent care providers
often develop stress-related illnesses. ``For many, dreams of the
golden years aren't so golden,'' he says. ``This is a new
phenomenon, and geriatricians and internists are just becoming
aware of it. We need to ask our patients more questions about their
home situations.'' (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- July 27, 1998 -- SCI-COMPUTE-MINSKY,
7-27 -- Dr. Marvin Minsky, one of the leading theorists of
artificial intelligence, at his home in Brookline. In the late
1950s, Minsky, 71, and a collaborator founded a research program
that would evolve into the MIT Artificial Intelligence Laboratory.
``You can pull something with a string, but you can't push it,'' he
says. ``That's common sense. And no computer knows it.'' (Rick
