<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5388 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRANT-BOMBS-AZR &LR;      07-27 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-BOMBS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLEGAL IMMIGRANTS' ROUTE LEADS THROUGH BOMBING RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YUMA, Ariz. _ On a day when desert temperatures burst above 120
degrees, Border Patrol agents stopped a pickup truck and found,
stuffed under a camper shell, 23 dehydrated illegal immigrants on
the verge of heatstroke.
</P>
<P>
   Heat was not their biggest enemy. The truck, its driver
oblivious to the danger, had crawled across a military bombing zone
called the Chocolate Mountain Aerial Gunnery Range northwest of
Yuma, a site controlled by the U.S. Marine Corps and used by
several armed forces, including those of NATO, to train pilots.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Harrier jets drop bombs of up to 2,000 pounds,
including ``cluster bombs'' that splinter on impact. Many remain
unexploded and can easily be triggered by heat, friction or even
something as delicate as AM radio waves, authorities warn.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the danger is advertised on warning signs in Spanish
and English, that hasn't deterred desperate crossers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four months, no fewer than 612 illegals have been
picked up by the Border Patrol on or near the range, according to
the agency. All were safely rescued, but military and Border Patrol
agents fear the increasing traffic is putting more men, women and
children at risk of being blown up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting large numbers of alien smuggling loads coming
through that area,'' said Donny Tibbets, Border Patrol
agent-in-charge at the Blythe, Calif., station. ``It's a concern
because we think there's a potential for a . . . significant loss
of life out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, more people have trespassed on the
range because the Border Patrol stepped up enforcement along the
California-Mexico border, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a new route that's being used to reach Los Angeles,''
says Rita Vargas, consul at the Mexican Consulate in Calexico,
Calif. ``It shows a high irresponsibility on the part of guides
taking people into this high-risk zone.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, no deaths of any illegal immigrants by explosions have
been documented. But the Marines and Border Patrol want to step up
their monitoring of the area and warn would-be trespassers to stay
out.
</P>
<P>
   The last fatality was in 1983, when a 35-year-old California
man, Jimmy Watkins, was killed and his father lost a foot when the
two ignored the no-trespassing signs to scavenge for scrap metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't want anybody wandering around out there because
it's very, very dangerous,'' said Capt. Winston Jimenez, spokesman
for the Marine Corps Air Station in Yuma.
</P>
<P>
   Military bomber pilots have been training in the Chocolate
Mountains since World War II. In the early '90s, Harrier jet pilots
practiced there for Desert Storm. Today, the range is the Marine
Corps' busiest aerial weapons training site.
</P>
<P>
   Along with explosives, aircraft also drop flares that hold 20
pounds of sodium nitrate and magnesium that burn at more than 1,000
degrees Fahrenheit. The deadly flares float to the ground on
parachutes and can be suddenly activated when the parachute is
pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   About four times a year, the Marines ordnance disposal unit in
Yuma sweeps through the training sites to remove unexploded
munitions.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the danger of the weaponry is the area's isolation
from sources of help. Although military police patrol the
456,000-acre bombing range and military pilots are warned to fly
over on the lookout for people before dropping munitions, an
injured person could easily die before being found, military
spokesman say.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Border Patrol agents find themselves conducting more and
more rescue missions when illegal immigrants get stranded on the
bombing range.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Rolon, spokesman for the El Centro, Calif., station, says
the smuggling vehicles, in bad shape and packed with people, will
often break down in the harsh terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once things go bad, the smuggler will often abandon the
group,'' Rolon says.
</P>
<P>
   ``On July 2, we brought 18 aliens out of the gunnery range after
their vehicle had broken down and they were out of water,'' Rolon
said.
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, a land and air search was launched when a
citizen alerted the Border Patrol to a group of 31 people,
including a pregnant woman and several children, who were stuck on
the northeastern edge of the bombing range. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
