<HEADER>
A5398 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NADER-MUSEUM-1STLD-WR     07-27 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-MUSEUM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NADER'S MUSEUM OF LIABILITY: CORVAIRS, PINTOS AND IMPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  
 (SUBS for additional information, rewriting, editing changes and
tightening throughout, and to add graphics note)   (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By JONATHAN RABINOWITZ   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTED, Conn. _ Who would want to visit a museum dedicated to
the seemingly arcane topic of tort law?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it would be hard to blame the people of this old mill
town for seeming a bit skeptical that a proposed museum to honor
some of the most reviled professionals in the country _ trial
lawyers _ was a sure-fire way to transform their downtown into a
mecca for weekend visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But listen to Ralph Nader, this town's most famous native son,
as he details his dream of a Museum of American Tort Law and brings
the same passion that started the consumer movement to the unlikely
cause of making personal injury law into a tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be the Pinto with the exploding gas tank, flammable
pajamas, asbestos and breast implants, the whole history of medical
malpractice, and of course the more recent toxic pollution, like
Love Canal,'' Nader said in a telephone interview, sounding like a
carnival barker reeling off a litany of horrors that could rival
the more macabre exhibitions at Madame Tussaud's.
</P>
<P>
   The project manager, Dr. Fred Hyde, remarked that there even
would be a gift shop that would sell ``the tchotchkes of tort
law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, like models of defective toys, products that were
taken off the market,'' added Hyde, a consultant with degrees in
both medicine and law. ``We don't want to trivialize it, but we
want to have a way to memorialize the visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader has taken several steps toward making his vision for a
family outing into reality. He already has the building _ a 19th
century factory that used to make fixtures for coffins _ and he has
raised $1 million of the $5 million he needs for the construction
and startup. That vision, of course, has a distinctly political
edge. He is promoting the museum at a time business groups have
been pushing Congress to pass legislation, known as tort reform,
that would restrict their liabilities and limit damages.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, scheduled to open in late 1999 or early 2000, is
clearly intended to cast a more positive light on the practices
that have resulted in large jury awards to consumers who bought
questionable products (not to mention the lucrative fees for the
lawyers).
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, proponents of tort reform dismiss the whole idea as
little more than propaganda for trial lawyers. ``Mr. Nader should
make sure to have ample parking space for trial lawyers'
his-and-her Learjets,'' mocked Lester Brickman, a professor at
Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law at Yeshiva University, who has
argued that lawyers' contingency fees are too high.
</P>
<P>
   And other critics have wondered aloud about the potential perils
of opening such a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Would it be able to serve hot coffee in a museum cafe for fear
of scalding customers' mouths? Should display cases be built
without sharp corners that could accidentally cut frisky children?
And will lawyers whose work is portrayed in a less-than-flattering
light sue for defamation?
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of this town in the foothills of the Berkshire
Mountains, residents were a bit puzzled by Nader's idea for a
museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a tort?'' asked Monique Goulet, 20, a clerk at Ivery &AMP;
Dudley Pharmacy on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't they the blue laws?'' suggested Bill Wood, owner of the
nearby Deluxe Package Store.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, tort does not refer to laws regulating moral behavior.
And no, it is not that rich cake. It is a legal term for a wrongful
act that can be the basis of a civil lawsuit, though its exact
place in jurisprudence is very much up for debate.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, who rose to prominence in 1965 with his book ``Unsafe at
Any Speed,'' revealing the design flaws of the Chevrolet Corvair
and other automobiles, said the American tort system was not
adequately appreciated by the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tort law, the law of personal injury, was a major step on the
march to justice,'' explained Nader, a 64-year-old graduate of
Harvard Law School who lives in Washington and spends much of his
time writing books and lecturing. ``There's been a lot of attention
to civil liberties but not to physical integrity _ how our law
protects the physical integrity of human beings from harmful
behavior, unsafe products, toxic chemicals or auto crashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lagassey, a 32-year-old machinist who was born and
reared here, said he appreciated Nader's efforts, though he would
prefer to see the building reopen as a factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much suing,'' he said. ``What we need is jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   But it seems unlikely that many manufacturing jobs will return
to Winsted, once an independent city but now a section of the town
of Winchester, population 11,000. Years ago, Winsted was a place
that made clocks, knives and woolen clothes. Today is a poor pocket
in tony Litchfield County, a haven for New Yorkers with country
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's father, a Lebanese immigrant who died in 1991, ran a
restaurant here. His mother, Rose, and a sister, Claire, still live
here. Another sister, Laura, an anthropology professor at the
University of California, Berkeley, spends summers here. And the
family is well known for its involvement in local politics.
</P>
<P>
   While some people here wondered who would come to this museum,
its boosters maintain that educational tourism is booming and that
the number of specialty museums has grown rapidly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has a lantern museum, a garlic museum, 63 medical
museums and 31 lumber and timber museums, not to mention a museum
on every conceivable sport,'' Nader said. ``But no law museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader has solicited design proposals from several prominent
museum design firms. The tort museum was incorporated in
Connecticut earlier this year and has already received pledges of
more than $1 million, said Hyde, with contributions coming from an
all-star cast of trial lawyers as well as figures in the
entertainment industry. The head of the fund-raising committee is a
Knoxville, Tenn., lawyer, J.D. Lee, a pioneer in litigation against
the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to raise $5 million by the end of the year that will
be used to renovate the factory building, establish a Web site and
cover administration costs.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Nader said he hopes to raise another $5 million
so that the museum can lease exhibition space in Washington and
hold conferences in Winsted.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is supposed to be interactive. Nader said that one
area could have re-enactments of famous trials where visitors could
hear the same testimony that actual jurors once heard.
</P>
<P>
   And there will be artifacts, Hyde promised, noting that he
wanted to find a vintage Corvair or an old Pinto fuel tank.
Already, lawyers are calling to donate trial exhibits to the
museum's collection.
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers have to capture a jury's interest, and there are
warehouses full of elaborate trial displays across the country,
Hyde said. ``They're like Hollywood,'' he added. ``Like seeing
Spielberg in a courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader insisted it would all be riveting. ``Some people try to
make fun of the museum, just by the artifacts, but this museum is
much more than that,'' he said. ``It is a tribute to a major
chapter in American history, the great struggle for health and
justice in the environment, workplace and marketplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
