</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEBOOK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINT-SIZE PCS OFFER WINDOWS PERFORMANCE  
 BY DAVID EINSTEIN 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY- NOTEBOOK   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
If you've been looking for a portable computer that you can carry
around without getting a hernia and buy without refinancing your
house, you're in luck.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new category of personal computer called the mininotebook
offers Windows 98 performance in a package that's smaller and
lighter than a conventional notebook PC but bigger and more
user-friendly than handheld PCs with their tiny keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The main contenders in this bantam-weight class include the
Sony 505 ($2,000), the Toshiba Libretto ($1,700), the Hitachi
VisionBook Traveler ($1,650), the Mitsubishi Amity ($1,500) and the
Panasonic CF-M31 ($2,300). All are Windows-based machines, which
means that they will run most applications you can put on a
full-sized notebook or desktop PC.
</P>
<P>
   The Toshiba, Hitachi, Mitsubishi and Panasonic machines measure
about 9 inches by 7 inches _ only three-fifths the size of a
regular notebook. The Sony is bigger, but it's the thinnest of the
bunch. All the units weigh less than 3 pounds _ half the weight of
a regular notebook.
</P>
<P>
   Because you can't alter physics, some trade-offs are necessary
to reduce size. The most important sacrifices are:
</P>
<P>
   _The screen, which measures 7 or 8 inches diagonally in the
mininotebooks (10.4 inches for the Sony), compared with 12 inches
for a typical regular notebook.
</P>
<P>
   _The keyboard, which is about 90 percent the size of a regular
notebook's.
</P>
<P>
   _Mininotebooks have smaller batteries, typically offering less
than two hours between charges.
</P>
<P>
   _There is no CD-ROM drive. An external drive is an option
available for about $300.
</P>
<P>
   There are other minor drawbacks as well. Most mininotebooks have
slower chips than you will find on full-sized models. And they
don't come with modems, though you easily can add a
credit-card-sized modem for exchanging e-mail or surfing the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Inconveniences notwithstanding, mininotebooks are ideal for
business travelers who use their PCs on the road for
correspondence, spreadsheets, e-mail and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they are under three pounds and are full Windows
systems makes them very attractive to real road warriors,'' said
Tim Bajarin, a Silicon Valley research analyst who closely follows
the notebook market.
</P>
<P>
   Whether mininotebooks will catch on in the mainstream market is
debatable. ``They've got a lot of people going `ooh and ah,' but
whether that translates into `Ooh, here's my credit card' remains
to be seen,'' said Dataquest analyst Mike McGuire.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, mininotebooks soon could be eclipsed by a new
generation of devices that are bigger than handheld computers but
smaller than mininotebooks.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``PC companions,'' these under-2-pound contenders use
Windows CE, the streamlined version of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Early entries in this new class include the NEC MobilePro 750C
and the Phenom Ultra from LG (formerly Goldstar), both going for
$899.
</P>
<P>
   PC companions look like full-size notebooks that have been cut
in half length-wise. The color screen is about half the height of a
full-size notebook display. The keyboard also is small. But it's
still large enough for touch-typing without getting instant
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Most PC companions come with built-in modems. Another big
advantage to these little guys is longer battery life _ up to eight
hours for the NEC.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect PC companions to give you everything you get even
with a mininotebook. You can't add applications, so you have to be
content with Windows CE 2.0, which includes ``pocket'' versions of
Word, Excel, Internet Explorer and Outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that's enough to let you do the basic stuff like word
processing, spreadsheets, scheduling and e-mail. Given their
portable size, PC companions could be perfect for students who want
a computer for taking notes in class.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire thinks PC companions have the look of a winner.
``Frankly, we think these are going to out-ship the
ultraportables,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Now that your interest has been piqued, you might want to
hold on for a while longer before snapping up a mininotebook or PC
companion. That's because the next version of Windows CE, version
3.0, is due out soon. It will spawn a generation of more-powerful
mininotebooks and PC companions, and prices on current models will
drop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
