<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GIANTS ARE GOOD. JUST DEAL WITH IT. 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It was a simple kickoff return, one of many
practiced last weekend at the Giants' training camp, but it stirred
the attending fans like nothing else to date at this year's
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   That is because Jason Sehorn, perhaps the team's most popular
player, had caught the kickoff, and with fluid, graceful strides
sprinted up the field behind a developing wedge of blockers.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later during a punt-return exercise there was more
applause. Tiki Barber, who is also among the team's most popular
players, had caught a punt and dashed down the sideline with it.
</P>
<P>
   These are training camp vignettes. They are meant to be frequent
scenes from a long-running regular-season play. At least the Giants
hope it is a long-running play.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is a risk to having two starters _ not to mention
two of your most valuable players _ running upfield, throwing
themselves into the fury of an opponent's special teams squads,
well, the Giants' coaching staff said it is willing to take that
risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a measured risk, but if you examine it, it's not the
return guy who usually gets hurt on special teams,'' Giants Coach
Jim Fassel said. ``Often, it's somebody getting blindsided chasing
the ball. I think Jason will be very good at avoiding people, and I
wouldn't even consider doing it if Jason wasn't so anxious to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, both Sehorn and Barber returned kicks in college. Both
have all but begged the coaching staff to give them the chance to
return kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet I want to do it; I asked them last year if I could
play wide receiver, too,'' Sehorn said. ``There's always a chance
you can get hurt anywhere on a football field. If it's going to
happen, it's going to happen. I don't want to hold myself back
because of the risk of injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber, meanwhile, said he liked his chances after catching a
punt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Why would you want to catch a punt with 11 guys
coming at you at full speed?' '' he said. ``But it's easier to make
something happen that way. You can make some moves when 11 guys are
chasing you and you're just getting out their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a regular play when they hand you the ball, you've got 11
guys standing there waiting for you. That's harder.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the velocity of collisions on special teams that tends
to make those moments among the most dangerous during a game. And
Barber, who at 205 pounds is considered a small running back,
missed four games with a knee injury last season and sat out parts
of another three games with other nicks and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' coaching staff has made some concessions to the
possibility of injury. For example, the staff still hasn't decided
whether to allow Sehorn to return any kickoffs during the four
exhibition games. At most he will get one or two attempts at it.
But in the regular season, he will get a shot, maybe as often as
once or twice a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't be back there every time,'' said Fassel, who added
that he does not fear the criticism he will hear if Sehorn is
injured on a kickoff return.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, two things forced the Giants to consider Sehorn on
the kickoff team. For one, they were in last place in the National
Football League in kickoff returns last season with a 18.9-yard
average. Also, LeShon Johnson, whom the team signed to help return
kickoffs, was found to have lymphoma and is sitting out the season.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, with an offense that ranked 27th in the league, the
coaching staff looked to the punt- and kickoff-return teams as a
way to score, or at the least to assist the offense with superior
field position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between kickoffs and punts, you've got about 100 chances to
give the ball to a guy in the open field with major big-play
potential,'' the Giants' special teams coach, Larry Mac Duff, said.
``How important is that?''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there seems to be no holding Sehorn back. The
topic brings a wide smile to his boyish face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, there's no outcry about me doing this now,'' he said.
``All I hear is everybody in the stands cheering. So if something
happens to me, people have to remember they were cheering.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if I get beat for a touchdown, even better; give me the
ball right away and let me get the points back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
