<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS CAST WARY EYE ON ONE OF THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ After an unbroken 22-year streak of Republican
governors here in Illinois, some prominent Democrats are lamenting
that Republican views will prevail yet again in this year's race _
even if the Democratic candidate wins.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic nominee, Rep. Glenn Poshard, has faced a storm of
criticism from liberals in his party for a starkly conservative
voting record on social issues like abortion, gun control and
homosexual rights.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that liberal voters might sit out the election or,
worse, cast a ballot for the Republican nominee, George Ryan, some
Democrats have met privately with Poshard, imploring him to reach
out to the party's base.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Carol Ronen, a Chicagoan who sits on the party's
state central committee, met with Poshard and later sent him a
letter urging him to ``reassure progressive voters that you are in
the mainstream _ not the fringe.''
</P>
<P>
   Poshard's opponent, Ryan, the Illinois secretary of state, is
certainly no liberal. He is generally opposed to abortion. During
the 1970s, when he was a member of the state legislature, Ryan was
instrumental in defeating the Equal Rights Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   And Poshard is a liberal on economic matters, a champion of
organized labor and a supporter of efforts to raise the federal
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   But Poshard's conservative positions on social issues have given
Ryan a chance to appeal to moderate and liberal voters by casting
the Democrat as an extremist. While Poshard skipped the recent Gay
Pride Parade in Chicago, Ryan had a car in the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who has supported some gun control measures, has also run
television advertisements that seek to cast Poshard as a right-wing
extremist on gun issues.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois is a state that tends to elect political moderates as
governor _ candidates who favor gun control and abortion rights,
and take a pro-business approach, like the current governor, Jim
Edgar, and his predecessor, Jim Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   The social conservatism of Poshard, a five-term congressman,
suits the sensibilities of his rural district, which reaches the
tip of southern Illinois, but riles many voters who live in Chicago
and other northern parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians in Congress have frequently had a difficult time
winning statewide office in Illinois. One politician who was able
to make that jump between its southern and northern reaches, former
Sen. Paul Simon, said Poshard was ``in the process of growing'' as
he ``becomes exposed to the very different perspectives'' of
northern Illinoisans on issues like gun control.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Simon, who is regarded as something of an archangel among the
state's liberals, said Poshard's stands have typically reflected
the views of ``a rural region dominated by Southern Baptists.''
</P>
<P>
   The former senator, who once represented that very southern
Illinois district, has endorsed Poshard's candidacy. ``Glenn has a
gut commitment to helping people who struggle in our society,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Simon also expressed hope that the nominee would ``shift his
position'' on some social issues, given that he would no longer be
representing a single conservative region but rather a big,
culturally diverse statewide constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Poshard has shown little willingness to abandon long-held
positions on abortion and other issues, however, saying that
principle is more important than popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of Poshard, even those who disagree with the Democrat on
certain issues, say that he is a man of strong convictions and that
he would not govern according to the latest public opinion survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very much his own man,'' said Don Johnson, the president
of the Illinois AFL-CIO, which played a crucial role in Poshard's
triumph in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of Johnson, the positions of Poshard on social
issues will not be critical to most voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our members are going fishing with a friend, or they're
out having a beer, they're talking about paychecks and pensions,''
he said, not social issues.
</P>
<P>
   The labor leader lauded Poshard's ``value system'' and his
compassion. He told of Poshard's concern for poor children at the
school in southern Illinois where he taught many years ago.
Noticing that many children wore skimpy coats during the cold
winters, Poshard started a drive to collect donated coats for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was before he ever thought about entering politics,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a side of Poshard that is little-known among many voters.
In recent days, the Democratic candidate has been publicly spurned
by some elected members of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Larry McKeon, the only openly gay member of the
Illinois Legislature, announced earlier this week that he could not
endorse Poshard, who has been cool to measures that would protect
gay Illinoisians from discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, three Democratic mayors of Chicago's southern
suburbs announced that they could not endorse Poshard because he
has not favored construction of an airport in Peotone, about 50
miles south of the city. Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr. has also withheld
his endorsement, citing the airport issue, which he believes would
bring development to some struggling towns south of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ronen, whose district is more than two-thirds Democratic,
said she had heard plenty of skepticism about Poshard among her
constituents. She said she remained optimistic that Poshard would
court liberals, but that time was slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not doing well in a district that's this strongly
Democratic,'' Ms. Ronen, said, ``that does not auger well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
