<SLUG> BC-GTE-BELL-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: PHONE MERGERS ARE HEATED GAME OF MUSICAL CHAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be a stretch to say that Bell Atlantic Corp. and GTE
Corp., two of the United States' biggest local phone companies,
have agreed to a $52.8 billion merger out of fear. But not much of
a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of deal-making in the telecommunications industry has
quickened to the point that it resembles a high-stakes version of
the children's game ``duck-duck-goose,'' with multibillion-dollar
corporations desperate to get one of the gargantuan seats that will
allow them to remain at the top tier of communications carriers in
the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   With competitors old and new joining forces all around them,
Bell Atlantic, with $30.2 billion in revenue last year, and GTE,
with $23.3 billion, simply felt too small to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like keeping up with the Joneses,'' said one executive
close to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   It is not difficult to understand the competitive anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   If Bell Atlantic completes its acquisition of GTE and if SBC
Communications Inc. completes its $62 billion acquisition of
Ameritech Corp., the nation's eight largest local phone companies
will have become four since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if Worldcom Inc. completes its $37 billion
acquisition of MCI Communications Corp., the nation's four largest
long-distance companies will have become three. One of the three,
AT&AMP;T Corp., also plans to acquire the No. 2 cable television
company, Tele-Communications Inc., for $31.8 billion and over the
weekend announced a $10 billion international joint venture with
British Telecommunications PLC, Britain's dominant phone company.
</P>
<P>
   So, as Bell Atlantic continues an advertising campaign featuring
drawings of monsters from the children's book ``Where the Wild
Things Are,'' the metaphor remains apt.
</P>
<P>
   For Bell Atlantic's top executives, the hardest question to
answer about acquiring GTE may not have been ``Why?'' but ``Why
not?'' After all, Bell Atlantic will actually pay slightly less
than GTE's market value, according to executives close to the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the two companies' shares trade at roughly comparable
multiples to earnings. (As of Monday's close, Bell Atlantic's
shares were worth 16.5 times estimated 1998 earnings and GTE's
shares were worth a multiple of 18.2.)
</P>
<P>
   That means that acquiring GTE will probably not dilute Bell
Atlantic's shares to a degree that would encourage institutional
investors to mount a huge sell-off of Bell Atlantic stock.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the telecommunications industry, with its high
fixed costs and low incremental costs, fuels corporate
consolidation and partnerships. In deal after deal,
telecommunications executives say they can make their acquisitions
add to earnings by wringing savings out of their combined
companies, even without revenue ``synergies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the big factors behind the flood of telecommunications deals
are not so much financial, at least in the short term, as they are
strategic.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, almost every big telecommunications company in the
United States is trying to get big enough to offer almost any sort
of communications service to just about anyone anywhere. The fear
in the industry, the fear that lurks behind many of the
multibillion-dollar acquisitions, is: If I don't do it, my
competitors will.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for product plans, geographic expansions and even
acquisitions themselves. People close to the negotiations said
Monday that BellSouth Corp. had expressed interest in GTE. For Bell
Atlantic, seeing GTE go to BellSouth would have been like the
general manager of a sports franchise watching an attractive free
agent join a divisional rival.
</P>
<P>
   A difference is that while professional athletic teams rarely,
if ever, acquire their competitors, Bell Atlantic and BellSouth
could very well pursue a merger of their own at some point.
</P>
<P>
   For Bell Atlantic, GTE brings experience in the long-distance
phone market and in high-speed data systems. Those are areas where
AT&AMP;T, the nation's biggest communications company, excels. Now that
AT&AMP;T is trying to get into the local market through its TCI deal,
Bell Atlantic is stepping up its efforts to go after AT&AMP;T's bread
and butter.
</P>
<P>
   The next stage may well be big international alliances for local
phone companies. Cable and Wireless PLC of Britain has long been
rumored as a potential partner for Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phone companies like SBC and Bell Atlantic have their eyes on
the next round, which is when they ask permission to link to
foreign carriers,'' said Dwight Allen, a telecommunications
consultant for Deloitte &AMP; Touche. ``They are trying to educate the
regulators that what is unthinkably large today might not be
adequate tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5430 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-WESTON-MENTAL     07-27 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-WESTON-MENTALHEALTH-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BOSTON: he said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A judge committed Weston to the Warm Springs hospital for 53
days in 1996, apparently after Weston made a threat against
President Clinton and was interviewed by the Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   After being placed on medication, he was released on Dec. 2,
1996, because the hospital ``deemed him no longer a threat to
himself or others,'' according to a spokesman for Gov. Marc
Racicot. A hospital employee drove him to his cabin in nearby
Rimini, the spokesman said, and made arrangements for him to
receive further treatment at a mental health center in Waterloo,
Ill., near his parents' rural home outside Valmeyer in southern
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn described this as ``Greyhound therapy,'' a way to save
Montana money by buying Weston a one-way bus ticket for a trip out
of the state.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews on Sunday, Weston's parents and
sister, April Callahan, said that he returned to Illinois with
three medications (whose names they did not remember) and that he
stopped taking them about a week later, despite his family's
protests. While his family described their growing concern over his
paranoid delusions, they also seemed to understand little about how
to seek help for him, or what treatment was available.
</P>
<P>
   The only community mental health clinic in Waterloo is Human
Support Services, a state-funded center. A spokesman for the
clinic, Rob Singer, refused to say on Monday whether Weston had
been a client there after his return from Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Torrey said people like Weston would be less likely to fall
through the cracks if states like Montana and Illionois used
existing laws that provide for involuntary outpatient treatment.
Such laws allow states to force a patient to take his medication if
he fails to show up for appointments at a local clinic or stops
taking his medication.
</P>
<P>
   Preventing a shooting like that attributed to Weston is
particularly difficult because the relationship between mental
illness and violence is very sensitive, and many experts have been
cautious about publicizing new research suggesting that in certain
situations the emotionally disturbed are more violent than other
people.
</P>
<P>
   Such situations occur when mentally ill persons have strong
paranoid symptoms that someone is out to get them or hear a voice
telling them to kill, said Bruce Link, a professor at Columbia
University School of Public Health. Another is when a patient fails
to show up for treatment or is off his medication, said Jeffrey
Sawnson, an assistant professor of psychiatry at Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, a MacArthur Foundation study found that mental
patients are no more violent than others unless they are abusing
drugs or alcohol. And Swanson said it is important to remember that
the mentally ill are responsible for only about 4 percent of
overall violence, making mental illness a smaller risk factor for
violence than being young, male or poor. But in a sign of how the
experts disagree on the subject, Torrey stressed that mentally ill
people commit 1,000 homicides a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
