<HEADER>
A5433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-NYT &LR;      07-27 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY LEWINSKY IS DEALING 
</HEADLINE>
   (With CLINTON-STARR) 
 (sw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Since January, independent counsel Kenneth Starr
has insisted that prosecutors would not grant immunity to Monica
Lewinsky unless they first met with her and judged her credibility
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no substitute for looking a witness in the eye,''
Starr has said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, six months and 10 days after the former White House
intern walked away from Starr's request that she cooperate with his
inquiry on an undercover basis, Starr's prosecutors finally looked
Ms. Lewinsky in the eye, meeting with her for five hours at an
undisclosed location in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The months-long obstacle to an immunity deal had always been how
the two sides would begin their alliance; Ms. Lewinsky had objected
to meeting before being assured she would get an immunity deal.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she changed her mind. Monday's secret meeting was the
idea of Starr's prosecutors. In a phone call last Thursday on Ms.
Lewinsky's 25th birthday, prosecutors invited her to sit down to
discuss the terms of an agreement. After consulting her lawyers,
she accepted.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides decided not to meet in Washington or Los Angeles,
where television reporters routinely follow Ms. Lewinsky's
movements. Although the choice of New York, the nation's media
capital, might seem odd, one lawyer said it was ``a neutral site''
preferred by Ms. Lewinsky because her mother and stepfather live
there.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Monday, both sides said they believe the meeting was a
successful first step toward an immunity deal. There are tentative
plans for another meeting later this week here, two lawyers with
knowledge of the discussion said on Monday night. It could not be
learned whether Starr is insisting that Ms. Lewinsky plead guilty
to a crime.
</P>
<P>
   In past negotiations with Ms. Lewinsky over the terms of a
possible deal for immunity, Starr's prosecutors had insisted that
she take a polygraph test. Two lawyers said that the subject was
not raised on Monday, but it could emerge as an important issue at
subsequent meetings.
</P>
<P>
   In a sworn affidavit given in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct
lawsuit against the president, Ms. Lewinsky said she had not had a
sexual relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier discussions with prosecutors, Ms. Lewinsky indicated
that she would be willing to testify that the two did have a sexual
relationship, according to lawyers familiar with the initial talks.
</P>
<P>
   Besides affording prosecutors the opportunity to ask questions
of Ms. Lewinsky and begin judging her credibility, the meeting laid
the building blocks for a likely immunity agreement that Ms.
Lewinsky had long sought and that Clinton's lawyers and White House
aides had always feared.
</P>
<P>
   According to two lawyers with knowledge of Monday's discussions,
Ms. Lewinsky told prosecutors nearly the same story that she had
told them in January. She again told them that Clinton did not urge
her to lie about their relationship, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting also sent a powerful message to Clinton and his
lawyers on the eve of the date that prosecutors had summoned him to
testify: Ms. Lewinsky may soon be in a position to testify against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must be sweating now,'' an associate of Ms. Lewinsky's said
on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   News of the secret meeting came as a surprise to some of the
president's lawyers and aides. Now that Ms. Lewinsky's testimony
looms as a possibility, several aides went out of their way to say
conciliatory things about her.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own view is Monica is still probably crazy about the
president, and does not want to hurt him,'' one senior adviser
said. ``I feel sorry for her. This has been an excruciating period
of time for her, just awful.''
</P>
<P>
   The terms of an immunity deal for Ms. Lewinsky have been
contentious since January. When she was first confronted by FBI
agents at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel in Arlington, Va., on Jan. 16, she
met with lawyers in Starr's office for nearly eight hours. They
asked her to cooperate. She rejected the offer.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of January, William Ginsburg, who was then her
lawyer, submitted a ``proffer,'' an outline of what Ms. Lewinsky
would be willing to say, to the prosecutors. Ginsburg had sought to
have a federal judge enforce an immunity agreement that he said the
prosecutors had signed. But the prosecutors convinced the judge
overseeing the grand jury inquiry, Norma Holloway Johnson, that no
agreement had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   An associate of Ms. Lewinsky said on Monday night that she was
pleased with the meeting on Monday and looks forward to cooperating
with Starr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
