<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5436 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-700     07-27 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MORIBUND COUTURE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By AMY M. SPINDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Here's an idea from a couture house this season: At the
dawning of the new millennium, we'll either be partying (thus
wearing tinsels, pompoms, streamers and confetti) or be victims of
mass destruction (thus wearing clothes shaped by the atom bomb).
There are two clues that the concept isn't from a top couturier,
but from an upstart house, Viktor &AMP; Rolf. The first clue is that
it's difficult to imagine Nan Kempner and Anne Bass in
mushroom-shaped togs. But the second is that it's an idea. And
ideas are something that top couturiers are seemingly waiting until
the millennium to share.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to recall a more moribund couture season, and
it's difficult to imagine that anything but the millennium is to
blame. While the rest of the world waits for the millennium bug to
come and eat its computers, the fashion community seems to be
expecting one to release a virus of creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor &AMP; Rolf, designed by Viktor Horsting and Rolf Snoeren,
offered ensembles in their show stuffed with fun things like
balloons, tinsel and confetti, and then they showed some of the
same outfits with all the fun stuff taken out, so that roomy drape
was left over. Those five outfits were called Anticlimax. The rest
of the Paris designers showed all of their outfits with the fun
stuff taken out. They called those outfits couture.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the pretense that couture lives up to its mission of
being a laboratory of ideas has been abandoned. But when did it
start being a wasteland?
</P>
<P>
   What has drained the last bit of life from the five-day schedule
is that the designers who were supposed to liven things up _ John
Galliano at Christian Dior and Alexander McQueen at Givenchy _ are
as predictable as those twice their age. The only designer who
wasn't creatively stingy this time around was Jean Paul Gaultier.
While other designers have their eyes on the millennium, Gaultier
had his on the couture crown, and he handily walked away with it
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at the end of the Yves Saint Laurent runway, Gaultier
looked every bit the obvious successor for the ladies on hand. It
has become tradition to marvel at the beauty of the Saint Laurent
show, even if every perfect ensemble is a familiar friend to those
in the front row, who are often wearing outfits that seem identical
to the ones taking their turn on the runway as part of the new
collection. Every year, when younger and younger fashion editors
arrive in Paris and don't quite understand what the big fuss is
about Saint Laurent, their elders patiently explain how
controversial, how hip, how surprising every Saint Laurent show
once was.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected to have to educate the young about Saint Laurent.
But did anyone ever expect to have to explain to them about Karl
Lagerfeld? It wasn't so long ago that Lagerfeld, at Chanel, defined
the entire season with whatever silhouette and cool new accessory
he had invented. Perhaps he defined the season this time, too, with
a shapeless silhouette, a blank slate of coloration and utterly
noncommittal clothes. It was a quiet, pretty look, skirts open in
the back to reveal starchy slips, pockets placed to give clothes a
soft slump. But it certainly wasn't the look that is going to put
society women back in Chanel suits and fashion editors back in
Chanel shoes, or to tempt strained Asian markets to take out their
credit cards. And it certainly won't start anyone talking.
</P>
<P>
   But the couture seems to have gone back to the days when women
bought it so that they wouldn't be talked about. There was
certainly little risk of that from these runways. The art form that
for years has been written off as a publicity ploy now coyly wants
to be pretty and practical. So, the season was defined by designers
who have made their ladies classically beautiful for years, like
Valentino, Oscar de la Renta at Pierre Balmain, Christian LaCroix
and Saint Laurent, not by those who have injected heat and light
into couture's cloistered corridors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Once again, what is considered modern is minimalism. This is the
second time that Lagerfeld's Chanel collection has looked to
Japanese designers for inspiration, the first time being a bout
with deconstruction he borrowed to fray Chanel suits years ago. But
the sensibility is familiar today from the ready-to-wear runways of
Donna Karan, who has embraced the Zenlike esthetic for seasons, so
it may seem out of place in couture to clients. The most visible
touches of the atelier's hand were in geometric embroideries that
were subtle decoration.
</P>
<P>
   That abstract decoration was one of the few trends of the
season, showing up at Valentino to give an icy gleam to the
designer's familiar silhouettes, skirts all covering the knees.
Surfaces looked scratched as if by a knife on glass, giving the
wispy dresses edge. Silk piping gave hard corners to another dress
where the top was formed by the intersecting pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the exuberance that has defined Lacroix for years was
buried in black this season, but what couldn't be hidden even in
those tones was the depth of the work, the play of textures in the
simplest black coat or the layers of detail in the easiest mohair
sweater. And when Lacroix worked denim to make a suit of intricate
braiding, or put fringed crochet over a devore velvet flowered
skirt, there was more magic in those two looks than in all of the
couture shows in Paris put together.
</P>
<P>
   At Pierre Balmain, de la Renta was inspired by St. Petersburg.
He produced a gentle collection full of charm, with fur-trimmed
pants cropped at the knee, mandarin-collar dresses with golden
embroidery, tunics over slim trousers and glowing jade gowns edged
in mink.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what was missing most from the shows was just a sense of
conviction, from the designers, the fashion editors and even the
buyers who attend to look for trends. In the past, couture has
seemed redundant with ready-to-wear, but it has never felt so much
so. There has always been, in the past, a determination in couture
that it make a case for itself. Either designers are convinced that
the case was proved long ago or, as clients add walkers and canes
to their more decorative accessories, designers have accepted the
inevitable end of an era. It is what was always predicted by Pierre
Berge, Saint Laurent's business partner, who presided with his
usual iron fist over the poignantly gentle showing of soft chiffon
dresses, slim velvet columns and tidy tweedy pants suits at Saint
Laurent.
</P>
<P>
   But what seems to be slowing the pace of fashion more than
anything is the fact that designers are watching the millennium
clock. Nearly every designer's news release had some reference to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Designers know that all artists are defined by their century.
Maybe they've done enough to be well represented in museum
exhibitions and retrospectives many years hence. Maybe for them,
the postgame party has already started. So it seemed at Thierry
Mugler, who closed the couture season last Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   There were serious pieces, like a herringbone dress frayed
gently at the edges with a spider-web stole over the top, or
impressive, thick knit tunics over slim skirts. But most of the
collection was made up of clothes decorated in fake gorilla hair
and monkey fur, some modeled by Jerry Hall and her daughter
Elizabeth Scarlett. Maybe the millennium will lead to designers'
creating couture that is inventive, eloquent and full of ideas. Or
maybe it will just lead them to create costumes for the remake of
``Planet of the Apes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
