<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-NY-COLISEUM     07-27 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-NY-COLISEUM-757&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE OF COLISEUM TO TIME WARNER, RELATED COS. IS EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
 (bl)  
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Metropolitan Transportation Authority is expected
to approve the sale Wednesday of the New York Coliseum, one of the
most treasured and star-crossed development sites in Manhattan, to
Time Warner and Related Cos. for a hotel and residential complex
that will also include a world headquarters and digital television
studio for Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of a tentative deal that will go to the MTA
board Wednesday for final approval, real estate executives and
government officials say the Related-Time Warner partnership will
pay about $345 million for the tract on Columbus Circle, at the
southwest corner of Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Related plans to build a pair of towers that would stand 750
feet over Columbus Circle and instantly create a soaring landmark
for a parcel of real estate that is the gateway to Times Square,
the Upper West Side and the luxury hotels on Central Park South.
</P>
<P>
   The 2.1-million-square-foot project would house Time Warner's
headquarters and broadcast facilities for the Cable News Network
and NY1, as well as a 425-room Mandarin Oriental Hotel, 325
condominiums and a 1,000-seat concert hall for Jazz at Lincoln
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The sale would mark another milestone in a tortuous 14-year
effort to sell the land, and it would conclude a wary political
dance between Gov. George Pataki and the MTA, which owns the land,
and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's administration, which has effective
veto power over any project.
</P>
<P>
   The first attempt to sell the property began during the
administration of Mayor Edward Koch in 1985 and ended nine years
later amid a recession and a flurry of lawsuits and community
opposition. A year ago, the MTA was on the verge of selling the
Coliseum site to Millennium Partners when Giuliani suddenly vowed
that he would block the deal unless it included a live theater or
performance space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a tremendous relief to the city, the state and many
New Yorkers to see the disposition of this trophy site finally
settled,'' said Mary Ann Tighe, executive managing director at
Insignia/Edward S. Gordon, a real estate company. ``The good news
about the years of struggle is that it appears that the winner is
going to create a structure that reflects Columbus Circle's role as
a crossroad of business, entertainment and tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no guarantee that the proponents of the latest plan
will fare better than previous efforts. The Related proposal does
appear to have the support of some civic groups, including the
Municipal Arts Society, which helped block earlier proposals for
the largely dormant Coliseum site. But some local residents are
vowing to derail what they still consider to be an oversized
project. The Committee for Environmentally Sound Development has
already filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Manhattan
challenging the proposed development on environmental grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll proceed with the lawsuit, an injunction, whatever's
necessary,'' Olive Freud, vice president of the committee, said
Monday. ``It's a very sad day. The city's being choked and nobody
seems to care. The only people getting anything out of this are the
developer and the bondholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Randy Levine and the MTA declined comment, as did
Related Cos. chairman Stephen M. Ross, whose Madison Avenue office
provides a spectacular view of the Coliseum site and who, friends
say, has long wanted to own the parcel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   MTA Chairman Virgil Shaw met Monday afternoon with Giuliani at
City Hall to settle on the winning bidder. The MTA's selection
committee is meeting this morning to review the deal, before making
a formal recommendation to the MTA board Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months city officials and the MTA have worked hard to
keep their top choices from becoming public knowledge, in hopes of
avoiding the kind of delay that occurred a year ago when Giuliani
suddenly blocked the MTA's plan to sell the site to Millennium
after word had filtered out that Millennium was the agency's top
choice.
</P>
<P>
   After months of delays, the city and state required developers
to include a 100,000-square-foot home for Jazz at Lincoln Center.
Bidding by five finalists finally resumed in April, although
Millennium had been negotiating with Jazz at Lincoln Center for two
years to build a new home at a different location.
</P>
<P>
   During the last week, the Related-Time Warner proposal edged out
its four competitors, including Donald Trump, the high bidder, who
threatened a lawsuit if he did not win.
</P>
<P>
   The real competition was between Millennium, which was planning
two luxury hotels, a large ballroom and 450 apartments, and
Related, which had the support of City Hall, mainly because of its
prominent tenant: Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   During the bid negotiations during the last four months,
Benjamin Lambert, the real estate consultant hired by the MTA, used
Trump's bid to force Millennium, Related and another bidder,
Tishman Speyer Properties, to increase their offers.
</P>
<P>
   With Related offering nearly the same contract terms as
Millennium, the MTA negotiators eventually came around to the
city's choice.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, Time Warner is expected to ask the city for
tax breaks and other incentives, a request that may put the
Giuliani administration in a quandary. The city has provided
similar incentives to many large corporations. But in May 1997,
Giuliani withdrew a tax break worth $50 million for luxury
apartments on the Coliseum site, saying a rebounding real estate
market made the subsidies unnecessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2252EDT &QL; 
