<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCHANNEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF CHANNEL PROVES TO BE A HIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICK HIPES  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Five months ago, Jack Nicklaus said he
rediscovered his old swing, the swing that helped him to 70 PGA
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Jack's old magic was back not because of extra time put in at
the driving range or a chalk talk with links guru David Leadbetter.
It was because of the Golf Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accuracy of my golf shots have improved greatly because of
it,'' Nicklaus told the South Florida Sun-Sentinel. ``It wouldn't
have happened if I had not watched the 1965 Masters tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Nicklaus watches the Golf Channel, and he is by no means
alone. After a quiet debut in January of 1995, the 24-hour
all-golf, all-the-time cable network has continually exceeded its
own expectations. Now, after a recent agreement with mini-dish
company Primestar, the Orlando-based company is hoping to reach 25
million subscribers by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The network has hooked millions of fans from PGA Tour pros to
weekend duffers, glued to coverage of everything from the Nike Tour
to documentaries of classic tournaments, like Nicklaus'
self-inspirational '65 Masters victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just started watching it, but my clients are fully
addicted to it,'' said Van Nuys Golf Course pro Wayne Tyni, who
must pry players from the pro-shop television to keep a lesson
time. ``A lot of them, they watch eight or nine hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The network, available on 45 cable systems in Southern
California from Anaheim to Victorville, began as the brainchild of
Alabama cable entrepreneur Joseph Gibbs. In August of 1991, he
commissioned a Gallup survey to test the idea. After favorable
feedback, he convinced Arnold Palmer of the potential and the two
became co-founders of the network, which launched in earnest on
Jan. 17, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the Golf Channel offered fans of the game
golf-at-all-costs programming. In the first year, starting with the
European Tour's Dubai Desert Classic, the network offered 64
domestic and international events, nightly news, a call-in show,
celebrity interviews and instructional tips.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics scoffed at the lineup, asking aloud who would watch
nonstop action of men walking about in checkered pants. Gibbs, who
raised $9.3 million in start-up cash, never blinked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely believed it was going to succeed,'' said Gibbs
from his production facility in Orlando. ``The original research
showed 44 million people either enjoyed playing or watching golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to shrewd deals with cable operators and satellite
systems around the country, the Golf Channel quickly picked up
speed. Sponsorship deals with Callaway Golf, Anheuser-Busch and
General Motors legitimized the network, and solid journalism _
strong interviews, reporting and documentary work _ made the
nonevents credible.
</P>
<P>
   By December of 1995 the network had 1.4 million subscribers. A
month later, Gibbs announced the year's advertising revenue doubled
the year before _ with 11 months remaining in the year. When the
Primestar deal was announced last month, the number of subscribers
was at 15.5 million, the network available in Japan and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be as big as it is now and even bigger
than it is now,'' he said. ``I anticipate it will continue to
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   The blossoming of the network means more innovative, original
programming will complement an already successful lineup. It also
means golf pros like Van Nuys' Tyni must continue stealing the
remote control from pro-shop TVs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Tyni said with a chuckle, ``it does more harm
than good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
