<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Buying GTE for $52.8 Billion in Stock
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, which dominates the local telephone business from
Maine to Virginia, plans to acquire GTE, the United States' largest
independent local and long-distance communications company, for
$52.8 billion in stock. The companies plan to announce the deal
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is the latest in a torrent of
multibillion-dollar mergers in the telecommunications industry. By
acquiring GTE, Bell Atlantic would become the nation's largest
local phone company, serving more than 62 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   American Express Beats Estimates
</P>
<P>
   American Express reported an 11 percent gain in second-quarter
earnings, mainly because of heavy use of its credit card and record
purchases of mutual funds. The results at the travel and
financial-services company exceeded expectations, and its stock
rose 5.37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The strong earnings at American Express lifted stocks. The Dow
Jones industrial average leaped above 9,000, rising 90.88 points,
to 9,028.24. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed 6.47
points, to 1,147.27, and the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite
index gained 2.27 points, to 1,933.26.
</P>
<P>
   Deal Near in Strike at Two GM Plants
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators are putting in long hours trying to resolve strikes
at two General Motors parts factories in Flint, Mich. Union
officials, with much to lose and little to gain, had a particularly
strong incentive to settle before an arbitration ruling on the
strikes' legality that could come as soon as Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Slump in Russia
</P>
<P>
   Russian stocks, which fell 17 percent last week, dropped another
9.1 percent, putting prices back to their levels before the
International Monetary Fund pledged to help avert default with more
loans. The market selloff reflected resilient investor doubts about
whether the government can extricate Russia from seemingly
intractable debts.
</P>
<P>
   A Nasdaq Market Maker Is Fined
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory arm of the National Association of Securities
Dealers censured and fined Troster Singer Corp., one of the
nation's oldest and largest market making firms, for fraud in
connection with 28 intentional Nasdaq trade reporting violations in
1994. The firm agreed to pay $950,000. Six Troster Singer employees
were sanctioned and fined a total of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Home Resales Fell Slightly in June
</P>
<P>
   Sales of existing single-family homes slipped 2.3 percent in
June, but remained robust. The seasonally adjusted annual sales
rate was 4.72 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf Group Buys Other Agencies
</P>
<P>
   Larry Wolf, the chief executive of privately held Wolf Group
Integrated Communications, has been described as ``the most
successful unknown advertising man in Canada.'' But he is trying to
change that by buying advertising agencies in the United States and
Canada with the goal of becoming a top-20 agency company in
billings.
</P>
<P>
   CBS Retreats From Cable Channel
</P>
<P>
   CBS will cede management of the CBS Eye on People cable channel
to Discovery Communications because of what the network called
significant losses. Discovery will acquire a 50 percent interest in
what will become a joint venture, and CBS will be dropped from the
name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
