<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-PROSTITUTES-ART-55     07-27 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-PROSTITUTES-ART-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY TASK FORCE FOCUSES ON CRIMES AGAINST PROSTITUTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ The woman known as Soft Touch stood barefoot on
the sidewalk by her house in the Central Ward and watched the
customized van glide gently to the curb. At 9 o'clock on a Friday
night, it could mean only one thing _ another ``date.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was off Friday night. She crossed her arms and began to
walk away. She had reached the gate to her tiny yard when a man in
a business suit stepped out of the van and called her name. At the
sound of his voice, she stopped and turned around.
</P>
<P>
   ``That you, Malik?'' she asked the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, all right,'' she drawled with a nod and a grin.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 10 minutes, Soft Touch, 33, a prostitute who
refused to give her real name, and Malik, a captain in the Essex
County prosecutor's office whose real name is Louis Portella Jr.,
stood on the street doing what they have done almost every night
for the last three months: discuss the unsolved slayings of 14
prostitutes killed in the county since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The neglected cases, all involving black women, touched a nerve
in Patricia A. Hurt, who became the county's first black female
prosecutor in January. In her first official act, Ms. Hurt made
these murders a high priority of her office and created a task
force to investigate them.
</P>
<P>
   While members of the task force have yet to solve any of the
original 14 killings, their constant presence on the street has led
directly to the arrests of seven men for crimes against prostitutes
that range from an unrelated murder to sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   In making these arrests, members of the task force have tried to
strike a delicate balance between getting close, but not too close,
to the prostitutes. While investigators need the invaluable
information that only these women can provide and sometimes turn a
blind eye to their soliciting, they cannot afford to give the
appearance of shielding the prostitutes, whose very occupations
violate the law.
</P>
<P>
   But even after just four months, the investigators have
succeeded in shedding new light on a world of violence and despair
that continues to exist in Essex County.
</P>
<P>
   The task force, composed of 14 detectives from agencies around
the county, embodies Ms. Hurt's profoundly held belief that
law-enforcement officers must go out of their way to protect
vulnerable segments of society.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, the prostitutes thought we would be bad for
business,'' Ms. Hurt said in a recent interview. ``But we won over
the confidence of a lot of women once they realized that we are
there, in a sense, as their advocates.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. Hurt said that many streetwalkers live in fear of
their lives, she added that her investigators had managed to
convince the women that they were on their side.
</P>
<P>
   Portella, a tall but gentle-looking man who could pass for the
owner of a bowling alley, is the head of the task force. In 22
years with the Newark Police Department, many spent patrolling
streets where prostitutes worked their trade, Portella, 60,
developed a rapport with the women, a rap-and-banter friendliness
that, he said, has won him credibility and respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing you can give these women is your
word,'' he said. ``And these individuals are the best source of
information in the early hours. Nobody sees it, nobody hears it
quicker than a prostitute out on the street.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A few short blocks in central Newark form one hub of the
county's prostitution trade. On a recent stormy night, children,
shirtless and thin, spun black umbrellas on their shoulders and old
men sipped at brown-bagged beers beneath the lighted shelter of a
yellow bodega awning. Music, warped by speed, blared from passing
cars. And in the midst of it came the Stroll, as investigators call
it _ the nightly parade of prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical case developed from working the Stroll, the task
force arrested Bharat Malde, 31, of Roselle, who was indicted on
July 8 on charges that he posed as a police officer and assaulted
or sexually harassed five women after luring them into what he
claimed was his unmarked squad car.
</P>
<P>
   The task force learned of Malde by canvassing central Newark and
talking to prostitutes who knew him from the Stroll. Without the
task force, Portella said, there may never have been a case against
Malde. The women who the task force says were his victims, all
prostitutes, never filed claims with the police.
</P>
<P>
   To make such cases, members of the task force have taught
prostitutes to jot down license plate numbers each time they climb
into a client's car. The task force members have taught the
prostitutes to remember names, identifying features, even unusual
sexual tastes.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the investigators have given assistance where it is
due: a well-placed word to a presiding judge, a couple of dollars
on a quiet Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wealth of information they have reaped,
investigators acknowledge that maintaining relationships with women
who break the law is a delicate, risky business _ particularly in
light of the discovery in New York City earlier this month that at
least 20 police officers and commanders in Manhattan's Midtown
South Precinct may have protected prostitutes in exchange for free
sex for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Portella adamantly denied that his investigators had anything
but a working relationship with the prostitutes they use as
informers, and he said he was concerned that the developments
across the Hudson could hinder his efforts. ``Any time cops get
into trouble, whether it's with prostitutes or narcotics, it
doesn't help us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what we're doing here is altogether different from what's
going on in New York,'' he said, largely because the prostitutes
involved in his investigations need help.
</P>
<P>
   While his investigators might turn a blind eye to soliciting or
to drug use, Portella said, they have no qualms about arresting a
prostitute who robs a man or breaks more serious laws.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators have chosen to focus on protecting
prostitutes. ``There is no conflict here, because we're never going
to eliminate prostitution,'' said Det. Al Burroughs, who joined the
task force after serving 10 years in the Newark Police Department.
``We're talking about people with nothing _ no education, no job
skills, no family _ except a knowledge of the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs maintained that his leniency was beneficial both to
the women and to his own investigative efforts. ``They're the ones
we turn to for information,'' he said. ``Who was in the red car
last night? Who was last seen with Soft Touch? Who was running from
the house on Sherman Avenue?''
</P>
<P>
   Although task force members say that information is easy to come
by on the streets, the investigators face a difficult problem. They
are compelled to build cases for a jury with testimony that comes
from notoriously suspect sources: prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one thing to understand when you're dealing with
prostitutes as witnesses,'' said Patrick Toscano, Essex County's
first assistant prosecutor. ``When you cast a play in hell, you
can't expect to get angels as actors.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Toscano said he did not believe that the
indictments already returned would be damaged by the reputation of
the witnesses. ``Just because you've prostituted yourself,'' he
said, ``doesn't mean you weren't beaten or raped.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newark has taken significant steps toward economic revival in
the last nine months, largely because of the New Jersey Performing
Arts Center, a grand glass-shelled structure that opened downtown
last October. The arts center has not only drawn suburbanites, who
once feared Newark, to the city, it has also formed the anchor for
a miniature boom in real estate speculation in recent months and
paved the way for other potentially lucrative tenants to relocate
in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   But by and large, the revival has failed to reach the wooden
frame houses and brick apartment buildings of central Newark, where
prostitutes say they have seen few signs of urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Though Newark's rate of serious crime plunged to a 30-year low
in 1997, the talk of Sherman Avenue and its surroundings in the
last three months has been of the prostitute murders, not of
falling crime statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared every night I go out,'' said a prostitute in a
tattered black dress who gave her name only as Theresa. ``I've been
out here three years, and it's just getting more violent.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of these women say they are grateful for the efforts
of the task force.
</P>
<P>
   Outside a lighted bodega window, a prostitute in a dark blue
halter top and cut-off denim shorts, who gave her name only as
Jackie, told Portella and Burroughs about a man she said she
believed was responsible for the murder of a streetwalker whom the
police know only as Yasmeen.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, not one of the 14 prostitutes on Ms. Hurt's original
list, was killed in 1991, investigators say, after stealing $2,700
from a client's pocket so smoothly that she was able to snatch the
big bills and return the singles to his wallet unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard it was a pimp who did it,'' Jackie said. ``He rides
around in Jheri curls. I think his name is Prince. He be getting
girls to take him out and then I don't see them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories one hears on the Stroll are often bound with the
twin threads of violence and strength. And the women who tell them
seem to possess a startling fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after speaking with Jackie, a third prostitute walked
past the two investigators, and Burroughs, with a rapid sideways
glance, approached her. Giving her name as only Iris, she said had
been kidnapped by a customer in 1990 and taken to his house, where
she was raped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in all the newspapers,'' Iris said, with a clinical
tone. ``I had to jump out the window and run up on the roof to
hide.'' Emergency workers later found her there, battered but
alive, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie, who had stayed to listen to Iris' tale, said, ``We see
all things.'' She added, ``For myself, I let my clients think I'm
not paying attention. But don't try nothing funny with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If something happens,'' she said, as the investigators stood
and listened, ``we both going to the hospital. I'm going to take
him out, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
