<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEOS-PHONE-MERGER-300     07-27 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEOS-PHONE-MERGER-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GTE AND BELL ATLANTIC CEOS BET ON POWER-SHARING AND PATIENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (js) 
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ivan Seidenberg, the chief executive of Bell Atlantic Corp., may
be the most patient executive in corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Seidenberg started as a cable-splicer's assistant at New York
Telephone out of high school at the age of 19 and rose steadily in
rank to become chairman, only to relinquish that position
temporarily when he merged Nynex Corp. with Bell Atlantic two years
ago, stepping aside so Raymond Smith, Bell Atlantic's chairman,
could hold the top job for a time.
</P>
<P>
   And now Seidenberg, joining the rush to consolidate in the
telecommunications industry with the expected announcement Tuesday
that Bell Atlantic will acquire GTE Corp., has agreed to accept the
second slot again on the organization chart.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the deal call for Seidenberg, 51, to be president
and co-chief executive of the merged company. Charles Lee, 58 and
is now the chairman of GTE, will be chairman and co-chief
executive. People familiar with terms of the arrangement said Lee
was expected to step aside in 2002, leaving Seidenberg in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Their plan to be co-chief executives is the latest example of
such power-sharing arrangements to grow out of the current rush
throughout corporate America to consolidate. John Stafford, chief
executive of American Home Products, and Robert Shapiro, announced
such an arrangement in June, for example. Sanford Weill, the
chairman of Travelers Group, and John Reed, the chairman of
Citicorp, agreed to share power as part of their planned merger.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Lee and Seidenberg can comfortably share the office of
chief executive in their new company, and whether Seidenberg can
remain patient _ again _ until he takes over, are issues that will
be central to determining whether this latest planned merger will
work.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For much of Lee's career, however, he has shown a degree of
patience, much like Seidenberg. Lee majored in metallurgical
engineering at Cornell University before attending Harvard Business
School. He then joined the finance department of U.S. Steel, and
moved to similar roles at Penn Central and Columbia Pictures. In
1983, he joined GTE as senior vice president of finance and rose
steadily, becoming chief executive in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   For the first several years under his watch, GTE remained at the
back of the pack in the telecommunications industry, reinforcing
its stodgy reputation as a hodgepodge of local phone businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But patience in a fast-moving industry like telecommunications
is not rewarded for long, and both executives have shown some
uncharacteristic impatience of late to get to the front of the
pack.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, for example, began declaring in 1996 to anyone who would
listen that GTE had decided it would become a growth company. GTE
even hired an actor to portray Gen. George Patton at a meeting with
securities analysts as a sign of the company's resolve. But actions
tend to speak louder than words, and Lee surprised the industry
last fall by joining a bidding war with Worldcom Inc. for MCI
Communications Corp. At the time, he called the bid ``an
opportunity to jump-start our strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   And with Seidenberg's merger of Nynex with Bell Atlantic, and
now with his plan to acquire GTE, the politically agile executive
has demonstrated a more aggressive approach as well, with his eyes
on a long-term reward of being a top player in the
telecommunications industry by the time he turns 55.
</P>
<P>
   The executives certainly have reaped considerable rewards
already, at least financially. In addition to $787, 500 in salary
and a $1.8 million bonus last year, Seidenberg received an
``implementation bonus'' of $3 million, according to Bell
Atlantic's most recent proxy.
</P>
<P>
   Lee earned a salary in 1997 of $1.04 million, a bonus of $1.5
million, and an additional long-term incentive payout of $2.4
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
