<HEADER>
A5585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-2NDL     07-27 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-2NDLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Starr turns up heat on Clinton
 &HT;    (EDS: Updates lede to 'first time in six months...' -- use this
version.)
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's face-off with independent
counsel Kenneth Starr intensified Monday as Monica Lewinsky met
with Starr's prosecutors for the first time in six months and an
appeals court rejected the president's claims of lawyer-client
privilege for one of his closest aides.
</P>
<P>
   These developments came even as Clinton's private attorney
negotiated with Starr's office over the president's looming
testimony before a grand jury investigating whether he had a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky and then urged her to lie about it under
oath. Clinton has denied both allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic development occurred in New York, where
Lewinsky held a secret five-hour meeting with Starr's prosecutors.
Some observers saw it as a possible prelude to a deal that would
grant the former White House intern immunity in return for her
testimony before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers with knowledge of the meeting indicated that the two
sides moved much closer to such an agreement, The New York Times
reported.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiations through her then-lawyer earlier this year,
Lewinsky was widely reported to have said that she was prepared to
testify that she had a sexual relationship with Clinton but would
deny that he or anyone else had pressured her to lie about it under
oath. Lewinsky repeated those assertions Monday, The Times said,
citing the unnamed lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Starr reportedly has insisted on a face-to-face meeting with
Lewinsky to gauge her credibility before considering any immunity
deal. With Starr nearing the end of his witness list before the
grand jury, he must decide whether to subpoena her if no immunity
deal can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigators want to weigh Lewinsky's answers against
the mounting evidence they have collected from a long string of
witnesses, most recently Secret Service agents who guarded the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she is telling the truth, you might see her before the
grand jury soon,'' an unnamed source close to the case told Scripps
Howard News Service.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, Starr would likely want to debrief her
extensively, which could take several days.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, meanwhile, Clinton suffered a potentially
damaging setback when a U.S. appeals court ruled that his
conversations with aide Bruce Lindsey, perhaps the president's
closest confidant, are not shielded by traditional attorney-client
privilege and are fair game for Starr's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``A government attorney may not invoke the attorney-client
privilege in response to grand jury questions seeking information
relating to the possible commission of a federal crime,'' the
ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   As an attorney working for the White House, Lindsey's job ``is
not to defend clients against criminal charges and it is not to
protect wrongdoers from public exposure,'' the judges said in a
2-to-1 ruling that upheld a lower court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey has appeared several times before the grand jury, but
reportedly has declined to respond to key questions, asserting
attorney-client privilege designed to protect the confidentiality
of discussions held between individuals and their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   White House Counsel Charles Ruff issued a statement Monday
assailing the court ruling and saying he is considering whether to
appeal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed that the Court of Appeals has decided
that, unlike every other attorney and client in this country,
government attorneys and their clients do not enjoy the right to
have confidential communications,'' Ruff's statement read.
</P>
<P>
   ``The practical result of the court's decision is that the
president, and all other government officials, will be less likely
to receive full and frank advice about their official obligations
and duties from government attorneys,'' Ruff wrote. ``Without the
privilege, frank and candid exchange of information and advice will
be chilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision was made by U.S. Court of Appeals Judge Judith
Rogers, a Clinton appointee, and Judge A. Raymond Randolph, an
appointee of President George Bush, according to The Associated
Press. Judge David Tatel, another Clinton appointee, dissented from
the main part of the decision, warning of the potential for the
sort of ``chilling effect'' to which Ruff alluded.
</P>
<P>
   Against this frenzied backdrop of court activity and immunity
talks, Clinton's personal lawyer, David Kendall, negotiated with
Starr's office over whether, and under what terms, the president
might testify before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall's office issued a brief statement confirming that talks
were under way, but offered nothing of substance beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working with the Office of Independent Counsel, as we
have in the past, to devise a way for the president to provide
information for the OIC's investigation, consistent with his
constitutional role and responsibilities'' the statement said. ``It
would not be appropriate to comment further at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of failed talks with the White House about the
prospect of Clinton coming forward to testify voluntarily, Starr
has subpoenaed the president to appear before the grand jury today.
The White House has yet to publicly respond.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers involved in the inquiry said Starr would not enforce
today's deadline as long as negotiations were still on-going The
New York Times said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Times, an unnamed adviser to the president said
the deadline is not crucial because both sides are seeking a
compromise. Clinton is willing to testify if the questioning is
limited to the Lewinsky matter and does not involve a broad fishing
expedition into unrelated topics, the Times said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also is adamant about not being forced to appear
at the federal court house, the newspaper said. Clinton is willing
to provide written answers to prosecutors' questions or to submit
to a videotaped interview.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's testimony has become inevitable, the Times said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is now put in the position that if he doesn't
testify he's got to have some really overwhelming reasons, and
there are damn few of them,'' the Times quoted the adviser as
saying. ``He has said in so many words that he is prepared to
cooperate under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
