<SLUG> BC-VIGIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two years later: Remembering the woman who died in Olympic park
blast
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOUGLASVILLE, Ga. _ John Hawthorne Jr. has decided he wants to
make somebody pay for his wife's death, but even more, he wants to
make sure people remember the Alice Hawthorne who died when the
bomb exploded during the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne and others had a candlelight vigil Monday night at
Charles F. Golden United Methodist Church in Douglasville, where
Alice Hawthorne was born. The 44-year-old Albany businesswoman was
killed by shrapnel from the Centennial Olympic Park bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The widower ``is doing as well as anyone who has lost the love
of their life,'' said lawyer Gilbert H. Deitch, who is representing
Hawthorne in the suit filed this month in Fulton County State Court
on behalf of Hawthorne and Fallon Stubbs, Mrs. Hawthorne's
16-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is dealing with the grief every day but going on,'' Deitch
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hawthorne had gone to the park with Fallon to celebrate
Fallons' 14th birthday when nails and screws from the bomb wounded
them. Mrs. Hawthorne died from a head wound, the only fatality
directly linked to the bomb that injured 111 other people.
</P>
<P>
   A Turkish cameraman, Melih Uzunyol, died of a heart attack while
rushing to the scene. Authorities later ruled his death a homicide.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been arrested in connection with the blast, but
federal law officers consider fugitive Eric Robert Rudolph a
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   They are searching for Rudolph, 31, in western North Carolina.
He has been charged with bombing an abortion clinic in Birmingham.
In addition to the Olympic park bombing, authorities want to
question him about two other bombings in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit, Hawthorne and Fallon claim that Olympic
organizers and security companies failed to keep the park safe.
They are seeking unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, Deitch said, is an attempt by Hawthorne to ``hold
someone accountable for the death of his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, 16 other victims of the blast sued for more than
$100 million, but none of the cases has come to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hawthorne spoke to about 50 people who marked the
first anniversary of the bombing with a wreath-laying ceremony in
Centennial Olympic Park honoring his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it hasn't been easy talking about what happened...
it was important ... to remember Alice,'' Hawthorne said last year.
``We can't let the world forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
