<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-PETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANDED PETS RETRIEVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-COLLAPSE)  
(lb) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After days of panicked pleas from pet owners and
animal lovers, city officials managed on Monday to pluck a
menagerie of beloved pets from apartments near the Conde Nast
building.
</P>
<P>
   The animals were all reported to be in good condition, if a
little dehydrated and famished.
</P>
<P>
   In all, city officials said, emergency personnel rescued a group
worthy of ``The 12 Days of Christmas'': a cockatiel, a guinea pig,
a hamster, two ferrets, 12 cats and a small school of goldfish.
</P>
<P>
   At least four cats had yet to be rescued Monday, said Sunny
Mindel, a spokeswoman for the Mayor's Office of Emergency
Management. Two were in a building on West 43rd Street, which
remained closed. Two others were on West 44th Street, but they
could not be found by firefighters Monday. The firefighters left
ample food and water instead, Ms. Mindel said.
</P>
<P>
   All the rescued animals were treated at the American Society for
the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals hospital on the Upper East
Side. A few were later returned to their owners, said Peter Paris,
a spokesman for the society.
</P>
<P>
   There were still discrepancies Monday night about the fate of
all the animals, Paris said. His office had a different tally of
animals rescued (18, but no goldfish), and of cats outstanding
(six, not four).
</P>
<P>
   There were also some questions about the two ferrets, which are
illegal to own. At last report, their owners had entered
negotiations with the city's Health Department to determine the
ferrets' legal status.
</P>
<P>
   But at least they, and all the other animals, were safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just really amazed that they weren't in more serious
condition,'' Paris said. ``It just defies what we would expect to
see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
