<HEADER>
A5603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAWLEY-SUIT-NYT &LR;      07-27 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAWLEY-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARPTON LAWYER ASKS LENIENCY AS JURY WEIGHS DAMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Fighting back tears as he delivered his
closing statement Monday, the lawyer for the Rev. Al Sharpton
pleaded with the jurors in the Tawana Brawley defamation case not
to punish Sharpton with a large damage award, which he compared to
a financial death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   After closing statements are completed on Tuesday, the jury is
expected to begin considering how much to award plaintiff Steven
Pagones, the white former prosecutor who won the first phase of the
case July 13. The jury decided then that Pagones was defamed by
Sharpton, C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox when they said he raped
Miss Brawley, a black teen-ager, in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In his emotional remarks Monday, Sharpton lawyer Michael Hardy
described Sharpton as a brave civil rights warrior and urged that
the jurors not give him ``the financial electric chair.'' But, at
the same time, he appeared to lay the groundwork for rejecting a
heavy award against Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   An award of millions of dollars against Sharpton, Hardy said,
would prove once again that ``black people in America have no
rights.'' He virtually dared the jury of two blacks and four whites
to make a decision against Sharpton that he said would be based on
race. ``If that is the statement you want to make, make it,'' Hardy
said, ``but the world would then know what a farce of justice this
trial really is.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury also heard Monday from the lawyer for Mason, Stephen
Jackson, and from Maddox, who represents himself. Each tried to
minimize the harm suffered by Pagones. Maddox is to complete his
remarks Tuesday and then Pagones' lawyer will deliver his
summation.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, S. Barrett Hickman of state Supreme Court, is
expected to instruct the jurors Tuesday that they can award
anything from $1 to the full $150 million in damages that Pagones
is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Only five of the six jurors must agree on each award of damages.
Because the jurors rejected Pagones' assertion that the defendants
acted in conspiracy, each defendant would only be responsible for
the damages assessed against himself.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the defense lawyers tried Monday to walk a careful
line, saying on the one hand that any damages suffered by Pagones
were slight, and on the other challenging the jury's original
verdict that he was defamed. Maddox suggested to the jurors that
``some adjustments'' could be made to Pagones' original victory by
awarding him only a nominal amount.
</P>
<P>
   The defense would clearly claim a small damage award as a
victory. Maddox on Monday compared the damages phase of the case to
the second half of a football game and said the only thing that
mattered was the score at the end.
</P>
<P>
   But Maddox also spent considerable time suggesting that Pagones
suffered no damages. Referring to Pagones' assertions of stomach
pain, insomnia and other anxiety symptoms, Maddox said: ``There was
nothing ever wrong with him. And if there was something wrong with
him, Mason, Maddox and Sharpton had nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Maddox had, Jackson also suggested that Pagones had not
suffered. But he also returned to an assertion Mason had made
throughout the trial: that Pagones in fact raped Miss Brawley, even
though a 1988 grand jury report exonerated him and the current
jury's verdict indicated that it considered the rape accusation
false.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson reminded the jurors Monday that Mason had declined in
testimony as recently as last week to retract his assertions of
years ago that Pagones raped, sodomized and kidnapped Miss Brawley.
``The truth is, he wasn't being wrongfully accused,'' Jackson said
of Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the attention Monday was on Hardy, as he sought to
position Sharpton for a continuing political career no matter which
way the verdict goes. He said the jurors should not impose a harsh
financial penalty that would be aimed at trying to stop Sharpton's
civil rights work. But he also said that Sharpton's work would
continue, no matter what the penalty is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is to financially perish, let him perish,'' Hardy said.
``But it will not stop him from calling for justice for the next
victim.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
