<SLUG> BC-MEMOS-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE BETWEEN JUSTICE DEPT. AND BURTON INTENSIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department refused Monday to let a
House committee see two internal memorandums in which the FBI
director and another high-ranking official urged appointment of an
independent counsel to investigate fund-raising abuses in President
Clinton's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The refusal, not surprising in view of previous disagreements
between the department and the House government Reform and
Oversight Committee, intensified a dispute between the department
and Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who heads the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said that he would discuss the refusal with committee
members on Tuesday, and that a contempt citation against Attorney
General Janet Reno was possible.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Louis Freeh, director of the FBI, will send a letter to
Burton on Tuesday further explaining the department's position,
which was conveyed preliminarily Monday in a letter from an
assistant attorney general, Anthony Sutin.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokesman, Bert Brandenburg, said Monday
night, ``No prosecutor anywhere should have to hand out a road map
to an investigation and reveal information that could tip off the
guilty and smear the innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton described that reasoning as disingenuous and said his
committee's subpoena was not seeking secret grand jury information
but rather the reasoning of the memorandum writers: Freeh and
Charles La Bella, who has headed the department's campaign-finance
task force. La Bella is leaving to become interim U.S. attorney in
San Diego, and told Reno this month that she had no alternative but
to seek appointment of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Brandenburg said Sutin offered to meet with committee staff
members ``at their earliest convenience'' to discuss ways to
satisfy their hunger for information without compromising the
department's principles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
