<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-GAS-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS REJECT GASOLINE TAX INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Democrats in the Assembly announced Monday that
they would not support Gov. Christie Whitman's proposed gasoline
tax increase. This prompted the Assembly speaker, Jack Collins, to
say that he would not put it up for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, R-Salem County, said that he would not ask Assembly
Republicans, who face re-election next year, to support the tax
increase unless it received bipartisan support. But he said that he
remained hopeful that some Democrats would change their minds. He
could still schedule the vote before the full Assembly meets on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would raise the state's 14.5 cent tax on a gallon
of gasoline by 1 cent in 1999, 2 cents in 2000 and an additional 1
cent in 2001 to pay for $1.7 billion in new mass transit and
highway improvement projects over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking what everyone thought was a done deal, the Assembly
minority leader, Joseph Doria, D-Hudson County, said the Assembly's
32 Democrats decided during a meeting Monday that they would not
vote in favor of the gasoline tax increase because they believed
that the transportation projects could be paid for out of the
state's budget surplus. ``They just felt that there were better
ways to fund it,'' Doria said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest skirmish in a long-running battle between
Whitman and lawmakers over her proposed gasoline tax increase. When
Whitman first announced her proposal last spring, she recommended a
5-cent-a-gallon annual increase to pay for transportation projects
and an additional 2-cent-a-gallon increase for her plan to purchase
half of the state's 2 million acres of undeveloped land over the
next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers balked at using the gasoline tax increase to
purchase open space, and they said that a 5-cent annual increase
for transportation projects was too high.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, Whitman and Republican legislative leaders
reached agreement on a 4-cent-a-gallon increase to be phased in
over three years, and to borrow $1 billion over the next 10 years
for the open-space plan. In a separate bill, the borrowing plan was
approved Monday by the Assembly Appropriations Committee and is
expected to be considered by both the Assembly and the Senate on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said that he would not go along with any gasoline tax
increase unless a ``significant'' number of Democrats joined
Republicans in supporting it. The tax increase was expected to win
approval with bipartisan support in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Whitman said that she was disappointed ``to
learn that such an important issue for all of the residents of New
Jersey has, at least temporarily, been turned into a partisan
squabble.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Republican legislative leaders in the Assembly and in
the Senate called lawmakers back to the State House this Thursday.
They were trying to meet an Aug. 3 deadline that would allow the
state to put a referendum on the November ballot, asking voters if
they approved dedicating all existing and new gasoline tax revenues
for transportation projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
