<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TOPS CHINA, 2-0, IN WOMEN'S SOCCER AT GOODWILL GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ In an intensely played match that saw five
yellow cards and countless hard tackles, a pair of goals by forward
Mia Hamm in the 66th and 87th minutes gave the United States a 2-0
victory over China on Monday night for the women's gold medal in
soccer at the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   The first goal was set up when Christine Lilly having received a
yellow card one minute earlier, passed the ball through three
defenders to Hamm, who beat the Chinese offside trap. Hamm hit a
right-footed shot into the lower-left corner from 14 yards out. The
second score was all Hamm, as she controlled a deflected pass and
then curled a shot from 35 yards out to clinch the match. Her two
goals gives her 97 in her career, tying her with midfielder
Michelle Akers on the U.S. career scoring list.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 11,307, only 693 short of capacity at the Nassau
County Mitchel Athletic Complex, saw the renewal of a rivalry that
dates back to 1987, when the U.S. team made its first of five trips
to China to face the Chinese national team.
</P>
<P>
   China was host for the first women's World Cup in 1991, a
tournament that the United States won, but in which the host
country stumbled in the quarterfinals. The loss was so devastating
that China shut down its women's national team program for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1995 women's World Cup in Sweden, China and the United
States opened group play with a 3-3 tie that saw the Chinese score
twice in the final 15 minutes. The two teams eventually met again
in the third-place match, with the United States winning, 2-0. A
year later, they met for the gold medal in the 1996 Olympic Games,
where a crowd of 76,481 saw the United States defeat China, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first half Monday night, the U.S. side had
dominated in every way except on the scoreboard. China only got off
one shot, while the Americans peppered Chinese goalkeeper Zhao Yan
with nine shots on goal. Forward Tiffeny Milbrett pushed a shot
wide right in the 32nd minute, while Lilly missed a breakaway shot
five minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   China seriously threatened in the 55th minute when defender Kate
Sobrero took down defender Liu Ailing at the top of the penalty
area, drawing a yellow card for Sobrero and a free kick for China.
Midfielder Sun Wen's shot hit the crossbar and a subsequent header
by forward Zhang Ouying flew over the goal. Ouying nearly tied the
match in the 78th minute when she found herself just inside the
penalty area. But U.S. goalkeeper Briana Scurry came out and cut
off Ouying's angle, forcing her to miss wide. Nine minutes later,
Hamm put it out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of penalty kicks was much kinder to Norway in the
bronze medal match. Norway, which lost 4-2 on penalty kicks to
China on Saturday, was able to defeat Denmark on Monday night by
the same score after battling to a 1-1 tie in regulation. Much like
Saturday's match, Norway got on the board first, getting a goal
from midfielder Unni Lehn in the 20th minute. The lead stood up
until the 82nd minute when, after a mad scramble in the penalty
area, midfielder Anne Nelson kicked a point-blank shot in for the
equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson opened up the round of penalty kicks by having her
attempt saved by Norwegian goalkeeper Bente Nordby. After Denmark
missed its fourth kick, defender Henriette Viker clinched the match
by converting her penalty shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
