<SLUG> BC-TV-CBS-DISCOVERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERY TO BUY 50 PERCENT STAKE IN CBS EYE ON PEOPLE CHANNEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS, citing ``significant losses,'' announced Monday that it
would cede management of the Eye on People cable channel to
Discovery Communications, which will acquire a 50 percent interest
in what will become a joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   The channel, previously known as ``CBS Eye on People,'' will
drop CBS from its title, although much of the programming will
still be generated by CBS News, both in original productions and in
material taken from the network library, executives associated with
the two companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery Communications, the operator of numerous other cable
channels including the Discovery Channel, will also supply programs
for Eye on People. The channel will continue to focus on the lives
of famous people.
</P>
<P>
   Don Mitzner, president of CBS Cable, said the decision to seek a
partner for the channel reflected a concern by CBS's corporate
management over what he called the ``cash flow issue'' surrounding
Eye on People. He said the channel had lost ``significant amounts
of money'' since it started up in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He did not specify a figure, but several CBS executives said the
network had lost between $50 million and $70 million on the
channel.
</P>
<P>
   The exact amount of CBS's losses is central to the deal because
Discovery Communications has committed to paying all the costs of
the channel until it matches the CBS investment to this point.
Discovery is putting no money up front to secure the 50 percent
interest, Mitzner said.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery Communications, which is largely owned by
Tele-Communications Inc., the largest operator of cable systems,
will try to drive up the distribution of Eye on People, executives
from the company said. The channel is available in only about 11
million homes. Cable channels usually need to reach at least 30
million homes to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Mitzner said he hoped Eye on People would be profitable in the
next three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is also known to be looking for a similar partner for
another cable channel it owns, Telenoticias, a Spanish-language
news channel. Mitzner would not confirm that CBS was looking for
such a deal, but he said that corporate management of CBS is
``trying to maximize cash flow right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He disputed the suggestion that CBS was backing away from cable
investments, citing the decision less than a year ago to pay $1.5
billion for the Nashville Network and Country Music Television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
