<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ALFONZO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALFONZO BOTHERED BY LACK OF OUTPUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If there was one certainty about the New York Mets'
offense this season, from the front office on down, it was that
Edgardo Alfonzo was headed for stardom.
</P>
<P>
   So now the question arises: What, if anything, is wrong with
Alfonzo this year?
</P>
<P>
   In 85 games, the 24-year-old third baseman is hitting .267 with
six home runs and 47 runs batted in. Not terrible. But not what one
would expect from someone who finished 13th in the voting for
National League most valuable player last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's having a bad year,'' manager Bobby
Valentine said in Chicago last weekend. ``But it doesn't seem to me
he's felt as good playing as he felt last year. Maybe it's just a
nagging looseness.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was referring to Alfonzo's right shoulder. Alfonzo
strained his right rotator cuff five weeks into the season, then
spent two weeks on the disabled list. He has also had tightness in
his upper legs from time to time. But Alfonzo, who has also had
back problems during his career, insisted on Sunday that he is
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's bothering me is that I can't be consistent at
home plate,'' Alfonzo said. ``That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is obviously affecting the rest of the Mets' offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a tremendous year for me,'' Alfonzo said. ``This
year, I've had more opportunity to play. I have just tried to do my
job and make things happen. But I've been up and down, up and
down.''
</P>
<P>
   And so have the Mets, who open a 10-game homestand when they
play the San Diego Padres on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the players on the Mets heading into spring training, the
one the team was least concerned about was Alfonzo, who batted .315
in 1997, his first year as an everyday player.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were hoping that Alfonzo, who settled on a one-year
base contract for $1.75 million after he and the Mets could not
agree on a longer deal, could build on his power numbers. That was
about it.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, 102 games into his second season as the regular third
baseman, Alfonzo's power numbers _ he had 10 home runs and 72 RBI
last season _ are on roughly the same pace. His average is way
down, especially against left-handed pitching. In 1997, Alfonzo hit
.378 against lefties. This year, after 71 at-bats, he is batting
.225.
</P>
<P>
   And with runners in scoring position, Alfonzo's average has
dropped from .417 last season to .327 this year.
</P>
<P>
   There are varying theories as to why Alfonzo has struggled in
his second season as a regular. Has he been hurting more than he
has let on? Has he failed to adapt to the adjustments pitchers
(especially lefties) have made to him? Or is he simply pressing
while switching between hitting leadoff and No. 2?
</P>
<P>
   And there is no clear answer, although Valentine quickly brushed
off suggestions of a so-called sophomore jinx.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sophomore jinx is caused by complacency,'' Valentine said.
``I don't think he's been complacent at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as hitting coach Tom Robson pointed out, pitchers make
adjustments after a hitter enjoys an outstanding year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so, when a hitter comes off a good year, he has to make
adjustments, too,'' Robson said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the injuries, Valentine has said that one of his biggest
mistakes of the first half was not insisting that Alfonzo go on a
rehabilitation assignment before he came off the disabled list. The
problem was that Alfonzo refused to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I have gone down?'' he said again Sunday,
contending that facing minor league pitchers would only have messed
up his swing.
</P>
<P>
   There have been questions, however, about Alfonzo's bat speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days, he has been perfectly sharp,'' Robson said.
``Others, he's just a little bit behind. He just has to get through
it and put together three, four, five weeks in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   If Alfonzo finally does, there is little question what effect it
will have on the rest of the lineup. It is clear that when Alfonzo
gets on base, the Mets' offense responds. Last season, Alfonzo hit
.330 in 406 at-bats in the No. 2 slot. This year, according to the
Elias Sports Bureau, he has batted .243 in 140 at-bats hitting
second, .226 in 106 at-bats leading off.
</P>
<P>
   In three games in Milwaukee last week, Alfonzo went 5 for 15
(.333), drove in four runs, scored a run and stole a base. The Mets
swept the series. On Saturday in Chicago, Alfonzo went 0 for 4.
Sunday, he grounded out with runners on first and second in the
eighth inning in his only at-bat. The Mets lost both games against
the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of consistency indeed seems to be a problem _ especially on
a team that can survive inconsistency from some of its regulars,
but not from Alfonzo. With Alfonzo hot and cold, the Mets' offense
has been thoroughly inconsistent all year long.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Alfonzo went into Valentine's office not long ago
and apologized for his performance this season. Valentine told
Alfonzo to relax. The Mets still feel he is destined for stardom.
</P>
<P>
   When that expectation was mentioned to him, Valentine said:
``What's that mean? That he will make $5 million a year? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is how.
</P>
<P>
   ``By staying healthy,'' Valentine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
