NYT-07-27-98 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5628 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-W     07-27 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: government attorneys.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton was informed of the appeals court decision following a
forum on Social Security in Albuquerque, N.M. Lindsey, who
frequently travels with the president, did not make this trip, and
Barry Toiv, a deputy White House press secretary, said he did not
know if Clinton had spoken with Lindsey on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Clinton planned to change his schedule on Tuesday,
when he will be in Washington, Toiv said Clinton still plans to
attend and speak at a memorial service at the Capitol on Tuesday
afternoon for the two officers slain by a gunman last week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ignored questions about the subpoena shouted at him by
reporters on Monday morning, as he has throughout the last several
days. Asked why the president would not answer any questions about
the subpoena, Toiv said: ``Sometimes the president answers
questions, sometimes he doesn't. But he has answered this question
on a number of occasions and we have answered this question on a
number of occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey's lawyer, William Murphy, said he would have ``no
comment on the opinion at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The president appealed a May decision by U. S. District Judge
Norma Holloway Johnson that said that presidential advisers enjoyed
a qualified privilege for communications with the president but
that government-paid lawyers like Lindsey could not claim a similar
privilege in criminal matters.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals Court Judges Raymond Randolph, appointed by President
Bush in 1990, and Judith Rogers, a 1994 Clinton appointee,
concurred in the lower court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   But David Tatel, appointed by Clinton in 1994, issued a strongly
worded dissent, saying that the sweeping decision by the majority
would chill discussions in the executive branch and force a
president to retain a battery of private lawyers to consult on
sensitive matters that are directly related to the demands of his
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since for any president the line between official and personal
can be both elusive and difficult to discern,'' Tatel wrote in the
Lindsey case, ``I think presidents need their official
attorney-client privilege to permit frank discussion not only of
innocuous, routine issues, but also sensitive, embarrassing or even
potentially criminal topics.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``weakening the privilege may well cause
presidents to shift their trust from White House lawyers who have
undertaken to serve the presidency, to private lawyers who have
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatel dissented from an earlier appeals court ruling in the case
of Vincent Foster, a White House lawyer who committed suicide in
1993. Prosecutors wanted access to notes of his conversations with
his lawyers, arguing that the lawyer-client privilege did not
extend after the client's death.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the appeals court panel ruled that the notes
must be surrendered. The Supreme Court this year sided with Tatel,
saying that the confidential relationship between lawyer and client
existed in perpetuity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-98 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
