<DOCNO> NYT19980727.0445 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-WORLDSERIES     07-27 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WORLDSERIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR YANKS, WINNING THE SERIES IS THE ONLY THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Yankees have already won so many games
with such numbing efficiency that two-game losing streaks qualify
as mild surprises. It is not even August, but the Yankees address
questions about competing in the postseason because the players
realize it is silly to act as if they will not make it. That is
what happens when a team has the chance to break a 92-year-old
record for regular-season victories.
</P>
<P>
   Other things will happen to the Yankees, too. With each victory,
the Yankees are escalating expectations. Simply getting to the
World Series is not an option and the Yankees know that. Winning a
championship is the only option, and no lecture from the principal
owner, George Steinbrenner, is needed to grasp this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to win,'' Derek Jeter said. ``We could win 150 and
lose 12 and then not win the World Series. What's the point of the
season? We have one goal, the ultimate goal.''
</P>
<P>
   It is why general manager Brian Cashman is still making calls to
the Seattle Mariners to gauge Randy Johnson's status in trade
talks. Cashman spoke to the Mariners late Monday but it is still
uncertain if Johnson is available. It is why the Yankees floated
the possibility of a Chuck Knoblauch for Roberto Alomar deal with
the Orioles earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees bypassed the opportunity to put Johnson in their
rotation and turned Orlando Hernandez into a vicious weapon out of
the bullpen to protect a prospect, would they have sleepless nights
if a trade could have made them more impenetrable? Definitely.
Cashman tinkered with the 73-26 team Monday by designating
infielder Dale Sveum for assignment and potentially eating more
than $1 million in salary, while recalling outfielder/first baseman
Shane Spencer from Class AAA Columbus, reiterating that the general
manager also knows this season must be THE SEASON. Greatness is not
bestowed on teams limited to remarkable regular-season records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting in isn't enough,'' Cashman said. ``Winning it is what
it's all about. It's always been that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Raines did not even let a reporter finish a question about
expectations before saying: ``I'm sure we've made it so that we
have to win the World Series or this will be a disappointment. They
don't remember the regular season if you don't go all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines is correct. When the Yankees won the World Series in
1996, they were not as dominating in the regular season, going
92-70. If the Yankees do not crumble, they will be favored before
the first postseason pitch is tossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think last year was the same thing,'' Paul O'Neill said.
``When we got knocked out, it was a major disappointment. I don't
see this season being any different. Going into the postseason,
we're expected to win. But you don't know what's going to happen
with every team.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Yankees have some mysteries to solve. The right-hander
Jeff Nelson will be sidelined until late August with a lower-back
injury, and he is an important part of an erratic bullpen. Without
Nelson, the Yankees have only one dependable righty setup reliever
in Ramiro Mendoza. Manager Joe Torre will not feel comfortable
entrusting a tight game to Darren Holmes or Mike Buddie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Nelson back and healthy,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Chili Davis is expected to return from ankle
surgery next month and will try to blend in with a team that has
won 75 percent of its games without him. Davis was signed to be a
full-time DH and his return will mean Darryl Strawberry and his
weak left knee must play the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chili Davis,'' Torre said, ``is going to fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre also wants the Yanks to continue displaying the
intangibles that have made them alarmingly productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see us sustain, maintain the energy level and
determination, and we've been pretty good,'' Torre said. ``We
haven't played perfect baseball. That's tough to do on a day-to-day
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   It gets tougher in the postseason. Then the Yankees, who would
win 105 games if they were to go 32-31 the rest of the way, will be
0-0 again. Everything that they won from April through September
will be erased. The Yankees will need 11 victories for a title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not break any records if we don't win it after
that,'' Raines said. ``Who won the World Series? That's what
everyone remembers. Nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   _ Even though infielder Dale Sveum had a two-year, $1.6 million
contract, he barely contributed while batting .155 in 58 at-bats so
the Yankees admitted their mistake and designated him for
assignment. The Yankees have 10 days to trade Sveum, release him or
try to assign him to the minor leagues. It is unlikely that they
will be able to trade Sveum and more unlikely that the nine-year
veteran will agree to go to the minors. Consequently, the Yankees
will probably wind up paying Sveum about $275,000 for the remainder
of the season and $800,000 for next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shane Spencer, the type of right-handed hitter manager Joe
Torre has expressed a need for, will join the Yanks at Anaheim.
Spencer hit .314 with 15 homers and 55 runs batted in at Columbus.
</P>
</TEXT>
