<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5633 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHWERTNER-COX     07-27 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWERTNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eugene Schwertner, successful livestock businessman, dead at 78
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Eugene Schwertner, who expanded a tiny cattle
auction that he started in Austin in 1946 into one of the country's
biggest livestock businesses, died Monday morning at his home.
</P>
<P>
   Schwertner, 78, had been diagnosed with cancer of the liver four
years ago. He died at 3:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Services will be at 10 a.m. Wednesday at Austin's Highland Park
Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   The founder and chief executive of Capitol Land &AMP; Livestock had
strong roots in Williamson County. Schwertner's business, one of
the top three in its industry, operated on land his grandfather
settled around the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Schwertner, who stood 6 feet 4 inches tall, cut an imposing
figure. He ate beef for lunch and dinner most days. Company
mailings are stamped with the message, ``Eat more beef.''
</P>
<P>
   As a cattleman, Schwertner (pronounced swet-ner) helped change
the industry by being among the first to offer cattle by the
truckload to feedlots, making the process more efficient.
Previously, feedlots, where cattle gain weight before going to
packing plants, had to buy cattle one at a time at auction.
</P>
<P>
   As Schwertner's company developed, it could customize shipments
for feedlots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the guy who designed the wholesale template of the cattle
industry,'' said James Herring, president and chief executive of
Friona Industries LP. The huge Amarillo concern, which operates
five Texas feedlots, buys more than 30,000 head of cattle annually
from Capitol Land &AMP; Livestock.
</P>
<P>
   ``In so doing, he became a powerhouse,'' Herring said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwertner continued to innovate. Today, the company posts daily
photos of cattle on the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he maintained old ways of doing business. For the 52
years he ran Capitol Land &AMP; Livestock, Schwertner needed just a
handshake to seal agreements with customers. The no-contract policy
is all the more noteworthy considering the size of the 80-employee
company, whose revenues are estimated to exceed $150 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Central Texas after serving four years in the U.S.
Navy Construction Battalion during World War II, Schwertner in 1946
started his cattle auction in what is now Callahan's General Store
southeast of Austin on U.S. 183.
</P>
<P>
   The business was well received by farmers, who were grateful to
have an Austin auction for their cattle. But frequently there were
more sellers than buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to have a market for those farmers,'' Schwertner said
last fall during an interview at the company's two-story, white
stone headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they would sell, we'd buy. We'd keep them if there wasn't a
market for them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a risky strategy at first. Schwertner, who had no inkling
of how his idea would blossom, started calling feedlots in Texas
and other Southwestern states to see if they would buy the leftover
cattle.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered there was a market for animals that been sorted by
such categories as breed, age and weight, because that enabled
feedlots to fill gaps in their inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Sales sometimes required the young business to truck the cattle
hundreds of miles over two-lane highways, but that strategy of
customizing orders for feedlots and, later, ranchers who were
building their herds, opened a lucrative niche in what is now a $5
billion U.S. cattle industry.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol Land &AMP; Livestock also owns 20,000 acres of land that it
uses for pasture and growing hay.
</P>
<P>
   Schwertner had to rely on friends and business associates to
make it through perhaps his biggest crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, his wife, Gloria, was discovered to have a brain tumor.
The illness required surgery and hospitalization in Austin for a
year, said the couple's son, Jim Schwertner. The elder Schwertner
struggled with running the business and raising Jim, who was 8, and
their 2-year-old daughter, Sherri.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Schwertner had no health insurance to help with the
$100,000 in medical bills stemming from his wife's treatment, Jim
Schwertner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty leveraged, but the banks stood by him and loaned
him the money for the hospital bills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A family friend and neighbor in Austin's Western Hills area,
Eloise Phillips, cared for the children during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Schwertner recovered and worked as the company's
bookkeeper. She died two years ago at age 73.
</P>
<P>
   Schwertner, who occasionally chewed cigars one bite at a time
rather than smoke them and sometimes sipped Jack Daniels in the
evenings, kept financial details of the business a closely guarded
secret among his family, a few key employees and his bankers.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was profitable from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   A key part of the company's way of doing business is that it
sells every head of cattle every day, even if it means losing
money. It would cost more in feed to keep the cattle another day
without a guarantee that the prices would go higher.
</P>
<P>
   So firm is that rule that is not uncommon for one of the
company's 25 cattle-hauling rigs to be loaded with unsold animals
and sent out in the early morning darkness before the driver knows
his destination. Once telephone negotiations at the Schwertner
headquarters produce a buyer for that truckload, the driver learns
via cell phone where to deliver the cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might not like the price, but we sell 'em,'' Schwertner
said last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Innovation and dedication
</P>
<P>
   Conservative in many business practices, Schwertner nonetheless
adopted emerging technologies that could help the company. The
company recently bought a digital camera to take photos for its Web
site (www.cllnet.com).
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Schwertner began monitoring cattle prices from the
Chicago Board of Trade _ the cattle futures market _ by a satellite
feed. The company uses the price information to help determine up
to the minute how much its buyers should bid for cattle at
auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of Eugene Schwertner's dedication to the
business, Capitol Land &AMP; Livestock became a family operation.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Schwertner, 47, is president of Capitol Land &AMP; Livestock.
Daughter Sherri Madden, 41, does accounting work in the office and
her husband, Tom Madden, manages the company's trucking operations.
</P>
<P>
   Schwertner's dedication continued even recently, when
chemotherapy treatments for liver cancer made him physically ill.
He would drive to the Lockhart Auction, one of several area
auctions he owned, and spend hours watching and bidding on cattle.
</P>
<P>
   He relished the serious yet good-natured competition with other
buyers, Jim Schwertner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him it was like going to the Austin Country Club and
playing golf,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Jim Schwertner and Sherri Madden, Schwertner is
survived by five grandchildren: Jimmy, Jason and Samantha
Schwertner of Austin, and Hunter and Nicole Madden of Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
