A5634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-TIMES-SQUARE-NYT     07-27 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TIMES-SQUARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE RETURN, ALMOST, OF TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, July 28:
</P>
<P>
   The blare of traffic is back. Sidewalks along Broadway are full
_ the usual mass of people buying, selling, gawking, pushing, all
at different speeds and in different directions. A small ark of
animals has been rescued from a building on 44th Street, including
12 cats, two illegal ferrets, several goldfish, one cockatiel, a
guinea pig, a gerbil and a hamster. Except for those areas in the
shadow of the Conde Nast tower, where loose scaffolding caused part
of an elevator tower to break away a week ago, crashing into a
residential hotel and killing an elderly woman, Times Square is
almost back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the city's crossroads reopened, and with the
breakaway scaffolding slowly being secured with what one television
reporter called ``our giant nylon stocking,'' this is a good time
to find out what really happened. Speculation is now focusing on
the possibility that beams holding the scaffolding to the building
on the 21st floor may not have been properly secured by contractors
working on the facade. Workers often remove the beams holding the
elevator shaft while they apply the facade. The question is whether
someone neglected to re-attach the beams or whether they were
somehow wrenched from the building in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and insurance companies are now circling the site,
undoubtedly setting the stage for a number of lawsuits. The U.S.
Department of Commerce, meanwhile, is investigating whether some of
the bolts used in the scaffolding are counterfeit. And the U.S.
Occupational Safety and Health Administration is looking at safety
issues.
</P>
<P>
   However, the primary responsibility for discovering causes of
the accident, and making sure that construction can safely proceed,
lies with New York City. City officials announced plans Monday to
hire an outside company that specializes in figuring out the causes
of construction accidents. That is a good start, but the city must
make certain that the report is finished quickly and used to help
prevent any similar accidents in this high-density city. At another
hour and on a busier street, this accident could have taken a far
greater toll on human life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
