A5637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLLAPSE-WORKER-NY     07-27 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-WORKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING OUT ON A BEAM WITH THE PICTURE GUY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the scaffolding at 4 Times Square gave way last
Tuesday, showering tons of orange-painted steel onto the streets
below, Gerard Suarez had a view most people would envy, until they
thought about it for a second.
</P>
<P>
   Suarez, a 51-year-old veteran ironworker with perpetually
windburned eyes, was ABOVE the top of the building.
</P>
<P>
   For about an hour that morning, he and a lone welder had
crouched in a crook formed by two pieces of steel within the frame
of a giant billboard jutting from the skyscraper's roof. In other
words, they were about 53 floors up in a 48-story building, where
the nervous welder hunched over a minor repair with Suarez, part of
the safety crew for the ironworkers, along to steady him.
</P>
<P>
   If not for a few of the words Suarez uses to describe what
happened next, a listener would be hard pressed to tell from his
clipped cadence and affectless tone that it was anything more than
another day on a skyscraper. ``So I was sitting on top, waiting for
this guy to get that done,'' he says, ``and all of a sudden I see
this guy Jerry running.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Jerry yell to the guys on the scaffold, `Hey, get out
of there. The thing is giving.' And when he said that, I heard a
crunch. I ran over to the other side of the beam, and I'm watching
it, and I didn't believe it.'' Asked what went through his mind,
Suarez pauses for several seconds. He says finally and
matter-of-factly: ``It's like your heart just wants to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   But besides his unparalleled view that morning, Suarez had
something else no one had: a camera.
</P>
<P>
   For at least the last 25 years of his 31-year career, he has
been known among his co-workers as the Picture Guy. He takes
pictures of the first columns as a building begins to rise. As it
rises, slowly, floor by floor, he takes pictures of what he sees on
its way up: gargoyles, birds' nests, intricate stone work,
forgotten spaces revealed by morning light behind broken windows,
the details of a city all but concealed from the street.
</P>
<P>
   For his co-workers, especially the veterans, for whom memories
of hundreds of jobs can begin to blur, he snaps work shots or poses
buddies across beams, smiling. At the end of a job, he hands out
copies to workers who are retiring. ``I really like to take
pictures of the old-timers,'' he said. ``I say, `Come on, let me
take a picture of you before you kick the bucket on us.' They love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the taller buildings _ like 4 Times Square, the Citicorp
Building, 7 Hanover Square in lower Manhattan _ he concentrates on
roofs, which he says are a woefully underappreciated facet of New
York architecture, one he has observed more than most. He has shot
the top of the Fraunces Tavern building on Pearl Street and Grand
Central Terminal and St. Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I look at things for a long, long time, and when I
was looking at Saint Paddy's I saw the design, like the sign of the
cross, so I tried to get it from different angles,'' said Suarez,
who was raised in a Catholic family in Ridgewood, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the collapse, he almost forgot he had tucked a
camera into his denim work jacket _ he once carried nice 35
millimeter cameras, but after one was stolen and another broken, he
downgraded reluctantly to disposables. When he remembered his tiny
cardboard Fun Saver 35 Kodak seconds later, he sat down on the beam
and with little to do except watch and pray that no one had been
killed below, he began to snap away. (Four of his pictures of the
collapse and repair efforts have appeared in The New York Times.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of a two-hour interview late last week after a
long day back on the building, Suarez was often slightly nervous
and reticent about discussing his life. But when the subject turned
to his pictures, he grew almost sheepishly poetic. ``There are
certain things I look for,'' he said at one point. ``I love the
lines of the tops of the buildings, the shapes of the buildings.''
And then later: ``There are certain things I wait for _ a certain
shape, the lighting, maybe a good shadow, a big load of beams
coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his life and work, he will allow that ironwork has sometimes
made for a difficult life. He joined Local 40 of the ironworkers'
union at age 20, even though his father, a union electrician,
considered such work unnecessarily daredevilish. By the time he was
married and his first son came along, he said, he was already
living the nomadic, modern-day-cowboy existence of an ironworker:
``booming out,'' sometimes for months at a time, to find work. He
helped place steel beams and bolt them up in Dallas, Atlanta and
Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   When he moved his family _ two sons and two daughters, now
grown, and his wife, Rita, a nurse _ to Peterborough, N.H., for a
more tranquil life, he found that he was rarely able to enjoy it.
He and Rita were divorced several years ago after 19 years of
marriage. Suarez married again three years ago; his wife, Eva, is a
beautician, and they live on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, nobody ever expects to get divorced,'' he said.
``It's a tough life. It breaks up a marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits it didn't help when he would sometimes tell his wife
how he got some of his better pictures. ``One time in Vermont,
Castleton, I shinnied out to the end of a pole that stuck out over
a gorge. I held on with one hand and took the picture with the
other,'' he said. ``I've done crazy things. But I have some
pictures you wouldn't believe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
